A3692 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIANS-LAUNDER-2NDL     08-20 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIANS-LAUNDER-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANK OF NEW YORK AGGRESSIVELY COURTED RUSSIAN BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ADDS 4th graf to put size of alleged laundering in context; 9th
graf with example of transaction.) (rk) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN with RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Bank of New York, in an effort to expand a
lucrative business in Eastern Europe over the last several years,
aggressively pursued relationships with many of Russia's largest
banks, a strategy that might have contributed to embarrassing
questions about money laundering that the bank now faces.
</P>
<P>
   The bank specialized in setting up cash and securities accounts
for Russian banks in the United States, a higly competitive market
that the bank dominated, according to American bankers and
financial analysts. The accounts allowed Russian institutions, many
of which collapsed last year beneath piles of debt and speculative
investments, to easily transfer money outside of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   At first, doing business with Russian banks seemed like a
fruitful new business. But now the bank is under federal
investigation for channeling billions of dollars through accounts
in what is suspected to be a major money laundering operation by
Russian organized crime, law enforcement officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe that it could be one of the largest money
laundering operations ever uncovered in the United States, with
$4.2 billion passing through one account alone from last October
through March. The bank said Wednesday that it has been cooperating
with the investigation, which involves the use of bank facilities
to transfer funds from Russia to other countries. The bank said
there are no allegations of wrongdoing and declined to comment
further. It also suspended two senior officers pending the outcome
of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The bank entrusted responsibility for much of the fast-growing
business in Eastern Europe to Natasha Gurfinkel Kagalovsky, a
senior vice president whom federal investigators believe to be at
the heart of a money laundering scandal inside the bank. Ms.
Kagalovsky, who was one of the employees suspended Wednesday, has
not been accused of any crime. But it remains unclear whether there
was wrongdoing by her or other individuals, and how adequately the
bank supervised their activities and their Russian customers.
</P>
<P>
   One of her best customers was Inkombank, a fast-growing Russian
bank that transacted more than 250 payments a day through the Bank
of New York. Inkombank brought its business to the Bank of New York
from the Republic New York Corp. in 1992, because Ms. Kagalovsky
promised to be less vigilant than Republic about the way in which
Inkombank's accounts were handled here, according to Emanuel E.
Zeltser, a former attorney for Inkombank.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kagalovsky assured Inkombank's representatives that ``Bank
of New York would be much more understanding about how to manage
correspondent accounts than Republic,'' Zeltser said. Republic
officials declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; When Republic and the Bank of New York handled similar
transactions with Russian clients some time ago, one investigator
said, Republic filed a suspicious activity report with bank
regulators but the Bank of New York did not. The nature of the
transactions could not be learned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bank of New York was very happy with the money Natasha and
Galitzine were making and routinely let them run their own show,''
Zeltser said referring to Ms. Kagalovsky and Vladimir Galitzine,
another Bank of New York officer. Bank of New York said Galitzine
was unavailable for comment. An individual familiar with the
investigation of the bank said that Galitzine has not been
suspended.
</P>
<P>
   It could not be determined who at the bank supervised Ms.
Kagalovsky. The bank declined comment further, and Ms. Kagalovsky
was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain: Ms. Kagalovsky, the wife of Konstantin
Kagalovsky, a prominent Russian banker and oil executive, was a
vociferous and active cheerleader in pushing Bank of New York to
expand its presence in Russia in the early and mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1995 memo to Thomas Renyi, who was then the president of
the bank and is now the chief executive, Ms. Kagalovsky and another
executive made note of how important one Russian bank, Inkombank,
was to the Bank of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inkombank is our largest generator of fee income, and they are
now the largest clearing bank in Russia for domestic
transactions,'' the memo noted. The memo, which Bank of New York
declined to comment on, was given to The New York Times by Zeltser,
who said he acquired it as part of a lawsuit he has filed against
Inkombank over unpaid fees. Lawyers representing Inkombank declined
to comment about the bank's involvement with Bank of New York or
Zeltser's lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Inkombank, like many of it counterparts in Russia, is now
insolvent. Another Russian bank that had accounts with Bank of New
York was Menatep, part of an industrial empire overseen by Mikhail
Khodorkovsky, one of Russia's prominent financiers, called
``oligarchs.'' Bank of New York had an active relationship with
Menatep and helped the bank list its stock for trading in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators are trying to determine whether some of
the money that was channeled through the Bank of New York came from
Menatep. Menatep, and related companies in Russia, are suspected by
Western investors and Russian regulatory authorities of having
looted money from the country, allegations that Khodorkovsky and
his representatives have firmly denied.
</P>
<P>
   Through Ms. Kagalovsky, Bank of New York had a personal
connection to Menatep. Ms. Kagalovsky's husband, Konstantin, is a
former senior executive at Menatep and is now the vice chairman of
Yukos, an oil company that is the flagship of of Khodorkovsky's
troubled business empire. Ms. Kagalovsky did not respond to an
interview request.
</P>
<P>
   Zeltser, the former Inkombank attorney, said that the
Kagalovskys were married in the mid-1990s, when Bank of New York
began doing business with Menatep. An American official close to
the money laundering investigation of the Bank of New York
described the Kagalovskys' business connection as ``extraordinarily
provocative.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kagalovskys own a condominium on East 47th Street in
Manhattan that Ms. Kagalovsky bought in January 1997, for $796,000,
according to real estate records. It appears that Ms. Kagalovsky
paid cash. The property records show no loan.
</P>
</TEXT>
