<HEADLINE>
BIAS SUIT THREATENS AIMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA BIGGS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizona's new high school gradu ation test may be in jeopardy be
cause of a lawsuit begun seven years ago by Nogales parents who say
the state does not do enough to educate Spanish-speaking children.
</P>
<P>
   This year's sophomore class is the first that will be required
to pass AIMS, or Arizona's Instrument to Measure Standards, before
it gradu ates in 2002. The test is given only in English to
high-schoolers.
</P>
<P>
   The case winding its way through U.S. District Court in Tucson
con tends that the AIMS is discrimina tory against limited-English
students as a graduation requirement. If a judge agrees, the test
could be declared unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``The graduation competency tests are to be English-only
tests,'' said attorney William Morris, who's rep resenting families
in the Nogales Unified School District.
</P>
<P>
   ``You start off by taking the English and writing tests, and if
you don't pass those, then that's it,'' Morris said. ``What about
the population of (non-English speaking) newcomers we have who
arrive here in eighth, ninth grade? They don't have a prayer of
passing them.''
</P>
<P>
   The case is reminiscent of the suit brought by the Arizona
Center for Law in the Public Interest that, after years of
litigation, determined that the state's school-construction fi
nancing mechanism discriminated against poorer districts.
</P>
<P>
   After four attempts, the Legislature last year crafted the
Students FIRST (Fair and Immediate Resources for Students Today)
bill, which central ized funding for school districts. But Students
FIRST does not affect such operating expenses as teachers sala
ries, nor extra tutoring needs for students lacking English
proficiency.
</P>
<P>
   One of the issues in the Nogales case involves whether the state
is ade quately funding programs for such students.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was initiated in 1992 by two parents in the Nogales
Unified School District seeking to force the state to help improve
programs for limited-English students. In amend ments during
litigation, it more directly came to address the AIMS graduation
requirement.
</P>
<P>
   During arguments, which ended Wednesday, consultant Sidney
Borcher testified that a 1988 study by the state estimated it costs
$450 more to educate a limited-English student than it does to
teach an English-proficient student. But Ari zona designates only
$150 in extra funds per limited-English student to the schools.
</P>
<P>
   Morris said there are effective tech niques for teaching English
pro ficiency, but they ``involve intensive tutorial skills'' and
funding.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Glass, associate dean for re search at Arizona State
University's College of Education, testified that an analysis found
that if 10 percent of Anglos fail the AIMS test, then more than a
third of Hispanic and Black students will fail.
</P>
<P>
   He said he came to his conclusion after analyzing Anglo and
minority students' results on the Stanford 9, the state's current
standardized test. He said 75 percent of the standards used in the
AIMS test are shared by the Stanford 9.
</P>
<P>
   State Department of Education offi cials could not be reached
for comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But, at the trial, Assistant Attorney General Roger Hall, who
represents the department, disagreed that other tests' results can
show how students will do on the AIMS, and said that race alone
does not determine per formance on standardized tests.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Alfredo Marquez will rule on the case after
both sides submit memos, due within 30 days. The two sides are
working on a consent decree on issues involving state monitoring of
English profi ciency programs.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs hope the judge will address adequate funding for
English proficiency programs, rather than just striking down the
AIMS test as unconstitutional. &QL; 
The Associated Press contributed to this article. &QL; 
Patricia Biggs can be reached at (602) 444-2473 or at patri
cia.biggs &LR; pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
