<HEADLINE>
SHAKE OFF MOSS, POLI-DIXON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Minnesota Vikings receiver Randy Moss might not
be much of a role model, but as a summer workout partner, he's not
bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's real cool,'' said UCLA receiver Brian Poli-Dixon. ``He
kept it real and gave us lots of inside tips. He made us feel real
welcomed. There wasn't any, `I'm Randy Moss and I'm not talking to
anybody.' &UR;  &LR; ''
</P>
<P>
   Poli-Dixon and teammate Freddie Mitchell trained with Moss and
Vikings receiver Chris Carter for eight days this summer in Boca
Raton, Fla., a few hours from Mitchell's Florida hometown of
Lakeland. They talked football, spoke of life and participated in
Carter's grueling conditioning program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous how hard those guys work,'' said Poli-Dixon.
</P>
<P>
   It was an experience to remember, for sure. But when Poli-Dixon
struggled during the opening days of training camp, Bruins coach
Bob Toledo wondered if his junior receiver should have spent more
time running routes and playing catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a little rusty,'' Toledo said. ``He talked with Randy
Moss, but he isn't playing like Randy Moss. He's dropping too many
passes.''
</P>
<P>
   Poli-Dixon's first practice was one of the worst of his life. He
was lethargic, his technique was poor and he couldn't concentrate.
The resulting drops were a shock to his coaches and his system, but
eventually his confidence returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could I have had a better summer? Maybe,'' he said. ``I could
have worked on my game more, but I learned things in other areas
and there's something to that.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; High praise: UCLA's dynamic offense averaged 40 points per
game the last two seasons and won admirers throughout college
football _ including former USC coach John Robinson, who's
replicating the system in his rookie season at Nevada-Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're copying a lot of what UCLA did last year,'' Robinson
told the Orange County Register. ``I thought they had the best
offense I've ever seen in college football.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Calling all bodies: Toledo hoped to hold a brief scrimmage
for freshmen and walk-ons Wednesday, then realized he didn't have
enough bodies. Minor injuries and the disabled-parking suspensions
have slashed UCLA's depth, especially in the secondary and
offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the linebackers, I think we can get through (the
suspensions) and be OK,'' he said. ``The defensive backs and
offensive line are my concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Bright future: The Bruins expect to redshirt freshman
tailback Akil Harris, although they're impressed with what they've
seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like him,'' Toledo said. ``He's a physical runner. He's
smart and he can catch the ball. He was a good recruit for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris might be the primary ballcarrier in two years, since
Jermaine Lewis is a junior and sophomore DeShaun Foster potentially
could bolt for the NFL after next season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Older and better? Redshirt freshman Sean Phillips was the
marquee catch among UCLA's 1998 defensive-line recruits, a Parade
All-American coveted by all the top schools. Yet he redshirted last
year while Anthony Fletcher and Ken Kocher played.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: age.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips was just 17 last season and lacked the physical
maturity necessary to compete against 300-pound offensive linemen
three and four years older. This season, he's stronger, leaner and
ready to contribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really starting to develop,'' said defensive ends coach
John Pearce. ``He's got tremendous talent, but he's still a young
guy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
