<HEADLINE>
H&AMP;R BLOCK'S NEW BUSINESSES INCREASE ITS REVENUE, BUT LOSS
INCREASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GENE MEYER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ H&AMP;R Block Inc. said its seasonal tax-service
losses widened in its most recent quarter, but its newer
mortgage-lending and business-services businesses helped produce a
72 percent increase in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Block said losses for its fiscal first quarter, which ended July
31, increased to $37.1 million, or 38 cents a share, up from $27.7
million, or 26 cents a share, in the same quarter a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue in the quarter rose to $121.6 million from $70.6 million
a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Block, based in Kansas City, is the nation's largest
tax-preparation service, handling about one in seven returns that
taxpayers send to the Internal Revenue Service. Because the tax
business is highly seasonal, the company also has been diversifying
into mortgage lending and other year-round business and personal
financial services.
</P>
<P>
   Increased expenses related to the continuing expansion of the
company's tax-office network and a reduction in investment income
were the biggest contributors to the latest quarter's wider
operating loss, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Block normally invests its surplus cash for additional income,
but it also has been using some of those funds since 1998 to buy
back its stock in the market to increase the value of the remaining
shares still held by investors.
</P>
<P>
   Block said that among its three main operations areas:
</P>
<P>
   - Tax operations revenue rose 7 percent, to $13.1 million,
primarily because of higher tax-preparation fees. Pretax losses
increased 23 percent to $71.1 million because of expansion costs
and a compensation and benefits package change for field managers.
</P>
<P>
   - Mortgage operations revenue increased 44 percent to $76.1
million, and pretax profit rose 54 percent to $21.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   - Business service operations revenue increased to $24.2 million
from a year-earlier $1.3 million, primarily because Block acquired
several regional accounting firms in the intervening 12 months.
Pretax losses for the unit were $185,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
