r a BC-ABORTION-ADS-KAN &LR;      08-20 0359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-ADS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABORTION FOES' ADS URGE MISSOURI LEGISLATORS TO DEFEND BAN ON
PROCEDURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL SENTELL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. _ Abortion opponents have begun a statewide
radio campaign to help override Gov. Mel Carnahan's veto of a bill
they say would criminalize a certain abortion procedure.
</P>
<P>
   The ads began Monday and will air until lawmakers decide the
issue at their annual veto session, said Susan Klein, executive
director of Missouri Right to Life. The veto session begins Sept.
15.
</P>
<P>
   Klein said the ads are part of a campaign backed by the Missouri
chapter of the Physicians Ad Hoc Coalition for Truth, Missouri
Right to Life, Missouri Catholic Conference, Eagle Forum, Christian
Life Commission and others.
</P>
<P>
   Backers contend the bill is designed to ban only certain
late-term abortions by classifying them as infanticide. The
procedure would be a felony unless it was done to save the mother's
life.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan vetoed the bill because he said it was a deceptive
attempt to outlaw all abortions. The governor, who favors abortion
rights, also contends the bill would allow people to use violence
to stop what the bill labeled a ``partial birth'' abortion, a new
argument that backers dispute.
</P>
<P>
   One radio ad airing in the Kansas City area, and financed by the
physicians group, questions whether the procedure should even be
labeled an abortion since it takes place outside the womb. The ad
says former Surgeon General C. Everett Koop and the American
Medical Association have said the procedure should be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Sifford, Carnahan's chief of staff, said Thursday the ad
is misleading because it deals only with one abortion procedure
when the bill would outlaw numerous abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan has held news conferences intended to build support for
his veto. Abortion-rights groups earlier started their own campaign
to defend the governor's decision.
</P>
<P>
   The House passed the bill 127-29. The Senate endorsed it 27-6.
An override requires two-thirds majorities in both chambers, which
is 109 in the House and 23 in the Senate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
