A3701 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-FAMILY-PLANNING-KAN &LR;      08-20 0411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-PLANNING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANNED PARENTHOOD TO GET FUNDS WHILE LAWSUIT IS DECIDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL SENTELL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. _ Planned Parenthood offices in Kansas City
and St. Louis can continue getting state family-planning funds
while a lawsuit on the issue unfolds, a circuit judge ruled
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Cole County Circuit Judge Byron Kinder dealt
only with a narrow legal issue. A hearing on whether Planned
Parenthood is getting state funds in violation of a 1999 law is
scheduled for Oct. 29. Any decision is expected to be appealed to
the state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The new law bans groups that get state family-planning funds and
their abortion affiliates from sharing the same or even similar
names, medical facilities, equipment, expenses, business offices or
waiting rooms.
</P>
<P>
   After the law was passed, Maureen Dempsey, state health
director, issued two-month contracts to Planned Parenthood of
Kansas and Mid-Missouri and Planned Parenthood of the St. Louis
Region Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan Cherrick, a special assistant attorney general, told
Kinder that Dempsey erred, that Planned Parenthood has not complied
with the new law and any tax dollars that go to the two groups will
be hard to recover even if his side prevails. State funding to the
groups should be stopped immediately, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they are saying is, `We want to do it our way. We don't
want to follow the law,' '' Cherrick said.
</P>
<P>
   Cherrick was named a special assistant attorney general by
Attorney General Jay Nixon. His hiring stemmed from complaints by
abortion opponents in the legislature who said Nixon had not
adequately defended Missouri laws designed to impose curbs on
Planned Parenthood.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer C. Jaff, an attorney for Planned Parenthood Federation
of America, opposed efforts to stop the funding. Jaff told the
court that the group would return family planning money to the
state if a court ever ordered it to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The state's financial year began July 1. Planned Parenthood is
getting family planning funds under a two-month contract, which
covers July and August.
</P>
<P>
   Jaff said that, since July 1, Planned Parenthood of Kansas and
Mid-Missouri provided family planning services to 280 patients at a
cost of $42,000. The St. Louis office has treated 100 patients at a
cost of $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Kinder also rejected a bid by Planned Parenthood to dismiss the
lawsuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
