<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3702 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKL-PERROT-ONCOURT-HN     08-20 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-PERROT-ONCOURT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
LOS ANGELES _ It was the second game of the best-of-three 1998 WNBA
Finals at Compaq Center. The Comets were facing elimination,
trailing the Phoenix Mercury by 12 points with seven minutes
remaining.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coach Van Chancellor called a timeout, drew up a series of
plays, then preached wildly in an effort to convince the Comets
they still could win the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could tell from the looks on their faces, they weren't
really buying it,'' Chancellor said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Up stepped Kim Perrot, the heart and soul of the team who was
already the source of inspiration, playing despite a severely
sprained right ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``What she said was this,'' Chancellor remembered. ```Hey, we've
got to play. We've got to do a job. We've got to play defense.
We've got to tighten up. We've got to play together. And we've got
to listen to coach.'
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question in my mind, that won us the second
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrot, 32, died Thursday at Houston's M.D. Anderson Cancer
Center after six months of fighting to overcome brain and lung
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor, struggling with his emotions, recalled fondly
Perrot's contributions last August as the Comets pulled out that
game against the Mercury and her value to the team as the Comets
won the WNBA's first two titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had Cynthia Cooper; we had Sheryl Swoopes; we had Tina
Thompson,'' Chancellor said. ``But I don't know if we would ever
have had one, much less two championships, if we had not had Kim
Perrot.''
</P>
<P>
   On the bleakest day in Comets history, Chancellor had no trouble
pronouncing Perrot's name. What a turnaround from the previous 2{
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mispronounced her name 98,000 times,'' Chancellor said,
``and she never once said, `Coach, you say it this way.'''
</P>
<P>
   Their first contact occurred during the Comets' inaugural tryout
camp at St. Thomas High School in the spring of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a point guard on the roster at that time,''
said Chancellor. ``I was completely amazed. Kim was flashy, but she
was so wild, threw the ball anywhere and everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``But she had so many friends. I accused her later of posting
friends about every 15 feet on the court. And they kept asking me,
`You going to keep little Perrot?' I used to kid her about that
after we won the first championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Signed as one of the Comets' two developmental players in 1997,
Perrot eventually beat out Tiffany Woosley and became the starting
point guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``A week after tryouts,'' said Chancellor, ``she told me this:
`You brought everybody to Houston to try to beat me out, from all
over the world, and they couldn't beat me out. I came to training
camp, and you tried to have me beat out again.'
</P>
<P>
   ``All the (rest of the Comets) thought she could be the person.
The only person who wasn't convinced was this hardheaded coach.''
</P>
<P>
   She had won the job as point guard. But Perrot felt she might
never win over the heart of her coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kim used to take it personally when coach would yell at her,''
said Cooper, Perrot's closest friend. ``She didn't understand that
what he was trying to do was make her better so the team would get
better.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the second preseason game in 1997, Perrot had
begun to contemplate leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Her boss, she thought, was too bossy. Her turnovers, Chancellor
thought, were too numerous and too costly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't seem to get it in her head what we were trying to
do in our system,'' Chancellor said. ``But she went from that to
being like a coach on the floor. It was like she knew what I wanted
done before I knew it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to minimize her points. I don't want to minimize
her assists. But Kim Perrot was the best defensive player in the
WNBA in 1997 and '98. Unquestionably. No one was better.''
</P>
<P>
   But when balloting for postseason honors was complete, the 5-5
Perrot wasn't included on the All-WNBA first or second team.
</P>
<P>
   She was overlooked in favor of New York Liberty guard Teresa
Weatherspoon, her friend and collegiate rival at Louisiana Tech, as
Defensive Player of the Year both seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Nonplused over the omission the first time, Perrot was vexed
last summer at being snubbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's understandable,'' said Chancellor. ``There was no one
who could tear down an offense like Kim Perrot.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was like a little gnat buzzing in your ear. Her hands, she
was so quick. Seemed like she was everywhere. Turn your head and
look away just a little bit, she had stolen the ball and was headed
to the other end of the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrot once scored 58 points in a game (the second-highest total
in NCAA history) at Southwestern Louisiana but didn't need to score
to help the Comets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't really need her offense,'' said Chancellor. ``We had
Cynthia and Tina and Sheryl. But, Lord, what she could do on
defense. It was unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just never going to be anyone else quite like Kim
Perrot.''
</P>
<P>
   Comets forward Tammy Jackson said, ``This team has lost a member
of its family. Kim's faith and determination in life will
constantly inspire us both as individuals and as a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her positive attitude will motivate us, not only to win games
but to enjoy life.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. 10 will always be a member of the Houston Comets.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
