r f BC-SERBS-BIAS-KAN &LR;      08-20 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERBS-BIAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS IN U.S. SEE DOUBLE-STANDARD IN AMERICANS' ATTITUDES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MALCOLM GARCIA  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Kan. _ For news about Kosovo, the Rev. Alexander
Bugarin stays up until 11:30 p.m. and listens to the British
Broadcasting System on public radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see it on American TV anymore,'' said Bugarin, of St.
George Serbian Orthodox Church in Kansas City, Kan. ``People here
say the war was a good thing. That's ignorance. They don't know
what they're talking about. The news has been very one-sided.
People just listen to CNN and think that's enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The disparity in coverage _ near-saturation during NATO's air
war in the Balkans, but only scattered reporting in recent weeks _
reflects an American double standard, he suggests. The pain being
inflicted on Serbs by ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, he says, is being
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs were demonized, and now the whole ethnic cleansing
experience is being experienced by them,'' said Wayne Ranick, a
fourth-generation Serb living in Kansas City, Kan. ``That is very
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent report by the New York-based Human Rights
Watch, ethnic Albanians appear intent on expelling Serbs and
Gypsies from Kosovo, using intimidation and murder.
</P>
<P>
   As examples of that abuse, the report cited the gunning down of
14 Serb farmers in a wheat field on July 23, and threats against
three elderly Serb women at gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have documented abuses on all sides,'' said Minky Worden,
electronic media director for Human Rights Watch. ``Between 1989
and 1998 much of the abuses were by Serb para-militaries. Now that
the Kosovo Albanians have come back and the KLA are in a sense
running things, there are abuses from that side.''
</P>
<P>
   Physician Jeff Colyer of Overland Park, Kan., a volunteer with
International Medical Corps, said the conflict has affected relief
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have several Serb physicians and nurses we work with,''
Colyer said. ``We try to be even-handed. But there is a level of
fighting going on now that we are very concerned about. We expect
it to continue for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Jovanka Jovanovich, a Belgrade-born parishioner at St. George's,
said she was not surprised by conditions in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a sheer tragedy what is going on over there,''
Jovanovich said. ``They bombed to protect Albanians, and now
they're moving Serbs out to protect Serbs. It doesn't make any
sense. I have a cousin in Kosovo. Nobody knows what happened to
him. They say, hopefully, he'll turn up some day.''
</P>
<P>
   Bugarin also has family in Yugoslavia. He was born in Pachir, a
small Yugoslavian village near the Hungarian border.
</P>
<P>
   ``The village I grew up in was just 3,500 people,'' he said.
``Mostly farmers. It was a different life. Over there in the
village people worked hard to live. They didn't care much about
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, politics is everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO didn't finish the work for the KLA extremists,'' Bugarin
said of the Kosovo Liberation Army. ``KLA said their work was not
done yet. They are not satisfied with the peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The killing by Albanians is not revenge against the Serbs.
It's what they've been doing for years. They're doing their best to
clean Kosovo of Serbs and Gypsies to make Kosovo Albanian.''
</P>
<P>
   Ranick blamed Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic for stoking
ethnic hatred, but said Serbs should not be blamed for his
policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a Milosevic apologist,'' Ranick said. ``He's an evil
man. But America spent billions of dollars bombing people and
schools and then said it was the people's fault for not changing
the Milosevic government. That leads me to question the humanity of
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Bugarin called the mass Albanian graves found by the
international peace keeping forces in Kosovo the ``tragic acts of
godless people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They were not local Serbs from Kosovo who did this,'' he said.
``The people that committed those rapes and killings are godless.
If the Serb military was forced to do bad things...I'm not proud of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   He recently started a Kosovo relief fund at St. George's. Cash
donations are sent to churches in Kosovo and distributed mostly to
Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   But it will take more than money to bring peace to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to stop the killing is to split up Kosovo,''
Bugarin said. ``This village, Serbian; this village, Albanian. We
have to do this in order to save the people and save the churches
and monasteries and shrines we have.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a small country. We had so many beautiful things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
