<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-INDIANS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANS COOL OFF RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. Sullivan 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The Rangers, except for some inclement weather and a
few scattered cases of food poisoning, had a fabulous stay here on
the shores of Lake Erie.
</P>
<P>
   Winning three of four in any American League city is cause for
some chest-thumping, whether it's against a first-place team or a
team looking at the first pick in next year's amateur draft.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers couldn't sneak out of Cleveland without at least
one reminder why the Indians have one of the best records in the
major leagues and why they've scored more runs than anybody else.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians knocked out starter Mike Morgan with five runs in
the first three innings and avoided getting swept by the Rangers
with an 8-0 victory last night at Jacobs Field. The game was
delayed 89 minutes at the start because of rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight was just a total washout,'' Rangers manager Johnny
Oates said. ``We just never got started.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Karsay and three relievers combined on a seven-hitter as
the Rangers were shut out for only the fifth time this season. The
Rangers still took three of four from the Indians, but they had
their lead cut to 5 1/2 games in the American League West because
the Oakland Athletics defeated Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a very good baseball team,'' outfielder Juan Gonzalez
said. ``To beat them three out of four here is great. This is
probably the first signs of the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, not enhancing his chances of starting against Cleveland
in the playoffs, faced 18 batters and 11 reached base. He allowed
seven hits and walked four, which is a little unusual for someone
who averages 2.7 walks per nine.
</P>
<P>
   However, Roberto Alomar, Jim Thome and Manny Ramirez aren't
average American League hitters, something that got lost during the
first three games of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had pretty good stuff the first two innings,'' Morgan said.
``I went into the third inning and basically didn't execute. I had
a hard time throwing strikes and made a lot of mistakes that
inning. That's the way it's gone for me the last couple weeks. I
haven't been able to make the big pitch to get me out of an
inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan is now 1-2 with a 10.18 ERA in his last four starts,
having allowed 36 hits and 20 earned runs in 17 2/3 innings. He is
39, but the Rangers don't see any signs of fatigue at this point of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's wrong with 39?'' Oates said. ``He's in better shape
than any of my pitchers out there except for \RJohn\S Wetteland.''
</P>
<P>
   There were some moments early that didn't help the Rangers. Ivan
Rodriguez was thrown out trying to steal third base with one out in
the first inning, runners at first and second and Juan Gonzalez up
to bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``My bad,'' Rodriguez said. ``I got a late jump. I've been doing
that all year, I just got a bad jump.''
</P>
<P>
   That cost the Rangers a chance to inflict some damage on Karsay.
Gonzalez followed with a single to left and Rafael Palmeiro walked,
but Todd Zeile fouled out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, still feeling tightness in his left hamstring, also
couldn't catch up to Enrique Wilson's long drive to right with one
out and one on in the second. Instead, the ball hit off his glove
as he reached over his head and went for a double. Richie Sexson,
who had singled, went to third on the play and then scored on Jesse
Levis' grounder to short.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a tough play, line drive over his head,'' Oates said.
``If he makes that play, you say, `Nice play.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Said Gonzalez, ``It's a little bit tough, but the grass is too
wet and I'm concerned about my leg. I'm trying to play but it's
still 90-95 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   This game really came down to the Indians proving they don't
roll over for anybody.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
