<SLUG> BC-ENGINEERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGE, DECLINING MEMBERSHIP BRING THE DEMISE OF SEATTLE ENGINEERS'
CLUB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHUONG LE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A Seattle club whose members built some of the
region's most lasting public-works projects has gone the way of the
slide rule.
</P>
<P>
   Over roasted chicken and potatoes and afternoon chitchat, the
Seattle Engineers Club met for its final lunch Thursday after 87
years of providing professional support to members, many of whom
helped build and shape this region.
</P>
<P>
   The group is calling it quits, blaming dwindling membership on
changing times and a failure to attract ``young blood.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of bittersweet,'' said Adrian Arnold, a former club
president who joined in the 1960s and whose father also held the
post. ``We've become outdated as an organization.''
</P>
<P>
   In its heyday, the Seattle Engineers Club was the professional
group to join.
</P>
<P>
   Members worked on some of the region's largest public-works
projects _ bridges, tunnels and engineering feats _ which continue
to shape the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Club engineers helped design and construct the Alaskan Way
Viaduct, Seattle's downtown bus tunnel, the West Seattle bridges,
Shilshole's breakwater and the electrification of city bus lines.
</P>
<P>
   They were ``people involved in building this city,'' said Joyce
Lem, club president and a bridge engineer with HDR Engineering in
Bellevue. At 42, she may be one of the club's youngest members.
</P>
<P>
   In ``the good ol' days,'' club lunch programs once drew
heavyweights including chief engineers from the city, county, Port
of Seattle and railroads. At its height, the club buzzed with more
than 300 members who met daily for lunches in the Arctic Building
at Third Avenue and Cherry Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a prominent place to network,'' said Arnold, vice
president of Andersen Bjornstad Kane Jacobs, civil and structural
engineering consultants.
</P>
<P>
   The club was established in 1912 to promote fellowship among
local engineers. From 1925 to 1968, the club was on the ninth floor
of the Arctic Building, where a kitchen, dining room and library
played host to engineers who came to unwind during long lunch
breaks.
</P>
<P>
   But little by little, the membership grew older and smaller.
</P>
<P>
   The once-thriving institution has since dwindled to about 60
members, half of whom are retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad thing,'' said Lem, the club's first female
president. ``At the same time, it's difficult to keep something
like this going.''
</P>
<P>
   Times have changed, said 91-year-old John Loux, club treasurer
and one of the club's oldest members. ``Young people aren't too
interested in clubs,'' Loux said. There's no longer an emphasis on
``sitting around and talking about ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   A final farewell bash celebrating the club's history will be
scheduled in late September.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found we were swimming up a stream,'' said club manager Dan
Lyons during lunch at Rock Salt Steak House, formerly Latitude 47,
where the club has held luncheons since 1976.
</P>
<P>
   He said the club knocked on the doors of the city's engineering
companies to recruit new members. The companies were receptive, but
younger engineers weren't, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young engineers tend to be too busy now to come for a lunch,
even when their employers pay,'' said Lyons, 76, a retired
electrical engineer who joined the club in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons proudly rattles off the engineering achievements of his
fellow members.
</P>
<P>
   There's Gordon Snyder, a retired naval architect who was
instrumental in the design of Alaskan and Washington state ferries,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   There's Gerald Van Faasen, a retired district engineer for the
Army Corps of Engineers who helped build the breakwater at
Shilshole Bay and worked on the large Fort Peck Dam in Montana.
</P>
<P>
   There's Roy Morse, a prominent city engineer who oversaw
important developments in Seattle's history. He joined the club in
1950.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, 18 members and guests reminisced and ate lunch during
a 2{-hour program.
</P>
<P>
   The guest speaker was Thom Mullins of Sparling Inc., the
electrical engineers hired to work on the Experience Music Project
at the Seattle Center. His topic was the future of technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
