<SLUG> BC-AIR-QUALITY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INACCURATE PROJECTIONS PROMPTED AVOIDABLE AIR POLLUTION CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFFREY SPIVAK  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Last month, the Kansas City region faced an
air pollution crisis. Federal highway money was going to be cut off
unless the Missouri and Kansas governors sanctioned a
less-polluting gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it turns out, the crisis could have been avoided.
</P>
<P>
   And if it had been avoided, Kansas' governor would not have
approved the reformulated gasoline for this area.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision would have been considerably different,'' said
Mike Matson, spokesman for Kansas Gov. Bill Graves.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan's office would not
speculate on how that office would have reacted.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis stemmed from projections showing that Kansas City's
vehicle traffic would grow to violate federal clean air standards
by 2020. That forced officials to formulate a plan to prevent that
from happening.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the region's air-quality officials revealed the
projections had been recomputed and Kansas City wouldn't violate
the standards after all.
</P>
<P>
   What changed? One method to lower pollution was taken out of the
projections and another method was put in its place. Had that
second method been put in earlier, Kansas City wouldn't have faced
the funding cutoff _ which triggered the governors' action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have avoided all this,'' said Craig Volland, a Sierra
Club representative on a regional air-quality task force.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Flournoy, the Environmental Protection Agency's regional
deputy director over air quality, agreed: ``We didn't have to go
through all the hoops'' to meet air quality standards.
</P>
<P>
   Added Jack Sell, who directs a local coalition of classic car
clubs and who has followed the region's air-quality issue: ``It's
an embarrassment. A fairly coercive situation was created where the
governors had to act quickly, and it was all based on the wrong
numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Reformulated gasoline has sparked national controversy because
one component of the fuel can contaminate ground water. But because
of the two governors' actions, the new fuel is expected to be
available at area service stations next year.
</P>
<P>
   Who's to blame for the crisis? Several government agencies had a
role to play.
</P>
<P>
   This week, officials from all the agencies involved gave
accounts of the crisis' chain reaction. All agreed on these basic
points:
</P>
<P>
   The first link in the chain was the Mid-America Regional
Council, the group that puts together the region's long-range
transportation plan. As part of that plan, the regional council
estimates how vehicle traffic will affect air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the regional council put together a
complicated model of air quality projections. It showed Kansas City
would have too much pollution by 2020.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce pollution levels in its model, the council had a
couple of alternatives. One was to include the impact of
reformulated gasoline, which both Missouri and Kansas already were
considering because of the region's previous violations of federal
clean air standards.
</P>
<P>
   Another alternative was to factor in the impact of EPA's
National Low Emission Vehicle Program. This program, started last
year in selected states, requires automakers to add extra
hydrocarbon emission controls to vehicles. Such vehicles will be
phased into the new-car fleet across the country by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But federal highway officials told the regional council that the
low-emission program wouldn't have much impact on this region's
future pollution projections. Also, the council had trouble
figuring out how to incorporate the program's impacts into its
model.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no rational reason to pursue that analysis, and we
were told not to (by the federal highway officials),'' said David
Warm, the regional council's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   So the regional council only put the reformulated gas
alternative into its model. With the new gas included, Kansas
City's future pollution dropped enough to satisfy federal standards
and state limits.
</P>
<P>
   This solution, however, hit bureaucratic snags. A federal court
decision in March caused the federal transportation department to
dictate a July 28 deadline for regional transportation plans to
meet clean-air standards. If they didn't, the regions could not
proceed with design and engineering work on federally funded
highway projects.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA, though, would not accept the regional council's
projections with reformulated gas unless there was a guarantee that
reformulated gas could come to Kansas City. To achieve this
guarantee, the governors had to act _ by July 28.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the regional council searched for alternatives that
would satisfy the EPA. It plugged the low emission program instead
of reformulated gas into its pollution model.
</P>
<P>
   It showed Kansas City's air satisfied clean air standards.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem was that the EPA wouldn't accept the revised
model's results immediately. The results had to be amended to the
existing transportation plan, which requires formal hearings and
approvals. The process would take 90 days _ well past the July 28
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   By July 28 the two governors were dealing with a deadline
dictated by a federal transportation department and a process
dictated by a federal environmental agency. And the transportation
deadline couldn't be postponed to accommodate changing
environmental considerations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of one of those concurrent processes,'' said Chris
Hess, an EPA air quality conformity analyst.
</P>
<P>
   So facing the prospect of approving reformulated gas or letting
the region lose federal funding, the two governors chose the
gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   But if the regional council had plugged the low emission program
into its pollution projections initially, the governors wouldn't
have faced a deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We opted in reluctantly at best,'' said Matson. ``Had there
not been a deadline, the governor would not have opted in.''
</P>
<P>
   Hess, however, said reformulated gas still could have been
required in the Kansas City area in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the governors) have a responsibility to achieve some
kind of emission reductions (based on the region's previous clean
air violations). Reformulated gas still would have been an issue,
but it took on a more urgent process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
