<HEADER>
A3710 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKL-PERROT-OFFCOURT-H     08-20 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-PERROT-OFFCOURT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID BARRON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The foundation of Kim's Place, a refuge for children facing serious
illnesses, will be the hundreds of thousands of dollars that
well-to-do Houstonians poured into the project at a charity gala
earlier this year.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the spirit of Kim's Place _ and of namesake Kim Perrot, the
Comets guard who died Thursday after a six-month battle with cancer
_ runs deeper and wider than one night.
</P>
<P>
   It was evident as recently as Monday night at Compaq Center,
where Comets fans arrived knowing full well that Perrot was at M.D.
Anderson Cancer Center and that the end was near.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, unbidden, they walked up to Rockets and Comets
employees on the arena concourse. ``I know you work for the
Comets,'' they would say. ``Please take this.''
</P>
<P>
   They were small donations _ five bucks here, 10 bucks there. But
when the workers counted the bills that night, they had received
more than $500 _ just a drop in the bucket toward the $600,000
price tag for Kim's Place but evidence of the love that fans from
every walk of life felt for Perrot.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had a childlike nature that was appealing to all people,''
said Fran Harris, a former Comets teammate who now works as a WNBA
analyst for Lifetime television. ``Everyone can identify with being
a kid for the first time taking up a sport, and that is how she
was, and she wasn't afraid to show it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are afraid to do that. They don't have that
level of openness about them. And that's it; that's it right there.
When you see it, you want to get close to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrot provided ample opportunity for people to do so. She
appeared at more than 100 functions across Southeast Texas in
recent months to promote the Comets, the Rockets and the
construction of Kim's Place.
</P>
<P>
   One of those appearances was at an April 12 gathering in
Beaumont, sponsored by Lamar University and Beaumont's I Have a
Dream program, that attracted more than 600 young people.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was weak and ill, and the children could feel her
sadness,'' said sponsor Regina Rogers. ``But they could feel her
strength, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kim's message was plain and simple: You can do it, and don't
let anybody tell you that you can't,'' said Sarah Joseph, the
Rockets' community services director. ``Kids would thrive on that.
</P>
<P>
   ``She would tell them the story of how she had to fight when she
got to the league and how she pushed her way through the door. They
would see the evidence that this little bitty person made it, and
this gave them hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrot's appeal extended into the stands at Compaq Center,
drawing in people who had never heard of Sheryl Swoopes' NCAA
championship days at Texas Tech or Cynthia Cooper's two stints on
the U.S. Olympic team but adopted Perrot as the symbol of something
new _ a new hero for a new league.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands wore white ribbons during the Monday and Wednesday
night games at Compaq Center. They will, no doubt, still be there
when the Comets return to the arena floor for the WNBA playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever thought up those ribbons for the light, that was
exactly right, because she brightened up many days for me,'' said
Rockets/Comets executive Carroll Dawson. ``We would talk about a
million things. It took me a year to realize this, but I was
getting a lot more work done after she would leave. I mean, she was
just amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   That quality led Dawson to hire Perrot as a Rockets goodwill
ambassador, and it led Rockets owner Leslie Alexander to adopt the
concept for Kim's Place as this year's charitable project for the
Clutch City Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``She (Perrot) took this city and this team by storm, and she
stole our hearts in the process,'' Alexander said Thursday night.
``She is loved by her family, her teammates, the entire Comets
staff and the city of Houston. We all will miss her deeply.''
</P>
<P>
   The sad duty of ministering to the Perrot family Thursday night
fell to Rockets communications executive Angela Blakeney. Today,
Blakeney and other team executives will continue working to make
Kim's Place a reality.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly two-thirds of the $600,000 required to begin
construction and provide initial operating funds has been raised,
although there is no word when construction will begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue,'' Blakeney said. ``It will be built, and it
will be special, and it will always remind people of Kim. Her
determination will live on. She would want the Comets' fans and her
friends and the people who loved her to remember that.''
</P>
<P>
   In lieu of flowers, the Perrot family has asked that memorial
contributions be made to Kim's Place. Checks should be made payable
to Clutch City Foundation and may be sent to 2 Greenway Plaza,
Suite 400, Houston, TX 77046. For information, call 713-627-WNBA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
