u s BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI &LR;      08-20 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS MISFIRE AT FINISH, FALL TO 49ERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ From an entertainment standpoint, it was a
winner.
</P>
<P>
   From an educational standpoint for a rookie quarterback, it was
invaluable.
</P>
<P>
   But when Brock Huard's two-point conversion pass kissed off the
outstretched hand of Michael Black in the end zone with nine
seconds remaining in 3Com Park Thursday night, the Seahawks had
lost their second preseason game in six days.
</P>
<P>
   This one was a wild 24-23 setback to the San Francisco 49ers
that featured an improved performance by the No. 1 offense in the
first half, but fell apart in the second half as Huard threw three
interceptions and special team's miscues led to 14 San Francisco
points in one dizzying 53-second span in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure after I see the film of this I'll feel a lot better
than I did after our first game,'' said new Seahawks coach Mike
Holmgren, whose homecoming was spoiled as the 49ers rallied for 21
fourth-quarter points. ``I liked our effort and hustle and the
first unit tackled well.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers improved to 2-0 as defensive end David Richie, a
former teammate of Huard at the University of Washington, returned
the last of Huard's three interceptions 35 yards for the touchdown
that gave the 49ers a 24-17 lead with 1:51 left to play.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks set the table for Richie's game-winner earlier in
the quarter by allowing rookie Damon Griffin to return a kickoff 96
yards for a score and then, on the ensuing kickoff, giving the ball
back to the 49ers as rookie Charlie Rogers muffed the return to set
up Steve Stenstrom's 22-yard scoring pass to Na'il Benjamin.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren didn't give up on Huard, who in turned refused give in.
The left-hander from Puyallup led the Seahawks from their own 29to
the 49ers' 9 with 24 seconds left. His pass to Mario Bailey,
another former Husky, was incomplete in the end zone. But 49ers
cornerback Wasswa Serwanga was flagged for pass interference,
giving the Seahawks a first down at the 1.
</P>
<P>
   Serwanga broke up Huard's first-down toss to Bailey and Huard
was hurried into throwing an incompletion on second down. On third
down, Huard went to tight Deems May, who beat 49ers linebacker
Anthony Peterson to the back of the end zone to make the catch.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than go for the tie, Holmgren elected to go for two
points to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a chance to get out of here and catch the plane,''
Holmgren joked. ``Seriously, it was something I rarely get to do. I
think it's OK for the players to feel the excitement urgency of
that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Huard played the entire second half, and finished with eight
completions in 16 attempts for 90 yards. But the pass he really
wanted _ the two-pointer to Black _ was thrown behind the former
Washington State running back.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what happens when you get rookies and inexperienced
guys in there, but the fact is we were inches away from winning the
game,'' Huard said. ``It was frustrating and humbling, but I'm sure
we'll learn from it.''
</P>
<P>
   The excitement, and disappointment, of the second half all but
overshadowed an improved first-half performance by the No. 1
offense, which had managed just three points last Saturday night in
a 24-10 loss to the Buffalo Bills in the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Starting quarterback Jon Kitna was much more active and
effective than in the opening loss. He completed 8 of 14 for 118 in
directing four first-half possessions. The Seahawks scored twice _
on a 1-yard leap into the end zone by Ricky Watters and a 33-yard
field goal by Todd Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   On the other two series, the Seahawks moved into 49ers territory
before Kitna's third-down pass to rookie Karsten Bailey was broken
up by 49ers cornerback Darnell Walker and Peterson slapped a
40-yard attempt off the right upright _ his second miss of the
preseason.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks also showed the run-after-the-catch element, so
vital to Holmgren's offense, that was missing in the opener.
</P>
<P>
   On the 12-play, 48-yard drive to Peterson's field goal, Kitna
dumped a 3-yard pass to fullback Reggie Brown, who turned it into a
20-yard gain with a nice run.
</P>
<P>
   On the 10-play, 75-yard drive to Watters' TD, Kitna found Sean
Dawkins with a 9-yard pass, but it turned into a 32-yard gain when
Dawkins ducked from the grasp of 49ers free safety Merton Hanks and
headed upfield.
</P>
<P>
   The special teams and defense also got into the act in the first
half. Charles Jordan returned a punt 18 yards to help set up
Peterson's field goal, and free safety Jay Bellamy intercepted a
Jeff Garcia pass to give the Seahawks the ball on the series that
ended with Peterson's miss.
</P>
<P>
   But it was all wasted when Huard's last pass fell incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sometimes harder to throw to a guy who is wide open,''
Huard said. ``I couldn't get a feel for whether he was going to sit
there or move. Still, it was a poor throw on my part.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
