<HEADER>
A3715 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     08-20 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAC-10 WOULD BE TOPS _ WITH TRADES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We just got back from a listening tour of the Pacific-10
conference. We wanted to hear the coaches share their observations,
speak from their experience, give shape to their hopes and fears.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 college football campaign kickoff is nearly upon us.
What matters most to the coaches at this critical time is of
primary importance to us.
</P>
<P>
   We share their concerns. We are determined to help Pac-10
football reclaim its swagger. We can't wait to make those folks in
the Southeastern Conference eat their haughty cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC the best football conference in the country? That's what
one national publication is claiming. So is Mississippi State
offensive coordinator Sparky Woods, who was quoted as saying, `It
sure is. No doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   We're not so sure. What we learned from listening to the Pac-10
coaches is the conference has an abundance of resources; they just
haven't been allocated right.
</P>
<P>
   With a little bit of deft re-distribution, we see no reason why
Arizona, UCLA and USC couldn't trump Tennessee, Florida and
Georgia. As for poor Vanderbilt, well, under our plan it would be
looking at the Beavers' tails for certain.
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10 schools just need to shift around a few players,
that's all. And don't tell us student-athletes aren't pawns in a
chess game, to be moved all across the board like their
counterparts in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   If the First Lady can claim an unfamiliar state as her own, for
no reason other than it has a job opening that suits her, why
should any athlete with ambition be held back? To paraphrase
Hillary Clinton, what's important is where you stand on NFL draft
day, not how you end up there.
</P>
<P>
   In the game all good politicians have down cold, like a
two-minute drill, the ends justify the means. So why shouldn't it
be so in the games our college athletes play?
</P>
<P>
   We submit that Washington's Joe-of-all-trades, Joe Jarzynka,
ought to be allowed to establish residency at USC. He could handle
the placekicking duties, lend his XXL heart to special teams, catch
a few passes in a pinch and teach R. Jay Soward a thing or two
about true passion in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Trojans senior center Matt McShane, who is on the verge of
losing his starting job to junior Eric Denmon, might feel more at
home in Seattle, where he would fill a huge hole on the Huskies'
offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   The ``J.P. Losman Rule,'' as we'll call it, would allow schools
to swap players with their permission. Kids interested in getting
their degrees and the most out of college would be awarded deferred
status. Everybody else would carry organ cards in their wallets
letting school authorities know their hearts may be transplanted in
another program if their football careers appear dead.
</P>
<P>
   It's a long shot, but maybe USC could persuade quarterback Mike
Van Raaphorst, whose feet are firmly on the ground, to take flight
to Cal to keep the starting job warm for freshman Kyle Boller the
same way he did for Carson Palmer. The Bears, in exchange, could
send down senior cornerback Drae Harris to help plug the holes left
by the losses of Daylon McCutcheon and Rashard Cook.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA has the most explosive group of receivers in the nation,
but no dynamo has emerged yet to spark them. That's why a move to
Westwood could be good for Stanford junior Joe Borchard, who is
stuck behind incumbent starting quarterback Todd Husak.
</P>
<P>
   Jermaine Lewis is a resplendent running back who is dwarfed in
the Bruins' backfield by DeShaun Foster. Lewis could hightail it to
Stanford, which would probably be far enough away to bust out of
Foster's shadow.
</P>
<P>
   Borchard for Lewis would work for us (and most assuredly for
Bruins baseball coach Gary Adams, since Borchard is a bona fide
star in right field).
</P>
<P>
   Tight end Brian Jennings is sitting behind Kendrick Bates and
Todd Heap at Arizona State. A senior, his internal clock has to be
ticking loud enough to bust his eardrums. He could defuse a
potentially bittersweet end to his collegiate career by
establishing residence at Washington State. We're sure linebacker
Steve Gleason's backup, James Price, would shine with the Sun
Devils, given the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Oregon State, owner of an NCAA-record 28
consecutive sub-500 seasons. The Beavers have a new coach with
big-league credentials in Dennis Erickson. They also have a
third-string center, Dustin Janz, who's as big as building blocks
come. The 308-pound sophomore doesn't figure to see much playing
time behind two-time letterman Keith DiDomenico.
</P>
<P>
   Janz, a Glendora High product, could do worse than establish
residency in Berkeley. Heaven knows the Bears' offensive line could
use some bolstering after yielding 58 sacks last year. Cal has a
stalwart center in John Romero, but new offensive line coach Ed
White, we're sure, would be delighted to deploy Janz at either
guard position.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears are stacked with defensive linemen, so maybe redshirt
freshman Zech Whittington or junior Johnny Jackson could be
persuaded to live in Corvallis for a spell. This wouldn't make them
carpetbaggers, even if the Beavers do play on artificial turf. As
Hillary herself explained, ``It's where you stand, not where you
are from.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Pac-10 follows her game plan, the conference could stand
second to none. It would have our vote. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
