<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ABBOTT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER LONG JOURNEY, ABBOTT LIVING HIS DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Others marvel at his resilience. Paul Abbott shakes
his head over the silliness.
</P>
<P>
   With almost religious zeal, he has wandered the countryside in
pursuit of his baseball dream. He has tried six major league
organizations, drawn paychecks in 15 different cities, left a
little of his soul in places such as Kenosha, Visalia and
Elizabethton.
</P>
<P>
   He was 17 when this quest began. He now has three kids, two
rapidly approaching their own teen years.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month from his 32nd birthday, Abbott has settled in
as a starting pitcher for the Seattle Mariners, enjoying his first
extended stay in the big leagues. It didn't have to take this long.
His arm never really betrayed him.
</P>
<P>
   Innocent fun just got in the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took the game for granted,'' Abbott says wistfully, ``which
will never happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Mariners clubhouse, this tall, slender Californian is an
unfailingly pleasant man, smiling and greeting everyone he passes.
With what he's gone through, it's a wonder he keeps his sanity, let
alone his fastball over the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Almost too embarrassing to admit is how he got off track. Pull
up a chair; it's a long story.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a rainout in 1989, Abbott spent several hours in an
air-conditioned motel room in Knoxville, Tenn., vigorously working
the controls on a video game, unaware the muscles were tightening
in his throwing elbow until it was too late. He had strained the
joint.
</P>
<P>
   That still wasn't as painful as his mishap with the Minnesota
Twins during spring training in 1992, another awkward tale to tell.
</P>
<P>
   Passing the time during batting practice, Abbott was hurt
playing ``500'' with fellow pitcher Scott Erickson. The game: 100
points for catching a fly ball, 75 for a one-hopper, 50 for a
two-hopper and 25 for a grounder.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott had a bead on a fly ball when he slipped and fell on his
shoulder, dislocating it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was screwing around,'' he said. ``If it was on the field
(during a game), it would have been a different story. They weren't
too happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Abbott had entered pro baseball full of promise, a kid with a
94-mph fastball, a third-round draft pick from Fullerton, Calif. He
was Orange County Register prep baseball player of the year. He was
offered a scholarship by college baseball power Cal
State-Fullerton. He signed for $50,000, significant money back
then.
</P>
<P>
   He made a steady climb to the majors, joining the Twins briefly
when he was 22. That was easy.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Abbott got two more callups, making 15 appearances
and winning three of four decisions for a Minnesota team that would
win the World Series. He didn't land on the postseason roster, but
his efforts were amply rewarded with a championship ring and
$60,000, a Series half-share.
</P>
<P>
   The Twins, however, gave up on him after the shoulder
dislocation.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott started knocking on doors, signing with the Cleveland,
Kansas City, Chicago Cubs and San Diego organizations. Only the
Indians gave him a major league look, bringing him up for five
games in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cleveland was great to me,'' he said. ``They gave me every
opportunity to make it. I pitched terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   On the rebound, Abbott labored through Omaha, Des Moines and Las
Vegas, unable to make anything happen. He was often close but never
moved up. He tried winter ball in Puerto Rico. One day on the
island, he felt a ligament stretch in his elbow after throwing a
curve. That was a warning sign of worse trouble to come.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated at his banishment to the minors and the reoccurrence
of pain, Abbott took stock of everything. He concluded he hadn't
been serious enough about the game. He changed everything _ eating
habits, workouts, outlook. No more pasta, french fries, Cokes or
video games.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Mariners decided to see what Abbott had
left and signed him in 1997. It was a perfect match, yet there
would be trying times before this relationship was cemented.
</P>
<P>
   At Tacoma, Abbott got off to an 8-4 start, was the Pacific Coast
League strikeout leader, and was close to joining the Mariners. He
felt his elbow throb. This had happened before, but with rest and
treatment he had always come back. This time was different. He sat
out for two months, went to Arizona on a rehabilitation assignment
and tore an elbow ligament.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy John surgery was required, a major ordeal. Abbott never
once thought of giving in.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I struggled and hadn't been throwing the ball well, it
might have been different,'' he said. ``I was too close to have any
negative thoughts.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleven months later, the persistent Abbott was back on the
mound, first in Arizona, then Tacoma and finally with the Mariners.
He went 3-1 in four late-season outings in Seattle, drawing praise
from manager Lou Piniella and earning an invitation to come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell he could pitch up here and win up here with
regularity,'' Piniella said. ``When a pitcher can throw strikes and
command his pitches, he can almost pitch out of any situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Abbott would stumble once more, literally. Preparing himself
for a second shot with the Mariners, he went to Puerto Rico for
winter ball. Covering first base, he tore up a knee, requiring more
surgery and putting him on the sidelines until June.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen Mariners appearances later, Abbott has averted any
calamities. Just the opposite. He has been superb in the bullpen,
effective as a starter, mixing his fastball with a baffling
screwball changeup.
</P>
<P>
   He enters the weekend series against Cleveland with a 4-0 record
and 3.92 earned run average, coming off a career-high
nine-strikeout game at Toronto earlier in the week. He pitches
again on Monday, against the Indians' Charles Nagy.
</P>
<P>
   Long-term, the Mariners are counting on Abbott to provide a
veteran touch to the rotation, to blend in with all the promising
rookies. He's certainly not lacking experience. Or tenacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You figure anybody who's gone through what's he gone through
must have a certain drive to get through any situation,'' Woody
Woodward, vice president of baseball operations, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done it the hard way,'' Mariners pitcher Jamie Moyer
said. ``He can look in a mirror and be happy with himself.''
</P>
<P>
   As Abbott enjoys the long overdue fruits from a sport he won't
abandon, his two sons play baseball and play it well. Trent, 11,
was a member of a California AAU team that recently won a national
championship in Orlando, Fla. Lance, 12, is part of another
California team that will play in a high-profile tournament next
week at Cooperstown, N.Y., site of baseball's Hall of Fame. Both
are pitchers and shortstops, and some of their dad's toughest
critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They rag me when I give up a home run to someone,'' Abbott
said. ``I have to pitch well to keep them off my back.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball runs deep in this family. Abbott married his high
school sweetheart, Yvette, the sister of one of his American Legion
teammates. They have traveled the country together, with the kids
in tow, looking for stability. They didn't buy a house in Fullerton
until 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Should the Abbott boys want to pursue this crazy game on the
professional level, their dad can show them how to do it. Or how
not to do it.
</P>
<P>
   He would advise them to be ready for anything, but mostly to
follow their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, all I tell them is to take it as far as they want
to take it,'' Abbott said. ``They have a lot of talent. but so much
goes into it. It's a hard road.''
</P>
<P>
   He can draw them a map.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 0051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 00:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3718 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-MAGAZINES-MERGER-1STL     08-20 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINES-MERGER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-770(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS OF FASHION PUBLISHING PLAN TO MERGE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ADDS Mademoiselle to first graf.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After a battle between two giant publishing
companies, Walt Disney Co. has decided to sell its Fairchild
Publishing division, which publishes Women's Wear Daily and W, for
$650 million to Conde Nast Publications, the glossy, high-profile
publisher of magazines like Vogue, Vanity Fair, Mademoiselle and
The New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would merge two of the fashion world's most powerful
publishing entities and their distinct publishing styles: the
frills-free but provocative style of Fairchild with the
no-expenses-spared ethos of Conde Nast, a company that will send
luggage overnight by Federal Express if a fatigued fashion editor
does not want to carry it on a flight. A Disney executive said the
agreement would be announced either Friday or Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at both Conde Nast, a unit of Advance Publications,
and Disney confirmed that S.I. Newhouse Jr., the chairman of Conde
Nast, had offered close to $650 million for the company _ which
includes influential trade publications like Women's Wear Daily and
Daily News Record and consumer fashion magazines W and Jane _ and
that Disney executives had accepted Newhouse's offer. Executives at
Hearst Magazines, the other bidder for Fairchild and the publisher
of magazines like Harper's Bazaar and Town &AMP; Country, would not
comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The sale, which is not the largest financial transaction in the
magazine industry in recent years but one of the most influential,
will certainly alter the advertising landscape that preoccupies
magazine publishers. Fairchild publishes Women's Wear Daily, the
influential daily that covers the American fashion industry and
determines the fortunes of designers, and W, one of the
fastest-growing and profitable consumer fashion titles in the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition will assure Conde Nast's continued dominance in
the fashion magazine industry, in part because advertisers will be
offered package rates to advertise in several magazines at once,
including both Vogue and W.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes advertising rates more attractive because Conde Nast
can put W in with the rest of the package,'' said Roberta
Garfinkle, the director of print media at the McCann-Erickson
advertising agency. ``That's the key. And advertisers will be drawn
to that.''
</P>
<P>
   And designers said that the purchase signaled Conde Nast's
continued confidence in the fashion industry. ``I think that,
unlike Harper's Bazaar, which has to change drastically, Women's
Wear and W are not going to change too much, because they are both
so successful,'' Bill Blass said. ``They both have a unique niche
in the fashion industry, and they are unlike anybody else. They are
daring, but with a certain restraint.''
</P>
<P>
   The merging of the companies means that Conde Nast will own more
fashion advertising dollars than any other magazine publisher. That
is an expanding field worth hundreds of millions of dollars in
revenue each year and includes advertising for toiletries and
cosmetics, apparel and accessories, home furnishings and jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   Apparel and accessories advertisers spent $536 million in
American magazines from January to July this year, an increase of
8.8 percent compared with the period a year earlier, according to
the Publishers Information Bureau. Virtually every fashion designer
_ from Calvin Klein to Donna Karan _ is expanding into home
furnishings and supplies, an advertising category that is up 16.2
percent, to $614 million for January to July. And retail
advertising is up 32.2 percent, to $313 million.
</P>
<P>
   The jewel of the deal, W magazine, has taken apparel advertising
from magazines at both Hearst and Conde Nast. In 1998, W boasted
2,005 advertising pages for the year, while Harper's Bazaar _
previously second to Vogue _ lagged behind at 1,542. Vogue led the
field with 2,681 pages of advertising last year, and in second
place, with 2,068 pages, was Elle, published by the
Hachette-Filipacchi Magazines unit of Lagardere Group.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, W generated $33.5 million in advertising revenue for
Fairchild, according to the Publishers Information Bureau, and by
1998 that figure had increased to $87.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear yet what Conde Nast proposes to do with the
numerous trade titles that Fairchild publishes _ small, profitable
publications like Supermarket News, Brand Marketing, Footwear News
and Children's Business _ but one Conde Nast executive said that
the company would prefer to keep them because they turn a profit.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of Los Angeles magazine, also published under the
Fairchild umbrella, is also not clear. A Disney executive said that
Disney might prefer to keep that magazine as a kind of home-town
periodical.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   What is clear is that Disney has wrestled with the issue of
whether to sell Fairchild since 1995, when Disney _ never a
traditional magazine publisher _ acquired Capital Cities/ABC, then
the longtime parent company of Fairchild. And for a while,
Fairchild seemed destined for the auction block: in 1997, Disney
even announced a decision to sell the division, then retracted it a
week later. But Disney has been under pressure recently from Wall
Street to revive its core businesses, such as its theme parks and
movie studio and sell its nonstrategic assets.
</P>
<P>
   The company has already sold some of the noncore assets it
acquired with Capital Cities. In April 1997, Disney sold four
newspapers acquired in the deal, including The Kansas City Star and
The Fort Worth Star-Telegram, to Knight Ridder for $1.65 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, Disney sold the trade publisher Chilton to the
British-Dutch company Reed Elsevier for $447 million and
Institutional Investor Inc. to Euromoney Publications for $142
million.
</P>
<P>
   Cathleen P. Black, the president of Hearst Magazines, was eager
to acquire Fairchild, a Disney executive said. And a deal with
Hearst seemed almost a fait accompli because the Hearst Corp. has
several affiliations with Disney: Hearst television stations are
affiliates of ABC, which is owned by Disney, and Hearst owns 20
percent of ESPN, of which ABC owns the balance. Hearst also owns a
small piece of ESPN magazine. And ABC and Hearst are both investors
in two cable services: Lifetime and Arts and Entertainment. But the
Hearst Corp.'s recent acquisition of The San Francisco Chronicle
for $500 million may have chilled the company's ardor for more
spending.
</P>
<P>
   Spokeswomen for Disney and Hearst declined to comment. Maurie
Perl, a spokeswoman for Conde Nast, said that the company did not
comment on acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   In the famously gossip-prone magazine industry, where glee at
other's misfortune is freely displayed and fortunes rise and fall
with the speed of a season's hemlines, the purchase of Fairchild
further cements the intensifying rivalry between Conde Nast and
Hearst Magazines, which is as competitive as two avid New York
shoppers fighting for the last pair of discounted Manolo Blahnik
slippers at a Seventh Avenue sample sale.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Tina Brown _ who edited two Conde Nast titles, Vanity
Fair and The New Yorker _ signed on with Hearst to produce her new
magazine, Talk. (The other partner in Talk is Miramax Films, a unit
of Disney.) In June, Hearst announced that Katherine Betts, the
fashion news director at Vogue, would become editor in chief of its
primary fashion title, Harper's Bazaar _ and Ms. Betts has hired at
least four of her former Conde Nast colleagues to accompany her in
remaking the magazine, earning the ire of her former co-workers at
Conde Nast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
