<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3723 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-BREWERS-HN     08-20 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BREWERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Pick your poison.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chris Holt, the Astros' starting pitcher in Thursday's 6-5 loss
to Milwaukee, allowed singles to seven of the first 10 batters he
faced.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Barker, speedy but sometimes overaggressive, was caught off
second base after taking too wide a turn. Jeff Bagwell was thrown
out attempting to stretch a single into a double.
</P>
<P>
   With the score tied in the ninth inning, Tim Bogar made an
ill-advised throw to first that sailed over the dugout and became a
souvenir for a fan sitting in the fifth row _ and set up the
winning run for the Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching. Running. Fielding. All contributed to a one-run loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a lot of mistakes, way too many mistakes to win,''
manager Larry Dierker said after the Astros' three-game winning
streak ended.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the things that went wrong in front of a crowd of
22,934 at the Astrodome, the outcome was not decided until the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We battled like crazy,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   After rallying from a three-run deficit, the Astros handed the
game right back in the final inning.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Ochoa singled off reliever Jay Powell (4-3), the Astros'
third pitcher, to lead off the Brewers' ninth. Marquis Grissom
attempted to sacrifice Ochoa to second, only to wind up there
himself when Bogar thought he had a shot at a double play after
taking Powell's throw for a forceout on Ochoa. Bogar's bad throw
set up Kevin Barker's go-ahead single.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have never thrown the ball,'' Bogar said. ``I didn't
have a good grip, but that didn't matter. Honestly, it was just a
bad decision. It came back to bite us.''
</P>
<P>
   Barker, making his major-league debut, also singled in the
third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to fit in and hustle and make it fun,''
Barker said. ``I admit I was nervous. I hadn't been able to breathe
since batting practice. This should help, but I'm sure I will still
be nervous. It will probably last another week.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Banks had a career-high four hits and Grissom went 3-for-5
as Milwaukee pounded Astros pitching for 17 hits. The hit total was
the most allowed by the Astros since Minnesota bashed out 21 on
June 6.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers took batting practice off Holt with seven singles in
the first two innings, five in the second alone.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee took a 2-0 lead in the second on run-scoring singles
by pitcher Scott Karl and Ron Belliard. The Astros tied it in the
bottom of the inning on RBI singles by Tony Eusebio and Holt.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers went up 5-2 in the third. Geoff Jenkins doubled and
advanced to third on a groundout. Grissom followed with a slow
grounder that third baseman Ken Caminiti fielded. Caminiti decided
to go home, Jenkins and Grissom were both safe, and the Brewers
went on to score two more runs in the inning on a double by Banks
and a sacrifice fly by Karl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, the one play that could have turned the whole game was
if Caminiti would have thrown the ball to first instead of home,''
Dierker said. ``That really put Chris in a hole and cost him a
couple of runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Karl, who allowed four runs and seven hits in 6 innings, had two
RBIs. He retired 11 straight Astros at one point.
</P>
<P>
   Holt allowed five runs and a career-high-tying 13 hits in seven
innings, but after the third he limited the Brewers to three hits.
The five earned runs allowed by Holt in three innings were more
than in his previous 22 innings (four).
</P>
<P>
   ``I made some bad pitches, and some good pitches they got hits
off,'' Holt said. ``I wasn't sharp. I didn't have my best stuff. I
weathered it and was able to get through some innings.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, who rallied in the eighth inning Wednesday, pulled
within 5-4 on a two-run homer by Eusebio in the seventh. Eusebio
went 2-for-3 with three RBIs and threw out two runners trying to
steal.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bagwell tied the game with an RBI single off Rocky
Coppinger (2-1) in the eighth but was thrown out trying for second.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were too aggressive,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Astros had a chance to tie or win in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   With closer Bob Wickman on the mound, pinch hitter Bill Spiers
led off with a single and Bogar walked with one out. Pinch hitter
Daryle Ward struck out, and Craig Biggio, who went 0-for-5, lined
to center field as Wickman notched his 25th save.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
