A3725 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-CHARTER-SCHOOLS-2NDTA     08-20 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARTER-SCHOOLS-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ students are coming.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Catholic Diocese of Kansas City-St. Joseph
said parochial schools expected to exceed last year's enrollment of
14,100.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think our enrollment is way, way up,'' said Rebecca
Summers. ``We just have to have the kids in the desks to count
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Trish Harris enrolled her two daughters at Southwest Charter
School this year after trying both the public and private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Harris moved her daughters out of the Kansas City School
District several years ago when she said the quality of teachers
began to decline, the class sizes grew too large and fewer and
fewer parents seemed interested in their children's education.
</P>
<P>
   She then enrolled her daughters at Calvary Lutheran, the same
school she had attended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought my children would always be there,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   But she said the school could not offer the multicultural
environment that she thinks is important for her daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like the kids in the big wide world today need to be
able to look at things from many different perspectives, both
cultural and racial,'' Harris said. ``I think the charter is going
to touch on cultural diversity in a way the private schools
can't.''
</P>
<P>
   The charter schools also are presenting a financial and staffing
challenge for the Kansas City School District.
</P>
<P>
   The district is estimating that it could lose millions of
dollars annually in state school aid that would follow district
students who choose to attend charter schools. State officials
estimate that Kansas City charter schools would receive a maximum
of about $5,100 per pupil based on the school foundation formula.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City charter school officials initially estimated that
the 17 schools would enroll as many as 9,000 students. The schools
have since cut that estimate to about 5,800 after several changed
the number of grades and classes they planned to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Some district schools, such as Foreign Language Academy and
Swinney Elementary, had to rebuild their teaching staffs after many
teachers left for the charter schools.
</P>
<P>
   District officials will not know until school begins Aug. 31
just how many students have abandoned the district for charter
schools. That in turn makes it difficult for officials to assign
the correct number of teachers to buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously you don't want to staff schools and not have
students show up,'' said Eugene Eubanks, a member of the
court-appointed Desegregation Monitoring Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
