<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LITTLE-LEAGUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENDING LITTLE LEAGUE CHAMPS RETURNING TO WORLD SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRISTOL, Conn. _ Playing like the Little League World Series
veterans they are, Eric Campesi and Casey Gaynor led Toms River
East of New Jersey to a 3-0 victory over Middleboro, Mass.,
Thursday night in the East Regional championship game at the A.
Bartlett Giamatti Complex.
</P>
<P>
   Toms River, which won the Little League World Series last year,
will return to Williamsport, Pa., to defend its title. The
eight-team World Series begins on Sunday, when Toms River will play
Phenix City, Ala., at 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Toms River became the third team from the United States to
return to the World Series the year after winning the title. It
will be Toms River's third World Series appearance in all.
</P>
<P>
   Campesi and Gaynor are the only returning players from the team
that defeated Kashima, Japan, to win last year's world title.
Campesi accounted for Toms River's only hit of the game Thursday
night when he punched a two-run homer over the right-field fence in
the third inning. Gaynor, who was all but unhittable in this
regional tournament, struck out 10 batters, including five of the
last six he faced.
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor, who pitched in last year's victory over Japan, allowed
only one hit Thursday night _ a second-inning single _ in pitching
a six-inning complete game and earning his fourth victory of the
regional. He surrendered no runs and four hits and struck out 39
batters in his four appearances.
</P>
<P>
   It was immediately evident that this would be no offensive
free-for-all. Both pitchers _ Gaynor and Middleboro's Sam Cole _
were among the biggest players on the field, and they threw like
it, humming fastballs by what seemed to be an endless stream of
batters. Cole opened the game by striking out Campesi and Gaynor as
the Toms River faithful sat in stunned silence. Cole would go on to
strike out 11 batters, including seven in the first three innings.
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor was nearly as dominant, striking out two in the first
inning. When he returned to the mound in the bottom of the second,
six of the game's nine batters had gone down on strikes, so a
feeling of uneasiness raced through the Toms River bleachers when
Middleboro's Kyle Jones ripped a single to center field on Gaynor's
first pitch. But the next three batters grounded out.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the game's turning point. After striking out Chris
Cunningham in the third, Cole walked Chris Fontenelli. With the top
of the lineup batting, the New Jersey fans grew excited, sensing
something special. Cole struck out Zack Delvento for the second
out, but Campesi then surprised everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Catching a Cole fastball with the fat part of his bat, Campesi
hit a homer over the right-field fence 200 feet away. The
opposite-field shot cleared the fence by only a couple of feet and
sent Campesi dancing around the bases to the cheers of the Toms
River fans.
</P>
<P>
   With Gaynor appearing to grow stronger as the game proceeded,
Middleboro could do nothing but lament. When Gaynor struck out the
side in the bottom of the fifth, the team and crowd from
Massachusetts seemed to know the game was over.
</P>
<P>
   Middleboro's players looked defeated when taking the field in
the top of the sixth and last inning, and Toms River added an
insurance run. Delvento walked, moved to second on a grounder and
stole third. He scored to make the score 3-0 after a short popup by
Gaynor landed in front of Ryan Seaman, the Middleboro first
baseman. Unsure what to do, Seaman grabbed the ball, turned his
back and first stepped on the bag, allowing Delvento to sprint home
ahead of his throw.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
