<HEADER>
A3728 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-CHARTER-SCHOOLS-2TAKE     08-20 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARTER-SCHOOLS-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEREST IN CHARTER SCHOOLS CONTINUES TO GROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Kansas City's experiment with charter schools
begins in earnest this fall, as 15 of the independently governed
schools are scheduled to be operating by the end of September.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at several charter schools report strong interest from
parents and say they are pleased with early enrollment numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the schools, however, also are experiencing
last-minute problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of chaotic,'' said Lisa Mallow of the Learning
Exchange. The nonprofit educational group is tracking and providing
guidance for the Kansas City charter school movement.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at one school, Banneker Charter Academy of Technology,
continued to negotiate for a permanent location as late as this
week, less than a month before the school's scheduled Sept. 13
opening. The school's principal said Friday that Banneker would
operate out of several temporary locations in churches and
community centers if a permanent site was not available.
</P>
<P>
   Several others have pushed back their opening dates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to be sure everything was done on time so there
wasn't chaos when the school opened,'' said Gina Valente, director
of operations for Scuola Vita Nuova, which moved its opening from
Sept. 7 to Sept. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Some schools were still awaiting word this week on whether the
Kansas City School District will provide them with cafeteria
service.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, many of the school officials are unsure of just how
much state money they will receive and when, making it difficult to
budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I would say there is confusion,'' said Gerri Ogle, the
state Department of Elementary and Secondary Education official
charged with overseeing the finances of charter schools. ``I
suspect they're not all clear on their budgets.''
</P>
<P>
   And some wonder whether it might all be for naught if a
challenge to the state law authorizing charter schools proves
successful.
</P>
<P>
   A lawsuit filed by the St. Louis Board of Education seeks to
block the opening of the first charter school in that city. The
lawsuit also alleges that the law authorizing charter schools is
unconstitutional. A hearing is scheduled for Aug. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Observers at the Learning Exchange and elsewhere said the Kansas
City problems were characteristic of those found in other states
when charter schools began their first year of operation.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Allen, president of the Washington-based Center for
Education Reform, a nonprofit group that advocates school choice,
partly blamed the first-year problems on confusion of local and
state officials over how to deal with the new schools and the haste
of grass-roots organizers to get the schools open.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things that charter schools have to do right now are
things the public schools have had years to plan or perfect,''
Allen said. ``There tend to be an awful lot of last-minute snafus
not due to mismanagement of anybody in the charter, but just
because that's the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the problems, the allure of the charter schools is
proving powerful for many Kansas City parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't only about my son,'' said Linda Fewell, parent of a
sixth- grader at the Kansas City Foreign Language Charter School.
``This movement has the potential to benefit generations to come.
That's an exciting opportunity and certainly makes it worth seeing
through any of the challenges that have come up.''
</P>
<P>
   Fewell, a former Kansas City School District parent, opted for a
charter school because of an atmosphere of high expectations and
the opportunity to more closely track and affect her child's
academic performance.
</P>
<P>
   Charter schools are part of a national education reform movement
designed to offer alternatives to failing public schools and
expensive private schools.
</P>
<P>
   The state has approved 17 charter schools for Kansas City. Two
are not scheduled to open until 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Charter schools typically receive the same amount of state money
per student as any public school but are free of a district's
central office and much of the state's regulatory control. They are
governed by an independent board.
</P>
<P>
   The schools cannot charge tuition, must observe all federal
anti-discrimination laws and meet health, safety and accessibility
regulations. All students must have an equal opportunity to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Under Missouri law, as much as 20 percent of the school's
teaching staff can be exempt from state teacher certification
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   As of April more than 1,205 operating charters were serving
300,000 students in 36 states and the District of Columbia,
according to the Center for Education Reform.
</P>
<P>
   Actual enrollment figures for Kansas City charters will not be
known until several weeks after the schools open, but Kansas City
charter school operators report few problems filling seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are getting a lot of interest, especially with the
kindergarten and first grade,'' said Vivian Roper, principal at the
Tolbert Community Academy.
</P>
<P>
   Roper said her school was considering whether to offer more
classrooms for kindergarten and first grades and fewer for second
and third grades than initially planned. Roper and others
speculated that parents of older students might be reluctant to
pull them from their current schools.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the grade level changes, Roper said she expected the
Tolbert charter school to meet its projected enrollment of 225
students.
</P>
<P>
   Several charters reported enrolling large numbers of former
private and parochial school students.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's parents who want a private school approach to education
but are finding it difficult to pay that price,'' Roper said.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear, however, from which schools those students are
coming. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 0058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3729 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ALCOA-REYNOLDS-1STLD-     08-20 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALCOA-REYNOLDS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALCOA AND REYNOLDS REACH MERGER AGREEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert share prices in 2nd graf; rewrites 12th graf and
corrects Alcoa to No. 1 from No. 2; strengthens lede graf.)  (th) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alcoa Inc., the world's oldest and largest aluminum company,
announced Thursday that it had reached a definitive merger
agreement with the No. 3 producer, Reynolds Metals Co., in a
relatively swift negotiation that left some Reynolds shareholders
grumbling.
</P>
<P>
   In an all-stock deal, Reynolds' shareholders will receive 1.06
shares of Alcoa for each Reynolds share. At Wednesday's closing
price of $66.875 for Alcoa, this deal would be valued at around
$4.4 billion, or $70.8875 a share for Reynolds' stockholders. Alcoa
shares fell $1.6875, to $65.1875, Thursday, and Reynolds was off
$2.6875, to $65.5625. While accepting this deal, however, Reynolds
left open the door for another buyer to come along, as both
companies agreed to allow Reynolds to solicit takeover bids for the
next 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Alcoa, which made its first bid for Reynolds last week, agreed
to this somewhat unusual clause because Alcoa executives believed
that Reynolds would find no other bidders, people close to the
merger talks said.
</P>
<P>
   The 30 day shopping-window allows Reynolds, which has been
looking for a potential buyer for nearly a year now, to placate
shareholders who have been angry at Reynolds' management for not
selling the company earlier and for more money.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the charge against Reynolds is Richard Grubman, managing
director at Highfields Capital Management, a Boston firm that owns
6 percent of Reynolds. In a letter to the Reynolds' board Thursday,
Grubman said, ``You have allowed Alcoa to steal the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Grubman was especially angered by a rejection last March by
Jeremiah J. Sheehan, the chief executive of Reynolds, of a
1.42-a-share exchange offer from Alcoa. At the time Sheehan was
telling shareholders that no one was interested in acquiring
Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your behavior is reprehensible,'' Grubman wrote, adding, ``You
sold us out.'' Grubman also accused Reynolds of ``squandering $2
billion of shareholder value'' and said that Reynolds ``effectively
lied to shareholders'' and ``has reached a new low in corporate
governance.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Grubman nor Reynolds would comment on this letter
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-day solicitation window also allows McCook Metals, owned
by the Chicago investment firm Michigan Partners, to make a bid, if
it is interested. Last week, McCook wrote to Reynolds expressing
interest in topping Alcoa's bid, but provided no details.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers close to the deal said McCook did not seem serious:
``There was no price, no financing, no nothing. It was all air,''
one said. Calls to McCook Metals were not returned Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, to make it difficult for anyone to halt this merger, the
agreement between Alcoa and Reynolds also contains a $100 million
break-up fee, which would increase the cost of acquiring Reynolds
by about $1.50 a share.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal is completed, Alcoa would remain the world's No. 1
aluminum producer. APA, a new company to be created by the
three-company, two-continent merger of Alcan Aluminium Ltd. of
Canada, Pechiney in France and Alusuisse Lonza Group of
Switzerland, would have greater revenue. The three-way $17.6
billion merger was announced last week and would create a huge
global competitor for Alcoa, with projected revenues of $21.6
billion.
</P>
<P>
   An Alcoa-Reynolds merger would create a company with $20.5
billion in projected revenues and 120,000 employees in 36
countries. But nearly all those revenues would be derived from
aluminum production, while around $4 billion of APA's projected
revenues would come from non-aluminum assets. This merger wave was
brought on by global overcapacity for aluminum and prices that have
plunged to five-year lows.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal is good for Alcoa, good for Reynolds shareholders
and good for the aluminum industry,'' said Richard Aldrich, an
analyst with Lehman Brothers. ``With fewer players, there will be
less redundant capacity, which is a long-term plus for the
industry.'' Aldrich dismissed Grubman's complaints as ``20-20
hindsight'' and said he doubted another buyer would come along, but
cautioned that ``anything is possible.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Alcoa and Reynolds executives said they expected that combining
the two companies would realize around $200 million in cost savings
_ a number some analysts said was low _ and they expected antitrust
problems to be minimal.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious antitrust problem is that the two companies
would represent more than 50 percent of the smelting capacity in
the United States, although analysts say the companies will
probably argue that smelting, a low-margin commodity business,
should be viewed as a global industry, and not as a domestic one.
</P>
<P>
   Other problem areas are minimal. Reynolds is best known for
making such consumer products as aluminum foil and beverage cans,
while Alcoa makes aluminum for heavy industries like planes and
autos. While both companies serve the auto industry, Alcoa is
bigger in castings like engine blocks, while Reynolds makes
aluminum components for wheels.
</P>
<P>
   The two overlap in producing alumina, a compound from which
aluminum is produced. In 1997, Reynolds sold an Alabama rolling
mill to another buyer, after the government rejected its sale to
Alcoa. As a result, say analysts, another antitrust impediment was
removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean that there won't be some asset divestiture,''
said James Kelleher, an analyst with Argus Research. ``But I do
believe that the companies are complementary. Alcoa's management
has said that Reynolds begins where Alcoa stops and I agree.''
</P>
<P>
   Alain J.P. Belda, Alcoa's chief executive, said, ``The new
company will be better positioned to address the ongoing
globalization of the metals industry and the new competitive
landscape this is creating.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds' chief executive, Sheehan, said, ``Reynolds
shareholders will receive an attractive price for their shares and
still have the opportunity to participate in the upside potential
of the combined company.''
</P>
<P>
   John Tumazos, an analyst at Sanford Bernstein, said the proposed
union ``creates no problems, only opportunities.'' His only concern
was that the automakers, as major users of aluminum, might seek to
lock in long-term, low-price aluminum supply contracts from the
combined company to protect themselves from any potential
monopolistic pricing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
