<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-FINE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAL-MED ORDERED TO PAY $250,000 FINE FOR EMERGENCY-ROOM CLAIM
DENIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Washington state Insurance Commissioner's Office
on Thursday fined QualMed Washington HealthPlan Inc. $250,000 for
improperly denying emergency-room claims, ending an eight-month
investigation into the handling of emergency room visits.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement followed a major investigation by Commissioner
Deborah Senn into emergency-room denials by QualMed and three other
large Washington state health insurers: Regence BlueShield, Premera
Blue Cross and Aetna U.S. HealthCare.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the denied claims reviewed involved people with broken
legs or head wounds, and people who were taken to an emergency room
by paramedics.
</P>
<P>
   The fine, one of the largest ever against an insurance company
in Washington, is designed to set an example so other carriers will
not deny appropriate claims, Senn said at a news conference
Thursday. QualMed said no patients were denied emergency care and
called the problem ``administrative.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation was triggered by complaints from emergency
room physicians, who said their patients were becoming hesitant to
seek emergency treatment for fear their claims would be rejected.
The physicians also said dealing with paperwork for denied claims
was eating up a growing percentage of their time, taking them away
from patient care.
</P>
<P>
   Under the state's ``prudent layperson'' emergency-care law,
insurers are required to cover the cost of screening and
stabilizing emergency-room patients when a prudent layperson would
have sought emergency treatment under the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The law went into effect Jan. 1, 1998. The Insurance
Commissioner's Office looked at claims submitted between then and
April 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Of 100,000 claims examined, about 15 percent had been rejected,
and more than half of those denials were illegal, Insurance
Commissioner spokesman Jim Stevenson said.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance reimbursement practices have been drawing increasing
fire from consumers, physicians and state officials. Two weeks ago
at an Insurance Commissioner's hearing in Spokane, a doctor told of
a patient who died after being admitted to a hospital with a heart
problem. The claim was rejected a few days later because the
patient was ``not sick enough to be in the hospital,'' Stevenson
said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the fine, the QualMed settlement changes the
insurer's contract so that the carrier no longer has sole
discretion on whether to pay for emergency treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The new language provides patients and their physicians with
more say in the final decision.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, QualMed said: ``It is important to note that at
all times, QualMed Washington members had, and continue to have,
full access to emergency room care. The issue in question was
administrative and dealt with how claims were processed by QualMed
Washington _ after emergency care was provided.'' QualMed has more
than 132,500 subscribers and is the fifth-largest insurer in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Regence BlueShield, Premera Blue Cross and Aetna U.S. HealthCare
all said Thursday they believed they were in compliance with the
law governing payment for emergency care but were cooperating with
Senn's office to resolve the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Senn said she hoped the other three carriers will follow
QualMed's lead and settle their own cases in favor of consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a settlement that truly serves the state's insurance
consumers because it underscores consumer protections that already
exist in state law,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Regence BlueShield said its own internal review
of 90,000 emergency room claims for a four-month period in 1998
showed that less than 14 percent were denied. Of those denials,
about half were denied because they were duplicate claims or
because coverage was not in effect at the time of the service.
</P>
<P>
   Another .01 percent were denied for not having referral
information. An even smaller number _ .001 percent _ were denied
because the member's condition was deemed not something a prudent
person would consider a medical emergency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very important to emphasize that the number of emergency
room claims that are ultimately denied by Regence BlueShield is
very small,'' the company said in a statement. ``Our members should
not be concerned about whether their emergency room claims will be
paid.''
</P>
<P>
   Premera Blue Cross also defended its claims record.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than 90 percent are approved the first time they are
submitted, and of those that are denied, many more are paid once
more information is provided,'' said Premera spokeswoman Clara Webb
Kinner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
