<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MABIKA A LONG WAY FROM HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ When she was around 12 years old growing up
in Kinshasa, Congo, formerly Zaire, she swept the dusty basketball
court at the nearby outdoor stadium just to get a chance to dribble
the ball. That was her reward, but it was worth it for the
youngster who later dreamed of playing with the big girls.
</P>
<P>
   Mwadi Mabika didn't have to wait too long. She not only got her
chance to play with the big girls, but overshadow them to become
the youngest member on the national team at 14 as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   She has gotten used to being the youngest player on many teams,
but her extraordinary athletic ability, raw talents and unlimited
potential always kept her a notch above the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``My home was close to the basketball court,'' Mabika said.
``That was like my favorite, to go play basketball. I was always
watching the girls play. I wasn't on a team, but I know basketball.
One day a coach on that team told me that `You have to come play.
You have to come play on the team, You know how to play.' I said,
`No. I don't want to play.' After a year I decided to go (play).''
</P>
<P>
   She jumped from the third to the first team on the city team
within a year.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't always that easy for Mabika. She had to shed some
tears and convince the older players that she wasn't a pest hanging
around the basketball court. Sometimes the big girls didn't give
Mabika the ball to bounce around and she would run home crying.
When it happened too often, her mother turned a wooden box into a
makeshift basketball rim and hung it by the window and rolled
together some cloth to act as a basketball. At home, Mabika was
free to shoot at will.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned to shoot the ball and learned how to be a winner,''
said Mabika, who played professionally in the African Championship
League and was the most valuable player when she was 16.
</P>
<P>
   Things haven't change much. Now arguably the most
athletically-gifted player in the WNBA, Mabika has the free will to
shoot the ball at her new home with the Los Angeles Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   At 20, she was the league's youngest player when she won a spot
on the team through tryouts in 1997. The year before she was in
Atlanta competing in the Olympics. Her national team finished last,
but she remembers fondly scoring 20 points against the U.S. squad
while being guard by Houston's Sheryl Swoopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a shooter and a scorer,'' said Lisa Leslie, the Sparks
center and USA national team member. ``Even then you could tell she
was very raw. She didn't necessarily have an understanding of the
game, but she could shoot and I think that's something she'll tell
you today, she loves to shoot the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   It was then that the 5-foot-11 forward-guard heard the rumors
about the soon-to-be WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   Many members of her team were reluctant to return home where a
civil war was engaged. But Mabika went home with the hopes of
returning to the United States to play in the WNBA. Thanks to
fellow countryman and Atlanta Hawks center Dikembe Mutombo, who she
met while playing on the national team when she was 16, she
eventually received her visa after being turned down once.
</P>
<P>
   She was intimidated when she arrived at the Sparks tryout to see
300 players vying for the couple of spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough,'' said Mabika, who will return to her country
after the season for the Olympic trials. ``There was like 300
people - all these tall girls. I didn't have any muscles when I got
here. I was like, `God, they're going to kill me.' But I just
stayed confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie can attest.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the tryouts, she outhustled people for rebounds by jumping
over them and shooting and scoring, taking off from the free throw
line. I think what's amazing is she is really starting to learn the
game. In three years, you could see her improvement,'' Leslie said.
</P>
<P>
   Mabika, whose English is also improving, earned a starting role
at the small forward five games into last season, but this year she
has played mostly shooting guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year I put her in a situation where she has a lot of
freedom on the court,'' Sparks coach Orlando Woolridge said. ``She
understands that as long as she rebounds, plays good defense,
distributes the basketball, offensively she has the freedom to do
whatever she wants and she flourishes under that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mabika leads the team is assists (3.3), is second in scoring
(11.3 points) behind Leslie, and third in rebounds (4.8). She'll
never forget the off-center shot she took to tie the score and send
the game into overtime against New York. She was so high in the
air, only she knew that the ball would fall in. The Sparks
eventually won the game.
</P>
<P>
   Mabika's mother, Lunkeba Tezo Helene, doesn't miss any of them
now. She received a visa and reunited with her daughter last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so happy to see her play,'' she said. ``She's playing a
good season. Now she is so happy because I am here. She doesn't
have to cook. I cook for her, I clean her clothes for her. I do
everything for her and she's very, very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks are 19-11 and in need of one victory to gain
home-court advantage in the single-elimination game against
Sacramento next Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 0108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
