<SLUG> BC-POLICE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL FINDS HUGE FLAWS IN HOW SEATTLE POLICE INVESTIGATES ITSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN SNEL AND KIMBERLY A.C.WILSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ An independent panel found major flaws in the way
Seattle police investigate themselves, recommending that a civilian
run a new office to pursue allegations of police misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   In a 37-page report issued Thursday by the panel after three
months of study of the Seattle Police Department, its members
offered a blueprint on implementing the most rudimentary police
standards.
</P>
<P>
   The document called for Police Chief Norm Stamper to declare
that lying, cheating and stealing will no longer be tolerated in a
department wracked by waning public confidence. And to win back the
public's trust, the department should clean up shoddy
record-keeping on misconduct investigation cases, respond better to
misconduct complaints and allow for face-to-face interviews of
accused police officers during inquiries _ a practice currently not
allowed.
</P>
<P>
   The four-member panel stopped short of suggesting a full-fledged
citizen watchdog committee, citing a lack of ``systemic''
corruption in the department. Though it chided Stamper for
delegating ``too much of his responsibility'' on investigations, it
did not recommend firing the beleaguered chief.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, panel members called for a hybrid option that blends a
civilian director overseeing existing police staff to run the
department's new Office of Public Accountability (OPA). Stamper
would hire the civilian investigations director, who in turn could
hire another civilian or police officer as second in command over
the eight-member investigations unit and auditors office.
</P>
<P>
   Allyson Collins, author of a recent book on police
accountability and senior researcher for Human Rights Watch, called
the recommended OPA an ``unusual set-up'' that is somewhat ``better
than absolute inaction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of another U.S. city that has tried to introduce
civilians over police in an advisory role,'' she said. ``Two things
are key to making it work: First, who will be made director of the
OPA and second, whether they'll blow the whistle on any discovered
wrongdoing.''
</P>
<P>
   The OPA would act as an umbrella over the Internal
Investigations Section, the police office under fire for failing to
properly investigate misconduct allegations and for allegedly
erecting the ``Wall of Silence'' to protect fellow police officers.
</P>
<P>
   For the recommendations to go into effect, Police Department
leadership, union representatives and the Seattle City Council
would have to sign off on it. Ongoing collective bargaining
negotiations could soon touch on a little-known policy in the
department unearthed in the report that allows officers accused of
misconduct the right to not be interviewed face-to-face during
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, appointed by Mayor Paul Schell and chaired by retired
King County Superior Court Judge Charles V. Johnson, took 90 days
to craft the report, released amid troubled times for Stamper. He
has overseen the 1,260-member force since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The report described an investigations process that lacked
consistency: ``No single person in the department makes the key
decisions regarding discipline. Employees describe cases in which
seemingly arbitrary decisions have been made regarding whether to
initiate an investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, the report recommended adding more training on
ethics and procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's significant reform,'' said panel member Jenny Durkan, a
Seattle attorney and former executive counsel to the governor.
``It's learning from other people's mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Rank-and-file officers and community members concurred, but
reaction to the report varied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on, these problems in the department may not be as bad as
problems in New Orleans or Albuquerque, but I would have expected
tougher recommendations as far as the leadership of the department
goes,'' said a West Precinct patrol officer who asked not to be
named.
</P>
<P>
   Another officer, also speaking on condition of anonymity,
offered a different perspective. ``I haven't seen the actual report
but from what I've heard, it ought to put some of the (recent) bad
talking about the Seattle Police Department to bed.''
</P>
<P>
   Harriett Walden, a longtime activist for police accountability,
said the panel's recommendations to restore integrity and personal
responsibility to the Police Department were ``a step in the right
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not unhappy _ or I won't be if we can get these
recommended actions implemented,'' she said after the news
conference in the mayor's office at which the panel officially
released the document to the public.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone was pleased.
</P>
<P>
   The panel outlined 23 major recommendations on oversight,
leadership training and rules, but failed to add a layer of
oversight to watch over the chief, said Councilwoman Tina
Podlodowski, chairwoman of the council's public safety committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a deep disappointment. That's one thing the council has
been screaming about,'' Podlodowski said. ``I'm hoping we can be a
little tougher than this group. The council has to address who is
watching the chief.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the panel's proposal, Stamper would remain accountable
only to the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   The chief was charged with underplaying misconduct cases after
revelations this year that at least eight officers, including an
internal-investigations sergeant, failed to report allegations that
a police detective stole $10,000 from the home of a city resident
who was killed in a shootout with police in October 1996. The money
was returned the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Stamper called the panel's suggestions ``bold and insightful,''
but declined to comment on endorsing specific remedies outlined in
the document. Likewise, Schell also would not bless any of the
specific reform proposals, other than to say ``one complaint is one
too many.''
</P>
<P>
   Stamper acknowledged that it will be a challenge to weave the
proposed reforms into the ongoing contract talks, but said that he
will try to hammer the measures into the labor pact.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations have several hurdles, including gaining
approvals from the city council and the Police Officers Guild. The
panel outlined a dozen suggested policies the police union would
have to approve in this year's contract negotiations, talks that
already have snagged on reform ideas Stamper has proposed.
</P>
<P>
   Current policies that trouble the panel were complaint
procedures that hamper effective misconduct investigations,
including a rule that calls for misconduct investigation files to
be destroyed three or four years after an inquiry is completed.
</P>
<P>
   The panel reserved its harshest language for these procedures,
tartly noting that Seattle's is perhaps the only law enforcement
agency in the nation that does not conduct in-person interviews of
employees that come before its internal investigations department.
Instead, the agency must submit written interview questions in
advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This current policy affords Seattle Police Department
employees more rights than those granted to citizens,'' the report
says. ``In essence, current policy obliges the Department to
conduct most investigations of misconduct by correspondence.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, head of the panel, was dismayed by that policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could not find any other police department that does
that,'' Johnson said. ``In fact, we asked the lawyer for the union,
and he was unable to name any other place that does it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the King County Sheriff's Office conducts internal
affairs interviews in person, said sheriff's spokesman John
Urquhart.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle policy has been in place only a few years, said
panel member Durkan, but already ``an erosion of management
function has occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   In its defense, the police guild has shown a willingness to
discuss the issue at the bargaining table, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. J.D. Miller, guild vice-president and a former IIS
investigator, who said he hadn't read the report closely,
nevertheless questioned whether the practice had been accurately
portrayed in the panel's report.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't appear accurate,'' Miller said, adding ``I would
disagree with the statement that we have additional rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The city council will discuss the report Aug. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Post-Intelligencer reporter Elaine Porterfield
contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
