<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3744 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-TRK-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     08-20 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRK-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FranBlinebury
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SEVILLE, Spain _ For the largest portion of a career that spanned
nearly two decades, Merlene Ottey was the Silver Queen, an identity
that was equal parts homage to her many accomplishments and
reminder of the frustration from so many second-place finishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The margin between the ultimate joy and the ultimate
disappointment is so small,'' she once said.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps getting larger because of her advancing years, which
might go some way toward explaining why the 39-year-old Jamaican
star withdrew from competition on the eve of the World Track and
Field Championships when it was confirmed she had tested positive
for an anabolic steroid at a meet six weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ottey, of course, released a statement expressing shock and
surprise, but the results from a second sample soon will be in
house, and if, as expected, it too is positive, then we will find
out if her imagination is as fast as her feet in offering an
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   When tests caught U.S. sprinter Dennis Mitchell in the chemical
web of an abnormally high testosterone level, he made the argument
before the appeals board of the U.S. federation that it was the
result of excessive drinking and sex with his wife. Maybe the first
time monogamy has been held up as too much of a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   But what sounds like fodder for endless one-liners is no
laughing matter to the International Amateur Athletic Federation,
the sport's ruling body, as another drug scandal threatens to
overshadow the events in the World Championships, second only to
the Olympic Games in terms of prestige.
</P>
<P>
   It is an old story. A tired story. But a story line that track
and field has been unable to shake for more than a decade and now
shows fresh legs entering the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of talking about Marion Jones' quest for four gold
medals here and at the 2000 Olympics in Sydney, instead of talking
about Maurice Greene's setting a world record in the 100 meters,
instead of talking about the continuing feats of the amazing
Michael Johnson, all conversations are coming back to what's new
and cooking in the lab these days.
</P>
<P>
   For it is not only a case of Ottey and Mitchell in the cross
hairs. World high-jump champion Javier Sotomayor of Cuba was
suspended following a positive test for cocaine at the Pan American
Games. Former British Olympic champ Linford Christie and teammate
Doug Walker have been suspended for showing evidence of nandrolone,
the anabolic steroid found in Ottey.
</P>
<P>
   Ato Boldon, the defending world champ in the 200 who is sitting
out the meet because of a leg injury, recently claimed his sport is
at an all-time low.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in Monaco, and in 24 hours, I see Dennis Mitchell get
banned, Linford Christie gets busted, Sotomayor gets busted and
you've got Ben Johnson wandering around the hotel lobby,'' Boldon
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian Johnson is, of course, the poster boy for steroid
abuse, having been stripped of his gold medal in the 100 meters at
the 1988 Olympics in Seoul. He was banned for life after a second
positive test in 1993 but has been hanging around the fringes,
hoping to get back on the track until the IAAF rejected him
permanently this week.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is gone, but his legacy lives on in a new generation of
athletes who are willing to break all of the old rules.
</P>
<P>
   One school of thought says the recent rash of positive tests
could be the result of athletes unwittingly taking strength
supplements that contain banned substances. Others question the
tests themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, over the past couple of weeks, having
so many sudden cases, I'm not 100 percent sure I'm confident in the
testing procedure,'' Jones said. ``To say yes, I'd be lying.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Ottey will come up with a perfectly reasonable or highly
implausible explanation for her test results. Perhaps she'll get a
Johnny Cochrane sound-alike to make her case in court: ``If the
urine sample isn't fit, then you must acquit.''
</P>
<P>
   But more likely, where there's smoke, there's fire. Remember,
until the incomparable Carl Lewis came along and stretched out an
amazing career over four sets of Olympics (1984-1996), the sprints
were always a young man's (or woman's) game. Virtually no one
competed into their 30s.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the big money that's at stake, you have Ottey, 39,
Christie, 39, and Mitchell, 33, all pushing at the limits, maybe
willing to do anything to get a competitive edge.
</P>
<P>
   It's a new story, an old story and one from which track and
field cannot seem to run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
