<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MARTINEZ: STORM BEFORE THE CALM 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ You can call him Pedro or you can call him Lata de
Aceite (Oil Can) or you can call him Cohete (Rocket).
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the top pitcher in baseball today, already one of the
best in Boston lore, righthander Pedro Martinez is suddenly
behaving like a mercurial millionaire ballplayer _ the latest in a
chorus line of Red Sox hurlers who pitched fits.
</P>
<P>
   Five days after he was banished to the bullpen for showing up
late at Fenway, Martinez (17-4, 2.52 ERA) returned to the mound
against Oakland Thursday &UR;  &LR; night and lost a 6-2 decision in which he
gave up three runs, fanned 11, and walked none in seven strong
innings.
</P>
<P>
   But he made most of his noise and news in the clubhouse before
the game when he unleashed an unprovoked tirade on his Godfather
General Manager, Dan Duquette.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is (Sox manager Jimy Williams) going to apologize?'' Martinez
shouted to a silent Duquette. ``Is he going to shake my hand?''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Pedro was a different man. It was as if the Sox
had drilled a tranquilizer dart into his tiny butt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just talking (with Duquette),'' he insisted. ``I'm just
a loud talker . . . My fans are fine. I'm fine with my teammates.
I'm fine with Jimy.''
</P>
<P>
   Weird. Very weird.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Saturday's bizarre spectacle, when the manager
publicly spanked his star pitcher, there had been great
apprehension about Pedro's start Thursday &UR;  &LR; night. There were silly
rumors that the habitually tardy Pedro might motor into Fenway
aboard the SS Nauticus accompanied by Peter Blute and Brandi
Chastain. Instead, Martinez arrived in a white Mercedes more than
two hours before game time, well within team rules.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyed that some cameras and reporters (``a couple of clowns,''
according to Pedro) recorded his arrival and were perhaps
suspicious that the usually invisible Duquette was ``checking up''
on him, Martinez unloaded on the GM in the near-empty locker room
while most of his teammates were out on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Five hours later, Pedro was all smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let it go,'' he told reporters. ``I didn't commit a crime or
anything like that. Let's go back to work. Jimy is not going to get
fired. I'm not going to get released or traded. It's time to let it
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, it was Pedro who kept the story alive all week.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his calm, measured postgame demeanor, there's evidence
of a growing split between Pedro and Sox management. First of all,
Martinez makes little effort to mind the wishes of pitching coach
Joe Kerrigan. Then there's residual bitterness over not being
allowed to pitch the fourth game of the playoffs last October (the
Sox were eliminated by Cleveland in four games and Pedro pitched
only once). More recently, the pitcher and the manager have
disagreed over the playing of music in the Sox clubhouse (Pedro
wants it, Jimy doesn't).
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday Martinez told reporters, ``I'm ready to go home. Get
this season over with and go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the tirade.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez backed away from his pregame anger and claimed he was
misrepresented by nosy reporters. His exchange with Duquette was
not for the benefit of reporters, but could not be ignored by
anyone within earshot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happens in the clubhouse, you're not allowed to
say,'' claimed Pedro. ``The clubhouse is my house. If you sneak
into my house and I don't know you, I will shoot you.''
</P>
<P>
   Sox lore is littered with tales of disgruntled Boston hurlers.
Roger Clemens was famous for misbehavior. If he wasn't dissing his
manager by not showing up in Florida, he was complaining about
carrying his own bags. And who can forget Dennis ``Oil Can'' Boyd,
the Sox' wild child of the 1980s? The Can saw demons even where
there were none, and was admitted to the hospital for psychiatric
testing after he quit the team and threatened to kill a teammate
when he was not selected for the 1986 All-Star team. The inimitable
Vicente Romo once disappeared for a few days in Chicago in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to bizarro moments by Sox hurlers, none can
top the stunt pulled by Gene Conley in 1962. The 6-foot-8-inch
righthander got lit up on the Yankee Stadium mound, then got lit up
again with the help of 19 beers (``I counted the empties myself,''
said Dick Radatz) in the clubhouse. When the team bus got stuck in
rush-hour traffic on the way to the airport, Conley got off, saying
he was going to use a saloon restroom. He was not seen again for
two days. Conley wound up buying a plane ticket to Jerusalem but
could not leave without a passport. When he returned to Boston and
got called on the carpet by Tom Yawkey, the Sox owner offered him a
drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``No thank you, sir, I don't drink,'' replied Conley.
</P>
<P>
   Now we have Pedro, who was late for a start, blasted the GM
before his next start, then smiled and took all the blame after
pitching well in a loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't commit a crime or anything like that,'' reasoned
Pedro. ``It was my mistake. I apologized to my teammates. I
apologized to Jimy. I never want to go through something like this.
But those reporters sneaking around today, those clowns, they make
it look like I'm a delinquent that committed a crime. That's why I
got a little upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro should know better. Clowns or no clowns, this is not
Montreal. This is Boston. Baseball matters. A $75 million ace
matters.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Lata de Aceite. Or Cohete.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
