u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-MARTINEZRE     08-20 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ'S TEAMMATES HAVE CATCHING UP TO DO 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-MARTINEZ REACTION-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ You could tell by the way Darren Lewis opened his eyes
wide that he knew nothing. John Valentin leaned in to learn what
had happened. Bret Saberhagen admitted from the start he would not
be much help. Even Ramon Martinez did not provide any special
insight.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox clubhouse was virtually empty prior to Thursday
night's game when Pedro Martinez voiced his displeasure about media
members lurking outside the players' parking lot. No teammates
witnessed his loud complaints in the clubhouse presence of general
manager Dan Duquette. They did not hear the ace was looking for an
apology from manager Jimy Williams.
</P>
<P>
   And the news traveled slowly before and after the game. A
contest with wild-card implications, a flight to Texas, and all the
luggage loading required for a road trip kept many of the players
ill-informed. While Pedro downplayed the significance of his
pregame outburst before a group of reporters five rows deep, his
teammates believed the large gathering was simply interested in
Martinez's first start since a controversial scratch for tardiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea what's going on,'' said Valentin. ``I'm sorry.
I wish I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams also pleaded ignorance and said, ``I was on the field
so how would I know what happened? I've talked to Dan. I don't have
any problem with Pedro. Everything's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen smiled his Cheshire cat grin as he offered no
comment. After learning more details _ particularly that the
display involved Duquette _ the injured pitcher saw an opportunity
to inject a little humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's over and done with,'' said Saberhagen. ``I know nothing
(about the new developments). Are (Martinez and Duquette) still
friends? Now maybe if there were fists involved, I would have heard
about it. If there weren't fists, I guess they must still be
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, it sounded as if the general manager and the
team's highest-paid player were of the same mind on the matter.
Pedro requested that reporters drop it and move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough is enough. I would echo that,'' said Duquette as he
exited the ballpark. ``It's August and we're in a pennant race.
It's time to play ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The upcoming schedule and playoff push seemed to be the only
concerns of Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have too many things to worry about,'' he said. ``We have
to play every day. Sometimes we're back there watching video or in
the batting cage. We're not just sitting around.''
</P>
<P>
   The man who grew up with Pedro and continues to advise him would
not have handled the situation the same way. However, Ramon
Martinez feels for his younger brother. Ramon's years in Los
Angeles schooled him about the persistency of big-market reporters.
He understands the difficulty his brother has dropping all the
issues stemming from his late arrival last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this whole thing kind of got bigger than it was,''
said the elder Martinez. ``He was upset a little bit because he saw
the press hiding a little bit. I don't think that's fair. He
handled it his own way. All I can do is talk to him so it doesn't
bother him. It has to get over with.''
</P>
<P>
   While Pedro looks to end the scrutiny, his teammates have a
plane ride to catch up on the news.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
