<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3747 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-A'S-BOS &LR;      08-20 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX FIZZLE IN FINALE WITH A'S 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-A'S-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When Pedro Martinez wakes up this morning, it will all
seem like a bad dream. Imagine, an 11-strikeout game and yet a loss
added to his impressive record. It doesn't seem right.
</P>
<P>
   But that was the reality of a 6-2 Red Sox setback to the Oakland
Athletics Thursday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   The scales were tipped in the sixth inning, when Oakland
shortstop Miguel Tejada hit a solo home run into the left-field
screen, breaking a 2-2 tie. Martinez left after seven innings, and
the Red Sox could not mount a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Martinez had ``lost it'' a couple of hours earlier.
Frustrated over events involving his being scratched from his
previous start, Martinez went off in the Red Sox clubhouse in such
a manner that reporters were asked to leave. Martinez directed his
remarks at general manager Dan Duquette for several minutes. But
the harshest comments were aimed at manager Jimy Williams, who was
busy with pregame batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez arrived at 4:05 p.m., exactly two hours before he was
to make his 22d start.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez and Williams apparently did not talk before the game.
And after the game neither wanted to admit there was a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said he is too much of a professional to let any
dispute affect his performance. ``I'm always ready,'' said the ace
righthander, who issued a blanket denial of all that was said
Thursday afternoon. ``Whenever I get a chance to go out there, I'm
ready. I do my work and 30 minutes before a game all I need to do
is warm up my arm. I wasn't angry. I respect (the media). There is
no need for any slipping around and doing crazy things. I will
answer questions. You guys are making such big deal of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Williams: ``Everybody's feelings are important out there.
They're important to me. I don't worry about distractions. I
thought we played pretty good. We just got beat.''
</P>
<P>
   When Martinez took the mound Thursday &UR;  &LR; night, he was sharp. He
had the full support of the sellout crowd of 33,393. Martinez was
their hero, and everything he did was magic. He struck out four of
the first five batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't last for long, as Oakland scored single runs in
the fourth, fifth, and sixth innings. The Sox got two runs in the
fifth off rookie Tim Hudson (8-1), but that was it.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Giambi singled and scored the first Oakland run in the
fourth. In the fifth, A.J. Hinch led off with a single and moved to
third on a sacrifice bunt and a ground out. From there he scored on
a double by Giambi, giving the Athletics a 2-0 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro pitched outstanding,'' said Williams. ``He walked nobody
and had 11 strikeouts. We'd probably let him go a little more, but
he's not that far removed from the disabled list and that shoulder
injury. He was around 115 pitches (actually 114). The Hudson kid
pitched good. Tejada hurt us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics found a way to hurt the Red Sox in the eighth
inning, too. With Rheal Cormier pitching, Giambi and Matt Stairs
singled to lead off the inning. After newcomer Bryce Florie
relieved Cormier, Giambi and Stairs advanced on a wild pitch and
scored on a single off the wall by pinch hitter John Jaha for a 5-2
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Boston had two baserunners with no outs in the ninth but failed
to score.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, Oakland earned a split of the four-game series
and moved within one game of Boston in the American League
wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said he was pleased with his performance but not the
result. ``I feel I had everything I needed,'' he said. ``They were
a little bit better than I was, and (Hudson) did a better job. They
battled their heart out. Hope to get them the next time. That team
is better than anybody thinks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
