<HEADER>
A3753 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-MARTINEZ-B     08-20 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ GIVES DUQUETTE AN EARFUL 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-MARTINEZ-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ At 4:05 p.m., all seemed well inside the Red Sox
clubhouse. Pedro Martinez leisurely strolled by a group of
reporters, went straight to his locker, and began to prepare for
Thursday &UR;  &LR; night's start against the Oakland A's.
</P>
<P>
   One minute later, all hell broke loose, triggered by the arrival
of Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette, who took the brunt of a
Martinez tirade that centered around manager Jimy Williams and his
decision to scratch Martinez from last Saturday's start against
Seattle. And Martinez was saddled with the loss in
Thursday &UR;  &LR; night's 6-2 setback to Oakland. He's had better days.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was angry at not only Williams but also the media horde
that was waiting to see if he arrived within two hours of game
time, a team rule. Martinez took particular offense to the
newspaper and television cameras that awaited him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he going to come over?'' said Martinez in a voice loud
enough to be heard by the reporters. ``Is (Williams) going to
apologize? Is he going to shake my hand?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want people following me around. I don't like the
cameras. I'm tired of these clowns following me around.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez had more to say, but reporters were asked to leave the
clubhouse by Kevin Shea, the team's director of communications and
baseball information, who declared, ``This is a private
conversation, and the locker room is now closed.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Martinez defended the sanctity of the clubhouse
and said those who would report private statements made there were
``clowns'' and not reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happens in this clubhouse,'' said Martinez, ``(the
media is) not allowed to say anything. You should be more
professional and stop sticking your nose where you don't have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez had arrived at the players' parking lot at 3:50 p.m. He
stayed in his vehicle for 10-12 minutes, then entered the clubhouse
exactly two hours before the 6:05 game time. Martinez had been
greeted inside the park by 10-15 reporters, all checking their
watches to see if he would be late a second straight time. He
wasn't. After discovering Williams was not in the clubhouse,
Martinez aimed his wrath at Duquette. At that point, the media were
asked to leave. But not before some spicy remarks were heard.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Martinez did what he said he wouldn't: carry the
story beyond the clubhouse. He repeated his apology to his
teammates and Williams. He acknowleged that he'd been late last
Saturday. His regret wasn't that he had been punished but that news
of what had happened had gone beyond the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was over after the game. Now some of the reporters are
trying to make a big deal out of it, and I don't see why,''
Martinez said. ``Jimy is not going to get fired. I'm not going to
get released. And I won't be traded. You guys need to let go.
Honestly, let go. Let me handle Jimy. Let me handle my clubhouse.
It was a great game out there today. Don't start digging into my
life with Jimy and my team in the clubhouse. The clubhouse is my
house and I don't know you, I will shoot you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any problems with Pedro,'' insisted Williams.
``He's an important part of our team. I think he showed that
tonight. Unfortunately, we didn't get a win. We just couldn't score
enough runs. If you go by the way he pitched, I don't know if he
can get much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said he did not go to the clubhouse to act as a
peacemaker. ``Don't even go there,'' he said. ``If you're trying to
position me between the player and the manager, you're wrong. I'm
not between the two. Did I resolve anything? I don't have any
issues to resolve with (Martinez). As far as we're concerned, the
item last week is resolved. That's gone by. The rest of it is
difficult for me to discuss.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's said in the clubhouse should stay in the clubhouse,''
Williams said. ``You might not agree, but that's the way I feel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
