   PARIBAS-RESIGN (Rome) _ Paribas's chairman, Andre Levy-Lang,
will resign next week, the first executive casualty arising from
the failure of the French bank's planned merger with Societe
Generale. By John Taliabue.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ROSENTHAL-COLUMN (Undated) _ ``On My Mind''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN (London) _ ``Foreign Affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (Moved ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BROOKLYN-BLACK-CULTURE (New York) _ In villages across Africa,
storytelling has long been an integral part of daily life. At
nights, even to this day, people gather in circles in courtyards
illuminated by a full moon and bright stars to hear gripping tales
from wise men and indelible stories from adventurous young men who
have returned to their hamlets from faraway places. This and other
African traditions are being kept alive in Fort Greene, Brooklyn,
which for years has been a mecca for black life but which within
the last three years has experienced an extraordinary burst of
cultural energy. The 135-year-old Brooklyn Academy of Music, which
has made its name as a center for cutting-edge arts programs like
the Next Wave Festival, has reached out to the surrounding
neighborhood with programs on black culture. By Garry
Pierre-Pierre.
</P>
<P>
   KAT-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ ``Kat and the Kings,'' a peppy,
exhaustingly eager show about a nonwhite doo-wop group, crooning up
a storm in the segregated Cape Town of the 1950s. Reviewed by Ben
Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON-SARGENT (Boston, Mass.) _ Boston is in a tizzy over
Sargent this summer. A traveling retrospective, ``John Singer
Sargent,'' already seen in Washington and London, is making its
final stop at the Museum of Fine Arts, and three smaller shows are
on view elsewhere. Even enthusiastic natives are finding it all a
bit much. By Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   SHELBURNE-FARMS (Shelburne, Vt.) _ I had been enumerating the
glories of the Inn at Shelburne Farms, a country estate on the
banks of Lake Champlain, practically since the day my friend Nate
and I had met, and now, on a summer evening three years later, we
were finally on our way, driving through the Green Mountains. We
turned onto the long, winding gravel road that marks the beginning
of the estate, at the southern end of Champlain, seven miles
outside Burlington. But as we left behind Route 7, with its
dispiriting artificial lights, fast-food outlets and strip malls,
we found the countryside illuminated by a full moon: the lake on
one side; pastures, woodlands and huge barns on the other. In the
distance, rising above a grassy hill, just as I remembered it, was
the rambling, Queen Anne-style, stone and red-brick building, with
its turrets, towers and 13 chimneys. Inside the curved and
diamond-shaped windows, the lights glowed. Nate reacted on cue:
``Wow.'' By Sara Rimer.
</P>
