<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BUSH-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BUSH'S DRUG DODGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Aug. 21:
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas has run into a distracting and
potentially dangerous patch in his presidential campaign. The issue
is whether he ever used cocaine or other illegal substances during
his youth. Bush has been dancing around the question for several
days, creating the impression that he probably did experiment with
cocaine and that he believes evasion rather than an honest answer
is the best response.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton years have left Americans understandably ambivalent
about prying into the private lives of politicians. The country is
weary of Clinton's inability to control his behavior, and sorry for
the lost time it cost the president and the nation. But the Clinton
experience has also made clear that questions of character and
personal conduct can severely distort a presidency.
</P>
<P>
   That is the environment that greets Bush and the new crop of
presidential candidates. While there is no clear-cut rule about how
much personal information they need to provide, more information is
almost invariably better than less. That is because efforts to
limit information usually just raise more questions, not only among
reporters but among voters. Evasion also diminishes those who
practice it. Sensitized by Clinton's 1992 campaign circumlocutions
on personal matters, Americans now fear such dodging may be a
signal of deeper flaws.
</P>
<P>
   Given this history and climate, Bush would be wise to quit
tiptoeing around the issue of drug use, and to stop complaining
that he is being unfairly questioned by the press. His statements
have become progressively more untenable. At first he refused to
respond or gave cryptic answers. Wednesday evening he told The
Dallas Morning News that he could satisfy the federal security
clearance requirement of not having used illegal drugs for the last
seven years. On Thursday he said he could pass a White House
background check under rules going back to 1989, when his father
became president. His spokesman later explained that this meant he
had not used illegal drugs since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush never used illegal drugs, he should say so. If he did,
he should 'fess up. For one thing, he might find that voters would
forgive a youthful indiscretion. Many members of his generation
experimented with illegal drugs when they were young. That ought
not to disqualify people from holding high office, provided they
gave up the habit. But Bush may need to square his own drug use as
a young man with the tough law enforcement policies he espouses as
governor for dealing with youthful drug offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Bush cannot have it both ways on his personal life. He
voluntarily proclaimed his marital fidelity, which is surely the
most private of subjects. That only adds to the impression that he
is hiding something about other aspects of his life. The best
course for him is to be honest, and to let the country take his
measure. In his campaign, the governor has emphasized the
importance of assuming responsibility for one's own actions. He
should be thinking now about how to set a good example.
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 0139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3760 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-LEE-CASE-NYT &LR;      08-20 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-LEE-CASE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE CASE OF WEN HO LEE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Aug. 21:
</P>
<P>
   Troubling accusations have been made, and denied, in recent days
that Wen Ho Lee, a Taiwan-born American citizen who is suspected of
leaking nuclear secrets to China, was singled out for investigation
and punishment because of his Chinese ethnicity. If those claims
are true, it would be a repellent act of discrimination by federal
government agencies. But based on the information now publicly
available, it is not possible to reach a definitive conclusion
about whether or not Lee was unfairly treated.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually everyone involved in this complicated espionage
investigation has some motive to twist the facts. What is needed
now is a careful review of the Lee case, carried out under the
leadership of a credible, independent figure who understands the
intelligence, national security and law enforcement considerations
bearing on this kind of investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Lee first came under suspicion in 1996 in an investigation of a
possible Chinese theft of nuclear weapons designs from the Los
Alamos National Laboratory. He drew the attention of investigators
because he was a computer scientist in the laboratory's weapons
design section who had traveled to China and had contacts with
Chinese scientists. Although scores of other Los Alamos employees
had also traveled to China, Lee soon became the prime suspect.
</P>
<P>
   He was dismissed for security breaches in March of this year.
After his departure, investigators found that he had transferred
masses of secret bomb test and design data from the laboratory's
classified computers to less secure machines.
</P>
<P>
   Lee now contends that there was nothing wrong or unusual about
his transfer of computer data or his meetings with Chinese
scientists and that he was singled out because he is a
Chinese-American. A similar charge that the investigation was
ethnically biased was made this week by Robert S. Vrooman, the
former head of counterintelligence at Los Alamos, whose motives
have been questioned because he himself faces possible departmental
discipline over security failures at the lab. Chinese-American
groups also question Lee's treatment.
</P>
<P>
   If those assertions turn out to be correct, Lee would be owed an
apology and the restoration of his reputation. The truth can best
be established by re-examining all aspects of the handling of the
Lee case by the Energy and Justice Departments. The review should
include a look at how the original list of suspects was assembled
and narrowed down to Lee, the significance of the computer data Lee
downloaded to unclassified machines and the nature of his contacts
with Chinese scientists. It is especially important to evaluate
whether or not Lee's conduct in these areas differed significantly
from that of other Los Alamos scientists who did not emerge as
suspects.
</P>
<P>
   The review should be headed by a knowledgeable, authoritative
figure like former Senator Sam Nunn or Gen. Colin Powell. Whoever
is chosen, Lee is entitled to an independent look at this
politically and ethnically charged case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 0143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 01:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3762 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-ALUMINUM-MERGERS     08-20 0287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ALUMINUM-MERGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: QUESTIONABLE MERGERS IN ALUMINUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Aug. 21:
</P>
<P>
   The sudden consolidation in the worldwide aluminum industry
raises troubling antitrust issues that must be addressed by
regulators in both Europe and North America before the mergers are
allowed to proceed. At a minimum, some divestitures are likely to
be needed.
</P>
<P>
   The Alcoa-Reynolds deal comes on the heels of an agreement by
Alcan Aluminium of Canada, Pechiney of France and Alusuisse Lonza
Group of Switzerland to combine into one company, APA, that would
have replaced Alcoa as the world's largest aluminum company. A
merger with Reynolds would vault Alcoa back into the top spot. The
two giant companies would then control 28 percent of worldwide
aluminum production, and nearly 75 percent of the North American
market. Both mega-mergers require careful scrutiny, and may need to
be blocked. There is a risk that European regulators might be
persuaded that the APA deal is needed to offset Alcoa, while Alcoa
tells the Justice Department that it must grow to confront APA.
</P>
<P>
   Aluminum prices have been very depressed, in part because of
weak demand overseas and in part because Russia, a major producer,
increased exports to raise needed hard currency. The companies
contend that huge mergers will produce efficiencies that will
enable them to cut costs and operate more effectively in a
low-price environment. But some financial analysts think the
combined companies will be in a better position to raise prices
more than would otherwise be possible. It is that prospect that the
antitrust regulators should examine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 0146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
