A3764 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-UNIVERAL-TURNAROUND-L     08-20 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIVERAL-TURNAROUND-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONFMAN DECLARES UNIVERSAL TURNAROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Seagram Co., which saw its Universal Pictures
bleed red ink for the past two years, proclaimed Thursday it has
solved the problems at the studio.
</P>
<P>
   The bold assertion from Seagram chief Edgar Bronfman Jr. was
delivered as part of the conglomerate's quarterly earnings report,
showing a $206 million operating loss from movies for its fiscal
year ended June 30. Bronfman, who began shaking up the executive
suite last year, noted that Universal is on a hot streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our film business is in the process of a turnaround,''
declared Bronfman in a statement. ``We have a new management team
in place. The recent releases, including `The Mummy,' `Notting
Hill,' `American Pie' and `Bowfinger,' have been very successful
and are early signs of a comeback.''
</P>
<P>
   Universal endured a hitless string of 20 movies between mid-1997
and late last year due to bad timing and questionable choices while
most rival studios posted improving results. Last November, film
studio chief Casey Silver and Universal Studios head Frank Biondi
departed after the release of a pair of high-priced flops, ``Meet
Joe Black'' and ``Babe: Pig in the City.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bronfman, the recent successes are sweet redemption
following years of brutal criticism on Wall Street over his 1995
decision to buy Universal Studios to launch the transformation of
Seagram from a liquor giant to an entertainment conglomerate. He
also said Thursday the studio has a ``strong slate'' of films for
the current fiscal year ending in June 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bucksbaum of Reel Source forecasting service said ``Man
on the Moon,'' starring Jim Carrey as the late Andy Kaufman, may be
a holiday season hit, and ``Viva Rock Vegas,'' a ``Flintstones''
sequel, could perform well next summer. Other coming releases
include ``For Love of the Game'' with Kevin Costner, ``The Story of
Us'' with Bruce Willis and Michelle Pfeiffer, ``End of Days'' with
Arnold Schwarzenegger and ``Erin Brockovich'' with Julia Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Linda Bannister of Edward Jones agreed Universal appears
to be on the right track but remained cautious, citing the highly
volatile nature of the film business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think Seagram can turn its businesses around,'' she said.
``Do the current hits at Universal mean its difficulties are over?
That's hard to say because all studios go through good and bad
streaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Seagram's report included an $87 million operating loss in the
fourth quarter ended June 30 for the film division, but those
results were not a surprise since they reflected shortfalls from
``EdTV'' and ``Meet Joe Black.'' Bronfman reiterated his projection
that Universal will need several more quarters to move out of the
red. Bannister noted Seagram will not see much profit from its
recent successful films until the titles go into home video.
</P>
<P>
   Bronfman also indicated Universal would continue to pursue
cofinancing and third-party funding for projects. ``We are seeking
to enhance returns by taking capital out of the business,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Kevin Skislock of Laguna Research Partners said the
strategy makes sense for a major studio because it has more chances
at potential hits. ``The statement could also open the door to be
even more aggressive about laying off the upfront risk,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the loss in the film business, Seagram Co. posted a
smaller quarterly loss than expected due to strong results from
music, theme parks and alcoholic beverages. Excluding one-time
factors, Seagram lost $129 million, or 32 cents a share, compared
with a loss of $12 million in the same 1998 period.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected Seagram to post a loss of 42 cents per
share.
</P>
<P>
   Seagram shares gained 7 percent Thursday, rising $3.50 to
$53.625. The stock is up 40 percent this year, mainly due to
investors' increased confidence in Bronfman's strategy of making
Seagram the world's largest music company by buying PolyGram for
$10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
