<P>
   It is the biggest step taken by individual Japanese banks to
overcome the effects of the nation's protracted recession, which
has left the banking industry hobbled by bad debts.
</P>
<P>
   The deal may face obstacles, however. The Fair Trade Commission
will examine the plan to check for possible violations of the
Anti-Monopoly Law, according to Friday's Nihon Keizai. The
commission declined comment on whether it had been consulted by the
three banks in advance about their collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement sent the banks' stock prices shooting higher in
morning trading on the Tokyo Stock Exchange, adding to already
impressive gains from Thursday, when Japan's leading business
daily, Nihon Keizai Shimbun, first reported that the banks were
negotiating.
</P>
<P>
   Industrial Bank of Japan shares, which closed at $8.80 on
Thursday, traded at $9.70 Friday morning. Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank
shares rose to $9 from $8.15; Fuji Bank shares were at $9.30, up
from $8.50.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance may help the three banks adapt to the deregulation
of the financial markets here, which is creating new competition in
the banking and securities industries. The banks said they would
consolidate overseas branches ``as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The shakeup dominated newspapers, radio and television. Many
commentators said such mergers were an international trend and drew
comparisons to the huge merger of Citigroup and Travelers Group
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This type of basic shakeup is inevitable given the situation
of the financial industry,'' said an editorial in Friday's Nihon
Keizai.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting widely held opinion, the newspaper said there were
simply too many banks in Japan, with 17, counting just the top
banks.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer magnitude of the three-way merger raises many
questions. Their combined assets surpass the $899 billion in assets
of Deutsche Bank (with Bankers Trust).
</P>
<P>
   It also surpasses what would have become the world's biggest
bank if Banque Nationale de Paris had succeeded in acquiring
Paribas and Societe Generale. The assets in that three-way deal
would have totaled around $1 trillion. Banque Nationale won
shareholder approval only from Paribas.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say there will probably only be more consolidations in
an industry that remains bloated and inefficient. Many banks are
still struggling under the weight of hundreds of billions of
dollars in loans that soured when the Japanese real estate market
collapsed in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   And though interest rates here have fallen to record lows, which
should stimulate more lending and help bank profits, the balance
sheets of many institutions remain weak.
</P>
<P>
   The three banks are among 15 that were beneficiaries of an
enormous government-financed rescue package in March. Although they
are all saddled with large bad debts, the banks concentrate in
different businesses that could complement each other, were they to
merge into one huge force.
</P>
<P>
   The Industrial Bank of Japan, for example, is the only domestic
bank that still specializes in long-term loans to Japanese
companies. Its two competitors, the Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan
and Nippon Credit Bank, were seized by the government after they
became insolvent.
</P>
<P>
   Fuji Bank could regain its presence in the securities business
through IBJ Securities, a subsidiary of the Industrial Bank of
Japan that is one of the most profitable securities operations in
the country. Fuji lost its securities business link nearly two
years ago when an affiliate, Yamaichi Securities, collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Dai-Ichi Kangyo, one of Japan's biggest lenders, will benefit by
gaining the customers of the two others.
</P>
<P>
   Nihon Keizai Shimbun's report Thursday, quoting unidentified
banking officials, said the three institutions would divide their
operations in retail, corporate and investment banking, hoping to
realize large economies of scale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
