<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 02:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3772 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      08-20 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHINING LIGHT ON PRESEASON'S MANY QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The NFL preseason is a time of many questions.
But here at your P-I searchlight of truth, we get to the answers,
as provided by Thursday night's earthshaker between the Seahawks
and San Francisco 49ers (Richter scale reading: 0.0).
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why did ESPN call this a ``preseason special''?
</P>
<P>
   A. For the same reason your favorite greasy spoon calls
2-day-old meatloaf the house special. It's not good, but it is
plentiful and fills a hole. Besides, most people will buy anything.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What's the deal with 49ers GM Bill Walsh hiring the felonious
Lawrence Phillips? Didn't Walsh a few years back trash the
University of Washington football fans for hiring ``mercenaries''?
</P>
<P>
   A. Ah, you fans of hypocrisy never forget. When he was Stanford
coach in 1993, Walsh told a booster group that the Huskies were
``mercenaries'' who spend their time in ``an athletic department
compound'' and return to society with ``none of the skills you are
supposed to gain in college''; remarks for which he apologized
after being reprimanded by the Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   His plunge from the moral high ground establishes that a guy
even as noble and principled as Walsh is entitled to change his
mind. As Wally Walker is apt to respond these days: Yeah, but he's
our thug now.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How did Phillips do Thursday night?
</P>
<P>
   A. He was stuffed for a yard loss on his first carry, then had a
short pass bounce off his shoulder pads. He finished with six yards
on three rushes, 12 yards on three catches and, at press time, zero
arrests. That should wipe the slate clean, no?
</P>
<P>
   Q. How come right tackle Howard Ballard didn't play?
</P>
<P>
   A. Ballard's arthritic joint is so bad that doctors are
replacing the old wood beams with steel, exchanging the old ropes
for bridge cable and strapping the whole thing with concertina
wire. He'll be fine tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Speaking of the missing, where was Joey Galloway?
</P>
<P>
   A. Joey Stayaway was reportedly home in Columbus, still waiting
for financial anointment as World's Greatest Receiver Who Hasn't
Done Anything. Expect Stayaway to sign with the Seahawks as soon as
the team is no longer in Cheney, which he hates. Once signed, you
can also expect him stay away from contact.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Was there any improvement in the Seahawk quarterbacking?
</P>
<P>
   A. Until a 32-yard catch-and-run with Sean Dawkins early in the
second quarter, starter Jon Kitna appeared to be on a post-surgery
regimen of soft toss, only he never had surgery. He threw sideways,
even backwards, rarely downfield. But in the second quarter, he
completed all three pass attempts that made for a 75-yard touchdown
drive, Kitna's first of the preseason. Coach Mike Holmgren was
believed to have fallen to his knees, sobbing with joy.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren did a little more weeping when rookie backup Brock
Huard took over with the second unit in the second half, but the
tears had a different flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Huard's first pass was intercepted. A fourth-quarter drive was
killed by another pick. Then came the backbreaker, a misread by
Huard that resulted in a pass returned 35 yards for a touchdown by
a former Husky teammate, defensive end David Richie, that became
the difference in San Francisco's 24-23 win.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a linebacker blitz on and dropped a defensive lineman
into the zone I was throwing to,'' Huard said of the Richie pick.
``I just didn't see him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how you learn,'' said Holmgren, who was taking the
defeat much more stoically than six days ago. ``Right now, both
quarterbacks are not only having to play the 49ers, they have to
learn a new system.''
</P>
<P>
   Huard hustled back valiantly from the precipice, taking the
Seahawks 81 yards in the final 1:42 for a touchdown. But his
two-point conversion pass to Michael Black, alone as a Republican
in Berkeley, sailed wide right for no particular reason.
</P>
<P>
   For now, too much Husky, too little Seahawk.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What else was noteworthy?
</P>
<P>
   A. Seahawk free safety Jay Bellamy made a lunging sideline
interception of a pass late in the second quarter; moments later,
Seahawk center Kevin Glover made a great block on a blitz that
saved Kitna and completed a 21-yard pass play; in the third
quarter, a flock of five pelicans flew in tight formation over the
stadium; and field goal kicker Todd Peterson hit an upright from 40
yards in 3Com Park's swirling gales, a feat rated slightly more
difficult locally than hitting a bee with a BB at a quarter mile.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What was that noise following back-to-back special teams
screwups that resulted in 14 San Francisco points in less than a
minute of the fourth quarter?
</P>
<P>
   A. Former special teams coach Dave Arnold, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What's the biggest difference between the old regime of
Dennis Erickson and the new one?
</P>
<P>
   A. The players no longer think they know more than the coaching
staff.
</P>
<P>
   Q. The Seahawks are 0-2 in the preseason with one touchdown
scored by the first-unit offense. Is this what the franchise calls
Now Time?
</P>
<P>
   A. Not quite. Right now, this is No Time, as in no time for fans
to care much about pro football results.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
