 A WHOLE LOT MORE BALL THAN PARK  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Welcome to No-Park Park, new home of your San Francisco Giants.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants open next season in their cool new ballpark in China
Basin, and lack of parking has become the major concern.
</P>
<P>
   OK,  &UR; one  &LR; of the major concerns. Starting pitching and Barry
Bonds' state of mind are other ongoing concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Solution? Of course I have a solution to the parking problem.
Two.
</P>
<P>
   One, take a couple aircraft carriers out of mothballs, dock 'em
next to the ballpark, load 'em with cars.
</P>
<P>
   Portable parking lots! In keeping with the ballpark's
dock-o'-the-Bay motif and ambience.
</P>
<P>
   Two, turn the players' parking lot over to the fans. Where will
the players park? At home.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants could make a huge breakthrough in public relations
and promote fan-player bonding by asking _ requiring _ the players
to take public transit to work.
</P>
<P>
   In New York back in mid-century, Yankees and Dodgers commonly
rode the subway to work. When Bob Welch pitched for the Oakland A's
and lived in the Marina, he frequently rode BART to the ballpark
and says nobody bothered him.
</P>
<P>
   Call it Bussin' with Barry.
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS SCHOOLS aren't teaching evolution anymore, and Peter
William Brown thinks maybe that decision is justified because
evolution hasn't occurred in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   I think it's all part of a plan to simplify education. In
biology, for instance, Kansas will eliminate weeks of study of
human reproduction, replacing that section in textbooks with a
full-page cartoon of a stork.
</P>
<P>
   PROHIBITION is a hit at Moose's restaurant in North Beach.
That's cell-phone prohibition; booze is still served,
enthusiastically.
</P>
<P>
   On each table is a stand-up card with a cartoon of a moose
making a cell call, with the universal don't-do-this slash.
</P>
<P>
   Result: Moose's clientele consists entirely of Himalayan wise
men, English poets and mimes.
</P>
<P>
   But seriously, Ed Moose says his diners are taking the cards for
use at work and home.
</P>
<P>
   One woman told Ed she put the card on her bedside table, a
subtle message to her cell-addicted companion.
</P>
<P>
   Which is a cute idea, but maybe what this woman needs is
mating-call-waiting.
</P>
<P>
   STEALTH BUS? A guy I know was driving on Market, found himself
behind a brand-new Muni electric bus. A sign in the rear window
said, ``Experimental bus, not in service.''
</P>
<P>
   The bus' trolley pole was lowered, unconnected to the overhead
power-supply cable, yet the bus was purring along.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be ... a bus powered by some kind of cosmic energy?
</P>
<P>
   I'M NO EXPERT on farmworker transportation, though I play one on
TV.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposed new law to make seat belts mandatory in vans
hauling farmworkers might not be the real solution to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   What about reports that the vans are old and rickety,
overcrowded even by sardine-industry standards and sometimes driven
by unqualified drivers who sell beer to the thirsty riders?
</P>
<P>
   Until those problems are addressed, all seat belts will do is
prevent dead people from leaving the scene of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   HOT RUMOR in Marin County is that Brad Pitt and Jennifer Aniston
are home-shopping in Ross, which is already an official suburb of
Hollywood. The rumor is they're eyeing the ``Jack'' house, a
magnificent Victorian used in the filming of the Robin Williams
movie ``Jack.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, they'd better close the deal soon. Property values are
skyrocketing, and Brad and Jen could find themselves priced out of
the market by the bonanza kings of the high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   MUNI YANG: A rider reports that a 22 Fillmore bus arrived one
minute earlier than indicated on the new NextBus info screen. New
Muni technology that works!
</P>
<P>
   And, an off-duty Muni driver, in uniform, driving a pickup, was
involved in a collision when a red light was run. And it wasn't the
Muni driver's fault!
</P>
<P>
   MUNI YIN: Kurt Rossetti was riding a 1-California bus when a
cockroach appeared on the shoulder of the female rider in front of
him.
</P>
<P>
   When informed of the situation, the woman did a few frantic
pirouettes, then got off at the next stop. Nobody called after her,
``Hey lady, you forgot your cockroach.''
</P>
<P>
   TWO MORE IDEAS for the Giants:
</P>
<P>
   1. Instead of a dreary organist or canned music, invite a
different local musician or musical group to perform at every game.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ladies and gentlemen, now playing ``Take Me Out to the &LR; 
 &UR; Ballgame,'' Carlos Santana. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   2. Give out 100 free tickets every game to fans who show up
outside with the best costumes, gimmicks or enthusiasm. Call it the
``Let's Make a Deal'' rooting section.
</P>
<P>
   INSTANT DICTIONARY: ``caboosed'' _ Stuck behind a heavy smoker
on a crowded sidewalk or escalator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
