<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOLSA-BLASTOFF-MEXICO-RESEND-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO INVESTORS: TIME TO HEAD FOR THE EXITS?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Business Editors...resending from 8-17)   (This 600-word ``separate buy'' financial story is from ``WORTH''
magazine. To publish this article, it must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been double-filed _ into the ``f''
financial news and ``i'' international news files.)  
  
 By TODD G. BUCHHOLZ  
 c.1999 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Between Jan. 15 and April 15, Mexico's IPC index, or Bolsa,
jumped about 65 percent, the best performance by a major stock
index this year.
</P>
<P>
   Had you been brave enough to buy Mexican stocks in mid-September
last year, while Brazil, Russia, and Long-Term Capital Management
were turning wealth into waste, you would have nearly doubled your
money.
</P>
<P>
   Few of us were so brave, however: The pundits were warning us
that Brazil _ as the next domino after Thailand, Malaysia, and
Indonesia _ would soon topple the rest of Latin America, including
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   But economists underestimated the confidence and resilience of
U.S. consumers, who bought more than 85 percent of Mexico's
exports. As long as American families kept shopping, Mexican
factories ought to keep humming to meet our demand for cars,
clothes, and furniture.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Mexico exports hardly anything to Brazil, a
key point overlooked during the frenzied sell-off last year in
Mexico's market.
</P>
<P>
   Just because Mexicans speak Spanish does not mean their economy
is linked more closely to Latin America than to North America.
Indeed, our 6 percent gain in gross domestic product in the fourth
quarter of 1998, despite tumbles in the New York Stock Exchange and
Nasdaq, was an excellent signal that Mexico would not collapse.
</P>
<P>
   As American consumers swiped their credit cards, Mexican
businessmen wiped their brows with relief. The several thousand
factories just south of the U.S. border _ in an area known as
Maquiladora _ have continued to thrive in 1999, with overall
exports increasing at a 7.7 percent pace in February.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of watching their economy shrink in 1999, as
Brazilians, Argentines, and Venezuelans will, Mexicans will see
their GDP rise by 2 to 3 percent. (In further tribute to the
country's resilience, the jobless rate fell to just 2.7 percent in
March.)
</P>
<P>
   Another factor behind the Bolsa's bounce is the rise in the
price of oil. Crude jumped from about $11 per barrel in December to
$18 by mid-April, thanks to an OPEC deal to cut production,
stronger economic prospects in Asia, and the war in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Because Mexico exports oil, higher prices improve Mexico's
expected trade balance and its budget revenue projections.
</P>
<P>
   Yet with the Bolsa hitting 5430 in the second half of April,
investors in Mexico might want to book some profits now, because
there are a couple of dangers looming.
</P>
<P>
   First, Mexicans will head to the voting booths to elect a new
president in July 2000. Months before the 1994 election, wealthy
Mexicans began sneaking their funds out of the country to the
safety of U.S. banks in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   They may get antsy again, recalling that the last presidential
election was marred by the assassination of the leading candidate,
rising inflation, and ultimately a collapse of the peso, which
triggered a deep recession in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the reigning PRI party, which has dominated Mexican
politics for 70 years, has been bloodied in recent years and even
been forced to share power with its rivals on the right (PAN) and
the left (PRD).
</P>
<P>
   President Zedillo's interior minister, Francisco Labastida, is a
candidate, but other cabinet ministers may challenge him for the
PRI's presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   A second possible trouble spot is the peso. It looked awfully
strong earlier this year, actually rising by more than 5 percent
against the U.S. dollar through mid-April.
</P>
<P>
   If Mexican exporters start bellyaching about how a stronger peso
hurts their ability to compete with other countries, investors
should head for the exits with their profits in tow. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Contributing editor Todd G. Buchholz is a former
managing director of Tiger Management and the author of ``Market
Shock.'') &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this 600-word ``WORTH'' magazine article, it must
be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES.
If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us
at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
