<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3958 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-BRACEROS-0818-     08-20 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-BRACEROS-0818-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ELDERLY MIGRANT WORKERS CLAIM MEXICAN GOVERNMENT OWES THEM $3
BILLION
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRAPUATO, Mexico _ They gathered by the hundreds here for a
protest, some hobbling on canes, others peering through thick
glasses, all with faces scored by wrinkles.
</P>
<P>
   They were ``braceros,'' just a handful of the 4.5 million
Mexican guest workers who were recruited to work on American farms
for 22 years, beginning during World War II. Decades later, they
have formed a movement and are claiming the Mexican government owes
them as much as $3 billion, money that was deducted from their
paychecks and deposited into Mexican bank accounts that have
mysteriously disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here because my husband can't walk anymore,'' said
Irene Sanchez Lopez, 74, the stooped, shawl-draped wife of
Margarito(CQ) Romero Troncos, 80.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went up there five years. I was left at home with two
little ones, suffering and wondering if he'd ever come back. We're
still poor now,'' said Sanchez Lopez, who attended a rally for the
former guest workers and their families Monday in this city in
Guanajuato, a state with a long history of migrant labor.
</P>
<P>
   The lost savings accounts, which the Mexican government admits
existed, date back to 1942, when men in the United States went off
to battle and Mexico agreed to send contract workers north to
Texas, California, Arizona, Arkansas and other states to pick
seasonal crops.
</P>
<P>
   The workers were known as ``braceros,'' literally, a pair of
arms, and American farmers became so hooked on their cheap labor
that they pushed Congress to extend the U.S. Labor
Department-supervised program until 1964.
</P>
<P>
   For some if not all of that time, the Mexican government
deducted 10 percent of the men's wages as part of the Farm Worker
Savings Fund, a program designed to ensure that the men would not
return empty-handed from their work abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that no more than 1 percent of our affiliates ever
received their money back,'' said Ventura Mendez Gutierrez of the
Union of Mexican Farm Workers and Emigrants, the group that
organized Monday's rally to demand the Mexican government locate
the money.
</P>
<P>
   The union has registered 15,000 former braceros in Guanajuato
and seven other Mexican states and is trying to contact more
workers or their survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Mendez said his organization, which represents the interests of
migrant workers, began researching the whereabouts of the fund when
elderly ex-braceros first came to him with inquiries about a decade
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bosses said that money was taken out by the Mexican
government and that we would get it when we got back to Mexico,''
said Panfilo Soria Garcia, one of those workers.
</P>
<P>
   Now 77, Soria picked cotton in La Mesa, Texas, among other
seasonal jobs north of the border.
</P>
<P>
   At the rally in front of Irapuato's town hall, Soria carried a
little plastic bag filled with yellowed documents, including a
laminated guest worker card issued to him in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the hundreds of men and widows of braceros gathered at
the rally clutched similar documents -- precious bits of history
proving they worked in the United States and might be entitled to
the savings.
</P>
<P>
   They swapped stories about the back-breaking work they
performed, picking cotton, lettuce, oranges and other crops. The
braceros were usually housed in barracks, and were not allowed to
bring their families or join unions.
</P>
<P>
   Consuelo Delgado, a frail 70-year-old widow, said her husband
died 15 years ago, but had talked about a savings fund. ``He went
to Arizona many times,'' she said, leaning on her granddaughter.
``He was strong then.''
</P>
<P>
   Jesus Morelos Gutierrez, 81, who picked cotton in Texas and
fruit and vegetables in California, said, ``We sure could use a
little of that 10 percent they took out.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the workers said they attempted to find out about the
savings years ago, but never had any success.
</P>
<P>
   ``One needs help sometimes figuring out how to track things
down,'' said Nicolas Galvan, 66, who harvested cotton in Texas for
three years in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference last Friday in Mexico City, a
representative of Mexico's Foreign Ministry acknowledged the fund's
existence, but said the government stopped taking out deductions
from braceros' checks after 1950.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means the period we are talking about is between 1942 and
1950,'' said Miguel Angel Gonzalez Felix, a legal consultant with
Mexico's Foreign Ministry, which is investigating the savings
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The deductions may have been deposited in three banks that later
merged into one institution called Banrural, Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we don't know,'' he added, ``is what amount was in the
fund, how it operated -- if there were individual or group accounts
-- and what became of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendez said that the union doesn't yet accept the government's
claim that deductions stopped in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 27, he said, the government is supposed to disclose the
findings of its investigation so far.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the government proves it didn't deduct money after 1950,
Mendez said, his union's position is that the Mexican government
should give the other workers credits to use for Mexico's social
security system or some other compensation.
</P>
<P>
   The $3 billion figure the union claims is owed is based on how
much several million braceros would be entitled to if deductions
were taken out over the duration of the guest-worker program -- and
interest were added. If the government proves it stopped deducting
money after 1950, the actual amount of the claim might be smaller
but still substantial, Mendez said.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Bustamante, an immigrant expert at Mexico's College of the
Northern Border in Tijuana, said he confirmed the fund's existence
more than 20 years ago when he served on Mexico's National
Commission on Migratory Labor.
</P>
<P>
   He said a Banrural official told him that the bank had issued an
advertisement years earlier warning that braceros who didn't pick
up their savings would lose them. Bustamante said he researched the
claim, and found that the bank couldn't legally strip the men of
their accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The practice of the government taking out deductions continued
beyond 1950,'' Bustamante added, but he wasn't sure for what
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Carlota Botey, a Mexican housing activist who also served on the
commission, said that she suspected that Banrural may have
erroneously used some of the money for rural development projects,
including loans to big farms.
</P>
<P>
   Mendez's union is also urging that the government help find out
what happened to deductions from the checks of 100,000 Mexicans who
were recruited to work on American railroads during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The men paid dues to American unions, Mendez said, and also had
deductions taken out by the Mexican government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wondered what happened to that money,'' said Jose
Avila Munoz, 74, who worked for 14 months in Arizona building
railways.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
