<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, Aug. 20, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Saturday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PIANIST-INSULT (San Francisco) _ The letter to Garrick Ohlsson
contains a brilliant symphony of insults. The letter came from
Ohlsson's manager, Vincent Ryan. Ohlsson responded with a lawsuit,
claiming the words are so brutal, that they cross the line into
defamation and ``infliction of emotional distress.'' By PETER
HARTLAUB.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIGRATION-REFORM (San Antonio) _ Immigrant advocates are
counting on a shift in national attitudes to help them roll back
part of a 1996 immigration reform law that is separating families
apart by requiring deportation of legal immigrants for minor
crimes. Members of a coalition pushing for changes in three 1996
laws affecting immigrants say they are particularly encouraged by
polls showing a warming of national attitudes toward legal
immigration. By ALISON GREGOR.
</P>
<P>
   DEL-RIO-FLOOD (Del Rio, Texas) _ A year after a devastating
flood in the poor San Felipe section of Del Rio, more than 100
families remain refugees of the inundation. But relief officials
say many of those who were displaced are ambivalent about taking up
government offers to move to higher ground, distraught over the
loss of cherished family homes and possessions. By JOHN MacCORMACK.
(For release Sunday, Aug. 22; photo available on Wieck database.)
</P>
<P>
   SEIZURE-SURGERY (San Antonio) _ Doctors at the University of
Texas Health Science Center performed a delicate neurological
procedure to try to halt a rare seizure disorder that plagues a
young Italian man. Although doctors say it's early, they are
optimistic that seizures will no longer torment Michele Angeloni.
By NICOLE FOY.
</P>
<P>
   JUDICIAL-REVIEW (San Francisco) _ In a decision hailed as
protecting judicial independence, the state's judicial watchdog
agency has dropped disciplinary charges against a San Francisco
judge who had been accused of failing to follow a controversial
California Supreme Court decision. By SETH ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Undated) _ Shootings in post offices have made
the phrase ``going postal'' part of the nation's everyday
vocabulary, even though many people who use it forget its bloody
origin. But the recent shooting at day-trading firms in Atlanta has
put employees more on edge, made workplace shootings more real. By
L.M. SIXEL.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ Webcams have become incredibly
inexpensive and are much easier to set up and use, though the image
quality they offer varies dramatically. Here's a look at three
low-priced cameras that plug into a PC using a Universal Serial Bus
port. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ A readers asks, ``I recently
received a forwarded e-mail that supposedly proves that all Windows
98 installations will fail to roll over to the correct date on Jan.
1, 2000. It gives a series of steps to fix the problem. I went
through the steps and, sure enough, I found my computer was set up
as shown in the message. This reads like one of those dumb hoaxes,
but it seemed to be correct. I've attached a copy for you. What
gives?'' Assorted Q&AMP;As. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   FEDEX-PARTNERS (San Francisco) _ Under threat of losing its
cargo facility at San Francisco International Airport, Federal
Express has agreed to comply with a court order to offer a limited
package of domestic partners benefits to its workers. By RACHEL
GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   APARTHEID-ARTIST (Albany, N.Y.) _ William Kentridge, the
acclaimed white South African artist, has devoted much of his
career to chronicling the horrors of apartheid and post-apartheid
life in his homeland. He has won international attention with his
stark animated portrayals of the country's troubled history. By
KRIS WORRELL.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-EYES (Undated) _ ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' is a Hugh
Grant vehicle with non-stop mob screwballing and a barrage of
ethnic joking held together by Grant flapping, fopping, squinting,
stammering and pulling himself into one long constipated face. It's
almost persuasive enough to make you forget that the movie
steamrolls Little Italy in the process. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-RAYMOND (Albany, N.Y.) _ At this time last year, the
consensus was ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' was roadkill, toast, a
cancellation waiting to happen. ``I thought we were dead,'' co-star
Brad Garrett said of the CBS show. Instead, the award-winning
program wound up in the Top 20 for the season. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-STEPS (Undated) _ Co-ed pop act Steps is one of the
hottest acts overseas and is about to embark on the biggest arena
tour for a pop group in British history. Meanwhile, the high-energy
group is hoping to score in the United States with an opening slot
on Britney Spears' tour and the Abba-esque single ``One For
Sorrow.'' By JOEY GUERRA.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-TINGLE (Undated) _ You probably won't see a more
pathetic sight this year than Helen Mirren, wrists strapped to each
end of a headboard, splayed on the mattress as though she were the
general's daughter. But Mirren's torturers aren't the frat boys of
the U.S. Army. They're a trio of high school seniors who've taken
their vengeance too far in ``Teaching Mrs. Tingle.'' By WESLEY
MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-SEBASTIAN (Undated) _ One of the big highs of Tod
Williams' ``The Adventures of Sebastian Cole'' is the way its hero
with the oily black locks never talks to the camera. He never
shoots us a sideways glance or addresses his audience in a
voice-over that would presume to tell you everything a lesser
filmmaker was too inept to show you. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-MOFFATS (Houston) _ Shopping with the teen group The
Moffats, a country band turned pop. By KRISSAH WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SEASON (San Francisco) _ Eriq LaSalle is getting $27 million
for three more seasons of ``ER.'' The numbers allegedly are
crunched to hide what the real deal is, but anytime you're getting
$27 million and you haven't won the lottery, this is shorthand for
your raise: Damn good. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-METS (Albany, N.Y.) _ They are on a collision course.
The New York Yankees have the best record in the American League.
The New York Mets have the best record in the National League. The
way the Yankees and Mets are going, they'll set baseball back four
decades and change. All the way back to 1956. The last subway World
Series. By STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BEATLES-TOUR (London) _ Let others journey to Paris in search of
Hemingway's cafes or walk the streets of Salzburg listening for the
echoes of Mozart. The Fab Four are my cultural heroes, and I'd come
to England for an immersion course in Beatlemania. By JOHN FLINN.
</P>
<P>
   POSTCARDS (London) _ When it comes to postcard wit, it's hard to
top Jimmy Buffett's classic line: ``The weather is here, wish you
were beautiful.'' But I don't know a single person I could send it
to who wouldn't slap me when I got home. By JOHN FLINN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Sen. John McCain was in town
Thursday, and I didn't ask him the ``did-you-ever'' question. He
made himself an easy target, too. He said of George W. Bush's nasal
privacy problems that ``the American people have a right to know a
lot of things.''By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ In part, at least, government
exists to help people through periods of hard luck. Sometimes it
works, and sometimes it doesn't. And sometimes government just
takes its own sweet time. One example is Jimmy Thompson, a man from
upstate New York who needed help from the government, but didn't
get it. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   SACCO-VANZETTI (Danville, Calif.) _ Aug. 23 is the anniversary
of the executions of Sacco and Vanzetti, two of the most famous and
controversial defendants in 20th century history. Seventy-two years
after their deaths in 1927, few people know much about them other
than their forever-linked names. By CYNTHIA BASS.
</P>
