<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AARP discovers sex sells
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ One of the almost daily shocks in my life
is the recent news that I have to share my Golden Years with baby
boomers becoming eligible for the rocking chair league. Other than
a father-son relationship with two of them, we don't have much in
common. Boomers are defined as those born between 1946 and 1964.
They listen to James Brown and Gladys Knight and the Pips (whoever
they are) rather than Glenn Miller and Bing Crosby.
</P>
<P>
   According to the American Association of Retired Persons, senior
citizenship begins at age 50. Old age in this country gets younger
by the year.
</P>
<P>
   This is because AARP is mainly a business enterprise on the
lookout for another marketing ploy. The hired executives who run it
can make more money by rolling back the age qualification so they
can collect more fees and magazine subscriptions from more people.
Pretty soon my granddaughter, who is only 14, will qualify for
membership.
</P>
<P>
   I've never belonged to the AARP, the Ku Klux Klan or a political
party. I'm a nonjoiner. After being expelled from the Rotary Club
for spotty attendance, the only thing I belong to is the Methodist
church, which in our family comes with the birth certificate.
</P>
<P>
   This may change. I found a newspaper story about the August
issue of Modern Maturity, the magazine published by AARP, highly
interesting. (FYI: Copies of Modern Maturity are available in
doctors' offices, along with 1988 Reader's Digests in large print).
</P>
<P>
   The August cover features Oscar-winning actress Susan Sarandon
in a sexy pose, wearing a clingy red dress with a large V in the
right place. Although she looks about 22, probably thanks in part
to Hollywood plastic surgeons, Susan is 52, which qualifies her for
a 10 percent discount.
</P>
<P>
   The teaser headlines on the August Modern Maturity cover say:
</P>
<P>
   ``GREAT SEX: What's age got to do with it?''
</P>
<P>
   Along with younger membership in AARP, Modern Maturity has a new
strategy and a new editor. He is 50 years old and has made a
startling discovery: People over 50 do actually engage in sex.
Therefore, the AARP publication is going to feature sexual topics
so senior citizens will be better informed about things previously
thought to recede into fond memories after the Big 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   Since I haven't been sick enough to go spend a day in Dr. Sams'
waiting room lately, I haven't actually read the Modern Maturity
story about ``great sex.'' I assume the editors decided to make the
subject a cover story after a survey turned up startling
information indicating that some Americans 45 and older enjoy
active sexual relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Being as this is a family newspaper, I'd never thought I'd write
a column about sex. I wouldn't now, except that with so many young
editors running things, a lot of misleading information is getting
into print.
</P>
<P>
   Having arrived at the stage in life when it's prudent to check
the obituary page before the sports or the funnies, I've become a
regular reader of the obits. What I read convinces me that the
people writing them must be in junior high. I was disturbed to read
a sentence that read something like this: ``He was active into his
seventies.'' The deceased was only 71 years old!
</P>
<P>
   As you get older, you do begin to wonder what the newspaper will
say about you at checkout time. The best I have hoped for is a
small headline that almost spells my name right: 'Jim Winter,
worked for papers.' With the new style of writing obits to include
human interest tidbits, maybe they will add a line pointing out how
that even at an advanced age I was able to do my own grocery
shopping every Wednesday so I could get the 10 percent discount.
</P>
<P>
   Like others in the over-the-hill category, I'm grateful for
advice meted out to senior citizens, even when it comes from
editors and writers barely out of the acne stage. As previously
mentioned, the company where I once was gainfully employed is
thoughtful enough to keep retirees supplied with an abundance of
helpful hints on topics from diet to driving a car.
</P>
<P>
   It's nice to be reminded to take our vitamins every day; to eat
more fiber and cut down on coffee; to get a flu shot; to keep our
hearing aids turned on when driving; and instead of making left
turns, circle the block and make a series of right-hand turns.
</P>
<P>
   Senior citizens have been overwhelmed with advice on everything
except sex. As I'm always looking for a way to supplement my Social
Security, I thought I saw an opportunity. I mentioned it to my wife
after reading the revelation about people over 50 having sex, and
how Modern Maturity is using sex stories and pictures to sell the
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's only the magazine segment of the market,'' I pointed
out. ``Why don't we do a husband-wife newspaper column about senior
sex? I bet we could syndicate and make a lot of money?''
</P>
<P>
   I thought her answer was unnecessarily sharp. ``Just go pick
your butter beans,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor in chief of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
