r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN21-COX     08-20 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Animals are people, too _ Or so think America's newest 'civil
rights' attorneys
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ There's new proof that lawyers are going to the
dogs.
</P>
<P>
   An emerging branch of animal jurisprudence will supply lawyers
with employment until the cows come home, if the cows want to come
home.
</P>
<P>
   No one should force a cow to come home against her will. Animals
have rights. They must not be considered property.
</P>
<P>
   Do not scoff. Animal civil rights lawyers are winning court
cases. Two of America's finest law schools _ Harvard and Georgetown
_ are preparing to offer animal law courses for bright young
students eager to make their mark in this new field.
</P>
<P>
   Last year an animal rights lawyer won a court case that gave
chimps the right to reside in group-living housing with appropriate
ape amenities.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, according to the New York Times, was filed under
1985 amendments to the Federal Animal Welfare Act that specifically
require ``the psychological well-being of primates.''
</P>
<P>
   A human visitor to the Long Island Game Farm Park and Zoo
thought that the rights of Barney (the zoo's chimpanzee) were being
violated. The United States Court of Appeals for the District of
Columbia Circuit agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Barney's case continues to climb the judicial appeals tree.
Barney does not. A zoo employee killed Barney after he escaped his
ape-inappropriate living quarters, tossed a sign at a
merry-go-round and bit someone. The incident smacks of a vast
anti-animal-rights-wing conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of lawyers across the nation are handling lawsuits on
behalf of animals. This new field of law promises to be profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Industry groups must hire lawyers skilled in fighting cases
brought by animal lawyers who can tap into millions of dollars
collected by animal welfare organizations that want to overturn the
principle that animals can be the property of humans.
</P>
<P>
   Steven M. Wise, the lawyer scheduled to teach the Harvard Law
School animal law course, once sued an aquarium on behalf of
Rainbow, a dolphin held captive by aquarium owners, according to
the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   A staff lawyer for the Animal Legal Defense Fund, according to
the newspaper, is studying legal precedents involving the
emancipation of slaves that can be used to assist animals.
</P>
<P>
   An animal law professor at Rutgers University has suggested that
gorillas should be considered ``persons'' under the U.S.
Constitution and granted constitutional rights.
</P>
<P>
   Animal lawyers point out that environmental and civil rights
lawyers also were ridiculed.
</P>
<P>
   If animal rights activists and their lawyers succeed in
overturning the legal principle that animals are property, then
people cannot own animals.
</P>
<P>
   If ranchers cannot own their cattle herds, surely they would
have to go to the courthouse and legally adopt each cow, bull,
steer and heifer by name. A few ranchers might object, but some
people always resist change.
</P>
<P>
   Once a rancher has adopted his cattle _ and all his sheep,
goats, chickens, dogs, cats and fish in his stock tanks _ the next
legal hurdle would come when he gave them up for adoption to a
slaughterhouse.
</P>
<P>
   No, it just won't work the old way.
</P>
<P>
   You can't take animals to market unless you can buy and sell
them. You can't buy and sell animals if they are not property. And
if you can't buy and sell animals, then you certainly have no right
to slaughter and consume your constitutionally protected animal
companions.
</P>
<P>
   So that's it. This new field of law is a one-way trip to
vegetarianism.
</P>
<P>
   Animal law will be an adjustment, of course. It's the next step
that worries me. That's when lawyers and law schools turn their
attention to plant law.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor at the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: rnethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
