<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woodworking builds respect for craftsmanship, tools
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Recently a correspondent on rec.woodworking asked
everybody how they got into woodworking and some of the answers
were rather striking. I'd like to share a few with you.
</P>
<P>
   ``My stepfather was a minister and a carpenter,'' replied one
woodworker. ``He was from the old school and could frame a house
using a handsaw and hammer and nails just about as fast (and much
more accurately) as any framer I ever saw.
</P>
<P>
   He made me work in costruction as a kid. While I thought it was
cruel back then, I gained a tremendous work ethic from him and I
owe a lot of my personal success to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I am substantially older and haven't had to work with my
hands in a while and can finally afford good tools. When I have the
time, I really enjoy making something that I can be proud of. I
also enjoy the problem solving. I never do a project directly from
plans. I use plans as a guideline and then try to improve on them
or make some changes. Finding solutions that allow you to turn out
a truly worthy piece is fun and challenging.''
</P>
<P>
   Another man added:
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought a 70-year-old house and I couldn't afford to have
other people work on it. I taught myself from books. Later on, I
worked as a carpenter's helper before I found a job as a computer
programmer (pays better).
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm trying to make nice furniture. It's a whole new ball
game.''
</P>
<P>
   And another:
</P>
<P>
   ``It is with a great, loving reverence that I use tools that
belonged to my great grandfather, that I remember my father using,
no doubt with the same reverence.
</P>
<P>
   ``My projects may not be masterpieces, but the soothing sound of
a plane slicing wood, or the sonorous tone of a hand saw cutting a
kerf is a relaxing therapy for my soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Another fellow replied to that:
</P>
<P>
   ``Well said. I often tell people that my woodworking is therapy
for me. That's one reason why I've moved more towards handtools for
my work. If my intent is to relax and unwind, then quieter tools
are the way to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also appreciate your idea of reverence for the tools
themselves. When I pick up an old plane, I am reminded of the man
who may have used it to make a living.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, from a soldier:
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was about 7 or 8 years old my dad was laid off from his
job as an operations manager at a power plant. The only job he
could find was delivering flowers 3 days a week. The rest of the
time he turned what had been a hobby into a business. I remember
many hours watching him work in an unheated metal outbuilding
making potato bins, bread boxes, signs and all sorts of stuff to
sell. Between that and mom working in a grocery store we got by. We
were never rich but there was always food on the table and clothes
on our backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then my junior year in high school I went to the local
vocational school and took carpentry. We built a 3,200-square foot
house my senior year. I joined the Army after high school and
didn't do any woodworking for about seven or eight years until I
moved into a place where I almost have the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I work in my carport out of a 5' x 8' storage closet where
my tools are stored. I spend my days at work teaching young
soldiers methods of destruction, so I balance that by creating
things when I'm at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of my tools were passed down to me from my dad, who
doesn't woodwork as much anymore because of arthritis. Whenever I
pick up one of his old tools it takes me back to the days when we
froze or baked together in that old metal shed. We never got rich,
but in a way I guess we were.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
