<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 11:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4029 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-DALAI-EVENT21-COX     08-20 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DALAI-EVENT21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dalai Lama brings message of love to sacred event in Indiana
 &HT;    By Kathy Whyde Jesse
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLOOMINGTON, Ind. _ A college cultivates a certain worldliness
in the community that surrounds it, and Indiana University is no
exception. Students from around the world bring pieces of their own
culture to this small southern Indiana town, and it makes for a
pleasant, mostly peaceful alchemy. It's a town where you can choose
from three Tibetan restaurants, or a number of bars with a good
selection of country-western on the jukebox.
</P>
<P>
   But just south of town, the country takes over. The narrow roads
dip and curve, and barn swallows dive crazily over open fields.
</P>
<P>
   The Tibetan Cultural Center keeps its distance here, located
about a quarter-mile off the road, on 90 acres of private property.
Still, it's been clear that something big is going on this week.
White tents have been erected inside the fence, and sheriff's
deputies keep traffic moving.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday afternoon, a group of bikers parked their Harleys
and formed a prayer circle in the yard next door to the Cultural
Center. ``Jesus, make the ground shake here tonight!'' A man
shouted and held his Bible high, while a woman swayed and spoke in
tongues.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Martindale was part of this spontaneous gathering of
Christians, a response to what's going on next door. ``Idolatry,''
he whispered. ``They're the anti-Christ.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are heating up spiritually.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, they are.
</P>
<P>
   While a small number of Christians spoke in tongues outside, a
larger number of Buddhists were chanting inside the largest tent _
expected to hold 5,000 this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The event is called the Kalachakra for World Peace 1999 _ one of
the most sacred of Buddhist rituals. It is being led by the Dalai
Lama, head of the Tibetan Buddhists, who have been driven into
exile by China.
</P>
<P>
   Security is tight at the Cultural Center. Nobody is allowed to
bring things in with them, and everyone passes through a metal
detector. Newspaper and television photographers have their
equipment checked by a dog trained to sniff out explosives.
</P>
<P>
   The Dalai Lama has made the rounds in the United States this
week, speaking to an adoring crowd in New York City's Central Park
last weekend; speaking in Indianapolis on Monday; participating in
a forum on youth violence Monday night, then at a public address
Wednesday in Bloomington.
</P>
<P>
   So, far, his message has been easily digestible across cultures
and religious traditions: Mankind is essentially loving and
compassionate; the 21st century will bring us to a ``oneness of
humanity.'' Call it Buddhism Lite.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kalachakra is a 2,400-year-old ritual, mysterious to
Westerners, with its sonorous chanting and clanging of cymbals. The
Dalai Lama, who is 64, has performed it only 25 times since his
exile in 1959. The Bloomington ceremony will end next Friday with
the public viewing and dismantling of a mandala _ a meditational
diagram, assembled grain by grain of colored sand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kalachakra is considered an almost magical thing, like a
communion,'' said Robert Thurman, professor of Tibetan studies at
Columbia University, who is attending the event. Kalachakra means
``wheel of time,'' in the sense that time is human evolution.
Buddhists are not monotheistic, but they believe in powerful,
all-loving deities who guide the world toward a time when it really
will be a better place, Thurman said.
</P>
<P>
   During the Kalachakra, a window in time opens, when participants
can get a glimpse of this ``fulfilling, joyful experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The mandala will be a representation of a palace, where the
deities can reside, according to Lhakdor, who serves as an English
translator for the Dalai Lama. Each particle of sand will be
transformed and visualized into the deities and the mansion. But
before that process begins, the monks seek permission from the
ground to build the mandala; then they bless the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The clanging of cymbals are ``offerings of sound, music _
everything that is good to the eye, the ear, and touching.'' Rice
is thrown as a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a Kalachakra ritual and offering dance will be
performed.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the tent, the proceedings may be exotic, but outside, on
the grounds of the Cultural Center, it's an all-American scene.
Vendors hawk prayer beads, books, Buddha statues, ``Dharmaware,''
Coke, candy bars, even Arby's roast beef sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to say how many of those on hand for the event are
practicing Buddhists. Monks wearing maroon robes, with shaved heads
and Adidas sandals, roam the grounds or tool about in golf carts.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the people here are dressed in secular garb. Allison
Kane came here from Canada. On her way to the tent, she stopped to
bow under the Kalachakra Stupa, a 45-foot-tall monument topped by a
copper and gold leaf spire. ``I'm just soaking up this good
sunshine and these good vibes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Daily events begin at 7 a.m. and last as late as 4:30 p.m., with
related evening events, such as a film festival, an art exhibit,
and lectures taking place elsewhere in the community. An interfaith
vigil for world peace will be held Monday at St. Charles Catholic
Church.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors are advised to arrive two hours early for events at the
Tibetan Cultural Center.
</P>
<P>
   How to go
</P>
<P>
   WHAT: Kalachakra for World Peace.
</P>
<P>
   WHEN: Through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE: The Tibetan Cultural Center, 3655 Snoddy Road,
Bloomington, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   COST: $50 per day; $40 for Tibetans, students and seniors.
</P>
<P>
   FOR MORE INFORMATION: Call (812) 334-7046, or visit the Web site
of the Tibetan Cultural Center at www.tibetancc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
