<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ There's new proof that lawyers
are going to the dogs. An emerging branch of animal jurisprudence
will supply lawyers with employment until the cows come home, if
the cows want to come home. No one should force a cow to come home
against her will. Animals have rights. They must not be considered
property. Do not scoff. Animal civil rights lawyers are winning
court cases. (Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   LATHAM-COLUMN _ This column will not move today.(Latham,
Marshall News Messenger)
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ Along with younger
membership in AARP, Modern Maturity, the group's magazine, has a
new strategy and a new editor. He is 50 years old and has made a
startling discovery: People over 50 do actually engage in sex.
Therefore, the AARP publication is going to feature sexual topics
so senior citizens will be better informed about things previously
thought to recede into fond memories after the Big 5-0. (Jim Minter
is a former editor of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ This column will not move today.(McCarty,
Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Death has taken a rare holiday in the Texas
criminal justice system, but don't expect it to stay long at the
beach. The Texas death penalty has a work ethic like no other. (Tom
Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED
THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ It was one of those channel-surfing nights. I
surfed over to ``Larry King Live'' on CNN. And who was it Larry was
talking with? I couldn't believe it. David Berkowitz, a.k.a. Son of
Sam; murderer of six women, fiend. What the hell are some of our
media coming to? (Howard Kleinberg is a columnist for Cox News
Service.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
