<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4033 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR; JOHN     08-20 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
   JOHN McGAIN: THE CANDIDATE WITH A PELLET
GUN  c
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sen. John McCain was in town Thursday, and I
didn't ask him the ``did-you-ever'' question.
</P>
<P>
   He made himself an easy target, too. He said of George W. Bush's
nasal privacy problems that ``the American people have a right to
know a lot of things.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said the media and the people decide the limits of
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   I decided to refrain from asking: ``Did you ever in the last 7,
15 or 25 years (or whatever Bush has established as a statute of
limitations on boyish naughtiness) shoot any beer cans with your
pellet gun?''
</P>
<P>
   Guns are of more interest to California voters than any
candidate's history of cocaine use. But I didn't want to get that
personal.
</P>
<P>
   Last week I read that all the major party presidential
candidates have toted guns, with the exception of Elizabeth Dole,
who seems so tough she doesn't need one. McCain's gun, according to
the story, is a pellet gun.
</P>
<P>
   It's just one more reason for moderates to like McCain. He
doesn't keep and bear a firearm. He keeps and bears a pellet gun.
</P>
<P>
   And because of his military record, right-wingers can't accuse
him of being a wimp who only shoots BBs.
</P>
<P>
   But California voters further to the left, which is a lot of
voters, might want to know more about that pellet gun, like if it's
an assault pellet gun.
</P>
<P>
   But I didn't want to go there. McCain _ a Republican from
Arizona _ faces enough potential problems on gun control.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech at the Commonwealth Club on Thursday, McCain
wriggled on gun control, calling for gun locks, tighter controls on
gun shows, development of high-tech gun safety devices, enforcement
of existing gun laws and an effort to restrain violence in the
media.
</P>
<P>
   It was the rhetorical equivalent of a pellet gun, with a lot of
air propelling a small, ineffectual projectile that could put
McCain's eye out. His gun-control stance (duck, basically) is
certain to offend both gun-owners and gun-haters.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is going the in-between route on both guns and abortion
in California, basically asking why Republicans can't all get
along.
</P>
<P>
   But who cares? McCain has character, principles, a real record
as an intelligent maverick and a sense of humor, even if it
sometimes gets mean. What's a sense of humor for, after all?
</P>
<P>
   And the press, Democrats and liberals love him. That's three
more reasons, besides character, he doesn't have a chance to be
president.
</P>
<P>
   One reason the press and Democrats like McCain is that he is an
actual, card-carrying human running for president as a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   He gave a knowledgeable and reasonable speech ranging from China
policy to labor issues in Silicon Valley, ending with references to
John F. Kennedy and a call to end cynicism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every place there's an illiterate adult, there's a great
cause,'' he said. ``Every place there's a hungry child, there's a
great cause...''
</P>
<P>
   OK, McCain sounded a little too much like Henry Fonda at the end
of ``The Grapes of Wrath,'' but most of the time he sounded like
John McCain, talking about big-money corruption of American
politics and making jokes about coming to California to visit
Arizona's water.
</P>
<P>
   Another winning quality to McCain is that he's edgy. After the
speech, he told a group of reporters, ``I'm ready to respond to any
questions, comments or insults.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm pretty sure I heard him say the same thing to the press a
few months ago. There's a prickliness to his humor that dares you
to take him on. The press likes that, too.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the press was more interested in getting McCain to
comment on Bush's problems than McCain's problems. That's the way
the game goes.
</P>
<P>
   The rich boy with $50 million in campaign funds has made his
first gaffe. Bush foolishly tried to avoid dumb questions about
past drug use by playing numerical games the way Bill Clinton
played grammatical games. That really put him in the barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Just as members of the media love seeing a front-runner in the
barrel, they love goading an opponent into poking him with sticks.
</P>
<P>
   McCain played the game his own skillful way, saying that his
personal opinion is that Bush is entitled to his privacy about any
past drug use, but noting there is a balance between privacy and
the public interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very delicate thing that we're going through,'' he
said. ``The American people are sort of feeling their way through
this, as is the media.''
</P>
<P>
   See why members of the media like this guy?
</P>
<P>
   McCain even said, ``I admire the way the media has treated
Chelsea Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   When I reminded him that a year ago he told a Republican crowd a
very offensive joke about Chelsea Clinton and Janet Reno (just from
the names involved you can guess how bad it was), he said he
regretted saying something so ``stupid, senseless and cruel'' and
hopes he never says anything like it again.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed genuinely remorseful. It's no fun shooting yourself in
the foot, even with a pellet gun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 1207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 12:09 </DATE_TIME>
