</P>
<P>
   One reason the press and Democrats like McCain is that he is an
actual, card-carrying human running for president as a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   He gave a knowledgeable and reasonable speech ranging from China
policy to labor issues in Silicon Valley, ending with references to
John F. Kennedy and a call to end cynicism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every place there's an illiterate adult, there's a great
cause,'' he said. ``Every place there's a hungry child, there's a
great cause...''
</P>
<P>
   OK, McCain sounded a little too much like Henry Fonda at the end
of ``The Grapes of Wrath,'' but most of the time he sounded like
John McCain, talking about big-money corruption of American
politics and making jokes about coming to California to visit
Arizona's water.
</P>
<P>
   Another winning quality to McCain is that he's edgy. After the
speech, he told a group of reporters, ``I'm ready to respond to any
questions, comments or insults.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm pretty sure I heard him say the same thing to the press a
few months ago. There's a prickliness to his humor that dares you
to take him on. The press likes that, too.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the press was more interested in getting McCain to
comment on Bush's problems than McCain's problems. That's the way
the game goes.
</P>
<P>
   The rich boy with $50 million in campaign funds has made his
first gaffe. Bush foolishly tried to avoid dumb questions about
past drug use by playing numerical games the way Bill Clinton
played grammatical games. That really put him in the barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Just as members of the media love seeing a front-runner in the
barrel, they love goading an opponent into poking him with sticks.
</P>
<P>
   McCain played the game his own skillful way, saying that his
personal opinion is that Bush is entitled to his privacy about any
past drug use, but noting there is a balance between privacy and
the public interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very delicate thing that we're going through,'' he
said. ``The American people are sort of feeling their way through
this, as is the media.''
</P>
<P>
   See why members of the media like this guy?
</P>
<P>
   McCain even said, ``I admire the way the media has treated
Chelsea Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   When I reminded him that a year ago he told a Republican crowd a
very offensive joke about Chelsea Clinton and Janet Reno (just from
the names involved you can guess how bad it was), he said he
regretted saying something so ``stupid, senseless and cruel'' and
hopes he never says anything like it again.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed genuinely remorseful. It's no fun shooting yourself in
the foot, even with a pellet gun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
