<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-RAYMOND-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYBODY LOVES `RAYMOND' (REALLY) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ At this time last year, the consensus was
``Everybody Loves Raymond'' was roadkill, toast, a cancellation
waiting to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were dead,'' co-star Brad Garrett said. ``I
thought we were history. I thought they were setting us up for the
kill. I thought I would be waitering at Friday's again.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS had decided to move the sitcom last fall from 8:30 to 9 p.m.
on Monday nights. So at the new time, with all the guys watching
``Monday Night Football,'' and all the women watching ``Ally
McBeal,'' just who would be left over to watch Ray Romano's sitcom
about a New York sportswriter and his extended family?
</P>
<P>
   Romano shivered at the memory of the moment: ``We were scared
(blank)less.'' Then two things happened. One was the show improved
markedly in its third season. That was not the surprise. What threw
critics, Romano and everyone else was that people tuned in, a lot
of them, propelling ``Raymond'' into the Top 20 for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were shocked more than anybody that we were getting the
numbers we were getting,'' Romano said. ``There just must be a ton
of people watching television on Monday night, because we thought
our days of coming in the Top 30 were over.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Garrett: ``We really, really found an audience, oddly
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Now cemented at 9 p.m., ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' has been
nominated for six Emmys, including outstanding comedy; lead actor
(Romano, as Ray Barone); lead actress (Patricia Heaton, as Romano's
wife, Debra Barone); supporting actor (Peter Boyle, as patriarch
Frank Barone); and supporting actress (Doris Roberts, as mom, Marie
Barone).
</P>
<P>
   Romano said the ratings and Emmy nods are great. ``You kind of
fantasize about it, and then you go back to work,'' he said, but
they have not lessened the pressure. That's because after 75 shows,
comedies must work hard to stay fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure now is that it's the fourth year,'' Romano said.
``Being funny is pressure no matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   Romano, who noted wryly that he has twice hosted the People's
Choice Awards, even though he was never nominated for one of their
awards, has some trouble believing he is in line for an Emmy just a
few short years after having to take acting lessons just to make
the transition from stand-up comic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a Y2K glitch (come) early,'' he said. Then he
concluded that, well, maybe it was just his turn.``I thought there
was nobody left,'' he said. ``I mean literally. There are a lot of
ensembles _ `Friends,' `Just Shoot Me' _ (but) there is no lead
actor. There weren't many eligible. I thought I might just get in
on that.''
</P>
<P>
   So Ray Romano is in. He is on Mondays at 9 p.m., and likes it.
He was this year's winner of the individual achievement in comedy
award from the Television Critics Association. The man who makes
his living portraying glum resignation does not have much to be
bummed about. In fact, only one thing would get him down and, no,
it's not if he lost out in the Emmy balloting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way I'm going to be disappointed if I don't win the
Emmy is if I come up with a funny (acceptance) speech,'' he said.
``Writing comedy is hard. If you got a killer speech and can't use
it, that is going to (tick) me off.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there is something Ray Romano doesn't mind worrying about.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
