<HEADER>
A4037 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-DEL-RIO-FLOOD-$ADV22-     08-20 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEL-RIO-FLOOD-$ADV22-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECOVERY REMAINS DISTANT YEAR AFTER POWERFUL FLOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 22)   (EDs: Photo available on Wieck database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL RIO, Texas _ On a blueprint spread flat on his kitchen
table, one corner anchored by a half loaf of bread, Juan Pablo
Infante displayed the familiar design of a spacious new house he is
itching to build for his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already bought another lot, on higher ground. All we're
waiting for is the money from the city,'' the burly carpenter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to buy my lot there. They are offering me
$30,000, but it was a two-story house and I think it was worth
$67,000. We're still negotiating,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Infantes, who now live in a government-issued mobile home,
were among several hundred Del Rio families who became homeless a
year ago when a killer flood ripped through the city's San Felipe
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Nine people died and about 700 families were displaced when the
San Felipe Creek, fed by 20 inches of rain from Tropical Storm
Charley, burst its banks early on the night of Aug. 23, 1998, in
this border city 140 miles west of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The flood caused $35 million in damage in Del Rio, the Val Verde
County seat with 35,000 residents, and triggered a massive and
extended relief effort.
</P>
<P>
   Today, almost all the outside help is gone.
</P>
<P>
   As the anniversary of the flood arrives, a small city staff
continues to grapple with the destruction and displacement wreaked
upon its oldest and poorest neighborhood, San Felipe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most daunting task is that we had a 100-year-old community
where people enjoyed a tremendous quality of life on a very low
income. They raised good kids. There was no crime, and then Mother
Nature ripped that neighborhood and hundreds of families from their
homes,'' said Thomas Nymann, the city's special projects director.
</P>
<P>
   ``So in some sense, we have to address the chemistry and sense
of community that was destroyed. To simply ask these residents to
go out and replace their housing, even if they had the means,
fragments the community,'' Nymann said.
</P>
<P>
   Housing remains the most pressing problem, and Del Rio has
formulated a program whereby homeowners in the flood plain can sell
their damaged homes to the city, which then demolishes them.
</P>
<P>
   In cases where the structure is less than 50 percent damaged,
the homeowner is allowed to repair it and return there to live.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no condemnation involved. It's totally voluntary, and
very few have said they do not want to be involved,'' Nymann said.
</P>
<P>
   More than $5 million in state and federal money is available to
buy flood plain property in San Felipe. The open lots will later be
used for parks and green spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Houses in the flood plain that are more than 50 percent damaged
can be rebuilt only if they are elevated, up to a dozen feet or
more, above the 100-year flood line. But for most, such
modifications are impractical.
</P>
<P>
   Already 50 families are involved in the purchase program, and by
Sept. 8, they will all have received buyout offers, Nymann said. A
second buyout phase will follow.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, he continued, about 170 houses in San Felipe will be
demolished. About half are already gone, and last week, wrecking
crews were busy tearing down more.
</P>
<P>
   Although clear lots and new parks have replaced the storm debris
and wreckage the flood left behind, much remains to be done.
</P>
<P>
   In San Felipe, scores of empty, flood-ruined houses marked for
demolition by green spray paint, sit waiting, many looking just as
they did the day after the flood.
</P>
<P>
   At Brown's Plaza, the 90-year-old heart of the community, bright
new paint adorns the kiosk and iron benches, but in the evening,
the flood-ravaged buildings that surround the square loom above it
like old ghosts.
</P>
<P>
   Of the businesses here, only the Texas Rural Legal Aid office
has reopened.
</P>
<P>
   And of the 134 homeless families who last year moved into
manufactured housing provided by the Federal Emergency Management
Agency, 121, including the Infantes, remain in their borrowed
mobile homes.
</P>
<P>
   All will have to leave by February. Some will buy the trailers
at reduced prices and move them to other sites. Others, like the
Infantes, will use the property buy-out money to build or buy
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, the money will come from sale of property in San
Felipe, but so far, the city has yet to close its first flood
buy-out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people are desperate. We've had a lot of meetings but
nothing happens. The money was available almost a year ago,''
Infante said.
</P>
<P>
   City workers say the complex program is slowed by unavoidable
red tape, and because in many cases, appraisals must be made of
houses that no longer exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of hurt and confusion, and we get a lot of
complaints. What hurts San Felipe is being illiterate to a lot of
the process,'' said Jesse Rodriguez, of the city's special projects
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people have to understand that this is something that
never happened before and may not happen again for 500 years,''
Rodriguez said of the massive flood.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Liz Elizalde, supervisor of mobile home operations for the Del
Rio Housing Authority, said ambivalence about selling and moving to
higher ground is typical of flood victims, particularly the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of them had lived there all their lives and paid for
their homes, and at this point I see confusion as to what to do
next. They are having to make decisions they never thought they'd
have to make,'' Elizalde said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard people say, `FEMA can take back everything they've
given me. Just give me back my one-bedroom house.' That's the
paradigm they live in, and its hard to adjust,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Elizalde said that of the 121 people currently in mobile homes,
81 plan to buy them, 30 are repairing their flood-damaged homes,
and 10 intend to buy or build a home elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Memo ``Blondie'' Calderon, well-known pianist and owner of a
riverside restaurant by the same name, will soon be reopening,
after surviving yet another flood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been here 63 years. We had a flood in '35, another in
'47, '52, '63, '75 and then the big one last year,'' Calderon said.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the glistening new dining room is a 1928
Steinway baby grand piano, purchased in part with donations from
Blondie's fans to replace the one ruined by the flood.
</P>
<P>
   But, Blondie said, he got little help in refurbishing his
flood-prone business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent $38,000, and I'm not through yet. It took a year
because I didn't get a loan. FEMA helped me a little bit with my
house but not here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, `If you want to get me out of here, you'd better
bring some ammunition,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Del Rio Recovers, an interdenominational housing
relief agency, closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rehabilitated close to 40 homes which means 40 families are
back in their homes,'' said Denita Patuel, the director of the
agency.
</P>
<P>
   But, Patuel said, long after everyone who was flooded out in San
Felipe has a place to live, the damage will endure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most difficult part is overcoming the loss of all their
belongings. The flood hit the lower-income sector of the
population, and whatever they had took them years to accumulate,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you lost everything, how do you show your child what your
father looked like? The picture is gone. The child will no longer
know what the grandfather looked like. Those are things you can
never replace,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
