<HEADER>
A4053 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SACCO-VANZETTI-HNS &LR;      08-20 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SACCO-VANZETTI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SACCO AND VANZETTI DIDN'T HAVE A FAIR TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA BASS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DANVILLE, Calif. _ Aug. 23 is the anniversary of the executions
of Sacco and Vanzetti, two of the most famous and controversial
defendants in 20th century history.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-two years after their deaths in 1927, few people know
much about them other than their forever-linked names. But their
courtroom battle in 1921 was the first ``trial of the century,''
dividing the nation and sparking worldwide protests.
</P>
<P>
   And the issue raised by their case _ the right to a trial which
is completely and unquestionably fair _ remains critical.
</P>
<P>
   For the rule of law to have any real meaning, everyone,
regardless of origins or politics _ regardless, even, of guilt _
must be entitled to a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   Considering how the affair convulsed first the nation and then
the world, the facts of the crime are simple. On April 15, 1920, in
South Braintree, Mass., a paymaster and a guard were gunned down
and killed. The motive was robbery: $16,000.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty days later, anarchists Nicola Sacco and Bartolomeo
Vanzetti were arrested. Both insisted _ and never wavered _ that
they were innocent. Both supplied alibis.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, both carried guns possibly linked to the
robbery, and both lied when questioned about their April 15
whereabouts. Both were indicted, tried and convicted, and both died
in the electric chair.
</P>
<P>
   The timing could not have been worse. The years just after the
Russian Revolution saw anti-immigrant sentiment in the United
States merge with anti-Bolshevism. It produced widespread loathing
of foreigners, political radicals and, especially, foreign
radicals.
</P>
<P>
   Anarchists were particularly feared, thanks to an orgy of
homemade bombs, including one which nearly killed the U.S. attorney
general. When a crime like the one in South Braintree took place,
foreigners were immediate suspects. When the suspects turned out to
be foreign radicals, they barely seemed to deserve a trial.
</P>
<P>
   And they barely got one. The trial judge, Webster Thayer, had
recently tried _ and convicted _ Vanzetti for armed robbery; for
him to be predisposed against Vanzetti isn't surprising, but his
prejudice toward the entire defense team (``those damn fools''),
especially attorney Fred Moore (``that long-haired anarchist from
California''), resulted in blatant bias which badly hurt both
defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did it help that each motion to retry (eight in all) had to
go before Thayer himself, who _ after rejecting motions 2 through 6
_ called the defendants ``anarchistic bastards.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial was flawed in other ways. Because of Sacco's and
Vanzetti's anarchism, it was assumed the trial was really about
politics; therefore, the defense team transformed their clients
into pulsing symbols of the oppressed Left.
</P>
<P>
   This strategy backfired, annoying the jurors, further
antagonizing Thayer and leaving problems with the prosecution's
case largely unchallenged.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, there was the Massachusetts state supreme court.
</P>
<P>
   Trapped by both legal technicalities and loyalty to a fellow
jurist, they supported all Thayer's rulings, however prejudiced.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the rejected appeals, one was especially egregious.
</P>
<P>
   In 1925, a convicted killer, Celestino Madeiros, sent Sacco a
note confessing to the murder. Madeiros was clearly an
untrustworthy creep but, since he had nothing to gain from
confessing, he seemed believable. The defense requested (again) a
new trial. But Thayer denied (again) their motion, saying Madeiros
was lying; the state supreme court (again) supported him. And that
almost was that.
</P>
<P>
   But not quite.
</P>
<P>
   In March '27, the case _ now a worldwide cause celebre _
exploded.
</P>
<P>
   Angrily labeling the entire affair a perversion of justice whose
meaning went far beyond the trial itself, Harvard law professor
(and future Supreme Court Justice) Felix Frankfurter all but called
Thayer not only biased but stupid.
</P>
<P>
   His public fury, combined with the death sentence pronounced by
Thayer one month later, prompted the governor to assemble a
committee for one last look at the details of the case. Had the
trial been fair? This committee said ``Yes.'' So Sacco and Vanzetti
died.
</P>
<P>
   Are they guilty? Ballistic tests in the 1960s convinced some
people that Sacco was; others questioned the authenticity of the
bullet tested. The '80s saw new revelations, new books and no
definitive answer. The question of guilt may never be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   What is clear is that the trial was biased. The judge
consistently favored the prosecution. Anarchism was presented first
as a character trait, then as a sign of guilt. Startling new
evidence was ignored. And the whole affair was conducted in an
atmosphere of rampant bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   If a trial is unfair but the guilty are punished, has justice
been done?
</P>
<P>
   Or is justice impossible without a fair trial?
</P>
<P>
   Such questions are best left to legal philosophers. What we do
know is this: An unfair trial, whatever the guilt (or innocence) of
those being tried, strikes a heavy blow to our justice system _ so,
heavy that its results, in the end, are as socially costly as crime
itself.
</P>
<P>
   (Historical novelist Cynthia Bass is an Examiner columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 1229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
