<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Saturday,
Aug. 21. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   BOMB _ For more than 80 years, chemical weapons and other
ordnance from a World War I-era research project have lay buried
beneath a cozy upscale D.C. neighborhood. They're even digging up
the backyard of the South Korean ambassador. 27. David Goldstein.
</P>
<P>
   DEAD: Autopsies are steadily losing their importance in Kansas,
Missouri and around the country, causing alarm among health care
professionals. They fear that patient care quality and medical
knowledge have been reduced as a result of the decline. Autopsies
have dropped because of efforts to reduce health care costs and
advances in medical technology. Bobby White. Photo, graphic.
</P>
<P>
   FAYE: Aug. 4 was just like every day for Faye Copeland. She rose
at 5 a.m. along with 1,402 other incarcerated women, drank a cup of
coffee and tended to her seedlings in the greenhouse. But there was
one difference in this 24-hour span. In a Kansas City court clerk's
cubicle some 220 miles away was a stack of papers holding one of
the best birthday presents Copeland may ever get in her life _ a
judge's commutation of her death sentence. Barring an appeal from
Attorney General Jay Nixon within 45 days of this judgment,
Copeland won't die in prison by lethal injection. But she will
probably still die there. Lee Hill Kavanaugh. 35. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   MED: The University of Kansas Medical Center starts a new ``mini
medical school'' for consumers who want to expand their knowledge
of various medical topics. Possible graphic. Alan Bavley.
</P>
<P>
   PHELPS. An anti-gay web site operated by The Rev. Fred Phelps is
taken over by a pro-gay web site operated by a gay man in New
Hampshire; he says he didn't hack into any computers and that the
transfer of the site was legal; a member of the Phelps family says
they don't believe him. Robert A. Cronkleton. 15
</P>
<P>
   BUREAU. Johnson County, Kan., where the numbers of county
employees has soared, shows what's happening nationally: a new
Census Bureau study finds that the total state and local government
workers in the U.S. has grown. In Kansas, on a per capita basis,
the state has the sixth-highest number of government workers in the
country. Missouri is in the middle. 25. John A. Dvorak. Chart
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   ROYALS. Kansas City at Tampa Bay, 6:05 p.m. Dick Kaegel. 16-18.
</P>
<P>
   MOON. A chat with Warren Moon on the eve of his first real snaps
with the Chiefs. He's expected to play against the Bucs on Saturday
night. Adam Teicher. 18-20.
</P>
<P>
   POZ. Joe Posnanski column wrapping up Chiefs training camp.
Who's looked good? Who hasn't?
</P>
<P>
   MU. Sizing up the Tigers' quarterback battle. Mike DeArmond.
</P>
</TEXT>
