<HEADER>
A4071 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-APARTHEID-ARTIST-HNS &LR;      08-20 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APARTHEID-ARTIST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE HIS FILM, SOUTH AFRICAN TRIES TO UNDERSTAND HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KRIS WORRELL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In the animated short film ``Felix in Exile,''
Felix Teitlebaum is a sensitive artist trapped in a country scarred
by tragedy and trauma. Made in 1994, just prior to South Africa's
first post-apartheid election, the film explores ``the condition of
someone trying to understand history,'' said the filmmaker, William
Kentridge.
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said for Kentridge himself.
</P>
<P>
   The acclaimed white South African artist has devoted much of his
career to chronicling the horrors of apartheid and post-apartheid
life in his homeland. The artist, former actor, designer and
theater director has found international attention with his stark
animated portrayals of the country's troubled history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The films have to do with traces of the past in the present,''
he said in a recent telephone interview from his home in
Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
   Kentridge, who began making films a decade ago, uses a primitive
technique to create his films, which are typically four to eight
minutes in length. He draws and redraws each sketch in charcoal,
filming the state of each drawing as he goes, thus creating rough,
textured, flickering images that change and mutate, the traces of
which are plainly visible. The artist makes about 20 drawings for
each film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no animation training or skill,'' said Kentridge, who
noted that his style (which he sometimes refers to as
``stone-age'') ``developed organically.'' He started out filming
his drawings, just to record what they looked like as they evolved.
It didn't occur to him until later that he could put them together
to create moving images.
</P>
<P>
   ``Animation has gotten really high-tech,'' said Katherine Myers
of the Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art in Lenox. ``His
technique is hand-drawn. Not to say he's not sophisticated, but
it's much more raw. You see the hand of the artist much more. The
technique is very intimate.''
</P>
<P>
   The technique is reflective of Kentridge's focus on the ``memory
and process'' involved in both politics and art. Kentridge was 6
years old when he first came across a set of photographs of the
1960 Sharpeville Massacre, during which the South African police
fired on a group of black demonstrators at the village of
Sharpeville, killing 67 and wounding 186. It was the first time
Kentridge realized that the world was not as he thought it was.
Since then, he has tried to recreate for audiences the experience
he had when he first saw those pictures that is, to get back to
that first sense of shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's art in the service of social change,'' Myers said.
``There's a story to his films. They're not overtly political. They
are more subtle than that.''
</P>
<P>
   By focusing closely on the lives and inner struggles of several
characters, Kentridge's films aim to see the political through the
personal.
</P>
<P>
   Other than ``Felix in Exile,'' Kentridge's ``Stereoscope''
(1999) features another recurring character, Soho Eckstein, whom
Kentridge describes as ``the quintessential industrialist'' _
white, wealthy, pin-striped. As mobs of people protest in the
streets, Soho sits at his desk, guilt-ridden and weeping.
</P>
<P>
   ``The films are about his weaknesses as opposed to his strengths
his anxieties, his guilt,'' said Kentridge. As the name implies,
``Stereoscope'' explores ``the divided self.''
</P>
<P>
   ``History of the Main Complaint'' (1997) finds Soho comatose in
the hospital, with ``the body as a metaphor for the psyche,''
Kentridge said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ubu Tells the Truth'' (1997) was gleaned from Kentridge's 1997
theater production ``Ubu and the Truth Commission,'' which
incorporated live actors, puppets and animation, and fashioned
after the title character in Alfred Jarry's trilogy of plays. The
film, which was a finalist for the Guggenheim Museum's Hugo Boss
Prize in 1998, features a mixture of animation and archival
material from apartheid history, including footage of the
Sharpeville massacre, the 1976 Soweto uprising and the recent
hearings of the Truth and Reconciliation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living in South Africa during the last 30 years, politics was
so much a part of what was eaten and breathed that it would be
difficult not to be influenced by it,'' the artist said.
</P>
<P>
   Kentridge's work has been shown in Istanbul, Havana, Sydney and
Johannesburg, and, in this country, in Houston, New York, Santa Fe
and San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his animation work, Kentridge, 44, has created
documentaries, full-length features and puppet productions. He is
at work on a new film titled ``Procession,'' which will be shown in
Turkey next month.
</P>
</TEXT>
