<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4086 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-SEBASTIAN     08-20 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-SEBASTIAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ADVENTURES OF ADOLESCENT WHIMSY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the big highs of Tod Williams' ``The Adventures of
Sebastian Cole'' is the way its hero with the oily black locks
never talks to the camera. He never shoots us a sideways glance or
addresses his audience in a voice-over that would presume to tell
you everything a lesser filmmaker was too inept to show you.
</P>
<P>
   More ``Rushmore's'' Max Fischer than Ferris Bueller, Sebastian
Cole (Adrian Grenier) is an underachieving high school junior
trying to graduate early so he can leave his upstate New York
microcosm.
</P>
<P>
   He says he wants to abandon it but keeps returning like it's
some ultra-vivid primal scene. He doesn't need to talk to us
because his charming delinquency speaks for itself. If there's
anything self-conscious about Williams' 17-year-old creation,
Sebastian Cole, it's that he lives life as if it were truth 24
frames per second, all cinema all the time. But he's neither the
insouciant camcorder brat of his Reagan-era times nor the
media-ravaged cynic that would follow them. Rather, Sebastian is a
more atavistic strain of disaffected youth, one who feels like he's
been lifted from the Louis Malle sketchbook.
</P>
<P>
   He's aimless, lonely but searching for some kind of
magnificence, even if it's just in something as evanescent and
dastardly as laying a smacker on his girlfriend's best friend
(Merit Weaver) in the rush of having just done whippits with her;
or something as quasi-valiant as rescuing a part-time prostitute
from her lazy pimp called Chinatown (Rory Cochrane).
</P>
<P>
   Williams' is a remarkable debut that instantly conjures Hal
Hartley in its mild deadpan stylings. But there's a heart beating
under all the pallor, and where Hartley manufactures irony,
Williams discovers it as if its participation in his movie was
completely out of his hands. It's a talent that director Wes
Anderson and his co-writer Owen Wilson have in spades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sebastian'' also has in Grenier and Clark Gregg as Sebastian's
stepfather, Hank, a poignant duo reminiscent of the rapport Jason
Schwartzman had with Bill Murray in Anderson and Wilson's better
structured, more adventurous ``Rushmore.''
</P>
<P>
   Early, Williams' script has difficulty finding its footing in
how best to tell Sebastian's story. He walks awkwardly into Hank's
disclosure that he intends to become a transsexual. It's an
announcement that sends Sebastian's mother (Margaret Colin) packing
back to her native England and lands his sister (Marni Lustig) on
the back of her boyfriend's (Gabriel Macht) bike headed for her
freshman year at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   It's Sebastian who remains close to Hank, forging a filial bond
with him more substantial than the one he has with his biological
father (John Shea). In an auspicious, affecting performance,
Grenier walks the fine line between obnoxiousness and congeniality,
pretentiousness and endearment. The 23-year-old has the face of a
teen-age Peter Gallagher with the mop-top hair and self-destructive
restlessness of an Oasis' Gallagher brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Williams has Sebastian serving as his object of whimsy,
10-speeding through the school halls in a ski mask, uselessly
chasing his school bus as Flock of Seagulls' ``I Ran'' races over
the soundtrack, attempting to graduate by filling his phys ed
requirement. Sebastian does this with a demonstration of a
proficiency in karate.
</P>
<P>
   It's a beautifully stupid scene stripped of soundtrack noise and
filled with only the sound of Grenier's sputtered ``hi-yas'' as he
crashes to the gym mats and an undistinguished panel of P.E.
teachers look on in relative astonishment, blinded by the organic
marvel of the moment in all its clumsy glory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 1303EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4104 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-TINGLE-HN     08-20 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-TINGLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A CLASS OF ITS OWN, `MRS. TINGLE' FAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You probably won't see a more pathetic sight this year than
Helen Mirren, wrists strapped to each end of a headboard, splayed
on the mattress as though she were the general's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   But Mirren's torturers aren't the frat boys of the U.S. Army.
</P>
<P>
   They're a trio of high school seniors who've taken their
vengeance too far in ``Teaching Mrs. Tingle,'' an infuriatingly
indulgent piffle of adolescent wish-fulfillment hellbent on taking
its own vengeance too far. Freeze-frame on that image of a
relatively helpless Mirren, for a sec. It's courtesy of Kevin
Williamson, the 35-year-old teen-man credited for ushering in the
capitalist deluge/youthquake called Teensploitation.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood and newsweeklies swarmed Williamson as if he'd
invented the cynical overstimulated teen-ager; he just gave it some
cliches to bust. Since Williamson materialized as a screenwriter in
1996 from the seemingly thin air of a moribund slasher genre with
``Scream,'' it was only a matter of commercial breaks until the
``Dawson's Creek'' creator tried to bust a movie of his own. When
word came that his directorial debut was to be ``Killing Mrs.
Tingle,'' a thriller he'd written about three students who take
their vicious history teacher hostage until she mellows, the
potential product had the suitable sting of catharsis. Who hasn't
fantasized about making a draconian teacher repent?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that was five or six high-school blood baths, seven
``Dawson's'' knockoffs and one rain-checked ``Buffy'' season finale
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever felt conceptually bracing about ``Mrs. Tingle'' 18
months ago is now grist for Pop Culture Court. ``Teaching Mrs.
Tingle'' still has three 12th-graders holding a grumpy teacher
hostage.
</P>
<P>
   But Williamson has written this thing with so much worship for
his 25-and-below audience that he's incapable of giving an adult
something edgewise to counter his dangerous
``teens-are-everything'' sycophancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Tingle'' is filled with enough post-grunge Prozac pop on
the soundtrack and sardonic lines delivered in a single breath to
choke VJ Carson Daly and a ``Party of Five'' cast member. (``You're
on the wrong side of glib, Mrs. Tingle,'' warns co-captor and ``7th
Heaven'' dreamboat Barry Watson as the dumb but unnaturally
articulate boozer.)
</P>
<P>
   Williamson has no idea what to do with himself here, happy to
let his cooler-than-you cast run amok in his riskless, conceited,
half-conceived and misguided comic-thriller. Trapped in a fun house
of incidental self-parody, he can't even make entertaining kitsch
of Molly Ringwald in a small part as a Mrs. Tingle sub.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Tingle'' is so afraid of disappointing its audience that
it requires its three leads to do less than they do on their shows
_ or in co-captor Marisa Coughlan's case, will do; Williamson made
her the star of post-teen-age ``Wasteland.'' But there's a certain
irresponsibility in crafting a clan of mini-heckraisers with zero
functional intelligence, marginalized psychologies and the
emotional depth of a soap dish that makes ``My So-Called Life''
look positively avant-garde and ``Kids'' seem like the apocalyptic
last testament.
</P>
<P>
   Williamson is the youngest grown-up in Hollywood trying to
parlay memories of adolescence into billions of dollars, showing
them in a retail mirror _ warped to appear skinnier, hotter, more
willing to spend. And in the wake of the casualties from one
ruptured vessel in the Heartland to the next, Miramax (via its
Dimension Films) even decided to step down from ``killing'' Mrs.
Tingle to just ``teaching'' the old bird a lesson. But what exactly
has she learned? Namely, that it doesn't pay to be an authority
figure _ especially when you are, as Mrs. Tingle is, sound enough
of mind to be disgusted with the lot of trendsetters and
ne'er-do-well Abercrombie shoppers to whom you've been assigned to
teach 12th-grade English. Mrs. Tingle seems to have honed her
student-body-wide contempt on one innocent little looker named
Leigh Anne Watson (``Dawson's'' Katie Holmes).
</P>
<P>
   Williamson wants you to believe that a) Mrs. Tingle is the
teacher from hell and b) she's preying on Leigh Ann because Leigh
Ann lives in a smaller house than her friends and has a disgraceful
waitress mom (Lesley Anne Warren) who dozes off in front of the
television every night. Neither of these proves to be accurate,
which brings us back to Mirren being tied to that bed.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tingle's been strapped there for having caught Leigh Ann
with Jolynn (Coughlan) and Luke (Watson), in the gymnasium holding
a copy of her final exam _ a test she needs to ace if she's gonna
win the only scholarship that'll get ``Mommie's little writer'' out
of her podunk suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Mirren plays Eve Tingle in an Anjelica
Huston-as-Morticia-Addams funk, all arched eyebrows,
elongated-uninflected phrasings and the hint that she might be a
little bit kinky. But because Williamson's most developed character
is the one he presents of himself to the media, it's up to Mirren
to figure exactly what to do with her character. Her verdict is
that she can find nary a reason to play her as a monster, so she
tries making her an interesting hostage, smarter than, but
vulnerable to her captors.
</P>
<P>
   The embarrassment you feel for her is edible as she watches
Coughlan do an ``Exorcist'' impersonation in a scene that is
nothing more than a glamorized outtake _ most of the film feels
assembled this way _ that Coughlan beats you into laughing at.
Mirren just rots there in Williamson's wasteland, seemingly wishing
she were in a movie revolution-minded enough to let a teacher knock
off her pupils.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 1317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
