<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4113 &Cx1f; tth-z
u l BC-ARTS-CAMP-ART-2TAKES-     08-20 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-CAMP-ART-2TAKES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THIS CAMP, IT'S EVERYONE INTO THE ARTS POOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT L. JAMIESON JR.  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Summer day camp for kids.
</P>
<P>
   Fun, fun, fun ...
</P>
<P>
   ... NOT!
</P>
<P>
   Think about it: those off-key counselors crooning corny
clap-along songs; the arts and crafts sessions of scratch pads and
broken Crayolas; and games so boring that time seriously fails to
fly.
</P>
<P>
   But a different picture of day camp is unfolding at The
Evergreen School in north Seattle, where the annual rite of
childhood summer is undergoing a state-of-the-art makeover,
courtesy of billionaire Paul Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Kids are soaking up art _ from music and drama to film and
sculpture _ while working alongside master artists and counselors
who nurture budding talent and creativity.
</P>
<P>
   The campers _ between the ages of 8 and 14 _ also are exposed to
technology during the two-week sessions, which gives them a strong
sense of how science relates to art.
</P>
<P>
   Interested in computers? Whisk over and learn animation and Web
design. Like music? Then create a CD or write a musical score.
Enjoy movies? Make a documentary. Prefer the stage? Act. Got stage
fright?
</P>
<P>
   Bone up on backstage production.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to these camp projects, surprise guests drop by and
share slices of their personal lives. Now in its second year, the
camp's current and past visitors have included jazz vocalist
Ernestine Anderson, glass artist Dale Chihuly, actor Tom Skerritt,
members of the rock band Presidents of The United States of America
and even, as one young camper put it, ``that guy who did the
special effects for `Jurassic Park.' What's his name again?''
</P>
<P>
   Call it day camp for the next millennium, though its official
name is the Experience Arts Camp. The program is part community
outreach, part educational extension of Allen's Experience Music
Project, the $100 million-plus interactive multimedia and learning
museum that will open next spring at the Seattle Center.
</P>
<P>
   In camp-speak, the program, which ends its second summer this
week, could very well be dubbed: ``Camp Follow Your Bliss.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because everyone - from camp organizers to counselors to
esteemed visitors - echo a common belief that bright, young people,
if given a little guidance and responsibility, should be allowed to
roam vast artistic pastures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are about giving kids a great sense of their potential by
exposing them to opportunities they may have never had before,''
says Zoe Melendez, special projects manager for Experience Arts
Camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you take a practicing artist who is successful and give
kids a chance to work with them, that connection is profound,'' she
says, adding, ``Kids will push beyond what they thought they could
ever do.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many of the young campers are experiencing a creative
blossoming. One father said his daughter, after hearing Anderson
last week, rushed home on wings of inspiration and wrote a song.
</P>
<P>
   Treaudain Christian, an unfailingly polite camp participant who
wears an oversize Sonics T-shirt, tells his mother and counselors
that he wants to be an actor. No. Playwright. No, wait. . . . His
mind seems to change each day because, well, he is encountering new
things that are attention- grabbing.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say, Treaudain digs the arts; his mother, Angye
Alexander, who volunteers at the camp, appreciates his zeal. She
says she is pleased that campers find kinship over the course of
the two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these kids, before they come here, believe they are
the only one who keeps a journal,'' Alexander says, watching
children play a day-camp staple - kickball - during a lunch break.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think, `Nobody else is like me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There are 80 children enrolled in this year's second two-week
session geared to ages 11 to 14. The session held earlier this
summer had the same number but was designed for those between 8 and
12. (The age groupings are created primarily to accommodate
different maturity levels among the kids, who fill out an
application for the program.)
</P>
<P>
   The camp costs $575 a session, but 30 percent of the campers
qualify for scholarships that are funded through private donations.
Melendez says the cost of the non-profit camp is comparable to
other day camps, and is far below the actual cost of what it takes
to put on the program. The camp draws high-caliber teachers and
accomplished guest speakers, who are paid a nominal fee. And costs
are incurred on field trips to artists' workshops and museums.
</P>
<P>
   Base camp this summer is Evergreen, a private school the camp is
renting because it is quasi-urban, quasi-pastoral and all-round
conducive to the artistic learning that is at the program's core.
Its first year was conducted at the University Child Development
School in the University District.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the value of the program is measured by the campers.
Let's take a look:
</P>
<P>
   Inside a red, wood-sided structure 18 campers are hanging on
every note luffing from the harmonica of Lee Oskar. Their ears
never heard Oskar's musical wizardry in the 1970s when his tunes
helped to define the sound of War, the funkadelic band.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 1324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4114 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-WASHINGTON-DROUGHT-AR     08-20 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASHINGTON-DROUGHT-ART-2TAKES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FARMERS FACE CRITICAL LOSSES IN YEAR OF WITHERING HARVEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDD SLIVKA  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   POMEROY, Wash. _ It is hot as the Devil's kitchen in the fields
of this year's failed wheat crop. A searing wind kicks up dust from
the roads and drags it into the empty blue sky.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Cox sways from side to side in his dull-silver combine,
coming up a hill and gazing out at a field of spring wheat that is
much thinner than it should be.
</P>
<P>
   Cox's almost-black eyes do a flat, sad stare under his blue ball
cap as he looks out and wonders how he's going to pay bills this
winter.
</P>
<P>
   The dryland farmers _ those who farm without benefit of
irrigation from the Oregon border straight up to the Okanogan
Valley and from the Columbia River to the Idaho border _ are
getting hammered this summer. Nowhere is the wheat crop worse than
in the southeastern pocket of the state, in Garfield, Franklin,
Walla Walla and Whitman counties.
</P>
<P>
   In an age where small American farms are struggling to survive,
a season like this summer could bring many Washington farms to
their end.
</P>
<P>
   When it costs $3.29 to produce a bushel of wheat but farmers can
get only $3.12 when they sell, there's not much to believe in these
days, except that maybe next year will be better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is mortgaged,'' Cox says. ``We had equity in the
mid-'80s, we were on our way to building a retirement fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all gone now.''
</P>
<P>
   The same heat that baked the country and caused 285 deaths in
the East has been equally fierce in Washington's breadbasket this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the rich, golden brown they should be, wheat fields
are a hard, sun-scorched brown or bleached-out white, like the
field Cox is combining.
</P>
<P>
   This is farming, and bad years are expected.
</P>
<P>
   But no one ever expected things to get this bad _ a result of
poor yields, the federal government using wheat as a bargaining
chip in foreign relations and a glut of wheat producing nations on
the world market.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Gov. Gary Locke asked the federal government to
declare the southeastern part of the state a disaster area to get
federal relief funds; the federal government has yet to respond.
Wheat farmers are hoping to meet with Sen. Slade Gorton and Rep.
George Nethercutt, both Washington Republicans, to plead their case
for disaster relief subsidies and low-interest loans to help them
get through until next year and, hopefully, a better crop.
</P>
<P>
   All of the meetings are to help farmers like Cox, who saw his
fields produce 40 bushels per acre of winter wheat this year, when
their average proven yield is 54 bushels per acre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winter wheat was our best crop; spring wheat looks like it
will be 50 percent off the average.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking at our overall production off the farm, this is the
worst I've seen in 22 years,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   It started last winter, which was mild until the week before
Christmas. Then the temperature plummeted below zero and the ground
froze, followed by a heavy snow which melted in a warm flash before
it had a chance to seep into the ground. Spring was cold and wet,
and the weather delayed planting a week to 10 days for most
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the summer, where no rain fell. Or little enough rain
that it didn't make the least bit of difference.
</P>
<P>
   A thunderstorm would blow in and wet the soil, then the winds
would pick up to 30 mph and two hours later there wouldn't be a
drop of moisture left on the field or in the soil.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the rains came. Last week. When area farmers were
trying to get their wheat in.
</P>
<P>
   In short, everything that could go wrong this year has.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I do real well with the weather,'' Cox says.
``Sometimes I don't. The other morning it was raining and I was so
despondent about it that I had to go off and be by myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The book of troubles
</P>
<P>
   Every setback in the weather is recorded in black and white. The
farmers write down rainfall, crop yield, crop conditions _ all the
information in longhand in little black books with rubber bands
around them or in big loose-leaf notebooks.
</P>
<P>
   The books this year all read the same, no matter where in
southeastern Washington the farmers were: more rain fell the week
of Aug. 9 than fell the entire months of June and July.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Neff, who dryland farms in Franklin County near Pasco, can
look in his little black book and see that June brought one-tenth
of an inch of rainfall, July fourteen-hundredths of an inch.
</P>
<P>
   To the north, in Garfield County, David Ruark can look in a
folder of rumpled papers and see that .92 inches fell in June and
.13 inches came down in July.
</P>
<P>
   Or he can look at the spring barley in his fields and see that
this year he'll get only 60 percent of what he expected, the rest
lost to drought.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Koller lives about 15 miles east of Ruark, north of
Pomeroy, and his weather book is about as depressing as the crop
yield.
</P>
<P>
   The year has not been good for Koller, his wife and two sons.
Winter wheat was off between 10 percent and 30 percent, depending
on the field it was harvested from.
</P>
<P>
   The recent rains have rendered him unable to get into the fields
to see what his spring crop is like.
</P>
<P>
   Monday afternoon found him squatting in one of his fields
overlooking the Snake River, testing a sample and finding it too
wet. Wet wheat doesn't play well with the granaries, who find that
it molds and gets hot in the silos when it comes in with a moisture
content of above 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The granaries will dock a farmer for anything. Hot weather can
make wheat too light, and that's worth a few cents per bushel off.
Wet weather can cause mold, and that, too, pushes prices down a few
cents per bushel. Getting the grain in at the right time is
essential.
</P>
<P>
   But with this year's crop, there may not be a right time.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my neighbors cut into his wheat the other day to make a
road,'' Koller says. ``And he said (the wheat) wasn't good.''
</P>
<P>
   Koller has been holding out harvesting his spring crop, hoping
it dries out enough to be salvageable. He estimates it will be 30
percent to 40 percent off the average.
</P>
<P>
   His family has been farming the area since the early 1900s;
Koller lives in a house his great-uncle built in 1916. In August
1973, he saw wheat selling for $3.47 a bushel in Portland, Ore.,
where most of the area's grains go.
</P>
<P>
   Monday morning, wheat was selling for $3.12 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that a good year would make up for a bad year,''
Koller says, sitting in a kitchen decorated with Washington State
University paraphernalia and school drawings from his kids. ``Now
it's like every bad year takes two years just to get out of.
</P>
<P>
   ``You used to be able to have a down year and it wouldn't bother
you so much. Now, you need the crops on a yearly basis. It seems
like we're farming year to year.''
</P>
<P>
   But they know the band's songs, including ``Low Rider'' and
``The Cisco Kid,'' either because they've looked it up on the
Internet or gotten tips from their parents. When Oskar stops
playing and talking, the kids swarm him as if he were a Beastie
Boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to say thank you,'' says 13-year-old Michael Nunes
of Seattle. ``Some of your theories about music were really, really
cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Oskar, slightly embarrassed, later explains the message he hoped
to impress upon the kids: ``It's not about the scales and the
lessons and the theory - those are just tools,'' the 51-year-old
Redmond resident says. ``But it takes people to make music.''
</P>
<P>
   Sue Ennis, a songwriter for the rock band Heart and a master
artist for the music class, adds: ``Some kids have never just
opened up and played,'' she says. ``Once these young people learn
there is no wrong way to do anything, it opens up their world of
creativity.''
</P>
<P>
   In an adjacent room, Nancy, a pretty girl with long hair and big
dimples, is touching up glass artwork that is real old school. She
is employing grisaille, a method dating back to the medieval period
that involves etching intricate leadwork on the back of a glass
sculpture. After the glass is fired and painted, the result is a
milky iridescence of colors that is vibrant when light passes
through the glass.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy gets bold. She recommends that a buddy use blue for her
glass plate. Never mind that Nancy is an 11-year-old camper and the
buddy she is advising is Cathy Chase, an accomplished artist and
class teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, art is like my life,'' Nancy says, drawing hoots of
praise from Chase and Cappy Thompson, the course's master artist,
who appreciate Nancy's moxie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so happy God gave me this talent,'' Nancy coos, bounding
away with her left shoelace untied.
</P>
<P>
   Across the school's campus, the students in the film class are
hatching an idea to put together a final documentary loosely
paralleling ``The Blair Witch Project'' horror flick.
</P>
<P>
   But in their version, a group of students making a documentary
are uncertain of what they are searching for; as of earlier this
week, the idea was still - to borrow the Hollywood parlance - in
development.
</P>
<P>
   The campers' notions about film are less embryonic. At times
they sound as if they go to the University of Southern California
film school, speaking about story arcs and dramatic tension, their
knowledge greatly expanded after they spend time with Roger
Baerwolf, a producer on the movie ``Smoke Signals,'' Craig Barr
(the person who handled the mechanical special effects for the
tyrannosaurus rex in ``Jurassic Park'') and their classroom
teacher, Brad Tollefson, a digital filmmaker who lives in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Tollefson has done plenty to give the kids a crash course in
film. They've discussed film theory. Written on a board are the
words ``wide angle,'' ``low,'' ``depth,'' ``opposite'' - terms for
camera positions and use. And there is a quote: ``A safe filmmaker
lives long enough to become a . . .'' with two blanks at the end of
the sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``GREAT filmmaker!!!'' a couple of kids sound off, thankfully
filling in the blanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned the real definition of drama,'' 13-year-old Lacey
Stuart explains, ``is when you have to provoke actors with a
situation that involves, um, conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, crisis!'' cuts in Kimberly Manning, an aspiring magazine
editor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, crisis,'' Lacey corrects, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly adds: ``We also learned a saying about plots in movies:
`You want to chase an actor up a tree, throw rocks up at him for an
hour and bring him back down. Then the audience will be
interested'.''
</P>
<P>
   She eyes a reporter writing in a notebook. ``Are we overwhelming
you with all of this information?''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone laughs.
</P>
<P>
   When the students leave Experience Arts Camp, each will have
completed a project. In Nancy's case that means a cool-looking
glass sculpture. For other campers there will be CDs, self-designed
Web pages, a short play they will perform, or a song or short film.
</P>
<P>
   But Alycia Long Allen, camp director, said the most important
aspect of the kids' experience is the process of learning, not the
product. (And camp instructors, many of whom took part because they
love children, say they learned from the kids!)
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Poitier, who has been teaching the students who chose to
focus on drama, sums it up this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``What we teach is passion!'' says Poitier, who delayed
development of a television sitcom project in the Bahamas because
she was so enthusiastic about being a part of the camp. ``They are
free to express themselves. No inhibitions, no qualms.''
</P>
<P>
   To underscore her point, Poitier - daughter of actor Sidney
Poitier - mentions a recent class in which, during just three
hours, campers learned a whole play, ``Why Mosquitoes Buzz in
People's Ears,'' based on West African folklore. For good measure,
the kids added a complex Brazilian martial-arts dance to the
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours? Start to finish?
</P>
<P>
   ``No one told them they couldn't do it,'' Poitier says, beaming.
``You break down those walls and they go right ahead and do it. And
we hope that is one lesson they will take with them for the rest of
their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   (END)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 1326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
