<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4119 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-WASHINGTON-DROUGHT-AR Wash.:yeartoyear   08-20 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASHINGTON-DROUGHT-ART-2NDTAKE-SPI </SLUG>
   POMEROY, Wash.: year to
year.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Low prices and bad yields are expected in farming; one area
farmer jokes that his grandfather farmed the land for 41 years and
saw one ``normal'' year. But this year has heaped insult after
insult onto injury after injury.
</P>
<P>
   The state's agriculture department projects the winter wheat
harvest statewide to average 58 bushels an acre, a third higher
than many farmers in southeastern Washington expect to get.
</P>
<P>
   Just two weeks ago, the state was projecting this year's harvest
at 60 bushels per acre, but adjusted downward after reports from
the field began trickling in.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers underscore the point farmers in southeastern
Washington have been making. ``I see on TV all about the droughts
in the Northeast,'' Cox says. ``No one seems to have noticed us.''
</P>
<P>
   But a government bailout, even if it comes, may not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   Through 1996, the state's farmers have run up an estimated
$3.125 billion debt.
</P>
<P>
   A study earlier this year by Veribanc, a bank research firm,
found the rate of delinquency for agricultural loans in Washington
jumped to 1.57 percent in the first quarter of 1999, up from .87
percent the year before, and .68 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last summer we sat down and refinanced and laid everything
out,'' Koller says. ``And we weren't alone. There were a lot of
people doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   `You do without'
</P>
<P>
   Poor crop yields in the United States used to mean good wheat
prices. But in a global market, supply and demand doesn't work that
way. Argentina will dump its wheat on the market this year at
cut-rate prices, the way it always does, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's state-controlled agriculture can undercut U.S. wheat.
Australia looks like it will have a good crop year.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the U.S. government has injected politics into the
equation, using wheat as a foreign policy weapon. When the nation
cuts off agricultural aid as a matter of protest _ like it did
recently to Pakistan _ American wheat is stored, not sold. Other
nations step in to fill the void, and American farmers lose market
share.
</P>
<P>
   Those forces translate into low prices in Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at it is that anytime wheat falls below $4
Portland, you better start pushing a really sharp pencil,'' Koller
says.
</P>
<P>
   The ``sharp pencil'' runs right out of the accounting ledger
into real life. It pokes hard, especially in Koller's second
straight year of farming where he's taking a loss on the wheat he's
growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do without,'' says Walt Neff of Pasco, whose crop was down
more than 30 percent from last year. ``You don't buy anything. And
you hope that nothing breaks down _ like that tractor, for
instance.''
</P>
<P>
   Neff nods out the window at an older tractor on which a
hydraulic line gave way Tuesday afternoon. There are precious few
farmers who have new tractors and combines these days _ the costs
are too high, the returns too low.
</P>
<P>
   How does someone losing almost a dollar per bushel afford a new
$200,000 farm machine?
</P>
<P>
   Koller drives a 17-year-old combine, and his two tractors are
from the early 1980s; a new back tire costs $4,000. The sharp
pencil has cut into the family's life, because the farm is
everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, we haven't gone anywhere this summer,'' he says
in his kitchen. ``I had to give a (World Trade Organization)
seminar in Spokane a few weeks ago, and we stayed overnight and
took the kids. You know kids, an overnight stay and a pool is a
vacation for them. And we went to the Alabama concert in Spokane
and stayed overnight there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were our vacations.''
</P>
<P>
   Problem rains
</P>
<P>
   The sky is a painful blue this day north of Kahlotus, or it is
until the wind gets going and the rising thermals start picking up
soil and weeds and send dust devils spiraling into the sky.
</P>
<P>
   The forecast calls for thunderstorms this night. The farmers
hope they will go north towards Pullman.
</P>
<P>
   They need two more weeks of dry weather to finish the spring
wheat harvest, then rain to moisten the soil for winter wheat
planting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year is gone,'' Chris Herron says, kicking at the dirt.
``This year is a bust.''
</P>
<P>
   Herron manages about 5,000 acres around Kahlotus. His crop yield
this year was about 12 bushels to the acre; a good year is about 30
bushels to the acre.
</P>
<P>
   The crops in Franklin County were worse than the ones in
Garfield or Adams or Walla Walla counties, and Herron couldn't get
work doing custom cutting.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the high price of farm equipment, many farmers
contract out their combine work. Herron made pretty good money
doing it, he says, except that this year every one of his customers
canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it goes bad'' he says, ``it just won't quit.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not just farmers feeling the pinch. The custom cutters are
an obvious victim of the area's drought. So are the towns _
Pomeroy, Kahlotus, Prescott _ that serve as centers for
southeastern Washington's farmers.
</P>
<P>
   They are fairly empty, now, as they usually are at harvest. But
there is more traffic than usual, testimony to the relative dearth
of crops to harvest. It is a false busy _ lots of activity, but
little spending of money.
</P>
<P>
   Koller talks about the sense of depression in these towns as the
merchants watch their clients go out of business, get foreclosed
on, flat give up. He's had one neighbor go under this year and
fears for another.
</P>
<P>
   He talks about the low prices of grain, about the neighbor who
didn't use herbicide at all this spring trying to cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   He talks about pushing the sharp pencil, of trusting old farm
equipment, of believing that next year will be wet and well-timed
enough for a bumper crop.
</P>
<P>
   What he is talking about is survival, and the Washington State
knickknacks and his master's degree in international relations
don't matter when it comes to that, because this is more than
survival of the farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to lose what my dad left me,'' he says. ``I don't
want to lose my legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   (END)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
