<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-EYES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE UBIQUITOUS GRANT IS BACK, WITH AN ITALIAN ACCENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When last we left Hugh Grant, he was being semi-miraculously
transformed from a Hollywood outcast with a stalled career to the
only man brave enough to listen to Julia Roberts' ``I'm just a
girl'' speech and still respect her in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   He'd been given back his halo and was free to stroll among the
beautiful people. He strolled himself straight from ``Notting
Hill'' to the Upper West Side, where he sells paintings for an
auction house and is dogged by the goodfellas in his new girl's
family.
</P>
<P>
   He's taken up with Jeanne Tripplehorn in ``Mickey Blue Eyes.''
It's a Grant vehicle with non-stop mob screwballing and a barrage
of ethnic joking held together by Grant flapping, fopping,
squinting, stammering and pulling himself into one long constipated
face. It's almost persuasive enough to make you forget that the
movie steamrolls Little Italy in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Grant, who for the sake of clarification plays a Brit named
Michael, has been dating Tripplehorn's Gina for three months, the
exact three months since that amicable split from Julia Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout ``Mickey Blue Eyes,'' Grant's fluster-chic is
challenged by holdovers from ``Analyze This'' and ``The Sopranos,''
if not actual cast members and other stock characters looking to
get his dander up, like the feisty Chinese lady (Lori Tan Chinn)
who foists on Gina the fortune cookie containing Michael's marriage
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The scene is a nicely handled little riot that gets a lot of
mileage out of Tan's militarism. (Maybe she knew the couple chose
her Chinatown eatery only after they lost their reservation
somewhere else.) Gina says ``no'' to Michael because she fears
he'll be dragged into the nightmare that is her big Italian family,
led by her father, Frank Vitale (James Caan), and her uncle (Burt
Young). She doesn't want them controlling his life with their mob
favors. But he doesn't care; he loves her. Grant has as much
chemistry with Tripplehorn as he can with his girlfriend Elizabeth
Hurley producing the film.
</P>
<P>
   Tripplehorn smiles big and bounds around with large make-believe
gestures for the first 20 minutes like she's selling Revlon and
Pantene. Gina's the golden child in the Vitale family, and the
bit-heavy script by Adam Scheinman and Robert Kuhn makes sure you
know this by giving her a trendy mentally ill brother (Paul Lazar).
</P>
<P>
   She's actually the only non-stereotypical Italian ``Mickey Blue
Eyes'' can find. Gina agrees to marry him as long as they don't let
her gangster family do them any favors. But the movie piles on the
offers Michael can't refuse anyway. Those painting shipments his
Sothebys-like employer was having trouble receiving on time? Taken
care of.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Michael is expected to auction off an awful painting
by Gina's hothead cousin Johnny (John Ventimiglia of ``The
Sopranos''). Director Kelly Makin hands the film over to Grant,
whose frustration and stuttering turn the auction scenes with
Johnny's paintings _ which depict a gun-toting Jesus and look like
art-school Thomas Hart Benton forgeries _ into something for the
Grant highlight reel.
</P>
<P>
   He's great because he manages to remain in opposition to the
ethnic chaos, but every time he thinks he's out, ``Mickey Blue
Eyes'' has pulled him back in. Soon a key member of the family is
dead, sort of at Michael's hands, and he's digging ditches with the
warm 'n' fuzzy Caan near the Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   Once Michael gets sucked into mob ways, he appears to enjoy it
as much as hates it, reminding himself to rent ``Godfather'' and
``Casino,'' taking his cue on how to speak Italian-American from
the stuffed gorilla Gina gives him. Grant squares his jaw and
mumbles like he should be dragging his knuckles and hanging out
with Gina's brother Ritchie. And Spike Lee's ``Summer of Sam''
caught flack for being anti-Italian because what?
</P>
<P>
   Grant's throwing himself headlong into the Italian/British
juxtaposition is often as winning in its conception as it is in his
execution. Everybody's a clown, everybody's here to amuse you. But
the film is as insulting as taking the queen to the Olive Garden.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
