<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS DEFENSE MISSING THAT CERTAIN CHEMISTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ On many days, the Patriots invite business
groups, advertisers, and other folks friendly to the team to sit in
tents in roped-off areas and watch practice.
</P>
<P>
   One group yet to be welcomed is the Concerned Chemists of New
England. And all chemists, not to mention a few coaches and fans,
should be concerned because developing chemistry in the New England
defense just might be the key to whether the Patriots have a
successful 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   And the key to that chemistry is whether a player or two step
forward to become the leader of the unit. Already, the Patriots are
without safety Willie Clay (waived) and middle linebacker Ted
Johnson (injured), two acknowledged leaders, and the fuss so far
has been whether Chris Carter is the right man to replace Clay and
if rookie Andy Katzenmoyer can step in for Johnson. Scant mention
has been made of replacing the intangible quality of leadership
that Johnson and Clay provided the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have to be more vocal,'' said cornerback Ty Law,
who is neither suited by position _ few cornerbacks can lead
defenses simply because they are lined up so far from the center of
the field _ nor by temperament. ``I'm not a rah-rah guy and I don't
jump up and down in the locker room. I can't act out of character
but I realize I have to try and be more vocal.''
</P>
<P>
   Law is like most cornerbacks in that ``I have to lead by
example, by what I do on the field.''. So, ``as for leadership of
the defense, we're all going to have to play a different part than
we're used to playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter has made strides toward replacing Clay, coach Pete
Carroll said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has really solidified that spot in the first few weeks,''
Carroll said. ``He's very sharp and in command of his decision
making on his calls. And he works well with (fellow safety Lawyer)
Milloy.''
</P>
<P>
   But a clear indication of the adjustment that must be made is
Law's admission that ``I still can't tell what's going on in the
defense. I just cover my man. And when Willie was there, I knew I
didn't have to think a lot. I just had to do my job. Willie was the
brains of the secondary and Willie was able to watch everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, too, is smart ``and he has brains _ hey, the guy's was
in medical school,'' Law said, ``but I can't lie. I'm going to have
be more aware of the (overall) defense.'' Milloy, too, was
comfortable in his role _ hitting people _ while Clay watched if
defenders were out of position when opponents lined up in
unfamiliar formations.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is more perilous at linebacker. Even the most
optimistic scenario won't have Katzenmoyer accustomed to the middle
until late in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have (repetitions),'' said veteran linebacker
Marty Moore. ``That's the only way you learn and feel comfortable,
by seeing things over and over. It took me a full season before I
felt comfortable there.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer's crash course has a domino effect as Tedy Bruschi
and Chris Slade have to keep one eye on the rookie and the other on
their own responsibilities. Katzenmoyer, in effect, is being
tutored on the complexities of middle linebacking. Nobody, of
course, had to worry if Johnson was doing his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just not been comfortable,'' said Bruschi of his own
play. And part of that discomfort has been the added responsibility
of calling defensive signals. Not to mention tutoring Katzenmoyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more calls that Andy starts to learn,'' Bruschi said,
``means the less calls that I have to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Thomas, Chad Eaton, and Willie McGinest are leaders of the
defensive line. Slade has stepped up his leadership role, while Law
and Milloy say they have to take a more active role in the
secondary. Carter, of course, may develop into ``the guy with all
the smarts,'' as Law described Clay.
</P>
<P>
   The New England defense will have 11 bodies on the field. But
whether those 11 form a cohesive unit is dependent on coaching, of
course, but also chemistry and leadership.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 1329EDT &QL; 
