<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESPN ANALYST MAGUIRE CAN'T WAIT UNTIL THE GAMES ARE REAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paul Maguire has been around summer football camps for the last
four decades, and, to tell the truth, he's sick of them.
</P>
<P>
   Sick of the cheeriness.
</P>
<P>
   Sick of the optimism.
</P>
<P>
   Sick of the injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Part of it is personal. When he turned professional in 1960 with
the Los Angeles Chargers, the team had six weeks of camp. Players
wore full pads for both daily practices. They also played six
preseason games. Maguire was one of the fortunate ones. By the time
the first game rolled around, the team was down to two linebackers.
The rest were out with injuries. A lean Maguire, fresh out of the
Citadel, where Al Davis was head coach, was summoned to duty.
</P>
<P>
   He had started both ways at the Citadel, playing linebacker and
wide receiver, and led the nation in touchdown receptions with a
whopping total of 11.
</P>
<P>
   With the Chargers, he was in the right place at the right time
and didn't get hurt. He started for four years. It helped that he
also could punt.
</P>
<P>
   His playing days are long gone. Maguire is a little rounder
nowadays and has been working in the broadcast booth for years. He
is with ESPN now and Saturday night will work the exhibition
between the Patriots and Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   He still can't wait for the regular season to start. ``No matter
what coaches tell you now, things will always be different when the
season starts,'' Maguire said. ``The interesting thing about
preseason is that the teams play the starters for a short period of
time and then they play everybody else. They want to take a good
look at everybody. They don't run anything too complex. It's all
vanilla offenses and defenses. For most teams, not all, preseason
is about looking for competent backup people.''
</P>
<P>
   The inevitable injuries are bound to change the makeup of teams.
Drew Bledsoe goes down with a little ankle injury. No big deal at
the time, but Maguire has been around long enough to know that some
of those injuries can take a long time to heal fully. Maguire said
that Randy Moss, for instance, was never at 100 percent last year
because he started the season with an ankle sprain.
</P>
<P>
   Maguire said that part of the problem is that the athletes of
today are better conditioned than those of the past, almost
overtrained.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I played, preseason camp was for players to get in
shape,'' Maguire said. ``Players of today are in shape when they
come to camp. These guys are overtrained, and it seems they all
come down with muscle pulls or some muscle tear. Think about it.
It's nice to hear that a player has 2 percent body fat. That means
they are all muscle and bone. When you tear one of those muscles,
they are hard to heal.''
</P>
<P>
   Maguire always finds a way to put humor in his analysis. ``I
always thought that the NFL was a great place in the world for fat
people,'' Maguire said. ``I tried not to get in good shape when I
played. It's a shame when a guy is in great shape but can't play
because he has a muscle pull.''
</P>
<P>
   Maguire doesn't quite know what to make of the Patriots this
season. The team has lost Ted Johnson and is anticipating the
emergence of rookie Andy Katzenmoyer to fill his shoes at
linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a lot of confidence,'' Maguire said. ``I would imagine
that they will try to protect him as much as possible until he
settles down and becomes comfortable. The pro game is much quicker
and faster than the college game. But he played four years at Ohio
State and he has seen most everything. But he has to play and he
has to play a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Patriots coach Pete Carroll has his own problems to worry about.
``Word around the league was that Carroll was in trouble last
year,'' Maguire said. ``He'd better put a superior product on the
field this year, because if it comes down to any question of
coaching, then Carroll could be out. Hey, the longest tenure of any
active coach is Denny Green at Minnesota with eight years. They
don't give you long, and as far as I can tell, this is Carroll's
second chance. The players feel it. They sense Carroll's sense of
urgency.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
