<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4125 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV2     08-20 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV22-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHBALL SMELL IS HARD TO GET RID OF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 22, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My old wood chests smell strongly of mothballs. How can I get
rid of that odor? The chests are lined with some sort of paper that
is not just set in, but sticks somehow.
</P>
<P>
   PETER CERUNDOLO, Arlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. This question comes up often, and over the years there have
been no improvements or sure-fire ways to dissipate the odor. The
original way, ventilation, is still as effective as any. The more
you ventilate, the better; keep the chests out in the sun for as
long as you can.
</P>
<P>
   That paper has probably absorbed much of the odor, so removing
it will make a big difference. However, if the chests are antiques
and valuable, then removing the paper might reduce their value.
</P>
<P>
   If you are reluctant to remove the paper, then try to pull the
odor out of the paper this way: Dampen it with a wet sponge, not
too much but not too little, either. Most paper will take some
dampening. If your paper begins to disintegrate from the water,
stop, unless you want to remove the paper altogether. Then sprinkle
baking soda liberally on the wet surface; leave it for half a hour,
sweep up, and dispose of it. Repeat as necessary.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no concern over value, with or without the paper,
remove the paper. Then wet the wood underneath and treat with the
baking soda. The baking soeda will not do its job of absorbing the
odor if the paper or wood is dry.
</P>
<P>
   If you have removed the paper and treated the wood, and still
have the odor, line the chest with Contact paper. Contact paper, by
the way, is easily removed when necessary. The old paper used to
stick like crazy and was extremely difficult to remove. Not the new
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Our family room is over a crawl space. We would like to get
rid of the wall-to-wall carpeting and put down hardwood. Is a
hardwood floor OK over a crawl space, or would too much moisture
damage it? We thought of ceramic tile, but wouldn't it be cold?
</P>
<P>
   JOHN AND PAULINE PANTANO, Reading, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. No problem at all in putting a hardwood floor over the
plywood left after removing the carpeting. If there is moisture in
the crawl space, you can get rid of most of it by ventilating that
space; open vents or windows, or make vents that you can keep open
from April to October. You can also put heavy plastic on the
earthen floor of the crawl space, to prevent water vapor from
coming into the space from the ground; this will happen no matter
how dry the earth feels.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, insulate the crawl space ceiling; put the vapor
barrier (paper backing on the insulation) up, touching the plywood
above.
</P>
<P>
   The ceramic tile will not be cold if you insulate the crawl
space ceiling under it.
</P>
<P>
   Two myths and a truism about ceramic tile: It is not cold if you
insulate below it. It is not hard on the feet if it is applied over
a plywood underlayment. The truism: Say goodbye to anything
breakable that you drop on ceramic tile. It (the glass, plate,
bowl, etc., not the tile) is guaranteed to break. Another truism:
It is great stuff.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have some weird grass in my small lawn that is spreading
like crazy. It is beautifully green in spring, but turns yellow in
winter, even as early as fall. What is it, and how can I keep it
from spreading?
</P>
<P>
   ELIZABETH WOODS, Wilmington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It sounds like Zoysia grass, a mail-order grass popular in
recent years. It spreads by underground roots, and is tropical, amd
therefore goes dormant (turns into yellow hay, it seems) in late
summer and fall.
</P>
<P>
   You might be able to halt its spread by building a deep border
wherever desired: 2 x 6 or even 2 x 12 pressure-treated boards.
Both may be deep enough to keep underground roots in their place.
To get rid of the grass, root it out physically or kill it with
Roundup, which biodegrades into a harmless material in a matter of
days. Then root it out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My house is less than two years old and is well insulated,
except for a gap beween the wall stud and the fireplace, where the
fireplace goes through the exterior wall. The gap is apparent on
both sides of the fireplace. How can I fill it?
</P>
<P>
   JIM KANGA, Pepperell, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The gap is probably only on the inside, because any joint
like that on the outside should be caulked or closed to make it
weatherproof; if that is so, it is unlikely it is losing much heat,
but it won't hurt to plug it. For inside, you can fill it with
fiberglass insulation, sticking it in tightly with a screwdriver.
Or use the expanding foam called Great Stuff, but be careful that
you don't put so much in that it expands excessively. Or, instead,
use a latex foam; it does not expand as much as the Great Stuff,
but will fill the gap nicely. Then cover the gap with wood trim.
</P>
<P>
   If there is already wood trim there, you could take it off,
caulk or fill with foam, and replace the trim.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
