<HEADLINE>
STILL WAITING FOR THAT NEW YEAR'S INVITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I know it's only Aug. 20, but I'm getting antsy. About New
Year's Eve, I mean.
</P>
<P>
   The subject is already coming up in conversation, sort of
casually, but with a discernible edge. People who've already locked
in plans clearly enjoy the upper hand. A couple I know said they
plan to usher in the next millennium in a cottage, alone, on Mt.
Desert Island. Nervous jokes about Bangor Hydro Electric's Y2K
preparedness ensued.
</P>
<P>
   It's not like I don't have options. But a part of me still
awaits that call from Teresa Heinz's social secretary, inviting me
out to Sun Valley for the bash of all bashes. I'm sure her husband
John Kerry has forgiven me for all those lies I published about his
plastic _ sorry, dental _ surgery earlier this year. If only I had
been nicer to Boston University! Special collections czar Howard
Gotlieb's New Year's Eve hoedown at the Fairmont Copley Plaza
promises to be especially grand this year.
</P>
<P>
   Even though I'm an Aquarius, I haven't been too faithful a
water-bearer for the Democratic Party, so it's quite unlikely that
Massport hack-turned-Federal-Aviation-Administration-boss Jane
Garvey is going to invite me on her Dec. 31 late-night flight
across America's time zones. The purpose of this ultimate
white-knuckle voyage to nowhere is to demonstrate the Y2K
preparedness of our air traffic control system. ``Don't be anwhere
near an airplane on Dec. 31,'' a smart friend says, and I'm taking
her advice.
</P>
<P>
   The Kenslea and Barron families of Wellesley have scarfed up the
entire Children's Museum for a combined grown-ups/kiddie party for
about 400 guests, with the cost shared among the invitees. Ms.
Kenslea seemed ready to invite me, but I assured her mine was a
journalistic, not a nest-feathering inquiry. Happenin' guys Harvey
Allen (liquor) and Richie Balsbaugh (media) haven't summoned me to
their ur-cool Mistral shindig; a holdup with the mail? I'm about
half an alphabet short of Barbara Jordan's A-list friends, so I'll
be on the outside looking in at her sensational Four Seasons bash.
</P>
<P>
   Invitations haven't yet been mailed for the Boston Bar
Association/First Night benefit/blowout at the new Federal
courthouse. At $500 a head, it's a little rich for my blood, even
with a perfect view of the harbor fireworks. As things stand now,
I'll be cooling my heels in front of the JumboTron on the Boston
Common all night, watching a considerably warmer Keith Lockhart
conducting from inside Symphony Hall.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dear Malcolm
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When we last checked in on the Museum of Fine Art's Hermann
Goering painting _ the 16th-century Flemish landscape by Herri met
de Bles that graced the Nazi Reichmarshal's office during World War
II _ the MFA had proposed binding arbitration to settle the
disputed ownership of the painting. Christine Koenigs, a
granddaughter of the painting's former owner, attended an early
August meeting with MFA officials to discuss the handover of the
painting, a piece of Nazi-looted art that the museum has supposedly
been trying to return for more than 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   But now all bets are off. The Dutch government, which requires
repatriation of all art seized on its territory during World War
II, has told the MFA to go fly a kite. The chief of the Dutch
Inspectorate for Cultural Heritage, Charlotte van Rappard-Boon, has
written to MFA director Malcolm Rogers, ``I must dismiss your
suggestion that the matter be resolved by arbitration.'' Van
Rappard-Boon explains that Koenigs and others are litigating their
claims to the painting in Holland. Thus, ``I feel it is essential
for the question of title . . . for this painting to be decided by
the Dutch courts, in accordance with Dutch law.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Rappard-Boon goes on to request ``the speedy return of the
painting to the Netherlands. While awaiting the decision of the
competent Dutch court who is the rightful owner of the Bles
painting, I suggest that the painting be handed over to the keepers
of the State Art Collection as temporary custodian.'' In the past,
the MFA has said it is willing to return the painting, but only
after a definite resolution of the ownership question. ``We're back
to square one,'' an MFA spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
