<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4128 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-DANDRIDGE-BOS &LR;      08-20 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DANDRIDGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TRAGIC TALE OF A PIONEER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
INTRODUCING DOROTHY DANDRIDGE 
Starring: Halle Berry, Brent Spiner, Klaus Maria Brandauer, Loretta
Devine 
Directed by: Martha Coolidge 
On: HBO, Saturday at 9 p.m. 
Rated: TVMA 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rich story of Dorothy Dandridge has been sitting in the back
of Hollywood's closet for decades, since the African-American
actress's death by overdose in 1965. It's the story of racism in
America, and in Hollywood, in the 1940s and '50s, and how talented
actresses were relegated to playing plantation mammies and
secondary roles because they were black. It's the story of what
celebrity can do to its most fragile chosen ones, from Dandridge to
Marilyn Monroe, as they masochistically salve their insecurities
with harmful men and pills. And it's the story of how, despite some
important growth, American entertainment (particularly TV)
continues to suffer from amnesia and apathy when it comes to people
of color.
</P>
<P>
   Dandridge, sultry and dynamic, was the first black movie star in
the iconic way Monroe and Audrey Hepburn were stars. She was the
first black woman to get a best actress Academy Award nomination,
in 1954, for ``Carmen Jones,'' the all-black version of Georges
Bizet's opera. The role brought her a deal with Twentieth Century
Fox that, miraculously, paid her the same amount as Ava Gardner,
and she landed on the cover of Life magazine. And she was a
nightclub sensation in an era when clubs were hot spots, headlining
major hotels in Las Vegas, Miami, and New York.
</P>
<P>
   But after signing her for a three-picture deal, Fox balked at
putting a black woman in leads. And Dandridge was frustrated by the
fact that many of the hotels in which she performed would not allow
her to stay in their rooms. One famous story has a Las Vegas hotel
draining its pool after Dandridge stuck her toe in the water.
Despite her fame, she was never exempt from professional
demoralization and oppression. Dandridge's personal life also
conspired to drag her down. Two ill-advised marriages, a
brain-damaged daughter, a doomed affair with Otto Preminger, sexual
abuse by her mother's girlfriend _ it's a list of sad events that
leaves a scriptwriter with an embarrassment of dramatic material.
</P>
<P>
   What a shame it is, then, that ``Introducing Dorothy
Dandridge,'' on HBO Saturday at 9 p.m., so poorly conveys the
promise and tragedy of the actress. Despite the best of intentions
from star Halle Berry, the biopic is painfully fragmented and leaps
from scene to scene without connective tissue or emotional
momentum. It even fails to capture a sense of Dandridge's
electricity onstage, although there are a few lip-synched
performance scenes. From the beginning of the movie, when the
applause at the Oscars melds into the applause at the Cotton Club
for a flashback, you know that it's going to trade shamelessly in
biopic cliches.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the entire movie is framed by the biggest cliche in the
book as, at the end of her life, Dandridge tells her life story on
the phone to her best friend as she fingers through photographs
that become scenes. As if out of central casting, we get the
true-blue manager and the jealous, drunken sister who quite
unexpectedly yells, ``I'm more than Dorothy Dandridge's big
sister.'' How odd to stuff the life of such a groundbreaking woman
into such limited conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Berry is a sweet presence in a role that requires harder edges.
Her facial expressions aren't quite distinct and sharp enough, and
she never quite succeeds in defining Dandridge's psyche _ the
personality traits that led her to make bold choices in the
industry and bad choices in her family life. When Dandridge finally
dies, it's hard to know what drove her to it. Berry's best work was
behind the scenes, mobilizing a movie that creates an appetite for
a deeper look at an essential figure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 1335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
