<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4133 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-FREIRE-BOS &LR;      08-20 1410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-FREIRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENCORE   FOR NELSON FREIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Thirty-one years ago a young Brazilian pianist made
his first recordings _ concertos by Grieg, Schumann, and
Tchaikovsky that were issued with great fanfare by CBS/Columbia and
greeted with rapture by the international musical press, which
acclaimed the arrival of a major new artist. ``A hurricane of
pianistic power,'' is what Irving Kolodin called Nelson Freire in
the Saturday Review. Time Magazine called him ``one of the most
exciting new pianists of this or any other age,'' and a European
newspaper dubbed him ``the jaguar with velvet paws.''
</P>
<P>
   Freire made a spectacular debut with the New York Philharmonic
in 1970, playing Rachmaninoff's Fourth Concerto, and played his
first New York recital the very next day. He arrived in Boston in
1977 to play a superb, unforgotten recital for the Peabody-Mason
Foundation in Sanders Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, this nervous young critic interviewed an equally
nervous young Freire in New York. Any lingering romantic notions
about the glamorous life of prominent young pianists took a beating
that day _ Freire was not staying in a posh hotel attended by
liveried servants, but sleeping on the floor of a friend's
apartment, like a graduate student.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday afternoon Freire returns to New England for the first
time in 22 years to play Chopin's F-Minor Concerto with the Boston
Symphony Orchestra under the direction of Charles Dutoit at
Tanglewood.
</P>
<P>
   Freire has not performed very often in America over the last 20
years, although he is a favorite of the Baltimore Symphony and its
former music director David Zinman, and he is a favorite of
audiences in Florida and in Carmel, Calif. Freire's recording
career has been fitful as well, and only a handful of his discs
remain available _ most of his early recordings, including the
debut concertos, the Chopin Preludes, and a magical set of Schubert
Impromptus are available on Sony's ``Essential Classics'' series at
budget prices, although sometimes in couplings you wouldn't choose.
His boldy imaginative Chopin Preludes, for example, share a disc
with the Ballades in boring perfrmances by Philippe Entrement. A
glorious volume in Philips Classics's new Great Pianists of the
20th Century series has now reawakened worldwide interest in
Freire, who does indeed sound like one of this century's pianistic
giants on these recordings, several of them collected from
hard-to-find CDs of Freire recitals recorded live on small labels.
</P>
<P>
   Freire lives in Brazil today, and maintains a pied-a-terre in
France. Speaking by phone from South America earlier this week, the
pianist said: ``I don't know why I haven't been so much in America,
because I have been all over every place else, mostly in Europe,
but also in Japan, Australia, and South America. Also, I don't like
to play as many concerts as most other pianists do; that's it.''
(Freire plays 30-50 concerts a year, about half what some of his
more famous colleagues play.)
</P>
<P>
   As to recordings, Freire said: ``The reason I haven't made so
many is a mixture of things. Also for my part, I always have a
dislike to learn certain pieces just for a record, and this is not
very commercial. I have a certain dislike to make commercial
things. Nowadays, too, there is a crisis in the record business, so
it has been quite a long time without recordings _ just a few
exceptions of three or four things I did with my friend Martha
Argerich. I would like to record again _ I am just waiting for a
proposition, and it has to be the right one. I think it is quite
important that records should be distributed all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the highlights of the two-CD Philips set are performances
of Godowsky's ``Symphonic Metamorphosis on Themes from `Die
Fledermaus' '' and Godowsky's transcription of Richard Strauss's
``Staendchen'' _ performances that are at once on the highest level
of technical brilliance and of musical distinction. If they had
been recorded on scratchy 78s, they would have been constantly
reissued as historic treasures of piano playing, like Ignaz
Friedman's Chopin Mazurkas. Instead these performances have rested
in the archives of a German radio station, where Freire recorded
them in 1972. ``I was asked to record some free repertory,'' Freire
recalled, ``and maybe a little bit some exotic things. Those
performances were almost an improvisation; I played them through a
couple of times and then recorded them for the radio. But I thought
it was a good idea to put these performances on the CD because
these pieces are not so much played any more. The Mozart Sonata and
the Schumann Fantasy on the CD were also recorded in live
performances, one in Miami, one in Toronto.''
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto recital unfolded in an atmosphere of crisis, the
kind that Freire appears to thrive on. ``I had been playing a
series of concerts with Martha, and then I flew to Toronto. I
thought the concert was two days later, but it was the next day.
`At least I can sleep in,' I thought, but then I learned the
concert was in the afternoon. I hardly had time to test the piano,
but sometimes these things turn out for the better.''
</P>
<P>
   Freire was born in Boa Esperanca, Brazil, in October 1944, and
at 3 had his first piano lessons from his sister, who was 14 years
older. Then he traveled five hours each way across unpaved country
roads to the nearest city, Varginha, to take weekly lessons. After
only three months, his unusual gift was abundantly apparent, and
his family reached the difficult decision to move to Rio de Janeiro
where their child could study seriously with Nisi Obino and Lucia
Branco, who had studied with a pupil of Liszt's. Later, when Freire
was 12, he played Beethoven's ``Emperor'' Concerto to such effect
that the president of Brazil awarded him a scholarship that enabled
him to go to work with Bruno Seidlhofer in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   An important friend and mentor was the great Brazilian pianist
Guiomar Novaes (1895-1979) _ who was characterized in an earlier
era as ``The Paderewska of the Pampas.'' The omission of this great
artist from the Philips Great Pianists series has been heavily
criticized, and Freire swells the chorus. ``I think I am the single
most angry person about that. She was quite important for my
musical life, and one of my favorite pianists. She was a very
special kind of artist, natural, different from the average, with a
very deep intuition. She spoke in the language of a housewife and
had a way of saying things that would maybe sound funny to some
people, but if you paid attention, there was a lot of depth in what
she said. And then she spoke mostly with her eyes, which was
marvelous.''
</P>
<P>
   Freire says that Novaes was not perhaps ``a recording person,
although she made lots of records. On the stage she was much more
spontaneous.'' Spontaneity is a central aspect of Freire's own art,
and so is the bel canto beauty and variety of his sound _ another
characteristic of Novaes's playing. ``The recordings she made for
Vox didn't really capture the quality of her sound _ although in a
way they are still marvelous. I love her records of Schumann's
`Papillons' and `Kinderszenen,' and Beethoven's sonata, `Les
Adieux.' They have just issued now some recordings she made in the
1920s, and these are marvelous, and I have a few live performances
that are wonderful. She playes the Chopin F-Minor Concerto with
Geroge Szell, using an orchestration by Paderewski _ but I like
Chopin's original. And there is a Schumann Concerto with the New
York Philharmonic and Andre Cluytens in 1957 which is the best I
have ever heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Freire first played the Chopin F-Minor Concerto in public in
Lisbon in 1967, with his friend David Zinman conducting. But he had
studied it earlier, when he was still 16. ``I remember playing it
in Seidlhofer's master class back in 1960, which was when I met
Martha for the first time _ I asked her to play the orchestra part
on the second piano. She did, and we became close friends for the
rest of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Seidlhofer's reputation rested on his teaching of the Viennese
classics and Chopin was a little outside his usual line. Freire
says he doesn't remember what he had to say about his performance
with Argerich. ``I was so in love with this piece that it really
didn't matter what he said. I still love it; it's beautiful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 1336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4136 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-TINGLE-BOS &LR;      08-20 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TINGLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING LEARNED FROM `TEACHING MRS. TINGLE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
TEACHING MRS. TINGLE 
Written and directed by: Kevin Williamson 
Starring: Helen Mirren, Katie Holmes, Barry Watson, Marisa
Coughlan, Jeffrey Tambor, Liz Stauber, Molly Ringwald, Vivica A.
Fox 
Running time: 93 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (thematic content, violence, sexuality, language and
some teen drinking) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With ``Teaching Mrs. Tingle,'' Kevin Williamson has finally
become what he has been making fun of, namely a maker of shlock
horror movies. The film's problem isn't so much that it panders
shamelessly to teen audiences, but that it panders so emptily. It
has almost none of the cool irony that marked his scripts for
``Scream,'' ``Scream 2,'' and ``I Know What You Did Last Summer''
and enabled him to keep scare movies going a while longer. Even if
he had tapped another vein of self-referential wit, it may just be
that his kind of scare movie is passing out of fashion in favor of
the more primal kind of horror represented by ``The Blair Witch
Project,'' ``The Sixth Sense'' and imminently, ``Stir of Echoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, ``Teaching Mrs. Tingle'' is mostly a screenful of
nothingness. Its bashing of adult authority figures is so crudely
drawn that its real crime is its total waste of the supremely
stylish Helen Mirren. She's Mrs. Tingle, a spiteful history teacher
thirsting on the eve of graduation for ways to shoot down a few of
the pupils she envies because they're getting out of the backwater
they live in, whereas she didn't. When she discovers three kids in
the gym doing things that look worse than they actually are, her
lips curl into a cruel smile and her eyes shine with a jackpot
glow. Katie Holmes' would-be valedictorian, Leigh Ann, who had been
hoping for a scholarship, is hardest hit. But her careless pal,
Marisa Coughlan's Jo Lynn, and Barry Watson's Luke, the guy they
both have a crush on, are torpedoed, too.
</P>
<P>
   They go to her Victorian house seeking clemency, but the
sadistic sarcasm with which she delightedly makes them squirm makes
it clear that they haven't got a chance. One thing leads to
another, and Tingle wakes up tied to her bedposts, bondage-style,
by the kids, who hadn't planned to have it go this way, and are
trying to seize the upper hand. Mirren is not only the best thing
in it, she's practically the only thing the movie has going for it.
Her Mrs. Tingle is more focused than her captors and less afraid.
Even when tied down, she's the most dangerous one in the room. The
clash of wills is no contest, given that Tingle is no slouch at a
form of combat for which these kids hardly qualify, namely mind
games.
</P>
<P>
   But hostage movies are hard to bring off because they turn
inert, especially this one. Even Mirren's brilliance can't hide the
fact that Williamson is giving us little more than heavily
manipulated cartoon figures who get bogged down early on. The fact
that Williamson is also a first-time director accounts only partly
for the film's sluggishness. Most of the problem lies with his
perfunctory script and the shrug with which he seems to have
written the characters. The deck is stacked against the adults.
Their ranks, filtered through Williamson's contempt, include an
alcoholic principal, a lecherous coach, and, in a sad comedown,
Molly Ringwald, as the school secretary. Nor do naughty photos and
a lethal crossbow give the film the lift it needs. ``Teaching Mrs.
Tingle'' underwent a title change in the wake of the Columbine High
School shootings. It had been called ``Killing Mrs. Tingle,'' an
inaccurate title at best, unless it referred to the ever-present
possibility of boring her to death.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 1337EDT &QL; 
