<HEADER>
A4139 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-CYC-ARMSTRONG-BOS &LR;      08-20 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-ARMSTRONG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUR DE FRANCE WINNER HEADS FOR THE MOUNTAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST DOVER, Vt. _ It sure looked like Tour de France winner
Lance Armstrong, but something was different.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the yellow jersey he proudly wore on the podium in
Paris last month, Armstrong was wearing a short-sleeved dark blue
sportshirt. Instead of talking about the sleek road bike he rode to
win the Tour, Armstrong was chattering about the dual suspension on
the knobby-tired bicycle he'll use this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   As if it wasn't enough that Armstrong, 27, overcame a battle
with cancer to become only the second American to win the Tour de
France, the Austin, Texas, native is turning heads again.
</P>
<P>
   This time it's by competing in the finals of the Chevy Trucks
National Championships, a series of six races sanctioned by the
National Off-Road Bicycle Association. Even though Alison Dunlap of
Colorado Springs, Colo., and Steve Larsen of Bend, Ore., lead the
women's and men's cross-country races, respectively, it's obvious
Armstrong is the main attraction.
</P>
<P>
   So the NBC crew, which coincidentally was assigned to this
weekend's race anyway, suddenly had to train its cameras on the
Tour winner. And fans were lurking for autographs.
</P>
<P>
   As Armstrong settled down behind the microphones to face the
media  &UR; last night &LR; , he immediately asked and answered the question
he knew was on everyone's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know all of the questions are going to pertain to why am I
here,'' he said. ``The reason is, not only did I make a commitment
to Trek (bicycles) last year to ride in mountain bike races, and I
feel it's important to honor that commitment regardless what
happened in the summertime. It's also something that I find
enjoyable.''
</P>
<P>
   It's what he does, he said with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's a road bike, a mountain bike, or a tandem bike, I
enjoy riding a bike,'' he said. ``So this fits into what I consider
my job description, and that's racing bicycles.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, who rode one mountain race last year in Park City,
Utah, had a different result than he had in France _ he didn't
finish. But he liked the sport that he has used for offseason road
training, and last spring agreed with Trek to race mountain bikes
for them. (Trek also makes the bicycles Armstrong and his US Postal
Service teammates use on the road.)
</P>
<P>
   This will be Armstrong's first major American race since he won
the Tour. He remained in Europe briefly to ride some criteriums,
came back home to be on talk shows, went back to ride a race in
Spain, then returned to be honored by his hometown and to visit the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's back, not on the roads, but on a mountain usually
covered with snow.
</P>
<P>
   The sport is different than what he's used to, Armstrong said,
because it's ``more athletic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What mountain bikers do and the skill that it takes are
different that a road racer needs,'' he said. ``There are a lot of
road racers who could never do this because of the technical stuff
and the coordinaton it requires. I'm one of them, I think. This
makes me nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   So even though Armstrong was in the front pack almost every day
in the Tour de France, he insists he won't be a ringer when he
takes part in the cross-country races with about 95 men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully I can stay upright,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
