<HEADLINE>
KEEPING PEACE A FULL-TIME JOB FOR REVOLUTION GM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Revolution general manager Brian O'Donovan's diplomatic,
interpersonal, and crisis management skills are being severely
tested this week. The accumulation of the Revolution's problems,
combined with a 1-0 loss to the Tampa Bay Mutiny, ignited
frustrations among fans, players, and a player-coach Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donovan found himself counseling the team's two oldest
players, recently-acquired midfielder Leonel Alvarez and
player-coach Walter Zenga, who was in a combative mood after the
defeat, which seriously damaged the Revolution's playoff hopes
going into Friday's game at San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga, 38, engaged in an argument with a fan while signing
autographs about 45 minutes after the game. The conflict was broken
up by other fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans have a right to say what they want, but this was way over
the top,'' O'Donovan said. ``Clearly, this sort of thing can't be
allowed to happen, but we have to do a better job of protecting our
coaches, just as we do with football coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga had been reluctant to meet with fans or media after the
Revolution's sixth successive defeat. After consulting with
O'Donovan, though, Zenga conducted a revealing press conference in
which he expressed his incredulity about the team's failures and
took responsibility for the defeats.
</P>
<P>
   Then, while walking in front of the Foxboro Stadium offices,
Zenga was beckoned by a vocal, supportive group of fans and he
approached them to sign autographs. But one fan taunted Zenga,
calling the Revolution a ``Serie B'' (second division) team, then
blaming Zenga for Italy's defeat in the semifinals of the 1990
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get a guy like Walter Zenga to come out and sign autographs
after a loss like . . . ,'' O'Donovan said. ``But no matter what
happens, a coach should never engage in (an argument) like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Alvarez, 34, had threatened to return to Dallas if
MLS failed to extend his contract. But after the game, Alvarez
enlisted the help of public relations assistant Jurgen Mainka to
interpret as he voiced his concerns to O'Donovan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had nothing to do with contracts,'' O'Donovan said. ``It
was the same thing as Zenga. Leonel was saying we need to keep our
hearts in this, keep our focus, our spirit. We need to keep a
positive attitude and he said, `You can depend on me.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Leonel had a contract problem before when he went to Mexico
and people were worried about it. But it didn't affect his play.
When he steps on the field, Leonel Alvarez doesn't know how not to
give everything he's got. We've gotten what we've expected with
him, and that's a leader.''
</P>
<P>
   At least the Revolution are not going into the dark night of a
losing streak lightly. And O'Donovan believes the adversity could
galvanize the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of players on our team have that same passion,''
O'Donovan said. ``I genuinely believe in this team. It's the best
group of players we've ever had in uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``The direction we are going is the right one. We need a break
and we need to change the mode from desperation to determination,
and that is happening. My role is not the football side of the
operation, but to monitor the pulse of the situation, and this is a
team that believes in itself and has passion. And if we lose that
passion we are finished.''
</P>
</TEXT>
