<SLUG> BC-FILENES-BASEMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$21.4M LOSS RAISES DOUBTS ABOUT FILENE'S BASEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Filene's Basement Corp. has been on the brink before,
only to bounce back and confound critics who say the concept of
bargain-basement retail is hopelessly outdated.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the case in 1995 when a bankruptcy filing was rumored,
but an earnings report issued this week suggests that the
90-year-old Boston-area legend could now be in for the fight of its
life.
</P>
<P>
   For the first half of its current fiscal year, the Basement lost
$21.4 million, more money than it lost for its last two fiscal
years combined. For the most recent quarter, ending July 31, the
Basement lost $14.9 million on sales of $144 million.
</P>
<P>
   While some of the losses are related to the launch of the
Basement's Aisle 3 chain, the numbers are still cause for concern
for the Wellesley-based retailer, which reported sales of $588.5
million last year.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the Basement has said some vendors have been
reluctant to ship it goods. And Thursday the price of Basement
shares fell 1/32, to close at 1. In the last month, share prices
have dipped below a dollar more than once.
</P>
<P>
   Calls made to Basement headquarters over the last four days were
not returned, but others outside the company weren't so reticent
about commenting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outlook for Filene's Basement is grim at best,'' said Kurt
Barnard, president of Barnard's Retail Trend Report.
</P>
<P>
   One problem may be that some of the company's stores are
faltering. In all, the company runs 51 stores under the Filene's
Basement name. But few have captured the magic of the original
flagship store in downtown Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among the Basement's immediate concerns is that some
vendors have been reluctant to ship merchandise, presumably out of
fear they won't be paid. Vendor jitters can start a debilitating
cycle for a retailer. When store shelves aren't fully stocked,
sales can drop, and problems get worse.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a new $125 million credit line, ``vendors still remain
concerned, and the company is continuing to experience problems
with receiving adequate quantities of inventory,'' the Basement
noted in the earnings report it issued Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Vendor jitters come at a bad time. For most retailers, it's
crucial to have enough merchandise on the store shelves for the
important back-to-school and holiday selling seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a cause for hope in the launch of Aisle 3, the
Basement's warehouse-store chain that opens for business only on
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aisle 3, from what I heard, is doing great,'' said Stewart
Cohen, chief executive of Paragon Capital of Needham.
</P>
<P>
   Paragon is one of the lenders behind the Basement's new line of
credit, part of which has been earmarked for expanding the Aisle 3
chain.
</P>
<P>
   Aisle 3 may offer the Basement its best opportunity for growth.
Four stores are up and running, and several more are set to open
shortly.
</P>
<P>
   A weekend-only store has two advantages over seven-day-a-week
retailers: Payroll costs are lower, and stores are open when
consumers do most of their shopping.
</P>
<P>
   The Basement isn't the only struggling bargain-basement
retailer. A few months ago, Loehmann's Inc. of New York filed for
bankruptcy protection.
</P>
<P>
   Because the two chains seem so similar and because the Basement
continues to report losses, vendors have grown nervous about
shipping the Basement goods.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the two chains together, some observers even wonder
whether the bargain basement may soon go the way of the
five-and-dime store.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are concerned there's no longer a place for stores like
Filene's Basement and Loehmann's in the marketplace,'' said Gary
Wassner, president of Hilldun Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Firms such as Hilldun are known as factors, and they play a key
role in New York's Garment District, often deciding whether a
struggling retailer will hang on or go under.
</P>
<P>
   In simple terms, factors guarantee that vendors will be paid for
the goods they ship to retailers. When retailers buy goods from
apparel vendors, it's akin to a consumer making a credit-card
purchase. The consumer gets the goods today, but the bill doesn't
come due for a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   If the factors lose faith in a retailer, some vendors won't ship
goods unless they're paid right away. But many retailers would be
hard-pressed to pay upfront. Only after they've sold the
merchandise do many have the money to pay the vendors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Factors control Seventh Avenue,'' said Cohen. ``If you don't
have factor support in the Garment District, it's very difficult''
for a retailer.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, stores such as Filene's Basement and Loehmann's
were places where department stores could unload goods they
couldn't sell at full price.
</P>
<P>
   Now many department stores discount slow-moving merchandise
themselves, and in the last 10 years or so, many have opened their
own outlet chains. Computerized inventory has also cut back the
amount of excess apparel.
</P>
<P>
   Bargain basements were famous for their scruffiness. Consumers
would put up with a low-rent shopping experience and rummage
through messy bins in hope of landing a good deal.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, comparable deals can often be found in department
stores during their many sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't need to shop in a place that's unpleasant to get
a good price,'' Wassner said. As practiced by small off-price
chains like Filene's Basement and Loehmann's, the bargain-basement
``concept doesn't make sense any more,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And with the economy booming, Wassner added, why should vendors
risk shipping to an ailing bargain basement when so many healthy
retailers are eager to buy the same goods?
</P>
<P>
   Other problems loom. As the price of Basement shares
occassionally dips below a dollar, there's some risk the company
could eventually be de-listed from Nasdaq, though the stock would
have to remain below a dollar for more than 30 trading days to risk
being de-listed.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from not being included in the stock listings printed
by many newspapers, the actual impact of being de-listed is
minimal, said Harry K. Eisenberg, editor-in-chief of Walker's
Manual of Penny Stocks. By the time a company is booted off a
mainstream stock exchange, a lot of bad things have already
happened to it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once a stock starts trading below $5, most investors lose
interest,'' Eisenberg said. Being de-listed simply means a company
is ``one level further removed to obscurity.''
</P>
<P>
   But that obscurity may not be permanent, he noted. A company can
recover and requalify to trade again on a major stock exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
