<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REYNOLDS DEAL LEAVES ONE HEDGE FUND MANAGER STEAMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Hedge fund manager Jon Jacobson has been hammering
managers at Reynolds Metals Co. since March, urging them to unlock
shareholder value by considering a sale of the aluminum and
packaging company.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson seemed to get his way Thursday, when Reynolds agreed to
be purchased by Alcoa Inc. for $5.9 billion in stock and assumed
debt. So why is he so steamed?
</P>
<P>
   ``This board sold us out,'' said Jacobson, whose Highfields
Capital Management became the largest single Reynolds investor by
spending more than $220 million for 4.3 million shares. ``It's a
great deal for Alcoa shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson complains that Reynolds managers and directors were
dragged kicking and screaming to the point where they put the
company up for sale, and only when they were faced with a hostile
takeover battle from Alcoa. Then they botched the sale
negotiations, quickly accepting an inadequate offer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Alcoa's opening offer in its hostile &UR;  &LR; takeover bid on Monday was
$65 per share in cash. The friendly deal announced Thursday
amounted to $70.89 per share in Alcoa stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board in this situation is accountable,'' said Jacobson,
best known for generating huge stock investment returns for Harvard
University's endowment at Harvard Management Corp. until last year.
``I think these guys are asleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Highfields wrote to Reynolds directors Thursday afternoon, hours
after the Alcoa deal was announced. On various points, it
complained the company ``effectively lied'' to shareholders about
previous interest from Alcoa and that the board ``failed
miserably'' to manage the sale process once it was under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your behavior is reprehensible and . . . you will forever be
remembered for your failure in this matter,'' said the Highfields
letter, signed by managing director Richard Grubman.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds officials did not return a call Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   It may be hard to believe amid the noise, but Highfields is
still in a position to make a substantial profit on its Reynolds
investment. Highfields, which began buying Reynolds stock in
January and was still adding to its investment as recently as Aug.
11, spent an average of $51.09 per share, according to the hedge
fund's latest public disclosure statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Reynolds sale price, which could go up or down based on the
future value of Alcoa stock, would represent a profit of about 35
percent over Highfields' average purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   But Jacobson clearly thought Reynolds was worth more, and so did
many others. In March, Highfields pressed its case for the sale of
Reynolds in public and suggested the company was worth $85 to $95
per share.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still don't think that's far off,'' Jacobson said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson, who left Harvard Management Corp. to create his hedge
fund last fall, is accustomed to making big bets on companies in
the midst of mergers or acquisitions, sometimes in the middle of a
takeover contest.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson first criticized Reynolds managers in March, after
Highfields had accumulated 5.5 percent of the company's stock,
arguing they were not ``fully committed'' to maximizing shareholder
value.
</P>
<P>
   He kept on them for months, but it was rival Alcan's deal this
month to buy Pechiney SA of Paris and Zurich-based Algroup's
aluminum and packaging units that sent aluminum leader Alcoa
publicly after Reynolds in a swift industry consolidation play.
</P>
<P>
   After Reynolds turned down a friendly offer of $65 per share
from Alcoa last week, the suitor turned around and launched a
hostile bid.
</P>
<P>
   Once Reynolds quickly agreed to explore its options, Jacobson
said, the company failed to establish a committee of independent
directors to run the process and rushed into the arms of Alcoa.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys had time and they just (wasted it) by caving in
after two days without contacting other potential buyers,'' said
Jacobson. ``It sounds like they did nothing but negotiate with
Alcoa from a very weak position.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson said he was aware of at least two industial firms and
one financial firm that had interest in all or part of Reynolds but
were never contacted.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds can still get out of the deal and take a better offer,
but only at the cost of a $100 million breakup fee.
</P>
<P>
   All Highfields can do is campaign for another offer and possibly
vote against the Alcoa proposal. ``It's an option we'll retain,''
said Jacobson. ``We'll see how the process unfolds.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   File under noncash compensation: So who got to tee up Thursday
with Arnold Palmer at the pro-am event for the BankBoston Senior
Classic golf tournament at Nashawtuc Country Club? We hear it was
BankBoston chief Chad Gifford and merger partner/Fleet Financial
Group chief Terry Murray. Beats hot dogs at the Patriots box.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
