<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUEFISH ADD DIMENSION TO A CONTEMPLATIVE SPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTUCKET, Mass. _ Few sports lead to quite the state of
introspection as fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Golfers, for example, do not go around wondering why they play
golf, as if there were some archetypal truth beyond the club, the
ball, and the hole in the grass.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do golfers' cousins, bowlers and pool players, so question
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But fishing is different, somehow at another level of being than
mere pastime.
</P>
<P>
   At a cemetery near my house a gravestone inscription reads
simply, ``Gone Fishing,'' with an engraved scene of lovely foliage
enclosing a stream with a leaping trout.
</P>
<P>
   So here was a guy whose love of fishing was so profound he
wanted to be known for all the ages for that passion, rather than,
say, any war he may have fought in or kids he left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Another fishing friend once told me he hoped that if any of his
kids got married in the summer they would videotape it because he'd
hate to miss the wedding. I think it was a joke. But I'm not sure.
</P>
<P>
   These thoughts were in mind on a matchless August afternoon as
we drifted along the rip water between Great Point and Sankaty Head
trolling for bluefish. It is much more fun and satisfying to catch
blues up on top with dry flies and plugs, but the fish don't always
cooperate, so we had to go down to them.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean fish cannot be ``called'' to the surface.
Sometimes the sound of a popper imitating a crippled fish will
bring the blues or even striper up to check it out.
</P>
<P>
   I was with a friend, John, and Colby, his 24-year-old daughter,
on a Nantucket vacation on which a 16-year-old son was pursuing his
own passion of surfing on the oceanfront beaches while John and his
daughter fished.
</P>
<P>
   My friend was just getting acquainted with his gorgeous new
34-foot Blackwatch, which made the seaway feel like flat water as
we charged along to the east toward Brant Point, cleaving perfect
twin curls of wake behind us.
</P>
<P>
   Underway, we rigged a few rods with various plugs, Hootchies,
pork rinds, leadheads with dressing of one kind or another. For a
while we tried drifting near the rip, casting plugs into the water
where it roiled as the deep incoming tide hit the shallows and
began to roll blue and white.
</P>
<P>
   Nantucket is surrounded by shoal water, which is what made the
island so dangerous in the age of sail. On the south side, the Old
Man Shoal sets up a curling wave so high you can sometimes, when
the wave is backlit, see the dark, torpedolike bluefish swimming
down through it. As in bonefishing, you can select the fish you
cast for.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because the fishery was threatened with collapse a short
15 years ago, striped bass somehow command more respect among most
anglers than do bluefish. In fact, there is a school of mystical
literature surrounding stripers that casts the fish in the sacred
role of demigod, as the Indians regard cows.
</P>
<P>
   Striped bass are given credit for humanlike intelligence,
warriorlike bravery in battle, and an ambrosia quality as
nourishment. In fact, stripers do sometimes seem to exhibit
reasoning powers, especially when compared with bluefish, which,
when excited by the smell of blood in a kill, become little more
than chopping machines hitting anything in front of those deadly
snouts.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with sharp teeth, a bluefish can be downright dangerous,
and has removed parts of fingers from many an angler unwise enough
to try to unhook it without benefit of pliers. Encountered in
frenzied schools that chop through whatever they encounter,
including their brothers, bluefish ``blitzes'' are exciting to
witness, especially with rod in hand.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps those teeth are the reason some idiots club a bluefish
unconscious, but there's also some tribal macho thing going on as
well. I know few experienced anglers who kill their fish this way,
and it is absolutely ruinous to the meat. If sudden dispatch is the
point, a shot of vodka in the gill will do just as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``So why catch buefish?'' goes the introspective voice that
sometimes comes to practitioners of the blood sports as they age.
Younger hunters and fisherpeople rarely ask this of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, the act of watching new anglers go through the
experience of catching one of their first fish holds a clue.
</P>
<P>
   Colby was up on the bow of the boat, pumping her rod as the
fishing guide showed her to do earlier this summer. Then, slam, it
bent double, and after waiting a correct interval, she pulled to
set the hook on the first fish of our day.
</P>
<P>
   The fight was typically bluefish, a wild, thrashing attempt to
escape. Colby kept the pressure on at critical moments, not letting
the line slack when the fish made a run. She stayed with the fish,
even when it lept out of the water shaking its head violently to
spit the hook.
</P>
<P>
   Now and then, Colby let out a whoop of delight as she fought
this fish, bringing it finally to the boat, where we inspected it
before releasing _ slate blue on top with pearly white underside
and deep red gill fans working in and out. After the fight with a
feisty, thrashing 14-pounder, Colby was breathless, glowing with
excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Connecting this deeply with the natural world, reaching into its
depths and finding its power in a creature's will to survive, is
profound. For many men and women, it is simply the most exciting
interaction they ever have with nature. I have known new anglers to
become absolutely disabled by the excitement in fishing, losing the
ability to tie a knot or cast the line. I saw one guy overwhelmed
and trembling as he tried to cast into a breaking school, and I
have often thought how interesting it would be to slap the blood
pressure cuff on an angler hooked up to an 18-pound bluefish on a
salmon rod.
</P>
<P>
   That day off Nantucket, Colby caught the first fish and the
most. We released them all, and her reaction became distilled into
a simple declaration. ``I want to get a really big one,'' she said.
``I want to go sharking. Tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tony Chamberlain writes about the outdoors for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 1344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4147 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV22     08-20 1374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV22-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT LUXURY, BUT NOT SUCH A BAD DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 22, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 56 years old, have over 25 years with my current
employer, and plan to work as long as I am able. I do realize,
however, that at my present age and salary I cannot take my job for
granted. I contribute 7 percent of my $85,000 salary to my 401(k).
We have a modest home with a $25,000 mortgage, a few thousand in
cash, a few thousand owed on credit cards, and about $30,000 in
stocks. My primary question is whether, at my age, I should be more
conservative with my 401(k) account. My current balance is
$256,677, spread over these funds: $27,396 in Janus Worldwide,
$27,401 in American Century Ultra, $126,014 in Fidelity Contrafund,
and $75,857 in Legg Mason Value Trust. My contributions are
allocated so 40 percent goes to Contrafund, 30 percent to Legg
Mason Value, and 15 percent each to the two remaining funds. In
addition, I have a choice of a few other Fidelity funds, a
Templeton foreign stocks fund, and some conservative to aggressive
strategies put together specifically for my company's 401(k)
program. Since I am in for the long run, I've always figured I
could ride out any bumps in the market. Have I positioned myself
for doomsday should I need to begin withdrawing from my 401(k) at
the minimum age of 59 1/2? I can probably count on at least $20,000
to $30,000 from my employer's retirement fund, depending on how
long I work, but if I should lose my job before age 59 1/2, I'm not
sure I can pay the bills.
</P>
<P>
   L.J., Poway, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. Boy, you're certainly in a gloomy mood. The way it looks to
me, you're likely to be quite a bit ahead of the typical situation
for retirees, although as you note, still pretty far from the lap
of luxury. I base this on the typical budget that calls for an
individual to need 60 percent of his preretirement income stream
once he retires. In your case, that would be $51,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   If you earned a $25,000 pension from your employer, and received
about $12,000 a year from Social Security, that would mean your
savings would need to produce an income stream of only about
$14,000 to put you in a solid, if not necessarily comfortable,
position.
</P>
<P>
   Since you seem to be focusing on age 59 1/2, let's look at what
your savings might be after 78 months. If you continue with your 7
percent contributions, which work out to $495.83 a month, and if
your 401(k) and your stock holdings produce average annual returns
of 8 percent during that time, you would have $523,363 accumulated.
</P>
<P>
   If you then invested half of the accumulation to produce an
income stream, that would bring you $17,009 a year, presuming a 6.5
percent average yield from a fixed-income portfolio. The remaining
funds could be left in a fairly conservative growth portfolio,
designed to protect you against the ravages of inflation in the
later years of your retirement.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't think you can live in retirement on about $54,000,
you could change the formula a bit and still be fairly safe. If you
put two thirds of your total savings on the fixed-income side, you
would get a $22,678 income stream, taking your total income near
$60,000, using the same assumptions as above.
</P>
<P>
   Now, you notice that I used an 8 percent growth assumption when
I projected the accumulation at age 59 1/2. This is partly a
function of my sour feelings about the current near-term prospects
for the stock market, but more so because I agree with your worry
that your position is too aggressive, and I am suggesting two
changes.
</P>
<P>
   The first is to get a broader allocation among various
stock-market sectors in your 401(k), and the second is to begin
building the fixed-income side of the portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   You don't specify what common stocks you hold, but I calculate
that 93.3 percent of the 401(k) portfolio is in either the
large-cap growth (American Century Ultra) or the large-cap blend
categories. The only diversification away from these sectors is the
63.3 percent of the Janus Worldwide portfolio, which is in foreign
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   All of your funds are excellent, but that's too much reliance on
large-cap domestic stocks. I suggest you look at the Templeton
offerings available through your 401(k), seeking an international
fund (which is wholly invested in foreign stocks) rather than the
world stock fund you hold, which holds 36.7 percent of its
portfolio in US stocks.
</P>
<P>
   I think after looking at the low one-star Morningstar rating for
Alliance Quasar and Morningstar's warning that the fund is ``for
the adventuresome investor,'' I would give that a pass.
</P>
<P>
   But you might look at some of the other offerings particular to
your 401(k), seeking vehicles with good records that will give you
exposure to the small- and medium-cap market sectors. I'd also like
to see a small position _ perhaps 10 percent at most _ in a
health-care sector fund, if such is available.
</P>
<P>
   Equally important is to begin work on the fixed-income side, to
get both more diversification and more safety. I would begin by
moving about 10 percent of the portfolio to the best intermediate
term bond fund that's available and then in each of the next two
years move another 10 percent to fixed-income holdings.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, I would reassess the situation. If after three
years you continue to feel as little job security as you felt when
you wrote your letter, you might continue the 10-percent-a-year
process into a fourth year; if you feel more secure at that point
and reckon that you are likely to continue working well past age 59
1/2, I'd hold the fixed-income side at 30 percent until you think
you're about three years from retirement, at which time you can
begin the process of transferring the final 20 percent to bond
holdings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a 29-year-old single mother or a 4-year-old boy, and
each month I have about $500 in discretionary income. I'd like to
begin saving for my retirement and my son's education, but my
knowledge of investment plans is virtually nil.
</P>
<P>
   Does it make sense for me to start a separate education fund for
my son, or should I just withdraw money from my own investments a
year or so before he goes to school?
</P>
<P>
   Second, I had planned to put my discretionary income toward
early repayment of my $45,000 in student loans, which have an
interest rate of about 8 percent. Is this a good idea?
</P>
<P>
   Also, what is the Morningstar Mutual Fund?
</P>
<P>
   T.B., Mattapan, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I think I'd suggest a little bit of each course. Certainly
beginning your IRA _ and making it a Roth IRA if you can afford to
absorb the slightly higher tax burden that comes with it _ is the
best first step, accounting for $166 of your monthly surplus. If
you were just embarking on a 10-year schedule of payments on the
loan, you would be paying about $539 a month. If you increased the
payment by $233 a month, the loan would be paid off in 73 months
rather than 120.
</P>
<P>
   That would leave $100 free, which could be put in a savings
account earmarked for your son (but in your name, so as to optimize
his access to financial aid should it be necessary and available).
After the 73 months of student loan prepayments, you could then
increase the level of the college savings, as well as perhaps start
a supplemental savings plan for your own retirement.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best ways to learn about mutual funds is from the
fund companies themselves. If you call Fidelity or Vanguard or any
other mutual fund company and ask for introductory information on
mutual funds, IRAs, and particular funds you suspect might interest
you, they will be happy to flood your mailbox with literature.
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar Mutual Funds isn't a fund company, but rather a
company that tracks and grades the mutual funds of other companies.
It produces detailed reports on mutual funds on a biweekly basis,
but they're fairly pricey, and a great deal of their very detailed
reports on mutual funds is available free on the Internet at
www.morningstar.net.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
