<HEADLINE>
FED EX COMPLIES WITH ORDER ON SAME-SEX BENEFITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Under threat of losing its cargo facility at the
San Francisco International Airport, the Federal Express Corp. has
agreed to comply with a court order to offer a limited package of
benefits to employees with unmarried partners.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, announced Thursday, came just before the deadline
to comply with an order by U.S. District Court Judge Claudia Wilken
regarding the city of San Francisco's Equal Benefits Ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   In an offer that complies precisely with Wilken's ruling,
Federal Express said it would offer bereavement leave and
discounted flights to unmarried partners, but would limit the
benefits to its employees in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement is much narrower than the package offered in
recently by three passenger airlines, United, American and US
Airways.
</P>
<P>
   Those companies offered employees with same-sex and opposite-sex
partners not only the flight discounts and bereavement leave, but
also medical and dental care, pension benefits and life insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The concessions have come while Federal Express, United and the
Air Transport Association, a trade group for the nation's largest
airlines, continue their legal fight against San Francisco's
2-year-old landmark law. The law requires companies doing business
with the city to provide the same benefits to workers with domestic
partners as they give to married employees.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines have filed a lawsuit, seeking exemption from the
law. Their position is that only the federal government, not local
jurisdictions, can make such mandates on the airline industry.
</P>
<P>
   In her ruling in May, Wilken said the airlines don't have to
provide health and pension benefits, but must offer bereavement
leave, discounted flights and other perks, but only to employees
who work in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines are appealing the ruling, but while the case makes
its way through the higher courts, Wilken ordered the air carriers
last month to carry out her order.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll comply with the court order,'' said Jess Bunn, a
spokesman for Federal Express, which is based in Memphis, Tenn.
``But in the meantime, we're going to vigorously pursue our
appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco law only kicks in when a new contract is
forged or an old one is extended. So far at the airport, the law
only has applied to United and Federal Express.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Express recently signed a 10-year lease for a new $59
million cargo warehouse and office complex at the airport to be
shared by three airlines. The company is paying the city-owned
airport $2.7 million per year in rent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
