<SLUG> BC-CLINTONS-VINEYARD-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTONS AROUSE LESS FANFARE ON FIFTH ISLAND VISIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ The crowd on the edge of the tarmac was the
smallest to greet Air Force One during President Clinton's five
vacations on Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   The White House blamed the relatively sparse turnout of 500
supporters and gawkers on airport renovations that have limited
parking availability.
</P>
<P>
   But on the island, where the president is usually warmly
received, there are subtle signs that the Vineyard is beginning to
wind down its greetings as the presidency does.
</P>
<P>
   Along the streets, only a few banners hung.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of Scoops ice cream parlor in Edgartown was running
late on his usual choosing of an honorific flavor. Thursday
afternoon, he decided on mango. Same as last year.
</P>
<P>
   The proprietor of the nearby By the Sea/Vineyard Gear clothing
shop dragged out to the porch those same old cardboard cutouts of
Bill and Hillary, which are slightly faded from too much sun and a
little tattered at the edges. Even the suits the first couple wears
in the lifesize likenesses are dated; the president's hair doesn't
look so gray.
</P>
<P>
   Shop owner Lois Boudreau said she just got fresh replacements
for the wilting figures (but has not yet put them on the porch) so
tourists can take snapshots with the fake couple as long as they
make an accompanying donation to a cancer charity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're more interested in the cancer funds than they are the
first family,'' Boudreau said, adding that during the Clintons'
first vacation here in 1993, ``There was huge hype. To be honest
with you, it's very low-key.''
</P>
<P>
   The presidential visit, of course, will hardly go unnoticed. The
state police warned that there will be the usual traffic jam.
Restaurants and stores will still be consumed when one of the
Clintons stops by, Secret Service and the curious in tow.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to solve the traffic problems when a large
motorcade snakes through a place with many narrow, one-way streets,
said Beth Toomey, West Tisbury chief of police.
</P>
<P>
   But the mood is different this year. ``We had a big incident in
July _ Kennedy,'' Toomey said. ``I think people are just looking
for normalcy.''
</P>
<P>
   Some cited scandal fatigue. ``Last year was the icing on the
cake,'' said Jack Rudy, a registered Democrat from the Philadelphia
area. ``Ho-hum is putting it nicely. I won't go any further than
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudy, pausing from a family bicycle ride, said he was
considering going to the airport for the Clintons' evening arrival
_ but only to check out the Air Force One DC-9.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons are only spending nine days at the Oyster Pond
estate of Boston businessman Richard Friedman before trading the
weathered cedar shingles for the unrelaxed Hamptons, for the East
Hampton home of movie maker Steven Spielberg. The Vineyard, locals
said, feels less like a destination and more like a pit stop on
Hillary Rodham Clinton's senatorial campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, she has been shopping for residences and votes
in New York and, for obvious reasons, wants to be seen vacationing
in that state. After doing some heavy fund-raising on the Long
Island gold coast, she and the president will dart upstate to the
upscale, polo-playing finger lake village of Skaneateles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an opportunity to see that part of the country,'' Julie
Mason, a spokeswoman for the first lady, said brushing aside all
talk of campaigning. ``And to be in a different place.''
</P>
<P>
   Robby Bick, manager of the Bunch of Grapes Bookstore in Vineyard
Haven, touched on the attention shift to the first lady in a letter
to the Clintons that accompanied reading material _ including the
second volume of Eleanor Roosevelt's biography by Blanch Weisen
Cook _ he set aside for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that Mrs. Clinton received a copy of the galleys, but
a bound copy is so much more lasting,'' Bick wrote. ``Since this
volume covers the period when Mrs. Roosevelt moved out of the home
onto the world stage, `Eleanor Roosevelt Vol. 2: 1933-1938 seems a
particularly timely gift.''
</P>
<P>
   In Nantucket, traditionally a Republican stronghold, there has
been some outright hostilty about the Clinton's planned day-trip
there Friday, involving a fund-raiser for the American Ireland
Fund. The Nantucket Golf Club snubbed the president's request to
play the 18-hole private course that members spend fortunes to
join.
</P>
<P>
   The Vineyard, meanwhile, remained low-key.
</P>
<P>
   In Oak Bluffs, the only noticeable tribute to the president was
a small chalkboard sign hung outside the general store, owned by
Susan Krueger, whose husband Steven, originally from Hot Springs,
Ark., went to the same high school as Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   And even that easily erasable scrawled welcome was vague.
``Presidents from Arkansas,'' ``Future Senators from N.Y.,'' and
``One particular (Stanford) student,'' were invited in for coffee
and soda.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if such visits had become routine, Susan Krueger, seated
behind the cash register, said: ``I don't know if `used to it' is
the proper verb. I would pour coffee for him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
