<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY HASN'T THE GOP FLOURISHED IN MASSACHUSETTS? NOW YOU KNOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Which photograph is more obscene? The one showing a brash young
blonde on the Nauticus flashing her breasts? Or the one showing two
boozy, backslapping pols, taking care of business, private and
public, compliments of the taxpayer?
</P>
<P>
   As eye-catching as the blonde might be, the second photograph is
more outrageous. Because it shows, as graphically as possible, how
low the business of state politics can sink in Massachusetts, along
with the state Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   The pundits keep asking why the state GOP can't capitalize on
the fact that Republicans have held the state's highest office
since 1991. Why can't the GOP grow? Why can't it build an
infrastructure and organization like the Democrats and field
strong, credible candidates for Congress and statewide office?
</P>
<P>
   Part of the answer lies in the puffy, dissolute face of
Alexander ``Sandy'' Tennant, lobbyist, political consultant, and
onetime executive director of the Massachusetts state Republican
Party. This perpetual bad boy is brazen, reckless, and successful _
because up until now, Governor Paul Cellucci let him be.
</P>
<P>
   Tennant drinks and swaggers his way around town, bragging about
his powerful connections. He insinuates that all political business
is a political fix, and if he isn't hired to do the fixing, the
business won't get done.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Blute, a former US representative and now former executive
director of the Massachusetts Port Authority, paid a high price for
his bad judgment in associating with Tennant. But if Blute ignored
the signals, so did Cellucci. Why?
</P>
<P>
   Just in the last few months, Tennant survived in high Republican
circles despite a reputation for indiscreet womanizing; a
drunk-driving arrest (he entered a plea of not guilty); and his
hypocritical questioning of Texas Governor George W. Bush about the
Republican presidential frontrunner's past drinking. Only after the
booze cruise was exposed did Cellucci pronounce Tennant unwelcome
in the State House.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Tennant is raking in big bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Documents filed recently with the Massachusetts Secretary of
State show that Tennant has not registered as a lobbyist. Tennant's
firm, New England Strategic Development Corp. earned $219,500 in
lobbying fees just since January. That may not represent all the
money Tennant gets from lobbying: ``We are not satisfied that the
records are complete,'' says Secretary Willim F. Galvin.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question political operatives like Tennant can earn
millions. There's also the possibility that their tactics scare
good, decent people away from politics and, in this case, the
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   John Brockelman, director of the Massachusetts Republican Party,
says the booze cruise ``has zero impact on the party. It's not
going to affect our candidate recruitment or our gathering of
signatures for the tax-rollback petition. Paul Cellucci just won a
convincing victory. He is probably the most popular elected
statewide official. If we stick with tax cuts and fiscal
discipline, we're going to win on the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   But another Republican insider, who is close to Cellucci, says
that while the Tennant controversy ``is not indicative of where the
party really is, it might hurt the party's progress. This is the
kind of stuff the Republican Party used to be known for. It brings
back all those crazy old Republican stories.''
</P>
<P>
   The state GOP can't find challengers willing to take on any one
of the Democrats in the state's 10-member congressional delegation.
State Republicans have put out the word that Plymouth County
District Attorney Michael Sullivan ``might'' launch an underdog
challenge against Senator Edward M. Kennedy. Imagine asking for
money and support from national Republicans, with the booze cruise
photo spread making the national political circuit?
</P>
<P>
   Republicans account for only 13 percent of Massachusetts'
registered voters. Brockelman is trying to build a statewide
organization and, since March, has raised $600,000 in GOP
contributions. So, even while he insists the Massport debacle has
no impact on the party's future, he also says that as of now
Tennant is no longer a Republican state fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the big picture problem for Massachusetts
Republicans is bigger than Tennant. It's the Cellucci
administration from the top down.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci should ban Tennant from the State House until he gets
the help he needs, and he should refuse to do business with anyone
who does business with Tennant.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a good first step, for himself and the state
Republican Party. The second step would be to start acting like a
governor with a future, instead of acting like one destined for a
single term.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Joan Vennochi is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
