<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FRIGHTENING REALITIES ABOUT NUCLEAR WASTE STORAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Maine _ If you live in small-town New England, you
take or send your trash to the dump.
</P>
<P>
   But if your trash is radioactive, it's very hard to find a dump.
And just as ``deaccessioning'' is the polite word museum operators
have for getting rid of the stuff they no longer want, the nuclear
industry's term for shutting down a nuclear power plant is
``decommissioning.''
</P>
<P>
   The mother of all bottom lines for nuclear power is the simple
question: what do you do with the deadly radioactive junk that's
left over? There is no permanent answer on what to do with the
lethal high-level waste that is the inevitable byproduct of all
those uranium-generated kilowatts.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday in Augusta, an obscure 10-member state rule-making
outfit, the Board of Environmental Protection, met to debate
intervening in the Maine Yankee utility company's scheme to build a
concrete pad on a gravel base to store spent nuclear fuel rods. An
earthen berm would be piled up around the ``hot'' rods, which will
remain dangerous to all forms of life for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Maine Yankee's old nuclear plant in coastal Wiscasset is now
shut down. But it continues to soak up dollars. Old nuke plants,
like old soldiers, never die; but neither do the radioactive sites
just fade away. They require constant monitoring, tending,
fretting, re-construction, and spending. Lots of spending.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has treated the nuclear power-for-profit
industry like the mother of all welfare mothers. And cleaning up
after this prodigal parent is a pricey proposition. Over two
decades, Washington dumped $3 billion into the Yucca Mountain
storage facility in Nevada, the intended resting place for the
worst of the waste. Nevada's state government has been trying to
block this scheme for years. But no way are the 49 other states
volunteering to receive the radioactive stuff. This is the ultimate
``hot'' potato.
</P>
<P>
   What will be stored here, if scientific fears about leaks,
earthquakes and water pollution are resolved, will be 70,000 tons
of extremely dangerous radioactive garbage, in miles of tunnels,
1,000 feet underground. The site is about an hour's drive east of
California's Death Valley, which may be the most aptly-named
national park in the system.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, you can dig a hole in the ground, bury the stuff, and
pray there'll be no earthquake, floods, asteroid hit or other Act
of God. Because the technical problems have proven insurmountable
to date, a lot of the 100-odd nuke plants in the United States have
become ``temporary'' storage sites for the radioactive waste that
is constantly generated.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reports that at least one storage cannister
of the more than 10,000 cannisters envisioned would fail within the
next thousand years. And after 10,000 years, all of the cannisters
would degrade, turning the lethal juice loose into the earth. The
stuff would remain dangerous for ``hundreds of thousands of
years,'' and there's no way to keep it out of the water supply.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with high-tech solutions to challenging scientific
problems is that huge mistakes are made _ almost as a matter of
routine. The Apollo One launchpad fire killed three prized
astronauts. Seven more died in the Challenger spacecraft. The
Titanic sank on its first trip. Things happen.
</P>
<P>
   Awareness of the potential for disaster is what fired protests
against the use of plutonium to power the Cassini spacecraft that
just curved around the earth like a slingshot and is on its way to
study the rings around Saturn.
</P>
<P>
   If this bus-sized machine had crashed into the earth during its
tricky manuevering around our home planet this month, we would have
had to swallow a very-bitter taste of our own nuclear medicine. We
don't want to be anywhere near this stuff. What makes you think the
Americans of the year 3000 will want it any more than we do?
</P>
<P>
   We are stuck now with what we have. We spend $30 billion a year
on nuclear weapons, which means we are creating more detritus. We
no longer build nuclear power plants because they only last 25 or
30 years, and are hideously _ and endlessly _ expensive to
``decommission.''
</P>
<P>
   The cold realities about waste storage effectively killed the
industry's expansion dreams. Their last gasp was the claim that at
least uranium-generated electricity didn't contribute to global
warming. True enough. Now, could I perhaps interest you in a nice
mountain vacation home with a wonderful view from atop Yucca
Mountain? I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign contributions that nuclear installation contractors
and utility execs gave to pro-nuke politicians bought the industry
about 30 or 35 years of political protection in high places. But
eventually, cold facts conquer even cold cash. There's no place to
put it; we're stuck with it. But it is mindless to keep producing
more of what eventually has to kill many, many of our fellow
humans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 1350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
