A4164 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-INVISIBLE-BOS &LR;      08-20 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-INVISIBLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HEARTFELT INSIDE LOOK AT LIVING WITH DIABETES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By IAN SHAPIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
SWEET INVISIBLE BODY 
Reflections on a Life with Diabetes 
By Lisa Roney 
Holt, 297 pp., $23.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Crafting a compelling memoir is a daunting task for any writer.
Those by celebrities often succeed, but that has more to do with
our own lust for their starry lives and less with their writing
talent. It's the ordinary folks, however, who must rely purely on
the content of their story and their ability to spin it to succeed
in our cutthroat, memoir-happy culture.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of Lisa Roney, for example. She has lived a life
most 39-year-old women might recognize, except that she is
diabetic. In Roney's first book, ``Sweet Invisible Body,'' she
reflects upon the everyday challenges of living through her
teen-age years, and as an adult, with a disease that affects 16
million people in the United States and is the seventh-leading
cause of death.
</P>
<P>
   Just before her 12th birthday in 1972, doctors diagnosed Roney
with diabetes mellitus, a chronic disease that requires her to
monitor and regulate her blood sugar continually.
</P>
<P>
   Roney's Tennessee childhood soon became an everyday challenge as
she coped with the little things of life. Walking home from school
or going to the movies was transformed from perfunctory to taxing.
</P>
<P>
   Diabetes forced Roney into constant awareness of her mental and
physical states, which in turn, led her to this therapeutic
literary medium. Seemingly, the author spares us not a moment of
her life: She introduces family, friends, and pets; she writes at
length about Carleton College (Minn.) roommates, about loves won
and lost, and about her years as an English teacher. Occasionally
you're reminded of Bobbie Ann Mason, as the story details a
Southern life jolted off track but restored by gritty stamina.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Sweet Invisible Body'' is only sometimes sweet and funny;
at other times, it's burdened with a hackneyed style and disjointed
anecdotes. From the beginning, Roney alternates between flat
phrasing and cliche, with occasional melodramatic touches:
</P>
<P>
   ``There is just about no condition I can think of that I hate
more. Is this, I wonder, what it's like to be psychotic, to have
multiple personalities, to move in and out of reality?'' She tells
us that she adores sleep, and ``longs for it like a fleeting
lover.'' And if Roney had to take only three insulin injections a
day, rather than having to constantly calibrate her health minute
by minute, just how happy would would she be? ``As a clam.''
</P>
<P>
   In recalling racism in Memphis (where she ``chose a smiling
brown girl named Suzette as my playmate'') and homophobia in
college (where she roomed with lesbians), Roney writes proudly of
her rebellious alignment with those who are outsiders. But it
becomes increasingly difficult to appreciate her sympathetic
qualities under the weight of her lackluster writing.
</P>
<P>
   Roney does succeed in capturing the queasy moments when
hypoglycemia has rendered her dazed, disoriented, even manic.
</P>
<P>
   And when she describes visiting a hospital inexperienced in
treating diabetics, she observes the sloppy blood-sampling
procedures with a keen eye: ``Try as she might, the nurse could not
get the needle to pierce my veins. As my entire body clenched in
pain, the nurse moved the needle back and forth under my skin,
twisting it sideways to try to nick the vein, turning it this way
and that at various depths of penetration. I felt as though a molly
bolt had been screwed into my arm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweet Invisible Body'' does offer diabetics (especially
younger women) a detailed portrait of what it's like coping with
life's daily minutiae bearing a seemingly invisible onus. Roney is
at her most colorful when she speaks most plainly _ when she
doesn't try too hard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
