<P>
   JAPAN-BANKS (Tokyo) _ Looking at the announcement by three of
Japan's biggest banks of plans to merge their businesses in an
alliance that would create the world's largest banking group, with
assets of more than $1 trillion. The three _ Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank,
Fuji Bank and IBJ _ say they will form a joint holding company by
fall of 2000 and then cut jobs by a fifth and close nearly 150
branches of the combined operations. The plan may give a lift to a
troubled national industry that has fallen behind in an
increasingly competitive global business. But others are skeptical
whether such a deal would solve the deep-seated problems in Japan's
banking system. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
