<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAITT AND COMPANY TO TOUR IN HARMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They've all sung on each other's records, shared each other's
musicians, and done benefit shows together. So it figures that
Bonnie Raitt, Jackson Browne, Shawn Colvin, and Bruce Hornsby would
eventually tour together, which they're doing this summer at a time
when ``none of us is trying to be a rock star,'' says Raitt.
</P>
<P>
   The artists have no new records to promote, so instead what
they're promoting is camaraderie and mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing it because of the high regard we have of each
other's music, and the love of one another,'' Browne says of a
national tour that begins at the Tweeter Center in Mansfield,
Mass.Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like you get to be a fan living out your fantasies by
working with your favorite singers,'' says Colvin. ``Expect a lot
of harmony singing. We all know each other's records.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We rehearsed for two weeks, then took a few weeks off to do
our own things. We'll be winging it a little bit when we get back
together, but there are a lot of good songs in there. I'm looking
forward to it,'' says Hornsby.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 35 songs to remember,'' says Raitt. ``It will be a
little hairy to do the first show, but luckily it's in Boston,
where we have a lot of support.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a minor miracle that we could have worked out our
schedules so we could do this tour at all,'' adds Colvin, a new
mother who is bringing her 1-year-old daughter on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the recent Bob Dylan/Paul Simon tour on which the artists
teamed for just part of the night, this new tour is ``more
adventurous,'' says Browne, and will see the participants play in
different configurations on each song. ``People will be on and off
the stage all of the time,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The format is still being worked out (``It won't just be a
jukebox of hits,'' says Browne), but ``we're basically each other's
band,'' Raitt says. Additional members include violinist David
Lindley, guitarist George Marinelli (who now tours with Raitt but
used to be with Hornsby), organist J.T. Taylor (now with Hornsby),
percussionist Wally Ingraham, and Browne's rhythm section of Fritz
Lewak on drums and Kevin McCormick on bass.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no musical director,'' says Colvin. ``It's fairly
democratic. The only rule is that everybody is in charge of their
own repertoire. You're responsible for the seven to 10 songs that
you do.''
</P>
<P>
   The tour grew out of some benefits that Raitt, Browne, and
Hornsby did to help victims of Hurricane Mitch. Colvin and Lindley
were then enlisted, followed by the rest of the cast.
</P>
<P>
   Each artist will play some hits, but also lesser-known numbers
from their archives and often in rearranged settings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some quiet, unplugged stuff and some wonderful, scary
funk that's very powerful,'' says Browne. ``There are all these
places that we can go.'' Adds Colvin: ``During rehearsals, on
certain songs somebody would jump in and that would change it.
Maybe it would be a different singing part. And then, other songs,
like Jackson's `The Pretender,' are very much like the recorded
version.''
</P>
<P>
   Colvin may try some new material (she has started making her
next album), but Browne says he'll stick with past tunes because he
fears that any new tune would be bootlegged immediately and ``put
on the Internet where you don't have control of it. There's just no
privacy anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the artists will tape some of the shows, and there's a
chance a live album will come from it, plus a home video. ``We
haven't made a definite deal yet on these things,'' says Colvin.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hornsby is doing his two New England dates with Fleck
this weekend. The two are old friends and have jammed together in
the past. Expect some bluegrass (Hornsby did a bluegrass reworking
of his hit, ``Jacob's Ladder,'' at Woodstock). Eventually, Hornsby
wants to make a bluegrass record, though his next album will be
with an orchestra, possibly the Roanoke Symphony, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Raitt calls Hornsby the ``focal point'' of the new touring group
coming to Tweeter on Thursday. She cites his versatility in
switching styles with such seeming ease.
</P>
<P>
   ``The music just pours out of him,'' Raitt says. ``I'm so in awe
of him and all the people in this lineup. There's a tremendous
amount of delight and spontaneity in being part of this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
