<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-STEPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING STEPS TOWARD U.S. AUDIENCE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOEY GUERRA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Don't be alarmed if you haven't heard of Steps _
you're not the only one.
</P>
<P>
   During the U.K. group's recent appearance in Houston, its five
members casually walked in and sat down in the lobby of the Aerial
Theater without the slightest fan flutter. No pleas for autographs,
no Backstreet-worthy squeals of excitement. The only interest came
from a clueless Page Parkes representative who was scouting the
area for potential cover girls. She approached member Claire
Richards with an application, which incited riotous laughter from
the rest of the group.
</P>
<P>
   The coed pop outfit, currently one of the opening acts on
Britney Spears' U.S. tour, is just getting started stateside.
Steps' first U.S. single, the love-lost dance anthem ``One for
Sorrow,'' was recently released and is also featured in the
upcoming Melissa Joan Hart flick ``Drive Me Crazy.'' Steps' U.S.
debut album, Step One, is a compilation of the group's two U.K.
discs and is due in October.
</P>
<P>
   In England, Richards, Lisa Scott-Lee, Faye Tozer, Lee Latchford
and Ian ``H'' Watkins are superstars. ``Step One,'' the group's
first U.K. album, has been certified triple platinum and boasts
five hit singles. In October, the group (which has rightfully
earned comparisons to Swedish pop supergroup ABBA) returns home for
the release of a new album and a tour _ the biggest U.K. arena tour
in the country's history.
</P>
<P>
   Steps was formed in 1997 after each member answered an ad in a
British newspaper looking for singers and dancers to form a pop
group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same kind of story as the Spice Girls,'' quips
Watkins, nicknamed ``H'' for his hyperactive personality.
</P>
<P>
   The group's first single, ``5, 6, 7, 8,'' peaked at No. 18 on
the U.K. charts. The next five were Top-10 hits and secured Steps'
place among Europe's current pop heavyweights.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, Steps is content playing second, third or even
fourth fiddle to its U.S. touring partners. (Spears' show features
four opening acts, including Tommy Jeans model Michael Fredo and
boy-band C Note.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's completely the opposite (in the United States),'' says
Latchford, 24, the oldest and quietest member of the group. ``It's
good, though, because it brings us all back down to earth in a way.
In the U.K., we can't walk down the street. To come here for the
first time, do a huge tour like this and be a support, it's like a
breath of fresh air. No one really knows us. We can go out. We can
have a good time. Hopefully, it will start a big wave _ we won't be
able to come back and walk down the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the lobby of the Aerial Theater, the members of Steps
play off each other like an old group of high-school chums.
Throughout the interview, Watkins pinches and plays with the girls
in the group, inciting squeals of ``That hurts!'' He is armed with
a camera and is videotaping everything around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we're waiting backstage to go out it's like, `Are they
gonna like us? Are they gonna join in?','' says Scott-Lee, 23. ``At
home, we know the minute we go out and do a show that all the kids
are gonna be singing along and doing all the dance moves. Sometimes
you may get an audience that will just sit there, and they don't do
a thing.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the case during Steps' brief but spirited set in
Houston. The group proved energetic and original, teaching the
young crowd a few quick dance routines (that's where the name Steps
came from) between songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The audiences are brilliant. Steps is about dancing as well as
singing,'' says Tozer, 23, the most talkative member. ``We weren't
sure if they'd join in over here, 'cause ... we're quite Euro-pop.
Having dancing breaks down all the barriers between the musicians
and the audiences. Everyone can interact with each other. It's a
lot more fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Steps' giddy pop sound appeals to the usual crop of
young teens. Their parents dig it, too, because it's squeaky clean.
The group has broadened its horizons to include British college
students (with whom they have a kitschy cult following).
</P>
<P>
   Potential cover girl Richards, 21, believes the keys to Steps'
success is simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's because we do look like we're having a good time,
and we do,'' she says. ``We all get on really well with each other.
I think that comes across to the audience, the kind of chemistry
between the five of us. With normal pop groups, there's like this
myth of pop stars (being) this untouchable kind of person, but we
try to break down all those barriers, and say, `No, come on, we are
accessible.' The clothes we wear are ones that you can go out to
the shops and buy, if you really want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Give them time. If Steps makes the right moves with American
audiences, they could find a few look-alikes in the crowd the next
time around.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
