<HEADER>
A4175 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-ILLUMINATA-BOS &LR;      08-20 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-ILLUMINATA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOROWITZ LIGHTS UP SCREEN IN `ILLUMINATA' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
ILLUMINATA 
Directed by: John Turturro 
Screenplay by: Brandon Cole, Turturro 
Starring: Turturro, Katherine Borowitz, Susan Sarndon, Christopher
Walken, Beverly D'Angelo, Donal Donnally, Bill Irwin, Ben Gazzara,
Matthew Sussman, Rufus Sewell, Georgina Cates, Leo Bassi, Aida
Turturro, David Thornton 
Running time: 119 minutes 
Rated: R (sexual content, nudity and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Affection slugs it out with heavy-handedness in ``Illuminata,''
John Turturro's farcical salute to theater folk. Ultimately,
affection prevails. What saves the day _ and the play _ is
Turturro's warm embrace of the world of the stage and its mix of
egos, aspirations, insecurities, and lusts. Turturro _ the
producer, co-writer, and star _ hasn't made it easy for himself and
his colleagues by serving up his playwright protagonist as
unrelievedly earnest and self-absorbed, then playing him for
sensitivity and not for laughs. It's a strategy that did a lot for,
say, ``Bullets Over Broadway,'' to say nothing of ``Shakespeare in
Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Turturro plays Tuccio, an ambitious writer in a
turn-of-the-century Manhattan repertory company, whose play is
thrown onstage before it's ready and is savaged by the most
powerful critic of the day, a gay dandy played by Christopher
Walken as if hellbent on becoming the Oscar Wilde of Park Row. The
film enters the realm of fantasy when the critic, Bevalaqua, is
induced to give the novice writer's play a second chance and a
second review. He's motivated by a visit from an actor who has
caught his eye. Played in crisply amusing horrified fashion by Bill
Irwin, the actor is cast by the company as a sacrificial victim and
dispatched to Bevalaqua's chambers, where the critic makes a clumsy
pass.
</P>
<P>
   Only Walken's fiercely funereal gravity could keep the scene,
and the critic, with his built-in-easy laughs, from
self-destructing. And so he does. Turturro pretty much neutralizes
himself as Tuccio, in whose brilliance we are vainly asked to
believe. The others in the company _ Beverly D'Angelo, Rufus
Sewell, Georgina Cates, Leo Bassi _ tumble with zest through a
daisy chain of sexual capers. But while warmly energized, their
carryings-on also seem a little generic. It's as if they, like
Walken's fatuous critic, are being put through their paces to cater
to what the writers believe the public expects from such
characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Illuminata'' would become pretty forgettable pretty fast if it
weren't for two heroic performances: by Susan Sarandon as a worldly
diva of appetite and style, and by Katherine Borowitz as the heart
and soul of the company to which Tuccio is attached. Turturro, who
is Borowitz's real-life husband, has said that ``Illuminata'' arose
in part from his and his wife's experience as artists trying to
live, love, and work together and survive the differing levels of
professional success each has experienced. As a theater piece,
``Illuminata'' is often as clunky as it is lively. But as a
valentine to an actress who fleshes out her material with beauty,
delicacy, and more radiance than anything around her,
``Illuminata'' justifies its title.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
