<HEADER>
A4177 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-SEIZURE-SURGERY-HNS &LR;      08-20 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEIZURE-SURGERY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURGEONS PERFORM RARE PROCEDURE TO RELIEVE MAN'S SEIZURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Michele Angeloni is CQ)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE FOY  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Every day over the last 12 years, epileptic
seizures overpowered Michele Angeloni.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden episodes would grip his body, wrestling all control
he had over his own actions. Sometimes, he would walk in circles in
a hypnotic state with his eyes closed. Other times, he would laugh
uncontrollably or fall down without warning.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't unusual for the 18-year-old, who lives on the Italian
island of Sardinia, to suffer up to a seizure an hour, every day.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, physicians in San Antonio performed what his
mother calls ``the miracle,'' a delicate, neurological procedure to
try and halt the young man's rare seizure disorder. Only about 100
such procedures have been reported worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me like a miracle because Michele has gone through
a very miserable life since he was 6,'' his mother, Silvana
Angeloni, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Angeloni family traveled to San Antonio from Sardinia so
that Dr. Alexander West, a neurosurgeon at the University of Texas
Health Science Center, could remove the tumor from the base of the
teen-ager's brain that was causing the bizarre seizures. He
underwent surgery Aug. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Although doctors say it's early, they are optimistic that the
seizures will no longer torment Angeloni and his family. Still,
some effects of the disorder, such as learning and cognitive
problems, may be difficult to reverse.
</P>
<P>
   The Angelonis took their son to the United States after Italian
surgeons shied away from the operation. The tumor, known as a
hamartoma, was located at the base of the brain, near the
hypothalamus _ which controls eating, sleeping and other actions _
and the optic nerve, which controls sight.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the location of the tumor, several Italian physicians
believed the intricate neurosurgery was too risky and could result
in loss of sight, smell or paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   But the Angelonis said they were tired of the seemingly endless
routine of seizures, medications and hospitalizations that had
become their son's life. He had already been diagnosed as having a
drug-resistant form of epilepsy, leaving the Angelonis with little
hope.
</P>
<P>
   Family members contacted the American Epilepsy Foundation and
learned of West. Soon after, West happened to be traveling to Italy
for an international medical conference. When he arrived, Silvana
Angeloni was at the airport in Milan to greet him.
</P>
<P>
   West spent more than a week with the Angeloni family. After
carefully evaluating Angeloni's case and determining the area of
the brain was fairly accessible, West agreed to do the procedure at
University Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was confident we could do it safely with minimal risk,''
West said, adding that the rare tumor ``may be the only one I see
in my lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   West and his surgical team temporarily removed a bone above
Angeloni's right eye to gain a clear view of the brain and remove
the tumor. The procedure, while complex, went without complication,
West said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Angeloni was born with the brain tumor, the first signs
of his seizure disorder didn't begin until he was 6. At first he
suffered the episodes in his sleep, leading his parents to believe
they were nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   But the boy soon began suffering from other, bizarre actions,
such as bursting out in sudden laughter. These extremely rare
episodes, known as gelastic seizures, were confusing to both
Angeloni and his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a normal social habit to smile when you're an infant, so
it was difficult to understand,'' said Dr. C. Akos Szabo, of the
health science center's Department of Medicine, who assisted in the
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The seizures progressed and varied as Angeloni grew older. On
the way to University Hospital the day of his recent surgery,
Angeloni even suffered a grand mal seizure _ an episode that causes
loss of consciousness, whole-body spasms and muscular convulsions,
as well as tongue-biting.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back on such traumatic times, Angeloni's mother noted
Thursday how the procedure seems to have opened up an ``entirely
new future'' for the family. ``It is one of the best periods of our
life,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
