<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4178 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-SUPERCHUNK-BOS &LR;      08-20 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SUPERCHUNK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERCHUNK CALLS THE TUNES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- One of the battle cries of the mid- to late-1970s punk
rock movement was DIY, or Do It Yourself. A number of rock bands,
both American and British, took that simple but revolutionary
philosophy and applied it to everything from making the music to
marketing it, often via small, independent labels. If you formed
your own record label, they reasoned, you had both artistic and
financial control.
</P>
<P>
   It is this path singer-guitarist Mac McCaughan and bassist Laura
Ballance chose for their band Superchunk 10 years ago. They set up
a label, Merge, in Chapel Hill, N.C. The small company _ it has
four employees _ prospers on its own terms. Costs are kept down,
allowing the company to profit on a CD that might only sell 2,000
copies. A ``big'' act, such as Neutral Milk Hotel, might sell over
20,000 copies. Merge does ``one-off'' projects with various bands;
McCaughan guesses the present roster contains about a dozen groups,
including his own offshoot, the gently rocking Portastatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I think we don't have any aptitude for (business) at
all,'' says McCaughan, from the Merge office, ``but we've managed
to hone our instincts about how we think our albums are going to
do. We're in a position where we have a small label with access to
great distribution.''
</P>
<P>
   The label's No. 1 act? That would be Superchunk, which is just
beginning a US tour and stops at the Middle East Downstairs this
weekend. A lot of rockers make a face when someone calls making
music a ``career,'' but McCaughan cops to it. He looks at his and
the band's evolution this way: ``When we first started, all we
wanted was to be in a band, to make records and play shows. After a
while, it takes on a life of its own, becomes its own entity,
becomes more of a job. It's not a choice of do we want to go oun
tour? You have to do certain things to support your record.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, if you're your own boss, you only have your own butt to
kick. And McCaughan says that for all boring routine of touring the
1 1/2 hours onstage makes up for it.
</P>
<P>
   Superchunk has been one of America's most consistent and
rewarding alt-pop bands over the past decade. Melody, crunch,
exuberance, wit, brains _ all there. Where does Superchunk fit into
the grand scheme of the pop parade?
</P>
<P>
   ``Movements and scenes are largely products of music writers,''
says McCaughan, ``and it's difficult to write about music. It's
easier to describe what they see as a movement. When we started, we
were the next Nirvana. Then (we were part of) the lo-fi scene, the
indie crowd grouped with Pavement. In some ways, though, if I had
to group us with anybody, I would group us with Pavement or Sebadoh
or Sonic Youth or Yo La Tengo, in terms of bands that have been
successful in doing what they want to do. All those bands have
changed the way they've sounded over the years, but the records are
consistently good. Somehow, we've managed to do that, too, and it's
not easy. I don't want to say we're as good or as influential as
some of those bands, but in terms of motivation and what the
results seem to be . . .''
</P>
<P>
   On the band's latest disc, its seventh full-length effort,
``Come Pick Me Up,'' the band recorded in Chicago and producer Jim
O'Rourke encouraged them to bring strings and horns to the mix.
They did so in a manner that seamlessly fits the music and adds
dimension.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't ever have a game plan other than to say `These are
the songs we've written and let's record them now,' '' says
McCaughan. ``We knew working with Jim would open us up to other
possibilities, horns and charts, string players. We didn't want to
go overboard with it, but the songs lent themselves to that.
Listening to it now, it may be our poppiest record, which I didn't
know when we made it. I think it's lighter sound-wise and
feeling-wise; it's pretty airy, actually.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lyrically,'' he adds, ``I don't usually see a theme until
later. Thematically, it seems to be about people being stuck in
their lives or finding ways to not be stuck, trying to take
control. It's a pretty universal thing, even for people who sit
back and say their lives are good. Everybody feels stuck in some
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if you allow McCaughan's assertion that ``Come Pick Me Up''
is a light record, be assured that it kicks, too, and the hooks
stick. As to the band in concert, make no mistake, with a
Buzzcockian power and punch. ``We're a punk rock band,'' says
McCaughan. ``Live, it's still pretty noisy and out of hand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
