 Friday, August 20, 1999    
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file or has filed the
following for Sunday. If you have questions, please call Chuck
Lewis or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in
all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   POVERTY-CHILDREN (Washington) _ On the third anniversary of the
new welfare law, a study by the Children's Defense Fund found that
the number of children living in the category of ``extreme
poverty'' rose 27 percent between 1996 and 1997. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   SOLOMON-LOBBYIST (Washington) _ Jerry Solomon, retired
Republican leader in Congress, has tried to duplicate his former
lifestyle in his new career as a Washington lobbyist. Many of his
former congressional staffers now work for his lobbying firm and
their boss follows the same legislative issues that he tracked for
20 years a congressman from the Albany, N.Y., area. He carries the
same brown cardboard portfolio with his name emblazoned on the
side, a personal trademark from his House days. He even spends his
week in Washington and returns to his former district on weekends,
just like the old days. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   OLDER-WORKERS (Washington) _ Gene Nelson, an experienced
computer programmer, has been looking for work for two years. He's
irked at the claim of the computer industry that 400,000 software
engineering and programing jobs go unfilled in the United States.
``There's no shortage of high-tech workers,'' Nelson says.
``There's a shortage of high-tech workers under the age of 35.'' We
examine the problem of older computer engineers looking for work in
an industry that favors the young. By MARK HELM. (Also in the ``f''
category.) (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOMBING-RANGE (Vieques, Puerto Rico) _ Puerto Rico's political
leaders and allies in Congress point to Hawaii's ouster of the U.S.
Navy from a bombing range on the island of Kahoolawe in 1994 as a
precedent for Puerto Rico's campaign to evict the Navy from a
58-year-old bombing range on the island of Vieques. The future of
Vieques is headed toward President Clinton's desk. By STEWART M.
POWELL. (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
</TEXT>
