<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MOFFATTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MOFFATTS SHOW STYLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KRISSAH WILLIAMS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ They may look alike.
</P>
<P>
   They may sound alike.
</P>
<P>
   But the Moffatts sure don't dress alike. Each member of the
boy-band has an individual style. The four members, all brothers
(including a set of triplets), shared their fashion secrets during
a recent stop on Teen People's Rock `N' Shop Fashion Van tour.
</P>
<P>
   Browsing the back-to-school fashions provided by Dillard's at an
area mall, the guys chose gear they said fits their personalities.
The Moffatt brothers _ Bob, Dave and Clint, all 15, and Scott, 16,
_ have their own closets and don't share clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Bob picked a long-sleeve, navy knit shirt with an orange collar.
``You don't have to be really built to wear this kind of thing,''
he said, laughing as he flexed his muscles. His fashion tips for
guys include: matching belts with shoes and wearing dark-denim
jeans with a small cuff.
</P>
<P>
   Dave selected a pair of olive cargo shorts. He said they
complemented his casual style. On the stage, he opts for brighter
colors, like orange and red.
</P>
<P>
   Clint, who said his style changes with his mood, chose a white
Guess T-shirt and dark jeans. ``I'm really into white T-shirts.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott found a pair of pants that he would wear with a T-shirt
and matching sneakers. A sports fan, he also picked out a blue
soccer jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The guys, who shop often to keep their style fresh, said they
sometimes try to go to the mall incognito, wearing baseball caps
and sunglasses. But when fans recognize them and ask for
autographs, they give them willingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shopping is a great thing. It's one of my passions. I love
getting new clothes,'' Clint said. ``I have to refill and restock
my closet. I really go through clothes really fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Teasing his brother Dave, Clint added: ``It's amazing, sometimes
Dave has cool clothes, but when it's on him I don't realize it's
cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Already widely popular in their Canadian homeland and overseas,
the Moffatts are working to develop a fan base here.
</P>
<P>
   The switch from country music to a ``rock-pop'' style on their
new CD, ``Chapter I: A New Beginning,'' could be the answer. The
album already has gone platinum in Canada, Indonesia, Thailand and
the Philippines. The CD's first single, ``Until You Loved Me,''
appeared on the ``Never Been Kissed'' soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   Scott plays guitar, Dave is on keyboards, Clint plays bass and
Bob is on drums. They all sing, with Scott taking the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Comparisons to other brother-bands (like Hanson) leave the guys
undaunted. Like their clothing styles, they feel their music
reflects their personalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're more alternative, and we have a lot more of an edge.
It's all music and (the variety of male-bands) give people
options,'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   The group has been well received at stops along the Teen People
tour, which includes a 68-foot van packed with the latest fashions
and accessories. At the south Houston mall, hundreds of teen-age
girls showed up to see the band.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've loved them since they were country singers,'' said
Kathleen Garrahan, 14, who has been a Moffatts fan since she was in
third grade. Kathleen came from San Antonio with her best friend
Krystina Scott, 13, to see the concert. ``They are like my other
favorite band, Hanson,'' Krystina said.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen, Krystina and other concert-goers left the mall with
free posters, CDs and other goodies. Only one question remained for
the Moffatts: What clothing trends do they suggest for girls?
</P>
<P>
   Baby-tees and dark-denim blue jeans or Capri pants.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
