<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRATION-REFORM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUPS PUSH TO REVERSE PUNITIVE IMMIGRATION LAWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALISON GREGOR  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Immigrant advocates are counting on a shift in
national attitudes to help them roll back part of a 1996
immigration law that these critics say is ripping families apart by
requiring deportation of legal immigrants for minor crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Members of a coalition pushing for changes in three 1996 laws
affecting immigrants say they are particularly encouraged by polls
showing a warming of national attitudes toward legal immigration,
which they believe has been reflected in the popularity of Texas
Gov. George W. Bush, a candidate for the Republican nomination for
president.
</P>
<P>
   But at least for now, Bush has decided not to talk about the
four bills filed months ago in Congress that the advocates hope to
have enacted.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, one of the GOP's leaders on
immigration issues and author of several of the provisions the
coalition wants changed, also isn't ready to say whether he would
support or oppose the bills.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has chipped away at Smith's Illegal Immigration Reform
and Immigrant Responsibility Act of 1996, along with provisions
that targeted immigrants contained in the Personal Responsibility
and Work Opportunity Reconciliation Act, also enacted in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Two House bills and two Senate bills filed this year would
restore more welfare benefits to legal immigrants and change a
provision that now requires federal authorities to round up and
deport legal immigrants who have committed crimes, including minor
offenses, no matter how long ago they occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``The X-factor in all of this is the race for the presidency in
2000,'' said Frank Sharry of the National Immigration Forum, a
pro-immigration group that, along with the American Bar Association
and the American Immigration Lawyers Association, are mounting a
campaign called Fix '96.
</P>
<P>
   ``With George W. Bush being the apparent leader for the (GOP)
nomination, it seems like both parties are likely to compete for
who could be more pro-immigrant,'' Sharry said. ``I think that's a
different dynamic in place that might result in surprising and
positive legislation to restore balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has publicly praised the contributions of immigrants and
two years ago helped create an $18 million nutrition assistance
program in Texas to replace food stamp benefits that the 1996
welfare overhaul had stripped from immigrants legally residing in
the state.
</P>
<P>
   But a week after a reporter provided copies of the bills to the
Bush campaign and asked whether he would sign or veto them if they
reached his desk as president, his campaign staff said the
candidate was declining comment on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the campaign develops, Governor Bush will lay out a
detailed platform on many subjects, including immigration,'' Bush
spokesman Dan Bartlett said this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush has consistently said that food stamp benefits
should not be retroactively denied for those elderly and disabled
immigrants who came to this country legally, worked and
contributed, but are now old and sick and cannot work,'' Bartlett
said.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration advocates said the proposed bills are the first of a
flurry of legislation expected to be introduced to change the 1996
measures, which they believe had much more stringent effects
against legal immigrants than Congress predicted or intended.
</P>
<P>
   With the support of President Clinton, Congress since 1997 has
restored about half the total amount of welfare benefits immigrants
lost under the 1996 overhaul of welfare. Sharry said he was
optimistic that trend will continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this year we're likely to see some movement to restore
benefits for legal immigrants,'' he said. ``That's happened in each
of the last two years, and there's strong bipartisan support for
it. As part of the budget negotiations, to some extent, you're
likely to see further restoration of benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS. &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The four bills being supported by Fix '96 are:
</P>
<P>
   _ HR 1485, introduced by Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., which would
give the attorney general discretion to cancel orders to deport
immigrants based on criminal convictions if they meet certain
criteria for length of residency and type of crime. It would modify
a 1996 provision that broadened the categories of crimes requiring
deportation.
</P>
<P>
   _ HR 185, introduced by Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., which would
establish a U.S. Immigration Court to preside over deportation
cases and appeals.
</P>
<P>
   _ S 1227, introduced by Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I., and
co-sponsored by Sen. John McCain of Arizona, a Republican
presidential contender, which would allow states to grant medical
assistance under the Medicaid program to pregnant women and
children who are legal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   _ S 792, introduced by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.,
which would allow states to grant medical assistance to legal
immigrants who are children or are pregnant, blind or disabled.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Vice President Al Gore, the leading Democratic
presidential candidate, said Gore favors the Chafee and Moynihan
bills and supports the goals of Frank's proposal, but not its
current wording. Gore is still studying the McCollum bill, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president is very much focused on the issues of
importance to the Hispanic community, and he will continue to be a
strong advocate on issues such as the unacceptably high Hispanic
dropout rate, restoring food stamp benefits to legal immigrants,
and the importance of the census,'' Gore spokesman Alejandro
Cabrera said.
</P>
</TEXT>
