<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH _ AKRON, Ohio _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush is in Akron,
visiting a social service center and a fund-raising luncheon.
(Hershey, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   NORWOOD _ Charlie Norwood came to Congress with one thing on his
mind: overhaul managed care. That single-minded vision has taken
the former dentist to a politically precarious spot. Norwood has
upset the Republican leadership by negotiating with senior
Democrats to get a bill to the floor despite Speaker Dennis Hastert
(R-IL) making it clear there would be no bill. w/Q&AMP;A (Carr, Cox
News Service). 35.
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   GA-TOBACCO _ ATLANTA _ Georgia's struggling tobacco farmers, who
have dealt with reduced growing allotments, diseased crops and
declining cigarette sales, finally get some good news: They will
begin receiving money by December from a settlement with the
tobacco industry. Gov. Roy Barnes appoints a board to oversee
distribution of the money, about $22 million a year, which is
separate from the state's $4.8 billion settlement. (Judd/Harvey,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   DALAIAMA-VISIT _ BLOOMINGTON, Ind. _ The event is called the
Kalachakra for World Peace 1999 _ one of the most sacred of
Buddhist rituals. It is being led by the Dalai Lama, head of the
Tibetan Buddhists, who have been driven into exile by China, and is
being held at the Tibetan Cultural Center in Bloomington, Ind.
(Jesse, Dayton Daily News). 26.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in the (a) General News and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
</P>
<P>
   COOTER _ SPERRYVILLE, Va. -- After slamming on brakes when he
spotted the organge '69 Dodge Charger parked beneath the Cooter's
sign, the Arkansas traveler led his family up to Ben Jones and
inquired ``You're the real thing, aren't you?'' Yessiree, or at
least as close to reality as Ben Jones gets. The former congressman
from Georgia has returned to his ``Dukes of Hazzard'' roots and
opened a roadside store near his home in the Blue Ridge Mountains
and is cashing in on the 1980s show's renewed popularity on The
Nashville Network. ``It ain't Disneyland,'' the host admits. A
visit to Cooter's. (Dart, Cox News Service). 25. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-STRIKE _ MEXICO CITY _ With the school year about to
start, there's still no end in sight three months into a strike
over a proposal to impose modest fees at the UNAM, this
hemisphere's largest university system. The UNAM is a huge,
virtually free university system in Mexico City that's paralyzed by
the strike. Mexicans empathize with the philosophy of free
education, but there are signs that people are simply fed up with
the students' tactics and intrasigence -- and think fees for
wealthier students might be a good idea. A July 24 poll showed that
only 48 percent of respondents would oppose the use of force to
re-take university facilities at this point. A month before, the
figure was 72 percent opposed. (Ferriss, Cox News Service). 20.
WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   CAYMAN-SUMMER _ GEORGE TOWN, Cayman Islands _ We needed this
family vacation. Four months of shuffling correspondents throughout
the Eastern Hemisphere to report on the bombing of Yugoslavia and
its aftermath had me in hives at the mere mention of the name
``Milosevic.'' Worse, my family was leaving me notes in lieu of
conversation. To re-connect we went to the Cayman Islands. It's the
off-season. Flights, car rentals and rooms are more reasonable.
Restaurants run the gamut: from expensive to affordable, from
authentic island cuisine to Pizza Hut. The primary entertainment
(read that, the beach) is free. And there are a few things you
can't put a price on: No theme park crowds. No panhandlers. A low
crime rate. (Christie, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   EDs: These travel stories are for Cox papers only. CoxNet is
constructing a Travel page from the package for use by all Cox
papers.
</P>
<P>
   CAYMAN-FALL _ GEORGE TOWN, Cayman Islands_ We needed this family
vacation. Four months of shuffling correspondents throughout the
Eastern Hemisphere to report on the bombing of Yugoslavia and its
aftermath had me in hives at the mere mention of the name
``Milosevic.'' Worse, my family was leaving me notes in lieu of
conversation. To re-connect we went to the Cayman Islands. As it
turns out, this gorgeous three-island chain may be one of the best
kept secrets for family vacations in the Caribbean off-season ?
generally the summer and early fall. Flights, car rentals and rooms
are more reasonable. Restaurants run the gamut: from expensive to
affordable, from authentic island cuisine to Pizza Hut. The primary
entertainment (read that, the beach) is free. And there are a few
things you can't put a price on: No theme park crowds. No
panhandlers. A low crime rate. (Christie, Cox News Service). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the same story as CAYMAN-SUMMER with a fall twist.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Mon., Aug. 16, in (i) International and (t) Travel
categories.
</P>
<P>
   CAYMAN-TRAVEL _ GEORGE TOWN, Cayman Islands _ Divers.
Honeymooners. Families. Encircled in powdery white beaches that
seem to float calmly in clear
</P>
<P>
   turquoise blue waters, the three islands that make up this
Caribbean chain _ Grand Cayman, Little Cayman and Cayman Brac _
have been expanding in the type of
</P>
<P>
   tourist they attract. For many of the same reasons. This tiny
group of islands has always seemed to hold a special place in the
heart of some wayward group _ from the adventurers who made them a
regular stop to load up on turtle meat, to the pirates rumored to
favor the coves of the sparsely populated islands, to the divers
who have made the Caymans one of the world's top diving
destinations. (Christie, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CAYMAN-BOX _ An If-You-Go ... With Kids box: Getting there;
getting around; getting going; and getting food. (Christie, Cox
News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Mon., Aug. 16, in International and Travel
categories.
</P>
