<HEADER>
A4228 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX     08-20 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE IN THE NOT-SO-FAST LANE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I have a 28.8K modem, but when I download
something, I download at 4.24K per second. Is there anything wrong
with my modem?
</P>
<P>
   _ Impatient
</P>
<P>
   DEAR IMP: Yes. You should go out immediately and buy a new one.
And I'm not saying that just because I'm trying to get a kickback
from 3Com. Well, that's not true, but because I haven't heard back
from them, here goes:
</P>
<P>
   Your modem is capable of connecting at approximately 28.8
kilobits per second. Most browsers measure downloads in kilobytes
per second. A byte is composed of eight bits. I know, the math
still doesn't work out, even with all the extra bits that help
verify a successful download thrown in. Download speed not only
depends on how fast you're connected, but how fast the remote
location can serve up a file to you, and there are so many
variables involved, it's not even funny. Be satisfied with your
4.24, and thanks for blowing the 3Com deal. I wonder if anybody
from Rockwell was reading this. ...
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I downloaded a game from the Net, and when it
asked what program to open it with, I didn't know which, so I
clicked on Dr. Watson. How do I change the program I open this file
with? Every time I download a game or demo, it won't open because
of it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Game Over
</P>
<P>
   DEAR OVER: Like the family cocker spaniel, Windows desperately
tries to please you. If it doesn't know how to do something, it
looks to you for guidance, which, in my case, explains why my
ex-dog thought drinking spilled beer on the floor was a good thing
and made everybody happy. In effect, you have told your cocker
spaniel to lick the kitchen floor.
</P>
<P>
   Windows tries to open programs based on file extensions. An EXE
extension means it's an executable file and should open or start
running on its own. Most downloads come that way. Something with a
ZIP extension is a zipped, or compressed, file, and you need a
special utility (WinZip32 is one) to open it. If you don't have the
utility, Windows asks you what to use instead. If you don't know
what to use, it's better to bail and try to figure out what you
really need.
</P>
<P>
   Open up ``My Computer'' and look for Folder Options in the View
menu. In there, you'll find File Types. This is where Windows
associates helper programs with file extensions. Just find the one
you added and delete it.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: What impressed me about your recent comments
about America Online is that you immediately said that you really
were not informed, for example, referring to AOL's on-hold music as
``Muzak.'' If you have ever been on hold with AOL and listened to
the background music (soft volume, not loud!), then you would know
they play classical music. ``Scheherazade'' and ``1812 Overture''
are two I have heard on numerous occasions. I don't think either of
them would be on the top of Muzak's easy-listening list.
</P>
<P>
   _ Classical Gas
</P>
<P>
   DEAR CLASS: You know, it's so much easier for me when people
hold themselves up to ridicule instead of having me do it. Thanks
for the break. Hope you get through to an AOL tech soon!
</P>
<P>
   (Dr. Bombay is looking for the Muzak version of ``Stairway to
Heaven'' to put on his voice mail, but will settle for anything by
the Go-Gos (soft volume, not loud!). He can be reached at
drbombay(at)star-telegram.com or via snail mail to Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Fax: (817) 390-7257.
In real life, Dr. Bombay is editorial systems manager for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 1441EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
