<P>
   BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN (New York) _ Sports of The Times column: Mark
McGwire comes to town, this time the home-run king making a new run
at the single-season record he now owns. But McGwire's body
language shows he wants something more these days _ a chance at
returning to the post-season. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-METS-CARDS (New York) _ St. Louis at the Mets, 7:40 p.m. EDT
start. By Judy Battista.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-TWINS (Minneapolis) _ N.Y. Yankees at Minnesota, 8:05
p.m. EDT start. By Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   RUN-WORLD-CHAMPS (Seville, Spain) _ The world track and field
championships open this weekend, with the focus finally on on-field
performance and not on drug speculation. Yet Dutch sprinter Troy
Douglas became the latest athlete to test positive for nandrolone
in a series of cases involving the steroid. The International
Amateur Athletic Federation's medical commission chief Arne
Ljungqvist said today the Dutch federation had confirmed Douglas's
positive test. By Christopher Clarey.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-CURCIC (New York) _ Sasa Curcic was hanging out with fans in
the parking lot, being his usual animated, over-the-top self. Why
not? He had not even played, having been suspended because of
previous on-field antics. Curcic may be playing for the worst team
in Major League Soccer, but the 27-year-old Yugoslavian has not
curbed his reckless style or his emotions. By Alex Yannis.
</P>
<P>
   With 2 photos, NYT9-10, on Aug. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ARMSTRONG-BIKE (Stowe, Vt.) _ Lance Armstrong, the Tour de
France champion, competes in a different kind of race: mountain
biking. By Frank Litsky.
</P>
