<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4234 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-BEATLES-TOUR-2TAKES-H     08-20 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEATLES-TOUR-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOURING THE ENGLAND OF THE BEATLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN FLINN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Let others journey to Paris in search of Hemingway's
cafes or walk the streets of Salzburg listening for the echoes of
Mozart. The Beatles are my cultural heroes, and I'd come to England
for an immersion course in Beatlemania.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment I heard their mono LPs _ with pennies holding
down the tone arm on my record player _ I've wanted to see
Strawberry Fields and Penny Lane and the train station from ``A
Hard Day's Night.''
</P>
<P>
   I've wanted to inhale the dank aroma of the Cavern Club and hear
a droll Liverpool accent and, yes, put my life on the line for a
picture in the Abbey Road crosswalk. Most of all, I've wanted to
understand the connection between these unremarkable places and the
remarkable music they inspired.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three decades after they went their separate ways, the
Beatles are firmly enshrined as cultural icons in Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Their handwritten song lyrics, scribbled on airline stationary
and the backs of greeting cards, are on permanent display in the
British Library, just steps from the Magna Carta and Chaucer's
Canterbury Tales.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Paul McCartney's childhood home in Liverpool is owned by the
National Trust, which also owns homes of Winston Churchill, Thomas
Hardy and Rudyard Kipling.
</P>
<P>
   Liverpool and London, the two main Beatles cities, abound with
Beatles walking tours, Beatles bus tours, Beatles guidebooks,
Beatles museums and Beatles memorabilia shops.
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense to visit Liverpool, the scene of their formative
days, first. There's enough to see that it's worth spending at
least two days there, but my wife Jeri and I journeyed up from our
base in London as, well, day-trippers. A ticket costs $114, round
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Unfairly, Liverpool has been stuck with the reputation as a
grim, depressed, dead-end city. This probably stems from stories of
the Beatles' early years in the late 1950s, when the port city,
bombed heavily in World War II, was still struggling to get back on
its feet.
</P>
<P>
   Today, England's third-largest metropolis is prosperous and
pleasant, with a lively downtown business district and expansive
green parks. New auto and pharmaceutical plants have opened, the
port is busier than ever and ferries still cross the Mersey river.
</P>
<P>
   Our first stop was 20 Forthlin Road, part of a tidy ``council
estate'' _ the British term for public housing _ in the city's
working-class Allerton district.
</P>
<P>
   The row house where Paul McCartney lived with his father and
brother between 1955 and 1964 has been faithfully restored to its
original condition by the National Trust. The walls are hung with
photos from those days taken by McCartney's brother, Michael.
</P>
<P>
   His mother (``Mother Mary'' of ``Let It Be'') died of breast
cancer shortly after they moved in, and Paul grew up as a latch-key
kid.
</P>
<P>
   According to his tape-recorded reminiscences on the self-guided
tour, he and his friend John Lennon used to cut school and sit for
hours in the house's tiny front parlor with their guitars,
composing songs.
</P>
<P>
   It was here and in Paul's upstairs bedroom _ so tiny you can
just about touch all four walls at once _ that they wrote, among
others, ``Love Me Do,'' ``I Saw Her Standing There'' and ``She
Loves You.''
</P>
<P>
   McCartney recalled the first time he played the latter, with its
``yeah, yeah, yeah'' refrain, for his father.
</P>
<P>
   His father complained about those ``Americanisms,'' McCartney
said, and wonder why he couldn't just sing ``Yes, yes, yes''?
</P>
<P>
   Next up was a quick tour of ``The Beatles Story,'' a museum at
the redeveloped Albert Dock with exhibits from their early Hamburg
and Liverpool days, including their collarless suits and original
drummer Pete Best's drumsticks. It was a good primer in Beatles
history, filled with baby boomers trying to explain to their
children what life was like before the Spice Girls.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the museum we joined the Magical Mystery Tour, a
two-hour circuit of Liverpool's Beatle sites in a 1960s bus painted
like the one used in one of the group's more ill-considered
projects. As a guest book was passed around to sign, I was reminded
yet again of the Beatles' universal appeal. On this day the tour
included fans from Japan, Australia, Israel and Chile.
</P>
<P>
   We visited each of the Beatles' childhood homes and punctured
the longstanding myth that John came from the toughest, most
impoverished background. Ringo, who grew up in the rough ``Dingle''
neighborhood of Irish immigrants, was easily the poorest, followed
by George and Paul.
</P>
<P>
   Lennon lived with his Aunt Mimi in Liverpool's leafy Woolton
district.
</P>
<P>
   Not far away, on Church Road, stands square-towered St. Peter's
Parish Church. It was here, on July 6, 1957, that John's schoolboy
skiffle group, the Quarry Men, was performing at the annual Woolton
Fete. Fifteen-year-old Paul dropped by _ he'd heard it was a good
place to pick up girls _ and a partnership was born.
</P>
<P>
   In the church graveyard there's a headstone with a familiar
name: Eleanor Rigby. McCartney always has maintained he invented
the name, but the grave site suggests his memory may be faulty.
</P>
<P>
   Around the corner from Lennon's childhood home, on Beacon
Street, we stopped at the gates to the Victorian-era Salvation Army
orphanage known as Strawberry Field. (For reasons unknown, John
pluralized it in the song.) Lennon could hear the Salvation Army
band playing from his backyard _ one of the inspirations, some
Beatleologists believe, for ``Sgt. Pepper.''
</P>
<P>
   The front gates were covered with chalk-written messages from
fans, bits of lyrics, scrawled signatures, declarations of love.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry Field still operates as an orphanage. Lennon paid for
a new wing to be built in 1979, and since his death his widow, Yoko
Ono, has given generously toward improvements.
</P>
<P>
   As we rounded a corner, our guide, Eddie Porter _ who grew up in
Liverpool at the same time as the Beatles, played in a rival band
and seems to know everyone in town _ waved to a white-haired old
man with a vaguely familiar face.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Charlie Lennon, John's uncle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not far away is the business district that played a central part
in the young lives of both Lennon and McCartney: Penny Lane.
</P>
<P>
   It looks much as it did in their time, although ``the shelter in
the middle of the roundabout,'' where Paul composed much of the
song while waiting for John, is now the Sgt. Pepper's Bistro. On
one side is Lloyds TSB Bank, where ``the banker never wears a mac
(rain jacket) in the pouring rain.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other is the Tony Slavin Ladies and Gentleman Stylists,
where ``the banker sits waiting for a trim.''
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't time to stop and walk around on this tour, but on
an earlier visit I talked to a Penny Lane shopkeeper who claimed to
remember John Lennon well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't much of a musician back then, but he was a right
good shoplifter.''
</P>
<P>
   (It should be pointed out, though, that hoodwinking tourists
with invented Beatle stories _ ``Fab Fibs'' _ is a favorite pastime
of Liverpudlians. Just the same, Lennon's juvenile delinquency is
well-documented.)
</P>
<P>
   Our tour ended at the Cavern Club, the subterranean,
catacomb-like venue where the Beatles played 274 times between 1961
and 1963 and met their future manager, Brian Epstein. The Cavern
was closed and paved over in 1973, but was rebuilt at virtually the
same site in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not exactly original,'' said owner Bill Heckle, ``but
it's not a fake, either.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a Beatles plaque at the entrance and ``Twist and Shout''
blares into Mathew Street from a speaker. Inside, down two flights
of stairs, I was glad to see it's a real, working club, not a tacky
Fab Four tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
   It smelled of disinfectant and sweat, just as it did in the
Beatles' days, and a playbill announced that two young Liverpool
groups, ``Warped'' and ``Pineapple,'' would be playing that night.
I yearned to stay and hear them, to see Liverpudlians crowding the
tiny dance floor and condensation running down the brick walls.
</P>
<P>
   But we had to return to Londaon, a three-hour train ride.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the day we'd set aside for our London Beatles
tour was a special occasion: the 30th anniversary of the shooting
of the Abbey Road photo. Richard Porter, president of the London
Beatles Fan Club, had put together a special day-long tour for the
ultimate Beatles fan.
</P>
<P>
   Our day began at the Abbey Road crosswalk in time to mark the
exact minute _ 11:35 a.m. _ the photo was taken. Downtown, we
walked past the site of the Indica Art Gallery, now vacant, where
John met Yoko at an exhibit in 1967. ``John dropped by for an event
called a `Happening in a Bag,' and was disappointed to find out it
wasn't an orgy,'' Porter said.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was on to 3 Saville Row, in the heart of the
fine-tailoring district. This stately office was the site of the
Beatles' last public performance, the rooftop concert at the end of
``Let It Be.''
</P>
<P>
   The street's tailors complained constantly to the police about
the groupies, mystics and autograph-seekers who crowded around the
front door 24 hours a day, Porter said.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away, on Argyll Street, is the theater where, in
1963, the Beatles first appeared on ``Sunday Night at the
Palladium,'' Britain's version of the Ed Sullivan Show. Thousands
of shrieking fans filled the streets outside, and London's Fleet
Street press coined a new word: ``Beatlemania.''
</P>
<P>
   The theater currently is showing a stage performance of
``Saturday Night Fever.''
</P>
<P>
   Next door is the place where Beatlemania first began to falter.
Sutherland House, manager Brian Epstein's London office, is where
John Lennon gave an interview to Maureen Cleeve of the Evening
Standard that included his infamous ``we are more popular than
Jesus'' quote.
</P>
<P>
   The people on the tour were almost frighteningly well-versed in
Beatles lore. They often finished Porter's stories for him, and no
site was too obscure for them. At least two of them had visited a
bakery owned by Jane Asher, Paul's one-time girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   A quick stroll down Carnaby Street, clothiers of Swinging London
(and a prime sartorial inspiration for Austin Powers), led us to
Soho Square and the headquarters of MPL Communications, Paul
McCartney's London offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you hang around here long enough, you'll eventually see Sir
Paul,'' said Porter, passing around snapshots to prove his point.
``He comes by about once a month.''
</P>
<P>
   We boarded minivans for a tour of Beatle film sites in London's
suburbs. Not everyone, it must be noted, was thrilled to see us. As
we crowded into the City Barge pub along the River Thames in
Strand-on-the-Green _ where Ringo ended up in the basement with the
tiger in ``Help!'' _ the bartender drew our pints with barely
disguised contempt. ``Beatles people,'' he muttered.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a different story at the row houses along Ailson
Avenue in Twickenham, where _ also in ``Help!'' _ the four Beatles
entered separate doorways only to emerge in the same large living
room. (The inside shots were filmed in a studio.)
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Brady, who lived there at the time, was happy to come
out of her house and share stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``The girls were screaming, and they had to string up a rope to
hold them back,'' she said. ``Paul would come out and give a wave,
and that would set them all off again.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``They were great guys. They'd come into peoples'
houses for tea, and they spent a lot of time chatting with us. For
years we were getting letters from fans, saying, `Please pass this
on to Ringo,' that sort of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in London, a special treat awaited us: a living piece of
Beatles history _ Rod Davis, an original member of the Quarry Men,
the Liverpool skiffle group that evolved into the Beatles.
</P>
<P>
   Thin, neatly groomed and gray-bearded, Davis was at the Beatles
For Sale memorabilia shop autographing copies of the Quarry Men's
reunion CD.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't kicked out of the group _ I just sort of drifted
away, and it didn't seem like any big deal at the time,'' he told
me.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
