r s BC-BBA-YANKS-METS-HNS &LR;      08-20 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-METS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBWAY SERIES REDUX? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ They are on a collision course.
</P>
<P>
   Like consonants in the last name of a Big Apple cabbie.
</P>
<P>
   Like Seinfeld and the Soup Nazi.
</P>
<P>
   Like a late-night jogger and a Central Park mugger.
</P>
<P>
   Like a lead-footed driver and a jay-walking pedestrian.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees have the best record in the American
League. The New York Mets have the best record in the National
League. The way the Yankees and Mets are going, they'll set
baseball back four decades and change.
</P>
<P>
   All the way back to 1956.
</P>
<P>
   The last subway World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, featured the one and only perfect game in
World Series history.
</P>
<P>
   Deal with it, America.
</P>
<P>
   Get ready to brave the $300-a-night hotels that serve eggs laid
by golden geese, if you want to get anywhere near the action.
Beware of the mud to be slung back and forth between the camps of
non-candidate candidates Rudolph Giuliani and Hillary Rodham
Clinton. Try and figure out whether the city doesn't sleep because
of: (a) the incessant honking of horns; (b) the clear and present
danger of police, without warning, barging into the homes of
innocent citizens and dragging them off to ``Cats''; (c) the
strange, mostly unidentifiable, smells; (d) the guilty conscience
that comes with having inspired in any way ``Mad About You''; or
(e) all the above.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some New Yorkers object _ angrily, of course; you got a
problem with that? _ to even the most gentle suggestion that the
Big Apple is not a new, improved version of the Garden of Eden.
Those in the know understand that it's best to fill the heads of
outsiders with horror stories.
</P>
<P>
   Keeps away some of the riffraff.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have been riffraff for so long, the natural impulse is
to take them about as seriously as Weird Al Yankovic. Mets manager
Bobby Valentine has as many first-place finishes as Charlie Brown.
The Mets tried to fortify their pitching staff by trading for
left-hander Kenny Rogers, who wilted under the white-hot playoff
lights as a Yankee. Valentine is as popular in baseball circles as
Larry Flynt is among the Republican Party, but that shouldn't
detract from what the Mets have accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, barely two months have passed since general manager
Steve Phillips fired three members of Valentine's coaching staff.
The Mets were 27-28 and had lost eight in a row, prompting
Valentine to give himself this ultimatum: ``I'm not worried about
my job. I believe, though, that in the next 55 games, if we're not
better, I shouldn't be the manager.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine has managed to steer the Mets to 26 games above .500 _
the franchise's high-water mark since the end of the 1988 season.
Those were the days when Darryl Strawberry and Doc Gooden had a map
and engraved invitations to the Hall of Fame. Orel Hershiser and
the Los Angeles Dodgers may not have done any humbling of the
Darryl-and-Doc Mets, but crumbling sure ensued.
</P>
<P>
   These Mets have won more road games than anybody in the majors,
evidence that they have the maturity to beat anybody anywhere. They
should have maturity on their side, what with fellow 40-year-olds
Rickey Henderson and Hershiser filling key roles.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a lot can happen between now and October. The Mets
are living proof of how much things can change in two months.
Having the best record at the end of the season, let alone now, is
no guarantee of a long and prosperous playoff life. If Dan Reichert
(12.08 earned run average before Wednesday) and Blake Stein (career
6.15 ERA before Thursday) can shackle the Yankees on consecutive
days, then everybody is vulnerable in a short playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two weeks ago, the Mets ran the gamut from hopeless to
helpless in losing three straight at home against the Dodgers. The
Mets have gone 7-2 since then to overtake the Atlanta Braves in the
NL East.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been through enough not to let (a bad stretch) get us
down,'' Valentine said. ``Yesterday doesn't affect today, and
tomorrow is far away.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the possibilities of October are too tantalizing to
ignore. The competition. The contrasts.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees manager Joe Torre, with his quiet self-assurance in a
city that once viewed him as Clueless Joe. Valentine, with his
moody, chip-on-the-shoulder demeanor. The classic pinstripes of the
Yankees. The cheesy black, blue and orange getup of the Mets.
Revered Yankee Stadium. Reviled Shea Stadium. Derek Jeter:
shortstop, superstar and eligible bachelor. Mike Piazza: catcher,
superstar and eligible bachelor.
</P>
<P>
   Against that backdrop, Giuliani and Clinton would be tussling
for the affections of the Yankees' constituency. Giuliani is a
life-long Yankees fan who treats the Mets like the stepson who will
not, under any circumstances, get any of the inheritance. The First
Lady is a life-long Chicago Cubs fan who recently declared her
allegiance to the Yankees. Of course, if the Yankees were to get to
the World Series, and fall behind to the other team in New York ...
</P>
<P>
   So the two teams proceed, on a collision course with the past
and future. October 1999 could turn out to have a retro subway
feel. Just don't ask the Mets to indulge in a look at the past or
present.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turn Back The Clock'' was all of the past the Mets could
handle. The Mets donned 1969 uniforms for a July promotion against
Tampa Bay and lost. Later in the month, they endured the indignity
of ``Turn Ahead The Clock.'' Wearing pseudo 2021 attire, the Mets
vanished into the Twilight Zone during a defeat to the Pittsburgh
Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't beamed up to the proper coordinates,'' Piazza
explained afterward. On the days when the Mets don't have to set
their clocks decades into the past and future, they have the best
record in baseball. No wonder they prefer to stay rooted in the
present.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
