<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POSTCARDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WISH YOU WERE HERE' AND OTHER POSTCARD MESSAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (for use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN FLINN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Whe it comes to postcard wit, it's hard to top Jimmy
Buffett's classic line: ``The weather is here, wish you were
beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   But I don't know a single person I could send it to who wouldn't
slap me when I got home.
</P>
<P>
   I thought of this the other day as I sat in a London pub with a
stack of blank postcards in front of me and an equally vacant mind.
Not for the first time, I wondered if mailing postcards was really
worth all the bother.
</P>
<P>
   The main problem, of course, is that no matter what you write _
no matter how breezily you describe the swaying palm trees or the
paisley sunsets or the frothy umbrella drinks _ your message can
always be summed up as: ``I'm somewhere fabulous right now. And
you're not.''
</P>
<P>
   Your friends who don't travel much probably roll their eyes,
mutter something unkind about you and toss your postcard straight
into the garbage can. Your friends who do travel a lot _ well,
they're probably not home anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Take it from me: It doesn't do any good to try to ease the
recipient's jealousy by quibbling with the weather or the food or
the flat, room-temperature beer. You come across as someone who's
somewhere fabulous _ and whining about it.
</P>
<P>
   If you're overseas and want your postcards to arrive home before
you do, you've pretty much got to mail them the day you arrive. At
this point in your journey there's usually not a whole lot to say:
``A bit of turbulence over Iceland. Luggage didn't get lost. Give
my love to Aunt Myrtle.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if there is more to say, I'm generally good for, at most,
only one pithy comment per destination. Once, in Kenya, I sent off
a batch of postcards with the line, ``We were charged by an
elephant and overcharged by a Nairobi shopkeeper'' _ only to
discover when I got home that the various recipients had all shared
their postcards with each other. After being repeated a dozen
times, the line _ admittedly pretty weak to begin with _ looked
considerably less than witty.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally I've gotten so carried away in my ramblings that
I've forgotten to leave room for stamps. There's nothing to do but
throw away the card and start over. However, a bigger peril these
days is the bar code strip the U.S. Postal Service affixes to the
bottoms of postcards. They have an unerring instinct for covering
up the punch line to a long anecdote, or, more commonly, for
blotting out the sender's name entirely. Every couple of weeks I
receive a postcard from some mystery correspondent who's having a
wonderful time on a palm-fringed beach and wishing I were there.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't find a hotel or convenience store that will sell
you a stamp, you've got to give up half a day of sightseeing and
stand in line at the local post office, many of which make the U.S.
Postal Service look like models of efficiency and cheerfulness.
</P>
<P>
   In some countries, guidebooks routinely warn that if you don't
watch the postal clerk cancel the stamp at the counter, he'll wait
until you leave, peel off the stamp and re-sell it to the next
person in line. Your postcard gets tossed in the trash. It's hard
to imagine anyone going to such lengths for 40 or 50 cents, but
I've read the warning so many times I half-believe it.
</P>
<P>
   You may end up doing what I usually resort to: carrying the
postcards home with you and hand-delivering them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
