   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-BANKS (Tokyo) _ Looking at the announcement by three of
Japan's biggest banks of plans to merge their businesses in an
alliance that would create the world's largest banking group, with
assets of more than $1 trillion. The three _ Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank,
Fuji Bank and IBJ _ say they will form a joint holding company by
fall of 2000 and then cut jobs by a fifth and close nearly 150
branches of the combined operations. The plan may give a lift to a
troubled national industry that has fallen behind in an
increasingly competitive global business. But others are skeptical
whether such a deal would solve the deep-seated problems in Japan's
banking system. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-BANKS-REACT (Undated) _ The view of the Japanese banking
deal from abroad and what it could mean to the U.S. banking
industry. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT-ARCHIVE (Cambridge, Mass.) _ More than 2,580 volumes of
handwritten credit reports from 1841 through 1891 may sound like a
particularly dull and dreary collection. But for business
historians, the R.G. Dun &AMP; Co. Collection at Harvard University is
the Holy Grail. The credit assessments are invaluable to historians
in part because they avoid corporate spin and show the unbiased
view of a third party _ in this case, the agents, or
``correspondents,'' across the nation who reported back to R.G.
Dun's home office on the creditworthiness of local carpenters,
grocers and milliners. By Julie Flaherty.
</P>
<P>
   CYPRUS-ASARCO (Undated) _ In another sign of the rapid
consolidation in the metals industry, Cyprus Amax Minerals Co. and
Asarco Inc., which agreed to merge last month, say they have
rejected an unsolicited offer from Phelps Dodge to acquire both
companies for $2.6 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-BANK (Singapore) _ Displaying internal divisions that
could hurt economic reform efforts, lawmakers from Indonesian
President B.J. Habibie's own political party are squaring off
against him over a widening corruption scandal over Bank Bali. By
Wayne Arnold.
</P>
