<HEADER>
A4284 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-PIANIST-INSULT-HNS &LR;      08-20 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIANIST-INSULT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIANIST RESPONDS TO CRESCENDO OF INSULTS WITH LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PETER HARTLAUB  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The letter to Garrick Ohlsson contains a
symphony of insults.
</P>
<P>
   A three-page missive addressed to the renowned concert pianist,
it appears to be separated into movements. Dizzying highs.
Deceptive lows. Dazzling crescendos of put-downs and personal
comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grow up,'' the letter states, in one of its livelier passages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your bone-crushing reign as a gifted adolescent ended a long
time ago and we're all bored to sobs with you.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter came from Ohlsson's manager, Vincent Ryan. Ohlsson
responded with a lawsuit, claiming the words are so brutal that
they cross the line into defamation and ``infliction of emotional
distress.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers say that if it's not a first, it's certainly a rarity:
The recipient of a nasty note suing to recover monetary damages
based on the contents.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint was filed against Arts Management Group Inc. in
San Francisco Superior Court last week. The war of words appeared
to begin when Ohlsson, a San Francisco resident, decided to change
management to Los Angeles-based International Creative Management.
</P>
<P>
   AMG's New York-based lawyer, Robert Helfand, said his client
doesn't want to discuss the matter with anyone except Ohlsson.
</P>
<P>
   ``AMG is sorry Mr. Ohlsson has felt the need to carry this
dispute into court,'' Helfand said. ``We believe the complaint has
no merit and that AMG will win the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohlsson, 51, has been playing in the San Francisco Bay Area for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Court records show that the virtuoso was represented by Ryan for
19 years. Ohlsson signed his latest contract in June 1998,
promising 20 percent of his gross fees to AMG.
</P>
<P>
   But the relationship declined drastically shortly after that
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Letters between Ohlsson and Ryan, included in the lawsuit as
exhibits, show that the pianist decided to leave AMG in part
because he wanted more exposure in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work at the highest international level,'' Ohlsson wrote to
Ryan and another manager in an April 30 letter. ``I need to work
with people capable of showing up and working at that level with an
international vision.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the lawsuit, Ryan faxed Ohlsson at a hotel in
Akron, Ohio, five days later. His response appeared to spare no
insult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since you have appeared just about everywhere in Europe for
three decades, it is remarkable that the message has not gotten
through to you that Europe has made its choices,'' the letter
reads. ``Wake up, for Christ's sake.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohlsson's lawsuit asserts that the letter harmed his
professional reputation, also causing him ``anxiety, embarrassment,
humiliation and anguish.''
</P>
<P>
   He wants punitive damages, along with his legal fees paid.
Ohlsson also is seeking a court order that says Ryan's letter
effectively terminated his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Ohlsson's lawyer, David Mattingly, said his client was ``deeply
admired and loved'' around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unfortunate that his former New York agent, Arts
Management Group, has sought to undermine his reputation and
well-being by its untoward conduct,'' Mattingly said.
</P>
<P>
   The letter may be harsh, but a legal scholar said it could be
very difficult for Ohlsson to get the case to trial.
</P>
<P>
   Marsha Cohen, a professor at the University of California
Hastings College of the Law in San Francisco, said there is a lot
of room in the law for angry people to express their opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law is not intended to do what our kindergarten teachers
wanted us to do: Be nice,'' Cohen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
