<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4297 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX     08-20 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE KEY TO THE `GUN PROBLEM': ENFORCE THE LAWS WE HAVE NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Through the twisted, dark recesses of the mind of Buford O.
Furrow Jr., one reality did manage to seep through. If you're going
to target someplace to make a statement with bullets, pick a spot
where no one will be shooting back.
</P>
<P>
   The avowed racist had several Jewish organizations on his hit
list last week as potential sites for his hate-driven ``wake-up
call to America.'' He picked the North Valley Jewish Community
Center outside of Los Angeles because security at the other
buildings was too intense.
</P>
<P>
   Even a madman was sane enough to recognize that when the good
guys have guns, it's not smart to jack with them.
</P>
<P>
   It is so basic that it should be intuitive for every American:
Good people with guns are a threat only to bad people, while bad
people with guns are a threat to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   So we should be doing what we can to keep guns from bad people,
right? Yet the push in Washington is to write more gun laws that
will impact the good people and continue to be ignored by bad
people for many reasons, among them the fact that the odds against
strict enforcement are in the bad people's favor.
</P>
<P>
   Policy-makers write laws hoping that they will deter
unacceptable social behavior. Since a negative can't be proven,
it's impossible to quantify how many people toyed with the idea of
mayhem but discarded it because a law stood in the way of carrying
out the plan. But a law with no enforced consequence is meaningless
against those who are willing to test it. If the tiger is toothless
and clawless, it doesn't take much for sick prey to outmaneuver the
beast.
</P>
<P>
   This nation does have a gun-related problem, and it's the lack
of will to put dollars into enforcing laws already scribbled within
government's legal tomes. This is one facet of the gun debate where
the most strident of both sides _ the vocal minority that would be
tickled by a complete ban on private gun ownership, and the vocal
minority that believes any regulation is a threat to
constitutionally guaranteed rights _ should be able to agree.
Enforcement must be a priority.
</P>
<P>
   Had existing laws been enforced, perhaps Furrow would not have
possessed the firepower he used to fire 70 rounds into that day
camp, wounding three children. Perhaps he wouldn't have had the
handgun from which to fire the fatal shots at postal worker Joseph
Ileto. Furrow was under a court order not to have firearms in his
possession. Law enforcement personnel never followed up on that
directive.
</P>
<P>
   The reality in this world is that subhumans like Buford Furrow
will continue to slither through the cracks. Evil has always had a
way of doing that. But that court order, if enforced, would have
been one more obstacle in his way, one more opportunity to
intervene.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers, obviously, make laws. But writing legislation without
including the dollars needed to enforce it is just an exercise in
political posturing.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Constant, one of the great classical liberal thinkers
of the 19th century (that's ``liberal'' in the traditional
definition of one who believes that liberty is mankind's highest
political goal and that religious faith, a free-market economy and
limited government are central to that goal), had it right when he
said: ``Whenever there is no absolute necessity, whenever
legislation may fail to intervene without society being overthrown,
whenever, finally, it is a question merely of some hypothetical
improvement, the law must abstain, leave things alone, and keep
quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the changes being proposed in the federal gun laws are
little more than hypothetical improvements. Although high-profile
cases such as Furrow's make it seem otherwise, gun violence is
statistically on the decline in this country. Unintentional
firearms deaths _ down. Homicides by firearms _ down. Suicides by
firearms _ down. School violence _ down.
</P>
<P>
   What this country has done, for the most part, is working. But
one more concrete step toward shoring up the gaps that remain is
making prosecuting gun-related cases a priority.
</P>
<P>
   Do what Chicago did this week. Agents from the federal Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms cracked down on suburban gun dealers
who violated the law by selling to people they knew were going to
take banned handguns inside the city limits of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Do what Richmond, Va., has done with Project Exile (for the
record, a program strongly supported by the National Rifle
Association). Police and prosecutors strictly enforce federal gun
laws, which carry stiffer penalties than state offenses. Anyone
arrested on a drug offense who is also carrying a gun feels the
full force of the law. The homicide and robbery rates in that city
fell 30 percent, and more than 500 guns were taken off the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of putting money into filing nuisance lawsuits against
gun manufacturers in an end-run attempt to legislate through the
judiciary, cities, counties and states should be putting dollars
into the enforcement of existing gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached via e-mail at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or by phone at (817) 390-7599. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
