<HEADER>
A4357 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN     08-20 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE MUST CHALLENGE THOSE WHO HATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We who live in the religious majority can't even imagine the
pain and the verbal slaps in the face _ and the occasional violence
_ endured by those who live in the religious minority.
</P>
<P>
   I was forcefully reminded of that last week when talking with
some of my Jewish friends and acquaintances concerning the
horrendous hate crimes that have occurred in America lately.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest instance, a white supremacist misfit named Buford
O'Neal Furrow
</P>
<P>
   fired 70 shots into a Jewish Community Center in California,
wounding five people. He also confessed to killing a postal worker
near the center.
</P>
<P>
   He did it all in the name of his twisted faith and said he hoped
his horrendous act would be ``a wake-up call to America to kill
Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   We need a wake-up call, all right.
</P>
<P>
   We need to be more alert to the hate groups, often identifying
themselves as ``Christian,'' that seem to be increasing in this
country.
</P>
<P>
   Religious freedom is a hallmark of our American democratic
experiment. But when faith turns violent, it needs to be
challenged.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate violation of religious freedom comes when crazed
people like Furrow decide to gun down those who have a different
faith or ethnic makeup.
</P>
<P>
   Other ``hate crimes'' have occurred recently. Two brothers,
Matthew and Tyler Williams, have been charged with torching three
synagogues and killing a gay couple in California.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Aaronson, executive director of Congregation Beth Shalom
in Arlington, Texas, said religious bigotry is an everyday concern
for Jewish families everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a day that a Jewish mother sends their child to
school that she doesn't worry about that child,'' she said. ``We
worry that someone will ask them `Why don't you celebrate
Christmas?' or `You are going to hell because you don't believe in
Jesus.'''
</P>
<P>
   Aaronson said the bigots are in the minority, but they are still
there.
</P>
<P>
   The California shooting is even more detestable, Aaronson said,
because it was aimed at children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who targets children _ the most innocent of innocents _
is committing more than a `hate crime,''' she said. It is a crime
against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   The Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith recently reported
that anti-Semitic incidents increased by 2 percent last year after
declines in such incidents during the previous three years. But
many such crimes go unreported.
</P>
<P>
   In the Fort Worth-Dallas area there are few anti-Semitic
incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have few problems,'' said Don Dossey, a leader of
Congregation Kol Ami in Flower Mound in Denton County. ``Our only
incident came when someone painted (swastikas) on the front of our
building. But they did the same thing to a Baptist church next
door.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Yosef Hodakov, the leader of this area's conservative
Chabad Lubavitch organization, sees little overt anti-Semitism.
When he hears a slur, he chalks it up to ignorance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, witnessing any of this is very painful,'' he said.
``In America, we've come so far as a nation that we've become known
as an open and welcoming society.''
</P>
<P>
   But the emergence of hate groups, including many with Web sites,
is a heightening concern, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult, because we are a free country and believe
in free speech, but we need to crack down on these groups,'' he
said. ``Words sometimes lead to actions.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the worst things that could be done, the rabbi said,
would be to return violence with violence.
</P>
<P>
   What the terrible hate crimes might do, he said, is to remind us
to be even more loving and accepting of all people.
</P>
<P>
   He is optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, light overcomes darkness,'' he said. ``You can
light a small candle in a dark room, and soon that tiny light will
brighten the entire room.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 1611EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4358 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-COOTER-0821-COX     08-20 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOTER-0821-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FORMER CONGRESSMAN AND TV STAR THRIVES AT ``COOTER'S ``
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    EDS: Moving in (w) Washington and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPERRYVILLE, Va. _ Followed by his hesitant family from Ward,
Ark., (population 700), Kevin Bernard approached the former Georgia
congressman perched on the hood of the orange '69 Dodge Charger and
inquired, ``You're the real thing, aren't you?''
</P>
<P>
   Yessiree. It's ol' Cooter, all right. Seven years after leaving
Capitol Hill, Ben Jones is living his role as the greasy,
good-natured mechanic on the ``Dukes of Hazzard'' and cashing in on
the show's revival on cable by The Nashville Network. From
Thursdays through Sundays, Jones presides at a garage converted to
the ``Hazzard General Store'' beside a two-lane highway winding
toward the Shenandoah National Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ain't Disneyland,'' Jones cheerfully concedes. ``If we're
open, I'm here. This is what it is _ me talking to folks, posing by
the General Lee, signing pictures, singing ...''
</P>
<P>
   The General Lee, for those who never visited TV's Hazzard
County, is the souped-up car with a Confederate flag painted on top
that cousins Bo and Luke Duke took airborne every episode in
eluding the greedy Boss Hogg and the bumbling Sheriff Rosco P.
Coltrane.
</P>
<P>
   The Charger parked beneath the ``Cooter's'' sign outside of
Sperryville is one of 229 General Lee's used in the series, said
Jones. About 1,500 vehicles of all sorts were wrecked during the
seven years that the program ran on CBS, ending in 1985. Cooter
spent considerable screen time driving a tow truck to pick up
police cars that had smashed up chasing the Duke boys.
</P>
<P>
   Few of the fans crowding around the orange car remembered Jones'
brief political career. A Democrat, he represented Atlanta suburbs
from 1988 through 1992 before being defeated by Republican Newt
Gingrich after redistricting altered the political landscape. But
the visitors all recognized the grinning fellow in the sleeveless
shirt as ``Cooter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just happened to be passing by and saw the General Lee
parked there,'' marveled Delbert Fioles, from Ponca City, Okla. He
promptly bought a $10 ``Cooter's Garage'' cap for Jones to
autograph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up with the 'Dukes of Hazzard'. I've still got the
little Hot Wheels cars,'' said Chris Dodson of Chesapeake, Va. He
drove his family an hour out of their way after overhearing a
conversation about ``Cooter's'' at a MacDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my favorite show,'' said Vince Barrick, who lives
nearby and brought his collection of character cards for Jones to
sign. ``I had all the matchbox cars and a scrapbook. It's good to
have one of them living around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooter's souvenir store and museum of ``Dukes of Hazzard''
memorabilia opened on July 4, about a year after Jones and his
wife, Alma Viator, moved into a log home in nearby Harris Hollow.
Viator runs a public relations agency in Washington, D.C., and met
Jones when he was serving in Congress. Since his defeat, Jones has
resumed acting _ appearing in the movie ``Primary Colors'' and a
``Dukes of Hazzard'' TV reunion, among other roles. He moved to
Rappahannock County, Va., after several years in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've found a wonderful home here,'' he allowed. ``The best
thing is that people judge you by the way you are _ not by how much
money you have but by the way you behave.''
</P>
<P>
   Viator said the roadside ``Cooter's'' store ``was a crazy idea
that he had that I let go in one ear and out the other for a long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   But in 1996, TNN began showing reruns of the ``Dukes of
Hazzard'' twice a day and people started recognizing ``Cooter'' in
shopping malls and asking for his autograph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started thinking that maybe it wasn't so crazy,'' said
Viator. ``When we came here, nobody cared that he had been in
Congress but they were excited that 'Cooter' was moving into the
neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones is happy to autograph ``Cooter's'' wares ranging from
$4.50 cast pictures to $7.50 baby bibs to $15 T-shirts with cut-out
sleeves like the ones he wears. Visitors can also buy local
foodstuffs like ``Daisy's Country Honey'' and ``Miss Alma's Apple
Butter.'' Not for sale is an array of artifacts inspired by the
program _ scripts, action figures, model cars, props, Cooter's
costumes, off-screen snapshots of the cast, and even The New York
Times obituary of Sorrel Brooke, the actor who played Boss Hogg.
</P>
<P>
   TNN has ``introduced the show to a whole new generation of
fans,'' said Jones. Indeed, ``Dukes of Hazzard'' Web sites abound
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Jones compares the show to the B-Westerns of old where action is
paramount and the good guys always win. Children can watch the
program with their parents, he said. ``It's not cynical. Nobody
ever gets hurt. I hear it every day from visitors _ 'Thank you for
putting on a show that was so much fun'.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Daisy Duke's long legs and short shorts may have
contributed as much as the car chases to the show's popularity with
teen-aged boys. Catharine Bach played Daisy. John Schneider
portrayed Bo. Tom Wopat was Luke. James Best was Rosco P. Coltrane.
Denver Pyle, who died last year, portrayed Uncle Jesse Duke.
</P>
<P>
   The surviving regulars will return for a second reunion program
to be taped this autumn, said Jones.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Viator's agency represented theaters in Washington.
She claims to have been a Hazzard fan from the start because she
knew Wopat from his appearances at the National Theater. So now she
splits her time between her PR business in Washington and the cash
register at Cooter's, 80 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben stays out here,'' she said. ``It's only for a rare,
personal favor that he'll come into D.C. any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said his two terms in Congress were ``a thoroughly good
experience and a real honor'' but ``I can't say that I miss it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he seems to relish being ``Cooter.'' He chats and poses
enthusiastically with everyone who stops by.
</P>
<P>
   Even on a Thursday, a sizable audience assembled as Jones took
the microphone with a local bluegrass band. ``We've had a lot of
requests but I'm going to sing anyway,'' he declared through
speakers set atop galvanized tin washtubs. Later he launched into
the lyrics popularized by Waylon Jennings, the narrator for ``The
Dukes of Hazzard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just two good ol' boys,
</P>
<P>
   ``Never meaning no harm,
</P>
<P>
   ``Beats all you ever saw,
</P>
<P>
   ``Been in trouble with the law
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the day they were born.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the store, videotapes of the ``Dukes of Hazzard'' run
continuously on a monitor. A sign advertises a ``blue plate
special'' of an RC Cola and Moonpie for $1. On the phone, Viator
takes an order for ``Cooter's'' T-shirts from somebody calling from
Connecticut. And the General Lee is pulling cars off the highway
and into the parking lot like an orange magnet.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
