<HEADER>
A4365 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-JUDICIAL-REVIEW-HNS &LR;      08-20 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDICIAL-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOARD CLEARS CALIFORNIA JUDGE OF MISCONDUCT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SETH ROSENFELD  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a decision hailed as protecting judicial
independence, the California judicial watchdog agency has dropped
disciplinary charges against a San Francisco judge who had been
accused of failing to follow a controversial state Supreme Court
decision.
</P>
<P>
   The Commission on Judicial Performance on Thursday issued an
order dismissing charges against state Court of Appeal Justice J.
Anthony Kline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am grateful that the commission has vindicated me ... and
vindicated the independence of all judges in the state of
California,'' said Kline, who was named to the appeals court in
1982 by then-Gov. Jerry Brown. ``If judges aren't free to think
freely ... we are in a sorry state.''
</P>
<P>
   The 8-1 vote by the commission marked a turnabout from a year
ago, when the panel of mostly Republican appointees voted to
proceed with the case. The charges triggered widespread criticism
of the commission as infringing on the judicial autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   ``At stake in this action was whether the law of California
would be decided by constitutionally appointed judges or whether it
would be decided by the staff of the commission,'' said James
Brosnahan, the San Francisco lawyer who represented Kline. ``The
present commission has answered that question in a clear way that
bodes well for judicial independence.''
</P>
<P>
   The charges stemmed from a 1997 case in which Kline dissented
from an appeals court opinion that granted a ``stipulated
reversal,'' an order allowing two sides in a civil lawsuit to
privately settle their case even after it has been decided at
trial, effectively wiping out the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   The state Supreme Court approved stipulated reversals in a 1992
case. Critics said the process allowed litigants to buy their way
out of unfavorable court rulings and to unfairly shape public law.
The U.S. Supreme Court disparaged stipulated reversals in a 1994
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   In his dissent, Kline refused to grant a stipulated reversal,
declaring ``judicial decisions are not for sale.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, someone filed a confidential complaint accusing
Kline of failing to follow the state's legal precedent, and the
commission brought formal charges against him for ``willful
misconduct.'' Kline denied the charges, which, if upheld, could
have ended his judicial career.
</P>
<P>
   The Kline case sparked concern that the commission was
interfering with legitimate judicial opinion. The California Judges
Association came to Kline's aid with a brief that asked the panel
to drop the charges, because they ``can only be seen by sitting
judges as a deterrent to their free expression.''
</P>
<P>
   While the case was pending, Gov. Gray Davis, a Democrat, was
elected and appointed new members to the commission.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the commission concluded that there was no basis to
punish Kline, 61.
</P>
<P>
   The commission said Kline had a ``tenable belief'' that the
state Supreme Court's rule on stipulated reversals was
``destructive of judicial institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot conclude ... that the dissent was improper,'' it
said. In a comment that seemed meant for the body's own critics,
the commission added, ``We readily reaffirm our fundamental belief
in the principle of judicial independence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 1619EDT &QL; 
