<SLUG> BC-SOLOMON-LOBBYIST-$ADV22-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLOMON PRACTICES SAME BRAND OF POLITICS DOWNTOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 22)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Rep. Gerald B. H. Solomon has changed his
job from lawmaker to lobbyist but you'd never know it.
</P>
<P>
   He has kept much of the same staff, the same legislative agenda,
the same in-your-face bluntness. He still has his office on
Pennsylvania Avenue _ though eight blocks from the House of
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   He still goes back to his ``district'' on weekends. And he even
totes the same trademark cardboard file folder with ``SOLOMON''
emblazoned on the side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty much doing the same thing, just from a different
point of view,'' said Solomon, who retired last winter after a
20-year career in the House. He ended up as chairman of the House
Rules Committee _ the powerful panel that can determine the fate of
legislation. Now he heads the four-man Solomon Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I had the power to go out and implement or block'' a
proposal, he says. ``Now I have to sell it.''
</P>
<P>
   A Ronald Reagan-worshipping conservative, Solomon says he limits
his lobbying clients to ``people I believe in.''
</P>
<P>
   He said couldn't bear being a ``show horse'' for a large
lobbying firm because that would mean working for clients whose
goals he doesn't share. ``I question people who change allegiances
for a dollar,'' Solomon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry Solomon has been doing what he has been doing for 30
years,'' he said, referring to himself in the third person as he
often does. ``He has stood up for business, industry and jobs in
the district.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomon's roster of lobbying clients includes many of the same
constituents he once served as a congressman.
</P>
<P>
   As a lobbyist for General Electric Co., a major employer in his
former district, he now tracks mortgage and insurance issues. He
stands ready, if asked, to lobby the Environmental Protection
Agency against requiring GE to spend millions of dollars to dredge
the Hudson River to remove the PCBs that the company legally
discharged into the river.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon has passionately opposed the dredging for years.
</P>
<P>
   The ex-Marine also represents veterans' groups, which he was
closely allied with in Congress. He says he works for ``half
price'' to try to keep dairy prices stable for farmers, another
cause he fought for as a lawmaker. But he says he has rejected
computer industry clients, whom he opposed in Congress by opposing
encryption technology they wanted to sell.
</P>
<P>
   He shares office expenses and clients with former Republican
Sen. Paul Laxalt, R-Nev., who was one of Reagan's closest
confidants, because ``Laxalt thinks the same way I do.''
</P>
<P>
   The most prominent photos in Solomon's office are framed
portraits of Reagan and President George Bush, which flank the
glass gavel given to him when he retired as rules chairman. ``Those
are my two heroes,'' Solomon says.
</P>
<P>
   His portable file holder contains notes from his meetings with
veterans groups and conservatives; he acts as liaison between them
and Speaker Dennis J. Hastert, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both the speaker and majority leader have me in a group to
give them advice every few weeks,'' Solomon said. ``I still have a
lot of input.''
</P>
<P>
   Ethics laws prevent Solomon from lobbying Congress personally
for a year after retiring but the rules leave a lot of room for
maneuvering. He said he often goes to the Capitol Hill Club, a
Republican social center, and meets with members. ``I'm allowed to
talk politics but just don't talk clients.''
</P>
<P>
   The law allows his staffers to lobby members of Congress. ``They
can identify themselves as members of the Solomon Group but they
can't say Jerry Solomon sent them,'' he said, adding: ``It's a fine
line.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Solomon Group payroll is his former press secretary, Bill
Teator, as well as Bill Crosby, former counsel for the House Rules
panel, and Dave Lonie, his one-time staffer on the Foreign Affairs
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon keeps the same travel schedule that he has followed for
two decades: He flies into Washington on Mondays at the crack of
dawn and returns to Albany on Thursday or Friday nights and when
Congress is in recess.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stewardesses still think I'm a congressman,'' he says. He
says while it was ``hard to give up'' the power he enjoyed as
chairman of the House Rules panel, he says it's been even tougher
to change his work schedule. ``It gets in your blood,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   His wife of 44 years, Freda Parker Solomon, joins him mid-week
in Washington when she is not selling real estate on Lake George
and caring for her Siberian Husky.
</P>
<P>
   She, rather than his constituents, is now in charge of his
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why you don't see any more stress on Jerry Solomon's
face,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He says he has piloted his motorboat around Lake George 40 times
this summer, compared to four times in 10 years while he was on
Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon lives in a one-bedroom apartment in the same Market
Square building that holds his office; the trip home is an elevator
ride. His neighbors include Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.,
Defense Secretary William Cohen and Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   On his 69th Birthday last weekend, Solomon greeted crowds in
Ames, Iowa, as he stumped at the Iowa straw poll for Texas Gov.
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon says he got to know Bush well during the 1996 Republican
Convention in San Diego when he was parliamentarian and Bush was
general chairman. They sat for days on the dais with ``no one to
talk to but ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   His seventh floor office has an awesome view of Pennsylvania
Avenue. Solomon says he hopes to use it as a box seat Jan. 20,
2001, to watch Bush's inaugural parade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
