<HEADLINE>
MAN WITH TIES TO MISSING ATHEIST SENTENCED ON WEAPON CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A federal judge on Friday sentenced a leading
suspect in the disappearance of national atheist leader Madalyn
Murray O'Hair to 8 years in prison on two firearms charges.
</P>
<P>
   David R. Waters, 52, a former office manager for O'Hair, was
sentenced last week by a Texas court to 60 years in prison for
stealing money from one of her organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Waters has a total and abject disrespect for the law,''
U.S. District Judge Sam Sparks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing to indicate he will not commit further
offenses,'' the judge said in imposing the maximum penalty
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Waters must serve the federal time once he satisfies the
sentence imposed for stealing $54,400 in 1994 from the
organizations run by O'Hair. It was not clear how much time Waters
must serve on the state sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Waters, who has been jailed since March, appeared in an orange
jump suit and laceless white sneakers. He declined an offer from
Sparks to address the court.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, however, argued that Waters, a prime suspect in the
disappearance of O'Hair, was really being punished harshly because
of that unsolved case.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair, her son Jon Murray and adopted daughter Robin Murray
O'Hair are presumed dead, but their bodies have not been found
since they vanished from San Antonio nearly four years ago. O'Hair
gained prominence more than 30 years ago for her court fights
against school prayer.
</P>
<P>
   No one has yet been charged in connection with the disappearance
but Waters and two other men are accused in a federal affidavit of
kidnapping and murdering them. One of the suspects was murdered
shortly after the O'Hair family vanished.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all understand the government's position is not motivated
by the issues at hand. There is a hidden agenda they don't want to
talk about,'' said Patrick Ganne, the lawyer who represents Waters.
</P>
<P>
   In recommending the stiffest possible sentence for Waters,
federal prosecutors dug deep into his criminal past, which goes
back 36 years and includes various violent crimes, including
murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes into consideration everything Mr. Waters has ever
done, from not helping old ladies across the street to every dog he
has kicked,'' Ganne told the judge.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Gerald Carruth, however, told Sparks
that it was appropriate to weigh everything in Waters' past in
sentencing him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had every opportunity to rehabilitate himself and has
failed to do so for 36 years,'' Carruth said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe that he can ever return to society again,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The weapon charges that landed Waters in court stemmed from a
March 24 raid on his Austin apartment in which the FBI found 119
rounds of ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   As a felon, Waters is prohibited from possessing guns or
ammunition. On May 27, he pleaded guilty to possessing the
ammunition and to shipping firearms from Texas to Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Carruth declined to respond to questions about Waters'
role in the O'Hair case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contrary to what Mr. Ganne said, I have no agenda,'' he said.
``Let me assure you, the investigation into the O'Hair
disappearance will continue until those responsible are brought to
justice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
