<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CODE-BREAKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WARTIME CODE-BREAKER: PROTOTYPE FOR TODAY'S COMPUTER HACKER 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Toward the end of Neal Stephenson's recently published novel,
``Cryptonomicon'' (Avon), two plot strands converge on attempts to
crack a particularly knotty Japanese code from World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the war a brilliant mathematician uses a
collection of abacuses and a primitive, heat-producing, vacuum-tube
computer to untangle a code that had stymied the Allies' best
minds.
</P>
<P>
   Then, 50 years later, the mathematician's grandson sits in a
Philippine prison with his laptop computer, attempting to crack
that same Japanese code, whose secrets have been lost. Yet he must
keep all results hidden from his captors' eyes; so the decoding
itself must be encoded.
</P>
<P>
   This 918-page novel has become something of a phenomenon in the
tech world (with over 100,000 copies in print), partly because of
the way it weaves back and forth between these hackers of two eras.
</P>
<P>
   It toys with the most advanced contemporary ideas while also
managing to ground them in the distant technological past,
suggesting that what we tend to think of as revolutionary _ the
Internet, electronic commerce, data encryption _ is actually
evolutionary. The origins of writing code (programming) lie in
historical efforts to break code (cryptography).
</P>
<P>
   This may be one reason why the codes of World War II have
provoked such interest in our obsessively high-tech age. In one
recent book, ``Between Silk and Cyanide'' (Free Press), Leo Marks,
a British cryptographer, later turned screenwriter, recalls basing
wartime ciphers on poems; encryptions would be written on silk
scarves, easily hidden and easily destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   In another book, ``Code Breaking: A History and Exploration''
(Overlook), a German mathematician, Rudolf Kippenhahn, gives a
breezy survey of codes, ranging from the betrayal of Mary, Queen of
Scots, in a deciphered letter, to the nature of credit card
security. The heart of the book, however, focuses on breaking the
notorious German code, Enigma, which was punched out on portable
typing machines equipped with four spinning wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Wartime code-breaking has taken on a mythic importance not just
because so much was at stake, but because it relied on a new way of
looking at the world that is only now coming to maturity: the world
is an agglomeration of information, much of it seemingly chaotic,
some of it hidden, all of it requiring interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   A technical field known as ``information theory'' began to
thrive just after the war. The notion of code was central, for a
code is an apparently meaningless stream of signals that contain a
hidden order. Breaking a code involves stripping away the ``noise''
to find the sense.
</P>
<P>
   In the decades before the war, theoretical mathematicians had
come to think about their own field in this way: when we are
presented with a series of statements, some of which are true, some
false, some provable, some not, how do we tell the difference? Is
there a procedure that might help separate, say, truth from
falsehood?
</P>
<P>
   In attempts to answer their theoretical questions,
mathematicians even created their own peculiar code, assigning
numbers to all mathematical signs, turning abstract statements
about truth or falsehood into numbers that could be more easily
explored.
</P>
<P>
   The mathematician Alan Turing (who plays a pivotal role in
Stephenson's novel), was involved in such speculations and _ not
coincidentally _ helped break the German Enigma code. He began to
consider the implications of all this for machines.
</P>
<P>
   After all, a machine creates a kind of material code, turning
one object into another according to a predetermined set of rules.
A machine that manipulates numbers _ a computer _ would literally
be a coding machine, transforming one bit of information into
another following strict procedures.
</P>
<P>
   The modern computer is a fantastically fast and subtle extension
of that idea. Everything is coded in number. Every movement of the
mouse, for example, is translated by the computer into a series of
numbers which are then manipulated and finally decoded, changing
the colors of pixels on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   A hacker is literally a cryptographer, the computer an elaborate
Enigma machine. And now that transactions involving the exchange of
objects and money are being replaced by the transmission of
computer-generated codes, billions of dollars are at stake in
making sure they are unbreakable.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these ideas bounce around in Stephenson's novel, which
is really an expansive portrait of the hacker mentality, then and
now. The hacker encodes and decodes experience with almost
compulsive energy.
</P>
<P>
   The water currents in a stream, the turning of a bicycle chain,
the pattern of street curbs in London, the churning of a bingo bin
_ there are patterns to decode in everything; everything is
connected. This creates a sense of Pynchonesque paranoia, in which
characters' concerns about secrecy regularly reach wartime
proportions.
</P>
<P>
   But it also inspires a kind of techno-mysticism that has become
familiar among the digerati: if everything is connected, a hacker
who could read the currents properly and reproduce them in digital
form might come to know the world's deepest encoded secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Stephenson's novel has an epigraph from Turing suggesting that a
physicist is a cryptographer who attempts to discern the laws of
the universe. That would be a hacker's fantasy as well: cracking
the ultimate code, created by the ultimate Enigma.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 1652EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4398 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS     08-20 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLAIM THAT WINDOWS 98 INSTALLATIONS WILL GO BELLY UP JAN. 1 IS A
HOAX 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I recently received a forwarded e-mail that supposedly proves
that all Windows 98 installations will fail to roll over to the
correct date on Jan. 1, 2000. It gives a series of steps to fix the
problem. I went through the steps and, sure enough, I found my
computer was set up as shown in the message. This reads like one of
those dumb hoaxes, but it seemed to be correct. I've attached a
copy for you. What gives?
</P>
<P>
   A: You're right, it is one of those silly hoax e-mails. But this
one plays on the limited knowledge most people have of how their
computer works.
</P>
<P>
   What the message purports to do is provide a Year 2000 bug fix,
but all it really does is change the way Windows 98 (and 95)
displays the date.
</P>
<P>
   By default, Windows' built-in calendar is set to display the
date as two digits _ the numbers 99 for 1999, for example. This, of
course, is how we got into this Y2K mess in the first place:
programmers using two instead of four digits to indicate a year.
</P>
<P>
   But in this case, it's purely cosmetic. Although the forwarded
e-mail says that this is how Windows passes information to other
programs, that's not true. A properly patched version of Windows 95
or 98 _ or the most recent full version, Windows 98 SE _ will pass
the year 2000 to applications properly, even if the calendar is set
to display it as just two digits.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the instructions given in the e-mail:
</P>
<P>
   Click on ``START''
</P>
<P>
   Click on ``SETTING''
</P>
<P>
   Click on ``CONTROL PANEL''
</P>
<P>
   Double click on ``REGIONAL SETTINGS'' icon
</P>
<P>
   Click on the ``DATE'' tab at the top of the page.
</P>
<P>
   Where it says, ``Short Date Sample,'' look and see if it shows a
``two digit'' year (yy). That is the default setting for Windows
95, Windows 98 and NT. This date RIGHT HERE is the date that feeds
application software and WILL NOT rollover in the year 2000. It
will roll over to 00. Click on the ``SHORT DATE STYLE'' pull down
menu and select the option that shows, mm/dd/yyyy. (Be sure your
selection has four Y's showing and not two.) Click on ``APPLY'' and
then click on ``OK'' at the bottom. Easy enough to fix. However,
every single installation of Windows worldwide is defaulted to fail
Y2K rollover. Please feel free to pass this on to your associates
and friends.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While setting this to be four digits is generally a good idea,
it's not critical. Your computer won't melt down Jan. 1 if you
don't.
</P>
<P>
   A good rule of thumb about Internet hoaxes is: If it says pass
it on, don't. A good Web site that tracks bogus online information
is Stiller Research Virus Hoax News at www.stiller.com/hoaxes.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've been amazed at the number of deals that offer free PCs
if you just agree to three years of Internet access with this or
that provider. Some of these look too good to be true. Are they?
</P>
<P>
   A: Depending on how you use a computer _ or, even more
importantly, how you might use a PC if you've never had one before
_ it could be a good deal. But there are definite pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the computers offered in these deals have minimal
specifications, such as only 32 megabytes of memory or underpowered
video cards. If all you plan to do is manage home finances, surf
the Internet or write some letters, they will be fine _ so long as
you don't try to do these at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   If you think your needs will be minimal, consider that most
people who buy a computer end up using it for things other than
what they initially intended.
</P>
<P>
   Also, realize that you will be locked into a three-year contract
with the Internet provider involved. That can be a long time if the
service is sub-par or the provider doesn't offer the kinds of
service you need.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
