<HEADLINE>
`UNIVERSAL SOLDIER:' THE RETURN OF THE HUNKY HUMANOID 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: production notes appear at end of review.) (DW) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who has succumbed to computer-borne paranoia in this year
of Y2K foreboding had better brace for another jolt to the ganglia
in the form of ``Universal Soldier: The Return.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the hyperkinetic action movie that posits the plot that
if it weren't for Jean-Claude Van Damme as a recycled corpse, the
world as undemanding movie fans know it would be at the mercy of a
megalomaniacal computer named Seth and a legion of pumped-up
zombies of a type known as a Unisol.
</P>
<P>
   That word, as Van Damme's followers are aware, stands for
Universal Soldier, which people _ if you can call it that _ a
government-financed experimental unit of resurrected Army dead,
whose heartening military motto is ``Dying to Serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Those familiar with ``Universal Soldier,'' the 1992 film that
introduced Van Damme as Luc Deveraux, an early model of one of
these hunky humanoids, accept that the typical Unisol, besides
having a chip in the head and a chip on the shoulder, tends to have
a screw loose as well.
</P>
<P>
   So for those eager to bid adieu to their credibility for 82
minutes and to promise not to wonder why none of the eight
gazillion bullets fired during the new film manage to hit Luc or
why he cannot be defeated in hand-to-hand combat by foes who are 2{
to 5 times stronger than he is, it should come as no surprise that
the Unisols run amok once again.
</P>
<P>
   This time they are under the control of Seth, a computer with
delusions of grandeur that manages to assume human form (Michael
Jai White) inside the Ryan-Lathrop Military Weapons Research
Facility, not far from Dallas, where the latest models of Chips are
being refined.
</P>
<P>
   Luc, restored to humanity these days, is a widower with a
teen-age daughter and is working with the military-industrial
complex on this project when that old devil Washington pulls the
budgetary plug on the entire shebang.
</P>
<P>
   Next thing you know, Seth is in a lethal snit, the Unisols are
battling the Army, Luc's daughter, Hillary (Karis Paige Bryant), is
in peril of either dying outright or becoming a zombie, and the
whole research facility, which also contains biological weapons,
could blow sky high.
</P>
<P>
   To complicate matters even more, all this begins on a day when
an ambitious television reporter named Erin (Heidi Schanz) is
paying a visit, which gives Luc a chance to protect a damsel from
harm, Erin a chance to save his life, and Luc and Erin an
opportunity to visit a topless bar and to exchange a couple of
steamless kisses while she gets the Big Story.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Universal Soldier: The Return,'' directed by Mic
Rodgers and written by William Malone and John Fasano, contains no
surprises, its action rarely flags. The hulking and comic Bill
Goldberg, familiar to those who follow World Championship
Wrestling, and Kiana Tom, the fitness guru of ESPN's ``Kiana's Flex
Appeal,'' compound the high level of physicality that characterizes
Van Damme's outings.
</P>
<P>
   All this, plus the fires, shattering glass, roaring explosions,
high body counts, trashed vehicles, head bashings and skull
surgery, leaves little time for the application of logic to
analysis of this foolishness.
</P>
<P>
   But one can surely carry away this lesson: If the world is ever
to be truly safe from Universal Soldiers, they, like Achilles, can
suffer a mortal wound in only one place. For them, it's the box
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Universal Soldier: The Return'' is rated R (under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). The film includes violence,
coarse language and partial nudity.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `UNIVERSAL SOLDIER: The Return'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Mic Ridgers; written by William Malone and John
Fasano, based on characters created by Richard Rothstein,
Christopher Leitch and Dean Devlin; director of photography,
Michael A. Benson; edited by Peck Prior; music by Don Davis;
production designer, David Chapman; produced by Craig Baumgarten,
Allen Shapiro and Jean-Claude Van Damme; released by Tri-Star
Pictures. Running time: 82 minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   With: Jean-Claude Van Damme (Luc), Michael Jai White (Seth),
Heidi Schanz (Erin), Xander Berkeley (Dylan Cotner), Justin Lazard
(Captain Blackburn), Kiana Tom (Maggie), Daniel Von Bargen (General
Radford), James Black (Sergeant Morrow), Karis Paige Bryant
(Hillary) and Bill Goldberg (Romeo).
</P>
</TEXT>
