<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4403 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-STRIKE-0821-CO     08-20 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-STRIKE-0821-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICO'S STUDENT STRIKE TOUCHED SENSITIVE NERVE, BUT IS LOSING
SUPPORT
 &HT;    1000&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ It's a scene that's repeated with more frequency
each passing day.
</P>
<P>
   Striking students from Mexico's National Autonomous University
hold their ground at campus gates, four months into a strike that's
paralyzed one of the world's largest university systems.
</P>
<P>
   Students furious that the strike has dragged on so long march
angrily past, prompting shouting matches that television cameras
eagerly lap up.
</P>
<P>
   And there's no end in sight.
</P>
<P>
   This week should have marked the beginning of fall semester for
Mexico City's sprawling, virtually free public university system,
known here as the UNAM. Normally, this university is home to
270,000 students enrolled in courses for degrees in everything from
literature and law to computer sciences and medicine.
</P>
<P>
   But thousands of students walked out last April 20 in protest
against a proposal by the university's rector that would have --
for the first time in 50 years -- increased tuition from a few
cents to about $75 per semester.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fear that if this happens all education, including primary,
will end up private in Mexico. How can you do that in a Third World
country?'' said Eric Gonzalez, a striking 23-year-old engineering
student whose father is a farmworker in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   At first the student movement seemed to have captured the moral
high ground, especially in a country where many fear Mexico is
going too far with free-market economic reforms that have cut back
on government spending and subsidies. The announcement of a
dramatic tuition hike was seen as another attack on Mexico's
working classes, whose best opportunity for higher education is at
the UNAM.
</P>
<P>
   But by mid-summer UNAM Rector Francisco Barnes had retreated,
declaring that the tuition hike would be voluntary and meant only
for students whose families could afford the increase. Suspicious
strikers said they didn't believe him -- and they shot back with a
range of other demands.
</P>
<P>
   Because the rector relented, the protracted strike is starting
to alarm the public and counter-demonstrations are growing
stronger. Recently, a star-studded group of liberal Mexican writers
published an open letter urging the adoption of a professors'
proposal for a suspension of the fee increases, a return to classes
and a series of assemblies where students and administrators could
negotiate their differences.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Fuentes, Mexico's best-known novelist, was one of the
signatories. Another was Elena Poniatowska, a novelist who wrote a
famous investigative book detailing the bloody massacre of hundreds
of Mexican students striking for free speech and political freedom
on the eve of the Olympic Games here in October 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Poniatowska has immense moral clout in Mexico because she dared
to publish one of the first chronicles of the massacre, which
shredded the credibility of Mexico's government at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Poniatowska's position against the continuation of the 1999
strike highlighted the erosion of support for the students, who
have themselves broken into factions known as ``ultras,'' the more
radical students, and ``moderates,'' those who are inclined to
negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you know, I am, in general, on the side of our youth,''
Poniatowska said. ``There should be space for the students to
express their concerns at the university.''
</P>
<P>
   However, she said, the students have already lost too much class
time. Now it appears the entire fall semester is in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Poniatowska also said she disagreed with the students' demands
for automatic UNAM admission for any any student who attends one of
a chain of high schools affiliated with the university.
</P>
<P>
   ``Universities need money,'' she said. But she suggested that
the UNAM should perhaps try other ways to increase funding rather
than asking the students to pay more. The fee increases would only
represent a fraction of the university's $994 million annual
budget.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping vigil at one of the entrances to the UNAM, striking
student Arcelia Sanchez, 22, said she was disappointed in the
writers' position.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just want a quick way out,'' she said. ``The problem is
we (the striking students) don't trust anyone anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez and others still devoted to the strike said their
parents support them, but fear for their safety -- especially
because of what happened to students in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would be more people out here with us, but because of
the ghost of '68 they won't come,'' said Eric Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez said the students feel they've been the victims of
unsympathetic television coverage, which has focused of late on
strikers blocking -- and sometimes fighting with -- students trying
to enroll for the UNAM's fall semester at alternative sites around
the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever is on that little box people believe,'' he said
bitterly.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of striking students have occupied classrooms and are
sleeping in them to maintain a 24-hour presence.
</P>
<P>
   Campus workers come and go freely and sensitive research in the
sciences and other disciplines continues. The UNAM is autonomous,
as its name implies, so ordinary police are not allowed on the
campus and conflicts are supposed to be settled within the academic
community.
</P>
<P>
   Earnest messages about the students' struggle are posted on
school buildings, along with traditional red-and-black strike
flags.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lose a few days to win over a lifetime,'' said a sign posted
on the School of Architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Corea, a 23-year-old literature student, said he supported
the strike at first because the rector simply imposed the fee hikes
with no prior consultation with students or teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Corea can't afford to pay much more -- his mother is a
housekeeper -- and he says he has friends who can barely afford bus
money every day to get to the campus.
</P>
<P>
   But he also believes students from wealthy families who drive
nice cars to the campus can afford the increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, the strikers themselves are divided now,'' he said.
``They're not unified, so it's hard to see where this is going.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows).
</P>
<P>
   Emma Garcia, a 21-year-old dentistry student, is also
disillusioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are fellow students who can't afford to pay
more,'' she said. ``But I've seen too many people who want to just
pay a few cents for tuition. And how much does a box of cigarettes
cost or a pack of gum?''
</P>
<P>
   But Sanchez said she fears that fee increases for tuition, the
use of libraries, laboratories and other services will continue to
climb if students don't take a stand now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is not whether there are rich students or poor
students attending the university right now,'' she said. ``The
question is whether the university will remain accessible to the
working classes. That's been the essence of this university.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
