<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLAIM THAT WINDOWS 98 INSTALLATIONS WILL GO BELLY UP JAN. 1 IS A
HOAX 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I recently received a forwarded e-mail that supposedly proves
that all Windows 98 installations will fail to roll over to the
correct date on Jan. 1, 2000. It gives a series of steps to fix the
problem. I went through the steps and, sure enough, I found my
computer was set up as shown in the message. This reads like one of
those dumb hoaxes, but it seemed to be correct. I've attached a
copy for you. What gives?
</P>
<P>
   A: You're right, it is one of those silly hoax e-mails. But this
one plays on the limited knowledge most people have of how their
computer works.
</P>
<P>
   What the message purports to do is provide a Year 2000 bug fix,
but all it really does is change the way Windows 98 (and 95)
displays the date.
</P>
<P>
   By default, Windows' built-in calendar is set to display the
date as two digits _ the numbers 99 for 1999, for example. This, of
course, is how we got into this Y2K mess in the first place:
programmers using two instead of four digits to indicate a year.
</P>
<P>
   But in this case, it's purely cosmetic. Although the forwarded
e-mail says that this is how Windows passes information to other
programs, that's not true. A properly patched version of Windows 95
or 98 _ or the most recent full version, Windows 98 SE _ will pass
the year 2000 to applications properly, even if the calendar is set
to display it as just two digits.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the instructions given in the e-mail:
</P>
<P>
   Click on ``START''
</P>
<P>
   Click on ``SETTING''
</P>
<P>
   Click on ``CONTROL PANEL''
</P>
<P>
   Double click on ``REGIONAL SETTINGS'' icon
</P>
<P>
   Click on the ``DATE'' tab at the top of the page.
</P>
<P>
   Where it says, ``Short Date Sample,'' look and see if it shows a
``two digit'' year (yy). That is the default setting for Windows
95, Windows 98 and NT. This date RIGHT HERE is the date that feeds
application software and WILL NOT rollover in the year 2000. It
will roll over to 00. Click on the ``SHORT DATE STYLE'' pull down
menu and select the option that shows, mm/dd/yyyy. (Be sure your
selection has four Y's showing and not two.) Click on ``APPLY'' and
then click on ``OK'' at the bottom. Easy enough to fix. However,
every single installation of Windows worldwide is defaulted to fail
Y2K rollover. Please feel free to pass this on to your associates
and friends.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While setting this to be four digits is generally a good idea,
it's not critical. Your computer won't melt down Jan. 1 if you
don't.
</P>
<P>
   A good rule of thumb about Internet hoaxes is: If it says pass
it on, don't. A good Web site that tracks bogus online information
is Stiller Research Virus Hoax News at www.stiller.com/hoaxes.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've been amazed at the number of deals that offer free PCs
if you just agree to three years of Internet access with this or
that provider. Some of these look too good to be true. Are they?
</P>
<P>
   A: Depending on how you use a computer _ or, even more
importantly, how you might use a PC if you've never had one before
_ it could be a good deal. But there are definite pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the computers offered in these deals have minimal
specifications, such as only 32 megabytes of memory or underpowered
video cards. If all you plan to do is manage home finances, surf
the Internet or write some letters, they will be fine _ so long as
you don't try to do these at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   If you think your needs will be minimal, consider that most
people who buy a computer end up using it for things other than
what they initially intended.
</P>
<P>
   Also, realize that you will be locked into a three-year contract
with the Internet provider involved. That can be a long time if the
service is sub-par or the provider doesn't offer the kinds of
service you need.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
