<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE WEBCAMS, 3 DIFFERENT PICTURES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the moment the graphical Web browser first illuminated the
previously darkened, text-only Internet, there have been cameras
online to capture magical moments.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so maybe most webcams aren't aimed at magical things. The
earliest cams were pointed at fish tanks, ferret cages, the inside
of refrigerators and even the ghosts presumed to live under one
woman's bed.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there are thousands of webcams, but the content hasn't
improved much. The pictures of fish, ferrets, moldy leftovers and
under-bed dust bunnies are just a bit clearer, and they're cheaper
to capture.
</P>
<P>
   Webcams have become incredibly inexpensive and are much easier
to set up and use, though the image quality they offer varies
dramatically. Here's a look at three low-priced cameras that plug
into a PC using a Universal Serial Bus port. Maybe you have
something goofy you can share with the world!
</P>
<P>
   _ Video Blaster WebCam 3, $79, Creative Labs: Of the three
webcams here, this new model from Creative Labs has the most
intriguing features. Unfortunately, it falls behind in the one
feature that counts the most: image quality.
</P>
<P>
   The WebCam 3 has one of the best physical designs of this group.
It has a jointed body _ one half has the lens, the other a solid
base with four legs. This is the most physically stable of the cams
I tried. The other two were more wobbly and difficult to aim
precisely.
</P>
<P>
   It comes with software called WebCam Monitor that lets you turn
the camera into a security device. It uses a motion-detecting
system to tell when someone has entered an area, then snaps a photo
of them. That image can be stored on a hard drive, or even sent to
an FTP or Web site. If you've got a sneaking suspicion that
someone's using your PC at work when you're not there, or that the
kids are scarfing one too many Oreos after school, this is a clever
way to catch the culprits.
</P>
<P>
   The WebCam 3 also comes with a program that lets you quickly
build a Web site around the camera's images, using a series of
templates and clip art.
</P>
<P>
   The camera can handle 16.8 million colors, with a maximum
resolution of 640-by-480 pixels. It was most efficient at capturing
video at the 320-by-240 resolution. On a 500-megahertz Pentium III
system, it slowed down dramatically at 640-by-480.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the WebCam also had the poorest image display of
any of the cameras I tried. It was difficult to focus, and colors
seemed washed out. Regardless of how much fiddling and tweaking I
did, I never could get a satisfying picture.
</P>
<P>
   Creative Labs has a gallery of Web sites that use the product,
and I can tell from looking at them that the problem wasn't
confined to my unit.
</P>
<P>
   _ HomeConnect PC Digital Camera, $159, 3Com: This is the most
expensive of the webcams I tried, but it also is one of the most
well-equipped. While its image quality is better than the Creative
Labs model, it's not the best of the three. However, if you need a
webcam in low-light situations, this is the one to get.
</P>
<P>
   The HomeConnect model comes with plenty of software, including
one that lets you instantly create picture postcards and send them
via e-mail. A launch bar lets you pick from various
image-management programs, including PictureWork Live.
</P>
<P>
   It also has the nicest software for uploading images _ either
still or video _ to a Web site in Webcam32, which is a Windows
application that allows video camera images to be displayed within
a Web page. In fact, Webcam32 can be used with all of the cameras
reviewed here, and you can get a trial copy of the latest version,
5.0.8, at www.kolban.com/webcam32.
</P>
<P>
   The HomeConnect camera can display images up to 1,280-by-960
resolution in software-enhanced mode, though in hardware it is
limited to 640-by-480. It can display 16.8 million colors and, like
the Creative Labs camera, has a comfortable frame rate at
320-by-240 resolution.
</P>
<P>
   This camera's best feature is its handling of low-light
situations. In a relatively dark room, the HomeConnect model was
great at compensating and making it look as though the scene was
well-lighted. However, the image always seemed a bit grainy to me,
even in normal light, and I had to fiddle with the settings to get
the colors right.
</P>
<P>
   _ PC Camera Pack, $79, Intel Corp.: This webcam has the best
image quality by far. It also will take advantage of the
multimedia-enhancing code found in Pentium III-based PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the software included here was created by Intel, and
isn't quite as nice as the offerings in the other packages. For
example, I found the e-mail postcard program here not as easy to
use as the one that comes with the 3Com camera. On the other hand,
the camera does come with Intel's Video Phone program, which I like
much better than NetMeeting, the videophone software that comes
with the other two cameras.
</P>
<P>
   The package comes with an additional CD that includes the Video
Phone program in a mailer. This lets you send it to a friend, who
can receive your video call, even if he or she does not have a
camera.
</P>
<P>
   There are even some games included in which your image on the
video interacts with a variety of cartoon objects, such as a
basketball. Put out your hand and the basketball bounces off of it.
It's an interesting diversion.
</P>
<P>
   The Intel camera can handle 16.8 million colors and resolutions
up to 640-by-480, and on a Pentium III system, video at that size
is quite smooth. If you install the camera on a Pentium II or older
system, you're better off backing the resolution down to
320-by-240.
</P>
<P>
   This camera had an incredibly clear, sharp image, and displayed
very realistic colors with almost no tweaking necessary. It did
not, however, handle low light as well as the 3Com camera. But of
the three, this one was my solid favorite.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
