<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4434 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-WALKMAN21-COX     08-20 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKMAN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sony Walkman turns twenty
 &HT;    By Don McLeese
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Though he was co-founder of Sony _ soon to be
chairman and CEO _ Akio Morita wasn't even sure he could sell the
concept to his own company. Music had long been a social activity,
a source of sharing, a force for bringing people together. And here
was Morita, proposing a device that would isolate each listener
from the rest of the world, sealed within a solo sonic universe by
the lightest-weight headphones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed as though nobody liked the idea,'' Morita recounts
in his autobiography, ``Made in Japan.'' ``Nobody laughed at me,
but I didn't seem to be convincing my own project team, though they
reluctantly went along. ... I don't think that any amount of market
research could have told us that the Sony Walkman would be
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years and worldwide sales of almost 200 million units
later, the Walkman has triumphed beyond Morita's wildest
projections, establishing itself as a vital organ, or at least a
crucial appendage, for the modern listener. It's an invention that
plainly scratched an itch where no itch previously existed, one
that not merely fulfilled a desire, but instilled a demand. The
initial concern at Sony was ``Why would anybody buy a Walkman?''
The answer came soon enough, in the form of another question, ``How
could anyone live without one?''
</P>
<P>
   With this summer commemorating the 20th anniversary of the
product's launch, portable technology has since spun more than 600
different models under the Walkman banner, from CD Discmans to TV
Watchmans, from budget versions (under $20) to rugged Sports models
to the new Psyc line, designed to create a fashion demand among
teens, with sherbet shades of plasticity reminiscent of iMac. Not
to mention the thousands of knockoffs by hundreds of competitors,
in a category generically dubbed ``personal portable stereo,'' as
Sony zealously protects the Walkman trademark.
</P>
<P>
   It's ironic, then, that ``Walkman'' as a name was the source of
Morita's own reservations, that he had would have preferred, as he
explains, ``something like Walking Stereo.'' The tag that stuck
couldn't have passed the muster of political correctness in another
decade or so, when ``Walkperson'' or ``Walkwoman'' would have been
demanded. And its plural still makes grammarians cringe, though
``Walkmen'' never became standard usage. In the beginning, it was
the concept that was marketed internationally, not the name, as the
product was introduced in Japan as the Walkman, (and briefly) was
sold as Stowaway in Britain, Freestyle in Australia, Soundabout in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The second irony of the product launch is that Sony hedged its
earliest bets on sonic solitaire, giving the device two headphone
jacks. The two jacks allowed the music to still be a shared
experience, or at least a shared sound source, for two listeners
separated by a headphone barrier. If they wanted to talk, there was
even a mini-microphone on the early model that would allow
conversation to cut into the music.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one could imagine people listening to music in solitude,''
Robert R. Nell, Sony's vice president of personal audio, later
reminisced to a reporter, though solitude proved to be precisely
the Walkman's appeal. Wearing a Walkman, you didn't need to talk
with anyone else, or even acknowledge anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   In a crowded subway, on a busy jogging trail _ is it any
accident that the Walkman and running crazes flourished together? _
on the beach or at the office, you could turn on, tune out,
relegate the rest of the world to oblivion, establish a shell of
sound where any intrusion was a violation of your personal space.
(The second headphone jack and the microphone were quickly
discontinued.)
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the ironies, though the Walkman was initially
designed as an instrument of politeness _ allowing Morita and other
corporate jet-setters to enjoy music while traveling without
disturbing others _ its self-centeredness ultimately helped define
the era of its popular boom, the so-called ``Me Decade'' of the
'80s. In wearing a Walkman, the listener asserted that whatever the
outside world might have to offer, from surprise to serendipity,
was of less interest than the pre-programmed, self-controlled
experience of headphone life. Sonically, you were the master of
your domain, creator of the soundtrack to the movie of your
existence.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, at least an earlier generation's infatuation with
the transistor radio (celebrated in 1961's ``Transistor Sister'' by
the immortal Freddy ``Boom Boom'' Cannon) left one ear open, while
offering the possibility of discovery, the chance you could be
overwhelmed by a new song on the Top 40 that would change your
life. Where rock 'n' roll from the start had provided the
soundtrack to teen-age mobility _ that is, freedom _ the adventure
of cruising to Chuck Berry's ``No Particular Place to Go'' or the
Beach Boys' ``I Get Around'' was that you really didn't know where
you were going, or what you might find there.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its implications for society at large, the introduction
of the Walkman helped revolutionize the music industry. Within four
years, cassettes eclipsed the long-indomitable vinyl of LPs and 45s
as America's most popular medium for recorded music (with CDs soon
to supplant cassettes). Where Japanese production previously had
been derided as cut-rate and inferior, the Walkman helped Japan
elevate its reputation as both a technological pacesetter and an
economic powerhouse. When the globalization of the '90s devoured
the American music industry, Sony acquired the recording division
of CBS _ Columbia, Epic and associated labels _ with a roster
extending from Bob Dylan to Barbra Streisand to Michael Jackson to
Bruce Springsteen. Before Walkman, ``made in Japan'' was a
merchandising epithet; in Walkman's wake, Sony owned ``Born in the
U.S.A.''
</P>
<P>
   So public, and yet so private, the Walkman was the first step in
transforming each individual into a mobile communications and
multimedia unit. We talk by cell phone rather than face to face. We
message by e-mail rather than voice. We see movies in the solitude
of home video rather than within the community of a theater. And we
listen to music on headphones. We are plugged in, we are wired and
we are each so very much alone.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
