<HEADER>
A4452 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-CHARITY-$ADV22-NY     08-20 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-CHARITY-$ADV22-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAIRING A TAX BREAK AND WEB GIVING 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Aug. 22) 
(jt) 
 By REED ABELSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some highly popular new Web sites have built impressive
followings on a simple premise: If you stop at them before shopping
on the Internet, some portion of what you spend will go to charity.
</P>
<P>
   As well intended as the pitch sounds, operators of the sites
have conceded that consumers were probably not eligible for tax
deductions on the money being diverted to the charitable groups.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the most popular of these sites, iGive.com, now says
shoppers at its site may be able to take that deduction after all.
The company sent e-mail to its shoppers last week to alert them to
the development.
</P>
<P>
   The company has petitioned the Internal Revenue Service for a
private letter ruling that would confirm the propriety of its
approach, but in the meantime it has received the approval of its
tax lawyers at Hogan &AMP; Hartson in Washington. A private letter
ruling, which could take as long as two years to secure, would give
the company confidence that its shoppers' tax deductions would not
be challenged, but it would not protect its competitors' patrons.
</P>
<P>
   The question of tax deductibility may be technical and, for some
consumers, may involve such small sums that they will not bother
with the paperwork. But given the rapid growth of these Web sites,
the nickels and dimes can add up. For example, iGive, said its
68,000 members have raised $307,000 for charity in the nearly two
years since the site's founding. And tax deductibility may broaden
its appeal. Already, one competitor, Greatergood.com, has said that
it, too, is looking at ways to offer a tax deduction.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, most of these shop-for-a-cause Web sites make their
money from the commissions they collect from retailers in exchange
for sending traffic their way. Shoppers then have the opportunity
to name a charity, which typically receives a cut of that fee, but
not always.
</P>
<P>
   The new approach at iGive.com is to give shoppers the option of
keeping that cut for themselves, in the form of a rebate, or having
it forwarded to the charity of their choice. Because the shopper
can demand the cash, routing the money to a charity would be more
likely to qualify as a tax-deductible gift for the shopper.
</P>
<P>
   ``This money looks like any other money you give to your worthy
cause,'' said the company's founder, Robert Grosshandler. He
pointed to the letter from his tax lawyers saying the IRS has once
before permitted such an arrangement, by a credit card company that
wanted to let customers divert part of their charge volume to
charity.
</P>
<P>
   Even if iGive prevails with tax authorities, consumers may find
it hard to count on the deduction. For starters, iGive allows
consumers leeway to name just about any cause under the sun, and
its devotees do. One beneficiary, for instance, is the Broken Nose
Fund, a Portland, Maine, cause that was not registered as a charity
with regulators when it was started by a man who wanted to raise
money for his third nose job.
</P>
<P>
   As long as no one was taking a tax deduction, it hardly mattered
if some causes were not bona fide charities under section 501(c)(3)
of the Internal Revenue Code. But if consumers are claiming
deductions based on their shopping habits on iGive, tax experts say
they had better be sure to count only charities that qualify.
</P>
<P>
   Grosshandler, who says he is a big believer in personal
responsibility, quarrels with the idea that his customers need a
lot of hand-holding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not in the business of vetting organizations for tax
deductibility,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential hitch to claiming the tax deduction would be
if the cause never gets the money. Although shoppers at iGive have
so far identified 5,300 causes to receive the $307,000 they have
generated in commissions, iGive has only sent $240,000 worth of
checks, to about 1,600 of these causes. In some cases, iGive cannot
locate a cause named by its shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, every cause must raise at least $10 through the Web
site before iGive issues a check. If shoppers do not spend much or
choose a cause that is obscure, the charity may fail to meet
iGive's minimum.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest question may simply be what happens if shoppers
start to flock to the site more for the rebate than to lend a hand
to charity. At least two other sites offering discounts, Ebates.com
and Esumer.com, have staked out the rebate turf. So, while the tax
strategy might work, it might also transform iGive from a
high-minded bankroller of charities to just another E-commerce
play.
</P>
<P>
   That might anger some retailers, who might not relish seeing
their goods discounted without any of the image-polishing they now
get by steering dollars to charity.
</P>
<P>
   Since iGive began offering the rebate last week, few people have
chosen to take the money rather than give it to charity, according
to Grosshandler. But he conceded that if people came to iGive not
to give, but to receive, the site would have to rethink its
mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everyone chooses to get a check, the business model will
not work,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
