<HEADER>
A4463 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-STAGE-AFFLICTION-LADN     08-20 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-AFFLICTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERUDITE PLAY ROOTED IN PAST, RELEVANT TO NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Describing Frank Dwyer's ``The Affliction of
Glory: A Comedy About Tragedy'' as a ``play of ideas'' is sort of
like describing the Harvard English department as a bunch of wise
guys.
</P>
<P>
   This engagingly eggheaded, if sometimes slow-moving, play about
(among many, many other things) the dumbing-down of popular culture
is a show with enough mental firepower to spark a dozen Ph.D.
dissertations.
</P>
<P>
   You practically can hear the author's mental synapses popping in
the background of the Getty Center's Harold M. Williams Auditorium,
where ``The Affliction of Glory'' opened a limited 15-performance
run Wednesday night. Dwyer is conceivably the only dramatist on
either side of the Atlantic who could make Tom Stoppard sound like
an ignoramus.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``The Affliction of Glory'' bears a more than passing
resemblance to Stoppard's own ``Arcadia,'' in which the mysteries
of the unquiet past create a literary sleuthing game for several
intrepid members of the confused present.
</P>
<P>
   The playwright, who also is a poet, director and literary
manager of the Mark Taper Forum, has attempted the Herculean task
of writing a play to mark an unusual collaboration among three of
L.A.'s premier cultural institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the Getty and the Huntington Library, Art
Collections and Botanical Gardens opened twin exhibitions of
paintings and drawings honoring Sarah Siddons, the regal,
porcelain-skinned British actress whose tragic performances were
said to make men cry and force women to be carried from London
theaters in hysterics. Co-commissioned by the Getty and the
Taper/Center Theatre Group, ``The Affliction of Glory'' adds
another dimension to the exploration of Siddons' formidable myth.
</P>
<P>
   Known in her heyday as ``the Muse of Tragedy,'' Siddons
(1755-1831) was cursed with the inability to play comedy
convincingly _ or, at least, to convince her idolatrous fans that
she should play it. (Think Meryl Streep in corsets and
uncomfortable shoes.)
</P>
<P>
   As Dwyer expresses it in the clever neo-Regency parlance he has
crafted for his talented and resourceful three-person cast (J.D.
Cullum, Nike Doukas, Patrick Egan), Siddons was ``betrayed by the
sublime.'' Like one of her venerable portraitists, the great Sir
Joshua Reynolds, she was an artist boxed in by the humdrum tastes
of Britain's burgeoning 18th-century middle classes, who couldn't
see that ``tragedies are concocted and irrelevant,'' whereas great
comedy is ``serious business.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're already scanning this page for footnotes, don't sweat
it. Though his script occasionally gets stalled in muddy fens of
allusion to 18th-century bowdlerizations of ``King Lear'' or the
neo-republican leanings of ``Paradise Lost,'' Dwyer for the most
part skillfully wrestles this abstract clay into compelling
flesh-and-blood portraits.
</P>
<P>
   His smartest conceit is making the play switch back and forth,
Pirandello style, from Siddons (Dukas), Reynolds (Cullum) and their
dynamic milieu to August 1999, when Bill (Cullum), a cerebral
actor-playwright, and Polly (Dukas), his scrappy co-star, muse and
significant other, are rehearsing a play about Sarah Siddons.
</P>
<P>
   For Bill and Polly, trying to make sense of Siddons' world and
her mystique triggers very modern questions not only about the
conflicting roles of wife, mother and actress that Siddons played,
but also about the difficulty of understanding her incredible
appeal. In some ways, ``The Affliction of Glory'' is about the
impossibility of truly knowing the past.
</P>
<P>
   Cullum and Dukas make Bill and Polly's brainy bickering quite
amusing, particularly in the Act 2 sequence when Polly recites one
of Siddons' legendary speeches, inserting squawks whenever the
flowery language (``Come, come, come, come, nay, come!'') seques
from sublime to ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   Both Cullum and Egan show remarkable versatility in a variety of
supporting roles, including Samuel Johnson, Lord Byron, William
Blake, a wandering German theater lover, a flamboyant Italian
painter and the wonderfully dotty English king (Egan) and queen
(Cullum), who address each other as Big Silly and Little Silly.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of ``Beyond the Fringe'' inspired looniness helps
deflate what might otherwise become an overwhelming sense of
self-importance. Corey Madden's direction, like John Iacovelli's
utilitarian set design, is sparsely effective. Candice Cain's
period costumes are without flaw.
</P>
<P>
   Dwyer and company have lifted Siddon's 2-D image off the wall
and set her before us in all her &UR;  &LR; 3-D complexity. Not a perfect
play, perhaps, but a glorious enterprise. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
What: ``The Affliction of Glory: A Comedy About Tragedy.'' &QL; 
Where: Harold M. Williams Auditorium, Getty Center, 1200 Getty
Center Drive, Brentwood. &QL; 
When: Through Sept. 5. Performances at 8 p.m. today, Saturday,
Thursday, Aug. 27, 28, Sept. 2, 3, 4; 2:30 p.m. Saturday, Sunday,
Aug. 28, 29, Sept. 4, 5. &QL; 
Tickets: $28; students, seniors $22. Call (213) 628-2772 or visit
the Mark Taper Forum Web site, !bold!www.TaperAhmanson.com. Getty
parking reservations are acquired; a $5 parking fee is included
with ticket purchase. &QL; 
Our rating: 3 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 1718EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4469 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-20 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIOLENT INCIDENTS BRING FEAR TO WORK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every time Debbie Jester hears about another workplace shooting,
she gets a little more nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if a disgruntled customer or disgruntled employee comes
in?'' asked Jester, the receptionist for a manufacturing company in
Houston. ``I'm the first one they'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, there has never been any trouble with violence at the
company. But she said that trouble-free record doesn't keep her
from thinking about possible escape routes if she had to get out in
a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Jester isn't the only one who is nervous these days. Shootings
in post offices have made the phrase ``going postal'' part of the
nation's everyday vocabulary, even though many people who use it
forget its bloody origin. But the recent shooting at two
day-trading firms in Atlanta has put employees more on edge, made
workplace shootings more real.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed to unnerve folks that an unhappy client _ not a
disgruntled employee or an upset spouse _ would come in and
randomly shoot people minding their own business.
</P>
<P>
   The fear almost sounds paranoid, Jester said, but she said it's
real. And it's something she and her co-workers talk about
frequently.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
EMPLOYEES WORRIED, SILENT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though employees like Jester are worried, they don't appear to
be passing along their concerns to their bosses.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't hit the radar screen yet and that's a bit surprising,
said Ruth Seiler, who hasn't heard a peep from her 30 client
companies. Seiler owns Staff Managers, which runs the human
resource operations for 30 companies in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   She expected to hear the same kind of concern with the recent
outbreak of workplace violence that she did last summer after the
U.S. Supreme Court issued two rulings encouraging employers to
conduct sexual harassment training.
</P>
<P>
   Though shootings like the one in Atlanta are few and isolated,
workplace violence is real and growing. From 1992 to 1996, there
was an annual average of 2 million violent incidents at work, twice
the average of a decade ago, according to a 1998 report by the U.S.
Justice Department. Of the 2 million incidents, 1,000 were
homicides and 50,500 were rapes and sexual assaults. The rest were
assaults and robberies.
</P>
<P>
   Workplace violence is a big issue to employees, but too many
times employers have not done enough to prevent it, said Lynne
McClure, president of McClure Associates in Phoenix, which
specializes in managing high risk behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Companies figure that it can't happen to them or that they
already have policies in place to deal with violence, McClure said.
But she said that when she has interviewed employees after a
workplace homicide, they're not surprised. It's the managers who
are surprised.
</P>
<P>
   Co-workers recognize the warning signs of problem employees,
such as frequent temper tantrums, a fixation on someone or
something or a tendency to blame others for their own problems, she
said. They worry because they never know what the employee may do.
And the longer an employer ignores the erratic, wild behavior, the
more it can fester, said McClure, author of ``Risky Business:
Managing Employee Violence in the Workplace.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CLOSE TO THE EXIT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The recent workplace shootings haven't escaped Larry Williams'
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, director of human resources for the Marek family of
companies, a Houston construction group, said that though he didn't
have much reason to worry, after terminating someone recently he
ducked out of his office and stayed close to an exit door _ just in
case.
</P>
<P>
   He has also changed his style of terminating an employee. Three
to five years ago, he used to explain exactly why someone was
getting the ax. If he was found stealing, he'd tell him that. Now,
he explains that things ``didn't really work out'' and suggests the
employee resign.
</P>
<P>
   Williams also sees a newly raised level of nervousness among his
managers. He suggested to one manager that he make sure that all
the money the employee had coming _ final paycheck, vacation pay,
severance _ was given to him at the time he was fired. That way,
the soon-to-be ex-employee has no reason to return.
</P>
<P>
   What if he was worried about a volatile ex-employee? It's a
tricky situation. Williams said he can't very well alert the
remaining employees because that would scare them unnecessarily.
And if the ex-employee found out, the notification might incite
him.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, Williams said, he could just set up a secret security
system where, at the sign of trouble, he could just buzz the
biggest guy at the office.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 1721EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
