<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-SMITH21-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   BUSH OFF THE HOOK IN ROBISON CASE
</P>
<P>
   (for commentary pages)
</P>
<P>
   By Susan E. Smith
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Larry Keith Robison, a paranoid schizophrenic, came
within hours of being executed this week. A stay from the Texas
Court of Criminal Appeals saved him from becoming the 99th
death-row inmate executed on Gov. George W. Bush's watch.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court ordered a hearing to determine Robison's
mental competency to be executed. But based on the outcome, he
could still be executed.
</P>
<P>
   The case, which illustrates the many problems with the death
penalty, has placed Bush's compassionate conservatism on the firing
line once again.
</P>
<P>
   The court's action let Bush, who had been asked to grant a
30-day stay of execution for Robison, off the hook during an
election season when such a decision could spell political disaster
with voters who support the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   But the Talk magazine article in which he reportedly mocked the
clemency appeals of Karla Faye Tucker exposes the shallow depths of
his compassion.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's execution of the born-again Christian brought
national and international scrutiny to Texas' death penalty.
Robison's story brings an even worse kind of scrutiny to state
practices. Texas leads the nation in executions, yet ranks 48th
among states in services for the mentally ill, a disparity that
cries out for compassionate intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Capital punishment is especially barbaric when applied to
individuals, like Larry Keith Robison, whose crimes, although
extraordinarily serious and extreme, were the products of profound
and untreated mental illness,'' William B. Moffitt, president of
the National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers, wrote Bush
prior to the court stay.
</P>
<P>
   Robison, whose schizophrenia causes violent outbursts, fell
through Texas' tattered mental health safety net before he killed
five people in 1982. Doctors would not permanently hospitalize
Robison because he had not committed violent acts, says his mother.
</P>
<P>
   As of Wednesday, Texas has executed 185 people since the death
penalty was upheld by the Supreme Court in 1976. Of the 99 cases on
Bush's watch, one person has been granted clemency.
</P>
<P>
   The court stay lets Bush off the hook in the Robison case, for
now. But he shouldn't be able to wiggle off the hook for his
unflinching support of the death penalty, which desperately needs a
touch of compassion for those, like Robison, who deserve it.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is an American-Statesman editorial writer. You may contact
her at susans(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
