<HEADER>
A4471 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-     08-20 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLKSWAGEN, THE REAL INVENTOR OF THE MINIVAN, STILL SELLS ONE
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by CARS-GLANCE) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I haven't been able to help myself. I laugh every time I've see
marketing literature from Chrysler Corp. (now DaimlerChrysler)
claiming that the company ``invented'' the minivan.
</P>
<P>
   Baloney.
</P>
<P>
   Baby-boomers know that the minivan was invented by Volkswagen,
whose Microbus debuted in the 1950s and was at its cutest during
the '60s, when it began serving as the semiofficial mode of
transportation for the hippie movement.
</P>
<P>
   I was never a hippie, but I've owned my share of VW buses,
beginning with a beat-up 1960 model I had while I was in college.
The body style changed a bit in the 70s, making the Microbus
slightly larger, and the engine also changed, giving the vans more
power. I owned several of those.
</P>
<P>
   That body style gave way to the slightly larger, more
squared-off Vanagon model in 1980, and I even owned one of those.
One of the trademarks of the VW buses was its air-cooled
rear-mounted engine, but the last of the Vanagons, in the mid-80s,
came with rear-mounted, water-cooled engines.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler, can't even claim to have invented the American
minivan. In 1962, Chevrolet rolled out the Corvair Greenbrier, a
VW-like minivan based on the rear-engine Corvair compact cars that
were introduced two years earlier. Ford introduced a small
front-engine van called the Econoline.
</P>
<P>
   The Greenbrier came with a six-cylinder, air-cooled pancake
engine similar to the later four-cylinder pancake used in the VW
buses and Vanagon. It was a true minivan; it was two inches shorter
than the Corvair sedan, which was one of the smallest cars on the
market.
</P>
<P>
   I learned to drive on my parents' 1962 Greenbrier, which had a
two-speed automatic transmission with a small shift lever that
stuck out from the dashboard, just like on the Corvair cars. Later,
I owned a Greenbrier, which I used as a remote-broadcast van for an
AM radio station I owned in Middle Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Today, DaimlerChrysler owns the lion's share of the minivan
market, and yes, the company did re-invent the minivan and take it
mainstream. The company has sold more than 500,000 of them a year
for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   But most of you probably don't know that Volkswagen still sells
a minivan, although it's drastically different from the Microbus
and the Vanagon.
</P>
<P>
   It's called the EuroVan, and it's a much more refined vehicle
than its predecessors. Introduced to the U.S. market initially in
the early 1990s, the EuroVan was discontined, except for a camper
version after 1994. But for 1999, the vans have been re-introduced
as regular passenger vehicles, and they are nicer than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect anything like the original cutesy Microbus. The
anemic rear engines are gone. The EuroVan has a much more powerful,
front-mounted 2.8-liter V-6 engine similar to the one used in the
VW Passat and Jetta sedans.
</P>
<P>
   It's rated at 140 horsepower and 177 foot-pounds of torque, and
it delivers enough zip to allow the EuroVan to run with the best of
the minivans. (That wasn't the case with the Microbus, some of you
might recall; mountain grades were especially challenging to its
four-cylinder engines).
</P>
<P>
   Compared with the DaimlerChrysler minivans, the EuroVan is more
accurately described as a midivan. Its interior _ 190 cubic feet _
is larger than the average minivan, but less than that of a
full-size van.
</P>
<P>
   Creature comforts abound, which also is a departure from the
past. The Microbus was simple. The EuroVan has power windows and
door locks, air-conditioning that works, antilock brakes, cruise
control, programmable intermittent wipers with heated washer
nozzles, rear-hatch wiper and washer with defroster, power outside
mirrors and a smooth-shifting four-speed automatic transmission
(rather than the old four-on-the-floor manual). Automatic climate
control is available on uplevel models. There also is a leather
interior package available.
</P>
<P>
   Families will love riding in the Eurovan. Different seating
arrangements are available. The base GLS model comes with two
forward-facing bench seats in the rear. With the two buckets up
front, it seats up to seven people.
</P>
<P>
   The uplevel MV model comes with a rear bench seat, two captain's
chair-style seats in the middle, facing the rear seat, and a table
that can be raised between the seats so you can eat or play games
while you're traveling.
</P>
<P>
   With the engine moved to the front, the cargo area is huge _
perfect for carrying camping gear and sports equipment. For more
hauling space, you can remove the center and rear seats, and the
cargo area is wide and long enough to hold standard sheets of
plywood.
</P>
<P>
   A camper model also is available. Its wheelbase is 15.7 inches
longer than the standard EuroVan's 115 inches, and it comes with a
pop-up top, swiveling captain's chairs up front, a two-burner gas
stove, refrigerator, and other amenities. (It is built in
partnership with Winnebago, which designed it to be essentially a
small motorhome.)
</P>
<P>
   But if you want to use the shorter EuroVan as a camper, the MV
model is available with a ``weekender'' package that adds a pop-up
roof with two-person bed, window screens for the two sliding side
windows, refrigerator, swiveling captain's chairs and more.
</P>
<P>
   The EuroVan can tow a trailer of up to 4,400 pounds, although
that would slow it down considerably on mountain grades.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, at highway speeds, the EuroVan is quiet _ also a
departure from the past. With its high roof and wide stance,
seating is comfortable and everyone has ample leg, knee and
shoulder room. There is one large sliding door on the right side
for access to the rear seating area. The rear hatch flips up for
easy loading of the cargo area.
</P>
<P>
   The ride is smooth, but not cushy. Handling is much crisper than
you would imagine for a vehicle of this boxy shape and size.
</P>
<P>
   Prices are higher than for most of the DaimlerChrysler minivans.
So if you're looking for a cheap people hauler, the EuroVan isn't
it. That, too, is a departure from the past. The GLS model lists
for $29,900 (plus $565 transportation), and the MV model begins at
$31,400. Add $3,495 for the weekender package to turn the MV into a
minicamper.
</P>
<P>
   Options include a 12,000 btu gas furnace, a power glass sliding
sun roof ($1,000, not available with the weekender package because
of the pop-up roof), alloy wheels ($315), heated front seats ($400)
and various seating arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Our test vehicle, the MV model, came with the sun roof, alloy
wheels, heated seats and special ``hot chili'' red metallic paint
$275). Total price, including transportation, was $33,955.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel economy ratings are 15 miles per gallon in the city and
20 mpg on the highway. The tank holds 21.1 gallons of gasoline, and
unleaded regular is recommended.
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III is transportation writer and
automotive columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Contact him
at 3201 Airport Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford, TX 76022; telephone
(817) 685-3810; e-mail chambers(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
