r l BC-CARS-GLANCE-TEX     08-20 0200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-GLANCE-TEX </SLUG>
 
(EDS: Accompanies CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN) 
AT A GLANCE: 1999 Volkswagen EuroVan 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE PACKAGE: Seven-passenger, V-6 powered, front-engine,
front-wheel-drive minivan.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHLIGHTS: Volkswagen has re-introduced its modern minivan to
the U.S. market. This van first appeared in 1992, but disappeared
in all but camper form. It's bigger than the average minivan, and
has lots of amenities and much more power than the rear-engine VW
Microbuses or vans of the past. A perfect family hauler, especially
for vacations and camping trips; even camper versions are offered.
</P>
<P>
   NEGATIVES: Not the most stylish-looking van on the market; ride
is a bit rougher than the more carlike minivans of DaimlerChrysler
and other manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   MAJOR COMPETITORS: Chevrolet Astro/GMC Safari.
</P>
<P>
   EPA FUEL ECONOMY: 15 miles per gallon city, 20 highway. Base
price: $29,900 (GLS model), $31,400 (MV model), plus $565
transportation. Price as tested: $33,955, including transportation
(MV model).
</P>
<P>
   ON THE ROAD RATING: A.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
