<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4510 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-SURFER-CAMP-$ADV22-2T     08-20 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURFER-CAMP-$ADV22-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURFING, AND ITS 1ST FAMILY, RIDES WAVE OF CULTURAL COOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday Aug. 22)  
(mk) 
 By JULIA CHAPLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ONOFRE STATE BEACH, Calif. _ On a hazy August morning in the
parking lot at San Onofre State Beach, Jonathan Paskowitz paced
back and forth inside a rickety camper van, wearing flip-flops and
salty board shorts. A cell phone was wedged between his ear and his
suntanned shoulder as he fielded a barrage of calls from Tommy
Hilfiger, the rock star Perry Farrell, his model-girlfriend and,
most important, his auto mechanic. The day before, while driving
from this Southern California beach to a surf shop in nearby San
Clemente, Paskowitz's 1970 Dodge van broke down, and he had to
nurse it back here.
</P>
<P>
   Paskowitz, a second-generation surf vagabond, is known to
friends as ``the TV'' because he is always on, always making noise.
But several phone calls later, the cell battery was nearly dead and
he did what any born-and-reared surfer would: He grabbed his long
board and headed toward the waves.
</P>
<P>
   Paskowitz is one of nine adult siblings who, along with their
parents, own and operate the Paskowitz Surf Camp, which was founded
in 1972 by the family patriarch, Dorian ``Doc'' Paskowitz, a
surfing pioneer.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, as surfing has ridden to ever greater
heights of cultural cool, the camp has become a ``must'' stop for
well-heeled hipsters eager to hang 10, ride the soup and mellow
out. Students have included musicians like Sarah McLachlan, Chris
Isaak, Mark McGrath of Sugar Ray, the members of Hanson and
Farrell, instigator of the Lollapalooza tours.
</P>
<P>
   Other graduates, who share bologna sandwiches on the beach
before plunging into the gentle three-foot swells, have included
Sky Dayton, the 27-year-old founder of Earthlink, the Internet
service provider; Kinka Usher, a film director whose ``Mystery
Men'' is now in theaters, and Tom Sachs, a New York artist known
for needling the fashion world with works like a plunger and toilet
bowl covered with Prada logos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great sport for aging hipsters because it's low-impact
and there's a lot of hanging around on the beach,'' said Sachs,
whose latest project is a fleet of long boards with Chanel logos,
which can be ordered from the Mary Boone Gallery this fall.
Jonathan Paskowitz is his design collaborator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm deeply indebted to the Paskowitzes,'' Sachs said. ``I went
to therapy for 20 years of my life, and I don't think I'll ever
need to go back now that I learned to surf.''
</P>
<P>
   Keki Mingus, the daughter of the jazz bassist Charles Mingus,
came to the Paskowitz camp for a weekend several years ago and
ended up staying three months. ``Almost everyone in the
entertainment business in Los Angeles that's kind of cool surfs,''
said Ms. Mingus, who works as a stylist for rock bands. ``It's this
kind of `secret-society-bonding' thing.''
</P>
<P>
   At Ms. Mingus' wedding in May in Cabo San Lucas, Mexico, to
Stirling McIlwaine, the manager of Hanson, the Paskowitzes gave
surf lessons to guests. ``When I'm surfing, I completely forget
about things like who needs what clothes for the Oscars or the
Grammies,'' Ms. Mingus said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McLachlan, founder of the Lilith Fair tour, learned to surf
at the camp a few months ago and is so stoked she plans to return
with her dog after the tour ends this summer. (Her managers made
her agree that she wouldn't surf during the tour, to avoid
injuries.)
</P>
<P>
   The eight Paskowitz brothers and one sister were raised in a
12-foot camper by their Mexican-born mother, Juliette, and father,
a Stanford-trained doctor who gave up his practice to travel the
world with his brood in search of endless summer. ``We'd pull up to
a city like Manhattan in our tiny camper, and there'd be surfboards
piled up on the roof,'' Abraham Paskowitz recalled. ``Dad would
double-park, and then nine kids in surf clothes would pile out onto
the street like a bunch of gremlins.''
</P>
<P>
   The parents gave most of their home-schooled children Old
Testament names. Besides Abraham, 37, they are David, 40, who, when
he's not involved in the camp, is the lead singer of a funk band
named Goldfish; Jonathan, 37, a former long-board champion and a
founder of Black Flys Eyewear, which makes surf sunglasses; Israel,
known as Izzy, 36, a former world champion surfer who now oversees
the camp; Moses, 34, who transports actors in the movie industry;
Salvador, 31, a graphic designer for surf clothing companies; Adam,
29, the lead singer of the Flys, a band signed to the Trauma label;
Navah, 27, the sole daughter and a model, and Joshua, 24, formerly
of the Flys and now beginning a solo career as a singer.
</P>
<P>
   The family has a development deal with Artisan Pictures, the
independent film company that distributed ``The Blair Witch
Project,'' for a feature based on their lives, Jonathan Paskowitz
said.
</P>
<P>
   Like a rising and falling swell, surfing periodically goes in
and out of fashion, both at the beach and miles inland, where
youngsters raised in suburban sprawl or inner cities turn up at
school in baggy board shorts or surf-shop T-shirts. The latest wave
of surf style has been gaining momentum for more than a year.
Roxy/Quiksilver, the world's largest surf-wear company, increased
its sales by 64 percent, to $128 million, in the first quarter of
1999, compared with a year earlier. Old Navy, Tommy Hilfiger and
Gucci all offered brightly printed board shorts this spring and
summer. Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch sold T-shirts inspired by vintage surf
contests, while the company's in-store magazine included a history
and guide to surfing naked.
</P>
<P>
   The Surf Industry Manufacturers Association, a trade group, says
the number of active surfers rose to 1.75 million last year, from
1.1 million in 1992. In the Playa del Rey, Calif., office of
TBWA/Chiat/Day, the advertising agency, meetings with executives
from companies like Levi's take place around a conference table
made of surfboards.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Manhattan, Roxy/Quiksilver opened a SoHo store
last year with two red surfboards outside to set it apart from all
the makeup stores. And Sharon Stone and Michael Douglas announced
the other day that they would be celebrity partners in a
surf-themed fast-food restaurant, Maui Tacos, which is to open next
door to Moomba this fall.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   All of this posing in the culture at large has spelled
opportunities for bona-fide, high-profile surfers like the
Paskowitzes. They are seen by nonsurfers as authentic
representatives of the surfing life _ but not so authentic that
they cannot be embraced by marketers and celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are like the little pulses in the water that eventually
make a perfect wave,'' Abraham Paskowitz said, referring to his
family's place in the surf-trend food chain. ``We are so `for
real,' it's scary.''
</P>
<P>
   When Tommy Hilfiger moved into surf-inspired clothing in a
significant way two years ago, he signed the Paskowitz family to a
sponsorship deal: They lend their name to a line of T-shirts and
caps with the PSC logo (for Paskowitz Surf Camp) sold in about
1,000 stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Tommy sponsors music, it's the Rolling Stones,'' Hilfiger
said. ``When we go after cars, it's Ferrari, and when it comes to
surfing, there's no one more cool and credible than the
Paskowitzes.'' Without the family, whom he supplies with clothing
to wear at their camp, Hilfiger said, ``It would have been very
difficult to get a toe in the hard-core surf community.''
</P>
<P>
   Some surfing purists have balked as nonsurf companies have moved
to market their apparel and style to the landlocked masses.
Hard-core surfers rejected Hilfiger's first batch of board shorts,
introduced last summer, because they had a net lining, which the
surfers considered uncool. Hilfiger conceded this was an oversight
and has since eliminated the net.
</P>
<P>
   Doc Paskowitz, the family patriarch, now 78, said he suspected
that the Hilfiger company had made only a ``fair weather''
commitment to his family and the surfing life. ``If they don't make
a lot of money in the short term, they'll just move on to the next
fad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine it would be any other way for a giant
national brand. But for the moment, the sun is still shining at the
beach. In fact, Hilfiger said that he and his family plan to try
their luck surfing at Camp Paskowitz in the next couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the no-frills camp, which is run from June through
October and is open to all ages and skill levels, may strike the
designer as a long way from the jet-set life he is used to. An
aqua-colored school bus transports the 15 to 20 students per
session between the beach and a nearby state campground, where they
stay in a few communal tents and eat at a long picnic table.
(Jonathan Paskowitz said that some celebrities check into a nearby
Ritz-Carlton.) The Paskowitzes themselves stay in a fleet of old
campers; both parents and all their children, along with wives,
grandchildren and other relatives are in residence at different
times during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   There are also more than a dozen young, fit blond instructors
and assistants, some related to famous surfers. The food is
notoriously bad, shade is minimal, and in-water instruction tends
to be casual _ critiques usually start out with ``Dude, you rock!''
Each session lasts one week and costs $900.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're looking for a camp with color-coded surfboards and
`Bay Watch'-y counselors, then it's definitely not the place,''
said Ms. Mingus, the stylist.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Paskowitz added: ``I think it's surprising to a lot of
people that our camp is not what everyone associates with surfing.
It's not the young, alternative generation, tribal, pierced,
go-for-it punks that you see on MTV. It's family-vibed and laid
back. That's what surfing is really about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
