<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Aug. 21, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Between 3 and 6 inches of rain fell in east-central Pennsylvania
early Friday ahead of a potent, slow-moving jet stream disturbance
sliding southeast from the Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, steady rains will spread into southeast New England as
Atlantic moisture streams inland north of a tandem of low pressure
systems along the Eastern Seaboard. Up to 2 inches of rain are
possible, particularly on higher ground away from the coast, where
moist ocean winds are forced to rise over the sloping terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, thunderstorms will erupt over the Middle Atlantic
Seaboard as a cold front associated with the low pressure system
over the Northeast wedges under and lifts very humid air. A few of
the storms will approach severe levels, with damaging straight-line
winds and large hail posing threats.
</P>
<P>
   The area at greatest risk will span from eastern Virginia and
the Delmarva Peninsula to North Carolina, where cooling aloft
associated with the jet stream disturbance combines with low-level
warmth to destabilize the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered heavy thunderstorms will rumble across southern
Florida as sea-breeze fronts lift low-level humid air. With
moisture also arriving overhead from Tropical Storm Bret swirling
slowly northward over the Bay of Campeche, rainfalls could exceed
two inches in some places.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, bands of fitful showers and thunderstorms on the
northern flank of Tropical Storm Bret will approach extreme south
Texas, though the heaviest rains will stay over northeast Old
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: WHAT'S IN A NAME
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Dora became a typhoon as it moved west across the
International Date Line late Thursday. The transformation was not a
meteorological one, but rather a matter of bookkeeping. Hurricanes
and typhoons are the same type of storm, but these mature tropical
swirls with winds over 64 knots are given different names in
different parts of the globe. They are called hurricanes in the
Atlantic or eastern Pacific and typhoons in the western Pacific.
Near the Philippines such a storm is locally called a baguio. In
the Indian Ocean, the storms are known by the generic name
``tropical cyclone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
