<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN IN EXTREME POVERTY UP 27 PERCENT, STUDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 22)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the third anniversary of the new welfare reform
law, the Children's Defense Fund released a report Sunday blaming
the controversial measure for what fund analysts said was a steep
rise in the number of children living in families at the bottom of
the income ladder.
</P>
<P>
   The study, drawn from U.S. Census Bureau data, showed 2.7
million children who fit the government's informal definition of
extreme poverty: Their family income is at or below $6,401 for a
family of three _ equivalent to $123 a week _ or $8,200 for a
family of four.
</P>
<P>
   The census numbers are from 1997, the last year for which data
is available. The Children's Defense Fund analysis reported the
number of 2.7 million children was 426,000, or 27 percent, more
than in 1996, the year Congress passed the welfare law requiring
work after two years and limiting a recipient's lifetime benefit to
five years.
</P>
<P>
   The government pegged poverty in 1997 at a yearly income of
$16,400 for a family of four, and $12,802 for a family of three. It
defines extreme poverty as annual income at half those levels.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Weinstein, director of the fund's family income
division, attributed the rise to the difficulty that former welfare
recipients encounter in making the transition from welfare to work.
She noted that 87 percent of the 426,000 increase came from poor
children in mother-only families.
</P>
<P>
   In Weinstein's view, the numbers are more striking since the
increase took place against the backdrop of a booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message is that more than 400,000 children are being left
behind, so we have a lot more work to do,'' Weinstein said. ``Yes,
more families are working and that's great. We want to encourage
work but families ought to be able to work and lift their children
out of poverty. So far, that's not happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its conclusion that the number of children in extreme
poverty is rising, the study also reported the 1997 level of 2.7
million children is below the 1993 level, when 3.2 million children
were in families at the lowest income levels. Also, it is below the
1994 level of 3 million children.
</P>
<P>
   The study is a marked contrast to upbeat assessments by
President Clinton and congressional Republicans about how welfare
caseloads have declined since the law took effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The welfare rolls have been cut in half,'' Clinton said
proudly earlier this month after the government reported 7.3
million people on welfare as of last March _ a 40 percent reduction
since the 1996 law, and a 48 percent reduction since Clinton took
office in January 1993. ``They're at their lowest level in 32
years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton signed the welfare reform law, many Democrats and
liberal social advocates warned it would usher in a new era of
extreme poverty for poor families and children.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein said her group is less interested in rolling back the
clock to the pre-reform era than in making sure that former
recipients now working get extra help from government.
</P>
<P>
   The states, which have saved $54 billion in welfare payments
since the law's enactment, have not spent an estimated $4 billion
in federal block grants intended to help ex-recipients ease into
the work force. While some states have used the funds to help these
new workers, others are saving it for ``rainy day'' emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Department of Health and Human Services spokesman Michael
Kharfen said the government has encouraged the states to use the
money to help new workers with childcare, transportation, anti-drug
and -alcohol abuse programs care and other needs.
</P>
<P>
   Kharfen said the Children's Defense Fund study failed to account
for the overall reduction in children living below the poverty line
since 1994, from 22.7 percent of all U.S. children that year to
19.9 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us can be content when such a large number of children
remain in poverty,'' Kharfen said. ``Nevertheless, when you look at
full picture, a number of (administration) policies have been
successful in helping families raise themselves out of poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   Kharfen cited the expansion of the earned income tax credit, a
raise in the minimum wage and Clinton's call last month for eased
eligibility rules for food stamps.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein said the fund's high rate of increase in extreme
poverty among children is attributable to their families losing
benefits that typically went along with welfare, particularly food
stamps.
</P>
<P>
   Government figures show a dramatic decline in the number of
recipients of food stamps, the U.S. Agriculture Department program
to provide food subsidies to the impoverished. Five months ago,
18.1 million people were receiving food stamps, a drop of 35
percent from 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts disagree over what has caused the drop, with some
arguing it's due to the robust economy. But Weinstein and others
attribute the decline to former welfare recipients who are unaware
that they may still qualify for this particular benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very troubling when we see that part of the safety net,
which wasn't supposed to change, has become far less available to
families with children,'' Weinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman announced an
effort to work with states to inform former welfare recipients
about continued eligibility for food stamps.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 and, by e-mail, at
dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
