<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-PRICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF SUPERMARKETS, CARTESIAN LOGIC AND THE PRICE OF FRENCH APRICOTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Sometimes the French really do seem to think
differently.
</P>
<P>
   In the country that Descartes imprinted with Cartesian logic,
people side with transit workers when bus, rail, and subway strikes
make it impossible to get to work on time.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers entering traffic at many intersections don't even cast a
glance at cars approaching from their left. By the logic of French
traffic rules, traffic from the right has priority and an accident
would therefore, a priori, be illogical.
</P>
<P>
   And because paid vacations have been a right only since the
1930s, and are a scrupulously observed August rite now, Paris shuts
down at the height of summer, leaving hordes of tourists to fend
for themselves. Therefore, the most celebrated ice cream parlor in
town, La Glacerie Berthillon on the Ile Saint-Louis, is closed for
vacation until Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   And logically, at the height of the summer fruit and vegetable
season, prices should be lower. But by a logic perhaps only the
French can understand, fruit and vegetable producers are hoping
that a new government regulation requiring retail stores to post
the wholesale prices they paid for the produce alongside the retail
price _ which is always much higher _ will pressure wholesalers to
pay the producers more.
</P>
<P>
   What would American consumers do on learning that the price they
pay for apricots at the supermarket, the equivalent of $1.48 a
pound at the G20 supermarket in Paris this week, cost the store 70
cents or less at the wholesale market? Ask the store to pay more
for the fruit wholesale, or to charge customers less?
</P>
<P>
   ``You're thinking capitalistically,'' a Frenchman who
understands Americans well, Prof. Patrice Higonnet of Harvard
University, explained to an American in Paris. ``This is French
republican thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   By Gallic logic, French consumers seeing the wholesale and
resale prices on the shelves will side with underdog farmers, just
as they do with underdog railway workers, and show their solidarity
by pressuring wholesale distributors to be fairer to producers,
explained one farmer, Guy Savanier, from his apricot orchard and
vineyard near Nimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consumer will know that every product with two prices
listed is a product in difficulty,'' Savanier said. ``We hope they
will buy more, which will increase demand and raise prices.''
</P>
<P>
   That sounded like economic logic, but Savanier hoped there would
be something more. ``We also expect a civic attitude by
distributors, in the sense that they will accept a more equitable
sharing of profit margins,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ergo, French supermarkets, the villains in Savanier's eyes, will
pay producers more for French fruit and vegetables, but not raise
supermarket retail prices. ``We don't want consumers to pay more,''
Savanier said.
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday, 200 farmers blocked the center of the historic
Rhone River city of Avignon with 2,500 supermarket shopping carts
to protest falling prices. The day before, Jean Glavany, the
minister of agriculture, posted an order requiring supermarkets to
list both wholesale and retail prices for peaches, nectarines,
apricots, melons and pears for a month, for grapes and apples for
two months, and for tomatoes and cucumbers for three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not naive,'' Savanier said. ``We'll see what happens and
decide what to do then.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing will happen, Christian de Boissieu, an economics
professor at the Sorbonne, told the daily Le Figaro on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The producers are counting on consumers to put pressure on
distributors,'' he said. ``But even if this solidarity mechanism
comes into play, it has no way of influencing the prices paid to
producers, which depend on many other factors like handling and
transportation costs, without mentioning phenomena like
overproduction. It's hard to imagine the consumer writing letters
to supermarket managers accusing them of pocketing scandalous
profit margins.''
</P>
<P>
   Chouki Abebssa, who runs a vegetable store on the Rue de la
Pompe in Paris, agreed. ``Consumers know there's a markup, and if
the quality is good enough, they're willing to pay for it,'' he
said. ``Telling them what the supermarket paid won't change
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Michel-Edouard Leclerc, the head of a chain of supermarkets that
bears his name, called the new regulation ``a political solution
responding to a demand by agricultural unions that won't make
prices rise.''
</P>
<P>
   He told the daily Liberation that when supermarkets eventually
posted wholesale prices, they would be national averages provided
by the Ministry of Agriculture, not the actual prices supermarkets
negotiate with producers' cooperatives, which are jealously guarded
trade secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Savanier said heavy spring frosts last year cost him most of his
grape crop, and now bumper fruit crops were making him sell at a
loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got as little as 3 to 3.50 francs a kilogram for apricots
this year,'' he said, the equivalent of about 25 cents a pound for
the fruit that G20 was getting $1.48. ``The average loss for
medium-size orchards around here this year has been 500,000 to
700,000 francs,'' he said, roughly $83,000 to $116,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
