<P>
   COOTER _ SPERRYVILLE, Va. -- After slamming on brakes when he
spotted the organge '69 Dodge Charger parked beneath the Cooter's
sign, the Arkansas traveler led his family up to Ben Jones and
inquired ``You're the real thing, aren't you?'' Yessiree, or at
least as close to reality as Ben Jones gets. The former congressman
from Georgia has returned to his ``Dukes of Hazzard'' roots and
opened a roadside store near his home in the Blue Ridge Mountains
and is cashing in on the 1980s show's renewed popularity on The
Nashville Network. ``It ain't Disneyland,'' the host admits. A
visit to Cooter's. (Dart, Cox News Service). 25. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-STRIKE _ MEXICO CITY _ With the school year about to
start, there's still no end in sight three months into a strike
over a proposal to impose modest fees at the UNAM, this
hemisphere's largest university system. The UNAM is a huge,
virtually free university system in Mexico City that's paralyzed by
the strike. Mexicans empathize with the philosophy of free
education, but there are signs that people are simply fed up with
the students' tactics and intrasigence -- and think fees for
wealthier students might be a good idea. A July 24 poll showed that
only 48 percent of respondents would oppose the use of force to
re-take university facilities at this point. A month before, the
figure was 72 percent opposed. (Ferriss, Cox News Service). 20.
WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   CAYMAN-SUMMER _ GEORGE TOWN, Cayman Islands _ We needed this
family vacation. Four months of shuffling correspondents throughout
the Eastern Hemisphere to report on the bombing of Yugoslavia and
its aftermath had me in hives at the mere mention of the name
``Milosevic.'' Worse, my family was leaving me notes in lieu of
conversation. To re-connect we went to the Cayman Islands. It's the
off-season. Flights, car rentals and rooms are more reasonable.
Restaurants run the gamut: from expensive to affordable, from
authentic island cuisine to Pizza Hut. The primary entertainment
(read that, the beach) is free. And there are a few things you
can't put a price on: No theme park crowds. No panhandlers. A low
crime rate. (Christie, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
