<SLUG> BC-STANDARD21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Standard Register's Internet sales increases
 &HT;    By Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Standard Register has gone from doing no business
over the Internet to about $150,000 a day in the last 12 months and
that number is expected to double by the end of the year, said Jeff
Allen, electronic commerce director.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just been through the roof,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By December, Standard Register expects to upgrade its SmartWorks
Web site to allow customers to order stock documents and
specialized print jobs via the Internet, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipate that we'll see significant growth in the
ordering of Standard Register products over the Internet. It will
also allow us to penetrate markets we previously didn't have access
to,'' Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   The self-service Web site will allow Standard Register to serve
small businesses, midsize banks and doctors' offices, he said. It
wouldn't be cost-effective to send sales representatives to such
small companies.
</P>
<P>
   Standard Register introduced a Web-based version of SmartWorks
12 months ago and it serves 600 customers with 11,000 users every
day. The new version, which will kick in automatically, offers more
features and functions, Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   Standard Register, based in Dayton, prints documents and forms
and offers document management services. It had $1.4 billion in
sales last year and company officials hope to hit $2billion in
revenues by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
