this summer, administrators have been gathering the parents of
incoming freshmen to gird them for the looking-glass journey on
which they and their families are about to embark. While
orientations for the freshmen themselves have been fixtures at
colleges for more than a decade, the systematic immersion of
parents is recent. Their purpose: to enlist parents as coaches to
prod their students, and to address parents' own emotions as they
prepare to break away from their companions of the last 18 years.
