<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4526 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-PEET'S-COFFEE-$AD     08-20 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PEET'S-COFFEE-$ADV22-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON A COFFEE FAMILY TREE, AN OLDER BRANCH SPOUTS ANEW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill., Ore., Mass.)  (For release Sun., Aug. 22) 
(jt) 
 By ANNE DONKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jerry Baldwin is convinced that he hasn't missed the boat. In
fact, he feels that the curious timing was practically forced on
him.
</P>
<P>
   Peet's Coffee and Tea, the model for and onetime sibling of
Starbucks, is at last ready to roll out nationwide _ 33 years after
it began in Berkeley, Calif., a decade after specialty coffee shops
emerged as a nationwide phenomenon and just as Starbucks, the
industry giant, is warning of slower earnings growth to come.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin, the chairman of Peet's, sees no alternative. ``My goal
for Peet's is to stay independent,'' he said. ``To do that, we're
forced to grow. Peet's would be more vulnerable in a single market
than in multiple markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Peet's, which is privately owned, currently operates 49 stores.
Only five are outside California _ three in Chicago, one in
Portland, Ore., and one in Boston. A second Boston store, No. 50 in
the chain, will open next month, and Baldwin wants to rev up to a
pace of 10 to 15 new stores a year until the roster reaches a few
hundred.
</P>
<P>
   Those are tiny numbers compared with Starbucks, which operates
or franchises more than 2,300 stores worldwide, opens new stores at
a rate of more than one a day, competes hard for the best
street-corner and mall locations and, last year, without breaking
stride, swallowed a rival chain in England that is bigger than
Peet's. But Baldwin said Peet's doesn't want to be another
omnivorous, Starbucks-like power; instead, it is aiming to carve
out a boutique niche.
</P>
<P>
   Comparisons with Starbucks are no stretch for Baldwin. Along
with two friends, he founded Starbucks in Seattle in 1971, as a
single coffee store in the Pike Place Market. To supply them with
coffee beans, they sought out Alfred Peet of Berkeley, the grand
old man of specialty coffee in America.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the 1950s that Peet, a Dutch immigrant from a family
of coffee merchants, began importing arabica coffee beans _ which
yield the strong, dark, oily brews favored in Europe _ to the
United States. When he opened his first retail store in 1966 at
Walnut and Vine Streets in North Berkeley, some customers dismissed
his dark-roasted coffee as ``burned.'' But it caught on with the
students, artists, writers and musicians of the city's burgeoning
bohemian scene, and a cult was born.
</P>
<P>
   Walk into a Peet's store, and the kinship to Starbucks is
obvious in everything from the warm wood paneling, the pungent
aroma and the choreographed service to the bean-roasting style.
</P>
<P>
   Peet, now 79, said Baldwin and his partners ``didn't know a
thing about coffee'' when they approached him, so he insisted that
they come to Berkeley and learn about the product before he would
sell to them. When they returned to Seattle, they opened a clone of
Peet's, which at the time emphasized sales of coffee beans and tea
leaves and did not offer muffins, espresso or, for that matter,
anywhere for patrons to sit.
</P>
<P>
   Peet sold Peet's in 1979, and Baldwin acquired it five years
later, adding its four stores to a portfolio that included
Starbucks and Caravali, a wholesale coffee brand. In 1987, he
decided to sell one of his businesses, and his wife persuaded him
to let go of Starbucks, by then a six-store chain, and to keep
Peet's.
</P>
<P>
   Peet's ``was the original,'' he explained, and however good
Starbucks became, ``it would never be Peet's.'' The buyer was
Howard Schultz, a former Peet's employee who left the year before
to start his own coffee company, Il Giornale.
</P>
<P>
   The deal that transferred Starbucks to Schultz's control
included a noncompete agreement that expired in 1992, the year that
Starbucks went public and began growing exponentially. After the
agreement ran out and Starbucks outlets began appearing near Peet's
stores in the San Francisco Bay area, ``everyone predicted Peet's
demise,'' Baldwin recalled.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Peet reckons that that was the time to expand
aggressively, not now. ``It is way too late in the game for
Peet's,'' he said of Baldwin's plans. ``They should have done this
a decade ago.''
</P>
<P>
   But Baldwin thinks that just as Peet's survived then, it can
thrive nationally now without having to meet the Starbucks
juggernaut head-on.
</P>
<P>
   New shops will be opened primarily in cities where Peet's
mail-order coffee business, which contributes 15 percent of its
revenue, already has a significant following, Baldwin said. The
company will stress the freshness of its product. ``We will never
sell coffee beans more than seven days after roasting,'' he said,
adding that a new roasting plant east of the Rockies may be needed
to fulfill that promise. ``Starbucks may be the volume leader;
Peet's is the national quality leader.''
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Starbucks says it is not prepared to cede any
ground at the high end of the coffee spectrum. ``Our quality is
best of class,'' said Cheri Libby, a spokeswoman for the company,
adding that it was Starbucks' policy not to comment directly about
its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   But the key to Baldwin's plan is market positioning. He said
Peet's wants to appeal to customers who now avoid Starbucks in
favor of local specialty shops, because they hope to find coffee
with more personality or because they just don't like giving their
business to a huge corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin is sure that customers will never think of Peet's that
way. ``Before I bought Peet's, I felt it was unique, and I continue
to believe that it is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
