<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4529 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-WITH-HODGES-AR     08-20 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-WITH-HODGES-ART-$ADV22-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING WITH DONALD AND CRAIG HODGES OF THE HODGES FUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Aug. 22) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Donald W. Hodges, who runs the $33.6 million Hodges Fund with
his son, Craig D. Hodges, has an investing mandate as wide open as
the Texas plains.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a nice blend of big, mid-cap and some small stocks,''
the elder Hodges said in his Texas drawl. ``We don't confine
ourselves to growth or value stocks, either. You need a strategy
that will enable you to score no matter what the defense is like.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does he pay much attention to the overall market. ``We don't
get overly concerned about the market per se,'' he said from his
antique-filled office in a turn-of-the-century mansion near
downtown Dallas. ``We're more concerned about individual companies
and where they are in their business cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodges' big-tent approach to the markets results in an eclectic
portfolio, with everything from sizzling growth companies to
beaten-down value investments.
</P>
<P>
   The Hodges Fund returned 20.9 percent, annualized, for the three
years ended Aug. 19, according to Morningstar Inc., the Chicago
financial publisher. That is better than the 16.3 percent, on
average, for mid-cap blend funds, a category that includes his
wide-ranging portfolio. But it is worse than the 27.9 percent
return of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index.
</P>
<P>
   Hodges, 65, says his stock-picking style has evolved over his 40
years in the securities business. Besides the fund, Hodges Capital
Management runs $55 million for individuals and small institutions,
partly managed by his son, 35, who became a co-manager of the fund
in April. The elder Hodges also owns First Dallas Securities, a
brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '60s and '70s, I was a pure contrarian, buying
out-of-favor stocks,'' he said. ``In the '80s, that stopped
working. I realized that sometimes it did make sense to buy stocks
with very high multiples.''
</P>
<P>
   That explains the fund's unusual portfolio, about equally
divided among fast-growing momentum stocks, blue-chip growth
companies and contrarian plays. Sliced another way, it includes
roughly equal amounts of small stocks, those with market
capitalizations of less than $1 billion; mid-cap stocks, with
market caps from $1 billion to $5 billion, and big stocks, with
market caps of more than $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The portfolio breakdown shifted slightly in the spring. ``I sold
many of my Internet stocks, because I think they got overpriced,''
Hodges said. He removed ETrade and Yahoo, among others, from the
fund.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, he has been adding value stocks. There is such a
disparity between price-to-earnings ratios and the growth rates of
revenues and earnings ``that the value today is in the slower
growers,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many other money managers, Hodges does not screen stocks
by computer. He relies on a much more old-fashioned method _
reading. ``I read in the morning when I get up and all day long,''
he said. In what he calls a ``diligent search for information,'' he
scours research reports, newspapers and anything else he can find
for news about companies.
</P>
<P>
   His son added, ``He's seeing the same thing that a technical guy
would see on a computer, but he does it just by watching the stock
trade for years and years.''
</P>
<P>
   The key factor in picking stocks, the son said, is management.
``We're not experts in retail or high tech, but we're good judges
of character,'' he said. They look for management that owns
substantial chunks in the company and treats shareholders fairly.
</P>
<P>
   But Donald Hodges also says intuition plays a big part in his
stock-picking.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to revenue gains, he said, ``I like to see
consistent growth, but I don't have any minimum, because slow,
steady growers can be just as valuable as faster-growing stocks
that may not be as reliable.'' He also looks for consistent
earnings growth and little debt.
</P>
<P>
   The two start with a small position in a stock _ 10,000 to
20,000 shares, depending on the price of the stock _ and build it
up over two to six months. The fund generally holds 50 to 55
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks typically are sold when prices rise quickly, the elder
Hodges said. He sold the fund's big position in ETrade in May,
after its price rose tenfold in six months. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In February, Hodges started buying Tractor Supply, a
Nashville-based chain of 257 stores that sells farm equipment,
animal feed and other supplies. Management knows the business well,
he said, and has successfully developed a local concept into a
national chain.
</P>
<P>
   He started buying at $26 a share; the stock now is at $18.50,
just nine times his 1999 earnings estimate of $2.01 a share, he
said, because it has suffered from the overall lack of interest in
smaller stocks. He expects earnings growth of 18 to 20 percent a
year over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   The fund added to its position in Starbucks, the Seattle coffee
giant, in early July, after the company announced that it was
starting a reserve to set up an Internet site and that its earnings
would not meet Wall Street expectations. The stock, which had
traded as high as $41 in May, tumbled after the announcement, and
Hodges picked up shares at $24 and $25; he first bought Starbucks
stock last October at $16.64.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that earnings and revenues have grown consistently,
Hodges said Starbucks is ``a great growth company that just had a
bit of temporary bad news but, like McDonald's, will continue to be
a great growth story for a long time.'' Management, he said, is
imaginative, generous with employees and aggressive about opening
new stores.
</P>
<P>
   The stock closed on Friday at $20.50, or about 38 times
analysts' estimated earnings of 54 cents a share for the fiscal
year that ends in September.
</P>
<P>
   Hodges has also expanded his position in Sun Microsystems, the
computer software and hardware maker. He started buying shares at
$41.90 in January, because Sun ``is the closest thing to a
contender to Microsoft that exists,'' he said. The company is a
momentum play, he said, adding, ``it's hard to rationalize the
stock price based on earnings, but I have to assume that as the
industry gets bigger, they'll have their fair share.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodges calls Sun's management ``very entrepreneurial.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They've defied pundits and naysayers by successfully taking on
risk,'' he said. The stock closed on Friday at $74.25, or almost 44
times analysts' consensus earnings forecasts of $1.70 a share for
the fiscal year ending next June.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
