<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV23-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE-HUNTING WITH THE CLINTONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Monday, Aug. 23)  
(mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Bill and Hillary Clinton are shopping for a house, an
ordeal that may strain their marriage even more than that
unpleasant business with what's-her-name.
</P>
<P>
   In preparation for Hillary's expected Senate bid, the Clintons
are house-hunting in Westchester County, a leafy and very expensive
suburb of New York City. According to The Washington Post, the
Clintons are looking at homes in the $1.7 to $2.3 million price
range, enough to get you a very nice pad around where I live but
barely enough for an unheated tool shed in Scarsdale. But deciding
how much they want to spend is only one of the arguments the
Clintons are likely to have while shopping for a house. The
president, one has to figure, will want a house close to a golf
course while Hillary will be looking for a home that is convenient
to shopping, restaurants and movie theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary will say that she doesn't want to live near a golf
course because she doesn't want errant golf balls crashing through
the windows and bouncing off the lanai while she's on the phone
discussing foreign policy with President George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bill will contend that malls make him itch and there hasn't been
a movie he's wanted to see since ``Air Force One.'' He will also
whine about how much he hates paying $25 for a cheese sandwich and
how there isn't a restaurant in all Westchester County that can
make chicken fried steak and hush puppies as good as Mama could.
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, will cause Hillary to roll her eyes and wonder,
once again, what kind of boob she married. Bill, who has seen that
look all too often, will lose his temper and tell Hillary that he's
through house-hunting for the day and that he's going out for pizza
and cigars with his friends.
</P>
<P>
   A sad scenario, indeed, but it doesn't have to be this way. As
someone who has been dragged through the house-hunting ordeal three
times in his life, I have learned a few (painful) lessons that I am
more than happy to pass along to the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   1) The house that you can afford and the house that you wind up
buying are two entirely different animals. The house that my wife
and I can afford, for example, would cost somewhere in the
neighborhood of $211. Unfortunately, it is hard to find houses in
that price range, even where I live. So we wound up buying a house
that costs what both of us will make at our jobs if we continue
working until age 211. (That, by the way, is the formula that real
estate agents and mortgage lenders use to determine what they think
you can afford to pay for a house.)
</P>
<P>
   2) Do not buy a house next to a house that has a nitro-fueled
dragster parked in the front yard. We learned this lesson the hard
way.
</P>
<P>
   3) Use a BB gun to shoot the rats that crawl along your
telephone line from your orange tree to your attic. Despite what
the animal-rights nuts may say, this is no more inhumane a way of
dispensing of rats than poison or traps, plus it sharpens your eye
and steadies your nerves, possibly resulting in lower scores on the
golf course.
</P>
<P>
   4) Make sure your new home has lots of cable-TV outlets. This
way Bill can go in one room and watch the Golf Channel while
Hillary can go in another and watch the Home Shopping Network.
</P>
<P>
   5) If you think that Chelsea may be living with you during
summer vacation or after she graduates from college (though I can't
for the life of me imagine why she'd want to), be sure to buy a
house in which the guest bedroom is located far away from the
master bedroom, preferably in another state.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
