<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4537 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-REL-IONA22-COX     08-20 1777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REL-IONA22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A tiny Scottish island that drew monks and Vikings alike became
a steppingstone for the spread
 &HT;    of Christianity
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLE OF IONA, Scotland _ If you're lucky enough to visit Iona _
site of abbeys for more than 1,400 years, often called the cradle
of Christianity for the northern British Isles _ don't wear your
church shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Comfortable footwear is not only acceptable for the informal,
nondenominational worship services thrice daily at the abbey
church, it's also a good idea for tramping across this ruggedly
lovely isle.
</P>
<P>
   Iona is only a mile wide and three miles long so you're always
in sight of the sea _ spouting against the outlying rocks, or
skerries. Almost always within earshot of bleating sheep. Always
aware that these religious buildings, faithfully reconstructed from
14th-century ruins, must have seemed to the monks like a way
station between Earth and heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Always reminded of the glory of nature and its designer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christians are one here,'' says Sister Filomena, a visiting
nun in her 80s from Glasgow, determinedly making her way with a
friend up the gently rising knoll from the jetty to the abbey.
``You don't think about denominations because we share the same
Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in the abbey church, which is run by the Iona Community
_ a worldwide network of clerics and laypersons working for social
justice, loosely associated with the Church of Scotland
(Presbyterian) _ sermons are delivered by ministers and laypersons
of all ethnic backgrounds. Recently they included a psychologist of
Greek Orthodox background, and a Canadian Methodist health care
worker who sermonized movingly about a paraplegic patient ``whose
spirit moves to the dance of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for wearing humble shoes is that they're bound to
get splashed with seawater when the ferry from the Isle of Mull _
the only public access to Iona _ crosses the one-mile channel,
lowers its squared-off bow onto the stone jetty and you walk
ashore, as if over a drawbridge. There's just a scattering of small
buildings on the island (population: about 150), so you're struck
first by the pristine white sands and mossy, boulder-studded moors,
the tiny yellow buttercups trembling in a steady breeze.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't help but feel more worshipful here,'' says Morton
James, a Welsh businessman visiting for the day with his wife and
another couple.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that all of Iona is pious or frozen in the
past: One stone cottage has a jolly yellow Bart Simpson sticker in
the window. Hiking across to the wilder seaward side of the isle, I
saw the silhouette of a man, facing the Atlantic and the setting
sun, with nothing around him for hundreds of yards but a few sheep.
He placed something on the ground, then stood and gazed out to sea.
What in the world? I wondered.
</P>
<P>
   Finally he raised his arms, swung his body around, and a flash
of metal indicated the golf club in his hand.
</P>
<P>
   So I am still in Scotland after all, I thought.
</P>
<P>
   A 1,400-year mission
</P>
<P>
   And yet Iona is a place apart.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors have felt that way ever since St. Columba, the
missionary and poet, sailed here from Ireland in his coracle _ a
primitive wood-and-skins craft _ in A.D. 563. He called the island
a ``thin place,'' a term from Celtic Christianity meaning a spot
where the material and spiritual worlds brush within whispering
distance of each other.
</P>
<P>
   Columba founded the first abbey _ a few stones are still visible
near the current buildings _ and sent his monks to convert the
fierce pagan tribes of the region. The monks also created the famed
Book of Kells (the four Gospels in Latin, magnificently
illuminated) before shipping it back to Ireland for protection
against marauding Vikings. The original book is now at Trinity
College, Dublin, but a fine copy is displayed in the abbey church.
</P>
<P>
   There was no protection, though, for 68 monks. They were
slaughtered by Norsemen in the ninth century at a spot _ Martyr's
Beach, just a few steps from the jetty _ that now looks surreally
spotless and serene.
</P>
<P>
   In the 14th century a Benedictine abbey and church were built on
Columba's old site, with an Augustinian nunnery down the hill; with
the coming of the Reformation they too were abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   When Samuel Johnson and James Boswell visited in 1773, the
island was crowded with half-starving farm families, and nunnery
ruins were being used to hold cattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``That man is little to be envied,'' Johnson wrote, ``whose
piety would not grow warmer among the ruins of Iona.''
</P>
<P>
   'Two sides of same coin'
</P>
<P>
   The flame of Columba's vision guttered but would not die. The
church was lovingly reconstructed in the early 1900s by the
island's owner, the Duke of Argyll, and donated to the newly formed
Iona Cathedral Trustees, representing the Church of Scotland and
several Scottish universities.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1938, the Rev. George MacLeod, a Church of Scotland
pastor in a gritty industrial quarter of Glasgow, brought some
seminary students to begin the 30-year reconstruction of the entire
abbey as part of their training for inner-city ministry and social
service. He founded the Iona Community, a worldwide _ but mostly
Scottish and British _ network of 220 clerical and laypersons
working for social causes.
</P>
<P>
   Though its full membership may meet only three times a year,
including a mere weeklong confab on the island, MacLeod decreed
that Iona, as Columba's ``thin place,'' is their spiritual
headquarters. It's the ideal model of the world they strive to
build. In a chamber off the church sanctuary there are exhibits and
pamphlets to describe the community's campaigns against the arms
trade and for the protection of women, children, political
refugees, exploited workers and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   The community members and their staff spend most of their days
on the island in prayer and study in the abbey and their adjoining
modern dormitories, so they have little contact with day visitors,
but they do accept up to 50 guests at a time for retreats in
Spartan bunk-bed style (two to five per room).
</P>
<P>
   ``We carry on the spirit of Columba, who pushed himself to the
literal edge of his world, where he felt closer to God,'' says the
Rev. Norman Shanks (Church of Scotland), leader of the Iona
Community. ``We see worship as the offering of one's whole life to
God, so social and spiritual concerns are two sides of the same
coin.''
</P>
<P>
   Plea for the homeless
</P>
<P>
   History and faith, too, are as gracefully intertwined as the
decorative swirls in the Book of Kells.
</P>
<P>
   When my wife, Cathy, and I stepped off the ferry one June
afternoon, we first toured the nunnery site, which is left in its
naturally ruined state but with beds of fresh flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Next, beside the abbey church, we reached the Reilig Odhrain, or
Graveyard of Kings. Though no direct physical evidence has been
found, scholars believe that ancient graves of Irish, Scottish and
Norse kings are under the turf. As a theater critic, I felt a
special tingle over the legendary resting place of the real
Macbeth.
</P>
<P>
   A moment later, running my fingers along the carved vines and
leaves on the beloved St. Martin's Cross, oldest standing artifact
on the island, I had to wonder whether Shakespeare's luckless thane
did the same in the 11th century. At that point the 12-foot Celtic
cross, which stands in front of the church, was a mere 200 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   In the museum _ which like every building on the island is never
locked _ adjacent to the church we found 12th-century grave slabs
from the Reilig. Their effigies of uniformed soldiers (kings, some
scholars believe) look a bit eerie, like ancient spacemen with
their pointed hoods of mail and massive swords held against their
bellies.
</P>
<P>
   The church itself has an earthy rough-edged grandeur, with the
weather-scarred remnants of some 14th-century arches artfully
incorporated with the 20th-century reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   The evening service, attended by about 50 people, consisted of
original poetry that incorporated lines of Scripture, and lovely
contemporary hymns, none of them familiar to a mainstream
Protestant service.
</P>
<P>
   There was a long period for silent prayer accompanied by
recorded music (a little too synthetically dreamy and New Age-y for
my taste, but barely troublesome). There was no sermon as such but
a stirring, poetic call to aid the homeless. We were all given
candles. It was lovely to see them all flickering just as the long
subarctic twilight settled in (around 10 p.m.).
</P>
<P>
   An old blanket, cup and bowl had been placed in the broad middle
aisle, and as we stepped around these objects they took on a
haunting presence, as if a homeless person had just risen from this
mean ``bed.''
</P>
<P>
   As we walked back to our bed-and-breakfast about a half-mile
away, there was still a touch of a violet glow in the clear sky,
and we sent our thoughts of appreciation to Sister Filomena, who
had said earlier, ``It does rain here, so I'll pray you have sun.''
We heard the waves lapping at the skerries, heard the bleats of
sheep tossed to and fro across the fields in conversational
rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   Our window was open that cool night, and we couldn't ask for a
better evensong.
</P>
<P>
   THE IONA FILE  &QR;  To reach Iona from Atlanta, the best method is
to fly into Glasgow, rent a car, drive to the port of Oban to take
the hour's ferry ride to Mull, drive the single-track road across
the island to Fionnphort and take a one-mile ferry to Iona.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Web site for the Iona Community is www.iona.org.uk.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For information on Iona accommodations, see the Scotland Rough
Guide, a softcover book published by Rough Guides, 375 Hudson St.,
N.Y. 10014, and regularly updated at www.roughguides.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For retreats sponsored by the Iona Community, contact the Rev.
Brian Babcock, warden: telephone, 011-44-141-445-4561; e-mail,
ionacomm(at)gla.iona.org.uk. For private retreats on the island
outside the community's sphere, with a more Celtic or New Age focus
(all-women and mixed groups), call Vivienne Hull, the Whidbey
Institute, Clinton, WA.: telephone, 360-341-1884.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  To purchase the video ``A Thin Place: Iona and The Celtic
Way'' ($29.95), call the Episcopal Media Center at 1-800-229-3788.
</P>
<P>
   (Caption)Dan Hulbert, 45, the Journal-Constitution's theater
critic since 1987, is beginning a year's sabbatical from theater
coverage to write on a variety of topics. He recently visited Iona,
birthplace of one of his ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   _Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
