<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4539 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-REL-OVER1STTAKE22-COX     08-20 1462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REL-OVER1STTAKE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHRISTIANITY AT 2000: The Americanization of religion
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 22
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On a Sunday morning in metro Atlanta, weekday traffic
is mercifully absent. Office buildings are shut down tight and
malls are closed. But there is plenty of life in area churches.
</P>
<P>
   Houses of worship have seen the town once called Terminus
through Civil War and civil rights, through booming growth and
urban decline. But the incredible diversity of almost 2,000
churches scattered across the region from Buford to Brooks is only
a tiny sampling of the even more diverse 250,000 Christian
congregations in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   All those congregations are essential to the warp and weft of
America's religious culture_from the simplest clapboard cabin where
unaccompanied voices rise in 100-year-old hymns to the most modern
mega-church with its orchestra and drama troupe, Christian
congregations are part of the warp and weft of America's history
and culture.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond their churches are a network of clinics and hospitals,
schools and universities, soup kitchens and homeless shelters
operated in the name of Jesus, the Nazarene man born some 2,000
years ago whom Christians regard as the messiah.
</P>
<P>
   The influence of Christianity on America is pervasive _ but so
is the influence of America on Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any question that it's a two-way
street,'' said Erskine Clarke, professor of American religious
history at Columbia Theological Seminary, an institution of the
Presbyterian Church (USA) in Decatur. ``On the one hand, it would
be very difficult to understand traditional American values and
institutions apart from western Christianity ... On the other hand,
Christianity in this country is, in many ways, distinctly North
American.''
</P>
<P>
   The American followers of Jesus have created powerful lobbying
groups in Washington and in statehouses across the country where
they are part of both the establishment and the anti-establishment
on issues from race relations to labor law to medical research.
Since colonial days, Christians and their churches have played
significant roles in the good, bad and ugly of American history _
they have preached slavery and abolition, segregation and
integration, war and peace, social reform and the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Christian voices have produced the literature, theater, art and
music of their country _ from Southern Catholic Flannery O'Connor's
stories to the singing style of rock 'n' roll's King, Elvis
Presley, whose hips swiveled with an exuberance grounded in gospel
music. Phrases from the Christian Scriptures, such as ``prodigal
son'' and ``good Samaritan,'' have gained common usage.
</P>
<P>
   Even the names of many of America's children _ Mary and Matthew
and Mark _ are from the Christian Gospels. And the best known of
modern-era American reformers _ the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. _
is the namesake of an early Christian reformer.
</P>
<P>
   It is an evolving story. As American culture has changed, so has
American Christianity. The oldest groups _ the Episcopalians and
Presbyterians, for instance _ have influence that exceeds their
numbers. Conservative Christians, under the label ``evangelical''
have set up in the last decades of the 20th century not only
powerful churches but a parallel culture. They have borrowed
elements from the American-born Pentecostal movement, an exuberant
Christianity that accepts such practices as speaking in unknown
tongues and which, from its beginnings a century ago, has become
the fastest-growing form of Christianity around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Worshippers entering a modern evangelical or Pentecostal church
hear tunes that could come from rock and country radio stations. At
home, they can watch sweaty preachers behind plexiglass pulpits
speaking to a television audience of millions. In their cars they
can opt for Christian music, Christian talk radio or even the daily
news from a conservative Christian point of view. They can read
Christian newspapers and Christian magazines, shop for Christian
greeting cards and gifts at Christian stores, and wear T-shirts and
baseball caps with Christian slogans to Christian concerts.
</P>
<P>
   Threads of Christianity
</P>
<P>
   North America's multifaceted brand of Christianity reflects the
diversity of its beginnings.
</P>
<P>
   Long before the so-called Founding Fathers sailed from Britain,
Spanish Catholic priests traveled into the Southwest and Florida to
convert Native Americans. Others, mostly French, brought
Catholicism down the Mississippi River out of Canada.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in 1492 when, as the child's poem goes, Columbus sailed
the ocean blue, he expressed hope in his first diary entry that he
would be able to contact native peoples to ``determine the manner
in which may be undertaken their conversion to our Holy Faith.''
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic presence in America is easily seen in the names of
cities such as St. Augustine, Los Angeles and San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   With the British Colonial movement, Anglicanism came to North
America, bringing the first wave of the Protestantism that was to
dominate American society. In this country's first English
settlement, Jamestown, the Book of Common Prayer was gospel. Within
a few years of the 1607 settlement, law compelled residents to
attend worship services and catechism classes, and imposed a death
penalty _ never really enforced _ for three unexcused absences.
There were also laws against gaming and intemperance.
</P>
<P>
   This stringent approach to Christianity showed shades of the
Puritanism that was soon to come to more northern colonies _
Massachusetts, Connecticut and New Hampshire_as dissenters from
Anglicanism fled England. The Puritans, whose name came from their
desire to purify the church of England from such fancies as liturgy
and clerical robes, in turn exiled people who failed to live up to
their high standards.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Rhode Island soon became a refuge for Baptists _ but was
still rooted in Puritanism.
</P>
<P>
   Puritans ``set the pace for the religious life of New England,''
wrote Catherine L. Albanese, author of ``America Religions and
Religion.'' They tried to shape government according to what they
saw as Biblical teaching, extending their belief in a
congregation-based structure to a suspicion of federalism in
government. Because of their belief in education, they established
schools, including Harvard and Yale universities.
</P>
<P>
   Puritans were not the only Christian souls seeking religious
freedom to come to North America. They were joined by the new wave
of Roman Catholics who founded Maryland, the French Protestant
Huguenots in the Carolinas, Quakers in Pennsylvania, and Protestant
sects from Germany, Holland and Sweden in the Middle Atlantic
colonies.
</P>
<P>
   Circuit riders carried Methodism to the farthest corners of the
new land, and the American Episcopal church separated from its
English home church soon after the colonies won their independence.
</P>
<P>
   The dominant segment of American society was the converged
membership of these groups _ ``a quite white, middle class,
mainstream Protestantism,'' said David Hackett, a associate
professor of religion at the University of Florida. ``The influence
has been tremendous and pervasive and long-lasting.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett credits this generic Protestantism with giving Americans
a strong dose of individualism, which can be traced back to
Reformation doctrine that people are ultimately responsible for
their own relationship with God. He also sees it in the American
impulse to be thrifty and work hard, qualities that have led to a
strong emphasis on capitalism, economic development and
materialism.
</P>
<P>
   Protestants helped lead the way in establishing laws that closed
businesses on Sunday and setting up entertainment standards that
today are regarded as prudish. Married couples on TV in the 1950s
and early '60s _ such as Rob and Laura Petrie on ``The Dick Van
Dyke Show'' _ had to sleep in twin beds; Lucille Ball and Ricky
Ricardo had to film the ``I Love Lucy'' episodes about the birth of
Little Ricky without once using the word ``pregnant.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there were other voices _ especially the growing
Catholic church and the socially active black Protestant
denominations _ the one that ruled was ``the dominant voice of the
dominant class,'' Hackett said. ``They stamped the world in their
image.''
</P>
<P>
   A sort of ``secularized Christianity'' or ``residual
Protestantism'' is so much a part of American culture that people
do not even notice it or define it as such, Hackett said. ``It is
part of the air we breathe. We don't see it. It's the way we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
