<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4538 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV22-     08-20 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV22-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUCH ME, TOUCH ME NOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Aug. 22) 
(jt) 
 By TOVAH MARTIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I grew up with cactuses. Throughout my formative years, the
windowsills were lined with them, and I spent a disproportionate
amount of time with tweezers, removing spines from my fingers. In
her defense, my mother often suggested that I might want to admire
her menagerie of tactile malefactors from a distance. But it was no
use. I've always been compelled to reach out and touch things.
Which explains why I now find myself gravitating toward plants that
provide positive palpable encounters.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the damage that working with the soil wreaks on your
fingernails, the hands-on side of gardening hasn't been given a lot
of play. And it could be argued that the industry is ignoring an
important selling tool.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas the sensual aspects of lingerie and satin sheets are
frequent points of discussion for purveyors of that sort of thing,
texture isn't a common highlight for horticulturists. Catalogs
sometimes mention the palpable qualities of plants in passing, but
a gardener's fingers are not their primary focus. In a visually
driven world, it's little wonder that plant catalog descriptions
overlook the nap of a leaf, devoting descriptive space to blossom
hues or foliar patterns. You have to read between the lines if
you're looking for a feel-good sort of plant.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Latin binomials are wonderful for revealing virtues
as well as warning of pitfalls. Plants with names that include
tomentosum (Latin for ``densely covered with woolly hairs''),
hirtus (``clad in stiff bristly hairs''), hispida (``bristly'') and
glauca (``having leaves covered with a white film or coating'')
tend to promise good things for your fingers. On the other hand,
you might want to give plants with names that mention glutinosus
(``sticky leaves'') or acanthus (``thorny'') a wide berth.
</P>
<P>
   Common names help, too. With something called teddy bear plant,
lamb's ears, pussy toes, chenille plant, eyelash begonia or
squirrel foot fern, intimate contact is likely to be a positive
experience. But sometimes common names send mixed messages. One
common name for Acalypha hispida, the chenille plant, encourages
children and adults alike to toy with its long, fluffy catkins. But
it's also known as the red-hot poker. As it turns out, the allusion
is not meant to be a warning. Instead, it describes the plant's
striking sizzling-pink streamers.
</P>
<P>
   Soft and fuzzy or felted leaves like the ones on foxgloves,
mullein and lamb's ears obviously invite fondling, but there are
other sensations available in the floral kingdom. In the furry
realm, leaves can feel like velvet (stachys), velveteen (peppermint
scented geranium), flannel (brugmansia) or corduroy (heliotrope).
Satiny foliage, like philodendron leaves, also fosters positive
finger play.
</P>
<P>
   And textures frequently change at different stages of
development. Young leaves are often softer and more cuddly than
their mature counterparts; buds are sometimes covered in a pleasant
down that disappears when the flower opens.
</P>
<P>
   Leaves offer tangible results most often, but flowers (magnolias
come to mind) occasionally gratify your sense of touch. The tufted
blossoms of grasses, for example, are a delight to run through your
fingers. Although easily damaged when fingered, rose petals are as
plush as Egyptian cotton.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes plant handling should entail more than a single leaf.
Many ferns feel soft when you run your fingers up their fronds,
Boston ferns being particularly sensuous (the cultivar name Fluffy
Ruffles says it all). Almost any fiddlehead is Nirvana for
compulsive feelers. Mosses fulfill your fingers when you give them
a full body massage.
</P>
<P>
   As with anything, there can be caveats. Reaching out to plants
has brought its fair share of nasty surprises.
</P>
<P>
   The downy stems of nettles, for example, appear soft but have a
mean bite. Their hairs are actually minute, easily shattered vials
holding a dermatological irritant that isn't painful at first but
follows up with a burning sensation.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, most plants with a touch-me-not policy are more
flagrant about their artillery. Roses and bougainvilleas are fairly
obvious with their thorny defense systems. Many cactuses bristle
with nasty prongs, several citrus are similarly well armed with
thorns, and some raspberries also have noteworthy thorns easily
spied from a distance.
</P>
<P>
   Prickly characters are in the minority. For the most part, you
can touch a leaf without fear of reprisal or harm to the plant, as
long as you're gentle. And many herbs spew essential oils into the
air when their leaf surface is brushed, scenting the atmosphere
with perfume. No matter how often you touch their leaves, they
continue to emit their redolence.
</P>
<P>
   Because frequent touching does no harm and yet can be as
soothing as cuddling with a favorite blanket, many tactile plants
have become houseplants. There are several obvious advantages. You
don't have to crawl around on all fours to sample the sensual
qualities of lamb's ears when it's in a pot on the windowsill.
Although woolly plants come in all shapes and sizes, they're
frequently sun worshippers: in their native habitats, their downy
hairs have adapted to protect the leaf or stem surface from sun
damage. Indoors, they'll need a bright exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Touching plants is not just for children, fidgety adults and
those in need of therapy. It's another way to link with nature. You
can learn a lot about a plant by feeling its leaves and flowers.
There are secrets that are revealed only to your fingers. In a
world where most things are kept at arm's length, it's a nice
touch.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 1821EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4540 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-DANCEISTTAKE22-COX     08-20 1733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCEISTTAKE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Classical, modern meet on Main Street
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 22
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The epicenter of dance at the start of the 20th century was
Paris. But just after World War I, ballet took a grand jete across
the Atlantic to New York, which has been the dance capital of the
world ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Modern dance was born when Isadora Duncan of Oakland, Calif.,
decided it was a lot easier to move if she took off her corsets and
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   And the all-American battle for supremacy between the fine arts
and popular culture was fought as vigorously on the dance front as
on any other _ perhaps more so. No Eudora Welty ever sighed to be
Danielle Steel, but Mikhail Baryshnikov acknowledges his admiration
for Fred Astaire.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most important influence on 20th-century dance is
the great emigration that followed the Russian Revolution of 1917.
</P>
<P>
   ``The development of ballet in this century,'' says Janice Ross,
a dance historian who teaches at Stanford University, ``comes from
where the Russians went and who they taught.'' Not only did the
revolution scatter dance talent across the United States, but it
also persuaded a young choreographer, George Balanchine, to accept
a job in America, where he totally changed the look, the technique
and the expressive potential of classical ballet.
</P>
<P>
   A clean slate
</P>
<P>
   It's an amazing phenomenon, the migration of dance to the New
World, which until then had had almost no formalized tradition of
expressive movement. Duncan, Loie Fuller and Maud Allan, the
founding mothers of modern dance, were all American, but they found
Europe a more open environment for their free-form dancing.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the turn of the 20th century, when American dance began,
there were no schools, no academies, no companies, no tradition
handed down through a royal line. Up to that time, classical
dancing had been imported from Europe,'' says dance critic Marcia
B. Siegel in ``The Shapes of Change,'' a thematic history of
American dance. Not until 1933 did the United States have so much
as a single professional ballet company.
</P>
<P>
   Compare this to the art form often stigmatized as the most
European (or, more accurately, least American): opera. Despite its
elitist reputation, opera had been presented in this country since
the early 19th century. The Metropolitan Opera in New York was
founded in 1883 _ a long couple of generations before any
comparable venture in dance.
</P>
<P>
   All through the 19th century, though dance satellites flourished
in Copenhagen, Denmark, and St. Petersburg, Russia, Paris was still
regarded as the capital of the art. So when the impresario Serge
Diaghilev and his Ballets Russes set out to conquer the world, it
was to Paris that they came to make a statement. It was quite a
statement, too: ``The Rite of Spring'' caused a riot at its Paris
premiere in 1913. Its self-conscious primitivism, its oversize cave
drawings in raw colors, its non-balletic choreography by Vaslav
Nijinsky and above all the neo-brutalism of Igor Stravinsky's score
set a new base line for artistic adventurism. The rest of the
cultural world saw it and knew there was no turning back.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Europe was engulfed in a new kind of war:
impersonal, mechanized, omnivorous. In its wake, the years between
the world wars were an age of disillusion, of crude cabaret satire
and social anomie, of abraded emotion masked by flippancy or
distorted by exaggeration.
</P>
<P>
   With the United States the destination of choice for European
intellectuals and artists, this country grew up in a hurry _
especially in dance, where the flood of emigre Russians after the
1917 revolution had an enormous influence. Russian troupes
overwhelmed the limited market for touring dance, with the result
that many of those highly trained dancers gave up the life of
artistic gypsies to set down roots in their adopted country.
Because of them, an artistic evolution that might have taken
centuries was compressed into a couple of decades.
</P>
<P>
   But the Russians also held back the development of indigenous
ballet wherever they went. Dancers from Alicia Markova (born Alice
Marks) to Vera Zorina (born Eve Brigitte Hartwig) Russified their
names to get a toehold in a profession dominated by exiled
Russians.
</P>
<P>
   The most important, of course, was Balanchine, a choreographer
for Diaghilev. His early work showed talent; no one could have
known, even after ``Apollo,'' that he was a genius. But Lincoln
Kirstein, a wealthy New York aesthete, took a chance that the
29-year-old Russian was the force needed to invent an American
ballet.
</P>
<P>
   When they met to discuss starting a ballet company, Balanchine
famously responded: ``But first, a school!'' For the initial group
of ballerinas-in-training, he created a masterpiece called
``Serenade'' (1934), the first plotless ballet. Built entirely of
classroom steps, ``Serenade'' displays all the traits of mature
Balanchine: It is fleet, complex, emotionally charged, musically
astute. It demands flawless pointe technique as well as stamina,
but any dancer will tell you it is a joy to perform. It gives back
in artistic satisfaction as much as it demands in artistic sweat
and discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Balanchine went on to create a large body of work for New York
City Ballet, the company that evolved out of his school. It ranges
from abstract ``practice clothes'' ballets (``Agon'' and ``The Four
Temperaments'') to full-length story-ballets (``A Midsummer Night's
Dream'' and ``Don Quixote''), from virtuoso spotlight dances in
classic mode (``Tarantella'') to full-corps showcases (``Symphony
in C'' and ``Jewels'').
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he continued the time-honored practice of building
repertory around important dancers, from Maria Tallchief to Edward
Villella. A generous colleague, he reached out to other talented
choreographers, notably Jerome Robbins, whom he made associate
artistic director in 1949, but also including such unlikely
dance-makers as Merce Cunningham. And his eclectic taste and
unconditional love for all things danceable allowed him to
incorporate such wide-ranging ingredients as Hollywood westerns and
Busby Berkeley musicals (``Western Symphony''); close-order drill
(``Stars and Stripes''); and Japanese ritual drama (``Bugaku''). He
believed ballet should not be insulated from the world beyond the
studio.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the ranks of New York City Ballet came the next
generation of American dance: Patricia Wilde founded Pittsburgh
Ballet Theater; Kent Stowell and Francia Russell, Pacific Northwest
Ballet (Seattle); Lew Christensen and later Helgi Tomasson, San
Francisco Ballet; Villella, Miami City Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   The curse of Isadora
</P>
<P>
   ``Modern dance'' has long been construed as the enemy of
classical ballet. Duncan started this by announcing, before her
1905 tour of Russia, that she intended to ``show that classical
ballet was all wrong.'' But in fact the founding mothers of
American dance reacted not so much to the rigidity of ballet as to
the restrictive society that ``protected'' (i.e., subordinated)
American women. Throwing off gentility along with their hobble
skirts, they helped the growing movement for women's rights by
raising questions about women's physical and expressive potential.
</P>
<P>
   The dance they created is not so much an opponent of ballet as
an alternative to it. Once ballet and modern dance began to pay
attention to one another, around 1950, the cross-fertilization was
immediate, productive and mutually beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   At first, there was little artistic discipline to modern dance.
Duncan's disciples, Ruth St. Denis and Ted Shawn, founded the first
``school'' in Los Angeles in 1915, offering a grab bag of yoga,
faux-ballet, what they called ``ethnic dance'' and rhythmic
exercises. They trained many of the most committed figures of
modern expressive movement, including Martha Graham and Doris
Humphrey.
</P>
<P>
   When these women founded schools and companies in the '30s,
``modern dance'' still connoted a deliberate lack of technique.
Perhaps their most important achievement was to prove the new dance
an articulate vehicle for the body and an expressive spokesman for
the heart and mind. And they imbued their pieces almost from the
start with an American flavor. Graham's ``Sketches From the
People'' (1929) celebrated the spirit of labor; ``El Penitente''
(1940), Mexican religious rituals; Humphrey's ``The Shakers''
(1930) and Graham's ``Appalachian Spring'' (1944), the grass roots
of the American spirit.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-'40s, Graham embarked on her most ambitious work: the
long series of dances, most inspired by classical mythology and
Freudian dream-theory, from ``Cave of the Heart'' (Medea) (1946)
and ``Errand Into the Maze'' (Ariadne) (1947) to ``Clytemnestra''
(1958) and ``Phaedra'' (1962). Partly these were a feminist
response to Western culture; partly they displayed the endless
possibilities of renewal in these seminal stories; partly they
offered meaty roles in which Graham could express her considerable
dance personality.
</P>
<P>
   But their larger purpose was to demonstrate that modern dance
had reached artistic maturity. These dances _ unhampered by courtly
traditions, the formalized aesthetics of classical ballet or
well-worn musical ``messages'' _ had the strength of intellect to
sustain great ideas and great characters. Though the choreographers
of Judson Church in the '60s and the Grand Union in the '70s
created their art out of vernacular movement (walking, lying down,
contact improvisation) and claimed that their dances told no
stories and delivered no messages, they were clearly children of
Graham. The anti-establishment flavor of their work, so closely
allied to the civil rights movement of the '60s and the anti-war
protests of the '70s, has roots in Graham's leftist sympathies and
serious artistic statements.
</P>
<P>
   In an influential essay called ``The Curse of Isadora,'' Lincoln
Kirstein, Balanchine's bankroller and the invisible monarch of
American ballet, argued that modern dance was so rootless and
ungrounded that it had no staying power, and that so free-form a
movement could not possibly deal with anything more meaningful than
music and drapery. He underrated both the technical and expressive
power of this dance.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
