<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4542 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-ELLIOTT-SIDEBAR22-COX     08-20 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIOTT-SIDEBAR22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thomas' great-grandson tries to fill in history's gaps
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 22
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Colin Monteith is 72 years old, but his face is
virtually unlined, his cheeks are as ruddy as a boy's, and his eyes
sparkle when he lays the huge scrapbook on the table.
</P>
<P>
   If you look at his family pictures and then squint your eyes a
little and look at his face again, it's easy enough to see his
great-grandfather: Deputy U.S. Marshal Heck Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Monteith, an engineer who lives in Lilburn, Ga., hasn't always
known about his great-grandfather. His grandmother was born Mary Jo
Thomas, the fourth of the four children the manhunter had with his
first wife, Isabelle Gray. She was born in Texas, before the family
moved to Fort Smith, Ark., and Heck became a deputy marshal.
</P>
<P>
   After the fifth child was born, Isabelle took the children and
returned to Georgia. She was unable to stand the Indian Territory's
absence of refinement and culture, and its terrifying lawlessness.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, Monteith says, wasn't that Heck Thomas remarried,
``but there was no record of any divorce. My grandma never forgave
him that. She thought he was a bigamist.''
</P>
<P>
   Some researchers, Monteith says, have told him there was a
general custom at the time that considered a couple divorced if
they had lived apart, by choice, for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he says, ``Grandma never spoke of him, and she and
I got along wonderfully.''
</P>
<P>
   Monteith's father met Heck Thomas when he ``was 8 or 10 years
old,'' when the lawman visited the family in Columbia, S.C., in
1910. ``He remembered him, but nothing in particular.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until Monteith's grandmother died, and he and his
father began rummaging in one of her trunks, that they discovered
photographs, newspaper clippings and even some frayed old letters
that Thomas had written to his children.
</P>
<P>
   Monteith says he is the oldest of numerous great-grandchildren
of the marshal. One granddaughter, Martha Lever, is still living in
Lexington, S.C. Few of the descendants, Monteith says, know much
about their heritage.
</P>
<P>
   He and his father have both provided considerable assistance to
the authors of three books about Thomas. The marshal left all his
papers to his daughter by his second wife, and they are now housed
at the University of Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I plan to visit that part of the country next
year,'' Monteith says. ``I want to go by his home in Lawton, which
is still standing.'' Jack Warner writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
