<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4543 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-REL-OVER2NDTAKE22-COX     08-20 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REL-OVER2NDTAKE22-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA: way we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Fostering renewal
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it may be the absence of state sanction for any one
form of Christianity that has contributed to its pervasiveness and
endurance as an American cultural force.
</P>
<P>
   In this nation's earliest days, its founders realized they had
diverse ideas about church and government, practice and doctrine.
If they were to form a more perfect union, they knew there could be
no established church.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, when the Bill of Rights was written for the new
Constitution, it expressly forbade government enforcement of any
religious belief. But it also clearly guaranteed the right to
follow one's faith without government interference.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a free market and an aggressive effort among some
quarters to proselytize, adding to the numbers and the coffers of
churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a church couldn't get a congregation to support it, it
simply withered on the vine,'' said Edwin Gaustadt, author of
``Religious History of America,'' and professor emeritus of
religion at the University of California, Riverside. ``Many people
thought that was a mistake. In the long view of history, it has
worked much better for the United States than the system in
European nations where churches continued to have state support.''
</P>
<P>
   That lack of security gave American Christianity a need for
renewal and revival. Great revival movements have spawned new
fervor and some new forms of Christianity, including modern-day
Pentecostalism.
</P>
<P>
   Older denominations have split and merged, taking on new names
and modifying their doctrine, powerful African-American
denominations developed, and some new religions evolved, such as
the Christian Scientists, Jehovah's Witnesses and Latter-day Saints
_ all made possible by the free enterprise system of religion in
America. And waves of new immigrants have made Catholics the single
largest Christian group in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Influence changing
</P>
<P>
   After a lengthy visit to America, Frenchman Alexis de
Tocqueville wrote in 1835, ``There is no country in the world where
the Christian religion retains a greater influence over the souls
of men than in America.'' Many would question whether that holds
true at the end of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   On paper a far larger percentage of Americans are church members
than in the earliest days, when barely one in 10 Americans were
likely to belong to congregations. The main reason for that is not
an increase in religious commitment but a slackening of membership
standards, said Bruce Holifield, professor of American church
history at Emory's Candler School of Theology. Around the time of
the Revolutionary War, church membership involved lengthy training
and questioning, and a willingness to subject oneself to the
discipline of the congregation, he said. Many more people attended
church than joined.
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup poll conducted in May 1999 showed that 71 percent of
those questioned _ who were overwhelmingly Christian _ claimed to
be a member of a church or synagogue, and 44 percent said they
attend almost every week. Studies of actual people in the pews put
that figure lower.
</P>
<P>
   The influence of this country's historically dominant faith has
been diluted in the modern age by differences within Christianity
and increasing numbers of non-Christian immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is that about 20 percent of Americans are diligently
practicing Christians from the 17th century to the present,'' said
Holifield, but they are more diverse in their beliefs and practices
than their ancestors. He predicts that no single religious group in
the future will be able to wield the kind of power the Protestants
did for the nation's first 150 years.
</P>
<P>
   The May Gallup poll shows that many Americans agree. Sixty-two
percent of those questioned said religion as a whole is losing its
influence on American life, compared to 32 percent who felt it was
increasing. At no time since 1957 has a Gallup poll shown that a
majority of Americans believed religion is gaining in influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``By 1999, we are unmistakably and undeniably a pluralistic
nation,'' Gaustadt said. ``We've been one for a long time, but
people could ignore the evidence. I don't think it's possible to
ignore any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Christians continue to influence American culture ``from the
grass roots up _ that is from the local communities and from human
hearts,'' he said. On Sunday morning in downtown Atlanta, that's
the way the Christianity of diversity is practiced:
</P>
<P>
   At Central Presbyterian Church across from the state capitol,
tables are set with white tablecloths and red napkins for the
congregation's traditional old-fashioned Sunday dinner. Next door,
at the Shrine of the Immaculate Conception, a priest will offer
food of a different kind as he prepares the Eucharist. And, around
the corner at Trinity United Methodist, adults are gathered in
Sunday School to share their stories with their new minister, the
Rev. Cornelius Minor.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away on Auburn Avenue, a sign in front of Big
Bethel African Methodist Episcopal Church apologizes for
construction: ``Please Pardon Our Progress.'' At historic Wheat
Street Baptist Church, young Jasmine Garrett is being baptized into
the fold. ``My dear sister,'' the Rev. Michael Harris calls her as
he pushes her under water in the name of the Father, Son and Holy
Ghost. Across Auburn Avenue in the new sunlight-filled Ebenezer
Baptist Church, Atlanta's church of Kings, the Rev. Mary Finley is
praising God, proclaiming, ``Church, this is the day that the Lord
has made. We should rejoice and be glad in it!''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
