<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4544 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-SAMELLIOTT20-COX     08-20 1701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SAMELLIOTT20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sam Elliott has no quarrel with career built on westerns
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 22
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``I see you have camp all set up.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Sam Elliott can step into a Ritz-Carlton in Marina Del Rey,
walk up to a linen-covered table set with silverware and white
china, and declare the scene a campsite.
</P>
<P>
   We recognize his gravelly twang right away; we've heard it utter
``I reckon'' onscreen more times than we reckon we can count.
</P>
<P>
   We recognize most everything else, too: The hair looks not so
much like the color silver as the metal itself; it practically
glows against the black eyebrows that have pitched camp, so to
speak, right below it.
</P>
<P>
   A few silver hairs also peek from Elliott's V-neck black jersey,
which he wears over black pants and black boots. That's what he put
on before he drove here from his Malibu home, where Elliott lives
with his wife, the retired screen actress and heartthrob Katharine
Ross (``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid,'' ``The Graduate'') and
their teenage daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the morning glare that bounces off the nearby water
and through the Ritz restaurant windows, Elliott looks a little ...
weird, frankly _ a little un-Elliott _ and right away it's obvious
why: the mustache is missing, the brushy logo that seems as much a
part of Elliott as those drawled ``I reckons.'' He shaved it off
for a movie he's about to shoot, a non-western.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reactions from friends, and people I don't even know, is,
`How can you shave off your trademark?''' he says when we mention
the bare lip, like, first thing. ``They take it serious _ it's more
than hair to some people.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott pauses to watch a waiter pour him coffee. Then, just
before he takes his first sip of the morning, he grins and says
drolly, ``It's only hair in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam Elliott, at 55, just might be our last western hero, a
largely small-screen Gary Cooper who's identified with filmed
westerns even as the genre seems perpetually on the brink of
extinction.
</P>
<P>
   He's acted for more than 30 years, in features as various as
``Mask'' (with Cher), ``Lifeguard'' (Kathleen Quinlan, Anne Archer)
and the Coen brothers' ``The Big Lebowski.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is westerns that he's most identified with. Among them
are the features ``Tombstone'' (with Kurt Russell) and ``Hi-Lo
Country'' (Woody Harrelson and Patricia Arquette), as well as five
TNT originals, including ``Conagher.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's latest, ``You Know My Name,'' in which he plays
real-life western lawman Bill Tilghman at the end of his career,
premieres at 8 tonight on TNT.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings the western to a western _ authenticity on every
level,'' John Kent Harrison, writer and director of ``You Know My
Name,'' explains of Elliott's appeal. ``The western is his home.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison adds that Elliott owns ``a subtle tone of melancholy; a
western hero carries his past.'' Producer Joel Silver once told
him: ``You got a lot of great baggage you carry with you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Men like him and women love him,'' sums up Eric O'Keefe,
editor at large of Cowboys &AMP; Indians, which features Elliott on its
September cover in a pose so cowpoke come-hither you might expect a
centerfold inside (there isn't one).
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys &AMP; Indians, a slick magazine devoted to western chic,
chose Elliott for its cover after a reader poll selected him in a
landslide as the celebrity they most wanted to read about.
</P>
<P>
   The western's appeal to Elliott is real basic:
</P>
<P>
   ``I love doing 'em _ I like being outside, going on locations,
being on a horse. I like the dialogue: clear-cut lines between good
and evil, not the psychological gray (stuff) you hear in most
movies. I like the upstanding moral characters that stand for
things _ there's not much of that in film today, or in anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the guy when nobody was doing it, and fortunately so,''
he adds. ``It's helped me get into this box a little bit, but so
what? I'm lucky to have a 31-year career no matter what I'm
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``box'' Elliott refers to is his western stereotype, a
circumstance that has at once kept him in work and kept him from
working. He might love making westerns, but he likes making other
kinds of movies, too, and sometimes westerns get in the way. He
didn't do a thing for a year after ``You Know My Name'' finished
filming. And while he's flattered by the magazine cover (``I really
like that western audience''), he doesn't expect it to raise his
profile in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe if I put it on the right desk in town _ maybe,'' he
says. ``But by and large, it's not going to do anything in terms of
translating into work.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott wasn't raised to be a cowboy. His family's roots are in
Texas and New Mexico, but Elliott was born in Sacramento, Calif.
His father was a fish and wildlife worker, ``a true El Paso
redneck,'' and while Elliott grew up loving the outdoors, he calls
himself ``one of those `Pleasantville' kids. I grew up on TV.'' He
spent Saturdays at matinees, dreaming as early as 9 or 10 of being
a movie star.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `That's what I want to do,''' he recalls. ``I want to
be part of this exchange I see between the actor and the audience
up there on the screen, but I want to be on the other side of it.''
</P>
<P>
   His father wanted Elliott to attend college and major in
business. Elliott wasn't much of a student, but he wound up at the
University of Oregon, where he ran track. When his dad died his
senior year, in 1966, Elliott dropped out and moved to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   He learned acting basics at a studio workshop, then signed a
six-year deal with 20th Century Fox, where he did a lot of bad TV
shows and small parts in major films such as ``Butch Cassidy and
the Sundance Kid'' (his poker playing role was small enough that he
didn't really get to know Ross).
</P>
<P>
   But the decades-old studio system that Elliott signed on with
collapsed two years later. One agent suggested the out-of-work
Elliott return to Oregon; another told him to get rid of ``this
gawd-awful accent _ the accent that has carried me through my
career.''
</P>
<P>
   Then what he thought was a break turned into a disaster.
Starring in the 1976 film ``Lifeguard,'' playing a kind of
precursor to David Hasselhoff in ``Baywatch,'' Elliott talked to
the press and slammed, with westernlike directness, those involved
in what he thought was the movie's mis-marketing. He didn't do a
movie for a long time afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if your opinion happens to be right dead on, you have to
be careful who you say that (stuff) to,'' he says. ``I did a great
disservice to myself _ I haven't worked at Paramount since.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's feature film drought ended in 1985, with ``Mask,''
directed by Peter Bogdanovich, in which he played Cher's
motorcycle-riding boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter said he was looking for a Gary Cooper on a
Harley-Davidson,'' Elliott recalls.
</P>
<P>
   His career since then has been that of an actor-on-the-verge:
recognizable, charismatic _ like Tom Skerritt, you're always real
glad to see him _ but not quite a bankable star. He's had a long
relationship with TNT, for whom he and Ross wrote,
executive-produced and starred in ``Conagher,'' which he calls a
career highlight.
</P>
<P>
   But Elliott has this sense that something .. . something is
about to happen to him; he can't put his finger on it. He's been
cast in a political satire set in Washington called ``The
Contender,'' which just started filming in Virginia (``(The
director) said, `Will you shave your mustache and cut your hair?'
and I said, `Now.''').
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Rod Lurie calls Elliott ``one of the best actors
in the business,'' but has said he's only been allowed to ``flex
his western muscles'' and that people will be ``amazed'' by what
they see in this film.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a major change of pace for me, in how I'm perceived in
the business and by people in general,'' Elliott says.
</P>
<P>
   We've sat with Elliott for more than an hour now. And while you
couldn't ask for a better dude to drink coffee with, something
about him _ that ``subtle tone of melancholy''? _ moves us to
blurt: ``Are you happy?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Happy?''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's startled by the question for about one second. Then he
answers it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' he says, ``I think I am. I get a lot of joy out of
what I do _ even for someone as cynical as me about the business,
I'm not so cynical that I still don't love the business.''
</P>
<P>
   He's got his wife, his daughter (``that, in a nutshell, is
really what life is about''), the three acres they garden together,
the mail from people who tell him the joy he's brought to their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not happy the leading-man thing has eluded me,'' he adds,
then grins and shakes his head, as if realizing how unwestern _ how
un-him _ that just sounded.
</P>
<P>
   So in his trademark drawl, without his trademark mustache, he
puts in, ``That almost borders on greediness.''
</P>
<P>
   THE SAM ELLIOTT FILE
</P>
<P>
   Age: 55
</P>
<P>
   Raised: Sacramento, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Family: Wife of 15 years, actress Katharine Ross (they met
briefly on the ``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid'' set but
became involved after filming 1979 horror movie ``The Legacy''),
and daughter Cleo Rose, 15.
</P>
<P>
   Movie sampler: ``Hi-Lo Country'' (1999), ``The Big Lebowski''
(1998), ``Tombstone'' (1993), ``Gettysburg'' (1993), ``Conagher''
(1991), ``Mask'' (1985), ``The Sacketts'' (1979), ``Lifeguard''
(1976), ``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid'' (1969).
</P>
<P>
   Quotes: ``There are a certain amount of (westerns) made by
people who know nothing about the genre. They figure if they throw
as much money as possible at it, it'll be good. `Wild Wild West' is
a prime example.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been good at intellectualizing the acting process.
I heard a quote of Spencer Tracy's too many times: `Just hit your
(bleeping) marks.' Whether you're a laborer or an actor, you have
to do three things: Show up on time, be a decent guy and bring your
tools. I'm closer to myself when I'm acting than I am to me
portraying some character _ nobody's going to call me a
chameleon.''
</P>
<P>
   DrewJubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
