<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-MILLENNIUM22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Art of dance hobbled by fiscal constraints
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 22
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Not all that long ago, dance was an art passed down
from mother to daughter via stories, stick-figure drawings and
vague memories of ``tradition'' and ``custom.''
</P>
<P>
   Then video cameras became easy to use and affordable, and the
art form with the least staying power became one of the simplest to
preserve. Nowadays, it's typical for a choreographer to load the
VCR and leave the company to learn the basic steps from a tape for
a couple of hours. Then the choreographer returns to polish the
piece, saving rehearsal time and expense.
</P>
<P>
   The computer has changed dance, too. Rudolf von Laban's
meticulous and laborious stenographic process for recording
choreography, Labanotation, which once took years to learn, now
exists on software. Information on the computer graphic program
LabanWriter can be obtained from Ohio State University's Dance
Department Web site, www.dancenotation.org
</P>
<P>
   /LabanLinks.html.
</P>
<P>
   But the greater art of dance itself is limping into the 21st
century. According to John Munger, who analyzes industry data for
Dance/USA, the struggle to provide a living wage for dancers is no
nearer its goal. Ballet companies that once prided themselves on
40-week contracts have cut back to 34-week contracts, on average,
leaving their dancers to survive on unemployment the rest of the
year. These include such giants as New York City Ballet and
American Ballet Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout the field of dance,'' says Munger, ``it's so
difficult (to raise money) that no one has succeeded.''
</P>
<P>
   All the arts are labor-intensive, but dance is more so than
most. A playwright can write in isolation; for a choreographer it's
easier to create steps with dancers. An orchestra rehearses 10
hours a week for each concert program; ballet dancers spend nine
hours
</P>
<P>
   a day, six days a week, keeping their bodies tuned in class and
rehearsal. And the time it takes to learn and practice choreography
is long and costly, involving as it does for most choreographers
the years spent being a dancer first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are the voices of the future being developed?'' asks
John McFall, artistic director of Atlanta Ballet. ``Mentoring (a
young choreographer) is a process, like cultivating a garden. It's
a huge investment. It demands continuity, and I really don't think
we're doing a very good job of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
