r e BC-DANCE-TIMELINE22-COX     08-20 1862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE-TIMELINE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Timeline of a century on the arts
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug.22.
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   1913
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rite of Spring'' (Stravinsky/Nijinsky) causes a riot at
its Paris premiere.
</P>
<P>
   1915
</P>
<P>
   Ted Shawn and Ruth St. Denis establish Denishawn School in Los
Angeles, the first American
</P>
<P>
   training ground for modern dance. First Denishawn
</P>
<P>
   company tour, 1921.
</P>
<P>
   1920
</P>
<P>
   Mary Wigman, who translated German expressionism into dance,
opens an influential school in Dresden.
</P>
<P>
   1921
</P>
<P>
   ``Les Maries de la Tour Eiffel'' (Les Six/Jean Borlin) puts the
</P>
<P>
   Ballets Suedois on the map in Paris. In its short life
(1920-25), this Swedish company reached out to avant-garde
</P>
<P>
   artists (Jean
</P>
<P>
   Cocteau, Fernand Leger, Erik Satie) and created a
</P>
<P>
   repertory of landmark works.
</P>
<P>
   1926
</P>
<P>
   Martha Graham gives a solo concert in New York. Founds
</P>
<P>
   school, 1927; company, 1929.
</P>
<P>
   John Martin is appointed the first dance critic of The New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
   Under Margaret H'Doubler,
</P>
<P>
   the University of Wisconsin becomes the first school to offer
bachelor's and master's degrees in modern dance.
</P>
<P>
   1927
</P>
<P>
   Isadora Duncan, the American free spirit who danced barefoot and
without corsets, dies at 49, in Nice, France.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shorty'' Snowden invents the Lindy Hop, a dance craze named
for Charles Lindbergh's trans-Atlantic flight. In the '90s, it gets
a new lease on life in swing dance clubs.
</P>
<P>
   1928
</P>
<P>
   ``Apollo'' (Stravinsky/Balanchine) premieres in Washington and
introduces George Balanchine to the West.
</P>
<P>
   Doris Humphrey and Charles Weidman leave Denishawn, found a
school and company.
</P>
<P>
   1929
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Ballet is founded by
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Alexander, who directs it for 34 years.
</P>
<P>
   Impresario Serge Diaghilev dies, and his Ballets Russes folds.
</P>
<P>
   1931
</P>
<P>
   Sadler's Wells Ballet is founded in London. Becomes the Royal
</P>
<P>
   Ballet in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   The first performance of
</P>
<P>
   ``The Shakers,'' greatest of
</P>
<P>
   Humphrey's explorations of American character.
</P>
<P>
   1933
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Ballet, the first professional ballet company in
the United States, is founded.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Astaire, whose screen test notes ``can dance a little,''
takes Ginger Rogers in his arms in ``Flying Down to Rio,'' the
first of 10 legendary movie
</P>
<P>
   collaborations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gold Diggers of 1933'' and ``42nd Street'' top off the career
of Busby Berkeley (1895-1976), creator of extravagant dance
production numbers for the movies.
</P>
<P>
   1934
</P>
<P>
   ``Serenade'' (Tchaikovsky/
</P>
<P>
   Balanchine), the first plotless
</P>
<P>
   ballet, introduces Balanchine's definitive movement style: fast,
fleet, musical, enigmatic.
</P>
<P>
   1935
</P>
<P>
   In the Soviet Union, Mariinsky Ballet becomes
</P>
<P>
   Leningrad Kirov
</P>
<P>
   Ballet, signaling a shift in Russian ballet from fairy-tale
pageantry (created for the aristocracy) to socialist realism
(created for the common people). Though continually resupplied with
superb dancers
</P>
<P>
   from their training academies, the Kirov and its cousin, the
Bolshoi in Moscow, become better known for sterile museum pieces
and defections that impoverish Soviet dance but enrich the West's
major
</P>
<P>
   companies.
</P>
<P>
   Frederick Ashton becomes chief choreographer for Sadler's
Wells/Royal Ballet (artistic
</P>
<P>
   director, 1963-70). In more than 50 ballets, he leads
</P>
<P>
   English ballet to a peak of intelligent classicism, typified by
his protege, Margot Fonteyn.
</P>
<P>
   1937
</P>
<P>
   Igor Moiseyev, patriarch of Soviet folk dance, founds the
Moiseyev Folk Dance Ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Graham is the first dancer to perform at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   1938
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy the Kid,'' the first of Aaron Copland's American
folk-influenced ballets, premieres, with choreography by Eugene
Loring that reflects the wide-open-spaces mythology of
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood westerns.
</P>
<P>
   1940
</P>
<P>
   Ballet Theater, later American Ballet Theater, is founded in New
York to preserve and expand the tradition of the great European
story-ballets.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine Dunham, a dance anthropologist who studied
</P>
<P>
   Haitian religion and dance,
</P>
<P>
   choreographs ``From Haiti to Harlem,'' a revue of
African-American culture, and ``Cabin in the Sky,'' a Negro musical
on Broadway, winning respect for black dance and dancers.
</P>
<P>
   1942
</P>
<P>
   Premieres of ``Rodeo'' (Copland/
</P>
<P>
   de Mille) and ``Pillar of Fire'' (Schoenberg/Tudor), both for
American Ballet Theater. Agnes de Mille stars as the cowgirl in her
own western comedy. ``Pillar'' is one of a handful of works by
Antony Tudor (1908-87), a subtle psychologist of dance.
</P>
<P>
   1944
</P>
<P>
   ``Appalachian Spring'' premieres, an incomparable collaboration
by Aaron Copland and Martha Graham that distills the American
pioneer spirit.
</P>
<P>
   1946
</P>
<P>
   Premiere of ``Cave of the Heart,'' the first in a series of
dances by Graham exploring
</P>
<P>
   the complexities of Freudian psychology.
</P>
<P>
   1947
</P>
<P>
   ``Symphonic Variations,'' the apex of Frederick Ashton's poetic
works for what would become the Royal Ballet, premieres.
</P>
<P>
   1948
</P>
<P>
   New York City Ballet is
</P>
<P>
   founded, the standard-bearer of the American style.
</P>
<P>
   Alwin Nikolais
</P>
<P>
   becomes director of New York's Henry Street Playhouse and founds
an
</P>
<P>
   eclectic company influenced by everything from electronic music
to Asian puppetry.
</P>
<P>
   1949
</P>
<P>
   ``The Moor's
</P>
<P>
   Pavane''
</P>
<P>
   (Purcell/
</P>
<P>
   Jose Limon)
</P>
<P>
   distills ``Othello'' into one of the simplest and most powerful
works of modern dance.
</P>
<P>
   1952
</P>
<P>
   Merce Cunningham founds a company at Black Mountain College,
N.C., inaugurating a lifelong collaboration with
</P>
<P>
   composer John Cage.
</P>
<P>
   1953
</P>
<P>
   ``Steam Heat,'' a dance number from ``The Pajama Game,''
introduces the pelvic thrust, Bob Fosse's gift to Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Taylor founds his company.
</P>
<P>
   1954
</P>
<P>
   ``The Nutcracker'' (Tchaikovsky/
</P>
<P>
   Balanchine), created for the New York City Ballet as a
</P>
<P>
   holiday diversion, becomes a fixture of the American Christmas
season and the most performed ballet in the world.
</P>
<P>
   1956
</P>
<P>
   Robert Joffrey takes six dancers on the road in a station wagon.
Founds his own company in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   1957
</P>
<P>
   ``West Side Story'' (Leonard Bernstein/Jerome Robbins) takes
Broadway by storm. The 1961 film version wins 10 Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   1958
</P>
<P>
   Alvin Ailey founds a company devoted to African-American
choreography, dancers and music.
</P>
<P>
   1959
</P>
<P>
   Though the first televised
</P>
<P>
   modern dance was Hanya Holm's ``Tragic Exodus'' in 1937, Alwin
Nikolais' company on NBC is the first to reach a major network
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Amalia Hernandez founds Ballet Folclorico de
</P>
<P>
   Mexico, ancestor of myriad companies that explore Latino dance.
</P>
<P>
   Ankoku butoh, ``the dance of darkness,'' created by Tatsumi
Hijikata in Tokyo, signals Japan's readiness to confront the legacy
of Hiroshima.
</P>
<P>
   1960
</P>
<P>
   Chubby Checker does the twist, a dance about sex without
physical contact.
</P>
<P>
   1961
</P>
<P>
   Rudolf Nureyev defects to the West and forms a legendary
</P>
<P>
   partnership with the Royal
</P>
<P>
   Ballet's Fonteyn.
</P>
<P>
   1963
</P>
<P>
   Judson Church choreographers (Greenwich Village, N.Y.) explore
vernacular movement, random combinations and other material of the
avant-garde '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Barnett becomes artistic director of Atlanta Ballet,
which he leads for 31 years.
</P>
<P>
   1964
</P>
<P>
   Eccentric heiress Rebekah
</P>
<P>
   Harkness founds Harkness
</P>
<P>
   Ballet, a showcase for American dance and dancers, in New York.
It disbands in 1970,
</P>
<P>
   scattering Robert Joffrey, Ben Stevenson (to Houston Ballet),
Lawrence Rhodes (the dance program at New York Univer-
</P>
<P>
   sity) and Benjamin Harkarvy (Pennsylvania Ballet).
</P>
<P>
   1965
</P>
<P>
   Twyla Tharp begins to choreograph, at first working just with
women. She founds a mixed company in 1976 and folds it
</P>
<P>
   into American Ballet Theater in 1988; after Baryshnikov quits
ABT, she returns to independent choreography.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monotones,'' an abstract miniature by Frederick Ashton to
music of Satie, shows the experimental side of Britain's greatest
20th-century choreographer.
</P>
<P>
   1967
</P>
<P>
   Joffrey inaugurates his new ballet company with a shocker _
</P>
<P>
   ``Astarte,'' the first mixed-media ballet (fusion score by Crome
Syrcus, dance, film, live-action videotape, nudity).
</P>
<P>
   1968
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Mitchell of New York City Ballet sets out to create a
memorial to the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. Dance Theater of
Harlem's school opens in 1969, the company in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   1970
</P>
<P>
   Grand Union, an informal cadre of New York choreographers,
explores everyday movement. Simone Forti, Douglas Duncan, Deborah
Hay, Trisha Brown and David Gordon keep it active through 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Arpino creates ``Trinity,'' the first rock ballet, for
Joffrey Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   1971
</P>
<P>
   Pilobolus, named for a light-sensitive fungus, is founded by
four Dartmouth College dancers to create organic choreography.
</P>
<P>
   1972
</P>
<P>
   New York City Ballet's Stravinsky Festival is an outpouring of
new and repertory works to honor the composer a year after his
death.
</P>
<P>
   The ``dance boom,'' a decade of growth for American dance, is
made possible by Ford Foundation grants and popularized by the
National Endowment for the Arts' Dance Touring Program.
</P>
<P>
   1973
</P>
<P>
   ``Deuce Coupe'' (Beach Boys/
</P>
<P>
   Tharp for Joffrey Ballet) celebrates youth culture and music.
</P>
<P>
   1974
</P>
<P>
   Mikhail Baryshnikov defects from Kirov Ballet. After dancing
with ABT and New York City Ballet, then directing ABT, he founds
White Oak Dance Project to create and perform small-scale
contemporary work.
</P>
<P>
   1975
</P>
<P>
   Premiere of ``A Chorus Line'' (Marvin Hamlisch/Michael
</P>
<P>
   Bennett) _ a valentine
</P>
<P>
   to American theatrical
</P>
<P>
   dance.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Taylor makes a contrapuntal ballet, ``Esplanade,'' to the
music of Bach, consisting of nothing more complicated than walking
and running, leaps, skips and hops.
</P>
<P>
   1976
</P>
<P>
   ``A Month in the Country'' (Chopin/Ashton for the Royal Ballet)
typifies English
</P>
<P>
   narrative ballet.
</P>
<P>
   1980
</P>
<P>
   Mark Morris starts Mark Morris Dance Group. It moves to
</P>
<P>
   Brussels, Belgium, in 1988, where American postmodern dance
receives a rocky reception. Returns to the United States in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   1983
</P>
<P>
   Balanchine dies at 79.
</P>
<P>
   1985
</P>
<P>
   ``Tango Argentino'' comes to Broadway, starts the tango craze
and makes a star of Argentine composer Astor Piazzolla.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Villella becomes artistic director of Miami City Ballet
and initiates a four-county mission in South Florida: a unique
funding approach in an area whose cities are separately unable to
support professional ballet.
</P>
<P>
   1988
</P>
<P>
   Frederick Ashton dies at 83.
</P>
<P>
   1989
</P>
<P>
   Robert Joffrey dies at 57, Alvin Ailey at 58, casualties of the
AIDS epidemic, which devastated dance in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   1991
</P>
<P>
   Martha Graham dies at 96.
</P>
<P>
   The fall of the Soviet Union unleashes a flood of dance
</P>
<P>
   talent on the world.
</P>
<P>
   1993
</P>
<P>
   Nureyev dies of AIDS at 54.
</P>
<P>
   1994
</P>
<P>
   John McFall becomes third artistic director of Atlanta Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   1996
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore does the macarena at the Democratic National
</P>
<P>
   Convention.
</P>
<P>
   1998
</P>
<P>
   English choreographer Matthew Bourne's all-male version of
``Swan Lake'' captivates Broadway audiences and wins three Tony
Awards.
</P>
<P>
   _ Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
