</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4547 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-DANCE2NDTAKE22-COX     08-20 1359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE2NDTAKE22-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: power of this dance.
</P>
<P>
   But modern dance bears the curse of Isadora in a way that
Kirstein never considered: continuity. From its earliest days, it
has grown not by evolution but by cell division. When young
choreographers outgrew their mentors, they started new companies.
The field has become so fragmented that both funding sources and
audiences are confused, and the casualty rate of modern dance
troupes is unusually high. In our time, the modern dance community
has backslid to the economic condition of the '30s. The field is
overpopulated, yet only a museum troupe such as Graham's draws much
of a mainstream audience. While ballet companies struggle toward
year-round employment, health benefits and pensions for dancers, a
living wage for modern dancers is still an elusive goal, according
to the national service agency Dance/USA.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Kirstein's ``curse'' has been a blessing for ballet. From
Agnes de Mille, who choreographed the immortal ``Rodeo'' (1942) to
Twyla Tharp, who made a repertory for American Ballet Theater in
the late '80s, ballet has appropriated modern dance.
</P>
<P>
   Balanchine (who seems not to have listened to Kirstein) asked
Merce Cunningham for a piece for New York City Ballet and got a
masterpiece, ``Summerspace'' (1966). Mark Morris has made wonderful
ballets for ABT and San Francisco Ballet, as well as a portrait
gallery of dances for Mikhail Baryshnikov and his White Oak Dance
Project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at someone like Glen Tetley,'' says Atlanta Ballet's John
McFall. ``He partnered Martha Graham. Then he'd sneak across the
street and take ballet classes at the Metropolitan Opera Ballet.''
Tetley's modern-inspired ballets are in the repertory of many
companies. ``I credit him with taking ideas that at one time were
segmented, that could not be crossed, and bringing them together,''
says McFall, whose ballets similarly draw on multiple sources.
</P>
<P>
   At the most fundamental level, modern dance has made modern
ballet possible. The prime illusion of classical ballet is the
denial of gravity. The modern dancer's commitment to the floor _ as
support, as roots, as the locus of regenerative energy _ was as
opposite to ballet's ethereality as it could be. Yet the greater
strength and technique of today's ballet dancers, the brilliance
and speed demanded by contemporary choreography, would not be
possible without the intelligent exploitation of gravity. The
overall ease and freedom of the body in modern dance have been
greedily co-opted by ballet choreographers eager to express more
than what ballet steps will allow.
</P>
<P>
   Culture wars
</P>
<P>
   Ever since ``Yankee Doodle,'' Americans have been stereotyped as
a nation of hicks. We contribute to the caricature by drawing
elaborate distinctions between high and low art, professing to be
intimidated by the one and comfy with the other.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, the line of demarcation is no line at all, but a
porous zone. And therein lies one of the paradoxes of 20th-century
dance. Fred Astaire's glittering technique may have been equal to _
in fact, it was better than _ that of Nijinsky. But Astaire is
known as an entertainer, Nijinsky an artist. Nowadays, an eminent
dance critic such as Arlene Croce (``The Fred Astaire and Ginger
Rogers Book'') can take theatrical dance as seriously as classical
ballet.
</P>
<P>
   One of the 20th century's major themes has been the breakdown of
the artificial barrier between high art and popular entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Why it should have taken so long is a mystery, because classical
ballet from the start grabbed ideas from everywhere. Sir Frederick
Ashton, the Royal Ballet's master choreographer, danced as a
youngster on the English music hall stage, and its rambunctious,
frequently off-color humor and pratfalls can be discerned even in
his refined story-ballets. Balanchine and Robbins choreographed for
Broadway and Hollywood, and you can see elements of Apache dance,
the wild jazz style of the '20s, in Balanchine's ``Slaughter on
10th Avenue'' and Robbins' ``Fancy Free,'' about three sailors at
liberty. By the time he got to ``West Side Story,'' Robbins turned
street smarts, a sock hop, a gang rape and a rumble into urban
ballet.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, they folded popular dance into their classical
work. Twentieth-century ballet devoured social dance and its
sensuous subtext in works from Nijinsky's ``La Spectre de la Rose''
(1911) to Robbins' ``Dances at a Gathering'' (1969). The capstone
may be Twyla Tharp's ``Nine Sinatra Songs'' (1983) enhanced with
designer gowns by Donna Karan and other haute couturiers.
</P>
<P>
   But all the while, modern dance choreographers from Graham
(``Appalachian Spring'') to Tharp (``Deuce Coupe,'' with its Beach
Boys score and California casualness) have plundered American folk
and pop culture for ideas. Dance anthropologist Katherine Dunham
began to investigate the Caribbean roots of African-American dance
in the '40s; and by the time Alvin Ailey started his company in
1958, the early civil rights movement promoted African-American
folk material _ spirituals in ``Revelations,'' work songs in
``Rainbow Round My Shoulder'' _ as a primal element of American
culture.
</P>
<P>
   World dance was slower to make its case, possibly because of the
emphasis on assimilation in our melting pot culture. The typical
American immigrant's working class origins also left its mark:
``The artists of the United States had usually regarded their folk
tradition as hopelessly inferior to the grand heritage of Europe,''
says Jamake Highwater, a dance historian of American Indian stock
and author of ``Dance: Rituals of Experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the so-called ``inferiority'' of folk culture has not
been exclusively American. Though today there are folk-dance
festivals everywhere, for many years there was little of
professional calibre other than Amalia Hernandez's Ballet
Folclorico de Mexico and Igor Moiseyev's Russian folk company.
Around 1980, after ``multiculturalism'' became a buzzword, a noisy
and colorful flock of world dance troupes hatched virtually
overnight. Not long ago, an American asked about folk dance might
have offered the ``Mexican Hat Dance'' as an example; today, an
ethnic dance roster might offer anything from Turkish dervishes to
Indonesian bedhaya.
</P>
<P>
   The American century
</P>
<P>
   Though America has led the way, the rest of the world has not
been idle, particularly with dance that addresses hard questions.
With rare exceptions (Anna Sokolow's post-Holocaust ``Kaddish''),
American choreographers have preserved a fundamental American
optimism, shrugging off the great political and social questions of
the century. It has fallen to others to recover the ``moral
compass,'' as dance critic Marcia Siegel calls it, that animated
Graham's early work.
</P>
<P>
   The German expressionist choreographers, from Mary Wigman in the
'30s to Pina Bausch in the '80s, plumbed the dark subconscious of
an impersonal, industrialized world. The Japanese movement called
ankoku butoh (dance
</P>
<P>
   of darkness) has been almost alone in confronting the
aftereffects of nuclear war.
</P>
<P>
   But by the midcentury, dance looked to the New World for an
infusion of creativity, as well as dance techniques that seemed to
spring right out of America's soil and sidewalks. Balanchine
technique required dancers of sleek muscularity: the kind that grow
naturally in an abundance of open space, fresh air and plenteous
food. The eagerness to fill the whole stage with movement is an
American trait. And where other countries pride themselves on their
homogeneity, American dance delights in diversity.
</P>
<P>
   It took the United States less than two centuries to grow from a
baker's dozen of struggling former Colonies to a world power. In
the arts, it has been a superpower despite a history of
anti-intellectualism and a cultural bias toward willful ignorance.
Nowhere has the American century _ its assurance, its defiance, its
egotism and its deepest democratic urges _ been more evident than
in dance.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
