<P>
   TURKEY-QUAKE (Izmit, Turkey) _ New pressures emerge after a
quake that has killed 9,000, possibley thousands more. While
neighbors besiege foreign search-and-rescue teams to keep looking
for loved ones, foreign experts are trying to get a shellshocked
government into action. By Aliza Marcus. 1400 words.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DETAINEE (Hong Kong) _ US citizen Daja Meston is
reportedly hospitalized with broken bones in the remote region of
Qinghai. Chinese authorities say he jumped from a third-floor
window; his wife rejects the idea. By Indira A.R. Lakshmanan. 950
words.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-BUNNY (Montreal) _ Should Bugs Bunny be banned for
insinuating that women are ``witches''? An Ontario woman who saw
``Bewitched Bunny'' thought so, but happily for the wascally
wabbit, Canadian censors didn't agree. By Colin Nickerson. 800
words. (Resending; previous version is released.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-DRUGS (Washington) _ As a GOP presidential candidate,
George W. Bush has not had a good week because his personal
considerations have trumped the conventional wisdom of giving a
straight answer to a question about drug use. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS-DOLE (Washington) _ Enthusiastic crowds and media
attention for a ``first woman'' in politics don't always translate
into votes. But the women's vote for Elizabeth Dole in the Iowa
straw poll indicates she may be able to turn the curious into the
committed. By Mary Leonard. 1500 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-FUNDRAISER (Edgartown, Mass.) _ With a run for the US
Senate on the horizon, the star of the Clintons' summer vacation
this year is clearly Hillary. She attends a reception in her honor
by the American Ireland Fund. By Bob Hohler. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-LOOK (Edgartown, Mass.) -- People are taking notice of
Hillary Rodham Clinton's new vibrant look, including modern,
no-nonsense short hair. She's a woman ready for battle. By Tina
Cassidy. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   GPS-RESET (Undated) _ Planes, ships and even Japanese
automobiles all use global satellites to navigate. This weekend,
however, operators may become temporarily disoriented when the GPS
resets itself. By Jennifer Zeiss. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-VIOLENCE (Boston) _ Psychologists contend that America is
raising a generation of youth who don't know how to express
emotions, and thus tend to violence. By Dolores Kong. 900 words.
</P>
