<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4553 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-PERES-ART-875(     08-20 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PERES-ART-875(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERES, AN ICON OF PEACE, IS STILL AWAITING AN ASSIGNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By ETHAN BRONNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Meetings have taken place at the highest levels,
including several with Prime Minister Ehud Barak. Memos have been
drafted, rejected, amended. Threats have been leaked to the press.
And despite assurances that a deal is imminent, tensions remain
high six weeks after the formation of the new Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is not peace with the Arabs. It is what to do with
Shimon Peres.
</P>
<P>
   Peres, Nobel Peace Prize laureate, architect of the Oslo
framework for peace between Israel and the Palestinians, and
Israel's longest-serving and best-known statesman, is the new
minister of regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   But his is a title in search of authority for a ministry that so
far has no budget, no staff and no agreed functions.
</P>
<P>
   To outsiders it may seem extraordinary that after his party
triumphantly returned to power, the Israeli leader most associated
with Middle East peace should find himself in a position that
friends and foes call humiliating.
</P>
<P>
   Equally surprising may be why Peres, who spent the last three
years building an Institute for Peace that bears his name and who
is hailed across much of the globe by leaders and adoring audiences
as a visionary and hero, would submit himself to such indignities.
</P>
<P>
   But to those who know Barak, a security-focused former general
who never liked the Oslo accords and trusts almost no one, and
Peres, a 76-year-old man with boundless energy and limited years,
the situation is hardly surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Barak to have Peres at a Cabinet meeting is like doing
your homework with your father looking over your shoulder,'' said
Akiva Eldar, a political columnist for the newspaper Haaretz,
referring to the 20-year age difference between the men. ``There is
this quality to him which says, `I've been there and I would have
done it better.' But Barak feels he can't afford to have him
causing trouble on the outside either.''
</P>
<P>
   For Peres, the new government is probably his last opportunity
to build what he has called ``the new Middle East.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is 76 and he feels he has three to four years to produce
the dream of his life,'' observed Mira Avrech, a longtime friend of
Peres. ``If he gets the authority he needs, he feels he can make it
happen. If he doesn't, he will leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Moshe Shahal, a lawyer, close friend of Peres and former
government minister said: ``Barak will never agree to being
upstaged. Peres is paying a toll by being humiliated, but if he can
contribute to the country in this way he will put up with the
sacrifice. The peace process needs continuity.''
</P>
<P>
   Peres says his aim was neither power nor prestige. In a
telephone interview, he said that at their last meeting, on
Thursday, he tried to explain to Barak that he wanted to revive
international donor conferences for the Palestinians, regional
economic meetings and Israeli-Arab projects, all of which fell away
in the three years when Benjamin Netanyahu was prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Barak I am not trying to run the country,'' Peres said.
``I am not trying to grab the power of the foreign minister. My aim
is to build things outside the country. With my experience and
connections and imagination, I want to try to do about 10 or 15
different things. The process needs someone who represents the
point of view of peace. I want to represent peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The two are due to meet again on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The threat that Peres might turn his back on Barak _ damaging
the prime minister's reputation among the Arabs and the West as a
potential peacemaker _ has been uttered often in the last week or
two. It is clear that Barak is trying to find a way to prevent
that.
</P>
<P>
   But some who know Peres say the one thing he will not do is
leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never write a political eulogy for Shimon Peres,'' said a
senior official who has worked closely with him and spoke on the
condition of anonymity. ``The more people write about the
possibility of his resigning, the less inclined he is to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a very, very patient man, and he thinks Barak is going
to crash at some point and then turn to him in need. And he is
willing to put up with everything for that moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the biggest problems, say those involved in the
negotiations, is that to create a ministry for Peres, Barak needs
to carve pieces off others, notably the Foreign Ministry, headed by
David Levy.
</P>
<P>
   But Levy has no intention of willingly giving up any of his
powers, already limited by Barak's authoritarian style.
</P>
<P>
   And Finance Minister Avraham Shohat has publicly rejected a
Peres request for a $125 million budget for the new ministry,
saying that Peres' ministry should serve a coordinating role but
not an operational one.
</P>
<P>
   For Nahum Barnea, the nation's most-read political analyst, the
problem comes down to conflicting commitments, as he put in a
recent column in the newspaper Yediot Ahronot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He promised Peres a senior ministry, he promised Levy a senior
ministry and he promised himself that he wouldn't let Peres lead
him into all sorts of arrangements that he dislikes,'' Barnea
wrote. ``Barak knows that Peres' resignation has a price. It will
damage the government abroad and make its life more difficult
inside. Peres is not just another minister. On the outside he can
be a bitter adversary.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There is no question among those who know him that Peres
sincerely hopes to make a difference in the government. But they
also say that this is a man who has spent his entire life in public
service _ he was director general of the Defense Ministry at 28 _
and he does not know how to live any other way.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Ben-Simon, a journalist of Moroccan origin at Haaretz,
said that last month, while attending the funeral of King Hassan II
of Morocco in Rabat, Peres met with a leader of Moroccan Jews. As
he has done often in recent months, Peres took the opportunity to
complain about his treatment by Barak.
</P>
<P>
   When the Moroccan asked him why he put up with it and did not
leave the government, Peres replied, ``Political death is more
difficult than physical death,'' the man told Ben-Simon.
</P>
<P>
   Peres has a history of fostering yet somehow overcoming
complicated relationships with his colleagues. He and Yitzhak
Rabin, the prime minister who was assassinated in 1995 while Peres
was foreign minister, never got along. Like Barak, Rabin, a
taciturn military man, feared independent Peres initiatives based
on grandiose visions.
</P>
<P>
   When Rabin first heard about efforts to make peace with the
Palestinians through secret meetings in Oslo in early 1993, he
dismissed them as more Peres pipe dreams.
</P>
<P>
   But when that channel led to a breakthrough, Peres' role in the
government grew substantially. The relationship between the two men
took on the quality of a long-married unhappy couple that need one
another.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear, say his close associates, that Peres expects
something analogous to develop if he sticks out the current process
of defining a set of ministerial duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is sure the time will come when Barak will need him,'' said
someone who speaks with him often. ``He thinks that if Barak enters
a serious phase of negotiations for an overall agreement with the
Palestinians, there is no way he can run it without Peres, because
it will be so complicated and you need so much vision and
understanding of the characters that only Peres has. The past and
the future conspire to teach him that it will be worth it if he
waits.''
</P>
<P>
   But some Israelis say they find the process of watching Peres
wait hat in hand too much to bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is he doing this to us?'' Eldar, the Haaretz columnist,
said of Barak. ``Peres is nearly a mythological figure, a pillar of
the peace camp, and there he is fighting to get the leftovers from
Barak. He is an icon. Why is he taking that away from us?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
