<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4556 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYT     08-20 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIPING DOWN SOUTH  
 GORE'S MINUTIAE  
 CHRISTIAN COALITION AIDS JEWISH STUDENT  
 EDUCATION OF A LABOR LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With George W. Bush maintaining a solid popular and
fund-raising lead in the GOP presidential sweepstakes, Southern
states are struggling to assert their relevance in the primary and
caucus process.
</P>
<P>
   Some state officials are griping that the campaigning has begun
so early this election cycle that states with primaries in the late
spring have become afterthoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become so front-loaded,'' said Dan Gurley, political
director for the North Carolina Republican Party. ``The states are
just trying to leapfrog one another to make their dates earlier. A
lot of folks realize this is becoming a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time North Carolina's presidential primary rolls around
on May 2, Gurley predicts that the GOP nominee will already be
known.
</P>
<P>
   National party figures agree that the primary season has become
too condensed, and they've set up a task force to find possible
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that if the system is more spread out, it will
allow voters to meet more Republican candidates in more regions and
to move our message into more areas,'' said Mark Pfeifle, deputy
press secretary for the Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina officials, however, appear in no rush to change
things. With a primary set for Feb. 19, officials there believe the
state will prove pivotal as the gateway to the South.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be the bellwether for what happens
nationally,'' predicted J. Sam Daniels, executive director of the
state GOP.
</P>
<P>
   First, however, comes Alabama, where a straw poll is scheduled
for Aug. 27-28. While party chairman J. Winston Blount believes the
event has ``new meaning and life'' this year, most candidates are
thus far snubbing the Alabama event.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana wants to grab some attention by hosting an early
caucus on Jan. 22. Florida may find it hard to grab much of the
sunshine; it is seen by many as a lock for Bush since his brother
Jeb is governor there. Florida is part of the Super Tuesday lineup
set for March 14th.
</P>
<P>
   Something for Everyone
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has been criticized for thinking too small in his
presidential campaign, concentrating on government minutiae rather
than bold, sweeping ideas that can inspire voters. A recent
announcement involving a Florida project might pour more fuel on
that fire.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president personally announced the award of $2.5
million to build a small dormitory at a job training center in the
state, a noble undertaking to be sure but not the magnitude of
project that typically attracts White House notice.
</P>
<P>
   But in their attempt to stay competitive in a state governed by
the sibling of the GOP front-runner, Gore and his advisers
evidently hold the opinion that it certainly doesn't hurt to be
associated with giving federal money to a community. Next up:
paving contracts?
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi Mensch
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Coalition is weighing in on the fight between a
Jewish student and school administrators in Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   The school board in Harrison County recently voted to uphold a
policy that bans students from wearing anything that could be
considered a gang symbol. They believe that includes the Star of
David, a religious symbol displayed by many Jewish people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Referring to the Star of David as a gang symbol is either
ignorance or religious intolerance,'' Christian Coalition President
Pat Robertson said in a statement. He called on the school board to
reconsider its decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow a school board may decide a Christian icon is
unacceptable,'' Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   Labor Pains
</P>
<P>
   File this under irony.
</P>
<P>
   The South, not exactly known for the strength of its labor
movement, produced one of the country's labor leaders.
</P>
<P>
   When former labor leader Lane Kirkland died this month, several
obituaries noted that he was a native of South Carolina, born in
Camden and reared in Newberry.
</P>
<P>
   Kirkland, who served as president of the AFL-CIO from 1979 to
1995, said in several interviews over the years that he grew to
appreciate the need for organized labor and unions after witnessing
the experience of some friends who worked in textile mills.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had company mill villages then,'' he said in a 1995
interview. ``If they'd fire a guy, he'd lose his house. He'd lose
everything. There's no better way to get an education in becoming a
liberal than to be exposed to those sorts of things.''
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse and Sean Loughlin are in the Washington bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
