<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4559 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-GURU-RAMDASS-SFCHRON &LR;      08-20 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GURU-RAMDASS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GURU SURFS THE SILENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle news file)  
 By JAMES SULLIVAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANSELMO, Calif. _ Words no longer come naturally to Ram
Dass. ``My, uh ... my word dressing room ...'' His eyes narrow as
he closes in on the thought. Then he smiles broadly. ``My word
dressing room is bombed.''
</P>
<P>
   It might seem the cruelest of ironies that a man who spent his
life as a self-professed ``word merchant'' now struggles with the
simplest dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   For three decades, the former Harvard professor gone
counterculture was a fixture on the spiritual lecture circuit. At
the time of his stroke two years ago, he was carving a new niche
for himself as a talk radio host.
</P>
<P>
   For 68-year-old Ram Dass, his affliction is no irony at all.
It's just one more switchback on the road of life. And the vista
around the bend is as wondrous as the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Friday and Saturday, the former Richard Alpert will make his
first major public appearances since the stroke. He will share the
stage at the First Unitarian Universalist Center in San Francisco
with his ``guru brother'' Krishna Das.
</P>
<P>
   For the events, dubbed ``The Heart of Devotion,'' Krishna Das
will perform ancient Hindu devotional chants; Ram Dass will speak.
</P>
<P>
   More precisely, Ram Dass will convene with the spirit of his
maharaji. Silence will play as large a role as words. Krishna Das'
songs, he says, ``will remind me, remind me, of the, um ... of the
Hindu roots. I feel that my speaking _ it will oil my speaking.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, his tranquillity has become a meditative tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Audiences say that the silence between my words keeps them
going inside,'' he says. ``I'll tell you what I'm doing _ I'm
surfing the silence.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses to shift his large frame. It's a serene 70-degree
afternoon at his home in San Anselmo, in Marin County north of San
Francisco. Boxes of books and cassettes spill from the front door
onto the leafy porch.
</P>
<P>
   Ram Dass is moving to a ground-level cottage in Tiburon, where
there are no steps. With his right side incapacitated, walking
short distances is now a monumental task. The steps to his porch
have made him ``a prisoner'' of this house.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, assistants are milling about, contemplating the packing
job. ``Take It to the Limit'' squawks from a portable stereo.
</P>
<P>
   Ram Dass has spent his life in search of the limits of human
experience. As a playboy Harvard professor in the early 1960s, he
threw fast-lane parties, collected expensive playthings and learned
to fly an airplane. But the material world, he says, left a hole in
his soul.
</P>
<P>
   With Timothy Leary, he found a famous new direction in
psychedelic drugs. In 1963 the two professors were thrown out of
Harvard for inviting students to take part in their experiments.
</P>
<P>
   Ram Dass' spiritual journeys in India led to ``Be Here Now,''
his lighthearted 1971 guidebook for the counterculture. The book
has sold over 1 million copies to date.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm known as a '60s, um, blub blub,'' he laughs, not grappling
with words so much as satirizing the stereotypes of his generation.
</P>
<P>
   Fame and nostalgia hold little contentment for the West's
best-known proponent of living in the moment. ``We've been going
through old lectures, getting ready to move. And I really find them
dull,'' he says, letting out a vigorous chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   The simple message of ``Be Here Now'' _ that every moment on
Earth should be ecstasy _ has been particularly useful as he
contends with his physical problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the stroke, it was a beginning of a new life,'' Ram
Dass says, breathing heavily. ``It's good to go this life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was toying with the power of the universe, because I was a
helper. That role is a power role. This role _ wow. You get up in
bed. All you are looking for _ `Will you help me? Help me, help me,
help me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Such dependency has ``a very bad press in this culture,'' he
says. The teacher is now devoting his energy to addressing common
perceptions about age and infirmity. He's working on a book called
``Still Here.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his determination, he freely admits that his ``spiritual
faith is being tested. I would call this tough grace.''
</P>
<P>
   His late guru, Neem Karoli Baba, continues to bring Ram Dass
inspiration. ``I talk to him all the time now,'' he says. ``It can
seem wiggy talking to a dead man, but it's like having an imaginary
playmate who is compassionate, is wise, is humorous, is a rascal.
All these good things.''
</P>
<P>
   In a time of accelerating complexity, he says, this weekend's
events with Krishna Das will be a celebration of the Buddhist ideal
of nothingness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good luck to those that want knowledge,'' Ram Dass says. ``I
want to be where that tree is.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
