<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4561 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-Y2K-WATER-HNS &LR;      08-20 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-WATER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVY DENIES IT EXPECTS Y2K FAILURES IN HOUSTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CARLOS BYARS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A Navy study pointing to a potential Year 2000
computer problem with Houston's water supply was mischaracterized
in a unofficial release of information obtained from the Internet,
a Navy statement said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The statement said the study does not predict widespread
problems with water, gas, electricity and sewer services in a
variety of cities, as an unofficial summary claimed.
</P>
<P>
   Although the report lists Houston among those facing a potential
failure of the water supply, a spokesman for the Public Works
Department expressed confidence that all will be well on New Year's
Day.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy report was summarized this week on an Internet site run
by Jim Lord, a Y2K author, who said he obtained it ``from a
confidential source of the highest reliability and integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   John Koskinen, President Clinton's top Y2K adviser, called the
military's conclusions overly pessimistic. He said that those
conducting the study were assuming that major utilities would fail
unless proved otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military has to work from the worst case (scenario), but
so do we,'' Lord told The Associated Press on Thursday. ``It's
reprehensible for them to know this and keep it from us.''
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen said the Navy wasn't withholding information from
anyone, noting that the continually updated report was available
until recently on a Web site maintained by the Defense Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last people in the world the department is going to keep
information from is their own people,'' Koskinen said. ``In fact,
the whole purpose of the exercise is to make sure they can provide
appropriate information to servicemen on their bases and their
families.''
</P>
<P>
   Wes Johnson of the Houston Public Works Department said the
department has been preparing for the calendar change for the last
year and a half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have completed all the system checks that we know of and
have replaced all the Y2K-sensitive hardware,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called Y2K problem refers to the possible failure of some
computer programs, especially older ones, when the date changes to
2000. Because the programs were written to recognize only the last
two digits of a year, such programs could read the digits ``00'' as
1900, potentially causing problems with financial transactions,
airline schedules and electrical grids.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said the city also has arranged for an outside
assessment of the city's preparations. That report is due in
mid-September, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the city will have complete crews standing by on
New Year's Eve at every sensitive location, Johnson said. All
vacations for that period have been canceled, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said that in case there are problems, the city will have
extra fuel for generators and extra chemicals on hand at the city's
treatment plants.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Corps of Engineers also has volunteered to fly in a
giant generator, if necessary, to power the city's main treatment
plant on Federal Road.
</P>
<P>
   The city also has tested the system by resetting computers and
letting the date roll over, not only for Jan. 1, but for Feb. 29,
which also is an unusual date, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement faxed to the Houston Chronicle, the
Department of the Navy referred to the study as ``an internal
working document.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no indications of likely widespread failures of
water, electricity, gas or sewer,'' the statement says.
</P>
<P>
   Lord's summary predicted ``probable'' partial water system
failures in Houston, Dallas, Nashville, Tenn.; Baton Rouge, La.;
Montgomery, Ala.; Tulsa, Okla.; and 59 other cities.
</P>
<P>
   The study predicted ``likely'' partial electrical failures, for
example, at the new year at bases and offices in Orlando, Fla.;
Gulfport, Miss.; Fort Lauderdale, Fla.; and nine other
small-to-midsize cities.
</P>
<P>
   It also predicted likely partial failures of natural gas service
_ in the middle of winter _ in Fort Worth, Nashville, Tenn.;
Albany, N.Y.; Columbus, Ohio; Pensacola, Fla.; and Charleston, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   A recent report issued by the White House said disruptions in
water service from the date rollover were ``increasingly
unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not nearly as interesting as the world coming to an
end,'' said Koskinen. ``The way they worked was, until you have
information for contingency planning purposes, you ought to assume
there was a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
