A4562 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-PROFILE-SANDS-ART     08-20 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-SANDS-ART-$ADV22-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROWING A GIANT IN A VINEYARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Aug. 22) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAIRPORT, N.Y. _ Richard Sands is an avid woodworker. He likes
to make furniture. ``But, you know,'' he said, making a circle with
his arms, as if he were hugging a bear, ``I prefer to work with
logs, cutting them with a chain saw and turning them on a lathe.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day I'd love to sculpt a really big log,'' he said,
laughing. ``I may even have my own sawmill.'' It was just an idea,
he implied, and may never come to anything. Perhaps. But it would
be a mistake to dismiss any of Richard Sands' ideas, especially
when they involve something big. Sands, a stocky, genial
49-year-old, is president and chief executive of Canandaigua Brands
Inc., one of the biggest names, and currently one of the hottest,
in the wine and spirits industry.
</P>
<P>
   Canandaigua was founded by Mordecai E. ``Mack'' Sands, Richard's
grandfather, in 1945. It became a large but unglamorous wine
company here in the Finger Lakes region of New York, with
downmarket brands like J. Roget sparkling wine and Richard's Wild
Irish Rose, a wine known _ unjustifiably, Sands says _ as an
inexpensive high for heavy drinkers.
</P>
<P>
   Richard's Wild Irish Rose is now only a tiny part of the
Canandaigua portfolio, but Sands defends it as a ``pleasant, sweet
wine whose market is mostly rural and mostly blue-collar.'' It was,
he said, named for him by his father.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after a dazzling string of acquisitions, Canandaigua has
become the country's second-largest wine producer, after E&AMP;J Gallo;
its second-largest beer importer, after Heineken, and its
fourth-largest spirits producer. Worldwide, it is 3d in wine
production and 10th in spirits.
</P>
<P>
   In a buying spree that began in 1991, the first trophy was Guild
Wineries and Distillers, a California growers' cooperative whose
Cook's champagne overnight made Canandaigua the nation's No. 2
producer of sparkling wine, after Gallo. In 1993, the acquisition
of Barton Inc. brought the rights to import Corona beer from
Mexico. Vintners International, picked up four months later,
brought in brands like Paul Masson and Taylor California Cellars.
In June 1994, Canandaigua acquired Almaden and Inglenook from
Heublein Inc. And in 1995, it bought 30 spirits brands from United
Distillers Glenmore.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Clark PLC, a major British producer and distributor of
everything from wine to bottled water, joined the fold in 1998. So
far this year, Canandaigua has picked up eight Canadian whisky
brands, including Black Velvet and Golden Wedding, two Canadian
distilleries and two prized California wineries, Simi and
Franciscan Estates.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all for the moment,'' Sands said, grinning like a cat
who has just swallowed a flock of very big canaries. ``Except
vineyards. We are always interested in vineyards.'' Canandaigua now
owns 5,000 acres of vines in California and Chile, not that much
for someone with Sands' expansive point of view. Since 1987, the
company has also owned the Manischewitz label.
</P>
<P>
   In photographs in the company's annual reports, Richard Sands _
everyone, even office assistants, calls him Richard _ looks stern
and businesslike. But strolling around the office in slacks and a
polo shirt, wrestling with the coffee machine and ducking outside
for a forbidden cigarette, he acts more like the laid-back academic
he once hoped to be.
</P>
<P>
   The Sands family was in the wine business as early as 1932, when
Mack Sands was a partner in a winery in Long Island City, N.Y.
Marvin Sands, Richard's father, preceded his son as chief
executive. ``My father never pushed us to go into the family
business,'' Richard Sands said. Which may help explain why he ended
up with a doctorate in social psychology from the University of
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   That followed, he acknowledged, a disjointed undergraduate life
that took him to the University of California at Berkeley,
Washington University in St. Louis and the University of Vermont.
``It was the '60s,'' he explained with a shrug, alluding to the
era's campus protests. ``I was gassed by the cops the day I arrived
at Berkeley.''
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, academia lost its charm. ``There was a glut of
Ph.D.'s in the 1970s and a decrease in the student population,''
Sands said. ``There was a lot of politics _ it was not the ivory
tower I'd hoped it would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleeing the campus gave him a chance to return to an earlier
passion: mathematics. ``I always had a mathematic bent,'' he said.
``I dropped it all in Berkeley when I looked around a math class
and realized there were no girls. But artificial intelligence?
Mathematical models? I love that stuff. Eventually, my dad
suggested I might be able to apply it in the business world. I
joined the company in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the financial side,'' he said. ``I never took a course
in accounting, but I can drive all the financial officers crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, there have been three marriages, the third
beginning three years ago. ``It will be my last,'' he said. He and
his wife, Jennifer, live with two of her children.
</P>
<P>
   It is tempting to see Richard Sands, at the center of companies
all over the world, as the tranquil eye of the storm. But to hear
him tell it, there is no storm. ``The presidents of the companies
have complete control,'' he said. ``We like CEO's who know their
companies better than we do.''
</P>
<P>
   For Sands, the newest Canandaigua acquisitions may be the most
exciting. Simi and Franciscan are the company's first ventures into
the fine-wine category. Not surprisingly, he sees them as a
stepping stone to a major presence in the high end of the wine
business, a long way from Richard's Wild Irish Rose. Only a small
part of the business now, they could turn out to be that really big
log he's been dreaming of.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
