<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4565 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AMERICAN-FAILURE-2TAK     08-20 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-FAILURE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAILURE, AMERICA'S OWN SUCCESS STORY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Ohio., Ill., Calif., Mass., Pa.)   By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a curious inversion afoot in Silicon Valley, where
Internet entrepreneurs whose start-up companies fail are more
marketable to venture capitalists than those who have never failed
at all. It is not how business is supposed to work, but there it
is: in that corner of the economy, failure has become an asset, a
resume-builder.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in an industry where people do not know what they are
doing, any experience is better than none; perhaps the willingness
to fail is admired because it suggests the courage to try. Whatever
the explanation, the turning of failure on its head is a reminder
of Americans' incessantly ambivalent and constantly mutable
relationship with the idea of not ``making it.''
</P>
<P>
   Failure has been with us as the shadow of success since the
republic's early days, when Benjamin Franklin lectured that
``little strokes fell great oaks'' _ that with enough diligence and
tenacity, anyone could succeed. In the two centuries since, as
capitalism has expanded its hold on American life, success has
become that much more important and failure that much more
catastrophic. Its definition seems to have quietly broadened to
encompass not just those who fail outright, but those who do not
achieve extraordinary and public success.
</P>
<P>
   As in Silicon Valley, there are exceptions. In the age of
instant memoirs and commercial endorsements, for example, Bob Dole,
Dick Morris, and others have shown that failure can be profitable.
To judge from talk shows and tabloids, the only true failure
nowadays sometimes seems to be obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   But for most Americans the stigma of failing remains, and thus
the quest to assign a moral cause for it continues. Whether the
blame for those who fail to make it up the ladder lies with larger
socioeconomic forces or with the individual is an unspoken subtext
of the ideological battle between liberals and conservatives. It is
the backdrop of countless policy debates, on subjects from welfare
to how hard it should be to declare bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while plenty of Americans have experience with failure, few
like to dwell on it, at least outside their therapists' offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historians in particular and Americans in general don't like
to talk about failure very much,'' said Scott Sandage, a professor
at Carnegie Mellon who is at work on a book called ``Forgotten Men:
Failure in American Culture,'' to be published by Harvard
University Press.
</P>
<P>
   There are, he says, dozens of studies of the ideology of success
in America, but until recently, historians have not looked at the
experience of failure. Sandage is doing just that _ researching not
great men who momentarily stumbled, but ordinary men who despite
their honest toil slowly, or sometimes instantaneously, sank.
</P>
<P>
   He has dug through family papers and diaries, credit reports and
letters, to understand how Americans grappled with failure in a
society where hard work was supposed to equal success.
</P>
<P>
   The answer was usually to find some flaw in the person's
character. He cites the example of Robert Brown, a farmer and
planter in antebellum Virginia, who was described in various
business records as ``one of nature's best sons'' _ a decent if
slightly naive man _ while he was prospering. But when he went
bankrupt some of the same people described him as ``a man of no
energy'' _ a phrase that Sandage says became common in the 1850s
and 1860s to describe failures who were not idlers or drunkards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a profound threat to the fundamental ideology of America
if it never comes together'' despite one's best efforts, Sandage
said.
</P>
<P>
   So when Fitch Raymond, a Cleveland grocer who failed during the
Panic of 1873, requested assistance from a friend, he defended
himself against the assumption that he was to blame: ``I have been
Struggling incessantly trying to regain a little foothold but
without success. ``Not because I am imbecile, shiftless, lazy,
listlessly, loafing about, no, not a bit of it, but the reverse is
true.''
</P>
<P>
   Over time Sandage said, failure has been transformed from an
action _ failing at a business or other venture _ to an identity.
Today, being known as a ``loser'' and the words ``I am a failure''
have become common coinage.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of super-successes like Carnegie and Rockefeller at the
end of the 19th century helped breed the phenomenon that might be
called failure through inadequacy: unless one achieved and amassed
on a grand public scale, one had failed. As capitalism exploded,
Americans began grappling with how to process failure in a society
that held that the individual made his fortunes or broke them. The
notion of treating failure as a bump on the road to success _ still
very much evident today in self-help books with titles like
``Failure: The Back Door to Success'' _ began to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1920s, the decade when the president proclaimed that
``the business of America is business,'' a little homily called
``The Failure'' circulated in popular magazines, Merrill Peterson
writes in ``Lincoln in American Memory.'' It recounted the defeats
Abraham Lincoln had suffered and concluded: ``How would you stand
in the face of such setbacks? Think it over!''
</P>
<P>
   The list of Lincoln's failures continues to circulate today,
most often in advice columns and motivational seminars. That it
happens to be somewhat inaccurate _ some of the defeats on the list
are exaggerated or did not happen at all _ has done little to
diminish its appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lincoln list'' embodies one of the most potent images in
American life, one found in politics, Hollywood and certainly
sports: the comeback. At its heart the comeback is nothing more
than failing, then rising from the ashes, with victory sweetened by
the defeat that preceded it.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a culture we are very forgiving of failure,'' said Steven
Biel, a professor of history and literature at Harvard, ``but
failure has to be one moment in a larger narrative where success is
secured.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Biel, the author of ``Down With the Old Canoe,'' a history of
cultural attitudes toward the Titanic, notes that when the ship
sank in 1912, ``everyone who looked at it tried to turn it into a
story of redemption _ pulling success out of the jaws of failure.''
The fact that women and children were saved first, he said, was
instantly spun as an example of American male chivalry.
</P>
<P>
   Such public and political efforts to transform grand national
failures into a narrative of triumph are not uncommon. Consider the
speech William Safire composed for President Nixon in 1969 in case
the men who landed on the moon had to be abandoned there. It would
have been a disastrous failure, but in Safire's vision, it became a
triumph of American character. ``Others will follow, and surely
find their way home,'' the speech read. ``Man's search will not be
denied.''
</P>
<P>
   ``American political culture has not changed,'' Biel said. ``It
is hard to envision any national figure not returning to the
rhetoric of progress _ that failure is part of the American
narrative of destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the turns of history have forced Americans occasionally
to adjust their attitudes toward failure. During the Depression,
for instance, failure became so widespread that blame shifted
somewhat from the individual to the system. The same is true, to a
lesser degree, of the wave of downsizing earlier this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Such larger phenomena may briefly elicit more public compassion.
But perhaps the gentlest and certainly most honest treatment of
failure comes in literature. As Willy Loman, perhaps the archetype
of American failure puts it, ``A man can't go out the way he came
in, Ben, he has got to add up to something.'' Robert Polito, the
biographer of the crime novelist Jim Thompson, calls failure ``one
of the great subjects of American fiction'' _ perhaps the great
subject. From Herman Melville's ``Pierre,'' to Hurstwood in
``Sister Carrie,'' who descends from prosperity to a Bowery
flophouse, to Dick Diver disappearing into smaller and smaller
towns at the end of F. Scott Fitzgerald's ``Tender Is the Night'' _
the list of fictional failures is endless. Often, Polito notes,
they are exploring the burdens placed on the psyche by the enormous
expectations of success in America.
</P>
<P>
   In most of these books the failures are men, and Sandage said
his research also reveals failure as a masculine category. ``People
don't fail unless they are supposed to succeed,'' he said, and in
the 19th century and much of the 20th success was the province of
white men.
</P>
<P>
   But Andrew Delbanco, a professor of the humanities at Columbia
University, notes that women, particularly in the 19th century, had
their own kind of failure to deal with: whether they married and,
in a certain social milieu, married well. Again, literature tells
the story: Lily Bart in Edith Wharton's ``House of Mirth,'' for
example, blows her chance to make a good match and is consigned to
poverty and ultimately death.
</P>
<P>
   Each subculture in American life _ whether gender or region,
profession or class _ seems to have its own code of failure: what
kinds are acceptable? How to treat those who fail. What rules about
failure will protect the status of the subculture and its members?
Where Silicon Valley exalts failure, Wall Street punishes it
ruthlessly, observes Michael Lewis, who is about to publish a book
on cyberspace entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can't be seen giving money to someone who has proven
inept with money,'' he said. On Wall Street, to readmit a failure
would suggest that the whole business is a crapshoot, based as much
on luck as skill.
</P>
<P>
   Among the underclass, conversely, failure has become normalized.
Sociologists like William Julius Wilson have devoted a sizable
portion of their work trying to establish why the ``achievement
ethic,'' the hunger for traditional notions of success, has not
permeated the inner city, or how structural forces grease the path
toward failure.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is politics, which Lewis, who spent the 1996
presidential campaign mostly with candidates who failed, calls one
of the few fields in American life with room for ``noble failure''
_ the principled and damned quest, waged by men like Ralph Nader or
John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   But even principle does not necessarily make defeat palatable.
Lewis said that he wanted to title his last book, on the 1996
presidential campaign, ``Losers,'' but his publisher refused. Lewis
said he was told there is no market in America for failure.
</P>
</TEXT>
