<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4593 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-BROWNS21-COX     08-20 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BROWNS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Browns ready for new season
 &HT;    By Bob Batz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Two months after he helped resurrect one of
America's most vociferous sports fan clubs at a goat farmers'
amphitheater near Versailles, Glen Foutz has a message for
Dayton-area pro football buffs: The Cleveland Browns are baa-ck.
</P>
<P>
   The 48-year-old Foutz, who grew up thrilling to the gridiron
exploits of Cleveland's Jim Brown and others on a small-screen,
black-and-white television set, is president of the Miami Valley
Browns Backers Inc.
</P>
<P>
   He and other Browns fans will be keyed up tonight as their team
plays its first game in the $283 million, 72,000-seat Cleveland
Browns Stadium. The preseason game against Minnesota is the first
NFL game in Cleveland since Dec. 17, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   This was already shaping up as a good year for the Piqua-based
Browns Backers chapter long before the Browns resumed play with a
20-17 preseason victory over the Dallas Cowboys on Aug. 9, after a
44-month hiatus that began when the original team was moved to
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though membership in Cleveland Browns fan clubs worldwide
is still down considerably from what it was before the team left
Cleveland, we're absolutely booming,'' Foutz says. ``We have 1,100
card-carrying members, which makes us the largest Browns Backers
chapter in Ohio, and one of the biggest in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   Foutz concedes, however, that the increased participation this
year may have something to do with the fact that the club isn't
charging a membership fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of our records were lost after the team went to
Baltimore,'' he explains. ``When we decided to put the fan club
together again, Browns officials suggested we make membership free
the first year so we wouldn't be charging some people twice for
joining the organization. When we resume collecting dues, they will
be $10 a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio has dozens of Browns fan clubs, including two in Dayton _
the Browns Backers of Greater Dayton and the Northwest Browns
Backers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team deserves much of the credit for the success of the
clubs because it is the only National Football League team that
employs a coordinator of fan clubs,'' Foutz says. ``Her name is
Krystal Thomas, and she is very helpful to us.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the latest get-togethers for members of the Miami Valley
Browns Backers Inc. was an Aug. 7 dance at the End Zone Sports Bar
in Covington. About 200 men and women shelled out five bucks a pop
each to take a few twirls around the dance floor and have a chance
to receive one of 138 game tickets the team set aside for members
of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Browns reserved 600 tickets for Browns Backers chapters
and we got 138 because we are a large club,'' Foutz says. ``Ours
are for the Nov. 7 Baltimore Ravens game. Each of the winners will
pay $30 for the ticket, and an additional $30 to cover the cost of
bus trip to Cleveland. We'll be taking at least three buses.''
</P>
<P>
   The turnout at the Covington watering hole was a pretty typical
one for the Piqua chapter, according to Foutz.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a nice mix of people,'' he says. ``Men and women _
the women call themselves ``Dawgettes'' _ and families, too. There
are rich people and poor people. Old people and young people.
Professionals and blue-collar workers. Many of them came to the
dance displaying the orange and brown colors of the team. They wore
T-shirts and hard hats and Browns bandannas. Nobody showed up with
face paint on, but I'm sure that'll come later.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days after the dance _ the night the Browns opened the
pre-season against the Cowboys in Canton's Fawcett Stadium _
members of the Piqua chapter gathered at The End Zone Lounge and
Slammer's Nightclub Inc. in Versailles to watch the game on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Lonnie Subler, owner of Slammer's, characterizes Browns Backers
as ``a rowdy bunch.'' Then he adds: ``They're beer drinkers . . .
and good people.''
</P>
<P>
   Foutz says Browns Backers come from all walks of life and then
offers a story to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the members of the chapter in Bowling Green is a
Catholic priest,'' he says. ``He wears his Browns stuff under his
robes so he can head for the game as soon as Mass is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Dayton's two BB chapters present contrasting images.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns Backers of Greater Dayton, founded in 1986, has about
500 members and is growing every day, says 46-year-old Mike
McDonald, a trustee for the chapter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had more than 1,100 members before the team left Cleveland,
but we're coming back,'' he says. ``The night the Browns played the
Cowboys, more than 300 of us watched the game at Wallaby's in
Beavercreek and we signed up 50 new members. Our dues are $20 a
year.''
</P>
<P>
   The next task for the chapter _ which has a new logo featuring a
Cleveland Browns helmet with Dayton's skyline in the background _
is to dispense 80 tickets for the Nov. 28 Browns-Tennessee Titans
game. The chapter's next business meeting is at 7 p.m. Aug. 30 at
VFW Post 9927 at Wilmington Pike and Marshall Road in Kettering.
</P>
<P>
   As McDonald watches membership mushroom in his chapter, Donald
Holmes, president of the 11-year-old Northwest Dayton Browns
Backers, talks of breathing new life into his organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now were trying to rebuild our membership,'' says
Holmes, who describes himself as a Browns fan since birth. ``We
currently have 28 members because everybody kind of took a little
vacation when the team left Cleveland. Now we're going to start
recruiting new ones.'' The chapter's dues are aren't determined
yet.
</P>
<P>
   Foutz remembers his first Browns Backers meeting of the year _
the BYOB session at the amphitheater built by goat farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pro football draft was over, so we knew what players were
on board by the time we had that meeting,'' he says. ``You could
tell that night that enthusiasm for the team was running very high
. . . and the excitement has been been building ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   Club members aren't expecting any miracles from the Browns this
year. Not major miracles, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's looking for a Super Bowl win right out of the
chute,'' Foutz says. ``If we go 8-8, we'll be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he points to the license plate on his sport utility
vehicle. It is GO BROWN.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state wouldn't let me add an `s' to it, but I still think
it looks pretty good,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
