<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4599 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH21-COX     08-20 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Questions of Bush's drug use level off during his second day in
Ohio
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AKRON, Ohio _ As days go on the often rugged presidential
campaign trail, Friday turned out to be much happier for Texas Gov.
George W. Bush than Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   After being verbally pummeled by reporters Thursday with
questions about whether he used illegal drugs years ago, Bush, 53,
faced relatively gentle queries Friday in Akron, and then received
a hero's welcome at a $1,000-a-person fund-raiser from supporters
who showered him with $365,000 in campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with the $300,000 Bush raised Thursday night at the
suburban Columbus home of Les Wexner, chairman of The Limited
Stores Inc., Bush raised $1,665,000 in less than a month in Ohio.
The first $1 million came at a July 22 event in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm going to be the next president of the United
States and I thank you for getting on my team,'' Bush said as
applause filled the ballroom at the Hilton Fairlawn Hotel just
outside Akron.
</P>
<P>
   As Ohio Democratic Chairman David Leland noted, Bush,
accompanied to Akron by Gov. Bob Taft, may have been getting a
little ahead of himself as he warmed to the partisan crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush has been lulled into a false sense of security,'' Leland
said. ``The Republicans have given him the nomination before a
single vote has been cast. Soon he'll find out we don't elect
presidents that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bush supporters said they believed the Texas governor has
emerged relatively unscathed from the frenzy of questioning about
possible illegal drug use, although the issue could come up again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The press is trying to find something. ... He'll survive
this,'' said U.S. Rep. Ralph Regula (R-Navarre), dean of the Ohio
congressional delegation.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Bush said in Roanoke, Va. that, in effect, he had
not used illegal drugs since at least 1974, 25 years ago. Once he
got to Ohio, he declined to repeat this but stuck to a statement he
reiterated Friday:
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the American people that years ago I made some
mistakes. I've learned from my mistakes. Should I be fortunate
enough to become president, I will bring dignity and honor to the
office.''
</P>
<P>
   His comments came before the fund-raiser, just after he toured
the Haven of Rest Ministries mission in downtown Akron. He cited
the mission, which provides shelter and training to the poor,
homeless and people with substance-abuse problems, as the kind of
faith-based organization that Americans should rely on to solve the
nation's problems.
</P>
<P>
   Promoting such groups is a key part of Bush's campaign. ``I
believe as we had to the 21st century, it's important to
reinvigorate faith-based organizations that help people change
their lives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush deflected a question about whether he had been
straightforward with his 17-year-old twin daughters about his past
use of alcohol and possibly drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate your question, but I'm going to leave my
daughters out of the campaign,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   He added, however, that members of his generation have a special
obligation to today's young people.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the interesting questions facing baby boomers is have
we grown up? Are we willing to share the wisdom of past mistakes. I
think the message ought to be to our children, `Don't use drugs,
don't abuse alcohol.' That's what leadership is about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he'd learned from the vigorous questioning of the
past two days, Bush said:
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned that sometimes politics can be unnecessarily ugly
and I'm trying to purge the system of ugly politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that he plans to return to Ohio frequently before the
March 7 primary and, if he gets the Republican nomination, before
the general election.
</P>
<P>
   He said he expects the fight for the nomination to be over by
March 7 when California, New York and several other states also
hold primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the general election, (Ohio) is always a bellwether state,
a swing state. I try to remember the '88 campaign and not the '92
campaign,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   His father, George Bush, won Ohio in 1988 when he was elected
president, but lost the state and the presidency in 1992 to Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
