<HEADLINE>
GPS SATELLITE RESET COULD CAUSE CONFUSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER ZEIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   People who rely on the global satellite system called GPS to
help them navigate will be closely watching the network Saturday
night as it resets itself, possibly throwing millions of electronic
direction-finders out of whack.
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K-like bug could cause just a technological hiccup, or it
could result in thousands of pilots, boaters, and even Japanese
drivers, to become temporarily lost.
</P>
<P>
   The network of 27 earth orbiting satellites used to aid
navigation for the military, businesses and individuals, was
programmed in 1980 with a calendar of just 1,024 weeks. At 13
seconds before 8 pm EST Saturday, that calendar will expire and the
system will reset to week one.
</P>
<P>
   The government says the satellites are prepared for this ``end
of week rollover,'' and will continue to transmit an accurate
signal. But just how the Global Positioning System receivers
interpret the epoch moment is a matter of some debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has the potential to be a major problem as in Y2K, but we
don't expect it to be,'' said Bill Schmidt of the Boston Coast
Guard, Aids and Navigation department.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt predicts there may be a second's lapse while receiving
the signal, but then the system should quickly reset itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get people to go to their manufacturers,''
Schmidt said, adding the older models are the issue. He also
advised that mariners not rely on the GPS as their only form of
locator.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the manufacturers of GPS receivers, including Lowrance
Electronics, Garmin and Magellan GPS systems have posted
reassurances on their Internet sites, telling customers that all of
their newer models are end-of-week rollover compliant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any prudent mariner that's out there that has any inkling of
sense will have more than one mode of navigation,'' Schmidt said.
Long Range Navigation, Type C and other traditional visual
navigation are two types of backup.
</P>
<P>
   The GPS receivers determine location via latitude, longtitude,
and _ with planes _ altitude by triangulating signals from at least
four of 27 satellites that orbit the Earth every 12 hours. GPS was
solely a military system until about 10 years ago, when a separate
signal was released to civilians. The civilian signal contains a
built-in random error to thwart terrorist groups from finding exact
locations of important landmarks or military installations.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, handheld and dashboard-mounted GPS receivers
have become popular ``techno-toys'' for everyone from general
aviation pilots, weekend boaters, and even big business. Federal
Express, for example, uses the signal to track the status of
shipped packages and relay them to customers via their website.
FedEx claims they aren't shaken by the rollover, but will switch to
a private satellite system, just in case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel confident that there will be no problems with the
receivers; we've been on top of this for some time,'' said Darlene
Faquin, a spokeswoman for Federal Express.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, where GPS-equipped automobiles have become
commonplace, drivers rely on the network as their only indicator to
navigate the country's unmarked streets. Drivers with navigation
systems made before 1997 have been told to check with their
manufacturers for reset instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Poossible problems include receivers that appear to be working
but display inaccurate positions, times, or dates, like displaying
Jan. 5 or Jan. 6, 1980, or receivers that fail to locate the
satellite signal, according to Ronea Alger, chief of media
relations at the Los Angeles Air Force base.
</P>
<P>
   Master Chief Petty Officer Rick Hamilton of the Coast Guard
Navigation Center in Alexandria, VA, said there's no top-secret
reason why the system was programmed with a limited calendar.
Programmers ``just drew a line,'' he said. ``It was probably just
an oversight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard, the government liasion to the civil sector for
GPS, refines signals from an accuracy of 100 meters to a more
precise 10 meters, is using this weekend as a test for the upcoming
rollover into the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Jan. 1, possibly unrecognizable leap-year dates
February 28 to February 29, 2000, may also be problematic along
with Sept. 9, 1999 (9/9/99) which the system may read as a purge
command.
</P>
<P>
   The Guard has set up checkpoint times one half hour before and
after the rollover for Coast Guard ships and planes, asking pilots
to double check time and location accuracy and call in any
problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
