<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-ALPHA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ DROPS ALPHA-WINDOWS 2000 PROJECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Compaq Computer Corp. is giving up on efforts to make its
powerful Alpha processor chips compatible with Windows 2000, the
next version of Microsoft Corp.'s Windows NT operating system.
Compaq says it has disbanded the 100-person team working on the
project and that some of them will likely be laid off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not plan to support 32-bit Windows 2000 on Alpha
systems,'' said Compaq spokesman Jim Finlaw. But he added that
Compaq is still committed to a future version of Windows 2000 that
will be customized to take advantage of the special design of the
Alpha chip. Meanwhile, Compaq will concentrate on selling
Alpha-based machines that run the Unix and Linux operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Bradshaw, a spokesman for Alpha Processor Inc., a Concord
firm jointly owned by Compaq and the Korean electronics firm
Samsung, said that the Alpha has a bright future despite the policy
shift. ``Less than 5 percent of the business that we see now comes
from the NT space,'' Bradshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Shannon, author of the industry newsletter Shannon Knows
Compaq, said that demand for high-end computers using Alpha
processors is actually on the rise, but few Alpha customers want to
use Windows NT. ``There are now over half a million Alpha platforms
out there,'' said Shannon. ``My guess is Alpha NT represents maybe
15 percent, perhaps less, of that total.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that Alpha wasn't designed to run NT in its
current form. The chip was developed in the early 1990s by
engineers at Maynard-based Digital Equipment Corp., before it was
acquired by Compaq. Alpha chips consistently have been faster and
more powerful than the popular Pentium series of processors from
Intel Corp. This is partly because the Alpha was designed to
process 64 bits of data at a time. Pentium chips can only handle 32
bits at a time.
</P>
<P>
   But the chip's 64-bit design is incompatible with Microsoft's
32-bit Windows operating systems, including Windows NT, a version
intended for business use. Alpha chips can run Windows software by
using a special program, but this method causes the Alpha to run
slower, thus reducing its speed advantage over the Pentium. The
ultimate solution would be to develop a 64-bit version of Windows.
Microsoft has been working on such a product to run not only on
Alpha but also on Merced, an upcoming 64-bit chip to be produced by
Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Most Alpha users run some version of the Unix operating system.
Unix is widely used for high-end corporate computing because it's
considered more reliable than Windows NT. Compaq already has a
version of Unix that takes full advantage of the Alpha chip's
64-bit design. In addition, many Alpha users rely on a 64-bit
version of the Linux operating system, which is available at low
cost from firms such as Red Hat Software Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Dube, an industry analyst with Wasserstein Perella
Securities in New York, said that Compaq's move signals a retreat
from Windows NT, not from the Alpha chip. ``NT has not really made
the big breakthrough,'' said Dube. ``It is not the elixir of love
everyone thought it would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft this year will introduce Windows 2000, a version of NT
that is supposed to be reliable enough for use at the highest level
of large businesses. But Dube said that many high-end users remain
skeptical that any Windows operating system will be trustworthy
enough for mission-critical jobs. These users are sticking with
Unix-based systems, for which Alpha is already well suited.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
