<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-JOBS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE JOBLESSNESS UP SLIGHTLY IN JULY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Massachusetts continued to add jobs in July, but a
rush of new workers entering the labor force nudged the state's
unemployment rate up slightly to 3.2 percent, the state Division of
Employment and Training said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The number of state residents with jobs rose by 3,100 during the
month. But at the same time 9,000 people decided to go looking for
work _ the largest one month expansion in the labor force since
December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The jump in the number of job seekers caused 5,900 more people
to report unemployment, pushing the monthly rate up from 3 percent
in June, the division said.
</P>
<P>
   The rise is so small that it's statistically insignificant,
economists said. And every sector of the economy except
manufacturing added jobs from the same time a year ago, with the
biggest gains coming at restaurants and retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   Still, while Massacusetts unemployment remains a full percentage
point below the national rate of 4.3 percent, economists said it is
slightly worrisome that the state added jobs at a rate of just 1.3
percent since last July. That's a more sluggish rate than the
nation, which showed 2.3 percent growth during the same period.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could be a sign of some slowing,'' said Nicholas Perna,
chief economist for Fleet Financial Group. ``Is it a cause for
concern? Probably not a huge one. It's still a very ebulient
economy. When you put everything together, it still smells pretty
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Massachusetts' slower job growth since last July, the
state figures show more than three-quarters of the gains came in
the last six months, suggesting the slowdown may have been
temporary.
</P>
<P>
   In July, jobs were most plentiful at the state's restaurants and
retail stores, which had 4,900 new positions. By far, that was the
biggest job addition of any sector during the month. Construction
added 200 jobs, manufacturing added 700, services accounted for
1,300 and there were 400 more in finance, insurance and real
estate.
</P>
<P>
   Since the same time a year ago, the period most economists use
to gauge trends, retail added 13,800 jobs in Massachusetts, a gain
of 2.5 percent. Construction showed an increase of 6,500 jobs, or 6
percent, though that rate has slowed significantly in recent
months. Jobs in finance, real estate and insurance climbed 4,600,
or 2.1 percent, and services showed an increase of 27,600, or 2.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs in manufacturing, meanwhile _ still suffering the lingering
effects of a sluggish world economy and the Asian financial
collapse _ dropped by 14,700, or 3.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In July, manufacturing jobs grew for the first time in a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early to know whether the July numbers for this
sector represent a change in the trend,'' the employment division
said in its report. ``However some manufacturing industries are
showing over-the-year increases,'' suggesting long-term
improvements may be in store.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
