<SLUG> BC-LIONBRIDGE-IPO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIONBRIDGE IPO FALLS $20 MILLION SHORT OF GOAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lionbridge Technologies Inc., formed as a 1996 management buyout
of a money-losing company once owned by R. R. Donnelley &AMP; Sons, the
Chicago printing firm, raised nearly $36.32 million in an initial
public offering Friday _ more than $20 million less than expected.
</P>
<P>
   The IPO ended Friday with the Lionbridge stock climbing 2 5/8
points points to close at 12 5/8 on the Nasdaq exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Based in Waltham, Mass., Lionbridge provides foreign language
versions of software publishers and computer hardware makers'
software, documentation, Internet support, and marketing
literature.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which employs 447 people, sold 3.6 million shares
at $10 each. That total is below the company's original goal,
announced in June, when it hoped to raise as much as $57.5 million
by selling more than 4.2 million shares priced between $12 and $14
a share.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to lower the price and reduce the volume of shares
sold was due to ``the market of late being softer than the
underwriters had anticipated,'' said Steven Lifshatz, Lionbridge's
chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street's concerns about higher interest rates, a widening
of the US trade deficit in June, and a weak dollar that has
heightened inflation worries, coupled with August market doldrums,
has led to an overall shaky market for IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   Lifshatz said Lionbridge _ among three Massachusetts firms that
planned to lauch their IPOs this week _ waited until the last
minute, acknowledging that ``the later you get in August, the more
challenging it is.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast another Waltham company, SilverStream Software Inc.,
had a more successful IPO earlier this week, selling sell 3 million
shares at 16 each, exceeding the expected range of 13 to 15. It
raised $48 million before underwriting fees. On Tuesday, the first
day of trading, the young company's stock soared to more than 39 a
share before closing at 31 1/2. Since then the shares have slid
down, closing Friday at 24 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company has shown strong growth and an impressive list of
large customers,'' said Paul Bard, an analyst at Renaissance
Capital Corp. in Greenwich, Conn. which runs a fund that invests in
IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts said telecommunications equipment companies and
software developers focused on the Internet infrastructure fared
better this week. SilverStream provides software to integrate
on-line software for corporate computer networks and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Agile Software Corp. of San Jose, Calif., which helps
clients use the Internet to coordinate manufacturing processes,
rose 90 percent on its first day of trading Friday, closing at 39
7/8, up 18 7/8. Agile competes against Parametric Technology Corp.
of Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   And while Lionbridge and SilverStream launched their IPO, a
third firm, HarvardNet, which provides Internet access and data
communications services, postponed its Wall Street debut. The
Boston-based company is looking to raise $124 milion by selling 8.9
million shares initially priced at between 13 and 15 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Lionbridge with a client list including IBM in France and Sun
Microsystems Inc. in China, was not alone in reducing its IPO share
price this week. On Thursday, New York-based LaBranche &AMP; Co., the
third largest floor trading firm operating in the New York Stock
Exchange, reduced its IPO to 14 a share, from 15 to 17 a share. The
result: the stock closed Thursday at 14 1/2 dipping on Friday to 14
1/16.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
