<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG SIXTH IN VERMONT MOUNTAIN BIKE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST DOVER, Vt. _ Lance Armstrong won the World Championship
Road Race in 1993, and he won the Tour de France earlier this
summer. So how did Friday's mountain bike race compare?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the hardest two hours of bike racing,'' said Armstrong,
rubbing his cramped legs after the race.
</P>
<P>
   Roland Green, of Victoria, British Columbia, finished the
22.8-mile race first in 2 hour 12 minutes; while Travis Brown of
Boulder, Colo., came in 48 seconds behind to win the national
mountain bike championship. Brown also won the Chevy Trucks NORBA
(National Off-Road Bicycle Association) series of six races.
</P>
<P>
   But Armstrong was no slouch as he rode in second place for part
of the race and finished sixth, 3:27 behind Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of respect for these guys,'' said Armstrong.
``Nothing in the Tour de France compares to this.''
</P>
<P>
   The 82 riders kicked up a cloud of dust as they sped away from
the starting line on the dirt road at the base of the Mount Snow
ski area. Then, as chair lifts _ some empty, some filled with
mountain bikes, some filled with spectators _ went up and down the
mountain, the riders traversed the course on their 18- or 27-speed
bikes. The cyclists went over tree roots, stumps, and rocks on the
course that climbed almost 2,000 feet each lap, and averaged 11.4
miles per hour as they covered the 3.8-mile circuit six times.
</P>
<P>
   Green, 25, who notched his first win of the year, said he didn't
even know he was leading most of the way. Riders don't bunches up
but get strung out in a line as they battle the course more than
each other _ which is why Green was impressed with Armstrong's
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fittest cyclist in the world can't just just come here and
win,'' Green said. ``You have to have the ability to handle a bike
on bumpy terrain, and I think it's a testament to just how
difficult the sport is.''
</P>
<P>
   He got no argument from Armstrong, who didn't excel in the
mountains Friday as he did in the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone thought I would lose time on the downhills, but the
second half of the race I was losing time on the uphills,'' said
Armstrong, a 27-year-old native of Austin, Texas. ``I don't have
the fitness on a course like that, it's undulating and always up
and down.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who rides on the same Trek/Volkswagen team that sponsors
Armstrong, said he surged ahead of Armstrong on the last lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in the lead and said, `Go T,' when I went past,'' Brown
said. ``I don't know if he was fading or did that on purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably a little of both, since Armstrong said that ``the first
half was sort of fun, but the second half wasn't fun at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said he didn't set a goal before the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I had no specific objective,'' he said. ``I wanted to try
and finish, I wanted to start well and see how it went.''
</P>
<P>
   It went very well.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Alison Dunlap, of Colorado Springs, Colo.,
won the women'a national championship and the Chevy Trucks series
championship in 1:45 over four laps of the 3.8-mile circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap, who won a gold medal in the mountain bike race at the
Pan Am Games earlier this month, divides her time between mountain
bike racing and road racing, and is hoping to go the Olympics next
year to compete in both categories. She was also cylco-cross
national champion for the past two years, including last year's win
at Devens, Mass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 1934EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
