<P>
   JAPAN-BANKS (Tokyo) _ Japan signals the start of a far-reaching
consolidation of its bloated and debt-ridden banking system with
official word that three of the country's biggest banks will unite
to form the world's largest financial institution. The merger
agreement announced by Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank Ltd., the Industrial
Bank of Japan Ltd. and Fuji Bank Ltd. is viewed by economists as a
significant change, not because of the combination's colossal size,
but because they say it will hasten mergers among other banks,
helping to reduce what has been one of the biggest drags on the
Japanese economy. By Calvin Sims. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m.
ET in ``f'' news file.) 1,200 words.
