<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA LEONE: LARGER U.N. PRESENCE
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Security Council has tripled the number of military
observers in Sierra Leone, to 210, and urged that the country move
quickly to begin putting a July 7 peace accord into effect. The
accord has been criticized because of the amnesty it grants to
rebel fighters responsible for the deaths and mutilation of
thousands of people. Peter Burleigh, the United States
representative on the council, said Washington is committed to
prosecuting war criminals, and views the accord as ``the best
guarantee for an end to the immense suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: TOURIST WAVE
</P>
<P>
   Britain recorded a record 11.8 million overseas visitors
spending an estimated $9 billion in the first half of 1999,
according to the Office of National Statistics. Some 2.2 million
came from the United States and Canada, a 7 percent rise that more
than compensated for a 1 percent drop in the number from Western
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: MURDER EXTRADITION
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has extradited a Mexican citizen, Luis Enrique Arenas
Hernandez, to face charges in an Arizona district court for the
murder on June 3, 1998, of a Border Patrol agent, Alexander
Kirprik. Arenas is charged with shooting the agent, who caught him
smuggling marijuana across the border.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: U.N. HARASSMENT RULING
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Development Program in Islamabad said it had dismissed
a senior official for sexual harassment after a disciplinary panel
ruled that the administrator ``created an intimidating, hostile and
offensive work environment.'' Dismissals on grounds of sexual
harassment have been rare in the U.N. system, in part because of
questions of cultural differences. The United Nations did not
identify the official, but employees familiar with the case said he
was a Pakistani.
</P>
</TEXT>
