<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRESHMEN-PARENTS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRESHMEN ORIENTATION FOR PARENTS SHOWS REALITIES OF CAMPUS LIFE
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds., this story was filed on Aug. 16, and HELD; it is now
released for publication. Please be sure to use this version. In
addition, this story is now on NYT P.1) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(ms) 
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADISON, Wis. _ Having bid occasionally tearful good-byes to
their loved ones, the 160 newcomers to the lakeside university
campus here pasted on their nametags and embarked on a two-day
introduction to college life.
</P>
<P>
   At times it was like boot camp, especially when a sergeant from
the university police, a 9mm pistol on his belt, informed them of
the first-time penalty for underage drinking: a $209 fine and a
90-day suspended driver's license.
</P>
<P>
   At other times it was like group therapy, as when a dean who
exuded all the comfort of a home-cooked meal, assured them that it
was painful to separate from those who had shared a roof with them
for so many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big leap from high school to the University of
Wisconsin, Madison,'' Sheila Spear, the dean of students, told
them, describing a campus of 40,000 inhabitants. ``It's like moving
from the farm leagues to the major leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   But none in this crowd would be graduating with the class of
2003: they were all parents, and at the moment, it was their
transition, and their jitters, that were of utmost concern.
</P>
<P>
   In a scene that has been repeated hundreds of times on dozens of
campuses across the country this summer, administrators have been
gathering the parents of incoming freshmen to gird them for the
looking-glass journey on which they and their families are about to
embark.
</P>
<P>
   While orientations for the freshmen themselves, especially
Outward-Bound-style bonding missions set in the woods, have been
fixtures at colleges for more than a decade, the systematic
immersion of parents is a relatively recent development.
</P>
<P>
   Though no one has undertaken a precise tally, Cherry Callahan,
the former president of the National Association of Student
Personnel Administrators, estimates that dozens, and likely
hundreds, of the nation's 2,200 four-year colleges have added or
substantially expanded parent orientation programs only in the last
few years.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose is plain: to enlist parents as coaches to prod their
students to greatness; to ply them with information about their
children's new lives, and to address the parents' own
roller-coaster emotions as they prepare to break away from their
companions of the last 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   At Bemidji State University, a school of 4,000 students in
northern Minnesota, parents are sent a homework assignment in
advance of their orientation: a 43-page script that instructs them
how to talk to their children about the odyssey at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time that you deem appropriate, approach your student
with the following questions,'' the manual advises, suggesting, as
an ice-breaker, ``What can I (we) do as a parent(s) to assist you
with the process of adjusting to college life.''
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Alabama's orientation, parents of freshmen
are told to call a toll-free hotline installed just for them in the
dean's office. There, they can find a sympathetic voice _ someone
willing, if pressed hard enough, to track down a student to upbraid
him for not calling home as often as his mother would like.
</P>
<P>
   At MacAlester College in Saint Paul, Minn., the parent
orientation includes a component lifted from an elementary school
open house: before their students even take a test, the parents
spend a day running through their children's course schedule, which
entails sitting in their child's seat, meeting his professors and
listening to sample lectures.
</P>
<P>
   If all this sounds like a grand scheme designed partly to coddle
baby boomers _ many of them raised on Dr. Spock, weaned from their
own parents on an analyst's couch and now confronted with the
daunting prospect of becoming college parents themselves _ then
that's hardly accidental, says Ms. Callahan, the associate vice
chancellor for student affairs at the University of North Carolina
Greensboro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my parents never talked about their feelings very
much, particularly my father, before I went to college,'' said Ms.
Callahan, 50, who graduated from Greensboro in 1971. ``This is a
generation, the baby boomers, that is more open than their parents
were in talking with their children about life experience, social
issues and what may lie ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``They also want to know what they're getting for
their money.''
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Wisconsin, almost all of the 5,700 incoming
freshmen had at least one parent accept the university's invitation
to spend two days on campus in July and August.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 160 parents in the last of 33 orientation groups, on
Aug. 10 and 11, said they paid the $40 parent orientation fee
because the university emphasized the program's value, because they
wanted a better understanding of what their children were going
through or because they were seeking ways to wrestle with their own
emotions.
</P>
<P>
   Her eyes red from crying, Tama Schmidt, 38, who had dropped out
of college in 1981 to raise her daughter Taylor, described how she
had been readying herself for Taylor's expected departure for
Madison on Sept. 1: each night the two have been watching a
different ``weepy mother-daughter movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Mrs. Schmidt had managed to get through ``Terms of
Endearment'' without choking up, she did not fare as well during
``Steel Magnolias.''
</P>
<P>
   The four-hour drive from New Richmond, Wis., to Madison had
offered little respite, with Mrs. Schmidt's mind replaying a
virtual highlight reel of her daughter's life, from birth to her
selection last year as ``Miss New Richmond.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest fear,'' said Mrs. Schmidt, a purchasing agent, ``is
that she's not going to be under my roof every night of the week
and I'm not going to know what she's up to.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Woods, 57, an architect from Milwaukee, arrived at the
orientation sweating, and covered with hay. He had spent the day
getting his daughter's thoroughbred _ she jumps competitively _
settled in a nearby stable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave him food when he got here and he met another horse so
he was happy,'' Woods said. ``He probably has a bigger stall than
she has a room.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods said he grew mournful when he realized that, for the first
time in a decade, he and his daughter, Jennifer, 18, ``aren't going
to spend time in the barn together.'' But he said he was also
relishing the prospect of free time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to get reaquainted with my wife,'' Woods said.
``Need I say more.''
</P>
<P>
   His daughter quickly interjected: ``I don't need to hear this.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
