<HEADER>
A4619 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-FRESHMEN-PARENTS-ART-     08-20 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRESHMEN-PARENTS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 
MADISON, Wis.: hear this.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   After dining with their daughters for the first session of the
orientation, Mrs. Schmidt and Woods were then separated from their
children for the balance of the program. While the students picked
their courses with their academic advisers, their parents were
sequestered across campus, their every concern addressed in
lectures and question-and-answer forums that went far deeper, in
time and substance, than the more social parent visiting weekends
that universities have hosted for generations.
</P>
<P>
   The parents were reminded, yet again, how much lighter their
wallets would be: the average cost of tuition and room-and-board
would be $8,987.70 for state residents, and $18,301.70 for others,
with checks due Oct. 1. They were told, to their surprise, that
that price included sheets, blankets and pillowcases, to be
laundered by the university each week if the students desired. (The
parents certainly liked the idea of guaranteed clean linens.)
</P>
<P>
   And they were warned that, should their children require
hospitalization, there would likely be gaps between the basic
medical coverage provided by the university and their own policies,
many of which cover college-age children. (A hypothetical anecdote
about a freshman breaking an arm after her bike got caught in
railroad tracks caused shudders.)
</P>
<P>
   But the speaker who seemed to draw out the most anxieties was
Sgt. Kurt Feavel, of the University of Wisconsin Police, who
assured the audience that his employer was ``the real police,''
with full jurisdiction over the campus, including the authority to
arrest students on criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The date-rape drug, is it a problem,'' one parent asked, via
an index card submitted from the audience, about a substance that,
when dropped in alcohol, can make someone faint, and ultimately
forgetful. The sergeant responded that ``we fortunately don't have
that problem,'' adding that there had been only three suspected
instances of the drug's use on campus in the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   Another card demanded, ``Is it dangerous for women to walk alone
on campus at night?''
</P>
<P>
   Again, Feavel assured that ``we're fortunate we don't have a lot
of assaults on campus.'' Yet he directed the parents toward a
poster advertising a self-defense program in which ``your daughter
will learn verbal, physical and psychological techniques to protect
and defend herself on and off campus.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, the father of the equestrian, said the brochure had
convinced him to enroll his daughter because, ``if she's really
backed up against a wall,'' she needs the ability to ``strike out
if she has to.''
</P>
<P>
   For Mrs. Schmidt, the teary movie-watcher who had despaired over
not knowing her daughter's every coming and going during the
upcoming fall, the entire seminar had proven as spiritual as it was
informative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel better,'' she said. ``You go home feeling a little
more educated about what's going to happen in the next couple of
weeks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
