<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4628 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-NORWOOD21-COX     08-20 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORWOOD21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Norwood puts patients over party in push to pass bill
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just before leaving town earlier this month, Rep.
Charlie Norwood (R-Ga.) unveiled the latest incarnation of his
legislation that would overhaul the nation's managed health care
system.
</P>
<P>
   This time, no amount of pressure from Republican leaders could
stop the former dentist. This time, Norwood, a consistently
conservative voter, was willing to work with top Democrats in
defiance of his own party's leaders to bring his managed care bill
to the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move would place most politicians in a precarious
political spot. Defying the wishes of party leaders usually comes
at a price. Bills without the leadership's blessing tend to die
before they reach the House floor. And the lawmaker's actions are
often remembered when it comes time to divvy up the federal budget
for local roads, bridges and schools.
</P>
<P>
   But none of that appears to influence Norwood's decision making
_ at least on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather pass this bill than be a congressman any day of the
week,'' said Norwood. ``I guess I have to say I am more interested
in patients than I am in party.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind such bravado is the reality that the Republicans control
the House by only a five-vote margin. With a contentious
congressional election approaching next year, House Speaker Dennis
Hastert (R-Ill.) cannot afford to risk losing an otherwise loyal
Republican soldier like Norwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing they could do is defeat me and then get someone
who would vote for Gephardt for speaker. Why should you want to do
that?'' said Norwood, referring to Democratic Minority Leader
Richard Gephardt (D-Mo.), who has launched a fierce campaign to win
the House back in next fall's elections.
</P>
<P>
   And behind Norwood's tough talk is the reality that the
Democrats in his 10th District want to overhaul managed health
care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he realizes that the 10th District is largely
Democratic and he's listening to what his constituents want in the
district,'' said Ron Schoeffler, chairman of the Richmond County
Democratic Party. ``If he had gone with the Republican leadership,
he would have a tough election next year.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill that Norwood and Rep. John Dingell (D-Mich.), the
ranking Democrat of the Commerce Committee, drafted encompasses
most of what Norwood first proposed in 1995, then in 1997 and again
this year.
</P>
<P>
   It would allow patients to choose their own doctors, create an
external appeals process and allow patients to sue their health
plans in state courts. In addition, it increases access to
emergency rooms and it gives women and children the right to see
gynecologists and pediatricians, respectively, without a referral
from a primary care physician.
</P>
<P>
   The most controversial issue is allowing patients the right to
sue their health plans. Republican leaders are opposed to the
measure, saying it would increase insurance premiums and strip
millions of Americans of their health coverage. Business groups
such as the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and insurance companies are
trying to defeat the proposal when Congress returns next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation is built on the erroneous premise that trial
lawyers are the sole guardians of good medical care,'' said Karen
Ignagni, president and chief executive officer of the American
Association of Health Plans, a Washington-based organization that
represents more than 1,000 managed care plans.
</P>
<P>
   To support the claim that premiums would increase, Ignagni cites
a study by the Virginia-based Lewin Group that found that a 1
percent increase in premiums would cause 300,000 individuals to
lose their health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, patients can sue in federal court only for
the cost of treatment and legal expenses, but not for punitive
damages. The law, the Employee Retirement Income Security Act of
1974, created obstacles for patients to file lawsuits, in part,
because Congress wanted employers to create health insurance plans
without being exposed to costly lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the Republican leaders face an uphill battle to
defeat the the Norwood-Dingell measure. With support from 21
Republicans, including Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), and the conservative
branch of the Democratic Party, it would appear that Norwood and
Dingell have the votes to pass their bill.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton also appears poised to sign the legislation if
it passes the Senate. The Senate passed a limited managed care bill
in July, but it does not include the right to sue health plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republican leaders need to stop fighting bipartisan progress
and let managed care reform move forward,'' Clinton said at a
recent Democratic event on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert and other leaders have tried to bring Norwood back
inside their tent, but he won't budge. At this point, he is
frustrated with the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is, every time I get the ball to the 10-yard line,
the leadership moves the goal post. ... I'm through with that,''
Norwood said. ``I don't mind getting beat. I'm a big boy. If you
get beat, you get beat. But I do believe in a fair fight and it
hasn't been a fair fight.''
</P>
<P>
   For every word against Norwood's bill from the business
community, doctors and medical professionals have words of support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie Norwood is popular because he puts his patients
first,'' said Dr. James Davis, a radiologist at the University
Hospital in Augusta and the Columbia Augusta Regional Hospital.
``This isn't popular with the Republican leadership, but it's
popular with the people in the district both Democratic and
Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
