<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4632 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-LAW-BOS &LR;      08-20 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-LAW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS MAKE LAW HIGHEST BONUS PLAYER IN TEAM HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ The previous two times the Patriots paid huge
signing bonuses, they received little for their money. Since
receiving their $8 million bonuses, both defensive end Willie
McGinest and linebacker Ted Johnson have wound up missing
significant time due to injury.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots can ill afford one more curse of the signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Yet they took that plunge Friday with Ty Law, agreeing to a
seven-year, $50 million deal that includes a $14.2 million signing
bonus, the highest ever paid to a Patriot.
</P>
<P>
   It came on the eve of the Patriots' exhibition game against the
Dallas Cowboys and their extravagant owner, Jerry Jones, who has
certainly been a pioneer in signing bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   The deal surpasses Drew Bledsoe's 1995 contract of $42 million
over seven years, which included an $11 million signing bonus.
Bledsoe, who will likely have his deal renegotiated in the next
year, eventually will surpass Law. For now, though, Law and his
agents, Carl and Kevin Poston, consider him the second-highest-paid
cornerback behind Dallas's Deion Sanders, whose deal averages $10
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the job that goes on between us and agents is figuring
out what the other deals are. Sometimes there are deals and
sometimes there are smoke and mirrors. The good news for Ty is that
this is a real deal,'' said Patriots vice president Andy Wasynczuk.
</P>
<P>
   Law's deal is made up of what both sides call ``real money,''
meaning most of it is achievable. About $4 million spread out over
the life of the contract is tied in to making the Super Bowl and
the Pro Bowl, but at least $46 million is money that Law could earn
just by playing.
</P>
<P>
   NFL deals are structured so that a player gets a great deal of
money at the beginning and at the end, when the contract can
usually either be restructured or the player is released. Most NFL
contracts are not guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   The seventh year of the deal _ in 2006 _ is worth about $10.3
million. By signing Law, the Patriots will save about $600,000 in
salary cap money. Law's cap figure for 1999 was $3 million. That
will be reduced to $2.4 by restructuring the deal and factoring in
a minimum salary of $400,000 for '99 and the $14.2 million signing
bonus. The cap figure will escalate yearly. The middle five years
are worth about $5 million apiece to Law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the biggest contract in Patriots history. It's a special
contract, but we think we have a real special player,'' said
Wasynczuk.
</P>
<P>
   Law made the Pro Bowl for the first time in his career last
season, intercepting seven passes and showing dominance against the
opposing teams' top receivers. He also got national attention when
he picked off a pass and ran 67 yards for a touchdown in the Pro
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Law thanked Pete Carroll for being the first coach to allow him
to ``be the player that I have always wanted to be. I would like to
thank you.'' He also said his agents were ``like fathers to me,''
and he thanked owner Robert Kraft and familty, vowing, ``I will put
everything I have into this thing. I'm so happy that it's done.''
</P>
<P>
   Law said during negotiations that he wanted to make sure Lawyer
Milloy would remain a teammate over the length of the contract. No
such assurances were given to Milloy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone around here wants Lawyer to sign, and I'm definitely
going to put up a big campaign for myself. We have to go out there
and do our jobs. The best negotiation I can do for Lawyer and
Lawyer to do for himself is to go out there and win a championship
together,'' Law said.
</P>
<P>
   Wasynczuk acknowledged that Milloy would be the next big
negotiation for the Patriots, with Bledsoe's extension an ongoing
issue. Bledsoe has one of the biggest cap numbers in the NFL at
$7.2 million this season, while his actual salary is $5.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried to work hard with Lawyer's situation,'' said
Wasynczuk. ``Ray Anderson (Milloy's agent) and I have got to the
point where we thought it might be good to take a break and we'll
revisit it at the end of the year. It may be sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasynczuk pointed out that the signing bonus was ``the Kraft
family stepping up and subsidizing the operation.'' He said that
some of the big signing bonuses handed out recently have not come
out of team revenue but out of Bob Kraft's pockets. Kraft had a
personal meeting with Law three days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Law was angry when Willie Clay was released, but he said: ``It
didn't take long at all (to get over Clay leaving the team). You
also have to keep in mind that this is a business and things
happen. It is all about winning. My job is to go out there and
play. The reaction I had with Lawyer and a couple of other guys who
were so close, it's hard not to get that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Postons have certainly found a money stream. Along with the
Law deal, they also recently negotiated an $86 million contract for
Penny Hardaway with the Phoenix Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an easy deal for us in terms of Ty being such a great
person and a great player that who he is and what he does speaks
for itself,'' said Carl Poston, who announced that Law would be
starting a charitable foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Law said the money won't change his work ethic; the past two
years, he's punished himself under legendary track coach Bob
Kersee's conditioning program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't play for the money,'' said Law. ``I play to earn
respect, to compete against myself and opposing players. I come
from a small town and I was already financially secure. That didn't
change my drive. This gives me more financial stability, but I
still have to go out there and do what I have to do to earn respect
throughout the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you say `cornerback,' you say `Deion Sanders.' I would
say `Deion Sanders,' but I'm working to get there. When I retire,
five years later, I want to get to the Hall of Fame. I can't rest
with one Pro Bowl and a multimillion dollar contract. The time I
rest is when I walk away from the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
