<HEADLINE>
SIGEL'S BACK NINE PROPELS HIM AHEAD OF THE SENIOR PACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, Mass. _ He toured the first nine holes of the verdant
6,773-yard layout at Nashawtuc CC at even-par 36. Nothing
spectacular. Just steady golf. However, Jay Sigel's back nine
proved to be a different story.
</P>
<P>
   It was there the 55-year-old Senior PGA Tour member gathered
himself for a strong finishing kick, carding five birdies _
including three in a row on Nos. 12, 13 and 14 _ for a 5-under 67
and a two-shot lead over a pack of eight tied at 69 after Friday's
first round of the BankBoston Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Christy O'Connor, winner of last week's Foremost Insurance
Championship in Ada, Mich.; Hale Irwin, the two-time defending
champion of the BankBoston Classic and Senior Tour's second-leading
money winner; and Tom McGinnis, who recorded the only eagle of the
day with a 6-iron from 170 yards out on the par-4, 423-yard 11th
hole, were among the eight golfers tied at 3-under.
</P>
<P>
   Eight more players, including Dana Quigley of Rehoboth, were
tied at 70, meaning 16 golfers were within three strokes of Sigel.
</P>
<P>
   ``My round was scratchy starting out,'' said Sigel, who last
year shot a final-round 66 but wound up two strokes behind eventual
winner Irwin with a 54-hole total of 13-under 203. ``Making the
birdie on (No.) 10 from the bunker really put me in a positive
frame of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it did.
</P>
<P>
   After he found the bunker with his second shot on the par-5,
538-yard dogleg right, Sigel rallied when he blasted out to within
6 feet for his first birdie of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``That changed my whole day,'' Sigel said. ``I had a very hard
shot. I was pleased I got it in the vicinity and to make birdie was
a real bonus. It was definitely the shot of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   After jump-starting his round with a birdie on the 10th, Sigel
followed with consecutive birdies on the par-4, 411-yard 12th (with
a wedge to within 4 feet), the par-3, 203-yard 13th (a 3-iron
within 12 feet), and the par-4, 367-yard 14th (an 8-iron to within
18 feet).
</P>
<P>
   Sigel closed out his round with a birdie 4 on No. 18, a par 5,
511-yarder, nestling a pitching wedge to within 6 feet after
hitting back-to-back 3-irons. Sigel's round (36-31-67) matched his
season best, which came when he gained a share of the lead with
Kermit Zarley and Bob Dickson in the opening round of the Home
Depot Invitational April 23 at Charlotte, N.C., which,
coincidentally, was the last time he led a senior event. He wound
up winning $31,200 after finishing tied for ninth.
</P>
<P>
   A two-time winner last year at the Bell Atlantic Classic and the
EMC(Squared) Kaanapali Classic, Sigel entered this weekend's event
ranked No. 45 on the money list with $261,922 after making 20 of 21
cuts. In his last 10 Senior Tour events, Sigel has recorded only
two Top 10 finishes: a tie for ninth at the NFL Cadillac Classic
June 6, and a tie for 10th at the Coldwell Banker Burnet Classic
July 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a strange year,'' said Sigel, who is still
remembered around these parts for his victory in the 1982 US
Amateur at The Country Club in Brookline, where he captured the
first of back-to-back crowns. ``I haven't done anything all that
bad. I just haven't done anything. It's hard to be patient. I just
haven't gotten the results. I'm delighted with this round and
hopefully I can build on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin, who will attempt to join Chi Chi Rodriguez (1986-88) as
the only three-time winners of the Senior Tour's Boston stop, is
hoping to do the same after he finished at 3-under (35-34). Irwin,
a winner of three of the last five Senior events and five times in
all this season, had five birdies (on Nos. 6, 8, 10, 13, and 18)
offset by bogeys on No. 9 and 16 to wind up 3 under.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't ever object to 3-under par,'' Irwin said. ``It's a
good start, but I won't say it was a `great' start. I made a few
too many mistakes out there and had too many short irons, 30-35
feet from the hole. I wasn't as mentally efficient as I tend to be
or as I want to be. Because of that, my game was not quite where I
want it to be. But then again I'm not complaining about 69. It's a
good round, but sort of an indifferent round.''
</P>
<P>
   But not for Sigel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through valleys before as an amateur, but they
haven't lasted that long,'' said Sigel. ``Perhaps I've played too
much over the last few years. I played conservative off most of the
tees on the front, and hit six drivers total all day. I probably
won't play it any differently the rest of the tournament.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
