<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY'S WIFE HAS DUAL CAMPAIGN MESSAGE: BREAST CANCER, POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CAHER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. _ It's quite a leap from Nazi Germany to the
White House, but for Ernestine Bradley it is just one more step
toward the American Dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half of the world wants to come to this country, so I don't
feel that I was a great exception,'' said the wife of Democratic
presidential hopeful Bill Bradley. ``It is in a sense the country
of the future, the country of so many opportunities. When I came in
'57, it seemed to me the one open country, open in the sense of
being receptive, flexible, and I wanted to be part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernestine Bradley's father served in the German air force, or
Luftwaffe, during World War II, primarily in France, but the
candidate's wife said that as a young girl she was too ``wrapped up
in my child's life'' to give much thought to Hitler and the Third
Reich. As an adult, however, Bradley, a professor of German and
comparative literature, has written extensively about the Nazi
reign. Her most recent book, ``The Language of Silence: West German
Literature and the Holocaust,'' was published in March.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who married the cerebral basketball star and later U.S.
senator from New Jersey in 1974, brought her husband's campaign for
the presidency and her campaign against breast cancer to upstate
New York on Friday. She found receptive audiences for both.
</P>
<P>
   In Schenectady, she met with other breast cancer survivors and
advocates at the Schenectady YWCA, where Bellevue Woman's Hospital
featured its mobile mammography van.
</P>
<P>
   ``Breast cancer is really something that can be nipped,
something you do not have to die of,'' Bradley said in Schenectady.
Bradley discovered in 1992 that she had breast cancer, and
subsequently underwent a mastectomy and chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am living proof _ living proof _ that you can survive,'' she
said. ``I find that life after cancer is a much more intense life,
much more precious. I have found my values, or I should say I have
found the courage to insist on my values more than I did before.''
</P>
<P>
   After enduring surgery and radiation _ and losing her hair _
Bradley said she emerged a ``much stronger person.'' At 63, she is
eight years older than her husband. The underdog campaign of Bill
Bradley is, according to polls, seemingly gaining momentum, and New
York could be pivotal if the former New York Knicks guard and
Rhodes scholar from Princeton is to overtake Vice President Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Paul Tonko, a Democrat, has not yet endorsed either,
but said he's always been impressed with Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has a good academic grasp of the issues,'' Tonko
said. ``We live in a complex world, and the academic skills he has
are a valuable asset.''
</P>
<P>
   Schenectady County Democratic Chairman Chris Gardner said he's
been in Bradley's corner ever since the then-senator came to the
Electric City in 1993 to support Barry Kramer's bid for a Surrogate
Court judgeship. Kramer _ now Judge Kramer _ and Bradley had been
roommates during the 1964 Olympic basketball trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It impressed me that 29 years later the senator was driving
several hundred miles to help out a friend,'' Gardner said. ``You
wouldn't have too many senators who would drive a 10-year-old car
700 miles.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner said Bradley is the better presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there are huge differences in policy between
Bill Bradley and Al Gore,'' Gardner said. ``I think it's more a
matter of leadership style, and I think Bill Bradley will get us
away from focus-group, poll-driven politics. ... He knows what he
believes in, knows what he stands for.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernestine Bradley, who first came to this country as a Pan Am
stewardess and had never seen a basketball game until meeting her
future husband, declined to compare the Democratic presidential
contenders. But she implied _ as did Gardner _ that the former
three-term senator would offer more than the finger-to-the-wind,
sound-bite policymaking for which the Clinton administration, and
by extension Gore, have been criticized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill has been a good politician for 18 years,'' she said. ``He
has worked very hard and tackled issues that are normally
considered either dangerous _ like tax reform, where you don't
really gain much support _ or volatile, like race relations. ... He
really does feel that the president is the one person who would be
able not to be guided by focus groups or polls, but guided by his
understanding of where the country should be going. ... We need the
kind of leadership that transcends the political.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, however, maintains a comfortable lead and has already
secured the backing of many Democratic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently, the party leadership, or a good portion of it, is
already committed to Gore,'' said Harold Joyce, former chairman of
the Albany County Democratic Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
