<P>
   For Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Akron, Ohio) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush says he will
still give federal money to faith-based organizations to perform
the social services once provided by the government, even if they
restrict membership to their own believers. The candidate for the
Republican presidential nomination makes the remark at an Akron
born-again Christian agency that once refused a Jew a seat on its
board. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-DRUGS (Akron, Ohio) _ Gov. George W. Bush, in response to
continued but more muted questions about possible drug use during
his youth, says that baby boomer parents must warn their children
not to use drugs. Asked what he would tell his daughters, Bush
responded that his daughters were not part of his campaign. By
BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-WIFE (Schenectady, N.Y.) _ Ernestine Bradley,
campaigning for her husband's presidential bid in upstate New York,
carries a dual message. One is her husband's bid for the
presidency, the other is her message about surviving breast cancer.
By JOHN CAHER. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ATHEIST-FIGURE (Austin, Texas) _ David R. Waters, a chief
suspect in the disappearance of atheist leader Madalyn Murray
O'Hair, is sentenced to eight years in prison on two federal
weapons charges unrelated to her case. This comes a week after a
state court sentenced him to 60 years for stealing money from
O'Hair's atheist organizations. By JOHN MacCORMACK. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-WATER (Houston) _ A Navy study pointing to a potential Y2K
problem with Houston's water supply was mischaracterized in an
unofficial release of information obtained from the Internet, the
Navy says. By CARLOS BYARS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   POVERTY-CHILDREN (Washington) _ On the third anniversary of the
new welfare law, a study by the Children's Defense Fund found that
the number of children living in the category of ``extreme
poverty'' rose 27 percent between 1996 and 1997. By DAN FREEDMAN.
(Filed Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   SOLOMON-LOBBYIST (Washington) _ It's difficult to tell that
Gerald B.H. Solomon has changed careers from U.S. congressman to
lobbyist. He has kept the same staff, the same travel schedule, the
same legislative agenda. He even totes the same trademark file
holder with ``SOLOMON'' emblazoned on the side. And the man who
heads the Solomon Group spends his week in Washington and returns
to upstate New York on weekends, just as he did during 20 years in
Congress. By JUDY HOLLAND. (Filed Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   OLDER-WORKERS (Washington) _ Gene Nelson, an experienced
computer programmer, has been looking for work for two years. He's
irked at the claim of the computer industry that 400,000 software
engineering and programing jobs go unfilled in the United States.
``There's no shortage of high-tech workers,'' Nelson says.
``There's a shortage of high-tech workers under the age of 35.'' We
examine the problem of older computer engineers looking for work in
an industry that favors the young. By MARK HELM. (Also in the ``f''
category.) (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOMBING-RANGE (Vieques, Puerto Rico) _ Puerto Rico's political
leaders and allies in Congress point to Hawaii's ouster of the U.S.
Navy from a bombing range on the island of Kahoolawe in 1994 as a
precedent for Puerto Rico's campaign to evict the Navy from a
58-year-old bombing range on the island of Vieques. The future of
Vieques is headed toward President Clinton's desk. By STEWART M.
POWELL. (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-CONSTITUTION (Caracas, Venezuela) _ President Hugo
Chavez is making good on his word to bring about a ``peaceful
revolution'' in Venezuela by writing a new constitution. Critics
say the special assembly charged with the task is a rubber stamp
for Chavez's whims and warn that it could lead to the closing of
Congress and the Supreme Court and authoritarian powers for Chavez.
By JOHN OTIS.
</P>
