<HEADLINE>
COUSY ON THE WAY OUT AS CELTICS BROADCASTER? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   His has been the voice of reason for the last 25 years, and now,
apparently, the people at Fox Sports New England are trying to
quiet it. The Boston Celtics without Bob Cousy on the telecast?
That's the talk at the cable outlet.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has given the Celtics a bundle of money to televise all
their games, paying much more than it should have for the rights to
such a poor team. But now the word is that it is trying to dump
Cousy, which would be a monumental mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I would like to say at this point,'' offered Fox vice
president David Woodman, ``is that we want Bob Cousy. We are still
talking with Bob Cousy. All of this (purchasing the rights to all
Boston TV games) happened fast, so we still have some thinking to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   But he still wouldn't say if Cousy would remain an analyst. In
recent years, Cousy has done the Celtics road games. He's the voice
of reason. If the Celtics are looking good, he says they are good.
If they are bad, he says that as well. He has terrific insights, is
always well prepared, and is a great balance to Tom Heinsohn, who
is biased toward the Celtics and against the officials.
</P>
<P>
   To spend all that money and not keep Cousy where he is best
suited would be stupid. There is no other word for it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After some boorish behavior by fans at the PGA Championship in
the Chicago suburbs last week, the people who will be running the
Ryder Cup show at The Country Club in Brookline are going to be
very sensitive to bad behavior on their grounds when the great
international event takes place there next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to tolerate what we feel is improprer
behavior by any fan,'' says John Cornish, who is in charge of
running the Ryder Cup from The Country Club. ``Every fan entering
the club will be given a program. In that program is a message from
both team captains asking for the fans to cooperate. The fans will
be asked to applaud good shots by both sides, not cheer bad shots
by anyone, and not to be offensive toward players on either side.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Cornish, ``Six years ago in Kiawah (Island, S.C.), there
was some bad behavior by US fans toward the European players, and
we don't want a repeat of that here. Our marshals will be on the
lookout for any problems, and if there are any, we will deal with
them accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   Fan behavior has been growing more troublesome at major events,
says Len Zaichowsky, professor of sports psychology at Boston
University and one of the country's top experts in fan behavior.
``I think one of the major reasons for it is that the fans are
paying more for tickets and feel they have a bigger investment,''
he said. ``If you pay $75 for a seat, then you probably feel you
have a right to get angry when some athlete who is making millions
of dollars does not perform up to expectation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money issue is a big factor on both sides. The athletes
who get the multimillion-dollar contracts often act like they have
a sense of entitlement, that they are above it all no matter what
they do, and that they shouldn't criticized. Then the prices are so
high now for tickets and everything else that goes with attending a
game _ parking, concessions _ that the fan feel he is entitled to
vent his feelings when he doesn't think he is getting what he paid
for.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The unrelenting pressure of his two-month court battle in the
Reggie Lewis case hasn't stopped Dr. Gilbert Mudge from moving on
with the rest of his life. We are told that in a 10-day period,
Mudge, who is chief of the cardiac transplant unit at Brigham &AMP;
Women's Hospital, oversaw five successful heart transplants, a rare
occurrence. Meanwhile, there is no settlement on the horizon in the
Lewis case. Mudge's lawyers are getting ready to go back to trial
with Donna Harris Lewis, his widow. A Suffolk County jury would not
convict Mudge of malpractice in the first trial, so Harris Lewis
says she is going to try again. In addition, the Equitable
Insurance Company is moving close to a decision on whether to take
legal action against the Celtics in trying to reclaim $5 million
paid out to the team in life insurance when Lewis died, if it deems
Lewis did not tell the truth in filling out answers on the
applications in regard to using drugs and being tested for drugs .
. . Jerry Jacobs, owner of the FleetCenter and the Bruins, has
decided to wait no longer to find a development partner. Jacobs now
plans to build a hotel, office building, and condominiums on the
site of the old Boston Garden, on the Causeway Street side of the
FleetCenter. The present plans call for three 30-floor towers on a
space now being as a parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Vikings must not have done their customary
diligent homework when it came to drafting defensive lineman
Dimitrius Underwood in the first round. Underwood's coaches at
Michigan State told NFL scouts before the draft that he really
didn't have his heart in playing football. So it was not a big
surprise to many teams when he told the Vikings he had discovered
God and didn't want to play any longer . . . Speaking of lack of
homework, one local pro team recently signed a free agent with a
dubious past. When this guy was leaving one team, he sold a
teammate a $10,000 Rolex watch that turned out to be a phony. When
he left another team, he sold a teammate a top-shelf sports car for
$20,000. Turned out he simply was leasing it . . . Clark Booth told
this story about Tom Johnson at his retirement luncheon this past
week at the FleetCenter. When Johnson was playing for the Bruins,
his career was ended by a vicious cheap shot from Chicago forward
Chico Maki, who kicked Johnson in the back of the leg with his
skate blade, severing his Achilles' tendon. Unable to play again,
Johnson went on to coach the Bruins to a Stanley Cup in 1972 and
work in the front office until retiring this year. Booth went back
to Johnson a year ago while writing a book on the history of the
club, and Johnson still refused to talk about the incident, saying
it was nothing important. As Booth pointed out, hockey players are
a different breed, accepting the most difficult aspects of their
rugged sport without complaint. Let's hope they stay that way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you want Ryder Cup tickets, the smart way to get them is to
buy into the deal Mayor Menino has set up. Menino is using Woolf
Associates to sell Ryder Cup packages combined with a golf tourney
that week at Franklin Park. Rather than deal with a scalper, you
would be better off with the Menino deal, through which you can get
a writeoff for a charitable contribution, play in the tourney, and
still pay less than with a scalper. The money goes to junior golf
in the city. Bobby Orr and Gale Sayers are co-chairmen of the
tourney . . . The coaches at Boston College are hoping that
freshman running back William Green of Atlantic City, N.J., is as
good as he has looked to date. Green, a 6-foot-2-inch, 220-pound
tailback, was highly recruited by top schools around the country.
He is currently with the third team . . . The Patriots didn't do
well in the Sporting News's Top 100 players of all-time. John
Hannah grabbed 20th, and Mike Haynes, who played half his career in
Oakland, was 93d. None of the other local lads got a sniff,
although Roger Staubach said that Raymond Clayborn was the
second-toughest cornerback he ever tried to throw against, and Mack
Herron made a couple of personal lists as being one of the toughest
players to tackle in the open field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
