<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4651 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-HILLARY-LOOK-BOS &LR;      08-20 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-LOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON'S `FOCUSED' LOOK DRAWS COMMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ She wore dark sunglasses, a shapely black
pantsuit and matching low-heeled, open-toed slingbacks as she held
a cell phone to her ear. It could have been a snapshot of any
modern woman strolling down a Manhattan street.
</P>
<P>
   But this was the First Lady moments after decending the steps
from Air Force One onto Martha's Vineyard Thursday, a jarring
contrast to the welcoming friends dressed in jeans, print frocks
and Hawaiian shorts.
</P>
<P>
   Although her Senate campaign staff huffs at the idea that
Hillary Rodham Clinton could have an image consultant -- they think
it's a sexist question, even though men regularly hire them --
people are taking notice of the new vibrant look, including her
modern, no-nonsense short hair. What they see is an independent
woman ready for battle and sophisticated enough to take on New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``She does look different,'' said Vineyard Haven resident Sue
Rogers, who was there to greet the Clintons and has met them during
their previous vacations on the island. ``She looks very focused
and very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Her choice of clothing-as-image may not be as blunt as, say,
former presidential candidate Lamar Alexander's trademark
I'm-one-of-you plaid shirts, but the change has been noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredible isn't it?'' shouted Boston-based Democratic
political consultant Michael Goldman. ``She's looking good.''
</P>
<P>
   In an age where image is everything, politicians are accutely
aware that how they look effects how much people relate to them,
whether they trust them and, ultimately, whether they vote for
them.
</P>
<P>
   But the First Lady's handlers denied that her new look was a
part of a conscious strategy. ``She does not have an image
consultant,'' Mrs. Clinton's spokeswoman Julie Mason said sternly,
adding that she did not really know what an image consultant is.
``No one is telling her what to wear. To tell you the truth I
haven't paid much attention to it. It may just be it's more
practical for her to dress that way. ... I also don't know whether
great thought has been given to this.''
</P>
<P>
   Never known for her fashion sense -- remember the blue hat and
awkwardly tied scarf around her neck on Inauguration Day? -- the
first sign of Hillary trying to break free of those matronly pink
skirt suits came last December when she became the only First Lady
to appear on the cover of Vogue in its 110-year history.
</P>
<P>
   The cover shot had her in a $4,000 burgundy velvet Oscar De La
Renta number with Cartier earrings and shoes by Manolo Blahnik, one
of the hottest footwear designers around. More telling, perhaps,
was the inside spread, where Mrs. Clinton wore her own Oscar De La
Renta pants and a Donna Karan sweater in pictures magazine
spokesman Patrick O'Connell calls ``poised'' and ``empowering.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine hit the stand right around the time when her
candidacy to replace US Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan was being
floated. And since then, her look has been further refined.
</P>
<P>
   Freddy Rodriguez, one of the stylists at the Cristoph Salon in
Washington who ran his brush through her hair as recently as two
weeks ago at the White House, says Mrs. Clinton has finally figured
out what looks good on her, or, in political terms, what's right
for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can I say this? I think it all kind of slowly but surely
happened that way,'' Rodriguez said. The current hairdo almost
makes you forget about the headband she wore when she was standing
by her man during the 1992 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this haircut and this hairstyle is very current,
fresh-looking, modern and hip without overdoing it,'' Rodriguez
added.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh hair. Fresh start. Scandals and nearly two terms of White
House living are practically behind her and she's shopping for a
home in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion watchers have also noted that Mrs. Clinton is moving
away from skirts -- the wearing of which can appear more feminine
than feminist -- and toward pants. Perhaps, they offer, it is a
symbol of a new freedom from her traditional role.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a change when you are primarily a supportive
person as opposed to being a principle'' said Kam Kuwata, a
California Democratic consultant who helped elect Diane Feinstein
to the Senate. ``It appears she's carrying herself in a different
way because of a change in status.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
