<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4652 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-VENEZUELA-CONSTITUTIO     08-20 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-CONSTITUTION-$ADV22-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENEZUELA STRUGGLES WITH NEW CONSTITUTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Aug. 22) 
(Eds.: A tilde is needed over n in Munoz) 
 
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ Until recently, Antonia Munoz had never
been to the white, colonnaded Capitol building in downtown Caracas.
But nearly every day this month, she has settled into its plush
chambers to help lay the foundations for a new Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz, a university professor from the western city of Guanare,
was elected last month to the Constitutional Assembly, which is
writing a new Magna Carta to replace the 1961 edition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had always dreamed of changing the rules of the game in this
country,'' said Munoz, who earned a doctorate in agronomy at Texas
A&AMP;M University before returning to Venezuela to teach. ``I wanted
to have honest government.''
</P>
<P>
   The assembly is the linchpin of President Hugo Chavez's crusade
to bring about a ``peaceful revolution'' in this oil-rich yet
impoverished nation of 23 million.
</P>
<P>
   Besides composing a new charter, the assembly is expected to
dissolve the Congress and to overhaul the justice system, political
parties and other institutions that are viewed as corrupt. Chavez's
vision is a complete makeover of the Venezuelan state.
</P>
<P>
   Critics express fear that the assembly could become a rubber
stamp for Chavez's whims and would allow the hugely popular
president to accumulate even more power. They note that pro-Chavez
candidates won an astounding 123 of 131 seats in July 25 elections
for the Constitutional Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   But during the first three weeks of deliberations, the assembly
has often displayed a feisty, independent attitude. Debates go on
for hours and the voting has been unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts point out that Chavez remains incredibly popular six
months after taking office. Polls put his public approval rating at
more than 70 percent. But because his support comes from the left,
center and right, the assembly tends to reflect all of Venezuelan
society rather than Chavez himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have different opinions. They are not like sheep,'' said
Luis Vicente Leon, director of the Datanalysis polling firm in
Caracas.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with foreign reporters last week, Chavez spent
the first 15 minutes criticizing the international media, saying
that they misunderstand the nature of the assembly and have
unfairly portrayed him as a dictator-in-waiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is totally false that the 120 or so people ... allied to us
are a homogenous block that will raise their hands for whatever
Chavez says,'' he said. ``No one can say that this is being cooked
up. If that's the way it really was, the constitution would already
have been approved.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Congress, which is in recess, the Constitutional
Assembly includes seasoned politicians as well as social workers,
teachers, journalists, retired military officers and Indians.
Voters even elected two folk singers and a racetrack announcer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a really weird mix,'' said Ricardo Penfold, vice
president of research for Santander Investment in Caracas. ``You
wonder if they have the credentials to be drafting a new
constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority of delegates are university graduates who are on
leave from their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not here for the money,'' said Jesus Rafael Sulbaran,
the racetrack announcer who also has a law degree. ``We are here
for our ideals. We are here to regain our rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Idealism has been in short supply in Venezuela. Although it is
the world's third-largest oil producer and Latin America's oldest
democracy, the country is in shambles.
</P>
<P>
   The unemployment rate is 15 percent and 80 percent of the
population live in poverty. Venezuelans put much of the blame on
government institutions gone bad.
</P>
<P>
   The judicial system often is singled out as the worst offender.
More than half of the nation's 4,700 judges and court officials
face complaints of corruption and other irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, a former Army paratrooper who launched an unsuccessful
coup attempt in 1992, won a landslide election victory last
December by promising to clean house. To do so, he says he needs a
new set of rules.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitutional Assembly, which began meeting Aug. 3, must
come up with a new charter within six months, although Chavez said
he would like the document ready in three months. Venezuelans will
then go to the polls to approve or reject the document.
</P>
<P>
   While nearly everyone agrees that a government shake-up is
essential, the exact powers of the assembly are unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez contends the assembly is the nation's ``supreme power''
and warns that existing government institutions must not be used as
``trenches'' from which to fight against the coming reforms. But
the Supreme Court maintains that the assembly must stick to writing
a new constitution and not meddle with the other branches of power.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the assembly ignored the Supreme Court's opinion by
declaring a ``judicial emergency,'' giving itself wide-ranging
powers to overhaul the court system and fire corrupt judges.
</P>
<P>
   It also appears likely that the Congress will be dissolved and
that new elections will be held next year, a measure that has
overwhelming support among average Venezuelans.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't want these institutions. They don't believe in
them. They no longer represent anything in Venezuela,'' said
Aristobulo Isturiz, vice president of the assembly and a former
mayor of Caracas.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers warn that the assembly could get so bogged down
addressing the nation's ills that it will lose sight of its
original purpose. And if Chavez loses patience with the process, he
may demand action, said Herbert Koeneke, a political science
professor at Simon Bolivar University in Caracas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid that whenever he decides that enough is enough, he
may have the votes to pass the constitution that he wants,''
Koeneke said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, U.S. officials have endorsed Venezuela's reform program.
Following a recent trip to Caracas, Under Secretary of State Thomas
Pickering said that Chavez ``intends to have a constitution that
has full respect for democracy, human and civil rights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is healthy stuff,'' added a western diplomat. ``This is
democracy, Venezuela style.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 2015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
