<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4653 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-INTERNET-STOCK     08-20 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INTERNET-STOCKS-ART-$ADV22-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE GLITTER OF STOCK OPTIONS TURNS TO DUST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (For release on Sunday, Aug. 22)  
(jt) 
 By ABBY ELLIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Brian Knapp arrived at Barnes &AMP; Noble's new media division,
as it was then known, in January 1997, he thought the risks were
amply justified by the rewards. He was given a salary in the range
of $50,000, a job he liked and, thanks to a generous stock-options
package, the prospect of a big windfall when the division became a
separate company with its own stock.
</P>
<P>
   On May 25 this year, when Barnesandnoble.com went public at $18
a share, Knapp and his colleagues hoped to watch the stock soar,
and to join the ranks of their newly wealthy friends at Amazon.com
and America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the shares stagnated. Without the prospect of a fortune
to hold him, Knapp left the company on July 23 to become director
of business development for the Allbusiness.com of San Francisco,
which offers business services on line _ and plans to go public in
a few years. The benefits included a new options package.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was much easier to leave because I didn't have the golden
handcuffs,'' he said of Barnesandnoble.com. ``It wasn't worth it
for me to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   After a huge run-up, the decline in Internet stocks since April
has loosened the strongest ties that employees have to some risky
young companies. Stock options, once limited to top executives,
have become the new common currency in the technology world, but
the wealth that many workers hoped their options would yield has
sometimes become as insubstantial as smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of companies, especially IPO's and Internet, are putting
all their eggs in the stock options basket,'' said Dick
Wagner,chief executive of Strategic Compensation Research
Associates in Manhattan. ``If the stock price doesn't perform, a
stock option, unlike performance shares or other forms of
compensation, won't attract or retain key employees. In fact,
underwater options can be a massive motivator to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   With more Americans hopping from job to job, options have become
a prime way for employers to build loyalty and morale. The options
provide the right to buy stock in the future _ at the eventual
offering price, the current market price, or often at a discount.
They typically vest, or become effective, 25 percent at a time over
four years. Employees usually get the most options when they
arrive, but many receive annual option grants as well.
</P>
<P>
   Jenn Shreve received a substantial number of pre-offering
options as an editor for three years at Salon.com, the online
magazine in San Francisco. When the company went public at $10.50 a
share on June 22, employees expected the stock, and the options'
value, to take off. But after running past $15 in early July, the
shares have fallen, closing on Friday at $6.25.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shreve, who is 26, quit her job at Salon.com earlier this
month to do freelance writing. While she did not leave solely
because of the stock's poor performance, she had less incentive to
stay. ``I never expected to get massively wealthy in the first
place, but it would've been nice,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At companies like Amazon.com or Yahoo, early employees were
compensated with minimal salaries but abundant stock options, so a
lot of youthful plutocrats were minted as those stocks soared.
</P>
<P>
   But the options have already lost some of their cachet in
dot-com land.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of hype in this industry, and for every
millionaire there are a hundred people who don't make anything off
their options,'' said Knapp, who is 25. ``We were always pitted
against Amazon.com, and a lot of those folks did very well. But
starting at Amazon and being a founder there is like winning the
lottery. They're doing a great job, but what happened there isn't
going to happen in most people's lifetimes, even for a successful
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Employers, meanwhile, find that they must pay high salaries in
addition to options. ``There's no way we can hire someone without
stock options, but we still have to pay market rate,'' said John
Williamson, chief operating officer of Surfmonkey.com, of Campbell,
Calif., a Web portal for children; the company plans to go public.
</P>
<P>
   With some Internet shares down more than others, job hunters
have become amateur stock analysts. ``They know they're in short
supply; they can negotiate,'' Williamson said. ``They're all
looking to find pre-IPO companies they can join and benefit from.''
</P>
<P>
   Where prospects still seem promising, taking a chance on an
options windfall doesn't necessarily mean taking a full-time job.
For the first time in his 21 years of doing business, Bob Eiland,
who owns EGS Elite, a consulting firm in Northboro, Mass., chose to
accept options as well as cash for his work the last few years with
Software.com, an Internet software company in Santa Barbara, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The shares were sold to the public at $15 on June 24, hit $48 on
July 15 and closed on Friday at $40.8125; Eiland's options allow
him to buy shares in the single digits. He cannot sell any shares
until December, but plans to hold most of them for the longer term.
</P>
<P>
   Eiland finds his compensation package both exciting and
unnerving, as he struggles not to spend money he does not yet have.
``Owning a significant amount of options in a high-growth Internet
company can be insidious in how it can sneak its way into your
unconscious,'' he said. (FM)`Without knowing it, you can start
making assumptions on how things will be easier financially.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, he said, he and his wife, Sharlotte, who have been
considering a move to a new home since the beginning of the year,
were tempted to buy a house that cost twice as much as their
present one is worth. Ultimately, they backed off, but still do a
little dreaming.
</P>
<P>
   Since his decision to accept the options instead of a higher
fee, he and his wife have retained a financial adviser, a tax
lawyer, an accountant specializing in stock transactions and an
initial-offering consultant who helps devise long-term investment
strategies. Eiland has also thought about charities to which he
could contribute.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, he does not even know how much his options will be
worth. ``It's possible, though improbable, that we could even lose
money _ especially considering the amount of money I gave up in
order to get the options,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With the potential for huge gains diminishing as Internet stocks
weaken, some employees are adjusting to working more for salaries
and intrinsic pleasures _ more like everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never said I'm going into an Internet company to be a
millionaire,'' Knapp said. ``I do it because I love the atmosphere,
the industry, that medium and the people. The fact that I get paid
to play on the Internet all day long is astounding.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 2015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
