<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SOLDIER21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Goldberg can't kick start `Soldier'
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There may not be a movie screen big enough for Bill Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   World Championship Wrestling's paramount wrestler and former
Atlanta Falcon is all over Jean-Claude Van Damme's latest
all-fists-and-kicks flick, ``Universal Soldier: The Return.''
</P>
<P>
   As one of the movie's robotic superhunks turned evil, Goldberg
gets shot, stabbed, set on fire and smashed by a truck. He falls
headfirst down stairs into a concrete wall, backside first off a
multi-story building onto rock-hard asphalt.
</P>
<P>
   What's this muscled goon to do? Toss it all off with his
trademark wrestling shoulder-shrug and charge ahead, body-slam-ming
some piece of tattooed male meat dressed up as a hospital orderly.
</P>
<P>
   This is a Van Damme movie. And that makes it an unapologetic,
full-borne, brawn brawl.
</P>
<P>
   There is a story to get in the way of all the fighting. As the
title so eloquently indicates, this is a return to Van Damme's 1992
``Universal Soldier,'' in which dead military guys are turned into
chiseled, nearly unstoppable, cyborglike warriors. This time,
there's a HAL-like computer dubbed Seth running things. And when an
ill-advised general orders the shutdown of the Universal Soldier
program, old Seth boots up the fighting force and orders a world
takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Only Van Damme, as a former human-robot who's now inexplicably
more human than automaton, stands in the way. He's got an injured
daughter to worry about, a shapely female reporter constantly at
his heels and the whole planet to tote on his back.
</P>
<P>
   The kicks, punches, bombs and firepower just keep coming as the
film's heavy metal soundtrack just keeps blaring.
</P>
<P>
   More amazing than all the explosions and noise is the tenacity a
movie like this has to sneak its story line inside a strip joint
where, naturally, lap dances turn into a fisticuffs free-for-all.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, but the only thing resembling a human actor in all this
is Michael Jai White, who plays Seth after the computer downloads
its smarts into White's monstrously buffed body. He's amazingly
evil.
</P>
<P>
   As with most Van Damme movies, this one's got some good jabs and
kicks. But it's devoid of the full-fledged physical artistry of
Jackie Chan or the mesmerizing carnage of the best Hong Kong action
flicks.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, without Goldberg and White, it'd be nothing but a
whimper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Universal Soldier:
</P>
<P>
   The Return''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jean-Claude Van Damme, Michael Jai White and Bill
Goldberg. Rated R for nonstop strong violence, and for language and
nudity. 1 hour, 22 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: It's loud, it's brutal and, unfortunately, not
packed with enough fun.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
