<HEADER>
A4656 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-BIO-COMPUTER22-COX     08-20 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIO-COMPUTER22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Researchers develop `living' calculator using real nerve cells
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 22.
 &HT;    By J. Matthew Aldag
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Paul Garcia makes an incision down the length of the
green and brown spotted back of a leech. He carefully clears tissue
and blood away from his target: a fragile network of nerve cells
that will soon function as a biological calculator.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a nutshell, we are utilizing the properties of leech
neurons to add,'' explains Garcia, a graduate student at Georgia
Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Blurring the distinction between biology and technology, Garcia
and other scientists from Georgia Tech and Emory University have
joined forces to create a method of computing that is part machine
and part animal. Garcia is combining living nerve cells, courtesy
of leeches, with a little machinery to create a calculator that
correctly answers a question that stumps all but a couple of
species worldwide: What is two plus three?
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta researchers hope the ability to add will be the first
step to a more sophisticated and new type of thinking for a
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, computers process information in a rigid procedure of
logic that cannot make guesses or assumptions about vague, inexact
problems. The ``language'' a computer understands is purely one of
numbers and mathematics.
</P>
<P>
   But in the future, these biology-based computer systems might
understand the messy scrawl of handwriting _ a decidedly difficult
task for a computer, but not for a 5-year-old, says Bill Ditto, a
former physics professor at Georgia Tech and collaborator on the
project. One day, the so-called ``neurosilicon computer'' might
also be able to help security experts break codes, recognize and
distinguish among human voices, and control the movement of
prosthetic limbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``My handwriting is terrible. My kids can read it, but a
computer cannot. They are stupid in that sense,'' Ditto explains.
That's because computers are unable to make sense of the tiny
variations inherent in everyday handwriting.
</P>
<P>
   Simply adding processing power to a machine doesn't solve the
problem, because computers need to ``think'' differently. Ditto
says that neurons _ nerve cells, the biological building blocks of
nature's most powerful computer, the human brain _ are much better
suited to filling in gaps of uncertainty that even today's most
powerful computers can't overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Humans don't think in terms of ones and zeros; they have
neurons,'' Ditto says.
</P>
<P>
   But a full-fledged biological computer is still far away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at a very primitive stage in this research. We haven't
yet done anything revolutionary,'' says Ron Calabrese, professor of
biology at Emory University. He says the research to date has
merely established that the building blocks for a biological
computer can work at a fundamental level. It's like proving a wheel
will roll before building a car.
</P>
<P>
   Calabrese is an expert of leech neurophysiology, studying the
bloodsucker since 1974 in his efforts to understand its nervous
system. Calabrese and Ditto plan to construct a large
conglomeration of neurons and silicon as a type of computer chip _
a true mixture of biology and electronics _ that they hope will do
much more than add.
</P>
<P>
   The leech computer is a typical example of the kind of
interdisciplinary work pursued by the joint biomedical engineering
department of Georgia Tech and Emory University. ``The leech
project is very innovative, taking the approach of looking at
nature and how it processes information as a model for computing,''
says Don Giddens, a biomedical engineer at Georgia Tech who heads
the joint department.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the schools joined forces to establish the department,
bringing together the strong technical and engineering strengths of
Tech with the biological and medical prowess of Emory. Among the
innovative research efforts under way:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Michelle LaPlaca of the joint biomedical engineering faculty
is studying how brain cells react to injury. She hopes to develop a
replacement brain tissue that would restore structure and function
to lost brain areas in victims of brain diseases and injuries.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Paul Benkeser, a Georgia Tech professor of computer
engineering who also is affiliated with the biomedical engineering
department, is using imaging techniques to develop a way to better
understand the pediatric heart under bypass surgery. Without the
presence of blood during bypass, the heart changes shape as it
collapses, looking much different to the surgeon who must make
crucial decisions for a successful procedure.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ditto is attempting to develop new techniques for electrically
stimulating the brain in epileptics that might eliminate seizures,
which are now treated primarily with drugs or surgery. Research in
animals has been promising to date, and Ditto may begin work with
human patients in the years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, studying for a medical degree from Emory as well as a
Ph.D. from Tech under an unusual joint program, is perfectly suited
for the interdisciplinary project. His knowledge of neural biology
and electronic engineering allows him to physically combine the
neurons of a leech _ officially known as Hirudo medicinalis, a
species commonly found in Eastern Europe _ with electronics.
</P>
<P>
   He is able to connect the two because the nervous system of any
animal involves electrical signals that travel along neurons and
jump from cell to cell in a biological network of communication. To
get leech cells to add, Garcia isolates a leech neuron and monitors
the electrical activity _ sometimes called ``cell firing'' _ of the
separated, living nerve cell with electrodes. A cell will ``fire''
with a certain amount of electrical activity to which Garcia
assigns an arithmetic number. Garcia is able to manipulate the
firing of an individual cell, controlling its activity level.
</P>
<P>
   The actual computation comes when Garcia connects two cells with
a computer system developed at Brandeis University that acts much
the way nature does. ``This artificial connection represents and
mimics a biological (connection) between the two cells. For our
purposes, it does so perfectly,'' says Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   The program causes the activity of one cell to influence the
firing of another, just as it might in a live leech. Garcia causes
the firing of two cells _ one, for example, whose activity level
corresponds to 2 and one whose level corresponds to 3 _ to combine.
The result is an overall activity level that reflects the
``answer'' _ in this case, that 2 plus 3 equals 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now this is a very trivial way of achieving computation;
it is really just the first step,'' says Garcia, who is exploring
more complex connections between leech neurons that may be able to
do more than just addition. ``We are on to something that nobody
has ever done before, and that is very exciting to us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The research is progressing very quickly,'' adds Ditto, ``and
this joint Emory-Georgia Tech program is right at the forefront of
this whole field.''
</P>
<P>
   J. Matthew Aldag writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
