<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPASHIN LEADS PRO-CAPITALIST COALITION IN RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Former Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin emerged Friday
as the leader of a new centrist alliance, as the unofficial race to
succeed President Boris Yeltsin continued to gather momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin will lead a political coalition that includes Viktor
Chernomyrdin and Sergei Kiriyenko, two former prime ministers who,
like Stephashin, were also fired by Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   The aim is to create a pro-capitalist alternative to the
left-leaning Yevgeny Primakov, another former prime minister who
has become an early favorite to win the 2000 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Stepashin and Primakov are simply preparing for
December's parliamentary elections. But those elections are widely
perceived as preparation for the more important competition next
year over control of the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   With many of Russia's economic reformers tainted by last year's
financial crisis, Stephashin, 47, has sought to become the
standard-bearer of the unruly collection of democrats, economic
reformers and power-brokers that Russians have taken to calling the
``center right.''
</P>
<P>
   A former head of the Interior Ministry and internal intelligence
service, Stepashin seems more pragmatic and hard-nosed than the
professorial Kiriyenko, who had the political misfortune to preside
over the fall of the ruble. And he is younger and more dynamic than
the stolid Chernomyrdin, 61, who has gained an unwanted reputation
for his fractured syntax and associations with powerful interests.
</P>
<P>
   Running well behind Primakov in the ratings, Stephasin seemingly
needs a broad base of support. Still, weaknesses in his emerging
coalition were already apparent Friday as some of the would-be
members squabbled openly among themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin's key aides were reportedly seeking to exclude the
movement led by Yegor Gaidar, Democratic Choice. An economist and
former prime minister who liberalized prices in Russia, Gaidar was
also the behind-the-scenes architect of much of Yeltsin's
unfulfilled agenda of economic reform.
</P>
<P>
   Anatoly Chubais, the former head of Russia's privatization
program and a member of Gaidar's party, met with Chernomyrdin at
his country home outside Moscow Friday to try to persuade him to
make common cause with the Gaidar faction.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing that he might be excluded, Gaidar said sarcastically
that there were ``anatomical differences'' between the members of
his party and those of Chernomyrdin's: The members of the Gaidar
party, he said, had moral backbones; the members of Chernomyrdin's
party did not.
</P>
<P>
   That was not the only sign of friction. Some of Chernomyrdin's
aides, for example, said there was no place in the new coalition
for Boris Fyodorov, the blunt-spoken former tax collector who once
assailed Chernomyrdin as a do-nothing minister, and Boris Nemtsov,
the reform-minded former aide to Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a feeling of lost grandeur and this feeling just
eats them up,'' Nemtsov said sarcastically, referring to the
Chernomyrdin faction. ``I hope that common sense prevails.''
</P>
<P>
   The ability of the new alliance to pull together _ or fracture _
could become clear as early as Saturday, when Stepashin and
Chernomyrdin may formally announce their new electoral bloc.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the announcement so pressing is Primakov's dramatic
reentry into Russian politics earlier this week and his partnership
with Moscow's mayor, Yuri Luzhkov, one of the nation's most
ambitious politicians.
</P>
<P>
   A former Soviet official, Primakov is seen as a force for
stability by many Russians. Primakov's critics say he is a typical
politician who steadfastly avoided difficult decisions during his
term as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   While opinion polls generally rate Primakov as the nation's most
trusted politician, that view is held by only a quarter of the
population, reflecting the widespread antipathy many Russians feel
toward their leaders.
</P>
<P>
   There are other contenders, too. They include Grigory Yavlinsky,
the stubbornly independent leader of the liberal Yabloko party.
Earlier this week, Yavlinsky and Stepashin discussed throwing their
lot together, but those talks broke down when Stepashin turned down
an offer to join the Yavlinsky ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Gennadi Zyuganov, the Communist leader, has a solid base of
mostly older supporters. But few observers give him a chance to win
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Stepashin's successor as prime minister, Vladimir
Putin, whom Yeltsin has publicly endorsed as his successor, and an
array of governors, like Konstantin Titov of the Volga River region
of Samara.
</P>
<P>
   A new poll did not give Putin, a former intelligence official,
much hope. Only 12 percent said they thought Yeltsin was sincere
when he offered the endorsement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
