<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4659 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-WALL-STREET-DORMITORY     08-20 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALL-STREET-DORMITORY-ART-$ADV22-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOMIES ON WALL STREET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(For release Sun., Aug. 22) 
(jt) 
 By JENNIFER 8. LEE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a Saturday afternoon that offered the first break
from an 80-plus-hour work week, investment bankers lay bronzing on
the rooftop terrace of 45 Wall St. Sipping Evian and Corona beer,
they took in a 29th-floor view of the landmarks of the financial
district, close enough to reach out and touch: the Goldman Sachs
building, the New York Stock Exchange, the World Trade Center, the
J.P. Morgan building.
</P>
<P>
   Other residents worked out in the building's mirrored penthouse
gym, or shot pool in a wood-paneled lounge. The logos on their
workout clothes formed a lineup of prestigious names: Harvard,
Wharton, Morgan Stanley, Merrill Lynch _ all alma maters and
employers.
</P>
<P>
   The residents of 45 Wall St. are relatively young. They are
urban. They are brazenly professional. The converted office
building in which they live, one block from the New York Stock
Exchange, has become known as an upscale dormitory of sorts for
armies of fresh college graduates, who invade Wall Street from the
country's premier universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question here is what Wall Street company do you work for,
not what do you do,'' said James Im, a University of Chicago
graduate, who was doing stomach crunches in the gym. ``Forty-five
Wall is famous. It's known to be an analysts' dormitory. If you're
an analyst, you know someone who lives in 45 Wall.''
</P>
<P>
   To most financial investors, a Wall Street analyst is a
respected stock picker. But ``analyst'' is also the title given to
the foot soldiers of the industry who fill the lowest level of the
Wall Street hierarchy. They put in back-breaking hours, pull
all-nighters regularly and grease the capitalist machine through
IPO's and mergers and acquisitions. They are intimate with
Microsoft Excel and Powerpoint. ``You're in the bottom of the food
chain,'' said Valerie Zonenberg, 23, a Harvard University graduate
who has worked for two years for a major Wall Street firm and lives
at 45 Wall.
</P>
<P>
   When it was converted two years ago to residential use, the
building, which is managed by the Rockrose Development Corp., was
designed for professionals, with home offices; some apartments even
have high-speed Internet access. But few take advantage of that
option. Today, half of the residents work in the financial
industry. The average age is 28. The average salary is $70,000.
</P>
<P>
   The address has resonance. The Wall Street subway stop on the
No. 2 and No. 3 trains is beneath the building. ``It's all part of
the mystique: `I live on Wall Street, I work at Goldman Sachs,'''
said one recent college graduate, tanning on the rooftop of 45
Wall, where he shares a three-bedroom apartment with two other
analysts for $3,400 a month. ``It's a culture. You walk downstairs
in the morning and everyone is in suits. You feel like you're at
the center of the world. Everything happens here.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The location is convenient, even though the financial district
becomes a ghost town after 6 p.m. Half the residents live less than
a 15-minute walk from work. ``From door to desk, it takes me 2
minutes,'' David Saenz, an analyst with J.P. Morgan, said during a
round of pool in the lounge.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the proximity helps ease the life style. ``When you
are working 100 hours a week, you want to be able to walk to
work,'' said Ms. Zonenberg, who pays $1,400 a month for a studio
apartment. ``Especially when you have three hours of sleep at
night, you want to be able to run home and take a quick shower.''
</P>
<P>
   She is one of a group of people fulfilling a high-cost,
high-payoff contract. They have agreed to serve as Wall Street's
drudges for two or three years, in exchange for another blue-chip
credential on their resumes. For many, Wall Street is just a stop
on the way to business or law school. Others will stay in the
financial industry. It's a combination rat race and paper chase.
The end of the road is a place in the American aristocracy, earned
through grit and luck.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The doormen at 45 Wall don't find it unusual when residents
stumble in at 4 or 5 a.m. Tenants regularly arrive home as others
are leaving for work. ``They shower, sleep for two hours, get up
and go to work again,'' said Thomas Wright, who was on the midnight
to 8 a.m. door shift in the marble and redwood lobby. Doormen often
give wake-up calls to rouse the employees from their naps. ``I have
some people come in so disgusted, they say the job is killing
them,'' Wright said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The analysts concede that their salaries are comfortable for a
first job, but they are quick to point out that computed hourly,
they are within a few dollars of minimum wage. ``The joke is a
McDonald's worker makes more per hour than we do,'' Ms. Zonenberg
said. ``Eighty hours a week is two jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents of 45 Wall say they find strength in sharing the
ordeal. ``When you come home at 3 in the morning, you can always
expect someone to walk in at the same time, also in a suit, also as
exhausted as you are,'' Ms. Zonenberg said. ``In the elevator ride,
you're too tired to talk but you give each other that nod: `I'm
there, too. Thanks for being there.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how they can work 100 hours a week,'' Wright said.
``I tell them, `Your health comes first. I don't care how much
money you are making.'''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In return for the fatherly counsel, the financial professionals
offer their doormen advice of their own. ``I don't know anything
about investments, but my tenants told me what to do with my
money,'' Wright related. ``They said take my money out of my
savings account. Now, I'm in the stock market,'' he said,
brandishing the current issue of the Janus fund report.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the building is a high-class dormitory at sky-high
Manhattan real estate prices. The young professionals live in
groups of up to five in an apartment. Living rooms are partitioned
to carve out bedrooms and economize. Bookshelves are filled with
textbooks from summer finance training courses like ``Essentials of
Accounting'' and ``Principles of Corporate Finance.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many dorms, 45 Wall even has a common area _ the rooftop
lounge, complete with pool table, big-screen television and a
party-size wrap terrace, which can be rented for $100 a hour.
Parties are a big part of life at 45 Wall. ``Before, I had sublet
in a building with older tenants,'' said Novisi Atadika, a recent
Harvard graduate, who works at Credit Suisse First Boston. ``There,
they posted up signs that said, `I'm sorry, I'm having a party.'
Whereas here it's commonplace to party.'' Instead of beer kegs and
pretzels, parties at 45 Wall typically have full bars and caterers.
</P>
<P>
   Children are unusual, though becoming slightly more common.
Older people wandering the hotel-like hallways are presumed to be
parents of residents. ``You are 35 in this building, you stand
out,'' Ms. Zonenberg said. ``If you are 45, you are the parent
visiting the kids, bringing food to a son.''
</P>
<P>
   Other differences between college and the real world: the
furniture is nicer, the televisions more expensive. Ikea is the
furniture store of choice for the young professionals. This being
Wall Street, the building has an indoor practice golf course. It
also has a dry cleaning service, critical to appearing well groomed
in a culture that hasn't fully taken to summer casual. Dry cleaning
bills for the young analysts can approach $100 a month.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Residents rarely cook, and kitchens are barren. The analysts eat
breakfast on the way to work, lunch in the office and dinner at a
restaurant, traditionally paid for by companies for employees who
stay late. Even when they're not working, the residents dine out or
order in. The doormen see a steady stream of pizza and Chinese food
deliveries on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not once shopped for groceries in a year,'' Im said.
``It's not out of the ordinary to go a few days without toilet
paper and not care enough to do anything about it.'' His apartment
refrigerator contains water, beer and leftover Chinese food. Ms.
Zonenberg ate at home so seldom that she didn't buy a dining table
and chairs until eight months into her lease.
</P>
<P>
   For those who actually do purchase groceries, the scarcity of
supermarkets in the financial district leaves them scrambling to
stock their cabinets. Many analysts will have the company cars that
drive them home make a loop to 24-hour groceries and delis so they
can pick up basic necessities at 2 in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Free meals, free rides home, free cell phones and pagers _ it
appears to be a glamorous life style,'' one analyst said. ``But
there's no such thing as a free lunch. It's hard work. I would give
up all those free meals to come home earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents compare life at 45 Wall to a financial version of
``Friends.'' The narrow pool of colleges and companies makes for
only a few degrees of separation between people. ``It's a great way
to start a conversation,'' Saenz said. `` `Hey, you work at
Salomon? I have a friend who works at Salomon.' `Really? What
group?'''
</P>
<P>
   But the intensity and sameness of the work can result in narrow
discussions. ``You can't say, `I saw this movie' or `I went on
vacation' because your life is filled with work,'' Im said.
</P>
<P>
   Unsurprisingly, 45 Wall reflects the demographics of the
financial industry. There are two men to every woman. Some say the
building, like the Street, has a socially conservative cast.
``There are fewer other gays in the building than anywhere else
I've lived in New York City,'' said Jim Nellis, 45, a a senior vice
president at Commpeople, a telecommunications company, who is one
of the few baby-boomer residents. ``Wall Street is so closeted.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zonenberg, who still keeps her stuffed animals next to her
financial textbooks, said that for her a building that is an
extension of college is just fine for now. ``I'm not ready to be in
a place where there are babies, dogs and cats and real families
everywhere,'' she said. ``We know this is not the real world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
