<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4666 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-GIULIANI-RADIO-ART-13     08-20 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-RADIO-ART-1300(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MORALITY LESSONS AND PSYCHOLOGICAL ADVICE, TUNE IN TO THE
MAYOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo of Mayor Giuliani is being sent. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If there's anything callers to Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's weekly radio show should know before dialing, it's this:
Be careful what you ask.
</P>
<P>
   When Tony from the Bronx called to question the mayor's handling
of the Amadou Diallo shooting, Giuliani told him, ``Either you
don't read the newspapers carefully enough or you're so prejudiced
and biased that you block out the truth.'' When Bill in Manhattan
asked why it was illegal to hang a flag from city property,
Giuliani shot back, ``Isn't there something more important that you
want to ask me?''
</P>
<P>
   When David in Oceanside last month complained about the ban on
pet ferrets, the mayor of New York City leaned into the microphone
on his desk and intoned, ``There is something deranged about you.''
</P>
<P>
   A three-minute diatribe against the ferret advocate ensued, with
Giuliani saying things like, ``You should go consult a psychologist
or a psychiatrist with this excessive concern _ how you are
devoting your life to weasels.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor created ``Live From City Hall with Rudy Giuliani'' in
1994 as a means of talking to ordinary citizens about the
frustrations of city life, and sure enough, he helps dozens of
callers navigate city bureaucracy, foil corrupt landlords and find
jobs. When Alina from Queens phoned recently to complain about dogs
that bark all night, the mayor offered soothing advice. When
Dorothy from Brooklyn wanted someone to crack down on the garbage
trucks that spew rotten milk on her street, Giuliani hopped to the
task.
</P>
<P>
   But the show is as much about trouble-making as
trouble-shooting. Every Friday morning from 11 to 11:45, Giuliani
uses his free air time on WABC-AM to lecture New Yorkers about
their bad habits, inveigh against their collective dysfunction and
exhort them to be more exemplary human beings, for crying out loud.
</P>
<P>
   Although he does solve many callers' problems, Giuliani often
sounds more like a bullying therapist than an elected official.
``Live From City Hall,'' is his most direct, unfiltered means of
playing a favorite role: telling people who disagree with them that
they are not only wrong, but psychically flawed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has made the radio show into an opportunity to give
morality lessons and ideological sermonettes,'' said Mitchell Moss,
who directs the Taub Urban Research Center at New York University.
``He is using it less as an elected official and more as a local
Rush Limbaugh.''
</P>
<P>
   With 75,000 listeners per show, ``Live From City Hall'' is
considerably less popular than Limbaugh's show, which airs on the
same station and draws about 170,000 daily listeners in the
metropolitan area. Still, Giuliani's show, which can be heard as
far away as Albany, is the city's second-most-popular AM radio show
in its time slot, said Phil Boyce, the program director at WABC.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has definitely built up a following,'' Boyce said. ``He's
no different from the rest of our hosts, who have a pretty high
opinion of their own opinion and like to tell people what they
think.''
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, Giuliani's radio style is not so different from
that of his role model, Mayor Fiorello H. La Guardia, who reached
out to New Yorkers on his own weekly radio show in the 1940s. La
Guardia used his show to rail against reporters and bookies and
people who wasted gasoline during the war years, moralizing just as
fiercely as Giuliani does today.
</P>
<P>
   But La Guardia also shared stories about his children, dispensed
shopping and cooking tips and, famously, gave dramatic readings of
the ``Dick Tracy'' comic strip.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was like Giuliani in that he had no doubt about the fact
that he was right,'' said Thomas Kessner, a history professor at
the City University of New York Graduate Center who wrote a book
about La Guardia. ``But his tone on the radio was much more
avuncular. He was like the older uncle telling men and women what
was best for them in a way that infused them with optimism.''
</P>
<P>
   On a typical show, Giuliani starts out sounding like a school
principal making announcements over the public address system. As
the jaunty theme music fades, he exhorts listeners to donate blood
and take brief showers, root for local teams and get some exercise.
``You should really keep yourself as physically fit as possible,''
he said on the Aug. 6 show.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 13, the subject was gridlock, and Giuliani patiently
explained why not clogging intersections, known as blocking the
box, is an exercise in spiritual growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason not to block the box is a very, very important one
for your development as a responsible human being,'' Giuliani said.
``It means respecting the rights of other people, understanding
that there are sometimes things you would like to do, things that
feel better to you, but in doing them you disrespect the rights of
other people.''
</P>
<P>
   After his discourse, the mayor opens the phone lines for
questions.A technician e-mails each caller's name and a summary of
their question to City Hall, where Giuliani chooses the exchanges
du jour.
</P>
<P>
   Two of his most startling tirades recently came in response to
calls from David Guthartz, the ferret advocate, and Margarita
Rosario, whose son Anthony, an 18-year-old robbery suspect, was
shot dead by two police detectives in 1995. Mrs. Rosario called
last month and said that she wanted to discuss Con Edison. But
instead, she started protesting the shooting, and Giuliani barely
let her speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe you should ask yourself some questions about the way he
was brought up and the things that happened to him,'' the mayor
told Mrs. Rosario, whose 21-year-old nephew, also a suspect, died
in the shooting. ``Trying to displace the responsibility for the
criminal acts of your son onto these police officers is really
unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Tapes of some of Giuliani's earliest radio shows suggest that
back then, he handled hostile callers with more equanimity. When
Ann from Linden, N.J. called in August 1994 to denounce his support
of the federal crime bill, he politely responded, ``Ma'am, why are
you so angry?'' When Belinda from Manhattan called him ``a snake''
for endorsing Gov. Mario Cuomo, Giuliani had nothing more biting to
say than, ``That sounds like it was a paid political
announcement.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   So why, at a time when the mayor is taking some pains to soften
his image, has he dismissed some of his recent callers as not only
misguided or disingenuous, but mentally unsound?
</P>
<P>
   ``Having these conversations in private doesn't do any good in
placing out there the other side of the story,'' he said in an
interview. ``If you believe in the search for truth, people have to
be able to see the biases and prejudices and the irrational
problems that are affecting somebody's point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani recently began asking listeners to experiment with his
brand of therapy on a particularly troublesome group of New
Yorkers: the ones who don't clean up after their dogs. Such people
tend to have ``a whole host of other problems that play out in
their personalities,'' the mayor said on Friday's show.
</P>
<P>
   It would help, he added, if listeners could confront the
perpetrators on the street and call them slobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may walk up to the wrong person and who knows, you might
get a punch in the nose,'' Giuliani said. ``But if you feel capable
of doing that, this is really something that people have to learn
in society.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
