<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-AID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN NAVY SHIPS CARRYING AID TO TURKEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TURKEY-QUAKE, TURKEY-LEARN, TURKEY-TOWN) 
(th) 
 By PHILIP SHENON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Three Navy ships carrying more than 3,000 sailors
and Marines and tons of relief supplies were scheduled to arrive
off the coast of Turkey this weekend, the spearhead of what is
proving to be a large American military response to Turkey's
devastating earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy ships are crossing the Mediterranean and will be ready
to provide medical care by Saturday evening, the Pentagon said.
Pentagon officials said they scrapped plans to send several Air
Force transport planes to Turkey to help fight fires set off by the
earthquake because the fires had largely been contained.
</P>
<P>
   The ships, led by the amphibious assault ship Kearsarge, carry
22 helicopters available for medical evacuations and have six
operating rooms, five X-ray rooms and 60 hospital beds. The medical
staff includes eight doctors, three dentists and 88 medics and
other medical specialists.
</P>
<P>
   A separate 22-member Navy medical team from Naples, Italy,
arrived in Turkey on Friday with 27,000 pounds of medical gear and
surgical supplies, including intravenous fluids and anesthesia
machines.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Agency for International Development, which is
overseeing the government's civilian response to the disaster, said
Friday that the United States had so far provided about $3 million
in nonmilitary aid to Turkey to support the relief effort.
</P>
<P>
   Additional money will be committed later to support the
reconstruction of towns and cities in Turkey ravaged by the
earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very much in the search-and-rescue phase of this
operation,'' said Harriet C. Babbitt, the agency's deputy
administrator. ``The president has been very clear that Turkey is a
longtime friend and ally and we will be responsive to their needs
and requests.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States has depended heavily on Turkey, a NATO ally,
in American-led military operations in both the Balkans and the
Middle East, and President Clinton said earlier this week that the
United States ``will do whatever we can to help them get through
this terrible crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   A 70-member search-and-rescue team from Fairfax County, Va.,
outside Washington, has been at work in Turkey since Thursday
morning, searching for survivors buried under the rubble of the
city of Izmit, near the epicenter of the quake.
</P>
<P>
   The team, which uses sniffer dogs and sophisticated electronic
equipment in its searches, is under contract to the AID and has so
far rescued four people from collapsed buildings. It is to be
joined this weekend by a second 70-member American rescue team,
this one from Miami.
</P>
<P>
   With whole Turkish cities virtually in rubble, American relief
officials said that the Turkish government's most pressing need was
for tents and other types of temporary housing for the hundreds of
thousands of people forced from their homes. The Defense Department
has said that it will provide Turkey with up to 30,000 tents and
more than 100,000 prepared meals.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Babbitt said that the Clinton administration was urging
members of the public who wish to help Turkish earthquake victims
to do so with money, not through donations of clothing, food or
other goods that would take time to ship to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   The AID has established a toll-free telephone number to provide
callers with a list of charity groups seeking contributions for
earthquake relief: 1-800-872-4373, or 1-800-USAID-RE.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
