A4668 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p BC-BUSH-DRUGS-TEX     08-20 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DRUGS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH ANSWERS ON DRUGS PUTTING MAR ON OTHERWISE CHARMED EXISTENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In his short but famously successful political
career, George W. Bush has led a charmed life.
</P>
<P>
   Applying an almost obsessive discipline that has kept him
focused on a core set of issues and little more, Bush beat popular
Gov. Ann Richards in 1994, crushed his re-election opponent in
1998, and catapulted himself into an instant national phenomenon in
his race for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for the first time, Bush's winning strategy is being put to
the test in a national feeding frenzy, as unsubstantiated rumors
about past drug use overwhelm practically anything else the
campaign would like to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the fallout does not appear to have put the brakes on
Bush's frontrunning presidential campaign. A new poll shows most
Americans want the media to stop asking about the issue, and that
most people say they wouldn't hold a youthful dalliance with
cocaine against him anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But some experts say the media swirl could damage Bush more than
the rumors themselves, depending on how he performs in coming days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes a problem if you don't handle it well,'' said Gary
Jacobson, a political scientist at the University of California in
San Diego. ``It's this kind of dribbling out of unpleasant
information that's really damaging.''
</P>
<P>
   Others suggest there is no good way to handle the issue. Absent
a definitive ``no,'' a strategy of either refusing to answer the
question or of divulging illegal drug use carries risks.
</P>
<P>
   Until a few days ago, Bush's answer to the drug question _ or
his non-answer _ had at least been consistent: He always told
reporters he would not inventory the mistakes he made as a young
man.
</P>
<P>
   That all changed this week when Bush was asked if he could
answer a questionnaire that requires potential White House
employees to say whether they had used illegal drugs in the past
seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he could respond, and that the answer would be ``no.''
He later went on to say he could go back even further. His latest
statement has been interpreted to mean that he hasn't used illegal
drugs since at least 1974.
</P>
<P>
   That partial answer, far from putting the issue to rest, sparked
a media blitzkrieg. And, at least temporarily, it undermined Bush's
knack for controlling the message voters are receiving.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, he was back to declining to answer questions about
drug use.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever headlines Bush may have envisioned from his recent
campaign stops _ whether it be the technology-wise Jefferson
Elementary School outside New Orleans or a faith-based homeless
shelter in Ohio _ they have largely evaporated in a hail of
late-night television jokes, political cartoons and calls for him
to come clean with whatever secrets he may have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally think Govovernor Bush is right to say I've
admitted mistakes and I don't have anything else to say,'' said
Chuck McDonald, who served as spokesman for former Governor
Richards. ``But you have to adopt a line and never waiver, because
there's a million follow-up questions. It never ends.''
</P>
<P>
   When she was running for the Democratic gubernatorial nomination
in 1990, Richards broke political ground by refusing to answer drug
questions and inviting voters to choose another candidate if they
just had to know.
</P>
<P>
   Bush followed a similar tack in his successful race against
Richards four years later. When asked by the Houston Chronicle in
1994 about illegal drug use, he said: ``Maybe I did, maybe I
didn't. Where's the relevance?''
</P>
<P>
   The issue pretty much died until Bush began campaigning for
president this year, when rumors about alleged drug use began
circulating on the Internet and, eventually, on the front page of
The Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Bush called the rumors absurd but said nothing specific until
this week, when he was confronted about the White House security
clearance issue.
</P>
<P>
   C. Boyden Gray, who was counsel to President Bush, helped draft
the policy regarding illegal drug use by prospective White House
applicants, and said the Bush campaign contacted him to determine
what that policy was.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to make sure that he is able to establish a tough
enough standard, but one that's not too tough that he can't appoint
anybody,'' Gray said. ``His father used to crack that, `my God, if
you had a rule that you never used drugs since you were 18, I could
never find anybody.'''
</P>
<P>
   Whether people will hold Bush's refusal to answer the question
against him remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   The danger is that many Americans who have been ignoring the
2000 campaign are hearing about the Bush rumors because they're
reaching beyond the narrow band of political reporting, said Allan
Saxe, a political scientist at the University of Texas at
Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the comedians and the cartoonists get on you, it can be
serious. A comedian can do more harm than a columnist or a
newspaper reporter, because it starts sticking,'' Saxe said. ``It
begins to resonate.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 2029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0294 </DOCNO>
