<HEADLINE>
SHORT TAKE ON PERSONAL BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Aug. 22) 
(JT) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't Forget to Floss
</P>
<P>
   What's the perfect accoutrement for a date in the 1990s?
</P>
<P>
   How about the ``Get Lucky Pak,'' a wallet-sized package offering
a LifeStyles condom and a sample of new Dental Dots, dime-sized
pads soaked in mint toothpaste with adhesive backing to adhere to
the index finger for a quick cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to get some press on it, maybe on late-night TV,''
said John Stoltzfus, president of Dental Dots Inc. ``While it's a
serious product for good oral hygiene, it does lend itself to the
tongue-in-cheek approach,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The disposable fingertip toothbrush is the brainchild of
Stoltzfus' late identical twin brother, Bob, who during a long
illness was unable to get to the bathroom to brush his teeth. John
left his career in commercial real estate, developed special
equipment to make the product and founded Dental Dots in Reseda,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The new, patented toothbrush sells in blister packs of six for
about $2 in drugstores and other outlets. The promotion with
LifeStyles condoms is one of the racier for the company. Stoltzfus
is also talking to the hospitality industry, especially airlines
and hotel chains, about serving travelers in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   -PATRICIA WINTERS LAURO
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 2031EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4671 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-DIARY-$ADV22-NYT &LR;      08-20 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-$ADV22-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT BUSINESS TAKES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Aug. 22) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Higher (Tech) Calling
</P>
<P>
   New graduates of the Harvard Business School, traditionally able
to pick and choose in the job market, are increasingly drawn to
technology and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the old ways are gone. Consulting, the top career
choice for the school's new graduates since 1988, kept its place
this year. But only 22 percent chose it, compared with 38 percent
in 1995. And the new No. 2, superseding investment banking, was
high technology, up to 20 percent from 8 percent in 1995. Many who
chose it, according to the Aug. 2 issue of The Harbus, the school's
student newspaper, picked Internet-based businesses. In 1995, no
graduate went to such a company; this year, 12 percent of the class
did.
</P>
<P>
   One incentive is a new way of doing things, according to Tracy
Lawrence, a 1999 graduate who, with her classmate, Sasha
Novakovich, is setting up Shopforservice.com, which will help
consumers choose communications services.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a very young age,'' Ms. Lawrence said, ``you have the
opportunity to build or help shape a company from the ground up, to
revolutionize an industry or process.'' And there is another lure
in a field known for twenty-something millionaires _ ``a huge
potential financial upside,'' Ms. Lawrence said.
</P>
<P>
   _BARBARA IRELAND
</P>
<P>
   Business, Retirement and Taxes
</P>
<P>
   The labor market may be tight, but 80 percent of the 7.6 million
U.S. States companies with fewer than 100 employees lack retirement
plans, and 70 percent of those have no plans to start them,
according to the Spectrem Group, a consulting company in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Still, within two years, Spectrem found, 167,000 more small
companies do expect to start retirement plans, with 1.6 million
more workers likely to be covered.
</P>
<P>
   The study comes as congressional Republicans promote a $792
billion tax cut bill that would significantly increase the tax
benefits to business owners and their highest-paid workers in
retirement plans, while weakening rules that encourage offering
plans to lower-paid workers.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has vowed to veto the bill. But Rep. Rob
Portman, R-Ohio, and others say that if he does, Congress will pass
a separate bill this fall containing only the pension rule changes.
</P>
<P>
   _DAVID CAY JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
