<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHEPPARD-EXHUME-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BODY TO BE EXHUMED IN CIVIL SUIT IN SHEPPARD SLAYING  (ko) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Lawyers defending the state of Ohio against a
wrongful-imprisonment lawsuit brought by the son of Sam Sheppard,
the Ohio doctor whose murder trials inspired the television series
``The Fugitive,'' said on Friday that they would exhume the remains
of Marilyn Sheppard, Sheppard's wife, who was slain in July 1954.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuyahoga County prosecutor, William D. Mason, whose office
is defending the state, filed a motion on Friday to postpone the
trial, which is scheduled to begin on Oct. 18, so genetic and other
tests could be made on Mrs. Sheppard's body. Mason said that DNA
currently available from Mrs. Sheppard might be contaminated and
that new technology would allow for better analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Reese Sheppard, who has tried for years to clear his
father's name, filed the lawsuit in 1995 seeking monetary damages
for his father's wrongful imprisonment. Under Ohio law, the state
could be forced to pay $25,000 for each year of imprisonment, plus
lost income and other expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Sheppard spent 10 years in prison for his wife's murder, which
he said was committed by a bushy-haired intruder. He was sentenced
to life in prison in 1954, but the U.S. Supreme Court, citing the
unfair effect of pretrial publicity, later overturned his
conviction. Sheppard was acquitted in a second trial; he was freed
from prison in 1966 and died four years later.
</P>
<P>
   His body was exhumed last year, resulting in new DNA evidence
that his son's lawyer, Terry Gilbert, says rules out Sheppard's
involvement in the crime.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs say a window washer at the family home, Richard
Eberling, killed Mrs. Sheppard. DNA testing, Gilbert said, showed
that Eberling could not be excluded as a match with blood stains
found at the crime scene. Eberling, who was convicted of an
unrelated murder, died in prison last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
