<HEADLINE>
BUSH THE ELDER ON A PASSION FOR FISHING
</HEADLINE>
  
 Advance for Monday August 23 or thereafter  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former President  &UR; George Bush &LR;  gets charmingly mushy in a
``Letter From Maine'' paean to fishing in the latest issue of
Forbes FYI.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandkids love it when we speed to our fishing waters,'' he
says. ``They get restless if the mackerel don't bite. ... They need
to learn to calm down and to relax when we troll or cast. ... They
need to grow up, but I don't want them to do that. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 74 now, but I don't feel old. I meditate a lot when I am
out fishing. I wonder how many more years I will have to fish with
my sons, my grandkids. ... I want to teach Gigi, our youngest
grandchild, now 2 1/2 years old, how to fish. When the fish aren't
biting, I want to listen to her tell me what makes her happy and
what makes her cry. Maybe I can start next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't tell her I was president. I'll just try to tell her
about the wonders of life and have her understand that our family
is what matters. ... I will tell her I love her. And when she says,
`Are you crying?` I'll say, `Yes, but these are tears of joy. Older
guys do that, Gigi.' You can do that kind of thing when you go
fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S.  &UR; Michael Robertson  &LR; says ``he has it on good authority''
(which means he made it up) that  &UR; George W. Bush Jr.  &LR; sniffed coke,
drank Coke, burned coke in his fireplace, had sex with
 &UR; Cokie Roberts &LR;  and was planning on having sex with former  &UR; Mayor &LR; 
 &UR; Koch  &LR; of New York until somebody corrected him on the pronunciation
of the old guy's last name.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEARER, MY GOD TO THEE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Oprah Winfrey &LR;  wants to talk with the  &UR; Dalai Lama  &LR; (who'll be
in Chicago on August 28), but the Dalai Lama's people say he
doesn't have time. Why would he ``turn down the chance of a
lifetime to get his message into millions of American homes?'' asks
the Chicago Sun-Times.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Pope John Paul II &LR;  is holding ``secret auditions'' for a
performer to sing a hymn for the church's Millennium CD, says
MSBNC, which speculates that the front-runner is  &UR; Andrea Bocelli &LR; .
 &UR; Bob Dylan &LR;  is said to be a dark horse.
</P>
<P>
   _ Radio talk-show host Dr. &UR; Laura Schlessinger  &LR; says that when
she visited the Vatican on July 7, she presented the pope with a
copy of her book on the Ten Commandments. She told the Washington
Post that ``the pope stands for right or wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIES AND MISDEMEANORS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ When  &UR; Barbra Streisand &LR; , who fancies herself a savvy investor,
heard that thestreet.com was going public, she called its boss,
 &UR; Kevin English &LR; , and offered to trade four tickets to one of her
concerts for the chance to buy some shares. Some haggling took
place; ultimately, English told the New York Observer, Streisand
agreed to have dinner with his family and friends in exchange for a
piece of the financial action.
</P>
<P>
   English forked over ``a very modest amount of stock,'' he told
the Observer, but Streisand never came through with the dinner. ``I
feel a little bit used in that respect,'' said the street-man.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Saul Feldman  &LR; writes that the food was so good when he and
his wife were dining in a chic Basque restaurant in San Francisco
last week, &LR;  that they didn't flinch when they heard a woman at the
next table say, ``I could see myself dating a Jew but never a
Democrat.'' Instead, ``my wife started talking loudly about how we
should host a fund-raiser for  &UR; Bill Bradley &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LITTLETON VOLUNTEERS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Undertaker  &UR; John H. Horan &LR;  of Denver writes in the summer issue
of Mortuary Management that while he offered to ``serve without
charge'' after the Littleton shootings, he believed ``that a `free
funeral' was secondary to the importance for these families to say
goodbye in ways that were constructive and meaningful. It has been
our experience in providing low-cost or free services upon the
death of a child that parents are generally more concerned about
things being done right.''
</P>
<P>
   In an essay forwarded by  &UR; Bob Treuhaft &LR; , Horan reveals that he
persuaded the parents of  &UR; Dylan &LR;   &UR; Klebold &LR;  to have a funeral
service, which was ``accomplished privately and confidentially.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``After years of fabulously corrupt rock 'n' roll albums that
nobody ever bought, Newman gave it up for movie soundtrack work.
... His soundtracks might be fine for what they are, but in the
rock 'n' roll scheme of things, writing a good song for `Babe: Pig
in the City' is even more pathetic than writing a bad one.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Rob Sheffield on Randy Newman, in Rolling Stone. Sheffield
says ``Bad Love,'' Newman's new album, is ``great.''
</P>
