<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4674 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-2000-HNS &LR;      08-20 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PROMOTES GREATER RELIANCE ON FAITH-BASED GROUPS TO HELP
HOMELESS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AKRON, Ohio _ When Texas Gov. George W. Bush took a tour Friday
of the Haven of Rest Ministries, a Christian homeless shelter, he
stressed that if elected president he would promote greater
reliance on these faith-based organizations to take care of the
nation's poverty needs.
</P>
<P>
   While the leading presidential candidates in both parties,
Republican Bush and Democratic Vice President Al Gore, have
promoted faith-based groups in their campaign platforms, this
downtown homeless shelter may also provide a lesson in the
potential pitfalls of making federal government partners with
private religious groups.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Haven of Rest Ministries informed a prominent
local Jewish businessman, whose company had contributed to the
shelter, that he could not join the organization's board because he
was not a born-again Christian.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the shelter, which is currently funded privately,
defended their policy of hiring only born-again Christians, arguing
that they wanted to preserve the mission's religious nature.
Because they took no government money, they did not have to comply
with anti-discrimination laws.
</P>
<P>
   Under Bush's plans the federal government would not only provide
tax incentives for people to donate to such faith-based groups but
would also make it easier for these religious organizations to
receive government funding.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the Haven of Rest Ministries' programs would be
eligible for government funding despite its exclusionary employment
policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The programs should qualify,'' he said. ``The questions we
should ask is does it work ...We ought to be funding programs that
work. ``
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that he understands the reluctance of many of these
religious organizations to work with government because of fears
``of having to dilute their mission, the fear of having to forget
the reason they exist in the first place.``
</P>
<P>
   But Bush tried to assure them that he did not want to change the
religious nature of these efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel strongly that government should fund programs and
people. And the institutions that provide the love shouldn't have
to change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, even as he has called for faith-based institution to play
a larger role in humanitarian services, apparently has not directly
addressed the exclusion issue. But he has pointed to the special
nature of religious groups.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech in May, Gore called for ``clear and strict
safeguards'' but said faith-based organizations should be able to
use public funds for a range of operations ``without having to
alter the religious character that is so often the key to their
effectiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also set other limits saying:
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as there is always a secular alternative for anyone
who wants one, and as long as no one is required to participate in
religious observances as a condition for receiving services,
faith-based organizations can provide jobs and job training,
counseling and mentoring, food and basic medical care.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we should extend this carefully tailored approach to
other vital services where faith-based organizations can play a
role _ such as drug treatment, homelessness, and youth violence
prevention.''
</P>
<P>
   However, it may not be so easy to funnel taxpayer dollars to
these private groups that do not comply with federal policies,
which bar discrimination against people on the basis of religion.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a future Bush administration decided not to impose those
policies on private groups, there undoubtedly would be court
challenges if taxpayer money went to organizations that refused to
hire people of certain religions.
</P>
<P>
   John Green, a political science professor at the University of
Akron, said the Haven of Rest controversy does ``reveal the
problems government would have if it started funneling taxpayer
money through these groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Green added that ``it also reveals the problems groups would
have once they take government money and they start having to
change their mission.``
</P>
<P>
   The Haven of Rest Ministries was founded in 1943 as a shelter
for homeless women and children by Marjorie Ruth and C.C. Thomas,
devout Christians who initially rented a small office with 25
chairs, an upright piano and a pulpit . Their effort has grown to
include three buildings and 40 employees. It lodges 150 people a
night and provides 400 meals each day.
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning the shelter has stressed its Christianity
and requires all board members and staff, including janitors, to
sign a statement of faith annually that includes the belief in
``the absolute Deity of Jesus Christ.``
</P>
<P>
   However, in 1997 that policy came under question when the top
executive of a jewelry company, Terry Burman, took a tour of the
shelter and inquired if he could serve on its 15-member board of
trustees.
</P>
<P>
   Burman told the Akron Beacon-Journal that shelter officials told
him ``we only want members on our board that walk with the Lord and
know Him in a very special way.`` Burman canceled his company's
fund-raising efforts for the shelter.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time the compliance officer with the Ohio Civil
Rights Commission told the Akron Beacon Journal that the mission's
hiring policy was ``highly suspect.``
</P>
<P>
   This week the shelter's executive director, the Rev. Curt
Thomas, who is the son of the founders, said the board has no
intention of changing the practice of hiring only born-again
Christians.
</P>
<P>
   He defended the policy as the only way to ensure that the
shelter's program, which includes prayer services and Christian
counseling, remains true to its mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have Christian organization you must have a Christian
board, a Christian staff and a Christian program, '' Thomas said.
However, he said, the shelter takes in people regardless of their
religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas acknowledged that the board would be wary of taking
government funding because they ``would be a little nervous because
in the past there have been strings attached to it.``
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Thomas welcomed Bush's visit and the governor's
promotion of faith-based groups. Thomas said Bush found out about
his organization through the office of Ohio Gov. Bob Taft, who
accompanied the Texas governor on his tour.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
