<HEADER>
A4681 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS &LR;      08-20 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALVAREZ EXPECTED TO BOOST REVOLUTION MIDFIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Walter Zenga's first extended coaching experience has
not been pleasant. The Revolution have dropped into fifth place in
the Eastern Conference and seem no more resourceful than they were
during nine-game losing streaks of the last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But, now, the team is receiving a boost from its most
experienced players.
</P>
<P>
   Colombian Leonel Alvarez, acquired last week from Dallas in
exchange for Ariel Graziani, appears capable of stabilizing the
midfield. And, probably more important, Zenga himself will return
in goal for Saturday night's game at San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Zenga literally rescued the Revolution from a
nine-game losing streak, returning from a knee operation, as they
advanced to the playoffs for the only time in their 3 1/2-year
history. This time, Zenga has had to recuperate from a strained
left knee ligament suffered during a 0-0 regulation-time tie at
Colorado Aug. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga missed the Revolution's losses to San Jose (2-1) and Tampa
Bay (1-0). Though reserve Jeff Causey performed well most of the
time, the own goal he surrendered against the Clash was costly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bad period for us and everyone has to take
responsibility, but mine is doubled because I am the coach, also,''
Zenga said. ``I don't want to leave the team alone during a bad
time in the season. I want to stay on the field and win or lose
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga appeared to have a magic touch as player-coach with the
Revolution for a while. But it appears his greatest value to the
team is as a player. The Revolution's overall regulation-time
victory total is 34, and nearly half of those have been with Zenga
in goal. Without Zenga in goal, they are 18-49-8, and with him in
goal they are 16-20-7.
</P>
<P>
   This will be only the second time this season the Revolution
will have the same starting lineup of field players available for
two games in succession. But the team has yet to establish
continuity. Now, the Revolution must assimilate newcomers Alvarez
and Jeff Baicher, who was acquired from the Clash in exchange for
midfielder Jair, and is still adjusting to the absence of central
defender Dan Calichman (groin).
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can play the same players, it's better for everyone,''
Zenga said. ``We have 22 players on the roster and we have to be
able to use everybody, but if we can use the same 11 starters when
we need a win, it's good. We all need to take responsibility and go
on the field and play with pride and passion.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez brings credibility and versatility to his role and
should help bolster the Revolution's defense, better addressing the
team's vulnerabilities than Graziani, a striker. But Graziani
received few opportunities with the Revolution, but scored in his
debut for Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know in soccer,'' Zenga said. ``Graziani did not
score for us and he scores on his first touch with Dallas. But I
think Leonel Alvarez is a very, very strong player, a good
personality, and it's only unlucky for us that he came here so late
in the season. But it's never too late to play good soccer. We have
to go out now and give everything we have on the field.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
