<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4683 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JACKSON-PHYSICS-ART-2     08-20 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-PHYSICS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENSSELAER'S NEW PRESIDENT, A CRUSADER FOR WOMEN IN SCIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Calif., Ill., Washington, D.C.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, N.Y. _ The reason there are so few women in science is
self-evident to Yale computer scientist David Gelertner: ``Women
are less drawn to science and engineering than men are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why monkey with female predilections?'' Gelertner asked in the
June 21 issue of The Weekly Standard, at a time when the National
Science Foundation and other organizations have been encouraging
schools to recruit more women and minority members. ``The result is
a diversity crusade that insults women scientists and
nonscientists.'' Ultimately, he concluded, academic institutions
will start limiting the number of men who can major in the
sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Such opinions do not ruffle Shirley Ann Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   In a steady voice so soft it sometimes does not even register on
a tape recorder, she offers what sounds like a practiced response:
``The real issue is about choices, about having the opportunity and
the exposure, and you make a choice. I'm not talking about
quotas.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jackson has been on the front lines of such debates her
whole life. Forced to attend an all-black elementary school before
the Supreme Court outlawed segregation in 1954, she became the
first black woman in America to get a doctorate in physics in 1973.
(There has not been much change since. Only 10 black women received
doctorates in physics from 1988 to 1997, the National Science
Foundation reports.) She was the first black and the first woman to
head the Nuclear Regulatory Commission in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Now she is the new president of Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute
here, the nation's oldest university dedicated to science and
engineering, a black woman heading a school where 75 percent of the
students are men and 90 percent are white.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in her luxurious new presidential office, Ms. Jackson, a
small, prim woman with close-cropped hair, listed her immediate
goals. In addition to attracting more women and minorities, she
also wants to increase RPI's $500-million endowment, to raise its
frayed academic reputation and to expand basic research.
</P>
<P>
   During a two-hour interview, in which she calmly recalled being
shot at and spat on during her years as one of the few black
students at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, she appeared
to have a will as tough as polished steel. She has a reputation for
decisiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very inquisitive, always very much of a take-charge
person,'' said her oldest sister, Barbara Avery. ``She would have
an idea, like let's repaint the bathroom. She would start it and
then, after my other sister and brother got involved, she would
disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, Ms. Avery, who is dean of students at Loyola
Marymount College in Los Angeles, invited her sister along on a
hiking trip she organizes each summer for a group of black women.
After a few days of alternating leaders on the trail, Ms. Jackson
took charge, even though she had not done much hiking.
</P>
<P>
   ``She got us up the mountain and got us there better than anyone
did it before,'' Ms. Avery said. One of the other women on the trip
started calling Ms. Jackson ``the general.'' The name stuck and now
Ms. Jackson always carries the map and walks first.
</P>
<P>
   But if Ms. Jackson is assertive, she is not antagonistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shirley was never needlessly adversarial,'' said Paul Gray,
who was associate provost at MIT in 1968 when Ms. Jackson served as
a leader of the school's black students organization. He was asked
to head a committee to deal with a series of their demands and is
now a close friend of Ms. Jackson's.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had strong positions,'' he said. ``She spoke for them
eloquently. She held to them. But she did not engage in rancor or
denigration or demeaning people for the effect.''
</P>
<P>
   The Washington she experienced as head of a federal agency was
quite a distance from the Washington she knew as a child. Growing
up in the city's northwest section in the early 1950s, Ms. Jackson
could not attend a nearby elementary school reserved for whites.
Instead, she had to travel several miles to the black school in
another neighborhood _ an interesting inverse of the later debate
over busing to achieve racial integration, she now points out.
</P>
<P>
   She showed an interest in math and science from an early age,
and her parents strongly encouraged her as well as her brother and
two sisters. (``Shirley was always tinkering with things,''
recalled Ms. Avery.) Her father, who rose to become a supervisor at
the Postal Service, graduated from high school but never got the
chance to attend college. Her mother, an orphan who was reared by
older siblings, attended college but had to drop out for financial
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   All of the Jackson children excelled. Ms. Avery got her
doctorate in education; Gloria Joseph, her younger sister, is a
lawyer who is director of administration at the National Labor
Relations Board. (Their brother, who was the youngest, died 15
years ago.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jackson attributes her opportunity to pursue science to
lucky timing. Three years after segregation was outlawed in 1954,
the Soviet Union launched Sputnik, the world's first orbiting
satellite. Cold War fears that America was falling behind in the
space race led to a new emphasis on science and engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jackson took advantage of the trend to indulge her interests
in math, biology and chemistry. She also studied Latin for six
years. The experience shaped her view of what is needed to attract
more women and minorities to science.
</P>
<P>
   ``Careers in these areas are a cumulative process,'' she said.
``You can't talk about being a theoretical physicist if you can't
do calculus. You can't do calculus if you can't add, subtract,
multiply or divide and learn some geometry, algebra and
trigonometry. So I think for some underrepresented minorities it is
both a question of how hospitable the fields are and the
institutions that educate and train people, but it is fundamentally
also related to what people are exposed to early on.''
</P>
<P>
   A vice principal at Ms. Jackson's high school suggested that she
apply to MIT. There were 43 women in her freshman class of 900; one
other was black. Though Ms. Jackson experienced the indignities of
Jim Crow in the South, she said she was exposed to very little
overt racism until she arrived in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   At MIT, many of her fellow students shunned her, refusing to let
her participate in study groups or even to sit next to her in
class. Once, while in downtown Boston, she said she was shot at.
Another time, a group of men shouted racial epithets at her and one
spit in her face. Ms. Jackson persevered. ``It was important to not
just focus on myself but rather to understand that I had a
particular opportunity,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking barriers and being a role model can be burdensome, but
Ms. Jackson said she was not resentful. ``Well, if that were the
sum total of my life and the sum total of what people had to say
about me, then it would be disturbing,'' she said. ``But I guess I
am older now and so I am philosophical.'' Ms. Jackson said that if
her being identified as a first black or first woman opened doors
for others, then it's OK with her: ``At the end, I operate in terms
of what my legacy will be.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jackson did post-graduate work at the Fermi National
Accelerator Laboratory outside Chicago and the European
Organization for Nuclear Research in Geneva before joining Bell
Labs in New Jersey in 1976. There, she met her husband, Morris
Washington, who is also a physicist. The couple have a son who is
about to enter college.
</P>
<P>
   In her research, Ms. Jackson focused on the electronic and
optical properties of atomic particles within layers of different
materials, an important aspect in the design and manufacture of
semiconductors. But her experience as a student leader at MIT had
kindled an interest in public service.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, when Ms. Jackson was nominated to head the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission, several anti-nuclear groups opposed her
appointment because she had served on the boards of both Public
Service Electric and Gas, a utility that operates nuclear power
plants, and the Institute of Nuclear Power Operations, an
industry-backed watchdog organization.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Jackson ended up surprising the group. She shook up the
commission's staff, overhauled the procedure used to evaluate
safety performance at nuclear power plants and opened up commission
hearings to groups on both sides of the nuclear power debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our opinion she was the best chairman the NRC has ever had,
from a safety and public-awareness standpoint,'' said David
Lochbaum, a nuclear safety engineer with the Union of Concerned
Scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Avery said that her sister had a vulnerable side that people
outside of her family and close friends were rarely allowed see.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, during the annual hike with her sister and friends,
Ms. Avery recalled, the group came to some narrow logs thrown
across a deep creek. Ms. Jackson, in the lead as usual, walked over
without hesitating, giving the others confidence to follow.
</P>
<P>
   But later, as the group relaxed in the evening, Ms. Jackson
admitted that she had been frightened.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had known that she was afraid,'' her sister said, ``we
would have never have gone across.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
