<HEADER>
A4687 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-HILLARY-FUNDRAISER-BO     08-20 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-FUNDRAISER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON GOLFS, HILLARY POLITICKS AS VACATION UNFOLDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ Like so many First Ladies on so many summer
sojourns, Hillary Rodham Clinton would quietly slip into bookstores
and boutiques. She would lunch behind closed doors with authors and
artists. Then she would flash a smile and a fleeting wave to
bystanders as the Secret Service rushed her back to her island
retreat.
</P>
<P>
   In the public's eye, she was President Clinton's all-but-silent
partner on his first four getaways to Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   Now this: As Bill Clinton Friday played as private a round of
golf as a president can play, Mrs. Clinton happily thrust herself
into the laserlike spotlight of the national media, playing to the
cameras in a carefully orchestrated event at a landmark Nantucket
whaling church as she pursued her historic evolution from
presidential spouse to US Senate candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The first full day of the Clinton family's vacation had hardly
begun and already one fact was as clear as a ship bell's peel. With
Bill Clinton entering the twilight of his lame-duck presidency, the
Hillary Era has dawned.
</P>
<P>
   Before the day ended, Mrs. Clinton raised more than $100,000 for
her Senate campaign and was honored during a dinner for the
American Ireland Fund, a recognition that could boost her candidacy
with New York's vast Irish American population.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who followed his wife to the podium at the
American Ireland Fund event, praised Mrs. Clinton's peace efforts
in a way that also hinted at their divergent political
trajectories.
</P>
<P>
   ''The women are doing better than the men now,'' Clinton said.
He paused amid the crowd's laughter, then added, ''in promoting
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hillary Era could dissolve as quickly as it began if Mrs.
Clinton abandons her exploratory campaign for a Senate seat from
New York, or if she enters the race and loses. She has all but
announced her intention to seek the seat being vacated by Senator
Daniel P. Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   But as Mrs. Clinton showed Friday in a whirlwind tour of
Nantucket, she no longer is curling up with a book in the family's
borrowed home on the Vineyard while the president pursues his
marathon quest to perfect his golf game. Clinton played Friday at
the swank Nantucket Golf Club with a foursome that included Senator
John F. Kerry.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Bill Clinton's visit to Nantucket was said to be the
first by a sitting president, the golf match was kept so private
that news photographers never saw enough of Clinton to capture a
single image.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Mrs. Clinton was on center stage for hours,
starting with an appearance to boost a restoration project at the
175-year-old United Methodist Church on Nantucket. As photographers
jostled for position in a scene that a pool reporter described as
''pandemonium,'' Mrs. Clinton appealed from the altar for donors to
help preserve the building as ''a real gift to the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton announced that $51,000 of the $148,000 needed for
the second phase of the restoration had been raised. And she tried
to boost the fund-raising effort by warning that the church's
demise would provide further evidence that ''we live in a real
throw-away culture.''
</P>
<P>
   With New York reporters hanging on every word, Mrs. Clinton
skirted any talk of the Senate race. Her only reference to New York
was praise for an effort to preserve Harriet Tubman's house there.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton left the church to cheers and applause from the
crowd outside, and she enthusiastically greeted scores of onlookers
before she continued her tour of the island, including a shopping
excursion. The crowd responded in kind, as they had when the
Clintons arrived the day before at Martha's Vineyard Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd be pleased to vote for her in the primary and the general
election,'' said Mary Flanagan, 42, of Port Washington, N.Y., a
summer resident of Nantucket.
</P>
<P>
   Others were less enamored of Mrs. Clinton, who has been a
lightning rod for criticism at least since her prominent role in
the president's failed effort in 1993 to overhaul the nation's
health care system.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after David Stein, a corporate consultant from New York,
expressed awe Thursday at shaking President Clinton's hand at the
Martha's Vineyard Airport, Stein said he was ''unimpressed'' by
meeting Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't in any way get a charge out of shaking her hand,''
Stein said. ''I'd rather shake Robert DiNiro's hand than Hillary's
any day.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein, like many New Yorkers, said he remains uncertain about
Mrs. Clinton's motives for exploring a New York Senate race. ''I'm
not sure if she is really looking to help New York or using us as a
step ladder,'' said Stein, 52, who lives in Mahopac, N.Y., and has
a summer home in West Tisbury.
</P>
<P>
   Yet more than 100 supporters donated at least $1,000 each at a
private reception  &UR; last night &LR;  to help fund Mrs. Clinton's
prospective Senate race. The reception was held at the sprawling,
Nantucket mansion of the former US ambassador to Portugal,
Elizabeth Bagley, where Clinton earlier in the day recorded his
weekly radio address that is scheduled to be broadcast Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Bagley estate, like many in the area, flew the flags of the
United States and Ireland, as did the home of Bob and Mia Matthews,
who hosted the American Ireland Fund dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy was supposed to co-host the Matthews
event but didn't show up. Those close to the senator said he is
still exhausted by the death of his nephew, John F. Kennedy Jr.,
and his wife and her sister. Kennedy has not kept a public schedule
since Congress recessed earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   If Kennedy does not hold court with the president during this
vacation, it will be the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The Bagley event marked the first time the president formally
spoke on Mrs. Clinton's behalf at a fundraiser. But in the end, the
day belonged to Mrs. Clinton, as, in the public's eye, might the
rest of the vacation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tina Cassidy of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
