<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-TOWN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORGANIZING RESCUE EFFORTS REMAINS A CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TURKEY-QUAKE, TURKEY-TOWN, TURKEY-AID) 
(rk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEGIRMENDERE, Turkey _ This summer resort town on the Sea of
Marmara lost more than 1,000 lives in the earthquake, and Friday
the town square was full of survivors trying to figure out how to
marshal the relief effort.
</P>
<P>
   In the first day after the quake struck, Degirmendere felt
stranded, begging the authorities and volunteers to bring them
essentials like food and body bags. But by Friday trucks were
clogging the main road, delivering tomatoes, bread, bottled water
and used clothing, dumping them into piles that were spilling off
sidewalks onto the roadway.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the chaos stood Mayor Akalin Ertugryl, his eyes
bleary and his hands shaking from exhaustion, trying to pull
together a relief effort that was spinning off in different
directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no problem with food,'' he said as he interrupted a
delegation of anxious women to talk to a Turkish military officer
who had arrived to oversee the rescue effort. ``The civilian and
military authorities are working together, but it is not so
organized.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the mayor and others in the town, Degirmendere is
now able to tend to its dead, but its biggest concern now is
medicine for the growing number of people suffering from dysentery
and other stomach ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road at a crisis center set up by the Turkish military
outside the Golcuk Naval Base, the atmosphere was more orderly.
There Vice Adm. Bulent Alpkaya was meeting with his staff,
dispatching the three engineering brigades called in to oversee the
rescue effort in Degirmendere and in Golcuk, one of the hardest-hit
cities.
</P>
<P>
   The headquarters of the naval base collapsed on the night of the
quake, killing many high-ranking officers who had gathered for a
celebration. Alpkaya said 146 people had been killed and 127
rescued. Work continues to clear the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just yesterday in the city we took 28 children out of the
rubble, all of them alive,'' he said. ``We have airlifted 600
people to Istanbul hospitals and have established an air bridge to
Ankara so that hospitals here can continue to take in new
arrivals.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day, every hour, it is getting more organized,'' the
admiral said.
</P>
<P>
   Teams of rescue workers from France, Israel, Russia, Germany and
Britain are in the Golcuk area, working around the clock. But
Alpkaya said more experts and equipment are needed to recover the
survivors and the victims still believed to be in the rubble.
</P>
<P>
   The French team _ made up of 61 rescue workers, four doctors,
six dogs and a veterinarian _ spent 12 hours, using sophisticated
cameras and heat sensitive devices, pulling two people out of one
collapsed building, Col. Bernard Modere said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This type of reinforced concrete construction, if it doesn't
flatten out completely, can leave spaces where people can remain
alive,'' he said. ``If the people are in those spaces, they can
survive up to a week.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The work is gigantic,'' he said. ``And there is never enough
help _ that is the definition of a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last two days, several boatloads of Istanbul University
students have been arriving at the Golcuk navy base, eager to help
the rescue effort. Some came bearing brand new shovels and pick
axes, hard hats and gardening gloves, as well as boxes and bags of
bread, toilet paper, disposable diapers, juice and milk.
</P>
<P>
   But as the rescue work moves into its final stages, requiring
trained specialists or heavy machinery, the volunteers were finding
that their help was in many cases superfluous.
</P>
<P>
   After the four-hour boat ride from Istanbul, one group from the
Istanbul Technical University was greeted by an instructor who told
them they might have to turn around and go back.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, jobs for the students were found, carrying rubble
off rescue sites or unloading cartons of goods off the boats and
trucks. ``We are not trained to do anything else,'' one young woman
said.
</P>
<P>
   But for many Turks, the rescue operations were a woeful reminder
of how unprepared Turkey is to deal with a powerful earthquake,
even though much of the country and most of its population are in
high-risk zones.
</P>
<P>
   The Turkish teams do not have search dogs or the sort of
equipment that the foreign crews brought with them. And the
volunteer effort was ad hoc, thrown together by sympathetic
enthusiasts at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of Turkey's biggest problems is the lack of
nongovernmental organizations,'' said Haran Ilhan, a graduate of
the Technical University who turned up on the boat Friday with
classmates drawn together by a blitz of faxes and e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   The same lament was echoed Friday in newspaper columns in which
commentators noted that Turkey is now paying the price for a
political system that has discouraged the growth of civic
associations, for fear that they would challenge the authority of
the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I for one would direct an accusing finger at those in
authority who never trust their own people,'' wrote Fehmi Koru, a
columnist for the English-language Turkish Daily News. He spoke of
those in authority ``who feel forever uneasy when they see the
people mobilizing as responsible civilians to take their fate in
their own hands, and who've consistently forbidden them to organize
into either religious or nonreligious groups.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
