<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4692 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV22-B     08-20 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV22-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO DISCO, PLEASE, WE'RE TRADE REPS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 22, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When New Zealand's Mike Moore takes over next month as director
general of the World Trade Organization, he faces a tall order. For
starters, he has to get ready in just three months for the trade
ministers' December meeting in Seattle at which a complicated new
round of negotiations lasting many years is expected to commence.
</P>
<P>
   A fast start is only part of the problem facing Moore. He must
prepare to make a fast finish, too. After a year-long stand-off
between industrial and developing nations failed to produce a
consensus candidate, they agreed to split between them the director
general's six-year term. Moore gets three years, and Supachai
Panitchpakdi serves for three years after that.
</P>
<P>
   In certain ways, it is a good progression. Moore, 50, is an
unusually attractive combination, a labor movement visionary and
free trader whose most recent tract is called ``A History of the
Future.'' He catapulted to prominence 1972 when he became the
youngest member ever elected to New Zealand's parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Panitchpakdi, 53, is a Rotterdam University economist turned
bureaucrat. He was Thailand's deputy prime minister during the
recent crisis and, not surprisingly, was often critical of the
austerity measures prescribed by the International Monetary Fund.
As a result, the United States worked vigorously behind the scenes
to keep him out of the job. But none doubt his commitment to the
principles of free trade.
</P>
<P>
   Neither man resembles his predecessors: the geopolitical
strategist Arthur Dunkel (he sometimes carried along the ten-year
Uruguay Round of negotiations on sheer strength of will); or ramrod
Peter Sutherland, who brought the treaty to its successful
completion in 1994; or even the affable Renato Ruggiero, who
breathed life into the fledgling World Trade Organization (though
Moore joked that his chief credential for the job was that he
looked a lot like Ruggiero.)
</P>
<P>
   It may not matter much, though, now that globalization has
entered a new realm of political sophistication, with the
highly-visible WTO succeeding the hidden-in-plain-sight General
Agreement on Tarrifs and Trade, or GATT.
</P>
<P>
   Because the United States is far and away the world's biggest
trading nation, much depends on the results of the next US
elections, congressional and presidential. But the rest of the
world has grown a great deal, so progress on trade also depends
critically on the ability of the WTO head to serve as a kind of
referee, leaning against the tendency of the United States to
insist that every disputed call go in its favor.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertain prospects were underscored last month in a two-day
meeting at Columbia University, sponsored by the university's law
school and its economics department. Present were a number of
senior figures from the trade commuity. The meeting was conceived
by Columbia economist Jagdish Bhagwati (who served for a time as
chief economic adviser to Arthur Dunkel) as a way of scouting out
the agenda for Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus seemed to be that there was no consensus.
</P>
<P>
   Among trade experts, the someday wish-list consists of generally
agreed-upon ``rules of the game'' in at least three new broad
areas.
</P>
<P>
   With respect to investment, hopes for a global agreement have
been chilled by the breakdown of talks aimed at an MAI (as a
Multilateral Agreement on Investment is known to the acronym happy
world of trade diplomacy) among the members of the Organization for
Economic Cooperation and Development.
</P>
<P>
   If 23 broadly similar European nations can't agree on where to
draw the line between national sovereignty and global investment
guidelines, what hope is there that the larger community of nations
can agree on matters ranging from capital movements to intellectual
property protection.
</P>
<P>
   With respect to competition, the differences are even more
pronounced. In the United States, the measures designed to ensure
that firms compete with one another for the benefit of consumers
are known as the antitrust statutes. But few other countries have
embraced such tough prohibitions, and in many cultures
price-fixing, group boycotts, and other forms of cartel conduct
have an honored place, to say nothing of the higher forms of
restraint of trade.
</P>
<P>
   The most controverial measures of all have to do with the
so-called ``linkage issues.'' These determined attempts to address
environmental and labor issues in the forum of the World Trade
Organization are the newly-discovered enthusiasm of large numbers
of activists. Representatives of some 600 NGOs (non-governmental
organizations) plan to converge on Seattle in December to plead
their cases _ everything from global warming to child labor to
animal rights.
</P>
<P>
   Trade specialists often respond that environmental and social
issues should be pursued mainly in other venues, such as the
International Labor Organization, the World Health Organization,
and the United Nations Childrens Fund, or UNICEF. ``The usual rule
is that to kill two birds you need two stones,'' says economist
Bhagwati. ``Otherwise you risk missing both birds.''
</P>
<P>
   But the new visibility of the WTO has made it irresistable to
those seeking change. The best hope is that new and more
disciplined forums will arise for airing the concerns of consumers,
labor, business and environmental groups, and that new mechanisms
for creating consensus will emerge.
</P>
<P>
   The high stakes of a new round of trade negotiations was
illustrated nicely by the US National Intelligence Council's
convening earlier this month of a elaborate mock ministerial
meeting behind tightly closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   As reported by Mark Suzman of the Financial Times, the US
Central Intelligence Agency (and spies in most other countries)
have turned to commercial intelligence now that the Cold War has
waned. Agents, former trade diplomats and academics took turns
trying to anticipate the bargaining strategems that others nations
are expected to bring to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Ambitious new undertakings on investment and competition
policies are unlikely to emerge from Seattle, despite the fond
hopes of companies like Boeing and Microsoft (which have paid
handsomely for the privilege of serving as hosts.) The NGOs
probably will upstage the formal proceedings. Uncertainty over the
elections will render diplomats more cautious than usual.
</P>
<P>
   What then, if anything, may be expected from a new round of
negotitions? In the absence of a preliminary consensus among the
rich and poor nations of the world, the best strategy would be to
aim low.
</P>
<P>
   The best that can be hoped for from a Seattle round would be
another few years of work on lower trade barriers and improving
mechanisms for dispute resolution _ the basic blocking and tackling
of trade diplomacy. ``I heard one negotiator complaining that
merely reducing trade barriers is a dull business,'' says Bhagwati.
``He was a trade diplomat wanting more action -- for which he
should probably go to a disco.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
