<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FELLS-ACRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FELLS ACRES CASE RUNS COUNTER TO TREND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The cases are strikingly similar, the outcomes
radically different.
</P>
<P>
   In notorious day care center sexual abuse cases in California,
New Jersey and North Carolina, convicted abusers were let out of
jail or exonerated on appeal after lengthy, divisive
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, freedom came for the defendants after testimony
by child witnesses was judged to have been coerced or tainted by
overly aggressive investigators. In others, jurors found the
accounts of some children too fantastic, or the prosecution's
evidence inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for years, Cheryl Amirault LeFave's attorneys and supporters
made similar arguments on her behalf in the Fells Acres case, and a
Superior Court judge agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's all but certain that LeFave will be returning to
prison within a month after the state Supreme Judicial Court
rejected those arguments earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews with prosecutors, defense attorneys, academics and
sex-abuse specialists, reasons for the difference are as divergent
and passionate as the opinions and emotions aroused by the case
itself.
</P>
<P>
   In a unanimous decision Wednesday, the six-member court ruled
that Superior Court Judge Isaac Borenstein erred when he determined
in 1997 that LeFave and her mother, Violet Amirault, also convicted
in the case, had an inadequate defense at trial.
</P>
<P>
   The justices also rejected the argument, raised in Borenstein's
1998 decision, that LeFave should have gotten a new trial because
her appellate lawyers found new evidence that children's testimony
can be tainted.
</P>
<P>
   To some legal experts, there are subtle but critical factual
distinctions between the Fells Acres case and the others. Some of
those cases fell apart because of inconsistent evidence, others
failed due to recanted testimony from the child victims.
</P>
<P>
   For example, at the Virginia McMartin Preschool in affluent
Manhattan Beach, Calif., a 1983 abuse claim led to charges against
seven people, including McMartin and her son. But seven years
later, after two defendants had spent time in jail, a jury
deadlocked in 1990 and the case was dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the matter cost more than $13 million, making it the
longest and most expensive trial in US history.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, prosecutors in North Carolina abandoned their case
against the Little Rascals day care center, where 29 children had
alleged sexual abuse _ but not before two defendants were convicted
and spent time behind bars. Their convictions were ultimately
overturned.
</P>
<P>
   Still others attribute the different outcomes to the varying
personalities of the courts that tried _ and often retried _ the
abuse cases.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, the Amirault controversy ``is probably one of
the most difficult cases the legal community . . . has had to
wrestle with,'' said Boston attorney Thomas Hoopes, a criminal
defense specialist and former Middlesex County prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see really well-intentioned people on both sides taking very
strong opinions and having very strong beliefs, but the bottom line
in this case is that it's just very hard,'' Hoopes said.
``Sometimes there are powerfully conflicting forces in a case, and
the more diametrically opposed and more powerful they are, the
harder it is to weigh them.''
</P>
<P>
   Several local attorneys attribute last week's decision by the
Supreme Judicial Court to deny LeFave a new trial, effectively
sending her back to jail, to the high court's inherent
conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that is absolutely clear is that this outcome had
nothing to do with the Amiraults,'' said Thomas G. Gutheil, a
professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School who has testified
in numerous abuse cases. ``It can only be about the political and
judicial system here.''
</P>
<P>
   Gutheil and others contend that the SJC's ruling was influenced
by politics and administrative expediency as well as the desire to
end once and for all a case that has lingered in the state's court
system for 15 years. They also charge that the SJC didn't want to
risk the embarrassment of changing a position it had staked out
years before.
</P>
<P>
   If that is the case, some legal scholars say, then the justices'
ruling may have come at the expense of fairness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will never know what happened at Fells Acres, just like the
communities that suffered through the other multiple abuse cases .
. . will never know with certainty'' if the defendants were guilty
or innocent, said Boston attorney Martin Weinberg, director of the
National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in a democracy, unlike in an accusatory system, when
there's uncertainty citizens remain free. It's the fundamental
notion of our nation's heritage, and I think that's been challenged
in this community.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the SJC's ruling reject claims that the court's
decision was driven by anything but a careful review of the
evidence and testimony in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many of the other cases, courts found technical reasons for
overturning convictions,'' said Boston attorney Laurence Hardoon,
the former lead prosecutor in Amirault case who is now in private
practice, ``so I don't think you can look at those cases and
conclude they were erroneously prosecuted.''
</P>
<P>
   And in several out-of-state cases, area lawyers noted,
prosecutors said they dropped charges not because their cases were
weak, but because they did not want to put the alleged victims
through the emotional toll of a retrial.
</P>
<P>
   If there is any consistent sentiment, it is that few people, if
any, have scrutinized the various cases both individually and
collectively in an effort to draw contrasts, comparisons and,
ultimately, conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very bad things that happen to kids and very bad
accusuations that are made against people that haven't done
anything wrong,'' said Stuart Grassian, a forensic psychiatrist who
studies sexual abuse. ``We have to be incredibly sober and humble
in trying to distinguish one from the other, because the
consequences of making wrong decisions in either case are so
overwhelming.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 2100EDT &QL; 
