<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4698 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GA-TOBACCO21-COX     08-20 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-TOBACCO21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia governor appoints board to oversee tobacco settlement
distribution
 &HT;    By Alan Judd
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gov. Roy Barnes has given an $80,000-a-year part-time
job to a former state revenue commissioner whose agency once lost
track of $1.5 billion in sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes announced Friday that Marcus Collins, who ran the state
Revenue Department from 1983 until he resigned under fire following
a critical audit in 1996, will be executive director of the new
Georgia Tobacco Community Development Board. The panel will
distribute money from the tobacco settlement to farmers.
</P>
<P>
   To remain eligible to draw his annual $55,646 state pension,
Collins, 72, will work no more than 20 hours a week _ an hourly
wage of almost $77. In the new part-time job, Collins will almost
match his old salary from his full-time job as revenue
commissioner, which was $81,400 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, along with a six-member board also appointed Friday,
will oversee about $22 million a year in payments to the state's
tobacco farmers. The money, which will be paid for 12 years, comes
from a secondary agreement to the state's $4.8 billion settlement
from the tobacco industry. His salary will come from the settlement
proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   Collins' appointment drew criticism from those who remembered
his departure from the Revenue Department, which followed the
disclosure that his agency had reimbursed cities and counties based
on estimates because it couldn't accurately track sales tax
receipts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty thousand dollars a year for 20 hours a week of work?
Cronyism is alive and well,'' said Senate Minority Leader Eric
Johnson (R-Savannah). ``I just hope he doesn't lose any of the
money.''
</P>
<P>
   But a spokeswoman for Barnes defended the appointment, which
will be made official when the new board meets in Atlanta on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marcus Collins is very knowledgeable about farming issues,''
said Joselyn Butler, the governor's press secretary. ``That,
combined with his experience in government, the governor felt, made
him ideally suited to the position.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As for the problems at Revenue,'' Butler added, ``a lot of
that was not of his making.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins, who has earned $40,266 a year _ in addition to his
pension _ as a part-time aide to House Speaker Tom Murphy since
1997, will be eligible for benefits from the fund he will oversee,
since he grows tobacco on his farm near the Mitchell County town of
Cotton. At Barnes' request, the state attorney general's office
issued an advisory opinion saying such payments would not violate
the law.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at his home Friday, Collins said that if his new job
requires more than 20 hours a week, ``I'll donate the time.''
</P>
<P>
   But he declined to discuss how his new salary was set.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I say won't have any effect on what you write,'' he told
a reporter. ``You can write anything you care to.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff Writer Peter Mantius contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
