<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4699 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-JAPAN-BANKS-ART-2TAKE     08-20 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-BANKS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE JAPANESE BANKS TO UNITE TO FORM WORLD'S LARGEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also JAPAN-BANKS-REACT) 
(ART ADV: Two graphics are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Japan signaled the start of a far-reaching consolidation
of its bloated and debt-ridden banking system Friday with official
word that three of the country's biggest banks would unite to form
the world's largest financial institution.
</P>
<P>
   The merger agreement announced by Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank Ltd.,
Industrial Bank of Japan Ltd. and Fuji Bank Ltd. was viewed by
economists and investors as a significant change, but not because
of the combination's colossal size. Rather, they said it would
hasten mergers among other Japanese banks, winnowing the weakest
and helping to reduce what has been one of the biggest drags on the
Japanese economy.
</P>
<P>
   Banks in Japan have suffered from years of bad loans, low
profits and antiquated technology despite numerous government
efforts to strengthen the system. Many continue to lose money or
are marginally profitable but there has been little pressure on
them to find partners. Analysts said the three-way tie-up announced
Friday, which was strongly endorsed by government officials,
suggested that era was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Size of course is not everything, but this does show a major
change in the mindset of Japanese bank management,'' said J. Brian
Waterhouse, an analyst for HSBC James Capel. ``Up until this year,
Japanese banks were determined to be independent, and suddenly we
have three major banks getting together.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement caused a surge in bank shares on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange, as investors bet that the 18 major Japanese banks
would eventually fall to fewer than half that number and make the
survivors far more profitable simply by reducing the number of
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   While executives of the three Japanese merger partners said they
were determined to become a global force, American and European
banks saw little competitive threat from the combination, nor did
they see it as an obstacle to a push by foreign banks to enter
Japan's market.
</P>
<P>
   The three-way alliance, which the partners hope to formally
establish by the fall of 2000, would create a giant with $1.3
trillion in assets, the benchmark for measuring a bank's size.
</P>
<P>
   It would dwarf the current world leader, Deutsche Bank AG, which
has $866 billion in assets, as well as the biggest American bank,
Citigroup, which has $668 billion. The bank also would be twice the
size of what is now Japan's largest bank, the Bank of
Tokyo-Mitsubishi, which has about $580 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although we will be the world's top bank in terms of assets,
we will not remain content just at that,'' Masao Nishimura,
Industrial Bank's president, told a news conference. ``We aim to be
among the world's top five banks in terms of capital, profits,
services and other areas.''
</P>
<P>
   The union of three major Japanese banks comes at a time when
there have been signs of a revival in the Japanese economy, which
has been suffering through the worst recession since World War II.
The yen, the most visible symbol of the country's economic might,
has risen to the strongest levels in seven months. Japan's stock
market has soared this year on a bet by many international
investors that the country may finally be turning around.
</P>
<P>
   The banking merger in Japan also comes against a backdrop of
consolidation among the biggest banks elsewhere. Deutsche Bank
recently acquired Bankers Trust Corp. of the United States,
Citicorp and Travelers Inc. merged in the United States, UBS was
created through the combination of Switzerland's two biggest banks
and France's Banque Nationale de Paris is acquiring control of
rival Paribas.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Japanese merger deal, the three partners will put
their retail banking, investment banking and brokerage subsidiaries
under common management and cut costs by combining overlapping
businesses. The banks said that by uniting, they also expected to
save on the huge costs of installing new information technology.
</P>
<P>
   The banks said that once the merger becomes complete they plan
to eliminate 6,000 jobs, reducing the entire work force to about
29,000 people, and cut the total number of branches from the
current 704 to 620.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said that the employee reductions did not go far
enough and reflected what they called a resistance on the part of
Japanese banks to shed one of the biggest drains on profitability,
a bloated work force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite their size, I'm rather skeptical that they can compete
on an international scale unless they undertake some serious
restructuring,'' said Toru Nakakita, a professor of economics at
Tokyo University. ``I hate to say this but I think we've created
another Titanic: We have the biggest bank in the world but it's
certainly not the most competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said that unless such mergers make banks more profitable,
they would not help the banks absorb the hundreds of billions of
dollars in bad debts that still litter their books. The government
has sought to help by slashing interest rates to nearly zero, which
lowers the cost of borrowing for the banks, and has injected money
into the largest banks to strengthen them. But many of these old
debts, vestiges of loans made during the speculative real estate
boom in the 1980s, will never be repaid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's evident that this government is better at reforming the
banking system than previous governments,'' said Mary Davis, chief
economist for emerging markets in Asia at Credit Suisse First
Boston in London. If such mergers strengthen the banks, she said,
``it could be a significant development, but they've had this
enormous bad debt problem which they have just begun to address and
there's so much more to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the size of the three-way merger, industry officials and
analysts said Friday that they doubted Japanese regulators would
challenge it as anticompetitive. ``Regulators think that there are
too many banks in Japan, so merging banks makes it easier to
improve profits,'' said Yoshinobu Yamada, an analyst for Merrill
Lynch. ``I'd be surprised if the government tries to block this.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Hakuo Yanagisawa, chairman of the Financial
Reconstruction Commission, Japan's regulatory body, said: ``We
sincerely welcome the move, which meets expectations for creating a
top-notch institution from Japan that can withstand stiff
international competition.''
</P>
<P>
   The shares of all three banks, which rose Thursday on news that
they were in talks, surged Friday on the announcement of a deal.
Shares of Dai-Ichi Kangyo gained 11 percent, Fuji rose 9.4 percent
and Industrial Bank of Japan rose 10.2 percent. The Tokyo Stock
Exchange's bank index, a measure of bank stocks, rose 10.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The three banks are among 15 major Japanese banks that received
7.5 trillion yen (about $675 billion) in public funds from the
government to help resolve their massive loan problems.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for the cash infusion, the banks agreed to
restructure their operations and become more profitable. The banks
are now under pressure to make good on those promises.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the three banks that plan to unite said Friday that
they planned to concentrate investment in computer systems for
payment settlements, management of databases, credit risk
assessments and other electronic banking operations.
</P>
<P>
   Most Japanese banks are far behind their foreign competitors in
the use of computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, the three banks will jointly establish a
holding company by the fall of 2000. Bank operations will be
gradually integrated into the holding company over a two-year
period.
</P>
<P>
   Individual shares of the three banks will be exchanged for a new
share in the holding company, which will be listed on stock
exchanges after the three banks exit the exchanges, the banks said.
</P>
<P>
   Two other major Japanese banks Friday confirmed their intention
to combine operations under a similar holding company arrangement,
which could also lead to a merger. In response to inquiries from
local reporters, a spokesman for Tokai Bank Ltd. and Asahi Bank
Ltd. said the two institutions planned to establish a joint holding
company in the year 2001. The banks originally announced the deal
last September.
</P>
<P>
   The combined assets of the two banks are about $531 billion,
which would make the new entity Japan's second-largest bank and the
seventh-largest worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not scale that we are aiming for in this union,'' said
Tsuyoshi Yamashita, a spokesman for Tokei Bank. ``We are investing
in our ability to offer customers a wider range of products. For
example, it's too costly for us to do investment banking along, so
we are seeking mutual effectiveness with our merger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
