<HEADER>
A4703 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-NYT &LR;      08-20 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SEEKS TO SHIFT DRUG DISCUSSION TO CAMPAIGN ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BUSH-STYLE) 
(ko) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAIRLAWN, Ohio _ Gov. George W. Bush, finishing his first tough
week on the Presidential campaign trail, tried Friday to use the
stir over his answers about possible drug use as proof of the need
to elevate American politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of this country reject trash-mouth politics, and so
do I,'' Bush told 363 Republicans who paid $1,000 a plate to hear
him at a lunch here. ``The people of this country want a campaign
that is positive and hopeful and optimistic. I will have a campaign
that appeals to our better angels, not our darker impulses.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor dealt with drugs in the speech, saying
children should be told that ``drugs will destroy you.'' But
neither here nor at an earlier news conference in Akron did the
topic that has followed him all week arise directly: whether he
ever used illegal drugs and why he will not deny it, if he had not.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference Bush gave another awkward answer, like
those earlier in the week in which he stated periods during which
he did not use drugs, that have made the issue linger rather than
go away.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked what he thought parents from the baby boom
generation should say, after telling a child not to use drugs, if
the child asked, ``Well, did you?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush replied: ``I think the baby boomer parent ought to say,
`I've learned from mistakes I may or may not have made. And I'd
like to share some wisdom with you.'''
</P>
<P>
   The governor, who has large leads in fund raising and public
opinion polls in the race for next year's Republican presidential
nomination, looked tired as he stopped first at the Haven of Rest
Ministries in Akron, an example of the faith-based institutions he
says the government should rely on more to help solve social
problems. But he seemed more at ease with reporters than on
Wednesday, the second day of the first storm to hit his campaign,
which had been sailing smoothly until now.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's complaints, both at the news conference and later in his
speech here, challenged the occasionally intense personal
questioning of presidential candidates, a recent reality of
American politics. But what he has been through this week does not
even remotely compare with the interrogations faced by Sen. Gary
Hart before he dropped out of the Democratic race in 1987, or by
Bill Clinton, who withstood accusations of adultery and
draft-dodging before winning the Democratic nomination in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the resonance of the issue has been Bush's claim
to success in fighting crime and drugs as governor. In 1997 there
were 26,436 arrests for possession of cocaine in Texas, and by
1998, the last year for which data are available, cocaine arrests
had increased to 28,158, Mike Cox, the spokesman for the Texas
Department of Public Safety, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the state's prison system, 13,501 inmates are being held on
various cocaine charges, including possession, sale and
manufacturing. That is about 10 percent of the state's prison
population.
</P>
<P>
   About 90 percent of first-time offenders caught selling or
possessing one gram or less of illegal drugs are given probation,
said Tony Fabelo, executive director of the State's Criminal
Justice Policy Council, a state agency. Bush secured passage of a
law that gives judges the option of probation or jail; previously,
probation was required by law.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, other than saying he would not discuss what he had
told his own daughters, the governor spoke about the drug issue in
generational terms. At the news conference he said, ``I think
parents, particularly baby-boomer parents, ought to say to
children, `Do not use drugs.'''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``One of the interesting questions facing baby boomers
is, Have we grown up? Are we willing to share the wisdom of past
mistakes?''
</P>
<P>
   At the luncheon, Bush was enthusiastically introduced by a
Republican colleague, Gov. Bob Taft, who said, ``Ohio is Bush
country,'' and by the Rev. Jim Wright of the St. Thomas Greek
Orthodox Church, who said in his invocation that Bush would
``restore dignity and honor not only to the Presidency but to the
politics of our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush used those themes himself. He told the applauding diners
that if elected President he would not only ``swear to uphold the
law of the land, but I will also swear to uphold the dignity and
the honor of the office to which I have been elected, so help me,
God.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to elevate politics,'' he said, ``after a time of
tarnished ideals.''
</P>
<P>
   On general policy questions, Bush covered familiar ground.
Arguing for more reliance on institutions like the Haven of Rest
Ministry, he declared that ``while government can hand out money,
it cannot put hope in our hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   He called for tax cuts, saying, ``I support reducing marginal
rates so we can continue to have high-quality, high-paying jobs in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   And he defined his philosophy of compassionate conservatism this
way: ``It's conservative to cut taxes. It's compassionate to give
people their own money back so they can save and work and build.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
