<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-PICNIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DONOR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 CONTROVERSY DOESN'T STOP McCAIN, DOLE FROM PICNICKING WITH FINED By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain of Arizona and Elizabeth Dole plan
to attend an annual Republican Party picnic on Saturday at a lush
island estate near Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats on Friday criticized their participation because
the event's host is a businessman who was fined $5 million by the
Federal Election Commission for making illegal donations to
political campaigns. The fine ranks as the third largest in history
for federal election-law violations.
</P>
<P>
   The businessman, Thomas Stewart, also served a 60-day home
detention sentence last year after pleading guilty to federal
misdemeanor charges. He has invited all nine of the Republican
presidential candidates to the annual picnic at his Misty Isle
Ranch on Vashon Island near Seattle. But only McCain, the Senate's
leading advocate for campaign-finance reform, and Mrs. Dole have
agreed to attend.
</P>
<P>
   McCain declined to participate in the Iowa straw poll last week,
dismissing it as ``a scam.'' But his supporters said he agreed to
attend the picnic at Stewart's home because it was an opportunity
to bring his message of campaign-finance reform to a large crowd.
Organizers said 8,000 people were expected to attend the picnic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more important to us to take the issue of
campaign-finance reform to the voters of Washington state than it
was to be concerned about this one individual who happened to be a
part of the event,'' said Howard Opinsky, a spokesman for McCain's
campaign. ``This is not about the individual whose home the event
is at.''
</P>
<P>
   A top aide of Mrs. Dole's acknowledged that there was a debate
inside the campaign about whether to attend the picnic. After
lengthy deliberations, Mrs. Dole decided to attend, saying the
benefits far outweighed the inevitable criticism from Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``He paid his fine and justice was served,'' Ari Fleischer, a
spokesman for the Dole campaign, said of Stewart. ``But does this
also mean that the Democrats who are criticizing will never attend
a Yankees game because George Steinbrenner was once fined? A lot of
hypocrisy going around.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner, principal owner of the New York Yankees, was
convicted of making illegal contributions to President Richard
Nixon's 1972 campaign, but later pardoned by President Ronald
Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Republican candidates, including Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas and publisher Steve Forbes, were also invited to
attend this year's picnic, but they declined because of scheduling
conflicts, organizers said today.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Berendt, chairman of the Washington State Democratic Party,
criticized McCain and Mrs. Dole. ``It's especially ironic that
Senator McCain, an outspoken critic of dirty money in politics,
would come here to pay homage to a poster child for
campaign-finance reform,'' Berendt said Friday. ``Elizabeth Dole
went to Iowa to buy votes last week, and now she's coming to
Seattle to do it again. The Republican picnic proves again that in
the GOP, money is more important than principle.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Stewart said that the criticism by Democrats was
unfair and that Stewart had paid his debt to society.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that this has been settled,'' said Gary L.
Odegard, the vice president of corporate communications for
Stewart's food services company, Services Group of America. ``His
penalties have been paid and no such occurrence will take place
again. There's nothing here to suggest that this has any relevancy
to what will take place here this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, 54, pleaded guilty to 24 misdemeanors for illegally
disguising about $100,000 worth of campaign donations, typically by
funneling them through employees of his company.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart is the chief executive of his company, which is
privately held. The company's subsidiary, Food Services of America,
was fined $1 million in 1997 for selling tainted meat and poultry
in the northwestern United States.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign-finance fine has hardly diminished Stewart's
enthusiasm for politics. ``I've never run from a fight in my
life,'' he told The Associated Press last year. Since then, Stewart
has continued to give large contributions to the Republican Party.
In the last decade, he has given more than $2 million to Republican
causes, making him the party's most generous donor in Washington
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, Tom Stewart was fined for tainted meat,''
Berendt said. ``Last year, he was fined for tainted money. Now he
wants to leave his mark on the presidential race.''
</P>
<P>
   At Saturday's picnic, guests will partake of free soft drinks
and hot dogs. But more important than the free food, the picnic
offers candidates a valuable campaign stop. The Washington primary
comes relatively early, on Feb. 29, and is considered an important
one.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, then-Speaker Newt Gingrich attended, drawing an
avalanche of criticism from Washington state Democrats. In past
years, Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi and Jack Kemp have attended
the picnic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
