<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR SATURDAY, AUGUST 21
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Saturday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-NYT (moved on Thursday, Aug. 19)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, Aug. 19,
about press inquiries on whether Gov. George W. Bush of Texas had
ever used drugs referred incorrectly to the drug-related questions
posed to job applicants at the Clinton White House. Prospective
employees are asked to disclose any use of illegal drugs as far
back as age 18 (not during the previous seven years or to age 18,
whichever is more recent). Mr. Bush has declined to answer whether
he could deny using illegal drugs since he was 18.
</P>
<P>
   BC-NAVY-TAILHOOK-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Aug. 10)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Aug. 10,
about the Navy's ties to the Tailhook Association misstated the
military background of Senator John W. Warner, Republican of
Virginia. He served in the Navy in World War II, rising to the rank
of petty officer third class, and served again in the Marine Corps
in the Korean War as a communications officer, not as a pilot.
</P>
<P>
   BC-ALUM-MERGER-TALKS-NYT (moved on Sunday, Aug. 15)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Aug. 15,
about the response of the Reynolds Metals Company to a takeover
attempt by Alcoa Inc. misspelled the name of a French company that
is merging with two other aluminum producers. (The three-way merged
company was rumored to be considering a rival bid for Reynolds.)
The company is Pechiney S.A., not Rechiney.
</P>
</TEXT>
