<SLUG> BC-INVEST-PHONES-ART-$ADV22-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPSTARTS' RISKY CHALLENGE TO BABY BELLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Aug. 22) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a long time, investing in the local telephone business meant
buying sleepy yet bedrock-solid stocks like those of the Baby
Bells. Substantially protected from competition until the enactment
of the Telecommunications Act of 1996, the Bells and other local
phone companies provided steady if unspectacular earnings growth,
healthy dividends and next to no surprises.
</P>
<P>
   As investments, these companies are still relatively
conservative and stable. But decades-old companies no longer have
the local communications business to themselves. Dozens of
upstarts, known in the communications business as competitive local
exchange carriers (or CLECs, pronounced ``SEE-lecks''), are out to
provide competition in local communications markets ranging from
phone service to corporate data applications. The companies hope to
use new communications technologies and lean cost structures to
undercut the local giants while still making money.
</P>
<P>
   Their stocks provide investors a new way to participate in the
local end of the communications revolution, but they are also an
entirely different breed of investment vehicle _ risky and erratic,
because of their dependence on borrowed funds. From mid-June to
mid-August, most of these stocks lost about 20 percent of their
market value, though they have started to crawl back.
</P>
<P>
   ``They bring a lot of rocket fuel to a portfolio,'' said Mark
Kastan, who tracks the stocks for Merrill Lynch. ``They could
significantly enhance performance. But it's obviously high-risk,
high-reward.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider RCN Corp., one of the few upstarts that is aimed at
residential customers, rather than at businesses. Along with
Nextlink Communications Inc., which was founded by Craig O. McCaw,
the cellular phone pioneer, RCN is one of Kastan's favorite CLEC's.
</P>
<P>
   RCN's stock opened 1998 at $17.0625, climbed as high as $30.625
and then fell that October to $8.75 as the bottom fell out of the
high-yield debt market. By April 1999, the shares had surged to
$54.50. But with interest rates rising, RCN's shares have swooned
again, closing on Friday at $39.50.
</P>
<P>
   ``MCI was the only competitive player on the long-distance
landscape for a long time, and it was an unbelievably volatile
company,'' said Alex J. Mandl, chairman of Teligent Inc., a local
service provider that uses fixed wireless links. ``In a sense, I
think you're seeing a similar situation in the local environment,''
he said. ``As 30, 40, 50 percent of the local market is occupied by
new players, I think that volatility will go away.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, said Alex W. Peters, a communications analyst
for Franklin Advisors and co-manager of the Franklin Global
Utilities fund, ``these are high-beta stocks, so they outperform
the market in good times and underperform in bad times.'' Among
Peters' favorites is McLeodUSA Inc., one of the more established of
the upstarts, which focuses on the Midwest and Rocky Mountain
regions.
</P>
<P>
   Perceptions of whether times are good or bad for the CLEC's tend
to change swiftly, because creating local networks is very
expensive. Pulling optical fiber under downtown streets, for
instance, can cost tens of millions of dollars in one city.
</P>
<P>
   So to maintain their growth, almost all of them will have to
return to the high-yield well in the next 12 to 18 months. If
interest rates go up, so will the companies' cost of borrowing.
Because Wall Street values them on a discounted cash flow model
that focuses mostly on results in some distant year, a small change
in interest rates can imply a big swing in long-term valuations.
Some Wall Street analysts estimate that a 1 percent change in
interest rates can result in a 15 percent change in the value of
one of these companies.
</P>
<P>
   But there have been other, more industry-specific concerns, too
_ for example, the impact of a proposal by a coalition of big local
and long-distance phone companies to lower the per-minute fees that
long-distance carriers pay to their local counterparts for
beginning and ending calls. In exchange, the local carriers would
be able to charge their customers higher fixed monthly fees. If
approved by federal regulators, the plan would have a small but
negative impact on many of the local upstarts because they focus on
serving high-volume business users.
</P>
<P>
   But the essential issues facing investors in all these stocks
concern the basic structure of the telecommunications industry, not
relatively small regulatory questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fundamentally, is the 100-year-old AT&AMP;T and Bell company
network the network for the next 10 or 20 years, given the way
people communicate now over the Internet?'' said David C. McCourt,
RCN's chairman. ``If the answer is no, then a basket of CLEC's is a
good investment. If the answer is yes, then CLEC's are not such a
great idea.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
