<SLUG> BC-BBN-HALLBRAVES21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Small Hall, but a big honor
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Like Hollywood stars, four Braves heroes of yesteryear
pulled the wraps off bronzed, diamond-shaped plaques that are set
among the bricks in the Walk of Fame at Turner Field on Friday.
Hank Aaron, Eddie Mathews, Warren Spahn and Phil Niekro received
smaller versions of the plaques to take home.
</P>
<P>
   But more important to these baseball legends was the recognition
that went along with their induction into the Braves Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is happening from park to park, it seems,'' Aaron said.
``It's a trend to have Walls of Fame or Halls of Fame. I'm just
happy that it happened because it could not have happened at all,''
said Aaron, who is in similar halls in Milwaukee, Eau Claire, Wis.,
Georgia, Alabama and the big one in Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad people remember,'' Spahn said. ``They've got a statue
of me in Oklahoma. I wish I had that kind of recognition when I was
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's on the same level as Cooperstown,'' Mathews said.
``My saddest day was the day I got traded by the Braves to Houston.
I was going to hit my 500th home run as a Brave. I hit it in
Houston. But people never talk about me with Houston, or even
Detroit. So the Braves are stuck with me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cooperstown is big, there's 300 or 400 in that Hall of Fame,''
Niekro said. ``But there's only four here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves Hall of Fame is part of a new exhibit in the Braves
Museum at Turner Field. It features a highlight video on each
inductee's career with the Braves, historic photos and paintings of
each by noted illustrator Bart Forbes. The four men hold 75 percent
of all Braves career records and each was with the franchise for at
least 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's ceremony began with a buffet luncheon in the 755 Club,
then moved outdoors to the plaza, where the sentiments of the four
honorees were as warm as the weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy driving me in from the airport told me the Braves have
a putting green in their clubhouse,'' Mathews said. ``It got me
thinking about my first entrance into the Boston Braves clubhouse.
We had a clubhouse man named Short Pendleson. He walked me in and
took me over to this wall. He said, 'That's your nail.' Actually, I
had two nails. And a stool. You know, I was really proud of those
two nails and the stool. I was proud to be a Brave.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(This) reminds me of a picture that is in Cooperstown of the
first inductees in baseball's Hall of Fame,'' Spahn said. ``One of
them happened to be Babe Ruth; he's got his legs crossed and he's
got his socks rolled. That was the thing of that era. So I've got
my socks rolled today because we are the first four inductees in
Atlanta's Hall of Fame. And what a cherished moment it is.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
