<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Burton sets record, takes Pepsi 400 pole
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLYN, Mich. _ Ward Burton is enjoying a career year in
Winston Cup. Burton, who is No. 11 in the points standings, has
accomplished a lot already this season without winning a pole or
race.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday's qualifying at Michigan Speedway, the Pontiac No.
22 no longer lacks a Bud Pole. Burton set a track-qualifying record
of 188.843 mph to capture the top spot for the Pepsi 400 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team did it all,'' Burton said. ``(The car) was great from
the minute I got into it. All we did was a little fine tuning.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton, whose only career victory was at Rockingham in 1995,
will share the front row with Mike Skinner, who was clocked at
187.999 mph. Points leader Dale Jarrett, Geoffrey Bodine, and
Jeremy Mayfield round out the top five.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ward was stronger than we were,'' Skinner said. ``We won
practice (against him), but he won qualifying. He had a perfect
lap.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon, who will start ninth on Sunday, had set the
previous record of 186.945 mph during the June race at Michigan
Speedway. It was Burton's first pole in 37 races since Pocono
during the '98 season, which was Burton's best in six years with a
16th-place finish in the final standings.
</P>
<P>
   Son ahead of father
</P>
<P>
   In his third Winston Cup race of the season, Dale Earnhardt Jr.
captured the No. 17 position for Sunday's race. His famous father,
however, ended up in the 35th position and will likely take a
provisional today to make the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just never got the car handling today,'' Dale Earnhardt Sr.
said sternly.
</P>
<P>
   Said the son, ``We made the first round, and I was worried at
the start of the year about just making the races.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jr. is scheduled to run in five Cup races this year, with
the final two being at Richmond, Va., and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Wrecking crew
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Irvan was not the only driver to make contact with the
wall during Busch practice on Friday. Gus Wasson was unhurt after
banging up the No. 96 Chevy.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Christopher, who suffered a bruised right knee during a
separate wreck, might consider changing the number on his No. 13
Chevy after this week's turn of events. He originally earned the
fourth position for today's NAPA 200, but it was disallowed due to
an unproven shock part. When he wrecked Friday morning, he was left
without a car to attempt second-round qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   Extra laps
</P>
<P>
   Busch driver Mike McLaughlin, who is eighth in the Busch points
standings, has been picked up by Innovative Motorsports, Inc., for
the 2000 season. It's an expansion move for IMI, which already
fields a team for Andy Santerre. McLaughlin will finish out this
year with Cicci-Welliver Racing. ... Joe Nemechek, Cup driver of
the No. 42 Chevy, and Team SABCO are parting at the end of the
season under mutual agreement. ``This was an extremely difficult
decision for the both of us, but one we had been discussing for a
while,'' said Felix Sabates, owner of Team SABCO ... Sterling
Marlin was fined $5,000 for bumping Chad Little in the pit area
after last Sunday's Frontier at The Glen. Marlin had no complaints
with the fine. ``I did what I needed to do,'' Marlin said. ``If a
guy runs over me again, I'll do it again. I'm tired of getting run
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
