<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quarterback Barnette Wolfpack's backbone
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. _ North Carolina State's Jamie Barnette and
Georgia Tech's Joe Hamilton are the top quarterbacks in the ACC,
probably in that order.
</P>
<P>
   Barnette, a shade under 6 feet and weighing 185 pounds, is
taller but about the same weight as Hamilton (5-10, 189), but
neither is big by college quarterback standards. No schools
recruited Barnette, a Roxboro, N.C., native, as a quarterback, but
his determination attests to his fortitude and single-mindedness.
</P>
<P>
   Add his ability to run the 40-yard dash in 4.8 seconds, and any
plan Wolfpack coach Mike O'Cain may have had for using Barnette as
a flanker, safety or corner was set aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't really have a choice,'' O'Cain said. ``He wasn't
fast enough to play one of the other skill positions, and he wasn't
big enough to play anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnette almost didn't make it to Raleigh. He had a son his
senior year in high school and decided to work to help support his
child. But after working at a fast food restaurant for a month, his
father told him that he would support the child while Jamie went to
school and got an education.
</P>
<P>
   And it has paid off. After injuring his knee last year and
playing in a bulky brace, Barnette is now healthy and eyeing three
ACC career records. He needs 12 touchdown passes to better the 57
of Florida State's Danny Kanell. (Barnette had 18 last year.) He is
2,474 passing yards from exceeding the 9,614 of Duke's Ben Bennett.
(Barnette threw for 3,169 last season.) He needs 2,002 yards of
total offense to pass the 9,296 of Georgia Tech's Sean Jones.
(Barnette had 3,182 last year.)
</P>
<P>
   Barnette, who seems to be easy-going and perpetually smiling,
characterizes himself as ``laid back, humble. I'm just like
everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes him go?
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is my heart and desire,'' he said. ``I'm not a
yelling guy. I think my teammates can tell by my facial expressions
when I mean business.''
</P>
<P>
   Said O'Cain: ``Jamie doesn't have to say a lot to get respect.
Our players want to play for him. People want to protect him.
They've seen him get knocked on his butt enough. We have a rule:
Nobody hits Jamie.''
</P>
<P>
   All-American flanker Torry Holt has graduated, and Barnette will
look to Chris Coleman, who caught 52 passes for 876 yards last
season but labored in the shadow of Holt (88 receptions, 1,604
yards).
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamie is very composed,'' Coleman said. ``But when he gets
fired up, you know there's a reason and you listen.''
</P>
<P>
   So Barnette is fire and brimstone when the going gets tough?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, like if I'm late breaking on a route or something, he
might say `Hey, Chris, the heat's on me. They're blitzing. Please
make that break a little quicker.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
