<HEADER>
A4711 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-UGA-KINES21-COX     08-20 0348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-KINES21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kines adjusting to new position at UGA
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Nobody knows how Joe Kines feels about being
reassigned from Georgia defensive coordinator to assistant head
coach. He barely managed a smile when his new duties were first
announced at a Jan. 15 news conference, and he remained mum on the
subject this week when asked how he was adjusting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to talk about all that,'' he said. ``If you want
to talk about one of the kids or something like that, that's fine.
But I don't want to talk about that. That ain't nobody's business
but mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Kines had been a Division I defensive coordinator for all but
six years since he entered coaching in 1972. Of those six years, he
spent four as linebackers coach with the NFL's Tampa Bay Buccaneers
and one as head coach at Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Kines was Georgia's defensive coordinator the past four years
before coach Jim Donnan brought in 37-year-old Kevin Ramsey after
last season. The move to assistant head coach was billed as a
promotion for Kines, 55, but he has not acted as though it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Joe about it,'' said Donnan, who made the moves
after assistants Chris Scelfo and Mickey Mathews left for head
coaching jobs. ``Obviously, he would rather be a coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (Scelfo and Mathews) left, I had to rework our staff.
They were two of my top guys, ever since we were at Marshall.
They'd been with me a long time. I had to look at experience, and I
felt like Joe could do a lot of the things you need an assistant
head coach to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Kines is the No. 2 man. He would call the shots if Donnan could
not be at a game. But Kines also is the defensive ends coach, which
means he must answer to Ramsey, a first-time coordinator 18 years
his junior.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey insists it's not a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and Joe had a great talk when I got here, mostly football
language,'' Ramsey said. ``It's been a smooth transition, in my
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
