<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4712 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-UGA-RAMSEY21-COX     08-20 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-RAMSEY21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A big step for Ramsey as UGA's defensive man
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ At 37 years old, Kevin Ramsey may seem young for
an SEC defensive coordinator. Then again, one has to consider how
long he has been in coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was one of those kids who would come home from school and
line little kids up in the fields and throw passes to them,'' said
Ramsey, who grew up in East St. Louis, Ill. ``I had my own little
team. I had a friend who lived about five blocks away, and I'd call
him up and say, `Hey, you get up your boys over there and y'all
come play the boys from Alhambra Court.' And we'd line 'em up and
play. So coaching has been a part of me for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like one of my gifts is mentoring and teaching.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey has been a college coach for 14 years, with stops at
Kansas State, Northwestern, West Virginia and Tennessee. But he has
no experience as a defensive coordinator, which is one reason his
hiring in January raised eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   But Ramsey's arrival is as much about head coach Jim Donnan's
desire to hire him, period, as it is about his role on the staff.
</P>
<P>
   Donnan had followed Ramsey's career for several years. Ramsey
was at Kansas State while Donnan, a former K-State assistant, was
at Missouri. When Donnan was head coach at Marshall, Ramsey was
across the state at West Virginia. And from 1995 through last year,
Ramsey was the secondary coach at Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   When Georgia assistant head coach Chris Scelfo left in December
to become head coach at Tulane and secondary coach Mickey Mathews
took the head coaching job at James Madison, Donnan made a move for
Ramsey.
</P>
<P>
   But after the Volunteers won the national championship, Ramsey
had NFL offers from Philadelphia and Green Bay, as well as the
option of remaining in Knoxville. Donnan knew he would have to make
it worthwhile for Ramsey to come to Athens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to give him more money and more responsibility,'' Donnan
said. ``He wasn't going to come here just as a secondary coach.''
</P>
<P>
   That posed a problem. Twenty-seven-year coaching veteran Joe
Kines had been Georgia's defensive coordinator for seasons.
Donnan's solution was to make Ramsey defensive coordinator and let
Kines, his most experienced assistant, take over Scelfo's role.
</P>
<P>
   Donnan had a specific charge for Ramsey _ create more turnovers.
Georgia had the ball less on offense than any other team in the SEC
last season. Donnan considered that unacceptable for this season,
especially with Heisman Trophy candidate Quincy Carter at
quarterback. With more talent at linebacker and on the defensive
line, Donnan wanted the Bulldogs to be more aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey had no trouble figuring out how to make that happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``My philosophy is velocity,'' he said. ``I firmly believe that
defense is about getting the ball back. It's about swarming around
and creating turnovers. You create turnovers by playing with a lot
of velocity. That's what we're trying to get our kids to buy
into.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey said that doesn't mean Georgia will look like Mississippi
State does or Mississippi did under Joe Lee Dunn, who stunted or
blitzed on nearly every down.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're talking about scheme, there's got to be a
balance,'' Ramsey said. ``But whether we're in a base defense or
we're bringing the blitz, we want all 11 guys playing with
velocity.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey doesn't care much for theories that Donnan hired him to
blunt Tennessee's recruiting efforts over the winter and infuse
Georgia's.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, I've been ripe to play this role for a while,''
said Ramsey, who earned second-team All-America and All-Missouri
Valley Conference honors as a defensive back at Indiana State from
1980-84. ``I've been around a lot of outstanding programs and
coaches over the years. I appreciate the opportunity Coach Donnan
is giving me, but I feel like I've been ready for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   At least since those childhood days in East St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
