<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4713 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FALCONS-BROOKING2     08-20 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-BROOKING21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brooking quick to mark for Falcons
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On the eve of the big show, the magnitude of it all
left Keith Brooking in awe. For him, the idea of starting in the
NFL is not nearly as overwhelming as the idea of playing for the
right to go to a Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   So when the former Georgia Tech star makes his second
consecutive preseason start tonight as the Falcons' weakside
linebacker, it will register as a relative blip on his screen.
</P>
<P>
   For Brooking, 23, it's possible no feeling will surpass that of
Jan. 16, 1999, the day before the NFC Championship Game at
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``The adrenaline of going to the Super Bowl was great, but when
we walked into the dome up in Minneapolis the day before, just
knowing we were going to play for the right to go to the biggest
game there is, that was incredible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we had our walk-through, I was looking at other players
and you could tell their tempo was picking up, the intensity was
higher. When you're a rookie going through all this, it just floors
you. You have to be in the position to understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooking is now in a position to understand it better.
</P>
<P>
   When the Falcons waived Cornelius Bennett in February, Brooking
became a starter. He will not immediately make fans forget Bennett,
whose 121 tackles last season broke middle linebacker Jessie
Tuggle's nine-year hold on the team tackling title.
</P>
<P>
   But his $1.32 million charge against the salary cap will be
easier for the Falcons to handle than Bennett's $3.7 million charge
would have been.
</P>
<P>
   Brooking's speedy ascension to the starting lineup has to do
with both money, and, well, speed.
</P>
<P>
   When the Falcons made the former East Coweta High starter the
12th pick of the 1997 draft, his quickness stood out.
</P>
<P>
   That's what moved him into the team's nickel passing defense as
a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   Tuggle sees it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say if he's better this year because we haven't
played a game,'' said Tuggle, entering his 13th season. ``But he's
got the speed to get to the ball. Like every young player, he's
just got to recognize things quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooking, who is 6 feet 2, 242 pounds, knows he needs to be
quicker making his reads and his reactions need to become more
instinctive.
</P>
<P>
   But he's proud to note one tremendous improvement from his
rookie season, when he had 32 total tackles, one interception and
an impressive three forced fumbles in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   He's not getting tied up in traffic as much on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been the biggest thing for me, getting separation from
offensive linemen,'' he said. ``Linemen at this level hold so much
more and get away with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't allow them to get inside of you and get hold of your
body because getting away from 350 pounds is not easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a rookie was not easy. Being a first-rounder was worse.
</P>
<P>
   After setting a Tech record with 467 career tackles and leading
the Yellow Jackets in tackles three straight years, being drafted
by his hometown team was, in a way, not so great.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of expectations for me last year. Everyone
was expecting me to play,'' he said. ``But Cornelius is a great
player and he had one of the best seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, I was frustrated last year, I really was, I admit it.
But I used it as more motivation to be a better player.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of being a better player, Brooking said, came from getting
completely away from football.
</P>
<P>
   First, he took up golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought a nice set of clubs and took a few lessons,'' he
said. ``I shoot in the 90s. I didn't have the time or the money in
college. It's an expensive game.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooking, who occasionally is teased for being tight with his
money, nearly bought a house on two occasions, even putting
contracts down. But he backed out both times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need a big place,'' said the apartment dweller. ``I'm
single; I don't have a family. I'd like to live on a golf course,
but all those places on course are so big.''
</P>
<P>
   In the offseason, Brooking and teammate Tim Dwight and former
teammate Sherdrick Bonner went to Bonner's hometown of Phoenix, and
then spent time in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   And Brooking, who grew up on a farm, and his girlfriend spent a
week in Los Angeles as guests of his agent, Gary Wichard.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he went to Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt 100 percent better going into training camp this year.
It really was like two straight years, going straight from playing
my senior season to trying to get ready for the draft,'' he said.
``I was working out harder than ever in my life for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, you go straight into (strength and conditioning coach)
Al Miller's program, then into training camp, then into the season.
In college, you play 12 games, if you go to a bowl. Last year we
played 23, counting preseason. I was gassed.''
</P>
<P>
   So Brooking insists he's not only much more knowledgeable now
than last summer, when he was learning at about 100 mph, but has
more gas in his tank.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he'll make fans forget Bennett sooner than later.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being in awe of the NFC Championship Game he had his
best game. His eight tackles against the Vikings on Jan. 17 were
second on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the rookies now and I can tell their heads are
spinning,'' said Brooking, who needs to play just 45 percent of the
defensive snaps to void the sixth and final year of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't view my situation as having any pressure. I'm just
living out my dream.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
