<HEADLINE>
BRITISH RAIDS SEEK MONEY-LAUNDERING EVIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The National Crime Squad has raided the home and office
of a Bank of New York officer here as part of an investigation of
what is believed to be a major money-laundering operation by
Russian organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   The special crime unit said it had searched the apartment of
Lucy Edwards, a Russian-born vice president at the bank, and her
husband, Peter Berlin. Berlin is a businessman who had authority
over some of the accounts at the bank that are the focus of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also searched the Bank of New York's London
office. At its New York headquarters, a bank spokesman confirmed
the search of the offices and said the institution was cooperating
with the authorities. The bank declined to elaborate. It also would
not discuss whether its offices in New York had been searched.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say they believe that Berlin and Ms. Edwards could
be involved in one of the largest money-laundering operations ever
conducted in the United States, with $4.2 billion passing through
one account alone from October through March.
</P>
<P>
   It was the British authorities who alerted the FBI to what they
suspected was a money-laundering operation at the bank.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the National Crime Squad refused to explain
what investigators had been looking for during the search of the
apartment, near Marylebone, an affluent London neighborhood, on
Wednesday night. The search lasted several hours.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Edwards, 41, who was suspended from her job on Wednesday,
may have left the country with her husband, friends of the couple
said. Neither Ms. Edwards nor Berlin has been accused of any
wrongdoing, and neither has been detained or arrested, said the
spokeswoman for the National Crime Squad.
</P>
</TEXT>
