<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CREATION OF BANKING GIANT SIGNALS REVAMPING IN JAPAN
</P>
<P>
   Japan signaled the start of a far-reaching consolidation of its
bloated and debt-ridden banking system with official word that
three of the country's biggest banks would unite to form the
world's largest financial institution, with $1.3 trillion in
assets. The merger agreement announced by Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank, the
Industrial Bank of Japan and Fuji Bank was viewed by economists and
investors as a significant change, but not because of the
combination's size. Rather, they said it would hasten mergers among
other Japanese banks, winnowing the weakest and helping to reduce
one of the biggest drags on the Japanese economy. The proposed
merger poses little competitive threat to American or European
banks, analysts said, nor will it do much to disrupt the push by
foreign banks into Japan.
</P>
<P>
   CHAT ROOM PROPELS A SHARE PRICE
</P>
<P>
   Online stock traders, goaded by an Internet chat room leader,
commandeered the shares last week of Information Management
Associates, which owns an Internet shopping site, taking it on the
kind of roller-coaster ride that longtime traders worry may harm
investors and undermine faith in the market.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS BENEFIT AS BOND YIELDS FALL
</P>
<P>
   Stocks climbed, helped both by a drop in the yield of the
30-year Treasury below 6 percent and a rush to buy metals and
mining shares after a takeover offer by Phelps Dodge, the copper
giant, for two rivals. The Dow Jones industrial average advanced
136.77 points, or 1.25 percent, to 11,100.61. In the broader
market, the Standard and Poor's 500-stock index gained 13.02
points, or 1 percent, to 1,336.61, while the Nasdaq composite index
rose 26.90 points, or 1.03 percent, to 2,648.33.
</P>
<P>
   CONTRACT EXTENDED FOR SOAP OPERA
</P>
<P>
   CBS agreed to extend its contract to broadcast television's
highest-rated soap opera, ``The Young and the Restless,'' in a deal
that will enable Columbia Tristar Television, the studio that
produces it, to use the program as a centerpiece in its plans to
begin a cable channel devoted to soap operas. The deal will give
CBS a stake in the channel, Soap City.
</P>
<P>
   RAID IN MONEY-LAUNDERING INQUIRY
</P>
<P>
   The National Crime Squad raided the home and office of a Bank of
New York vice president in London as part of an investigation of
what is thought to be a money-laundering operation by Russian
organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   RESIGNATIONS CALLED FOR IN INDONESIA
</P>
<P>
   Displaying internal divisions that could hamper efforts to
overhaul Indonesia's economy, lawmakers from President B.J.
Habibie's own political party are taking sides against him over a
widening banking scandal. Members of a faction in Indonesia's
ruling party joined opposition politicians in calling for the
resignations of both the Finance Minister and the chairman of the
Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency.
</P>
<P>
   SHARES OF DILLARD'S DECLINE 19.5%
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Dillard's fell $5.75, or 19.5 percent, to $23.75, amid
declining sales and rising costs at former Mercantile stores being
converted into ones for Dillard's. The company said Thursday that
earnings in the quarter ended July 31 rose less than expected as
sales at acquired Mercantile stores dropped 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   QUANTUM PLANS TO CUT 800 JOBS
</P>
<P>
   Quantum, which makes computer disk drives and storage drives,
said it would cut 800 jobs, about 13 percent of its work force, to
compete better in the rapidly growing low-cost computer market. The
company will take a $50 million second-quarter charge as a result.
</P>
<P>
   COMSAT HOLDERS BACK LOCKHEED
</P>
<P>
   Comsat shareholders voted overwhelmingly to approve the
company's purchase by Lockheed Martin, even though the value of the
stock deal has fallen to $2.2 billion from $2.7 billion when it was
announced last September.
</P>
</TEXT>
