u i BC-TURKEY-LEARN-NYT &LR;      08-20 0437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-LEARN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TEAMS SEEK LESSONS IN TURKEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (With TURKEY-QUAKE, TURKEY-TOWN, TURKEY-AID) 
(th) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As many as 20 researchers from the United States
are going to Turkey to see if there are any lessons relevant to the
San Andreas fault in California.
</P>
<P>
   Teams from the U.S. Geological Survey in Menlo Park, Calif., and
Golden, Colo., will be looking for lessons on ground shaking,
structural engineering and the geology of the North Anatolian Fault
where the earthquake occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from the University of Southern California will
examine the fault for lessons that can be applied to the San
Andreas Fault that runs through California, which bears several
similarities. Others from MIT, Columbia University and San Diego
State University will also be examining the quake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of these large earthquakes is an important data
point for evaluating models that already exist, for modifying
models and for developing a better idea of how things work,'' said
David Schwartz, a geologist for the geological survey in Menlo
Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Izmit quake is the seventh to have occurred along the North
Anatolian Fault since 1939. The fault is similar to the San Andreas
in length, speed of slippage and type _ a ``strike-slip'' vertical
fault with horizontal movement. Both have branches at either end,
with the San Andreas' spreading out through the San Francisco Bay
area in the north and through the Palm Springs area in the south.
</P>
<P>
   By examining the way the earth moved and what the effects of the
movement were, both for the land and the structures built on it,
researchers hope to apply that knowledge to California in presaging
what will occur during quakes along the San Andreas.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this is very important for thinking of building codes
and design of critical facilities,'' Schwartz said. ``North
Anatolian is really an analog of the San Andreas.''
</P>
<P>
   Nano Seeber, a research scientist at Lamont-Doherty Earth
Observatory of Colombia University in Palisades, N.Y., said one
hypothesis that American researchers hope to test will be how fluid
under the earth's crust affects earthquake velocity, as waves move
in and out of cracks.
</P>
<P>
   Another area of interest, Seeber and others said, will be
testing a theory that surface damage is worse in areas with soft
surface sediment than in areas with a stronger base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, if we can understand that, we can understand the
physics that regulate earthquake occurrences,'' Seeber said.
``That's basic understanding that you might be able to use in all
kinds of ways.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
