<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4723 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MICH-HALFWAY-HOUSE-NY     08-20 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICH-HALFWAY-HOUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALFWAY HOUSES ARE CLOSED IN MICHIGAN AS A RESULT OF
TRUTH-IN-SENTENCING LAW  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Washington, D.C., Calif., Ohio)   By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ As an unintended consequence of the state's
truth-in-sentencing law, halfway houses around Michigan are being
closed, leaving prisoners fewer chances to obtain job experience or
training, drug-abuse treatment or other services to help them ease
back into society.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan, like 26 other states and the District of Columbia,
passed a truth-in-sentencing law intended to reduce or eliminate
the chances that violent criminals would be paroled before serving
their minimum sentences. Because Michigan's law, which went into
effect last December, specifically requires prisoners to serve
their terms in prisons, soon none will be eligible to serve the end
of their sentences in any of the state's 14 halfway houses, as
1,300 criminals now do.
</P>
<P>
   By next week, there will be just 900, and the number is expected
to drop to zero within a few years. Four halfway houses _ those in
Detroit, Flint, Battle Creek, and Port Huron _ closed on Friday.
One in Jackson and one in Monroe closed late last month. The
remaining eight are likely to shut down as the number of prisoners
eligible to use them dwindles over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   The Michigan Department of Corrections said that the halfway
houses should be kept open, but that they could not be used under
the state's new law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would prefer they were still open and a viable option for
us,'' said William J. Martin, director of the department, which
oversees the state's prisoners as well as offenders on parole or
probation. Martin said he otherwise supported the
truth-in-sentencing law.
</P>
<P>
   Just 1 percent of those who pass through Michigan's halfway
houses before being paroled end up being charged with committing
another felony within four years, while 14 percent of all prisoners
commit new felonies in the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan's approach of eliminating halfway houses appears to be
unusual. ``Most states do not eliminate community programs from the
truth-in-sentencing model,'' said Richard J. Billak, president of
the International Community Corrections Association, a nonprofit
organization in La Crosse, Wis., that represents American and
Canadian halfway houses.
</P>
<P>
   Billak noted that many states with truth-in-sentencing laws,
including California and Ohio, have expanded their use of halfway
houses and other community-based programs to avoid sending
additional offenders to prison. ``What is troublesome is Michigan
used to be very progressive,'' Billak said.
</P>
<P>
   Billak and other criminal justice experts said closing halfway
houses would result in more repeat offenders. ``Halfway houses and
transitional programs have been proven time and time again to
reduce recidivism rates,'' said Barry A. Krisberg, president of the
National Council on Crime and Delinquency, a nonprofit criminal
justice research organization based in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth-in-sentencing movement has had all kinds of
unintended consequences,'' Krisberg said, some of which are only
coming to light now because of the time lags between when the laws
took effect and when prisoners wend their way through the court and
prison systems. ``All these little sentencing land mines are
exploding now that were passed four or five years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Truth-in-sentencing laws were part of the Republicans' 1994
Contract With America, which included a pledge to get tough on
crime, and many states, including Michigan, rushed to pass them in
the mid-1990s. Michigan's law was passed in 1994, but did not go
into effect until new sentencing guidelines could be drawn up,
which took several years. As a result, prisoners committing violent
crimes after Dec. 14, 1998, fell under the new law, and the law
will cover nonviolent crimes committed after Dec. 14, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for additional federal financing under a 1994 law,
states must demonstrate that their prisoners serve at least 85
percent of their terms. In Michigan, the law requires that violent
criminals serve at least the minimum time of their sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Before the truth-in-sentencing law was passed, certain prisoners
who drew, for example, a 10-to-15-year term would serve perhaps 8
years of their 10-year minimum sentence in prison, then be released
to a halfway house for an average of 8 to 14 months before being
paroled. Now, prisoners must serve the minimum sentence _ 10 years,
in this example _ before they are eligible for parole, with the
full time served in a prison.
</P>
<P>
   Those who work most closely with the prisoners said the halfway
houses, also called corrections centers, helped prisoners lead
law-abiding lives after they were released.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times guys come to us with no skills,'' said David
Fields, a veteran corrections officer and author of children's
books at Detroit Western Corrections Center, which closed on
Friday. ``The centers do serve a good purpose to help equip them to
be law-abiding citizens. It is going to have a tremendous impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin said that it would take action from the Statehouse to
keep Michigan's halfway houses open as an option for some of the
state's 130,000 offenders. No such action seems to be forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   The chief sponsor of Michigan's truth-in-sentencing law, state
Sen. William J. Van Regenmorter, a Republican, said he did not see
why the state could not use halfway houses for prisoners who had
already served their minimum terms in prison. Closing them is ``an
administrative decision by the Department of Corrections,'' the
senator said.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin, a former state representative, disagreed. ``Our
statutory language is what causes our difficulty.'' He said he had
explained the problem to a number of state senators and
representatives. ``The general response has been, `Gee, I didn't
know that was what was going to happen, it is an unintended
consequence, and I'm busy doing other things.'''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John Engler, a Republican who strongly supported the
truth-in-sentencing law, also believes the halfway houses serve
good purposes. ``I prefer the option of taking people and putting
them in the community to see how they adjust rather than just
flinging the door open and letting them out,'' Engler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Legislature is willing to look at this we're certainly
willing, and think it is worthwhile,'' his spokesman, John
Truscott, elaborated. But the governor has no immediate plans to
intervene because he feels that the truth-in-sentencing law, as a
whole, works well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
