<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0341 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4733 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-STYLE-2TAKES-NYT     08-20 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-STYLE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GREGARIOUS BUSH WARMS TO POLITICKING 
</HEADLINE>
  (Political Memo) 
(See also BUSH-CAMPAIGN) 
(ko) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROANOKE, Va. _ Former President George Bush's biggest problem,
an old friend of his once suggested, was that he liked policy a lot
more than politics.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody who has watched him would ever say that about Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, who plunges into crowds _ a crowd of 10 at an
airport late at night, a crowd of hundreds at a fund-raiser, a
crowd of thousands at a rally _ with all the enthusiasm of Bill
Clinton or Nelson Rockefeller or that formidable flesh-pressing
Texan of yesteryear, Lyndon Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody would ever mistake him for Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   It was obvious on a two-day campaign swing this week that Bush,
the front-runner for the Republican presidential nomination next
year, has a lot of work to do on his platform style. Ideas he
expressed with vigor and conviction in a private talk in his hotel
suite came out sounding tired, flat and mechanical when he tried
them later on a ballroom full of 400 New Orleans-area supporters
who had given him at least $1,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was there much on offer for the policy wonk. He wants to set
his own pace and his own rhythm, Bush said, and to that end he
plans to make a half-dozen major speeches starting next month. But
Bush _ now referred to by newspapers around the country not as
George W. Bush or even George W. but simply as W. _ demonstrated
real mastery of one-on-one campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   His style is an amalgam of East and Southwest, Yale and the oil
patch. Call him the Madras Cowboy.
</P>
<P>
   Watch him with a classroom full of second graders in Jefferson
Parish, near New Orleans. After a relaxed discussion of how
caterpillars turn into butterflies, a youngster asked him why the
sun had a smiling face. Beats me, the Governor replied; why does
the chicken cross the road? Well, his interlocutor said, the cow
crosses the road to go to the mooovies.
</P>
<P>
   Good television, of course, but something more as well: it gave
the governor a chance to promote the school, Jefferson Elementary,
as a prime example of the kind of public-private partnership he
wants to see more of _ in this case, Lockheed Martin and Shell Oil
helping a school set up a computer laboratory and Internet
connections.
</P>
<P>
   Watch him, again, reading with a group of mostly black
inner-city 6- and 7-year-olds at the West End Center for Youth here
in Roanoke. When ``hop'' and ``top'' sound the same, Bush asked,
what's that called?
</P>
<P>
   ``Rhyme.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right. Good.''
</P>
<P>
   I have two daughters the same age, he said, his hands resting on
the shoulder of a tiny child with red and yellow pony-tail holders
braided into her hair; what are they called?
</P>
<P>
   ``Twins.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right. Great.''
</P>
<P>
   He told them that his dog, Spot, had been born in the White
House, and assured them that, no, he had not arrived in Roanoke by
limousine.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he finished, Bush had worked in a pair of plugs: one
for reading as the key to the American Dream, another for more
Federal aid to after-school facilities wholly or partly sponsored
by church groups, as is the West End Center. Then he stopped for a
chat on the playground with some older youths, and as he walked
back to his van, Sam Sapp, lanky and 13, walked with him, an arm
draped fraternally across the governor's shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Then on to the Farmers' Market in downtown Roanoke, which has
been around since 1882. It is a traditional local campaign stop,
and 250 or 300 people had gathered on a hot August morning to meet
a candidate in an election that is not three weeks or three months
but 15 long months away.
</P>
<P>
   Bush keeps saying it is much too early for long speeches, too
early for debates. But his campaign is already an
industrial-strength gig, with long motorcades, a private jet, staff
and security people talking furtively into their sleeves, White
House-style ``bibles'' detailing every move and seven video cameras
(not to mention still ones, tape recorders and notebooks) following
along.
</P>
<P>
   Not even Dwight Eisenhower, a victor in history's greatest war
just a few years before, had this kind of entourage this early in
1951.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing seemed to faze Bush in the slightest as he moved slowly
past market stalls stacked high with peaches, pole beans, Japanese
eggplants and Silver Queen corn, the bounty of late summer in the
Virginia Piedmont. After he had spent more than an hour shaking
hands, posing for photographs, chatting about the military and the
local museum and the weather, kissing a baby swathed in pink (and a
grandmother or two as well), complimenting Gina Thomas on her
``good-looking'' family of four children and signing a lot of
autographs, a man handed him a $100 bill and asked him to sign
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must be doing pretty darn well,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not as well as you and your father,'' the man replied, and the
governor, laughing, gave him a chummy punch on the upper arm.
</P>
<P>
   Where did this come from, a campaign visitor asked, this knack
for putting people at ease, this common touch. Well, Bush said
pointedly, he grew up in Midland, Texas, and not in Greenwich,
Conn., like his father. Then he thought a minute and added, ``I
must get it from my mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for one thing, it was a loosy-goosey, laughter-punctuated
couple of days. Except for one big thing: the never-ending
questions about drugs. Bush tried without much success to fend them
off, insisting that he would not talk in any detail about the
various ``things,'' never specified, that he did 20 and more years
ago and now regretted having done.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same Gov. Bush, of course, who has come down hard on
young hard-drug users.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the decision not to play the game,'' he said in a long
talk aboard his campaign jet. ``No
float-a-rumor-and-force-him-to-answer. No more trash-mouth
politics. No politics of personal destruction. The baby boomers who
are so eager to purge their souls send a very mixed message to the
young. You know, if George Bush did it when he was a kid, why can't
I?
</P>
<P>
   ``Another thing _ people are being turned off politics by all
this negativism. I can't control the nastiness and the ugliness of
the system, but I sure can do my best to clean it up. People want
it to end.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has staked a lot on that proposition, and he is also
betting that the public is repelled by President Clinton's sexual
adventures. They want to know ``who you are today, not who were you
yesterday,'' he said, ``and they want someone to bring dignity back
into the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He insisted that he was not bitter about Clinton's defeat of his
father seven years ago, even though he described that defeat as ``a
pretty nasty experience, limping back into Houston the night before
Election Day, knowing that you were beat.'' If he was bitter about
anyone, he said, it would be Ross Perot, who he thinks tipped the
election to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But the president's involvement with Monica S. Lewinsky
``embarrassed lots of people,'' Bush said. ``They long for someone
they can trust, even though they're content with the economic
situation. They give Clinton credit for all this prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   One such person, he said, was a woman who approached him in Iowa
several weeks ago and gave him a picture of her 3-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told me to keep it, that she was counting on me to
remember that I had a big responsibility,'' Bush said. ``She was
saying that the president had not lived up to his, I guess. But I
don't think I can get elected president just by talking about Bill
Clinton. He's fading into history. His time is over.''
</P>
<P>
   So he talks more obliquely, about the need for a change in
leadership and in the nation's values. Two of his favorite lines
relate to this. Over and over, he talks about ushering in ``the
responsibility era'' and ending the present one, when ``if it feels
good, you do it, and if it goes wrong, blame someone else.'' He
promises a ``fresh start after a season of cynicism.'' Over and
over, he insists that ``prosperity alone is simple materialism''
and calls for ``a richness beyond money'' available to all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worth of America has never been proven by cities of
gold,'' he said in New Orleans, as he has before, ``but by citizens
of character.''
</P>
<P>
   Details to follow on all that, but Bush is a bit more specific
about national security policy. He senses that the American
military services are dispirited, ``because they think their role
is not valued by our leaders'' and because military spending has
been cut too quickly. Yet he talks of a top-to-bottom
reorganization that would lead, for example, to a single
fighter-interceptor to be used by all branches of service. That
idea has been floated before, only to generate considerable
opposition from the services.
</P>
<P>
   He backed Clinton's action in Kosovo and endorsed his refusal
``to let the United Nations act as the surrogate for the United
States.'' He took a swipe at the Administration's Asia policy,
arguing that China was a competitor of the United States, not a
strategic ally.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, as the plane headed for Roanoke, the Governor talked
politics, swapping tales of campaigns old and not so old,
victorious and calamitous. He expected more attacks, he said, like
the one started last week by Marilyn Quayle, the wife of former
Vice President Dan Quayle, who dismissed Bush as ``a frat boy'' who
had accomplished very little in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have tried that before, and it hasn't worked,'' he
said. ``Ann Richards called me `Shrub' in the governor's race, and
it backfired. But I like the give and take of campaigning anyway. I
grew up with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 2146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4735 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-HQ-HQ_SFCHRON &LR;      08-20 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HQ-HQ </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Rumors Say H&AMP;Q For Sale
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Sam Zuckerman &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
A surge in the stock price of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist Group, one of San
Francisco's leading securities firms, is prompting speculation that
the company could be sold soon.
</P>
<P>
   H&AMP;Q's stock rose 13 cents to $42.25 in trading of 581,700 shares
yesterday, more than twice the average volume of the last six
months. During the day, the company's shares changed hands for as
much as $44.63, a 52-week high.
</P>
<P>
   In the last eight trading days, the company's stock has jumped
nearly 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock has been suspiciously strong this week, which occurs
when rumors of a merger begin to circulate, whether substantiated
or not,'' said Michael Flanagan, an independent brokerage industry
analyst based near Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Flanagan said a buyer might have to pay as much as $1.3 billion,
or $50 a share, for H&AMP;Q.
</P>
<P>
   H&AMP;Q Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Dan Case was out of
town yesterday and couldn't be reached for comment. Paul Cleveland,
a managing director and head of the firm's merger advisory
practice, said he had no comment on the takeover speculation.
</P>
<P>
   If H&AMP;Q were taken over, it would mark the latest in a series of
acquisitions of leading San Francisco investment banks.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, both Montgomery Securities and Robertson Stephens
sold themselves to commercial banks. Today Montgomery is known as
Banc of America Securities and is owned by North Carolina's Bank of
America. Robertson Stephens is owned by BankBoston Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of independent investment banks would be left in
the city if H&AMP;Q were bought, including Thomas Weisel Partners,
started last year by the former chief executive of Montgomery
Securities, and Volpe Brown Whelan.
</P>
<P>
   Stock traders said speculation about possible buyers for H&AMP;Q
centered on discount and online brokerage giant Charles Schwab
Corp. or Merrill Lynch, the nation's largest securities firm.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab in recent years has developed a close relationship with
H&AMP;Q, distributing the firm's public stock offerings and research to
its retail brokerage customers. And H&AMP;Q was nearly sold to Merrill
two years ago before the talks broke down, according to published
reports.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Schwab and Merrill declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the rumors, analysts said they were skeptical that H&AMP;Q's
business with corporations would fit with Schwab's consumer focus.
And Merrill, they noted, is widely thought to be exploring a much
larger merger with a big bank.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the strength of the technology, health care and
consumer products industries from which it draws clients, H&AMP;Q's
business is booming.
</P>
<P>
   It ranks seventh nationwide among stock underwriters, acting as
lead or co-manager in 94 initial or secondary public offerings so
far this year, according to CommScan, an investment banking
research firm. And in the quarter ended in June, H&AMP;Q earned $37
million on $178.1 million in revenue, up 166 percent and 73 percent
respectively from the year before.
</P>
<P>
   ``The have a formidable franchise,'' said Lauren Smith, a
brokerage analyst with Putnam, Lovell, de Guardiola &AMP; Thornton.
</P>
<P>
   Since talks with Merrill broke off, H&AMP;Q officials have
repeatedly said they want to go it alone, maintaining that
independence allows the firm to be more nimble and provide better
service than its rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Still, noted Smith, ``Everyone who has sold out had previously
said they wanted to remain independent.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
