<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4737 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-DREYERS-DREYERST_SFCH     08-20 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DREYERS-DREYERST </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 How Nestle's New Deal May Affect Dreyer's
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Carol Emert &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
What seemed Thursday like a vote of no confidence in Dreyer's Grand
Ice Cream Inc. by its biggest shareholder now looks like just the
opposite.
</P>
<P>
   The shareholder, Nestle USA, announced two days ago it was
forming a joint venture with Haagen-Dazs Plc, best known for its
superpremium pints of ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   That partnership raised questions about Nestle's commitment to
Dreyer's since Dreyer's, which is headquartered in Oakland, is on
the verge of launching its own superpremium line, Dreamery, which
will go head to head against Haagen-Dazs starting this month.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyer's also competes less directly with Haagen-Dazs through
its premium ice cream, which is sold as Dreyer's brand on the West
Coast and Edy's in the eastern United States.
</P>
<P>
   But in a Securities and Exchange Commission filing later
Thursday, Nestle indicated that it remains interested in Dreyer's.
The filing disclosed that, as part of the deal, Nestle and
Haagen-Dazs agreed that if either one attains a majority stake in
Dreyer's, it must offer to sell the stake to the joint venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the big question yesterday was whether ... Nestle was
no longer interested in Dreyer's,'' said Jeffrey Kanter, an analyst
with Prudential Securities, in a telephone interview yesterday.
``The wording in the filing suggests they certainly are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Nestle would like to own us eventually,'' said
Dreyer's Chief Financial Officer Timothy Kahn. ``I think they see
this venture as a long-term vehicle'' that could one day include
Dreyer's.
</P>
<P>
   A Nestle spokeswoman said no executives were available to
comment yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Nestle first acquired an interest in Dreyer's in 1994 and
currently owns 18 percent of the company. But Kahn said no
acquisition is likely before the expiration of a standstill
agreement that prevents Nestle from buying a controlling share of
Dreyer's until mid-2004.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's announcement points out the convoluted nature of the
ice cream sector, in which rivals often join in manufacturing and
distribution partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   The joint-venture allows Haagen-Dazs to distribute Nestle ice
cream novelties, such as Nestle Crunch bars, to convenience stores,
a channel where Nestle wants to establish a greater presence.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Dreyer's distributes Nestle novelties to some
supermarkets, a business that represents about 3 percent of
Dreyer's total revenues, said Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyer's also manufactures and distributes ice cream in some
parts of the country for Ben &AMP; Jerry's, the other major player in
the superpremium pint category _ while Haagen-Dazs distributes Ben
&AMP; Jerry's in other parts of the U.S. Dreyer's also makes and
distributes the Godiva, Starbucks and Healthy Choice brands.
</P>
<P>
   Ice cream companies have calculated that it makes more sense to
work together than for each to set up an extensive distribution
network, said Mike Corby, who manages distribution for Dreyer's.
</P>
<P>
   As an example of the expense of transporting ice cream,
refrigerated trucks suitable for carrying ice cream cost $120,000
each, whereas bread trucks cost $25,000 to $30,000, Corby said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
