<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4738 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-ETICKET-ETICKET_SFCHR     08-20 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETICKET-ETICKET </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Critics charge Internet ticketing by airlines leaves
noncomputer  customers in the cold 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Rebecca Smith &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Consumers with access to airline Web sites are reaping discounts
not readily available to those without computers. That's raising a
howl from critics who think Internet ticketing discriminates
against those without computers and widens the digital divide.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, for example, United Airlines was offering round-trip
tickets from San Francisco to Boston at a special $269 fare to
those booking travel over the Internet. The lowest-priced ticket
available by phone was $217 higher, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska Airlines offered $88 round-trip tickets from Oakland to
Seattle over the Net, $53 less than the next-cheapest seat booked
by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   To some consumer watchdogs, this practice is elitist and should
be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shouldn't matter whether you're closer to your telephone or
your computer, you should get the same deal from the airlines,''
says Mark Silbergeld, co-director of the Washington, D.C., office
of Consumers Union.
</P>
<P>
   Early this month, the American Society of Travel Agents (ASTA),
an Alexandria, Va., trade group, filed a complaint with the
secretary of transportation, overseer of the Federal Aviation
Administration, seeking to block Internet ticketing promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines say they aren't necessarily looking to become
e-commerce powerhouses, or to compete with online ticketing
services like Priceline.com.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, they want to reduce transaction costs and commissions
paid to travel agents, and they see the Web as a way to accomplish
that. For many airlines, travel agent commissions represent the
third-highest expense, ranking after labor costs and jet fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines also say they are using the Internet to build loyalty
among the most well-heeled travelers, to give consumers a tool many
want, and to clear out unsold inventory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airlines aren't trying to segregate passengers,'' said
Mark Vacheresse, an analyst with Olde Discount Corp. in Detroit.
``They're trying to lower distribution costs. If they get people to
go to their Web site, they don't have to pay commissions to travel
agents.''
</P>
<P>
   Lower prices aren't the only way airlines are enticing customers
to book flights over the Internet. They are offering bonus
frequent-flier miles.
</P>
<P>
   Consider:
</P>
<P>
   _Southwest Airlines doles out a free ticket to members of its
Rapid Rewards frequent-flier program after they log four round
trips if they book those flights over the Internet. Other Rapid
Rewards members who book the traditional way need twice as many
round trips per year to get that free ticket.
</P>
<P>
   _American Airlines gives its frequent-flier program members
4,000 bonus miles when they book their first trip over the
Internet. Thereafter, they get 1,000 bonus miles for
Internet-booked flights in addition to regular mileage.
</P>
<P>
   _Delta Airlines and others give Internet customers a special 10
percent discount.
</P>
<P>
   As flight dates approach, many airlines dump remaining seats at
discounted prices on their Web sites. Southwest and United, for
example, post discounted seats each Wednesday and e-mail Web-site
customers to let them know what deals are available for travel
between cities customers have identified as significant to them.
</P>
<P>
   The ASTA complaint accuses the airline industry of
discriminating against consumers who don't have computers _ the
group of consumers that may need low prices most _ and of widening
the gap between the affluent and the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of folks don't have computers now and they're never
going to have them,'' says Paul Ruden, vice president of legal
affairs for ASTA. ``The public owns the airspace and the airports.
We think there should be rules in place that make low prices
available to everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   A Transportation Department spokesman said the agency will look
into the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll respond to ASTA when we have an answer,'' says spokesman
Bill Moseley. ``Since they're raising questions of deceptive
practices and discrimination, we take it seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Airline representatives say the digital divide argument, or fear
about a widening gap between technically proficient ``haves'' and
``have-nots,'' is a ruse. What ASTA really is mad about is
reductions in the commissions airlines pay travel agents, they say,
and the threat posed by Internet sites that let consumers book
their own flights.
</P>
<P>
   They disagree with the depiction of Internet users as rich
yuppies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's about every demographic group imaginable on the
Internet now,'' says American Airlines spokesman Tim Smith. ``We've
noticed a big increase in seniors with disposable income and
flexible schedules. The reality is that those without Internet
access are not doing a lot of flying anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   But travel agents say they aren't simply motivated by
protectionist sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   Internet sites give the impression consumers are getting the
best prices, though that may not be the case. There's no guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The harsh reality is that it's often difficult and confusing
for people to use these sites,'' says ASTA's Ruden.
</P>
<P>
   In general, consumers still get the best prices by working with
travel agents, says Laurie Berger, editor of the Consumer Reports
Travel Letter in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with the Web is there's no easy way to do good
cost projections,'' says Berger. ``It's hard to know if you're
truly getting a bargain.''
</P>
<P>
   ASTA and Consumers Union are not the only ones concerned about
the fairness issue. U.S. Rep. John Sweeney, R-N.Y., has introduced
legislation that would mandate that Internet fares be made
available to those using airline telephone reservations systems or
travel agents, as well.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation isn't expected to make it into law this year,
but it has raised awareness of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The multiplicity of prices isn't about finding what the market
will bear,'' says Consumers Union's Silbergeld. ``It's about
finding what each consumer will bear.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
