u f BC-UTILITIES-MERGE-NYT &LR;      08-20 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTILITIES-MERGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAROLINA POWER MAY BE BUYING FLORIDA UTILITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., S.C., Fla.)  (Eds.: This story is now on the Times business front page) 
(mk) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carolina Power and Light Co., the second-largest utility in
North Carolina, is close to an agreement to buy Florida Progress
Corp., the second-largest utility in Florida, in a deal worth as
much as $5.3 billion, a person close to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction would be a combination of cash and stock valued
at about $54 a share, the person said. Carolina Power's board was
thought to have met Friday to discuss the proposal, and Florida
Progress' board was expected to meet over the weekend. As with any
deal, talks could collapse, but both companies were planning to
announce the deal on Monday, the person said.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Progress, based in St. Petersburg, would add 1.3 million
customers in Florida's west and central regions and along the Gulf
Coast to Carolina Power's 1.2 million in North Carolina and South
Carolina. Carolina Power, based in Raleigh, N.C., recently bought
North Carolina Natural Gas Co. for $354 million and is eager to
expand into the Florida electricity market.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really have no place left to expand, and they want to
stay in the fast-growing Southeast,'' said Edward Tirello, an
analyst with Deutsche Bank Alex. Brown, who has a ``hold'' rating
on both companies.
</P>
<P>
   If a deal is announced, Carolina Power will compete with its
larger rival, Duke Energy Corp., which has 2 million electricity
customers in the Carolinas. Analysts have said that Carolina Power
needs to find more sources of revenue to remain competitive. And
Duke, the second-largest utility holding company in the United
States, has been expanding. Last year, Duke said it wanted to build
a $160 million power plant on Florida's eastern coast to sell power
to utilities and large energy users.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's electricity market is the fourth-largest in the United
States and has for some time been considered an attractive target
for companies outside the state. But many companies have been
restricted in their efforts to sell power into Florida because of
limited access to transmission lines.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Progress has been seeking a merger partner. The company
has had numerous problems, including a trouble-plagued nuclear
plant and a lawsuit brought by regulators in Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Progress began as St. Petersburg Electric Light and
Power Co. in 1899. During the 1920s and '30s, the company acquired
several rival utilities. But in the '80s, it decided to diversify
into equipment- leasing and life insurance, a decision that proved
full of problems.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Florida Progress ended talks with Scottish Power, the
British utility company, after the two companies failed to agree on
a price. Scottish Power agreed in November to buy Pacificorp, a
utility based in Portland, Ore., in a transaction valued at about
$11 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Florida Progress rose $1, to $44.625, while Carolina
Power rose 6.25 cents, to $39.
</P>
</TEXT>
