   &UR; STYLE (L Category) (All moved) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WALL-STREET-DORMITORY (New York) _ The residents of 45 Wall
Street are relatively young. They are urban. They are brazenly
professional. The converted office building in which they live, one
block from the New York Stock Exchange, has become known as an
upscale dormitory of sorts for armies of fresh college graduates,
who invade Wall Street from the country's premier universities. By
Jennifer 8. Lee.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   JOINT-CUSTODY-PETS (New York) _ More and more couples appear to
be arranging what might be called pet joint custody, especially in
a city like New York where there are lots of childless adults
bonding intensely with their animal companions. By Alexandra Zissu.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SURFER-CAMP (Undated) _ Jonathan Paskowitz is one of nine adult
siblings who, along with their parents, own and operate the
Paskowitz Surf Camp, which was founded in 1972 by the family
patriarch, Dorian (Doc) Paskowitz, a surfing pioneer. In the last
few years, as surfing has ridden to ever greater heights of
cultural cool, the camp has become a ``must'' stop for well-heeled
hipsters eager to hang 10, ride the soup and mellow out. Students
have included musicians like Sarah McLachlan and Chris Isaak, Mark
McGrath of Sugar Ray and the members of Hanson. By Julia Chaplin.
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-WES-ANDERSON (New York) _ On the town with Wes Anderson,
whose first film, ``Bottle Rocket,'' about a gang of petty thieves,
skyrocketed him to indie-film cult status. Anderson's second film,
``Rushmore,'' a surprise hit comedy about an eccentric prep school
student, only added to his legend among obsessed cineastes whose
idea of a big night is sitting around drinking and talking about
film theory, dissecting scripts and Truffaut's use of the iris
shot. By Susan M. Kirschbaum.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Touch me, touch me not: Plants have
rules, too. &QL; 
By Tovah Martin.
</P>
