<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: MAC RECALLS A DIFFERENT KIND OF RACE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mark McGwire played in the World Series in his
second, third and fourth seasons in the major leagues. He thought
that was how his career would always be.
</P>
<P>
   Now, McGwire has to glance into the opposing dugout for the
surreptitious scoreboard watching _ the players cheering a
strategic fine point, the tension of a pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   He is not complaining about his station in life _ he hit a
ridiculous 70 homers last year and had 48, one behind Sammy Sosa,
going into Friday night _ but McGwire looks wistful when he
remembers those early autumns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was spoiled at a young age,'' McGwire said, hoping to take
his home run cuts at a soggy Shea Stadium, as the moribund St.
Louis Cardinals were playing the contending Mets.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, now 35, came over from Oakland in August 1997 in one of
those modern baseball clearance sales, a low-budget team divesting
itself of a respected slugger it could no longer afford. Now, by
the vagaries that allow a small-market team to actually compete
once in a while, Oakland has hopes of the wild card and the
Cardinals have no hopes at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so happy for them,'' McGwire said Friday night. ``I watch
the scoreboard. They've got a brand-new team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk to Jason all the time,'' McGwire added, referring to
Jason Giambi of the A's. ``He says they are all eager to go to the
ballpark every day.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire is happy to come to the ballpark, too. He has the
positive glow of a man who has known physical pain and psychic pain
and has come through to the other side. Friday night he recalled
his role models when he came up. ``Don Baylor, Carney Lansford,
Dave Stewart, Dennis Eckersley,'' he said. ``They had a great
coaching staff. Tony.''
</P>
<P>
   He came from one of the great college programs, the University
of Southern California and coach Rod Dedeaux, but he said he was
stunned at the mental scope of the major leagues under manager Tony
La Russa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came up thinking you can play with physical ability,''
McGwire said. ``And you can, for a while. But not for long. You
learn baseball is 99 percent mental'' _ the little things that win
pennants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every athlete wants to win,'' McGwire said. ``Nobody puts on
the uniform and doesn't want to win. But people don't understand
how difficult it is for six months. It's not easy. Injuries.
Players not playing up to their level that year.''
</P>
<P>
   He was not being critical of anybody, just acknowledging that
the Cardinals could be spoilers, and not much more. However,
McGwire does not buy the theory that being out of contention frees
him and Sosa to take three big swings every time up, 12 or 15 each
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``My swing's the same all the time,'' McGwire said, flexing
those massive forearms. ``I think I'm pretty patient. I get a lot
of walks. You're not going to hit a home run off a pitcher's pitch.
It's got to be off a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   He expected that fans in Shea might cheer for him to hit one,
but not if it would jeopardize the Mets' run toward October. On one
level, McGwire is chasing Henry Aaron's career record of 755. On
another level, he and Sosa are a stirring sideshow to the pennant
races.
</P>
<P>
   He accepts that, just as he accepts that he cannot go out for
dinner anonymously, just as he accepts that he must answer his
complicated relationship with the substance androstenedione.
</P>
<P>
   Last year he was criticized because his 70 home runs drew
attention to a bodybuilding steroid that just might cause long-term
health problems. Baseball looked worse, however, tolerating the
stuff as if afraid to tarnish McGwire's record.
</P>
<P>
   This year, McGwire stopped taking andro at the start of the
season but never mentioned it for four months. Friday night,
McGwire explained his reasoning, saying: ``It's legal; you can buy
it over the counter. I still don't think there's anything wrong
with it, but I got tired of hearing about young kids under age who
were probably taking it improperly.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire said the ban by most sports leagues and federations was
``hogwash _ it's all natural.'' But he said that he would advise
his own son, Matthew, 11, against using it because ``I wouldn't
want him associated with it,'' meaning the stigma rather than any
physical danger.
</P>
<P>
   His eyes showed great zest for the last six weeks of the season,
another race with Sammy, another weird flirtation with 60, maybe
even 70. But he grew a trifle somber when he recalled the joy, the
terror, the challenge of a pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciated it,'' McGwire said. ``If I ever get it again,
I'd appreciate it more.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
