<HEADER>
A4752 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-NEWSPAPERS-ART     08-20 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-NEWSPAPERS-ART-$ADV22-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWSPAPER STOCKS AN INTERNET STORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Aug. 22) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JOANNE LEGOMSKY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom of the new economy says newspapers ought
to be on their last legs. In this view, it will not be long before
the Internet eats the newspapers' lunch by siphoning off readers
and advertising to Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, that kind of thinking depressed share prices of
the big publicly traded newspaper companies. In 1998, while the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index was rising 26.7 percent, the Bear
Stearns Diversified Newspaper Index inched up just 1.5 percent, and
the trend was little better in the first part of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Not any more. Since April 1, newspaper stocks have surged 22
percent while the broader market has been bouncing up and down. And
there may be more good news ahead for the sector, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   William Drewry, an analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, said
the spurt is just the start of a long stretch of outperformance, as
stock valuations catch up with important improvements in
fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
   A new cadre of cost-conscious and shareholder-friendly managers
has been slashing payrolls, shedding ancillary businesses, reducing
debt and buying back stock, Drewry said. By his calculations,
industry revenue is growing at 5 percent annually, bolstered by
firm advertising prices, while costs apart from raw materials
(mainly for labor) are growing only 3 to 3.5 percent a year. And
with the often-volatile price of newsprint now low, he expects the
industry to parlay its widening margins into double-digit earnings
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Those factors make newspaper stocks attractive as a value
investment, even after the recent run-up. But there may be a growth
investment here, too: Largely unnoticed by the market, newspapers
have invested aggressively in their supposed nemesis, the Internet,
and are already generating impressive revenues on line. For
example, the second-largest job recruitment Web site,
CareerPath.com, is run by a consortium of newspaper companies.
</P>
<P>
   And newspapers control valuable Internet assets in their vast
archives of articles and photographs, as well as data bases and
reporting resources, said Steven Barlow, an analyst with Credit
Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, moving on line means grappling with a host of nimble
and aggressive new competitors for readership and ads. ``The big
question,'' Drewry said, ``is not how big the Internet market
becomes, but how much can newspapers capture.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Gruneich, an analyst with Bear Stearns, said he thinks
``the Internet fear factor'' may wane in coming months. Gruneich,
who began advising investors to shy away from newspaper stocks in
early 1998, turned bullish in June on near-term prospects for
several of them. A broad-based rebound in advertising and a sharp,
23 percent decline in newsprint costs since January prompted his
change of heart, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Knight Ridder is an example of a company with an upside both on
line and off, he said. Every decrease in newsprint prices bolsters
its profits, he noted, while its Internet operations, principally
the Realcities news, entertainment and commerce Web site, yield at
least $30 million a year in revenue. He expects the stock to rise
to $64 or $65 within a year, from $54 Friday.
</P>
<P>
   William Bird of Salomon Smith Barney is bullish on the
Washington Post Co. because of its combination of strong free cash
flow and a history of using cash effectively for share repurchases
and acquisitions. The stock is also attractive, Bird said, because
of its overfunded pension plan, its Internet assets and its Kaplan
Education subsidiary. His 12-month price target for the stock is
$675; it now trades at $556.
</P>
<P>
   Barlow of Credit Suisse First Boston said he thought
newspaper-company profit margins would hold up relatively well,
even if the economy slowed. His choices in the sector include the
Gannett Co. and the Tribune Co., which get one-third to one-half of
their cash flow from broadcasting operations. He sees Gannett
rising to $80 a share, from $68.9375 Friday, and Tribune to $100,
from $94.75, within a year.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Marcin of Gabelli Asset Management said she is keen on
The New York Times Co., because ``the best way to invest in the
Internet is through companies that sell their own products over the
Web.'' She expects the company's Internet operations to expand the
reach of its principal newspaper properties, The Times and The
Boston Globe, and account for $4.50 of the $48 price she expects
the stock to reach within a year; it closed at $37.4375 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's price-to-earnings multiples, which ran at an
average 40 percent premium to the broader market from 1988 to 1998,
now lag behind the S&AMP;P 500. But bullish analysts like Drewry think
the multiples will rise again as newspapers spin out their online
businesses with their own stock listings.
</P>
<P>
   Drewry sees a precedent for newspapers in the shift in investor
perception that turned cable stocks into highfliers. ``Two or three
years ago, cable companies were seen as losers in the next
generation of communications,'' he noted. But partly because of
Microsoft's investment in the Comcast Corp. in 1997, investors
began looking at cable companies as attractive bets on the Internet
infrastructure. Newspapers look ripe for a similar rethinking by
investors, he said, even if Bill Gates doesn't buy one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
