<HEADER>
A4756 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CYPRUS-ASARCO-NYT &LR;      08-20 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYPRUS-ASARCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHELPS DODGE BIDS FOR SMALLER COPPER PRODUCERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., N.Y.)  (ko) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Continuing a consolidation trend among basic commodity
industries, Phelps Dodge Corp., the copper producer, made a bid
Friday and then sweetened it to acquire Cyprus Amax Minerals Co.
and Asarco Inc., which themselves had just agreed to merge. The
Phelps Dodge bid was promptly rejected.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say Phelps Dodge's all-stock bid, which started at
$2.4 billion and grew to $2.66 billion by the end of the day, may
ultimately be hard for the newly combined targets to resist given
the difficult economics of the copper industry. Prices are hitting
rock bottom, there is global overcapacity and there are no apparent
prospects for a change in this dismal combination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Phelps bid is a bold move; it is a complex move, and, at
the end of the day, it will prevail,'' said Vahid Fathi, a metals
industry analyst with ABN Amro in Chicago. ``The combined trio
would be propelled to the top of the chain as the No. 1 producer.
Truly, this is remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   An equally bold note was sounded Friday by Phelps Dodge's chief
executive, Douglas Yearley, who said, in a call to analysts, ``We
are now prepared to take all necessary steps to make this happen.''
Among those, Yearley said, was perhaps raising the bid again.
</P>
<P>
   Cyprus Amax, which is based in Englewood, Colo., and Asarco,
based in New York, reaffirmed their intention of going it alone
Friday. On Thursday, the boards of the two companies met
separately, and both voted to reject the Phelps Dodge bid, saying
the directors of both companies had ``determined that pursuing the
Asarco-Cyprus merger was in the best interests'' of both companies'
stockholders.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether Cyprus and Asarco are simply holding out
for a higher price from Phelps Dodge or if they are firm in their
determination to resist it. Also unclear is whether their
shareholders will allow them to continue to reject this offer. The
sweetened Phelps Dodge offer would give 0.4098 shares of Phelps
stock for every Asarco share and 0.3135 a share for every Cyprus
share.
</P>
<P>
   At Friday's closing price of $59.125 for Phelps Dodge, which was
up 56.25 cents, this would be valued at $24.23 for every Asarco
share, which rose $4 Friday to close at $22.4375. And it would be
valued at $18.54 for every Cyprus share, which rose $2.875 Friday
to close at $17.375. The sweetened Phelps Dodge offer values Cyprus
at some $1.7 billion and Asarco at roughly $960 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question of should the shareholders accept is a pretty
easy one,'' said Raymond Goldie, an analyst at St. James Securities
in Toronto. ``Cyprus and Asarco have given their shareholders
returns in the minus-20 percent range, while Phelps has had
something like a 160 percent return in the same time period. I'd
take the money and run.''
</P>
<P>
   If the three-way deal goes through, it would create a company
that would surpass Chile's state-owned Codelco as the world's top
copper producer and would unite production in the copper-rich
American Southwest. Right now the world copper market is being
flooded with copper from Chile and Indonesia, where the mining
costs are lower and the mines are newer.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts expect that copper prices, which have plunged in
the last few years, should remain relatively flat for the
foreseeable future. Copper has been trading at around 70 to 75
cents a pound lately, the lowest levels in over a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is swimming in copper,'' said John C. Tumazos, an
analyst with Sanford Bernstein &AMP; Co. ``And North American companies
realize they are in big competitive trouble. It's a given that
things have to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Tumazos, however, said Cyprus and Asarco shareholders might be
persuadeded by management to give the newly combined entity a
chance on its own. That would leave Phelps Dodge, the world's No. 4
producer, out of a global merger wave unless it raised its bid even
further. If it did so, it could run the risk of overpaying for
assets.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's bidding was part of a large consolidation trend
sweeping not only copper but all basic commodities: aluminum,
chemicals and oils. Commodity giants have been pairing up to gain
market share and reduce costs in a world flooded by raw material
overcapacity and declining demand. This week, the world's largest
aluminum maker, Alcoa Inc., won agreement to acquire Reynolds
Metals, which would make it even bigger. This comes on the heels of
a three-way merger on both sides of the Atlantic to unite a
Canadian, a Swiss and a French aluminum maker into one giant
company rivaling Alcoa.
</P>
<P>
   Cyprus and Asarco announced their merger plans in July and have
set a Sept. 30 date for shareholders to vote on the deal. Those two
companies say this union will save $200 million in costs. Fathi of
ABN Amro said a merger with Phelps Dodge could realize another $200
million in savings _ by eliminating redundant operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
