<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4768 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-YUGO-MONTENEGRO-ART-N     08-20 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-MONTENEGRO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELGRADE'S SHADOW FALLS ON MONTENEGRO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Italy)  (See also YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS) 
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By CHRIS HEDGES  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAR, Montenegro _ The rows of slate-gray missile boats rock at
their moorings behind a chain link fence, the Yugoslav sailors
shaded from the unforgiving sun by tarps over the back decks.
Frigates patrol the emerald green waters off the coast and board
incoming freighters for inspection.
</P>
<P>
   A few thousand Yugoslav Army soldiers, in a spacious, grassy
base up the road from the port, drill in combat fatigues and do
maintenance work on Soviet-style tanks and armored personnel
carriers. The outward appearance of order, aided by the soporific
heat, belies a looming rebellion, one that could draw these units
into yet another conflict in Yugoslavia's seemingly endless cycle
of war.
</P>
<P>
   As Montenegro, the second Yugoslav republic, grows more
vociferous in its demands for independence, there are mounting
calls for military intervention from Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The political leadership in Montenegro says that in recent days
the generals and admirals who command some 10,000 Yugoslav soldiers
and sailors here have become antagonistic and uncooperative.
</P>
<P>
   Bar, a major deep-sea commercial port, would probably be the
first piece of real estate seized by Belgrade in the event of a
clash.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yugoslav Navy abuses its privileges in the port,'' said
Mico Orlandic, Bar's deputy mayor. ``During the NATO air strikes
the navy fired missiles at NATO planes and blocked entry to the
port. We were powerless to stop them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The navy ships stop freighters coming into the harbor to carry
out inspections and look for arms,'' he said. ``The army, when it
leaves its barracks, sets up unauthorized roadblocks and seizes
goods. When we try to speak to the high command, they ignore us, as
if this is not our country. If the conflict worsens, we expect
Belgrade to try to seize the port.''
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro, a republic of 600,000 people, occupies 5 percent of
Yugoslav territory. The rest is Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Its president, Milo Djukanovic, once a protege and ally of the
Yugoslav President, Slobodan Milosevic, has moved steadily to
distance himself from Belgrade and build ties with the Western
alliance, a policy that largely spared Montenegro from NATO attacks
during the bombing. Djukanovic made his boldest bid to break away
on Aug. 5, proposing that the union between the two states be
scrapped to create a ``commonwealth of the states of Serbia and
Montenegro.''
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro, he said, would maintain its own army and foreign
ministry and issue its own currency. If the proposal, which has
been branded ``unconstitutional and undemocratic'' by Belgrade, is
rejected, as now seems certain, Montenegro will hold a referendum
this fall calling for independence.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade has compared the proposal to the one it spurned with
the Kosovar Albanians in Rambouillet, France, one of the incidents
that led to the war. The Yugoslav government has been lashing out
daily at the Montenegrin leadership in the state-controlled media,
painting it as a ``stooge of NATO'' and part of the Western effort
to topple Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, allies of Milosevic, like Montenegro's
Socialist People's Party, have asked the Yugoslav military to
``restore order.'' The party, led by the current Yugoslav prime
minister, Momir Bulatovic, lost power to Djukanovic in elections in
Montenegro last year, but is the only party representing Montenegro
in Belgrade. The Belgrade press now paints him as the legitimate
leader of Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Tomislav Nikolic, the deputy prime minister of Yugoslavia, said
this week that if Montenegro goes ahead with the referendum ``the
army will have to get involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrija Perisic, an executive member of Montenegro's ruling
Democratic Party of Socialists, said he and other Montenegrin
officials are convinced that Belgrade is secretly preparing ``the
same scenario that was used in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   The Montengrin republic, bereft of profitable industry, has
become a haven for smugglers who race fast boats across the
Adriatic to Italy. Djukanovic, Western diplomats say, made his
fortune running untaxed cigarettes and fruit to Italy and importing
black market gasoline. Pencil-thin cigarette boats line the docks
or cruise slowly in the harbor, their powerful engines purring.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro, unlike Slovenia, Croatia or even Bosnia, would have
a tough time severing economic ties with Serbia. The port, an
extremely profitable enterprise, has been deserted since NATO
bombed the rail links with Serbia. The airy warehouses, vast
30,000-ton grain silos and docks are lifeless. Bar, which can
handle 5 million tons of goods a year, has moved less than half a
million tons this year. The tourism industry that brought in $150
million a year before the war is dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be suicide to try to run the port without Serbian
imports and exports,'' said Alexsander Jovtic, one of the directors
of the port.
</P>
<P>
   One recent day two off-duty soldiers sat writing letters home.
</P>
<P>
   They said they did not relish any clash with the local
population, but would not disobey orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the army one does what one is told,'' said one of the
soldiers. ``We are being prepared for this. If we are told to take
the port, we will do it. It is our job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 2226EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
