<HEADER>
A4769 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKL-PLAYER-MOTHERS-AR     08-20 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-PLAYER-MOTHERS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHERHOOD IS A BALANCING ACT FOR WNBA PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Colo., Ariz., Calif., Md., Ohio, Pa., Hungary,
Brazil, the Netherlands)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By LENA WILLIAMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Edna Campbell juggles the demands of her job with the
responsibility of being a parent, a dual life complicated because
she is also a single mother.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike women in the male-dominated corporate world, she
works in an environment dominated by women who share her burden and
who help ease the strain. Campbell plays basketball for a living.
</P>
<P>
   As a guard for the Phoenix Mercury she is one of 13 mothers who
play in the Women's National Basketball Association. The league,
which ends its regular season Saturday, also has a working mother,
Valerie B. Ackerman, as its president.
</P>
<P>
   Athletes who are mothers are nothing new, especially in
individual sports like golf, where age does not diminish skill and
itineraries can be tailored for each player. But just as
high-profile team sports are new for women, so are the demands on
mothers who travel with the teams.
</P>
<P>
   Two members of the U.S. women's national soccer team are married
mothers who traveled with their children _ but not their husbands _
for the six months they were preparing for the World Cup
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the WNBA mothers say, the complexity of parenthood, coupled
with the problems of travel and night games, has forged changes in
the way they organize their work and family lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're charting new waters, but it's a great way in which we
are doing it,'' Carla McGhee, a guard with the Orlando Miracle who
is raising two children, said. ``We're including extended families,
getting friends and our teammates involved. It makes the job a lot
easier.''
</P>
<P>
   McGhee, like nearly half of the players with children, is a
single mother. So is one of the league's biggest stars, Sheryl
Swoopes. The Houston Comets player, whose pregnancy coincided with
the WNBA's making its debut in 1996, announced her separation from
her husband before the WNBA season began in June.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, mothers throughout the 140-player league were
distressed when they learned that Pamela McGee, who played forward
last season for the Los Angeles Sparks, had lost custody of her
3-year-old daughter after her former husband said she missed
several scheduled visits with the child. The husband's lawyer
argued in court that McGee's WNBA career interfered with her
parenting. Before the start of the season, McGee, who is also
raising a 10-year-old son from a previous relationship, retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``As athletes we're disciplined and strong minded and think we
can handle it,'' said the Miracle's McGhee, who also recently
separated from her husband and is raising a 17-month-old son,
Chancellor, and a 13-year-old stepdaughter, Alexandria. ``Being a
professional woman, in the spotlight, making good money, would put
a strain on any relationship. Then with the travel. A lot of people
can't handle that.''
</P>
<P>
   The league does not provide child care, and the issue did not
arise during contract negotiations between the league and the
players union earlier this year. The WNBA's 32-game schedule, which
runs from June to August, makes child-care arrangements easier
because players can draw from a pool that includes college
students, family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely helps having that spouse there,'' said Suzie
McConnell Serio, whose husband, Pete, a schoolteacher, cares for
the couple's four children while she plays guard for the Cleveland
Rockers. ``The biggest thing for me is having the support of my
husband to do this, and having him be able to take care of the
kids. I can put time into training camp and stay focused on what I
need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Basketball mothers routinely bring their children to the
workplace, taking them to home games, practice, shoot-arounds and
on the road _ nannies and grandmothers in tow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having him on the road with me eases my mind,'' said Swoopes,
who has a nanny travel with her on the road to care for her
2-year-old son. ``Something could happen to him, but at least we're
in the same city. If he were at home, it would drive me crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell has managed to raise her 15-year-old son, David, and
pursue a successful nine-year career overseas, in the defunct
American Basketball League and now in the WNBA, with help from
family and friends. No matter how far she traveled, she called
David every other day.
</P>
<P>
   Now, when she is out of town on business, he runs up her
cellular phone bill calling her.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were supposed to call me when you arrived at the hotel,''
he has told Campbell when she forgets to call home the minute she
checks in. He calls to say he loves her. He calls to compliment her
on a job well done. He calls if he thinks she is slacking off.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   In 1948, before Fanny Blankers-Koen of the Netherlands became
the only woman to win four gold medals in track in one Olympics,
she was criticized for competing despite having two children.
Things have changed.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Swoopes, who graced the cover of Sports
Illustrated for Women magazine when she was nearly nine months
pregnant, managed to make her WNBA debut six weeks after giving
birth to her son.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was my role model,'' said McGhee, who turned a deaf ear to
those who suggested she hang up her ABL jersey after giving birth
to her son. ``A lot of people questioned my decision to return
after I had Chance, but I talked to Sheryl and seeing her do it
gave me the incentive.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior mother of the league is Campbell, whose son is the
oldest of the players' children.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell was a 15-year-old sophomore at Pittsburgh's Taylor
Allerdice High School when she discovered that she was pregnant.
She played 17 games before her coach, Janet Davis, found out that
her 5-foot-8-inch shooting forward and one of the school's most
popular students was three-and-a-half-months pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   The child's father offered little help. Campbell's mother was
battling alcoholism and her father had difficulty coping. Were it
not for Davis and her maternal grandmother, Jane McCloud, Campbell
might have become another statistic _ one of the millions of unwed
teen-age mothers who spend a lifetime wondering what might have
been.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to be another statistic, a welfare mother living
in a project raising my child,'' Campbell said during a telephone
interview from her Phoenix home. ``I had standards for the life I
wanted to live.''
</P>
<P>
   McCloud cared for David while Campbell attended college, first
at the University of Maryland, then at the University of Texas. In
1991, soon after she earned her degree in kinesiology, McCloud
died. David was 6 and Campbell was prepared to defer her dream of
playing overseas until Davis agreed to take care of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to leave my son, but I knew I also had to
provide for him and I wanted to play basketball,'' said Campbell,
adding upon reflection that if she had to do it again, she would
take David with her. ``Those were some tough times because I was
making decisions, not for the moment but for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   She played in Brazil for two years (1993-95) and in Hungary
(1995-96), leading the team in scoring. She called David every
other day. Still, she missed the hugs, the kisses, the tucking him
into bed at night, and when the ABL started in 1996, she jumped on
it like a loose ball. She signed with the Colorado Xplosion.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, mother and son have been inseparable. He is her
biggest fan. Those who know David, described him as smart, polite
and mature beyond his age. She is his role model, the player he
aspires to be like, measuring his own progress on the court by what
she accomplished at a similar age.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Campbell recently started a youth foundation in Colorado aimed
at helping teen-age parents pursue their education and future
careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many constraints and restrictions about what a
woman should or shouldn't do when she becomes a parent,'' Campbell
said. ``Should she stay at home with the kid or find a job or do
both? Over the years, I've found that it's not so much what people
think you can and cannot do. It's what you decide you want to
do.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 2227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
