<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-DIARY-$ADV22-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTMENT NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Aug. 22) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Stock Investors, A New Star System
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola got an F for value, Amazon.com flunked profitability
and Fruit of the Loom received a failing grade for financial
health.
</P>
<P>
   That was the harsh judgment of Morningstar Inc., best known for
its star system of mutual fund rankings, which has begun to rate
individual stocks as well.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to ``take the frustration out of analyzing stocks by
wrapping up all the calculations and financial statistics into a
straightforward grading system,'' said Haywood Kelly, editor of
Morningstar Stock Investor. About 7,500 American companies are
evaluated, relative to their industry peers, on four criteria:
growth rate, profitability, stock price and overall financial
condition.
</P>
<P>
   The ratings, updated each Saturday, are available free on the
company Web site, www.morningstar.com, though it takes some
burrowing. Type in a stock symbol, and then click on ``snapshot.''
</P>
<P>
   For the week ended Friday, Morningstar gave 43 companies all A's
. About 35 got three F's; most of these stocks are too young to be
rated on all four measures, though two _ Cogeneration and Robotic
Vision Systems _ did flunk across the board.
</P>
<P>
   By rating stocks on a variety of counts, the Morningstar grades
let investors plug holes in their portfolios or shop for companies
that fit their style.
</P>
<P>
   For example, though Fruit of the Loom got D's for growth and
profitability to go with its F for financial health, it may still
merit consideration because its stock is so cheap _ down from over
$30 a year ago to around $7 last week, when it had a B for
valuation from Morningstar.
</P>
<P>
   The rating systems of Standard &AMP; Poor's and Value Line, by
contrast, boil their findings down to a single score _ a star or
number, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Sanborn, research director at Value Line, said he did
not want to denigrate the new competition. But he noted that his
company's rankings offer much more background data on companies.
</P>
<P>
   _ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.
</P>
<P>
   FUNDS WATCH: Spiders and Their Close Kin
</P>
<P>
   As the bull market lures more mutual fund investors to trade
individual stocks, the giants of finance are devising more and more
investments that blend the characteristics of mutual funds,
closed-end funds and stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Salomon Smith Barney is joining Barclays Global Investors in
making plans to widen the assortment early next year of these
so-called exchange-traded funds, which are listed on the American
Stock Exchange. Barclays is expected to offer dozens of the
products, which trade like individual stocks but, like index funds,
represent a bundle of shares; Salomon Smith Barney will offer a
single Internet fund. So far, each company has filed only a request
for certain legal exemptions, but not a registration statement.
</P>
<P>
   The filings are further evidence of the growing popularity of
exchange-traded funds. The first such investments, Standard &AMP;
Poor's depository receipts, commonly known as SPDR's (pronounced
``spiders''), have virtually doubled in trading volume each year
since their introduction in 1993. Now SPDR's and similar
investments account for almost $21 billion in assets and are core
products of the American Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a kind of cottage industry around here,'' said
Gary Gastineau, senior vice president for new products at the
exchange. ``While we do some marketing, it has not been done in a
professional way.'' He expects Barclays and other fund sponsors to
do more. And, Gastineau added, he is expecting other investment
firms to announce plans in the next two months for as many as 50
more exchange-traded funds.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the funds have proved most attractive as hedging
vehicles for managers of smaller funds. But intraday pricing, the
ability to sell short and place limit orders, and the low costs
should appeal to retail investors, said Ed McRedmond, senior
analyst at A.G. Edwards, the St. Louis-based brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   The 51 prospective funds listed in the Barclays filing would
track 24 Dow Jones and 16 S&AMP;P domestic and international equity
indexes and 11 Russell domestic equity indexes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect _ and no one expects _ that Barclays will do
all of those,'' Gastineau said. ``But everything they say suggests
that they will do a substantial number of them.'' Barclays declined
to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The funds are designed so that any deviation from the value of
the indexed stocks provides someone with an arbitrage opportunity;
the trading, in effect, forces the funds to track the index. They
have low annual fees, but investors must pay commissions on
transactions. _SARA ROBINSON
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
