<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-WES-ANDERSON-$ADV22-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NIGHT OUT WITH WES ANDERSON DISSECTING FILMS AND SERIAL KILLERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use on Sunday, Aug. 22) 
(jt) 
 By SUSAN M. KIRSCHBAUM    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shortly after 10 p.m. the other night, Hampton
Fancher was at Black and White, a bistro in the East Village,
nursing a minibottle of Buzet, an inexpensive Bordeaux he had
bought at the corner wine shop. The 60-year-old screenwriter, best
known for the 1982 sci-fi thriller ``Blade Runner,'' was at the
post-screening party for ``The Minus Man,'' a low-budget feature he
wrote and directed about a mild-mannered serial killer.
</P>
<P>
   By Hollywood standards, it wasn't a glamorous affair: no rope,
no paparazzi, no one dressed to kill. Fancher, in a wrinkled check
shirt, was clocking time at the bar, waiting for the arrival of his
pal the writer and director Wes Anderson, the party's host. So was
everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the J.D. Salinger of film,'' Fancher said of Anderson,
30, whose first film, ``Bottle Rocket,'' propelled him to cult
status. Anderson's second film, ``Rushmore,'' a surprise-hit comedy
about an eccentric prep school student, added to his legend among
obsessed cineastes whose idea of a big night is sitting around
drinking and talking about film theory and Truffaut's use of the
iris shot.
</P>
<P>
   Janeane Garofalo, who stars in ``The Minus Man'' as the killer's
girlfriend, was one of the first to arrive, dressed in navy sweat
pants and an Iams dog food T-shirt. ``What are your doing here?''
Fancher asked, surprised she was in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm taping some bumpers for the MTV video awards,'' Ms.
Garofalo said, ``and I'll be doing some voice-overs for
`Felicity.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``What is Felicity?'' he asked, unaware of the show, set in a
New York University dorm. ``A cartoon?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me make it clear,'' Ms. Garofalo said. ``I'm not Daria.
It's a series, like ``My So-Called Life.'''
</P>
<P>
   Those references, too were lost on Fancher, who is more
interested in Chekhov and Fellini. Just then, Anderson arrived. In
thin-rimmed glasses and a button-down shirt, he sat in a booth
beside Fancher, looking like a college preppy or a Salinger
character. A waiter was taking orders for dinner. ``I'm having the
flank steak,'' Anderson said. ``I've gotten criticism for being
skinny all of my life. I want to put on a solid 10 pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Back to the round table of cinemaspeak. ``How many good scripts
have you read in your life?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked `Rosemary's Baby,''' Anderson replied. Then he began a
discussion of Truffaut films including ``Love at 20'' (1962).
``There's something about those movies that's not cynical,''
Anderson said, ``an affection for his characters, trying things to
give emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   As Anderson finished his steak, Erik Feig, a producer of the
teen-age blockbuster ``I Know What You Did Last Summer,'' stopped
by to pay homage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Wes that `Rushmore' was a soul movie,'' Feig recalled,
``so Wes said, `Yes, but you're making a movie that kids like.' I
felt better after that.'''
</P>
<P>
   By dessert, the table was deep in a discussion of the
photographer Jacques-Henri Lartigue, until Anderson ran out of gas.
``I've got to go speak to some people,'' he said, excusing himself.
Fancher joined him, saying, ``I'll come, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
