Council House Global Conference Center of the Johnson company. The
Johnson family, owners of S.C. Johnson Intl., is one of the few
large corporations that is still family owned. A plan -- to carve
the $5 billion enterprise into three unequal parts, giving each
interested child a separate company to run -- was more than 30
years in the making and born out of earlier brushes with family
disaster. (Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Aug. 20, 1999 -- JOINT-CUSTODY-PETS, 08-20
-- Michael Cecchi and Jennifer McConnell with Luca, their
Staffordshire terrier. Cecchi and McConnell, who broke up three
years ago, share custody of the dog. More and more couples appear
to be arranging what might be called pet joint custody, especially
in a city like New York where there are lots of childless adults
bonding intensely with their animal companions. (Philip
Greenberg/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) TROY, N.Y. -- Aug. 20, 1999 -- JACKSON-PHYSICS, 08-20 --
Shirley Ann Jackson, president of Renssalaer Polytechnic Institute,
stands in front of the Troy Building, which houses her office. The
institute is the nation's oldest university dedicated to science
and engineering. During a recent interview, Jackson calmly recalled
being shot at and spat on during her years as one of the few black
students at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. She also
revealed a will as tough as polished steel. (David Jennings/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Aug. 20, 1999 --ADV. FOR AUGUST 22 --
INVEST-PHONES, 8-20 -- Competition is rising in local phone markets
and decades-old companies no longer have the local communications
business to themselves. Splicers, above, installed fiber-optic
cable for RCN in Manhattan. Below, the interior of a connection
box, or splice. (Frances Roberts/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MADISON, Wisc. -- Aug. 20, 1999 -- FRESHMEN-PARENTS,
08-20 -- Parents and students going through freshman orientation at
the University of Wisconsin-Madison. While orientations for
incoming freshmen have long been fixtures at colleges around the
U.S., the systematic immersion of parents is recent. Universities
that are including parents in the orientation hope to enlist them
as coaches in proding their children to greatness as well as assist
in the parents' own roller-coaster emotions as they prepare to
break away from their companions of the last 18 years. (Andy
Manis/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) DOWNERS GROVE, Ill. -- Aug. 20, 1999 --
BIZ-DOWNERS-GROVE, 08-20 -- Construction in the town's main street.
The town thinks the past is the future: To preserve its prosperity,
this aging Chicago suburb is redeveloping its business district
away from big-box retailing and back toward a traditional Main
Street. Other towns are doing the same, and the reason may come as
a surprise: The Internet. (Steve Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BOSTON -- Aug. 20, 1999 -- NEW-GORILLA, 08-20 -- The
Franklin Park Zoo's western lowland gorilla, Kiki, 18, cuddles her
first-born baby on Thursday. The gorilla infant, whose gender has
yet to be determined, was born on August 8, in a delivery that zoo
officials said was completely natural and without complications. A
contest for the public to contribute ideas on names for the young
gorilla will begin on September 4. (David L. Ryan/Boston Globe
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NAPLES, N.Y. -- Aug. 20, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 22
-- BIZ-PROFILE-SANDS, 08-20 -- Richard Sands, left, CEO of
Canandaigua Brands Inc., watches the production line with Jake
Makepeace, the winery manager. Canandaigua Brands Inc., is
currently one of the hottest names, in the wine and spirits
industry. After a dazzling string of acquisitions, Canandaigua has
become the country's second-largest wine producer, after E.&AMP;J.
Gallo. (Mike Groll/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) JERUSALEM -- Aug. 20, 1999 -- ISRAEL-PERES, 08-20 --
Shimon Peres, the former Israeli foreign minister during a meeting
earlier this year. Peres, a Nobel laureat for his work as architect
of the Oslo peace framework between Israel and the Palestinians,
and Israel's longest-serving and best-known statesman, is the new
Minister of Regional Cooperation. But his is a title in search of
authority for a ministry that so far has no budget, no staff and no
agreed functions. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) SEATTLE -- Aug. 20, 1999 -- CHEMICAL-SENSITIVITY-SPI,
08-19 -- Nancy Morris searches for a movie on laser disk in a local
video store. Because Ms. Morris suffers from severe asthma and
Multiple Chemical Sensitivity (MCS) she often wears a masks when
venturing out of her home. Individuals with MCS generally trace the
start of their illness to a massive chemical exposure or repeat
exposures. Ms. Morris attributes hers to contact with the pesticide
2,4-D as an infant. (Rick Giase/Seattle Post-Intelligencer Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) ATLANTA -- Aug. 20, 1999 -- TWIN-DOCS-2-COX, 08-14 -- Dr.
Travis K. Jasper, top, an emergency room doctor at Emory University
