<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAMING-GIRAFFES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE BRONX ZOO, JAMES XI, IS A BENEFACTOR'S TALL LEGACY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Regarding summer babies of New York, there are
probably none whose eyelashes are as long and lovely as those of
James the 11th, who arrived July 8, at the Bronx Zoo. He is a
giraffe, and like all male giraffes born at the zoo is named for
James Walter Carter, a benefactor who died in 1981, at age 85.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 11 James the giraffes born at the zoo since this
practice began, shortly after the death of Carter. Female giraffes
are named for Carter's wife, Margaret, who died in 1984, and there
have been only three. The zoo does not keep all its Jameses and
Margarets, but at present, in its 7-member herd, five are so named,
which, from a zoo keeper's point of view is like being invited to
dinner at George Foreman's house.
</P>
<P>
   ``We give them other names,'' says Kristine Theis. ``James 5th,
for instance, who is the father of James 11th, we call James Lee,
for one of the keepers. People think giraffes aren't that
intelligent, but they do know their names, and if we called them
all James, they would all come. At one time we had 11 giraffes; it
got a little confusing.''
</P>
<P>
   Who is this guy Carter and why are all our fine New York City
giraffes being named for him?
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who also underwrote the Carter Giraffe Building _ which
opened in 1982, was a private fellow who specified in his will that
all personal files and records be destroyed. &UR;  &LR; Newspapers carried
the briefest of obituaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a coal miner in Virginia and he owned a farm in
Virginia, and when they sold the farm and were divvying it up, they
asked us if we'd like the tractors and some of their stuff,'' says
Linda Corcoran, the spokeswoman for the Wildlife Conservation
Society, which runs the zoo. ``They were regular folks. They had
either an apartment in the Carlyle or stayed in the Carlyle. I
remember her, she was quite elderly, this teeny, tiny little lady
they were always loading into a golf cart.''
</P>
<P>
   A coal miner living in the Carlyle?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think an owner of some kind. They weren't pick and shovel
people.''
</P>
<P>
   An amplification, from Dr. William Conway, who heads the
Society, and met the pair on many occasions: ``He made a lot of his
fortune in coal mining and had sat across the table from John L.
Lewis, the famous labor leader. They were not friends.''
</P>
<P>
   One hopes that a fellow who was so generous to a public park was
not a union buster.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was too nice a man,'' says another zoo person and another
James, this one being James G. Doherty, a curator who holds the
Carter Chair of Mammalogy at the zoo. ``They were both wonderfully
gentle human beings. I don't think they would have stepped on an
ant.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York City Carter giraffes, which the zoo has been
shipping all over the country, have quite a history in Virginia.
George Lafayette Carter, the father of James Walter Carter, was a
wealthy mine, rail, and land owner. So strong was Carter's desire
for privacy that he forbade his own newspaper, The Bristol Herald
Courier, to print his name. His son, James Walter Carter, the owner
of the Carter Coal Co., was, according to information furnished by
the Virginia Historical Society and the United Mine Workers, a
``lone wolf.'' He sold the Carter Coal Co. in 1947 during a
nationwide strike involving the creation of a health and retirement
fund for the mine workers, ``because he refused to submit to union
domination.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Portraits of the young and handsome Carters _ he, on
horseback, in a riding costume; she in a feathered evening gown,
with a fan _ by the noted portrait artist Sir Oswald Birley hang at
the offices of the Virginia Historical &UR;  &LR; Society.
</P>
<P>
   Why the couple, who collected rare books and coins, and left
equal parts of their estate to the Metropolitan Museum of Art and
the zoo, were interested in giraffes, no one knows.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of naming the giraffes for Carters, ad infinitum, was
Conway's.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is the usual bronze plaque on the Carter Giraffe
House,'' Conway says, ``but a living memorial is so much nicer.
They gave us a series of magnificent gifts and remembered us very
generously.''
</P>
<P>
   How generously?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was just under 20 million dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   There are, Conway notes, other animals at the Bronx Zoo named
after humans. A rhino is named for Mrs. Gordon B. Pattee, the vice
chairman of the society, who has given ``most generously.'' Jack
Rudin, the real estate executive, contributed an elephant, or
rather the cost of an elephant, a few years ago in honor of his
father, Sam. The zoo wanted a female and got one, but the elephant
is still called Sammy. Conway does not recall whether the tab was
$25,000 or $35,000.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Are animals ever named for people who don't have money?
</P>
<P>
   ``I confess there are a pair of gibbons at Jungle World named
for my wife and myself,'' Conway says. ``There are animals that are
named for an important employee or some trusted keeper. We do have
some fun with the mole rats. Mole rats _ I hate to say this about
any animal _ but mole rats are not pretty. Naked little pink guys
with big protruding teeth and little squinty eyes that do not work
and holes for ears. We sometimes joke with the trustees or other
donors: `You have a choice of making a gift or not making a gift
and having us name a mole rat after you.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 2319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4869 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RUN-WORLD-CHAMPS-NYT &LR;      08-20 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-WORLD-CHAMPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WORLD-CLASS WEEK IN SEVILLE: HOT, FAST, HOTTER, FASTER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Brazil, Germany, the Ukraine, France, Trinidad and Tobago,
Cuba, Jamaica, Switzerland, N.C.)   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEVILLE, Spain _ There is a painting by Gonzalo Bilbao in the
Museo de Bellas Artes here that is called ``A Summer Night in
Seville.'' It depicts people sleeping in the street in an attempt
to cope with the heat for which the Andalusian capital is nearly as
famous in Spain as for its Moorish monuments, elegant bullring,
flower-filled patios and Sybaritic spring festival, La Feria.
</P>
<P>
   August, with temperatures that routinely approach and surpass 40
degrees centigrade (more than 100 Fahrenheit), is not usually a
month for moving fast in a city where beads of sweat can form in
the midst of a very short stroll or even a very long siesta. But
this August will be a glaring exception: most of the world's best
runners, jumpers and hurlers of javelins and sundry other objects
have arrived, and beginning Saturday, they will spend nine
potentially steamy nights competing for medals in the world track
and field championships.
</P>
<P>
   It is a somewhat curious marriage: this event and Seville, a
proud, provincial city whose denizens remain, in principle, much
more interested in El Juli, the extraordinary teen-age matador,
than in Hicham el-Guerrouj, the extraordinary middle-distance
runner; more interested in whether Real Betis or FC Sevilla will
win their soccer matches over the weekend than whether Maurice
Greene will win the men's 100; more interested in having a private
caseta at La Feria than a private box for this event.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the seventh edition of the world championships,
which began in 1983 and shifted from a quadrennial to biennial
affair in 1991 in Tokyo. It was hot that year in Japan, too, just
as it was hot in Athens in 1997. But Seville could raise the bar
and the mercury to new levels, although the sagacious scheduling _
there will be only a smattering of competition between 1 p.m. and 6
p.m. _ should alleviate some of the suffering. With the exception
of the women's marathon, all medal events will be held in the
evening, and though recent evenings have been pleasant, if hardly
cool, a heat wave is forecast for next week.
</P>
<P>
   At least one distance star, Ronaldo da Costa, the Brazilian who
ran the fastest marathon in history last year in Berlin, has
decided not to compete here because of the heat. He is hardly the
only prominent absentee. Sergei Bubka of Ukraine, who has won the
gold medal in the pole vault in all six previous world
championships, is still recovering from injury. Heike Drechsler,
the German long jumper who also had competed in every previous
championships, withdrew on Friday with an injury of her own.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Jose-Perec of France, a double gold medalist in the 1996
Summer Olympics, only recently returned to minor competition after
recovering from Epstein-Barr syndrome and other ailments. She is
not yet ready for a major event like this one. Ato Boldon of
Trinidad and Tobago, the defending world champion in the men's 200
meters and perhaps the only man who could have threatened Greene's
dominance in the 100, has withdrawn with a hamstring injury.
Donovan Bailey, the reigning Olympic champion in the 100, is not
entered here because he is still finding his form after rupturing
his Achilles' tendon.
</P>
<P>
   Dan O'Brien, the best if hardly healthiest decathlete of the
1990s, is out, as is James Beckford, the Jamaican long jumper and
former world silver medalist, along with Beckford's star teammate
Merlene Ottey, who withdrew after traces of the banned steroid
nandrolone were found in one of her urine samples. Javier
Sotomayor, the defending world and Olympic champion in the high
jump from Cuba, tested positive for cocaine earlier this month and
then withdrew, citing a herniated disk in his back.
</P>
<P>
   El-Guerrouj, the world-record holder in the 1,500 and the mile,
once announced plans not to compete here and focus instead on
winning the Olympic gold medal next year. But he was persuaded to
change his mind, and after an acute case of hemorrhoids sidelined
him in July, he returned for meets (and big appearance fees) in
London and Zurich and ran well enough to re-establish his dominance
in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Other overwhelming favorites in their events include Marion
Jones in the women's sprints, Greene in the 100, Wilson Kipketer in
the 800, Haile Gebrselassie in the 10,000 and Ivan Pedroso in the
long jump. In normal circumstances, Michael Johnson would be on
that list, too. But the three-time defending world champion in the
400 has had recurring problems with his hamstrings and withdrew
from the U.S. national championships, where he planned to run
against Greene in the 200.
</P>
<P>
   Though thousands of tickets remain unsold, the crowds should be
quite respectable, despite the fact that many locals are in the
midst of their annual pilgrimage to the highlands or the beach.
They have fled to escape the heat, leaving their monuments and tapa
bars to the tourists and their fast new track to the athletes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
