<HEADLINE>
SUPPORT SLIPPING FOR FLAT VEHICLE-LICENSE FEE, POLL SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELA GALLOWAY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLYMPIA, Wash. _ A ballot measure to cut vehicle license taxes
to $30 still enjoys wide support among voters, but that support is
eroding, a new poll shows.
</P>
<P>
   Initiative 695 would impose a flat $30 license tax for all
vehicles, regardless of worth, and would require voter approval for
all new government fees or taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Elway Research, an independent pollster, reported this week that
59 percent of voters polled supported the initiative; 32 percent
opposed it; and 9 percent were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, with a margin of error of 5 percentage points,
surveyed 400 voters throughout Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The results buoyed the initiative's supporters. ``The Elway poll
simply confirms people's own common sense and conviction that I-695
will pass overwhelmingly this November,'' said sponsor Tim Eyman.
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Funk, spokesman for the No-on-695 campaign, said the
results show that support for the measure is dropping.
</P>
<P>
   A June poll found that 73 percent supported the initiative, with
22 percent opposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (Eyman) is not cresting 60 (percent) on this one, he could
have some tough times coming up,'' Funk said. ``Clearly,
something's happening out there. The numbers are coming down and we
think it's going to be a steady trend downward.''
</P>
<P>
   The findings came on the heels of the Secretary of State's
Office releasing its voter guide on the measure a few days ago on
the Internet. Eyman interpreted that guide as a breakthrough for
his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He was pleased that the statement against the initiative
contained only two endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   Eyman's voters guide statement for the initiative had eight
other endorsements _ from campaign volunteers including retirees, a
plumber and a homemaker.
</P>
<P>
   But Funk said the two men endorsing the opposition statement
represent thousands of Washington entrepreneurs and workers. They
are Don Brunell of the Association of Washington Business and Rick
Bender of the Washington State Labor Council, AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   While Eyman has pitched his campaign as a battle between
Everyman and the ``special interests that own Olympia,'' few
politicians have spoken out against the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   But Eyman's group should not underestimate the grass-roots
opposition on the horizon, Funk said. It's a movement expected to
spend $2 million to $4 million, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those opponents will bring home to voters how the measure's
elimination of an estimated $1 billion in revenue over the next two
years will hurt police and fire services, health programs, mass
transit and highway construction, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will see in the next few weeks that there are going to be
hundreds and thousands of people in Washington state that are going
to come out against this proposal,'' Funk said. ``We will have
plenty of people in the trenches when this thing gets up and
running, trust me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
