<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUMMER-SCHOOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOST SUMMER SCHOOL STUDENTS PASS A TEST FOR PROMOTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ More than 60 percent of the students from the third,
sixth and eighth grades who took the standardized tests at the end
of mandatory summer school in New York City this year passed and
will be allowed to move on to the next grade, according to
preliminary results released Friday, pleasing Board of Education
officials but suggesting that thousands of children will be held
back.
</P>
<P>
   Board officials said it would be a couple of weeks before they
could say definitively how many students would be promoted to the
next grade, though local administrators could begin notifying
students next week.
</P>
<P>
   Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew and his aides said that except for
extraordinary mitigating circumstances students who failed the test
or tests they were required to take would not advance to the next
grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that absolute,'' Crew said Friday in an interview. ``I am
not letting kids go forward if they did not pass the tests.''
</P>
<P>
   Crew said he was heartened by the results, which he said
demonstrated that the small class sizes _ none were to exceed 10
students _ and intensive focus on reading and math could yield good
results.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of instructional format works,'' he said. ``I was
pretty pleased about all of it.'' He added that he found the
results encouraging because ``the range in actual percent that
passed was pretty much within what we thought was feasible.''
</P>
<P>
   There was wide variation in test results, with performance
generally reflecting patterns observed on other standardized exams.
Poorer districts still did worse overall than more affluent ones.
</P>
<P>
   The data released Friday is not the final word on the program,
which was the largest use of mandatory summer school in New York
City in a decade. In past years, students were routinely promoted
to the next grade regardless of their academic achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Board officials said 37,050 students were in the mandated
program, but they did not release a figure for how many of them did
not take the tests or how many of the students took both tests,
which were given Aug. 3 to 5.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Tobias, the board's director of assessment, said that at
least 70 percent of the students took at least one test but that
officials were still reviewing the results and score sheets for
discrepancies and could not yet release a firm number.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the percentages of who passed and failed are likely
to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all pretty raw,'' said Karen Crowe, a spokeswoman for
the board, which nevertheless released the early findings because
of the strong public interest in summer school.
</P>
<P>
   The board reported the results of 20,000 students who took
reading tests in grades 3, 6 and 8; 19,000 who took math tests in
those grades, and, as part of a smaller program, 2,145 bilingual
students who took a written portion of the English proficiency
exams, the Language Assessment Battery.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 20,000 students who took reading tests, 63.8 percent
passed, the board said. Of those who took math exams, 61.2 percent
passed. And among students who took the Language Assessment
Battery, 72.2 percent passed.
</P>
<P>
   There were wide variations among the grades and among community
school districts. In third-grade reading, for example, a barometer
for the overall academic health of the system and an area Crew has
vowed to greatly improve, 57.9 passed the test citywide. But among
eighth graders, the passing rate on the reading exam was 74.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Rizzo, the deputy chancellor of instruction, said
officials would review the results and make changes for next year,
when Crew has proposed expanding the program to grades 3 through
12.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
