<HEADLINE>
PAPADAKIS OUT INDEFINITELY WITH BROKEN FOOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ USC had its first significant injury of
training camp Friday when senior tailback Petros Papadakis broke
his right foot in practice.
</P>
<P>
   Papadakis, who averaged 3.9 yards per carry last season, broke
his foot while being tackled by defensive end Kori Dickerson during
a full-contact play and will be sidelined indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just broke it clean and a guy tackled him from behind. It
wasn't anything unusual,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said. ``How
extensive is it? We don't know yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Papadakis was USC's short-yardage specialist last season,
scoring eight touchdowns and rushing for 468 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing Petros, he will be back as soon as humanly possible.
That's a blow,'' Hackett said. ``He's really the power guy. That's
going to be one of the real challenges the rest of camp, to see who
takes that role.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Papadakis, several players will now try to replace him
as the No.2 tailback behind Chad Morton.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates are redshirt freshman Sultan McCullough,
sophomore Frank Strong, senior Jabari Jackson and sophomore
Malaefou MacKenzie.
</P>
<P>
   MacKenzie is practicing only once a day, as Hackett tries to
bring him back slowly from last year's knee surgery and a sore
hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   ``That'll be wide open,'' Hackett said. ``We've got to give that
a lot of thought now.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of nowhere: It's early, but true freshman
linebacker/defensive end Omar Nazel, who received little publicity
coming out of high school, might not redshirt this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's worked his way into an opportunity in our nickel
defense,'' Hackett said. ``If he continues to progress, he'll get
some playing time.''
</P>
<P>
   Nazel is among those who are surprised that Hackett is already
offering praise this early in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say being a freshman, I'm surprised,'' Nazel said. ``A
lot of people are skeptical. I don't pose any threat to anybody.
I'm not the biggest thing out there. I don't scare anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Nazel is 6-foot-5 but weighs just 220 pounds. His athleticism
has impressed coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Steele practices: Linebacker Markus Steele finally practiced,
although he was allowed to wear only shorts. He has missed nearly a
week while waiting for his junior-college transcripts to be
processed and sent to USC.
</P>
<P>
   Steele hasn't practiced or worn pads since Dec.13 of last year,
when he played for Long Beach City College.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very possible for me to go out there and try to start
(the season opener against Hawaii),'' Steele said. ``I feel very
confident at weakside linebacker. I feel like I'm two weeks behind
everybody. It'll probably be another week before I'm in game
shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said Steele will practice at least two more days in
shorts before wearing pads.
</P>
<P>
   Steele will wear No. 55, which was worn by Chris Claiborne and
is traditionally worn by USC's best linebacker. Middle linebacker
Zeke Moreno declined the number to wear his high school No. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Craig Mitchell, another JC transfer, visited USC
on Friday but has not received his transcripts and is not expected
before midweek.
</P>
<P>
   Depth chart news: Hackett said true freshman Kareem Kelly is
practicing behind Windrell Hayes at wide receiver while Marcell
Allmond is behindh &Cx1f; FyD
</P>
</TEXT>
