<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4889 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-20 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELIGIOUS LEADERS, CAMPAIGN FINANCE REFORM IS A MATTER OF
FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By PETER STEINFELS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is campaign finance reform a religious issue? Obviously, some
religious leaders say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The National Council of Churches' longstanding commitment to
campaign finance reform grows directly from profound religious
faith,'' the Rev. Joan Brown Campbell, the council's general
secretary, said in February 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Campbell cited the belief that ``every human being is a
person of dignity and worth as a child of God'' and that ``in our
democracy a signal of that dignity and worth is a fair and just
electoral process.''
</P>
<P>
   She was speaking at a news conference called by Religious
Leaders for Campaign Finance Reform, a group of leaders from more
than 20 Christian denominations or churches as well as Reform
Judaism and the Unitarian Universalist Association.
</P>
<P>
   At the same conference, Rabbi David Saperstein, director of the
Religious Action Center of Reform Judaism, declared that ``campaign
finance reform is not an esoteric technical issue of election
regulations, but one that goes to the essence of the ethical and
moral life of our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Still pressing its cause, in a letter sent to House members in
May, the group stated, ``Campaign finance reform is a moral matter
for the religious community. The temptation to use money to buy
unjust favors is an ancient one that is dealt with often in
Scripture.''
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, what these religious leaders say is undeniable,
and, as vast sums are being amassed for next year's elections, even
more timely now than when they organized in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that if campaign finance is a moral, and
therefore a religious, issue, the same can be said of much, perhaps
most, of what politics is about. If organized religion has a
distinctive contribution to the public debate, the question becomes
not whether religious bodies should care about campaign finance
reform but how. How should they mobilize religious categories and
rhetoric? What ought to be their tone and who their primary
audience?
</P>
<P>
   There are several models, not necessarily mutually exclusive.
The Religious Leaders for Campaign Finance Reform present the
standard lobbying model. Their statements appeal to familiar moral
arguments: government's responsibility to the common good rather
than special interests, the equality of citizens and the need to
protect the weak from the powerful, the danger of public cynicism
and the erosion of trust in public authorities, honesty and
accountability.
</P>
<P>
   The language is similar to what many politicians might use,
although the group does provide a list of pertinent Scriptural
references. Many are condemnations of bribery in the Hebrew
Scriptures and of partiality for the rich over the poor in the New
Testament.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition specifically endorses the Shays-Meehan bill in the
House and the McCain-Feingold bill in the Senate as first steps and
the Kerry-Wellstone proposal for public financing of campaigns as a
more comprehensive solution.
</P>
<P>
   A draft statement on campaign finance reform being circulated
for comment by the state conference of Roman Catholic bishops in
Wisconsin offers another model. At about 3,000 words, it is much
more discursive and philosophical in tone than the religious
leaders' punchier assertions, although it makes similar points. It
begins, for instance, with ``a central tenet of Catholic social
teaching,'' the view passed from Aristotle through Aquinas, that
``the human person is a social being.''
</P>
<P>
   From there, the Wisconsin bishops' draft moves to ``the right
and responsibility to be involved citizens,'' the common good, the
need for virtue in public life and the distorting effect of current
campaign financing. There are no references to Scripture but
several to church documents.
</P>
<P>
   The bishops also offer some disclaimers. First, they note that
``like most citizens, we lack expertise in the art of campaigning
for office.'' Second, they warn that no reforms can substitute for
citizens' willingness to devote time and effort to political
activity. Third, they indicate that ``we do not intend to endorse
any specific reform proposal'' but instead propose criteria for
evaluating various proposals.
</P>
<P>
   While leaving the specifics of reform ``to lay citizens and
their elected representatives,'' the draft takes up two questions
of special moral or religious concern. Would public financing of
campaigns make taxpayers morally complicitous in advancing opinions
or practices they find morally repugnant? Would limiting campaign
expenditures restrict free speech, ``including educational efforts
by religious groups''?
</P>
<P>
   Both questions may reflect the concerns of anti-abortion groups,
who have sometimes worried along with some civil libertarians about
the impact of restrictions on private political expenditures. It is
interesting that the bishops' conclusion is ``no'' on both counts,
but perhaps not as interesting as their diligence in airing the
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a third model emerges from the efforts of the Religious
Action Center of Reform Judaism. On the one hand, the center is a
major partner in the Religious Leaders for Campaign Finance Reform.
On the other hand, like the Wisconsin bishops, it addresses the
issue within its own community in the terms specific to that
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the center alerts Jewish congregants not only to
Biblical passages but also to passages in the Talmud where the
rabbis warned that gifts blind the eyes of the wise as well as the
foolish and pervert the words of the righteous as well as the
wicked. The center addresses concerns that the Jewish community's
security and political role depend on campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   The Religious Leaders for Campaign Finance Reform are obviously
not afraid of appearing in tone and approach like other lobbying
groups. As a coalition, their approach cannot tap deeply into any
one religious tradition. Instead, it looks outward to the citizenry
at large and the nation's legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin's Roman Catholic bishops just as obviously assume that
their effectiveness depends on much more restraint. Their approach
strongly reflects a Catholic style of reasoning about public
issues. It looks inward more than outward, more concerned with
educating Catholics than lobbying legislators.
</P>
<P>
   The Religious Action Center seems to look both inward and
outward, drawing on familiar moral and political arguments but also
reflecting specific Jewish sources and concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from all three groups, by the way, certainly agree on
one point: It's an uphill battle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 2350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
