<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIANS-LAUNDER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI SEEKS MONEY-LAUNDERING EVIDENCE AT BANK OF NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for complete rewrite with new lede and new reporting. Note
different byline and hed.)  (mk) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Agents from the FBI searched the Wall Street
headquarters of the Bank of New York Friday, removing more than two
boxes of documents from the office of a top officer of the bank who
is at the center of an investigation of what is believed to be a
major money-laundering operation involving Russian organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   An individual close to the bank said that on Friday afternoon,
the authorities searched the office of Natasha Gurfinkel
Kagalovsky, a senior vice president of the bank, who supervised its
Eastern European division. The agents sealed Ms. Kagalovsky's
office before they left.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time federal agents had entered the bank's
headquarters, said the individual with knowledge of the raid.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kagalovsky was one of two bank employees suspended from the
bank on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The other employee was Lucy Edwards, a vice president in London.
Both women are married to Russian businessmen, one of whom is
believed by investigators to have controlled some of the accounts
that are the subject of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The action was the third such raid this week. In London, the
National Crime Squad searched the home and office of Ms. Edwards on
Wednesday and Thursday. Ms. Edwards' husband, Peter Berlin, had
authority over some of the accounts at the bank.
</P>
<P>
   The individual close to the bank in New York confirmed the
search of the London offices. He declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say they believe that Ms. Kagalovsky and Ms.
Edwards could be involved in one of the largest money-laundering
operations ever conducted in the United States, with $4.2 billion
passing through one account alone from October through March. But
because some accounts have remained open to help a continuing
investigation, the authorities estimate that as much as $10 billion
may have flowed through the bank since early last year.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Ms. Edwards nor Berlin has been accused of any
wrongdoing, and neither has been detained or arrested, said a
spokeswoman for the National Crime Squad.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said it was the British authorities who
alerted the FBI to what they suspected was a money-laundering
operation at the bank.
</P>
<P>
   The spokeswoman for the National Crime Squad refused to explain
what investigators had been looking for during the search of Ms.
Edwards' apartment, near Marylebone, an affluent London
neighborhood, on Wednesday night. The search lasted several hours.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Edwards, 41, may have left Britain with her husband, friends
of the couple said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-99 2353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990820.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4895 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CBS-SOAP-OPERA-NYT &LR;      08-20 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CBS-SOAP-OPERA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CABLE CHANNEL TO PRESENT CBS'S TOP-RATED SOAP OPERA
</HEADLINE>
   (ko) 
 By BILL CARTER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ CBS agreed Friday to extend its contract to broadcast
television's highest-rated soap opera, ``The Young and the
Restless,'' in a deal that will enable Columbia Tristar Television,
the studio that produces it, to use the program as a centerpiece in
its plans to begin a cable channel devoted to soap operas.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will give CBS an equity stake in the channel, to be
called Soap City. The network will share that financial stake with
its affiliated stations.
</P>
<P>
   CBS entered into a new long-term agreement with Columbia, whose
parent is Sony Corp., guaranteeing that ``The Young and the
Restless'' will be broadcast on CBS through 2004 and at the same
time allowing the studio to use episodes of the show on Soap City.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia plans to present the episodes in prime time on the same
day they are shown on CBS. The ``day and date'' repeat is central
to Columbia's plans to establish Soap City as a viable channel,
which it will distribute not only on cable, but also on satellite
and future digital channels.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia is competing with ABC, which has announced plans for a
soap channel of its own. ABC's channel will feature same-day
repeats of four soap operas it owns, including ``General
Hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding ``The Young and the Restless'' means that Soap City will
be able to fill its prime-time hours with at least two of the
highest-rated soaps on television, the other being NBC's ``Days of
Our Lives,'' which Columbia also owns.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, which is owned by Walt Disney Co., went through difficult
negotiations with its affiliated stations earlier this year over
its plans to reuse episodes of ``General Hospital'' and its other
soaps. Network executives said they needed to find ways to generate
additional revenue from soap operas, which are expensive to
produce. Executives from the affiliated stations complained that
the same-day repeats on a cable channel could reduce audiences for
the daytime telecasts and could pull viewers away from ABC's
competing prime-time programs.
</P>
<P>
   ABC later reached an agreement with the affiliates that
guaranteed them certain exclusive rights to ABC shows, but the
network retained the right to repeat episodes of its soap operas on
the cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   When Columbia announced its own plans for a soap opera channel
in May, CBS executives, citing deference to the network's
affiliates, said CBS would not relinquish its exclusivity. But CBS
was faced with the need to maintain rights to ``The Young and the
Restless,'' which has led the network to dominance in daytime
ratings for 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of winning a long-term renewal for the show,
coupled with Columbia's offer of equity in the new channel,
persuaded CBS to make the deal, a senior CBS executive said.
</P>
<P>
   The network won a measure of support from its affiliates with
its offer to share in the financial stake in the channel.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Karpowicz, the chairman of the CBS affiliates board, said
Friday in a statement: ``Obviously it's difficult for CBS
affiliates to agree to any loss of exclusivity in our local
markets. However, the affiliates and group owners that we talked to
agreed that it was important to keep `The Young the the Restless'
on our network and we certainly appreciate having a stake in
Columbia Tristar's new channel.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither ABC nor Columbia has said how widely it expects its new
soap channel to be distributed. Both channels are scheduled to go
on the air in January.
</P>
</TEXT>
